<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-FUTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURING THE DIGITAL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The future of home video is here right now, and it's digital.
Much of the technology is in place. Other aspects will be soon.
It's just that most people are not yet plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   Home video screens are going to be bigger and look more like
multiplex screens, and there will be more choices in what to see.
</P>
<P>
   The new Sony Trinitron HDTV monitor is typical of the shape of
things to come. It's in the wide-screen, letterbox format and
measures 34 inches diagonally. It sells for $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, Sony also has DVD video goggles for
personal headset viewing that cost $800.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is going to be watching some sort of digital TV,''
says Jim Barry, spokesman for the Consumer Electronics
Manufacturers Association. ``Even more important, they will have
more control over what they're watching and when they're watching
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The four most powerful forms of communication _ the telephone,
radio, television and the Internet _ will be coming together and
bringing it home on a screen, Barry says. ``Now, is that screen a
television or a computer?''
</P>
<P>
   He says people ``are going to start thinking of TV as
components. Separate receivers and screens and set-top boxes. Is
that a TV set or maybe just a monitor?''
</P>
<P>
   Digital computer code brings it all together.
</P>
<P>
   The innovators include cable systems, satellite companies,
telephone companies, computer companies, electric utilities _
``anyone who has a pipeline into the home to deliver information
and entertainment is going to be looking for ways to leverage that
to get better quality,'' Barry says.
</P>
<P>
   People will continue to watch feature films on home video, as
they do now, on cable, via satellite dish or videocassette. DVD
will be a growing presence. But it's the set-top boxes, which
provide interactive communication, that will lead to a much wider
range of choices.
</P>
<P>
   There is already the equivalent of a digital VCR. ``You'll have
things like Replay Networks with a box that you hook up to the
TV,'' Barry says. ``By plugging it into the phone line, you become
the programmer. For example, you can record all Tom Cruise movies
(shown on TV) or all the basketball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Just around the corner in the Bay Area is video on demand:
feature films available through cable any time the viewer chooses.
There will also be special events, such as rock concerts.
</P>
<P>
   The video-on-demand company DIVA in Menlo Park, Calif., is set
to roll out the service this fall via its first Bay Area cable
system, Chambers Communications in Novato, and other local cable
systems will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Customers using a remote control will be able to choose a
feature film from a library that can eventually reach 1,000 titles
through a service that streams video out through the cable to the
set-top box.
</P>
<P>
   The functions include pause, rewind and fast-forward. They apply
to concert events as well, so a song can be replayed _ or skipped.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Widespread availability of feature films on the Internet is
further down the line. The limited bandwidth now in place through
telephone lines leaves a lot to be desired for feature-film quality
on home computers.
</P>
<P>
   As for what is available online, Barry says, ``The challenge for
the moviemakers as well as the electronic delivery people is
protecting the copyright, putting a gate around it and a cash
register. This is one of the big obstacles right now.'' (The
situation is similar to downloading music via MP3.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want the best picture quality and surround sound,'' he
says, ``right now you go DVD.'' As viewers plug into other digital
systems, they'll get better picture and sound quality, too.
</P>
<P>
   Films will still premiere in all the new multiplexes that are
springing up, but ``it is a very small percentage of the population
who actually go out to the movie,'' Barry says. The film studios
know this as well as anyone, and the first showing of movies in
theaters is also a marketing device for later release through the
chain of electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for DIVA, the video-on-demand company, says
big-studio premieres are not likely in the near future, except
perhaps as isolated special events. As video on demand becomes more
widely used and provides a larger revenue stream, ``the studios
will adjust the availability of brand-new releases accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   On DIVA, new releases are available in the same window as
pay-per-view on cable. The order of release is: theaters,
airplanes, video stores and cable.
</P>
<P>
   The bigness of home video extends to price. The $7,500 basic
price for the Sony Trinitron HDTV monitor at the Metreon store in
San Francisco is part of an integrated system that may cost as much
as $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   For an additional charge, the $800 DVD goggles hook up to a
Discman. The feature-film picture seen in this headset fills the
field of vision like a 19-inch screen seen from five feet.
</P>
<P>
   People may be shocked by the prices of digital TV, Barry says,
``but if history is any guide, prices will come down fairly
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
