<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GENERATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERATION V: BORN INTO THE VIDEO AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 By RUTHE STEIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jacen Prete tore through the video section at
Virgin Megastore in downtown San Francisco. Within minutes he had
picked out a half dozen DVDs to buy, including ``The Exorcist,''
``Batman &AMP; Robin'' and ``Crash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I spend all my money,'' said Prete, a
23-year-old accountant, balancing his growing stack in two hands.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, he used his first paycheck to start a collection of
videos that has mushroomed into more than 1,000. Now he's in the
expensive process of replacing them with DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Videos have been around for a quarter of a century, which means
Prete's generation can't remember a time when they didn't exist _
much as earlier generations can't imagine what it was like not to
have a radio or television. People younger than 25 have been
referred to as the MTV generation, but they could just as well be
called the video generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone with my dad to rent videos as long as I can
remember. I know if there's a movie I miss, I can always catch it
on video,'' said Chris Lovos, 15, of Cupertino, Calif., who was
shopping for action movies at Virgin at the same time as Prete.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, 16-year-old Alice Pasto and her friend, Silvia Scarbini,
17, checked out a display of classic films. They were visiting from
Padua, Italy, where older American movies are hard to locate on
video.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find something we want, we don't mind carrying it
back,'' said Scarbini, picking up a copy of ``It Happened One
Night.'' The girls settled on ``Gone With the Wind'' and ``Doctor
Zhivago.''
</P>
<P>
   The influence of video may be greatest on people born after
1975. Many seem to view the theatrical release of a movie as just
the first step to bringing it into their living room. Movies and
video have merged into one in their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Take an offhand comment in a recent episode of ``The Sopranos,''
the hit HBO series. A young aspiring mafioso is trying his hand at
writing a movie script _ about the Mafia, of course. Discussing his
love of movies with a friend, he says, ``I get excited just walking
down the aisle at Blockbuster.''
</P>
<P>
   The generation born since the invention of video has put its
money into this new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frequent and valuable renter segment are those
between the ages of 18 and 34,'' said Robert Liuag, director of
research for the Video Software Dealers Association, a consortium
of video store owners and those who operate the home video division
of major studios.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers as a group haven't been surveyed because they're hard
to locate to interview, Liuag said. ``But we know kids are a big
component of our market.''
</P>
<P>
   That market has been consistently growing over the past 2 1/2
decades. According to a 1998 survey, the most recent statistics
available, nearly 70 percent of Americans rent a video at least
once a month.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage climbs to 78 when there is a child in the house.
``The presence of children in the household determines frequency of
renting and purchasing videos,'' Liuag said. ``People who have kids
tend to watch more videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Videos have become baby sitters for young children. VCRs give
parents more control over what their offspring are watching than
does television, with its multitude of channels.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread use of video has made children literate about
movies at a young age. Seven-year-olds can give a scene-by-scene
synopsis of the initial ``Star Wars'' movie. How this early and
frequent exposure to movies will influence them when they grow up
can only be guessed at.
</P>
<P>
   The first video generation already has been affected. It can't
be coincidence that every other creative young person these days
wants to be an independent filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Prete, for one, acknowledges that seeing so many movies on video
has gotten him thinking about becoming a screenwriter. ``I used to
just watch movies. But now I pay attention to how they're written
and really listen to the dialogue. I can stop the video and go back
and watch a scene again and again. And I think, `I could write
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
