<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC_SFCHR     08-24 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pacific Exchange Takes On New Wave of Competitors
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The Pacific Exchange has gotten caught up in the maelstrom of
change that is washing over the tradition-bound world of securities
exchanges around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's stock and options emporium is trying to find a
place for itself as computer technology increasingly takes over the
functions of the brokers and traders who haggle over securities on
exchange floors.
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of digital competitors called electronic
communications networks is directly matching buyers and sellers of
stock, and could soon bypass the existing exchanges altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Similar rivals are emerging in the options business. Within a
year or so, electronic exchanges will open for business in
competition with floor-based options marts such as Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, competitive pressures have touched off an
old-fashioned donnybrook among securities exchanges anxious to
ensure their survival as the ground shifts underneath them.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, wholesale warfare erupted among U.S. exchanges
after the market leader in options, the Chicago Board Options
Exchange, said it would begin trading Dell Computer options,
formerly the sole turf of the Philadelphia Stock Exchange. That
threatened to unravel the gentlemen's agreement that gave different
exchanges the privilege to trade exclusively the options of
specific companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pacific Exchange, it's fallen to a new chief, Philip
DeFeo, a 53-year-old New Yorker installed as chairman and CEO just
21/2 months ago, to navigate through these shoals.
</P>
<P>
   DeFeo was president and chief executive of Van Eck Associates
Group, a New York fund company with $1.5 billion in assets that
specializes in commodities and international stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's CEO is a music lover who relaxes at home by playing
the clarinet. A mustachioed grin and jovial manner belie his
hardheaded, decisive executive style, associates say. He says it
will take dramatic action to keep the exchange healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a world where our competitors are not just other
exchanges, but entrepreneurial companies that are continuously  &LR; 
 &LR; changing,'' he noted. ``The marketplace around us puts us in a
position where we have to reinvent ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say DeFeo must make two decisions quickly: What market
niche should the Pacific Exchange carve out for itself as
electronic technology gains ground? And what kind of organizational
structure will best allow it to compete?
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost overnight, the dynamics of the Pacific Exchange's
business have changed,'' said Don Putnam, managing director of
Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton, a San Francisco investment
bank that specializes in brokerage and money-management firms.
``DeFeo has got a very short period of time to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The 117-old Pacific Exchange is the third-largest options
exchange in the nation, but a minor player in stock trading. On
average, 17 million shares of stock and 271,000 options contracts
change hands daily on Pacific's trading floors.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is structured as an association whose 552 members
hold seats entitling them to trade stocks and options, and vote on
major policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific is the only exchange that trades options of such
companies as Microsoft and Sun Microsystems, and its business, at
least for now, is thriving. Despite banks of computers that process
orders, frenzied traders still crowd around ``pits,'' gesturing as
they shout ``buy'' and ``sell'' offers.
</P>
<P>
   Business is not as robust in stock trading. Dwarfed by giant,
well-heeled rivals such as the New York Stock Exchange and the
Nasdaq Stock Market, Pacific's equity operation is losing market
share and hemorrhaging cash.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, under retired CEO Robert Greber, the exchange struck
a merger deal with the Chicago Board Options Exchange. But the
Chicago exchange backed out, explaining that it needed to focus its
energy on countering electronic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Left in the lurch, Pacific cobbled together a go-it-alone
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   It adopted a series of measures to make its stock business
profitable, including a plan to close equity trading floors in San
Francisco and Los Angeles, and have electronically linked brokers
work from their own offices instead. Most observers viewed the
moves as preparations to spin stock trading off on its own, sell it
or shut it down altogether.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the exchange sought a joint-venture partner
capable of providing the advanced technology the exchange needed to
stay competitive. By the time DeFeo arrived in June, Pacific had
nearly reached an agreement with New York broker Cantor Fitzgerald
to start an advanced computer-based options trading system.
</P>
<P>
   The new CEO faced a competitive landscape that was changing on a
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   To gird for battle and make themselves more nimble, the NYSE and
Nasdaq both announced plans to junk their membership structures and
reorganize as for-profit, publicly held corporations. In options
trading, a shifting series of alliances and mergers was remaking
the business.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, DeFeo said it was too early for him
to show his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I'm new here, I want to be careful and cautious about
taking actions that have long-term effects,'' he noted. All the
same, he said, '`I have a preliminary assessment of where we ought
to go.`` One indication of DeFeo's thinking was the exchange's
recent move to reorganize its stock-trading business as a
for-profit subsidiary, similar to the proposals NYSE and Nasdaq
have made.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange members have said that could be a model for
restructuring the options business, too, by letting seat holders
swap membership for stock in a new corporation. ``We need to speed
up our decision-making processes,'' DeFeo said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the stock business, DeFeo thinks it could become a
moneymaker again. ``It's been buried before its time,'' he said. He
is even reconsidering the decision to close the San Francisco
equity trading floor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the joint venture with Cantor Fitzgerald appears
dead. People close to Pacific said the New York broker demanded too
much control over the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   DeFeo said he is still considering potential alliances, but he
is not convinced such a partnership is essential. He insisted the
exchange doesn't need outside help to modernize its computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he stressed, Pacific has plenty to offer a
potential partner. Its status as a regulated exchange recognized by
the Securities and Exchange Commission would be valuable to a
potential partner because it provides important formal protections
and controls to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he prepares to remake the institution he heads, DeFeo
must walk on tiptoes. That's because Pacific membership structure
requires consensus and is not suited for quick, dramatic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, adopting electronic technology could cut
commissions and take business from the wholesale brokers who hold
seats on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exchanges have historically been run for the benefit of their
members,'' said Junius Peake,cq &LR;  a finance professor at the
University of Northern Colorado. ``If bank tellers had run banks,
how many ATMs would we have?``
</P>
<P>
   The fact that exchanges around the world are in turmoil helps
DeFeo. ``There's a clearer sense of urgency here,'' said exchange
spokesman Dale Carlson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, wooing the members is a delicate task requiring great
political skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The membership and board had been unwilling to move faster,''
said Warren Langley, who stepped down as the exchange's No.2
executive earlier this year. ``But bringing in someone new lets you
break the mold.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
