<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GOOD-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTY-FIVE GREAT FILMS FOR HOME VIEWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In honor of the silver anniversary of video, The Chronicle's
movie staff has put together a list of 25 great movies to watch on
tape. These aren't necessarily the best movies ever made, but they
are particularly well suited to home viewing _ they don't lose a
lot in the transition from big screen to little one.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``All About Eve'' (1950): &LR;  Bette Davis as fading star Margo
Channing had better look over her shoulder at deceptively sweet,
ambitious Anne Baxter as Eve Harrington. George Sanders as the
vinegary Broadway critic is not deceived, and there's never a dull
moment.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Breaking Away'' (1979): &LR;  For a bicycling nut, this is
absolutely the best movie ever made about the passion for
two-wheeling. It's a charmer as a coming-of-age story.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The Bitter Tea of General Yen'' (1933): &LR;  The tall Swedish
actor Nils Asther, believe it or not, is convincing as the title
character, a Chinese warlord, and Barbara Stanwyck is the woman who
falls in love with him in this atmospheric Frank Capra film.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Driving Miss Daisy'' (1989): &LR;  Jessica Tandy and Morgan
Freeman are superb artists, and their pas de deux here as a starchy
Southern matron and her African American chauffeur should be
required viewing for acting students everywhere. It's a dream to
behold.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'' (1986): &LR;  Director John Hughes
never topped this comedy that made Matthew Broderick the coolest
guy around. On video, it's wonderful brainless entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The French Connection'' (1971): &LR;  This great humanistic cop
movie _ with perhaps the best chase scene ever _ has a visceral
energy and wise-guy intimacy on video. Poppy Doyle was far ahead of
Andy Sipowitz on ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``How Green Was My Valley'' (1941): &LR;  John Ford's saga about
a Welsh mining town and one family's travails is a model of vintage
Hollywood filmmaking. The actors, including Donald Crisp, Maureen
O'Hara and Roddy McDowall, are wonderful, the sets astonishingly
realistic and the elegiac tone never turns gooey.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The Last Tycoon'' (1976): &LR;  Though not everyone's cup of
tea, Harold Pinter's moody adaptation of F. Scott Fitzgerald's
last, unfinished novel is both a stark character portrait and a
somber evocation of Hollywood in the 1930s. It stars Robert De
Niro, in one of his best performances, as an Irving Thalberg-like
producer. Elia Kazan directed.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Laura'' (1944): &LR;  Falling in love with a dead person never
seemed more appealing than it does in this terrific film noir. Gene
Tierney is the haunting ghost, Dana Andrews the detective who falls
for her while investigating her death. Also boasts Clifton Webb at
his drollest and one of the best theme songs ever composed for a
movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Lolita'' (1962): &LR;  Some think they should have called this
Stanley Kubrick adaptation of Vladimir Nabokov's novel ``Quilty''
for Peter Sellers' many-faced dominance of the action, but who's
complaining? James Mason is perfection as the self-deluded
professor in the thrall of teenage Sue Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Maurice'' (1987): &LR;  This Merchant-Ivory production of E.M.
Forster's class-conscious novel, published posthumously, is one of
those films that keeps getting better on repeated viewings. Hugh
Grant is left wondering if he should have rebuffed aristocratic
friend James Wilby, who is much better off with gamekeeper Rupert
Graves.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``My Fair Lady'' (1964): &LR;  Those who think Julie Andrews was
robbed need to see Audrey Hepburn as Eliza Doolittle again; it's
her best performance. Repeated viewings bring out the continuing
delights of Stanley Holloway's turn as her father and Rex
Harrison's as Professor Henry Higgins, the role he owned. Still the
best movie version of a great stage musical.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The Postman Always Rings Twice'' (1946): &LR;  Footloose John
Garfield is stopped in his tracks by the ultimate femme fatale,
Lana Turner, as blond as blond ever gets.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Remember the Night'' (1940): &LR;  Barbara Stanwyck is a
shoplifter and Fred MacMurray the prosecutor who brings her home
for Christmas in this little-known gem from director Mitchell
Leisen and screenwriter Preston Sturges. Beulah Bondi plays
MacMurray's mother and Elizabeth Patterson is his old-maid aunt.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The River Wild'' (1994): &LR;  For a film shot entirely in the
vast outdoors, this one plays terrifically on the small screen.
It's a harrowing mix of whitewater action and evil, with Meryl
Streep as a macho mom.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Roman Holiday'' (1953): &LR;  The screenwriters of ``Notting
Hill'' were obviously inspired by this fairy-tale romance. But the
pairing of Audrey Hepburn and Gregory Peck can't be matched. The
ending breaks your heart at every viewing.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Savage Nights'' (1993): &LR;  French novelist Cyril Collard was
suffering from AIDS when he wrote, directed and starred in this
film, an adaptation of his novel about a promiscuous bisexual
suffering from AIDS. A shattering picture about sex and death, rage
and futility, about trying vainly to hold on to the moment. In
French with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Say Anything'' (1989): &LR;  One of the great teen romance
movies, too often overlooked. It's the best of John Cusack, and a
nearly perfect video flick.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``The Strange Love of Martha Ivers'' (1946): &LR;  Kirk Douglas
made his screen debut in this offbeat melodrama, and he has star
written all over him. Barbara Stanwyck gets to make love to him _
and she gets a great wardrobe to boot. Irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
