<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATING THE ONLINE VIDEO SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 By EDWARD GUTHMANN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no secret that e-commerce is reshaping our culture and the
way we purchase goods. We buy appliances, books and CDs online,
find lovers online, unload unwanted belongings online and shop for
the best schools for our children online.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable, then _ especially considering the
stay-at-home nature of many video hounds _ that cassette and DVD
sales would spread from retail outlets to a new crop of Web sites.
Without overhead costs, the Web sites peddle the same titles as
stores, but usually at lower prices, and with greater selection.
</P>
<P>
   We surveyed online marketers and did comparison shopping on two
films: last year's box-office smash ``There's Something About
Mary'' and a best-picture Oscar winner from 50 years ago, ``All the
King's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Reel.com, the Berkeley, Calif., video seller, has the lowest tag
on ``Mary'': $13.99 for a VHS copy, compared with $16.99 at most
sites. Its DVD version of the gross-out comedy is an even bigger
bargain: $17.49, next to the more typical $27.98.
</P>
<P>
   Every site has its loss leaders. Tower Records' Web site
undersells the competitors on ``All the King's Men,'' with a $13.99
sticker price for VHS, $27.99 for DVD.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget eBay, the online swap meet/auction house.
Bidding prices start at $9.99 for a new, sealed copy of ``Mary,''
while another peddler lists ``All the King's Men'' at $7.01.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; Amazon.com: &LR;  This online giant _ known for bargains, breadth
of choice and speedy delivery _ pushes its video line just as
aggressively as its books. Example: The DVD of ``Titanic,'' due
August 31, is half-priced at $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of information here: For every video title, Amazon
offers a synopsis or general description and posts lengthy reviews
from viewers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; bigstar.com: &LR;  This site bills itself as a ``movie
superstore'' with 100,000 listings for videocassettes, DVDs and
laserdiscs. Browsing is a bit frustrating: The site is overcrowded,
resembling a print tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; blockbuster.com: &LR;  So you hate the fluorescent glare of
Blockbuster's ugly, cookie-cutter stores. Spare yourself and shop
online.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; DVD Express &LR;  (dvdexpress.com): Viewers can save up to 50
percent at this online emporium, which offers same-day shipping and
claims to have the biggest selection of DVDs anywhere. Contests and
giveaways are frequent, and the site also sells movie merchandise.
DVD titles can also be preordered before the films are out of
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Reel.com &LR;  This Berkeley firm also has a retail store but does
the bulk of its business on this Web site, offering discounts up to
40 percent and special sections on kids' movies, Oscar winners and
editors' picks. The site is attractive, with clean, uncluttered
graphics and fun features like the ``Movie Anatomy'' chart that
rates each title on the basis of action, drama, humor, sex,
violence, suspense and offbeat.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tower Records  &LR; (towerrecords.com): The retail chain offers
400,000 music and video titles on this site and gilds the lily with
contests, half a million songs to sample, a music magazine and
overnight delivery. The site, which emphasizes music over videos,
has a cluttered look.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
