<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-VIDEO-GOOD-2NDTAKE-SF     08-24 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GOOD-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to boot. Irresistible.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``To Each His Own'' (1946): &LR;  Olivia de Havilland has an
illicit affair and pays for her indiscretion. A bit of a soap
opera, but still compulsive watching. De Havilland's character
turns out to be an independent woman at a time when that was pretty
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' (1962): &LR;  Harper Lee's novel of
racial intolerance and a child's awakening is perfectly realized in
this Robert Mulligan drama, starring Gregory Peck as the widowed
Southern attorney Atticus Finch. The film's graceful rhythm, modest
physical scale and emphasis on character and dialogue are all well
suited to home viewing.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Two for the Road'' (1967): &LR;  Audrey Hepburn and Albert
Finney fall in and out of love in what may be the smartest movie
ever made about marriage. Should be obligatory viewing for couples
every few years.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``An Unmarried Woman'' (1978): &LR;  Very few movies in the past
40 years have been love poems to the beauty and resiliency of
American womanhood, but this Paul Mazursky film is one of them. The
film's unsentimental look at sex and romance from a woman's point
of view has aged well, and Jill Clayburgh gives a career-defining
performance.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``Viva Las Vegas'' (1964): &LR;  This Elvis Presley movie is a
pillar of '60s kitsch. A writhing, shaking Ann-Margret is Elvis'
best co-star ever, and the movie has a breezy, just-for-pleasure
rhythm that makes for ideal TV viewing.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &UR; ``War and Peace'' (1968): &LR;  Sergei Bondarchuk directed and
stars (as Pierre) in this towering cinematic masterpiece _ a 6
1/2-hour version of Tolstoy's mammoth novel. Don't think of it as a
movie. Think of it as the ultimate miniseries to be watched over
the course of three or four nights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
