<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-BAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE KNOW WHAT WE LIKE: GUILTY PLEASURES ON VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world of video is filled with guilty pleasures. These come
in two varieties: 1) movies that we know are bad but like anyway;
and 2) movies that appeal to us on a gut level that has little to
do with quality.
</P>
<P>
   The gut-level appeal can be one of titillation or perverse
amusement. Funny dramas, hideous love stories and the lowest of low
comedies have appeal. What follows are 10 guilty pleasures from a
variety of genres. The nice thing about these films is that, unlike
good movies, whose appeal fades with repeated viewings, a guilty
pleasure is a joy forever.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Beverly Hills Ninja'' (1997): &LR;  This is the best film from
the late comedian Chris Farley. It's not to be watched for the
story line about a clumsy white guy who tries to become a Ninja
master. It needs to be seen for Farley's physical shtick, which was
as vulgar and flamboyant as the Three Stooges'.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Cracking Up'' (1983): &LR;  Jerry Lewis plays a neurotic who
seeks psychiatric help in this bizarre comedy that is funny for the
right reasons _ and for the wrong reasons. Lewis stretches each
joke to the breaking point, then extends it further, until it
becomes funny again. One example: He walks onto a slippery floor
and keeps falling down.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Devil in the Flesh'' (1987): &LR;  This art film/sex movie isn't
a guilty pleasure for its titillation, which is minimal. It's a
perverse pleasure for director Marco Bellocchio's relentless
fascination with Maruschka Detmers, a pretty but unremarkable
actress whom he photographs as the ultimate example of allure _
until it becomes ridiculous. The picture was a scandal in its time
because it was the first ``serious'' art film to include a graphic
scene of fellatio.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Godfather III'' (1990): &LR;  This is a good movie despite an
incomprehensible plot. What makes this film a guilty pleasure is
that it can be enjoyed solely for the performance of Sofia Coppola
as Michael Corleone's spoiled daughter. The climactic moment, in
which she is shot and says, ``Dad?'' is one of recent cinema's
great unintentional hoots.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; ``The Harrad Experiment'' (1973): &LR;  This film, about a college
in which students learn about sexual relations, has wall-to-wall
nudity, yet it's about as sexy as ``Schindler's List.''
Then-unknown actors Don Johnson and Bruno Kirby get fully,
frontally naked in this amazing time capsule _ a complete immersion
in '60s-style psychobabble.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``High School High'' (1996): &LR;  Jon Lovitz stars in this
delightfully stupid parody of the ``To Sir, With Love''
teacher-as-saint genre. Highlights include the scene in which two
prim students do an X-rated dance at a high school social.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Mirror Has Two Faces'' (1996): &LR;  This is a terrible
film, but it's enjoyable for perverse reasons. Barbra Streisand
plays a plain college professor who undergoes a beauty makeover
that makes her look like an over-the-hill call girl. From then on
everyone swoons over her, probably because Streisand directed the
film. This is a clueless vanity piece, the product of both
grandiosity and insecurity. It is an embarrassment, and so awful
it's hard not to watch.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Naked Killer'' (1993): &LR;  Lesbian assassins do battle against
a pair of heterosexual female assassins in this sexy and demented
Hong Kong thriller in which the women are lethal and the men are
spineless and pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Showgirls'' (1995): &LR;  This movie boggles the mind. Viewers
will tie themselves into knots trying to imagine how director Paul
Verhoeven and screenwriter Joe Eszterhas expected anyone to take it
seriously _ or how Elizabeth Berkley expected to become a star by
licking her own nipples. Beware: Stay away from the R-rated
version. This film must be seen in all its NC-17 glory.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Torch Song'' (1953): &LR;  Joan Crawford is tougher than any man
in this bizarre film about a hard-as-nails Broadway star and her
romance with a blind pianist (Michael Wilding). In the case of
Crawford, the blindness helps. Crawford's appeal is elusive, to say
the least, but that's what makes the film fascinating _ not to
mention the scene of her onstage performing in blackface. You won't
believe your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
