<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-VIDEO-TEACHING-SFCHRO     08-24 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-TEACHING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST-FORWARD TO THE HEAD OF THE CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 By PETER STACK  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With thousands of videos on history, science, nature, how to
make things, concert performances, music instruction, criticism,
poetry, fine arts, religion, personal growth, transportation,
health, politics and parenting, a person could earn several college
degrees' worth of knowledge while curled up on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, feature films still dominate home viewing, accounting
for more than 90 percent. But a lot of educational programming on
video is fascinating and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   History? There are hundreds of video accounts, from the
scholarly, five-tape ``Charlemagne'' ($90) to the ``American Women
of Achievement Video Collection'' ($400), with inspiring profiles
of Jane Addams, Emily Dickinson, Amelia Earhart and Sandra Day
O'Connor, among others.
</P>
<P>
   One question that always arises with specialized home video is
where to get the goods. It's not as hard as many think.
</P>
<P>
   Public libraries usually have a good stock of educational and
documentary programming. Perhaps the best source in Northern
California is the San Francisco Public Library (main branch is on
Larkin Street between Grove and Fulton streets; call (415)
557-4400). The big advantage there is that tapes circulate for
free.
</P>
<P>
   Try video dealers, too. A good store should have some basics _
those terrific National Geographic nature programs, for example.
But video dealers are also willing to share catalog information and
order videos for customers.
</P>
<P>
   A surefire source is the nation's largest mail-order video
rental and sales firm, Facets Video (1517 W. Fullerton Ave.,
Chicago, IL 60614. Call (800) 331-6197). The Facets catalog is vast
and the folks there are very helpful.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Other sources are gift shops at museums, nature centers,
zoos, aquariums. Music and record stores stock programs on how to
play instruments. Check theater bookstores for drama videos,
hardware stores for tapes dealing with construction methods.
Sporting-goods retailers often sell videos _ a way of getting their
customers stoked about skiing, mountaineering or kayaking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Here are some suggestions for history buffs: A fine, populist
U.S. history is ``Ken Burns' America'' (about $90). There are
superb videos on historic speeches (``Great American Speeches,''
``The Speeches Collection''), and there are dozens of riveting
videos about World War II (``World at War'' is a fascinating
overview in 26 volumes; $20 per tape), Vietnam (including the CBS
seven-volume series ``Vietnam''), World War I and the Civil War.
The Smithsonian Institution's ``Great Battles of the Civil War'' in
seven volumes ($30 each) is memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians of North America'' is one of the most extensive
filmic overviews of native cultures ever made. It looks at 20
tribes (about $40 per cassette; also available in 10-volume sets).
</P>
<P>
   There are histories of Africa, Europe and the ancient worlds of
Greece, Egypt and Asia. Dozens of tapes are available on world
religions, scores on biblical subjects alone. Check out the
fascinating series ``According to Kossoff,'' featuring biblical
scholar David Kossoff telling Old Testament stories.
</P>
<P>
   Biographies are a major source of pleasure. Great portraits of
baseball players, presidents, inventors, poets, filmmakers,
painters, criminals and statesmen are available. Some titles: ``The
Complete Churchill'' (four parts, $60), ``Patton: A Genius for
War'' ($20), ``FDR'' (four-tape boxed set, $70), ``Houdini'' ($20),
``Jim Thorpe _ All American'' ($20), ``P.T. Barnum: World's
Greatest Showman'' ($20), ``Thomas Jefferson: Philosopher of
Freedom'' ($20) and ``You're the Top _ The Cole Porter Story''
($20).
</P>
<P>
   In sheer volume, music, dance and fine arts videos outnumber all
other specialty programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the visual arts, entire critical surveys are contained in
programs such as the ``Impressionism Box Set'' ($80), the 10-volume
PBS survey ``Art of the Western World'' ($100 per tape) and several
excellent video collections from the Metropolitan Museum, the
Whitney Museum, the Louvre and the Hermitage. The ``Metropolitan
Museum Box Set'' ($80), three tapes showing and discussing the
museum's collection, is outstanding. And don't forget those
amusing, insightful Sister Wendy surveys.
</P>
<P>
   If you start feeling numb from too much couch time, there are at
least a dozen tapes by health experts on back care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
