<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7300 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-VIDEO-PORN-SFCHRON &LR;      08-24 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-PORN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE COMPETITION, PORN VIDEO SALES STEAMING ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (with VIDEO-25YEARS-SFCHRON)  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although exact figures are difficult to obtain, there's no
question that adult video is big business.
</P>
<P>
   Adult Video News, a trade magazine, claims the genre has a 19
percent share of the entire video market, but the number is tricky
because there is no exact definition of ``adult video.'' What is
clear is that flesh-film distributors gained an immediate foothold
when the home video revolution began in the 1980s, because home is
where the privacy is.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Internet is eroding the video scene, but there's still a
steady supply of product. And DVD, with its clearer picture and
potential for multiple camera angles, is making inroads.
</P>
<P>
   Argument rages over what adult video is. To many people, it
seems to include everything from the relatively tame,
market-dominating Playboy Home Video line to a current crop of
hard-core, made-for-video films that redefine the concept of
raunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own niche, our own category,'' said Barry Leshtz,
senior vice president and general manager of Playboy Home Video.
``We don't consider ourselves adult video, per se, though we are
adult in content. We're very mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Playboy, specializing in naked women and a relatively new Eros
series of ``sensual'' feature films, has no fewer than three big
titles on Billboard magazine's top-selling videos chart _
``Playboy's Celebrities,'' featuring Pamela Anderson Lee, Carmen
Electra, Jenny McCarthy, Dian Parkinson and others; ``Playboy's Hot
City Girls''; and ``Playboy's 1999 Playmate of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't show explicit sex,'' Leshtz said. ``The concept we
follow is that we're showing beautiful people enjoying eroticism
and sensuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is ``girl on girl'' action, as the trade calls it.
Playboy has made significant inroads in attracting couples _ the
company produced a popular tape called ``Playboy's Couples'' _ and
an increasing number of women as video buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding that a lot of decisions about home entertainment
are made by females, and women generally feel comfortable knowing
we don't show violence, S&AMP;M, bestiality or things that would be
threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Rival Penthouse is more explicit. Current top sellers for
Penthouse, ``Sun, Surf and Centerfolds'' and ``Girls of the
Zodiac,'' are far racier but stop short of explicit sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   The number of hard-core titles has skyrocketed in the 1990s,
from about 1,300 to last year's record 9,000. Dozens of producers
churn out a vast range of adult fare catering to every taste,
fetish and gender. The chart-topping rental this month is a John
Leslie production, ``Fresh Meat 7,'' part of a continuing series,
while first in direct sales is Seymore Inc.'s ``Tushy, Anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
