<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7301 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-INSURANCE-SMALL-2TAKE     08-24 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-SMALL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL COMPANIES GRAPPLE WITH HEALTH-CARE COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Larry Shandy flinched at the voice mail
message he received when he walked into his small, tidy office the
morning of July 19.
</P>
<P>
   The voice on the recording said Shandy's company, Kansas
City-based CPS Distributors Inc., was facing a 14 percent rate
increase on its health insurance premiums. The company has about 35
employees here and five in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go again,'' Shandy muttered to himself, disgustedly.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't surprised. Shandy said CPS, which distributes
audio electronics such as car and boat stereos, had gone through
many health insurers in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really frustrated, because it's really getting old,'' he
said. ``They come to me with these great quotes and the next year
we get tremendous increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Shandy's not alone. The U.S. Chamber of Commerce says small
businesses got socked with an average premium increase of 19
percent last year, compared with an average increase for all
businesses of 7 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many small-business owners feel they must provide health
insurance to attract qualified employees in an extraordinarily
tight labor market. Besides a strong economy, competition for
employees in the Kansas City area has been revved up by attractive
benefit packages offered by casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Some small-business owners feel compelled to drop coverage when
their premiums jump. Others grit their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm being gored, but I'm getting used to it,''
said Jim Bichelmeyer, co-owner of Bichelmeyer Meats, a Kansas City,
Kan., firm with 12 employees. ``It's another cost of doing business
and we have to count on the cost going up 10 percent to 20 percent
every year. You just wonder when ... it's going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Others turn to group plans designed for small businesses, such
as ChamberCHOICE, a program endorsed by the Greater Kansas City
Chamber of Commerce and operated by Blue Cross Blue Shield of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Chamber of Commerce said recently that it is
putting together a program to help small businesses offer health
insurance to their workers.
</P>
<P>
   And in Kansas, small businesses can apply for tax credits to
offset the cost of providing health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The various programs aim to address overwhelming economic
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of small businesses compiled earlier this year, the
U.S. Chamber found that 81 percent of respondents cited the cost of
health care or insurance as a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 percent of respondents who said they did not offer
health insurance, more than half said they probably would offer it
if it were more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   In a May survey of small businesses conducted by the Missouri
Chamber, one-third of the responding companies said they offered
their employees no medical benefits. Of those, three out of four
cited cost as the reason.
</P>
<P>
   And while small-business owners may want to provide health
benefits to their workers, experts say small businesses lack the
purchasing power of big companies to negotiate lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small employers just don't have the leverage to attract
competitive pricing,'' said Daniel P. Mehan, the Missouri Chamber's
president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, small-business owners may have to choose between
giving their employees health benefits or bigger paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that small businesses offer a smaller pool of
individuals for an insurer to spread risk over. Don Brain, a
health-care consultant and president of Corporate Benefits
Consulting Group in Overland Park, said some small businesses see
their rates jump because one employee has a controllable health
condition such as high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating costs are squeezing some small businesses out of
the health insurance market, Brain said.
</P>
<P>
   CPS provides its employees with health insurance through United
HealthCare of the Midwest Inc. Under the proposed 14 percent rate
increase, the company's premium payments would have gone from
$120.65 to $137.54 a month for each employee. The total annual
premium cost to the company would have risen from about $58,000 to
$66,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shandy, the CPS president, said CPS looked at about 12 other
bids and ultimately chose an offer from United for a less extensive
health plan for $123.79 a month per employee, bringing the
company's annual premium costs to about $59,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shandy said he isn't thrilled with the outcome, but feels it's
the best he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't want to switch (insurance companies),'' Shandy
said. ``You have to requalify everybody. Some of the people
wouldn't be able to use the same doctors or hospitals. And even
when an insurance company gives you a quote, you may not get it for
that price after they check everyone's health history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bichelmeyer, whose business also gets health insurance through
United, said the meat company's premium rate jumped 18 percent last
March.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Tracy, vice president of sales and marketing in United's
Overland Park, Kan., office, said United and other insurers are not
trying to squeeze their small-business customers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tracy said United and its competitors must raise rates
to a level that will cover higher use of health services and higher
costs for those services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to see increases in prescription drug usage and
the cost to provide those drugs, as well as in outpatient services
and additional costs resulting from recent government mandates,''
Tracy said.
</P>
<P>
   Such mandates include greater coverage for emergency room visits
and requirements to provide coverage for people in poor health,
Tracy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flip side to it is we are taking as many steps as we can
to put products and plan designs into the marketplace that allow
the small employer to have more choice and still protect their
employees,'' Tracy said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Coorsh, a spokesman for the Health Insurance Association
of America in Washington, said the industry group agrees that it
can be tough for small businesses to obtain health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Coorsh said the association has proposed tax incentives to help
small businesses that do provide coverage. It also has recommended
other measures, such as widening the availability of medical
savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   One option for small businesses is the ChamberCHOICE program,
which began in 1994 and now covers more than 4,200 businesses.
Participants may choose a health maintenance organization (HMO),
preferred provider organization (PPO) or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs and PPOs are both forms of managed care, but HMOs are
stricter in their control of access to care.
</P>
<P>
   ChamberCHOICE offers small businesses price stability, said
Roger Foreman, a Blue Cross senior vice president who oversees the
program. Members saw an average premium increase of 8 percent this
year and can expect about the same in 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ChamberCHOICE currently serves businesses with fewer than 25
employees, but will expand in October to include those with up to
49 employees, Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the businesses participating in ChamberCHOICE is Oz
Accommodations Inc., a rental home and apartment finder based in
Lenexa, Kan. The company has 15 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are plans out there that are less expensive,
but we feel that for the service we get it's worth the money,''
said Marlene Abbey, Oz founder and co-owner. ``Being able to offer
a good insurance package attracts excellent employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Missouri Chamber's plan calls for a statewide
health insurance purchasing cooperative that would offer small
companies more choices and purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated launch date is January. Preliminary plans are to
offer the program through local insurance agents and to involve
local chambers of commerce in the marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stumpf, an independent insurance agent who represents
ChamberCHOICE, said virtually any small business can obtain some
type of health coverage for its employees if it considers all the
options.
</P>
<P>
   The plan they end up with may not be a ``Mercedes,'' but
``certainly a workable plan that protects against catastrophic
claims,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
