r f BC-MIAMI-CASINO-KAN &LR;      08-24 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-CASINO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTHOUGH FEDERAL APPROVAL WAS WITHDRAWN, INDIAN CASINO PLAN ISN'T
DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Plans for a tribal casino in Miami County,
Kan., aren't dead yet.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Interior Department late Friday informed Kansas Gov.
Bill Graves it had withdrawn approval for the gambling hall,
proposed by the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma for 35 acres near La Cygne
Lake, about 45 miles south of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But in a more detailed letter Friday to tribal officials, the
government explained that it had acted on technical grounds only
and encouraged the tribe to begin the process again.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' office, which also received the tribal letter, released
copies Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Les Cusher, executive director of the Miami Tribe, said Monday
that the tribe's attorneys were reviewing the matter and that it
was undecided about its next step.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has signed casino pacts with four indigenous tribes that
reside on reservations in the state. But the state has resisted the
Miami Tribe's casino plan, saying the site is not within a bona
fide tribal reservation.
</P>
<P>
   After years of litigation against Kansas and others, the Miami
Tribe last year won various court and federal agency rulings
declaring the site was eligible for casino gambling according to
the 1988 Indian Gaming Regulatory Act, even though the tribe had
relinquished the land more than 120 years ago when it migrated to
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   In an administrative ruling last year that is being challenged
by the state in federal court, the Interior Department declared
that the land had requalified as reservation since 1996, when the
tribe accepted its current owners as full tribal members.
</P>
<P>
   However, that strategic move came after the tribe had first
approached the state in 1992 about a casino and had been rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Department rules _ also under challenge by Kansas and
other states _ empower the agency as a last resort to approve and
license casinos when tribes and their state governments are unable
to negotiate mutually acceptable tribal gambling agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Interior was moving toward issuing such a license to the tribe
when the state sued last month.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter to the tribe, the Interior Department reversed its
position and agreed with the state, at least in part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state had no duty to enter into such negotiations (in
1992) because the Miami Tribe had no claim to jurisdiction over any
Indian lands within the state,'' the government said. Those facts
voided Interior's intervention in the case, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the (Miami County land) is now recognized as Indian
lands,'' the letter concluded, ``we encourage the Miami Tribe to
seek negotiations with the state of Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Graves would not open talks with the tribe
until all legal matters are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Graves wants a judge to weigh in on the reservation
land issue,'' said spokesman Mike Matson. ``Until then, everything
else is a nonstarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also wants a final judicial determination of the
status of the land, said Interior Department spokeswoman Stephanie
Hanna.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are also hopeful the tribe and the state would begin to
negotiate an amicable and voluntary compact,'' she said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
