<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7305 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KOSOVARS-COLLEGE-KAN &LR;      08-24 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVARS-COLLEGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE BRINGS ETHNIC ALBANIANS TO KANSAS CITY
COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two years ago, Mrika Tahiri spent her first
week of college in Kosovo facing down police who fired tear gas at
a student protest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She limped away with a gash on her leg. Other classmates were
badly injured. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is why Tahiri, 21, couldn't help but shake her head at the
contrast between that ordeal and her first week at Rockhurst
University. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the university's quadrangle, students horsed around, smiles
on their tanned faces as they shared stories from summer vacation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here and everyone is having fun. Everyone is so
happy,'' she said Monday. ``I was like, `What is this?' We're not
used to that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri is one of nine ethnic Albanians attending Rockhurst
through Project Concern, which has placed about 45 students at 22
colleges. Rockhurst, which accepted the most students, is providing
tuition, room and board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College life is carefree for many students. But Tahiri and other
students from Kosovo say that for them, university life has been a
painful experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the government took over Pristina University in
Kosovo. Students were evicted from dormitories, and teachers were
barred from classrooms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the education didn't stop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Professors taught classes in cramped basements of private homes.
Students had no desks. Many classmates fled the country
altogether. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We never gave up,'' said Kole Krasniqi, 19. ``They continued
to keep up the lessons. We continued to try to learn.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic conflict worsened this year when NATO began bombing
Yugoslavia. That caused the Serbs to tighten the screws against
ethnic Albanians, who make up the majority in Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri remembers eating dinner and hearing the first bombs
drop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh my God, my life is about to change,' '' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri and Krasniqi fled for the border, becoming separated from
family and friends. Both ended up in refugee camps in Macedonia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri arrived with less than $20. Krasniqi's stay was equally
miserable _ he often waited two hours to brush his teeth from a
rocky spring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Tahiri's last memories of the camps was seeing a former
professor whose face was bruised from a police beating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both students contacted relatives in America and reached New
York in June. Both wanted to return to college but didn't know
how. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Carol Detweiler of Oneonta, N.Y., was watching
news footage of the refugees' plight. With the help of her husband,
who is president of Hartwick College, she started Project Concern. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detweiler solicited interest from colleges across the country,
including Rockhurst. About 145 refugees applied for scholarships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detweiler hopes the program will address Kosovo's ``brain
drain,'' in which thousands of professionals fled the province
during the conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``After a war like this, to build a country back up, you need to
have educated people,'' she said. ``My hope is that some of these
young people will go back home and be the future of their own
country.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rosita McCoy, a university spokeswoman, said playing host to the
Kosovar students is consistent with Rockhurst's mission to help the
less fortunate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She hopes their presence will benefit American students, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll bring a new perspective to our classes and add
diversity to our student population,'' McCoy said. ``They've
actually lived something that was a critical period in world
history.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, Tahiri and Krasniqi are adapting to their new country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri's cropped blonde hair and Krasniqi's high-top Adidas
sneakers already blend right into American college fashion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They are looking forward to the start of classes on Wednesday.
Tahiri plans to study pharmacy, Krasniqi is pursuing a dental
career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although they only arrived in Kansas City last week, the
students already are dealing with the staples of college life:
parties, long lines for registration and frightening cafeteria
food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri said her classmates' eyes light up when they hear she is
from Kosovo. ``They can't wait to hear about it,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They are dealing with cultural differences, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many classmates turn their dormitory rooms into an electronics
store display: VCRs, televisions, video games stacked eye-high. The
Kosovar students feel self-conscious because they have only a few
bags of possessions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And although Tahiri's English is polished, she still is
deciphering the nuances of American slang. She was stumped when her
query of ``What's up?'' was met with the reply: ``Just chillin'.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It also took students awhile to feel comfortable asking campus
police for escorts. In Kosovo, an encounter with police often
resulted in beatings or other abuse, Krasniqi said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You never approached the police. You tried to avoid them,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both students hope to put the loneliness and bad memories out of
their minds once classes start. It isn't easy contacting relatives
left behind. Krasniqi's family must travel more than 74 miles to
Pristina to call him because phone service still is out in his
hometown of Peja. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first, both Tahiri and Krasniqi dreamed of returning home one
day just as Detweiler, the program's founder, hoped they would. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, they say they cannot imagine returning to a country where
towns have been leveled, relatives displaced and friends
traumatized. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The life I knew has ended. It's over,'' Tahiri said. ``I'm
trying to continue it here. This is a new start. I can't wait.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
