<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-DEFENSE-HNS     08-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ If Mack Brown could use a remote control to operate his
defense, the first button he would push would be the one marked
``volume.'' The energetic Texas head coach, who is never at a loss
for words, has a high-energy defense filled with soft-spoken
players.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From 300-plus-pound junior linemen Casey Hampton and Shaun
Rogers to lead-by-example linebackers Anthony Hicks and De'Andre
Lewis to quick and quiet defensive backs Joe Walker and Ervis Hill,
most of the UT defenders prefer to let their play speak for them.
</P>
<P>
   When the Longhorns take the field Saturday against North
Carolina State, they hope their play will deliver a more positive
message than it did in last year's season opener, a 66-36 win over
New Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they expect it to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we are better,'' said Lewis, a sophomore who started
all 12 games last season. ``Last year we didn't really know what we
had; now we know. Now that we know that we have the best coaching
staff in America, we know that if we just buy into what they say,
everything will work out well. That's what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said this year's defense will enter the season looking for
an emotional leader, a talker _ the role filled by middle
linebacker Dusty Renfro last year. Lewis, who was an All-Greater
Houston running back as a senior at Aldine, is trying to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to step up and take that responsibility,'' Lewis
said. ``Dusty was a great leader, and it will take a lot for
somebody to give the team what he brought to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis brings speed to the middle, where he is expected to start,
depending on how Hicks fares in practice this week. Hicks, a
fifth-year senior who was named the team's Most Improved Defensive
Player last season, had reconstructive knee surgery after suffering
a season-ending injury at Texas Tech last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough players and athletes to step up when somebody
is out, and we haven't had that,'' Hicks said. ``You can see the
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   You could also see the defense's improvement after that sloppy
beginning in '98. New Mexico State rushed for 233 yards and passed
for 250 in that first game, but by season's end the Longhorns were
able to stuff eventual Big 12 champion Texas A&AMP;M's running game (25
carries for minus-seven yards) while holding the Aggies to 173
total yards.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said this year's defense is much better going into the
season and should be better than the group that ended last season
with a win over Mississippi State in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run faster than we did at this time last year, we're
playing with more confidence, we have more depth at linebacker and
the defensive front, our safeties are tackling better than we did
this time last year, and we're playing better man coverage,'' Brown
said. ``I think everything on defense is better than it was last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its marked improvement, which helped the Longhorns to
a 9-3 season, the Texas defense was one of the worst in the country
against the pass. Texas gave up 220.9 yards a game through the air
and 15.9 yards per reception, more than its big-play offense was
able to generate (15.6). Baylor was the only Big 12 team to allow
more passing yards (2,499 to Texas' 2,430).
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Longhorns finished 92nd in the country in pass
defense.
</P>
<P>
   And the Longhorns finished 83rd in the nation in scoring
defense, allowing 29.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Enter N.C. State, which finished 7-5 a year ago and comes to
town on the shoulders of Jamie Barnette, the school's all-time
leading passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let some people make big plays on us, and we had some tough
games, but it'll be different this year,'' said Walker, a junior
who started 11 games last year. ``We've worked really hard to
improve our man-to-man coverage, and it'll show.''
</P>
<P>
   It had better, because the 6-0, 196-pound Barnette has a
penchant for making big plays. The fleet-footed senior, who has
been a starter since midway through his freshman season, completed
55 passes for more than 20 yards last year and is on track to
become the Atlantic Coast Conference's all-time leading passer.
</P>
<P>
   With Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese's love for all-out
blitzes, the Longhorns could be in for a long night if they do not
get to Barnette early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we've got to do to help our secondary is get to the
quarterback,'' Brown said. ``No one can cover guys that run 4.4 or
4.5 very long. Our secondary gets beaten up every time there's a
deep ball that's thrown for a touchdown, but in some cases that's
because we're not getting pressure on the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Barnette) gets to stand back there long, we're in bad,
bad trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that Texas' defense can carry its less experienced offense
early in the season put even more pressure on Walker and Co. N.C.
State finished 10th in the country in passing yardage a year ago,
and Stanford, which comes to Austin on Sept. 4, ended the year at
No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the defense has nothing to fear from those two squads
since it takes on a potent Longhorns passing offense every day in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cornerbacks going against Kwame Cavil, one of the best
receivers in the country, and Major Applewhite, one of the better
quarterbacks in the country, helps us a lot as a team,'' he said.
``Our guys have had to fight every day. We're ready to see a
different-color uniform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     08-24 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NO one cried.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, a few puddled up. I saw a younger woman, a blonde, and an
older, silver-haired one, a few rows apart, dab at their eyes with
a hankie. But four days after her death, there were not many tears
left to be shed for Kim Perrot, the cuddly little Comets guard who
captured a city's heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to cry when the house is jumping. This house happened
to be the palatial Second Baptist Church, with its stained glass
dome and an auditorium large enough for a basketball game. The
music from the choir and two soloists almost blew off the roof, and
what they staged Monday was more than what had been advertised,
much more than a celebration of life. This was a concert.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the guests were on their feet, standing and clapping,
and from different points in the room the word ``right!'' would pop
up like bubbles, in response to a nicely turned phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the sky was growly, with dark clouds that threatened
rain but never delivered. So the day was drier than you had
imagined, as Kim's family, friends, fans and teammates gathered to
comfort one another.
</P>
<P>
   They were not in a mournful mood. There was no casket, no
burial, just candid shots on the video screen and loving words from
half a dozen speakers, including Les Alexander, the owner of the
Comets; Van Chancellor, their coach; and Cynthia Cooper, the team's
star and Kim's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper read a passage from a poem that Perrot had included in a
letter written in her final days. The poem was titled Me, and
included this haunting and perfectly aimed thought:
</P>
<P>
   ``I look in the mirror and don't know what I see,
</P>
<P>
   ``I look again and see that it is me.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my head there is no hair,
</P>
<P>
   ``And an upside-down horseshoe that causes people to stare.''
</P>
<P>
   The scar was the visible reminder of the surgery that removed a
brain tumor the size of a golf ball but could not save her life.
She did not wear a wig, and only on occasion donned a cap or a hat.
There was nothing self-conscious about Kim, before or after her
illness. This was her look, her essence, herself. She had that gift
of making you feel you knew her, even if you had never gotten
closer than 20 rows from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, we did get to know her in the not-quite-three years
that she helped represent women's basketball in Houston. She didn't
have a lengthy career, nor life, but she never wasted a minute of
either. She was not a legend, or a superstar, or a national name or
face. She was uniquely Houston's own, out of neighboring Louisiana,
Our Girl.
</P>
<P>
   She had pride and energy and wit and the kind of courage that
inspires those who have it to get close to the flame because the
light is better.
</P>
<P>
   She wore No. 10 on her jersey, and she was one, a perfect 10,
certainly in heart and soul. You think of her with her curly hair
cropped short and blond, taking the ball to the hole after a steal,
pointing both index fingers at the crowd behind the basket in a
two-gun salute. And flashing a smile that said, simply, ``Can you
believe it? I get paid to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   She dealt so openly with her battle against cancer that she drew
most of the sports community, and many outside it, into her story.
They embraced her with hoops of steel.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd on the first workday of the week was around 3,000, and
as you studied them filing out of the church, a non-scientific poll
suggested these results: Half were men and half were women, half
were young and half were old, half were black and half were white.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Dawson, a former coach and now an executive with both
the Rockets and the Comets, may have given us the best of all
character insights. ``She reminded me of Calvin Murphy,'' he said.
``Calvin woke up every morning feeling that he had something to
prove. Kim was exactly the same. She never stopped competing.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 5-5 and feisty, flush with confidence, a role model for
any girl, or boy, who wants to dream. She beat the odds to become a
star in college at Southwestern Louisiana, broke records, played on
USA championship teams, and went to Europe for modest money. In the
late 1980s, women's basketball didn't really exist in America. It
was like being an astronaut, spending your life in training, and
being told there was no moon.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Perrot was 32, with potential and plans, when her time ran
out. She didn't smoke or drink or do drugs; there was no
self-destructive behavior that can be blamed for what happened to
her. It just happened. After the services, the guests mingled in
the parking lot, reluctant to leave. You only hope that she really
knew how deeply she touched this city, and these fans, because the
outpouring for Kim went well beyond the usual grief for an athlete
dying young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
