<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RUN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     08-24 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEVILLE, Spain _ The problem with being Marion Jones is that only
first place counts.
</P>
<P>
   So on a night when a little fellow from Morocco broke up an
expected sweep by the Kenyans in the steeplechase, wrapped himself
in his country's flag and cried joyously to celebrate a bronze
medal, Jones fought back tears of disappointment Monday over a
similar finish of her own in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bronze is just not gonna cut it for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, bronze doesn't cut it for an
American audience that pays real attention to track and field only
in Olympic years, or for the worldwide perception of a sport that
is trying to fight off the latest round of drug scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, it had been hoped, would be the poster girl for the new
millennium in the U.S. heading into the 2000 Olympics in Sydney and
also the beacon whose light would outshine all of the recent
negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
   She had come here in a sort of reverse-Columbus move to discover
entirely uncharted ground, to become the first athlete ever to win
four gold medals at a single World Championships. And she had taken
the first step with a convincing win in the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   That was not surprising at all, since the running part of Jones'
act has always come easy. She has not lost a 100 since September
1997 and has not been beaten in the 200 since 1995. Put those two
events into the bank, along with another expected win in either the
4x100 or 4x400 relay at the end of the week, and the long jump was
the only part of her ambitious schedule where she appeared
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Which turned out to be precisely the case. The best Jones could
do was a leap of 22 feet, 5 inches on her fifth attempt, which came
up short to both Niurka Montalvo of Spain (23-2) and Fiona May of
Italy (22-9\) and was also well off her personal best of 23-11}.
Dawn Burrell of the University of Houston finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was called for a foul on her last and best jump, having
appeared to barely get the tip of her toe on the plasticene strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mighty close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The evening then ended in a storm of controversy when the
Spanish judge allowed the final and winning jump by Montalvo to
stand, even though replays on the giant video board indicated she,
too, had fouled. The Italian federation filed an official protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get me into that,'' said Jones. ``I've got
enough problems of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   First, learning how to refine a very ugly jumping technique in
order to be a real gold-medal threat in the long jump next year in
Sydney. Also, to convince herself and the rest of the world that by
winning ``only'' three gold medals here, it would be an awesome
week.
</P>
<P>
   In Jones' mind, it is as clear-cut as when the matador enters
the ring at the Plaza de Toros de la Maestranza: There is only one
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to win every event that I entered here, and I
think everybody knows that,'' Jones said. ``I have no excuses. I
can sleep well knowing that I didn't hold anything back, but it
just didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, nobody should say Jones doesn't deserve applause
for at least sticking her neck out there and trying.
</P>
<P>
   While there was so much pre-meet talk of her going for four
golds, there has also been a groundswell of behind-the-scenes
gossip about Jones. There are track fans and some competitors who
viewed the attempt as a grandstanding play for attention and some
rivals who've begun sniping.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Arron of France, the European 100 champ, accused
officials in the sport of being lax in out-of-competition drug
testing and wondered how it is possible that ``American sprinters
put together victory after victory despite so much travel.'' Arron
also labeled Jones as ``cold, distant and pretentious.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is interesting, because those were some of the same words
used to describe Carl Lewis during the prime of his incredible
career.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is a case of simple jealousy from those on the outside.
Or maybe the truly great ones carry themselves a little differently
because they are competing on a different level. Does anybody
remember another athlete with the initials M.J. being downright
haughty at times in a game?
</P>
<P>
   But as Lewis learned at the 1984 Olympics, when you go public
with a historic goal, the public then merely expects you to do it.
Anything less is seen as failure, and Lewis was even booed in LA
for passing up his last two attempts in the long jump to preserve
energy in his grueling quest.
</P>
<P>
   This is Marion Jones' time under the microscope. What she has to
understand is that between here and Sydney, it only gets worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
