<HEADLINE>
KU OFFERS MINI MEDICAL SCHOOL FOR THE LAYPERSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Have you thought about going to medical
school, but you can't stand the sight of blood? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The University of Kansas Medical Center has a deal for you: an
eight-session course taught by some of the center's top faculty
that will give you a working knowledge of the human body and its
ailments without ever having to make an incision or give an
injection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's called Mini Medical School, and it is a form of education
that a growing number of medical schools are offering
successfully. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they're offered, mini medical schools attract sellout
crowds of people eager for a quick immersion into the scientific
discoveries affecting their health care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry for this information,'' said Mary Beth
Gentry, assistant dean of the KU School of Medicine in Kansas City,
Kan. ``A lot of people don't understand what academic medicine is
all about. This way, we can put a human face on it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the school is to encourage support for the
medical center's research, said Jasjit Ahluwalia, a faculty member
and organizer of the Mini Medical School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have the public behind us (to foster research)
because it's the public's money,'' Ahluwalia said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each lecture will be followed by an extended question-and-answer
period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the essence of medical school,'' Gentry
said. ``It is going to combine the science and the treatment of
disease. It won't be dumbed down.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first mini medical school was held in 1989 at the University
of Colorado as a gesture of community outreach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Cohen, a professor of immunology who organized it, said he
expected the mini medical school to have the same kind of limited
popularity a bird-watching course might attract. Perhaps 20 persons
would sign up, he thought. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a newspaper ran an article about it, 1,200 people called
to enroll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were swamped. We had to find a big hall,'' Cohen said.
Colorado has continued its mini medical school every year since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remained one of the hotter tickets in town. We've never
been able to get rid of our waiting list,'' Cohen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Colorado's success, more than 70 medical schools, health
departments and other institutions have held mini medical schools.
About 55 schools offer them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to rest until every medical school is doing
one,'' said Bruce Fuchs, director of the National Institutes of
Health's Office of Science Education and an advocate for the mini
medical school movement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs started mini medical schools at the Medical College of
Virginia and more recently at the National Institutes of Health. He
is writing a how-to manual for medical schools that want to start
one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea we want to get across to people attending mini
medical schools is that you're going to learn serious information
and you're going to have more fun than you imagine,'' Fuchs said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to send people away with a sense of what's possible,
what they can learn if they put their mind to it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs said the people who enroll in mini medical schools ranged
from truck drivers to clergy to homemakers to college professors.
Some are students considering a medical career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More often they are people trying to learn how to make good
medical decisions for themselves and their families. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People are feeling pressure to become more knowledgeable about
health care,'' Fuchs said. ``They're being asked by their doctors
to be more of a participant in their health care, rather than
receiving it passively.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That intense interest shows up frequently during one of the most
popular parts of mini medical schools, the question-and-answer
sessions that follow the lectures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Cohen said. ``That often goes on until the
janitor turns out the lights.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
