<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-SHARPTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GOES TO HARLEM TO SPEAK ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to replace `sentencing of criminals' with `prison terms' in
lede. No other changes.)  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In some of his most detailed remarks about race
relations and the plight of urban America to date, Bill Bradley
told a Harlem audience Monday night that he would use the power of
the presidency to push for universal health care, end child
poverty, abolish mandatory prison terms and end racial profiling by
police.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-hour appearance before more than 500 people at the
National Action Network, a group led by the Rev. Al Sharpton,
Bradley said that the desire to improve race relations was a major
reason he first became interested in Democratic Party politics some
35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is that racial unity is not a political
position,'' he said. ``It is who I am. It's what I believe. It's
what I care most about. It's one of the main motivations for my
being in politics in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bradley, the former U.S. senator from New Jersey,
has been telling audiences that he considers race relations a
``defining issue'' in American politics today. But in appearing
before Sharpton's group, he made it clear that he is willing to
work closely with the most liberal wing of the Democratic Party, at
least on issues concerning race and urban poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appearance also provided a political boost for
Sharpton, who at times has been ostracized by some Democratic Party
officials, but whose standing within the party seems to have risen,
partly because of public outcry against police brutality in New
York City and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Though he declined to say whether he would endorse Bradley,
Sharpton praised the former senator for being, he said, the first
presidential candidate since Robert Kennedy in 1968 to campaign in
Harlem. And he called on the other candidates to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not continue an illicit affair where people have fun
with us in private but don't want to deal with us and our issues in
public,'' Sharpton said to much laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has described his campaign as being in a phase where he
outlines general positions without getting into policy details. For
that, he has been criticized as overly vague by supporters of Vice
President Al Gore, who is generally viewed as the front-runner for
the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, during a speech he gave from notes as well as
in answers to questions from the crowd afterward, Bradley did not
shy away from taking clear and strong positions on a number of
major issues. And more often than not, his remarks drew warm
applause from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how he would help the urban poor, Bradley said he
would institute policies intended to end discriminatory lending
practices by banks, press for tax cuts specifically aimed at
helping middle-class and low-income people, raise the minimum wage
and push for legislation that would make it easier for workers to
join labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he would veto a $792 billion tax cut recently
approved by Congress ``in a nanosecond,'' Bradley also said he
would use the federal surplus to extend health insurance to all
Americans and to reduce childhood poverty. But he did not offer
specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know that because of what we did over four or
eight years that every child in America has a chance to realize his
or her potential,'' he said. ``There are still 14 million children
today who live in poverty. There are still 45 million people in
America without health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   As he often does in his speeches on race, Bradley, a former New
York Knick, recalled his experiences playing alongside blacks on
athletic teams. In his hometown of Crystal City, Mo., he said, the
Little League baseball team was integrated ahead of other town
institutions. And he recounted being forced to stay in ``third-rate
hotels'' and being denied service in segregated restaurants while
traveling with the Little League team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked out of more than one restaurant in our time,'' he
said to applause.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who received a standing ovation when he finished, also
asserted that he had made it a point to speak forcefully about race
relations on the floor of the Senate. He recounted a floor speech
he gave after the beating of Rodney King by Los Angeles police
officers in March 1991, when he pounded the lectern 56 times in two
minutes to dramatize the number of times the police hit King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to show that a white face could talk about race
without vaporizing before your eyes,'' Bradley said. ``I'm still
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NYC-COL-PETE-ROSE-NYT     08-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PETE-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FORGIVENESS ELUDES PETE ROSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In worlds as diverse as professional sports and
radical politics, the subject Monday was redemption. Sounds like a
topic better suited for a theology class, but there it was, popping
up from Police Headquarters to Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   At headquarters, the police brass made clear that they saw no
chance for redemption, not now anyway, for people who belonged to a
Puerto Rican nationalist group responsible for a series of
bombings, including one that killed four people at Fraunces Tavern
in 1975. President Clinton has offered conditional clemency to 16
imprisoned members of the group, the FALN. Although these people
were not themselves convicted of shedding blood, the police
commissioner, Howard Safir, suggested that the mere hint of
absolution amounted to a betrayal of terrorism's victims.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the question of redemption along Park Avenue may
seem almost trivial, but it probably intrigues far more people
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Park Avenue, among its many attributes, is home to Major League
Baseball, which can often be a world unto itself. That point is
being vividly underlined this week on the anniversary of one of its
most hotly disputed actions: the lifetime banishment of Pete Rose
for gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In case you are not familiar with baseball, Rose was one of the
all-time greats, with more hits (4,256) than anyone in the history
of the game. He was called Charlie Hustle. Day after day, he showed
what a gung-ho attitude can do _a lesson seemingly lost on proud
underachievers of the Bart Simpson generation.
</P>
<P>
   But by most accounts, Rose was also one of the all-time great
jerks, squandering his considerable reputation on an insatiable
desire to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago Tuesday, Major League Baseball banned him for life
and declared him ineligible for its Hall of Fame in Cooperstown,
N.Y. That was because its investigators said his gambling included
wagers on baseball games, even some played by the team he was then
managing, the Cincinnati Reds. Although Rose denied having placed
such bets, the baseball commissioner then, A. Bartlett Giamatti,
did not believe him and hurled him into the sport's equivalent of
the netherworld.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are a decade later, and in the morality play that
professional athletics has so often become, the question for the
powers on Park Avenue is whether Pete Rose has suffered enough. Is
there no chance for his redemption in a sports world that has given
second and even third chances to players who abused drugs, raped
women, choked their coaches, drank themselves into stupors and beat
girlfriends to a pulp?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. The present commissioner, Bud Selig, sees no
reason to reverse the much-respected Giamatti, who died a few days
after banning Rose. ``Basically what he's said is that he doesn't
see anything new to warrant any changes,'' Richard Levin, a
spokesman for Selig, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Many would agree. Their argument is that if Rose did indeed bet
on his own team, even to win and even with no public evidence that
he ever tried to alter the result of a game, he struck at the heart
of baseball's integrity. This is a sport that has yet to recover
fully from the terrible scandal of 1919, when members of the
Chicago White Sox ``threw'' World Series games.
</P>
<P>
   But some see a moralizing on Park Avenue that they regard as
smug at best and hypocritical at worst.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, how some baseball officials are citing Rose's
fondness for casinos and race tracks as proof that he remains
hopelessly unrehabilitated. Yet the sport lets George Steinbrenner
run the New York Yankees, though he also owns race horses. Do those
horses exist for any purpose other than gambling? And if wagering
is by definition unsavory, how is it that virtually every state
makes millions through lotteries, and many allow Indian-run casinos
to thrive?
</P>
<P>
   ``The judgment on ballplayers should be confined to their skills
on the field,'' said Eliot Asinof, who detailed the 1919 Chicago
scandal in his 1963 book ``Eight Men Out'' (Holt, Rinehart &AMP;
Winston). ``Rose was never complicit in throwing a game. He never
did anything that even suggests he was capable of such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years is enough,'' Asinof said, a thought that Rose echoed
Monday in an interview on NBC's ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans of America are willing to forgive me,'' he said. ``It
seems like everybody's willing to forgive me except Bud Selig.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
