<SLUG> BC-NY-ARRESTS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE COMMISSIONER DEFENDS THROWN-OUT ARRESTS  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir on Monday defended
the validity of thousands of arrests made by police officers,
saying the arrests, which city prosecutors deemed flawed and threw
out, should have been prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, who called for police officials and prosecutors to meet
and review the problem of unprosecuted arrests, singled out the
office of the Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, for
failing to prosecute valid gun charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gun case that's not prosecuted in Brooklyn is prosecuted in
all four of the other boroughs,'' Safir said. ``We're the only city
in the United States that is in five counties, where you have five
separately elected district attorneys who all have different
policies and procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hawkins, chief of investigation for Hynes, challenged the
police commissioner's statement, saying Hynes is tough on gun
crimes and has a policy of offering no plea bargains in gun cases.
The district attorney announced the policy, an attempt to curb a
rise in gun-related homicides, in a news conference with Safir in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's remarks were in response to an article Monday in The New
York Times that found a sharp rise in the number of arrests
prosecutors deemed to be flawed. Last year, prosecutors tossed out
18,000 of the 345,000 arrests made in the city even before a judge
reviewed the charges, more than double the number of four years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The figure means that citywide, 50 people a day are arrested,
fingerprinted and jailed, then released after prosecutors have
rejected the charges against them, often after those arrested have
spent hours or overnight in packed holding cells. Former
prosecutors and courthouse lawyers said the rise might signify a
decline in the validity of arrests in the city as officers struggle
to keep arrest totals high in an era of declining crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir said Monday that the validity of arrests had not
declined, and he blamed prosecutors for the problem, pointing out
that the rate of nonprosecutions varied among the boroughs. The
rate of cases rejected by prosecutors doubled in Brooklyn and was
up 41 percent in the Bronx and 23 percent in Manhattan, but was
down in Queens. Prosecutors on Staten Island said that records from
previous years had been damaged in a fire, making comparisons
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's largely due to the interpretation of individual
assistant district attorneys,'' Safir said. ``My police officers
and my legal bureau very often disagree with whether or not a case
is prosecutable.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors throw out arrests for a variety of reasons,
including improper searches and inconclusive evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But other elected officials called the increase in unprosecuted
arrests troubling and said it might represent a major problem in
the department. They called for the state attorney general, Eliot
Spitzer, to expand his investigation of the Police Department's
policy of stopping people on the streets and searching them for
weapons, known as stop and frisk, to see whether officers
frequently made flawed arrests in minority areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Leffler, chairman of the City Council's Public Safety
Committee, which oversees the Police Department, said the number of
flawed arrests is too high and that they waste taxpayers' money. He
said his committee might investigate the rise if Spitzer and
federal authorities do not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
