<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR COACH PICKS ALFRED TO START AT QUARTERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 12-NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH AND MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor coach Kevin Steele selected Jermaine Alfred as his
starting quarterback Monday, ending a competition with Odell James
that dated to last season, when both players split time at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, a senior, will start in the team's Sept. 4 season opener
at Boston College and will begin taking the brunt of the snaps in
daily practices. James, a junior who began the 1998 season as the
team's starter, might earn playing time in selected situations,
Steele said. But Steele stressed that, with a team playing for its
third head coach since 1996, stability at quarterback is crucial to
the Bears' rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in a one-quarterback system, and particularly in
this environment right now,'' Steele said. ``There's been a lot of
fluctuation in a lot of areas around here and we need to build some
stability. Quarterback is a good place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not rule out the possibility of James, the better
runner of the two, being used in selected situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see them both in the game. They both have
strengths,'' Steele said. ``But I don't believe in pulling somebody
just to prove a point. The way we play them will be scheduled and
game-planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred led the team in passing last season, completing 97 of 188
attempts (51.6 percent) for 1,268 yards. James connected on 52.9
percent of his passes (45-of-85) for 435 yards. Both players threw
seven interceptions in 1998, with Alfred tossing two touchdown
passes to one for James. A&AMP;M'S jOHNSON HAS PIN SET IN FOOT
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M sophomore wide receiver Bethel Johnson is questionable
for the Aggies' Sept. 4 opener against Louisiana Tech in
Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   The speedster from Corsicana, who is counted on to be an impact
receiver after sitting out last season as a partial academic
qualifier, had a pin set into the fifth metatarsal of his right
foot Monday. Johnson apparently injured the foot last week and
X-rays taken after Saturday's scrimmage discovered a stress
fracture. The guess is that with an open date after the Louisiana
Tech game, Johnson should return for Tulsa on Sept. 18. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
