<HEADLINE>
TCU PROMOTES FRESHMAN QB TO SECOND STRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Dennis Franchione held out as long
as he could, but the play of freshman quarterback Casey Printers
forced him to put the eraser to the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said Monday that Printers has jumped into the No. 2
quarterback spot behind starter Patrick Batteaux. If Batteaux were
injured in the season opener against No. 4 Arizona, Printers would
play despite never having taken a collegiate snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the second-best quarterback now,'' Franchione said. ``If
he keeps going at the pace he's going, he'll be the starter. But
there is still separation between No. 1 and 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into two-a-days, Matt Schobel was listed as No. 2. He
asked to be moved to wide receiver last week, leaving Printers,
Sean Stilley and Jeff Dover battling for the backup role. Printers
separated himself from the others with his passing and big-play
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt myself moving along,'' Printers said. ``This is exactly
where I wanted to be, but at the same time I still have a lot to
accomplish. I'm still not satisfied with the way I'm performing.''
CAST WORKS FOR MAIDEN
</P>
<P>
   TCU trainers tried a new cast on linebacker Terrance Maiden's
right arm Monday, allowing him to participate in full-contact
drills for the first time in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is designed to prevent movement in Maiden's wrist, hand
and fingers while allowing him to tackle and drop back into
coverage. Maiden hadn't been involved in full contact since he
suffered a hairline fracture in his arm 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncomfortable,'' Maiden said of the cast that completely
covers his hand. ``But I think I will be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dennis Franchione said this week that the new cast will
determine whether or not Maiden will be ready by the Arizona game.
Maiden was expected to be other starter alongside Shannon Brazzell
at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   And if Maiden's arm isn't ready, who would play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Franchione said. ``Nobody has been
consistent there.''
</P>
<P>
   The choices include Chad Bayer, John Turntine, Adrian Lewis and
his brother, Allen. GLAD HE'S BACK
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was happier to see Frogs backup quarterback/holder Jeff
Dover return for his senior season than kicker Chris Kaylakie.
</P>
<P>
   Dover missed spring practice, playing baseball for TCU, and
Kaylakie missed him.
</P>
<P>
   The walk-on, who made 15 of 20 field goals during the season,
found himself struggling to hit an extra point in the spring. He
said the difference was all in the hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had gotten so used to Jeff,'' Kaylakie said. ``I really
struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Dover is back and so is the Kaylakie, who was a semifinalist
for the 1998 Lou Groza award, given annually to the nation's best
kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten his holder situation more stable,'' Dennis
Franchione said. ``There is a bond of trust, and Chris feels more
comfortable.'' LINE MOVE
</P>
<P>
   TCU redshirt freshman offensive lineman Brady Barrick was
practicing at center Monday. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
