<HEADLINE>
SAMAKI WALKER WORKS OUT FOR SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samaki Walker's next NBA stop might be a short trip from Dallas
down Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the free-agent forward flew to San Antonio to work out
for the Spurs, who are fresh off winning the recent NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Walker hopes to get the three-year, $8.9 million contract the
Spurs offered Los Angeles Clippers free agent Tyrone Nesby this
month. The Clippers matched that offer to Nesby, leaving the Spurs
searching for another front-line player.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs also have a $2.75 million medical exception _ from the
Sean Elliott case _ that they can offer Walker. Elliott had a
kidney transplant last week, and his basketball future remains
uncertain. In addition, San Antonio has its $1.1 million exception
available.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Spurs are set to sign backup center/forward Will
Purdue this week, it's not certain where Walker will fit in on this
squad. Purdue, also a free agent, turned down a four-year, $12
million contract extension from the Spurs during this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's agent, Norm Nixon, said he also has talked to
Vancouver, Washington, Minnesota, Orlando, Houston, Utah and Miami
about signing Walker. All of those teams have offered Walker their
$2 million exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get the ($2 million) exception all over the place,
but we really haven't pursued the exception,'' Nixon said. ``I
talked to (Washington coach) Gar Heard on Friday and he told me
they had the exception on the table to offer Samaki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando is still interested in doing something with Samaki,
and I know Milwaukee is interested in him. But we're going to meet
and try to bring this stuff to a head within the next week or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is hoping Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson would
agree to a sign-and-trade package involving Walker. Nelson is
expected to return from China on Wednesday and could not be reached
for comment. TRENT TO SIGN
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent forward Gary Trent will sign a contract with the
Mavericks within a week, a source close to the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the collective bargaining agreement, Trent can
either sign a one-year, $2 million deal or a two-year, $4.2 million
contract with the Mavericks. CEBALLOS WAITS
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Ceballos' agent said he is very intrigued about what will
happen to his client once Don Nelson returns from China.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos has a two-year, $8 million offer on the table from
Nelson. But the free-agent forward wants a four-year, $16 million
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie told me not to do anything until he gets back,'' said
Fred Slaughter, the agent who represents Ceballos. ``And I can't
get Ced's deal done without that team's representative being across
the table, or without that team's representative talking to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once Nellie returns from the mainland, we're going to try
and see if we can go ahead and get the deal done.'' PRESEASON GAMES
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will play three preseason games at Reunion Arena
this year.
</P>
<P>
   They include Oct. 16 against Charlotte, Oct. 21 against Toronto
and Oct. 26 against the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' road preseason schedule will be released later
this month. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
