<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LONGHORNS SUDDENLY DEEP AT LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ By signing linebacker Cory Redding, Texas
defensive coordinator Carl Reese thought he had found the remedy
for a recurring itch.
</P>
<P>
   Reese envisioned Redding, the 1998 ``USA Today'' defensive
player of the year, as an impact freshman who could prevent him
from spending a second consecutive season ``scratching all over the
place'' in search of three linebackers he felt comfortable putting
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of fall drills, Reese said Redding has been
``something special,'' a must-play freshman of the highest order.
Yet when Redding takes the field for his first snap in Saturday's
season opener against North Carolina State (7:30 p.m., Austin),
Reese plans to play him at defensive end. In fact, Reese said
Redding might never play linebacker at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a testament to the guys we've got,'' said Reese, who has
been stunned by the progress of five linebackers (three sophomores,
two redshirt freshmen) who played few or zero snaps at the position
in 1998. ``Cory Redding is something special. He could have played
linebacker for us. But he would have had to split time with these
guys. We need him on the field. So, he's needed elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese never envisioned making that statement in February. But
that was before he saw returnees Anthony Hicks and De'Andre Lewis
adjust to life at middle linebacker. That was before outside
linebacker Aaron Babino regained his academic eligibility after
sitting out spring drills. That was before Reese saw the speed and
versatility of fresh faces Tyrone Jones, Marcus Wilkins, Everick
Rawls, Jamal Joyner and Adam McConathy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a position that has been a perennial problem spot for
the Longhorns throughout the 1990s is awash in young, fast, talent.
Hicks, who is coming off reconstructive knee surgery, is reminded
of the change every day during wind sprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we run as a group, I'm used to being at the front of the
lines and leading the pack,'' said Hicks, who has been cleared to
begin contact drills this week in preparation for Saturday's
opener. ``But these guys make me look slow.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not because of the knee, said Hicks, who graded out at
92 percent on strength and agility tests last week as part of his
rehabilitation process. It's because guys such as Jones (6-foot-4,
230 pounds) and Joyner (6-2, 205), two converted defensive backs,
have filled out since last season without slowing down. It's
because Wilkins and Rawls, two sophomores who combined for 20
tackles last season, can break 4.5 seconds in the 40-yard dash and
are close to breaking into the starting lineup as well.
</P>
<P>
   That would be just fine with Texas coach Mack Brown, who lost
the leading tackler from last season's linebacker corps (Dusty
Renfro) to the NFL and has kept his two most experienced returnees,
Hicks and Lewis, out of contact drills for much of two-a-days
because of knee and ankle ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after the team's final scrimmage, Brown said he would
be comfortable with an all-sophomore starting lineup of Jones
(strong side), Wilkins (middle) and Rawls (weak side) against North
Carolina State. None of the three have started in a college game.
But all three worked with the No. 1 defense Monday, pending the
availabilities of Hicks and Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told our (veterans), `You can lose your position because
of an injury,''' Brown said. ``I'm not concerned about the young
guys we have out there. They're playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, in particular, has turned heads with his speed, long arms
and jumping ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to bring Texas linebackers back to where they used
to be,'' Jones said. ``We're going to be faster, more athletic and
more explosive than the guys that have played here the past few
years. I think we'll surprise a lot of people, even our coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Count Reese among the pleasantly perplexed. For the North
Carolina State game, he plans to use a seven-linebacker rotation
for three positions. And none of the seven is named Redding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been anywhere before where I had that many
linebackers I could play and feel good about,'' said Reese, whose
prior stops include LSU, Virginia and Missouri, among others. ``No
question, it's a lot different from last year, when we were
scratching all over the place just to find three linebackers to put
out there.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
