<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WARREN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARREN'S TARDINESS UPSETTING TO COWBOYS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys waited until the
next-to-last full day of training camp to have a little controversy
over what could be a big injury, if it lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Warren, a four-time 1,000-yard rusher in his second season
as Emmitt Smith's backup with the Cowboys, flew to Colorado
Springs, Colo., last week to see a specialist for a recurring groin
injury. The Cowboys were informed by Warren's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris made the decision on his own. We were made aware of it
through his agent,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Monday night.
``Chris is going to be a very important part of what we do this
year, so we'll sit down and visit, and get a real good picture of
where he is with this injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones wouldn't speculate on a possible fine until he and coach
Chan Gailey have a chance to meet with Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey admittedly was caught by surprise last week when he
learned that Warren had left camp to visit Dr. Michael Leahy in
Colorado Springs. He seemed perturbed Monday by Warren's failure to
report back to the team in time for the team's first practice
following Saturday night's 34-14 loss to New England.
</P>
<P>
   To Gailey, Warren should have been in camp and attending a 4-6
p.m. practice. Warren is expected to be on the field for both
practices Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Schaeffer, Warren's agent, said that his client is
``apologetic,'' and accepts all blame for the ``misunderstanding
over when he was supposed to be back.'' Warren will formally issue
an apology to Gailey and the rest of the team, Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris had some problem getting back ... a logistical thing ...
details of what happened are nobody's business,'' Schaeffer said.
``It was his error, his oversight, but it was nothing more than
that. There was no hidden agenda. And he takes full responsibility
for what happened,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Warren apparently has benefited from this latest treatment.
Leahy uses his hands to break up scar tissue in the damaged area,
Schaeffer said, and during the off-season, the specialist was able
to increase Warren's ``range of motion by eight inches in one
30-minute session.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris recognizes the great opportunity that has been given to
him by the Cowboys. He just wants to get himself well, so that the
injury isn't exacerbated,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Warren wasn't the only Cowboys running back not practicing
Monday. Smith sat out with blurred vision as the result of a slight
concussion suffered Saturday night. He had his pupils dilated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys offered to meet Warren at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport
Monday night and give him a ride to camp. Warren preferred instead
to make the two-hour drive in his pickup truck so that he will have
it here when the team breaks camp tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was eager to talk to Warren upon his return to the
players' dorm Monday night, obviously as much as to learn about how
Warren's groin injury has responded to treatment, as about the
details of Warren's weeklong odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me because I had asked him a couple of times how
he was doing and there didn't seem to be any ill effects,'' Gailey
said, when asked Wednesday about Warren's trip to Colorado. ``So, I
am anxious to talk to him to see what brought this on.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar groin injury forced the former Seattle Seahawk to miss
eight games last season, including the Jan. 2 playoff loss to
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cowboys' first two preseason games, Warren had seven
carries for 23 yards. He also caught three passes for 18 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey had hoped to occasionally utilize Warren and Smith in the
same backfield this season. When asked if that experiment has been
delayed by Warren's week away from camp, Gailey replied, ``We'll
just have to wait and see how that all works out.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
