<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MOVE SPELLMAN FROM END TO TACKLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Roughly four weeks ago, the signing of
former Chicago Bears defensive end Alonzo Spellman was a
questionable gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, it became the Dallas Cowboys' latest attempt at solving
their problems at defensive tackle in the aftermath of Leon Lett's
indefinite suspension for violating the league's substance abuse
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman, who sat out last season after being cut by the Bears
because of a string of bizarre emotional incidents, welcomes the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see how it goes,'' said Spellman, a career defensive end,
who has only previously played tackle as a nickel pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time to get used to the speed of things inside,''
Spellman said. ``But I'll get used to it. The No. 1 thing is
whatever is going to make us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also the way the Cowboys are looking at it. Second-year
tackle Michael Myers, who had been tabbed as Lett's primary
replacement, has been a disappointment in training camp. Spellman
worked out with the first team Monday in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the Cowboys were afforded the
luxury of moving Spellman because of the progress of rookie
defensive ends Ebenezer Ekuban and Peppi Zellner.
</P>
<P>
   Despite early struggles from the layoff and being out of
football shape, Spellman, a seven-year veteran, has impressed the
Cowboys with his development. Gailey said Spellman has the
potential to be a standout at tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see how learns the position and adapts to the change,''
Gailey said. ``But obviously we wouldn't move him there if we
didn't think he could be a really good defensive tackle. We'll see
if he can do better than the other guys that are in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 294-pound Spellman has more experience than Myers
and the other tackle candidates Darren Benson and Nate Davis. But
he also has the strength to do the job as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I offer is the ability to take on a double team and not
get moved out of there,'' said Spellman, who has played tackle as a
member of the Cowboys third-down pass rush unit the past three
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the off-the-field stuff, Gailey said Spellman, who
suffers from bipolar disorder, said has been everything the Cowboys
had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has been very positive with him at this point,''
Gailey said. ``Every aspect has been positive.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
