<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMS RIVER WINS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ The only question surrounding Toms River as
it began its quest for a second straight Little League World Series
title was whether the team had enough quality pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that question answered. Zack Del Vento, the New Jersey
team's No. 3 starter, allowed just four hits over 5 1/3 innings and
struck out nine Monday night to pitch Toms River to a 4-0 victory
over Boise, Idaho (0-1), before 16,500 fans at Howard J. Lamade
Stadium. Toms River, improving to 2-0 in the tournament, virtually
assured itself of a spot in the U S. championship game on Thursday,
with the winner playing for the Little League title on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River defeated Phenix City, Ala., 6-0 on Sunday night and
meets Brownsburg, Ind., on Tuesday afternoon. ``Being 2-0, it looks
pretty good,'' Mike Gaynor, the Toms River manager, said.
``Everyone else has at least one loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor did not make his decision to match Del Vento against
Boise's No. 1 pitcher until hours before Monday's game. Gaynor's
strategy saved Eric Campesi, No. 2 in the rotation, for Tuesday's
game against Indiana, although Campesi came into a two-on, one-out
jam and induced a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that was my best game,'' said Del Vento, who started
only once in the regional tournament but went 2-0. ``I was able to
hit the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Vento's fastball didn't have the velocity, nor did his curve
have the bend that Casey Gaynor's pitches did on Sunday, but Del
Vento was more than adequate.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight teams in the Little League World Series
tournament, four U.S. teams and four international teams. Each team
plays a minimum of three games. The two teams with the best records
from each pool then play one another other for their respective
championship on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Del Vento struck out three of the four
batters he faced, allowing only a bloop single to Seth Anderson. In
the second and third innings, he was just as dominant, retiring six
straight batters, striking out three of them. And he just kept
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   The Boise pitcher, Devon Biddinger, also had outstanding stuff
Monday night. He allowed only two singles through the first three
innings with three strikeouts and no walks. He proceeded to retire
the side in order in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Biddinger unraveled in the fifth inning, but Toms River failed
to exploit the situation and scored only once, Chris Fontenelli,
the shortstop, coming home on a wild pitch with the bases loaded.
Toms River loaded the bases again with one out, but did no further
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the sixth inning Toms River finally had the breakout
that everyone had been waiting for, scoring three runs on four
hits. The key hit was Casey Gaynor's two-run single coming after
Campesi drove in a run with a single.
</P>
<P>
   While most teams have only relatives and close friends cheering
for them, Toms River has an entire town rooting for the team here.
Or at least it has seemed so through their first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Toms River's fans were clad in their trademark
``Beast of the East'' T-shirts and occupied an entire section in
the stands. Their boisterous chants, ``Beast is back!'' and ``Let's
go East!'' intimidated the Phenix City players, the Alabama coach
said after Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people up there in the stands don't have any kids
on the team,'' said Debbie Fontenelli, the mother of Chris. ``It's
pride. We're so proud of them and we're proud of where we come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Chris was not on the squad, but his mother came to
Williamsport anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent us,'' she said. ``That's us out there in those
12-year-old kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Kyle Tidwell's grand slam in the top of the
sixth capped a Phenix City comeback from a four-run deficit and
gave it a 5-4 victory over Brownsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The home run to center came on a 1-0 count with one out and just
cleared the glove of the leaping 5-foot-8-inch outfielder Sean
Veza. Tidwell said he hit a fastball from Lance Lynn that came
across the middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the international bracket Monday, Puerto Rico beat Victoria,
British Columbia, 6-4, and Osaka, Japan, beat Ramstein Air Force
Base, Germany, 5-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
