<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ISMAIL EXPECTED TO PLAY AGAINST BRONCOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. AND RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Receiver Raghib Ismail, offensive guard
Tony Hutson and cornerback Charlie Williams are expected to make
their preseason debuts for the Cowboys this week after being
sidelined for the first three games with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail (sprained shoulder) and Williams (fractured wrist) should
be in the starting lineup for Sunday's matchup against the Denver
Broncos. Hutson (sprained knee) should help the backup offensive
line, which has been maligned for a poor preseason performance.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is expected to fill the void at right cornerback in
place of Deion Sanders (toe) and Kevin Smith (back), who are out
with injuries. Rookie free agent Duane Hawthorne has started at the
position opposite left cornerback Kevin Mathis the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey said he was unclear on the prospects of guard
Everett McIver (knee) and running back Beau Morgan (toe) for the
Broncos game. Both are expected to practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are awaiting word on the status of cornerback Kevin
Smith, who remains in Dallas getting therapy on a ruptured disk in
his back.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Jim Maurer said Smith had an appointment Monday with Dr.
Andrew Dossett and that he would get a progress report Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   It all has Gailey unsure of when Smith will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reacted positively to the treatment'' last week, Gailey
said. ``But where that puts him I don't know. We'll find out more
when we talk to the doctor.'' GAILEY EVALUATES
</P>
<P>
   Tight end David LaFleur, linebacker Nate Hemsley and defensive
tackle Darren Benson saw their first action of the preseason
Saturday in the 34-14 loss to the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey offered observations of each.
</P>
<P>
   About LaFleur, the team's staring tight end who has been out
since minicamp after with having back and ankle surgeries, Gailey
said, ``He did some good things. It was obvious he was rusty. But
he benefited from having played in the game. I am looking forward
to him practicing this week and continuing in installing him back
into the offensive process.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur had two catches for 10 yards in the game, including a
6-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsley, who is fighting for a roster spot at outside
linebacker, has been out since fracturing his ankle during training
camp last year. He had four tackles in the game.
</P>
<P>
   `He played pretty good,'' Gailey said. ``He got kicked in the
other ankle, but it was not bad. He did OK on special teams. It
will be good to continue watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   That Benson missed the first three games was a huge
disappointment to Cowboys, because they were considering him as
candidate to make up for the loss of the suspended Leon Lett.
Benson, who missed the 1998 season with a knee injury, has been
slowed for much of camp by knee swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Benson had a fragmented performance against the
Patriots, despite
</P>
<P>
   recording five tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was off and on as well,'' Gailey said. ``He did some good
things at the point of attack. But at times he was a little high.
He has to work back into things.'' HE'S ALL-PRO ... WHEN HE PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Quentin Coryatt has yet to appear in a Cowboys
preseason game since being acquired from Indianapolis through free
agency. And he's not expected to play this week against Denver,
either.
</P>
<P>
   While Coryatt continues to nurse a strained hamstring and
Achilles', second-year strong-side linebacker Darren Hambrick is
impressing Chan Gailey and his coaching staff at a position that
has Coryatt's name all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick ``has made the most of his opportunity,'' Gailey said.
``He still has a lot to learn, but he's playing hard and playing
well.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of their careers, Coryatt and Hambrick are no
comparison. As Gailey put it, ``When Quentin Coryatt is healthy and
playing ... I don't know if he's made All-Pro or not, but when I've
coached against him, he's been All-Pro. Hambrick might get there
one day, but it's not fair to compare the two right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
