<HEADLINE>
GLAUS IS SURPRISE HOME RUN LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Question: Who leads the Anaheim Angels in home
runs this season?
</P>
<P>
   Hint: It's not Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon or Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the season, if anyone would have guessed Troy Glaus,
they would be right. They also would have had to know the Angels
would have serious problems in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have affected the Angels' three main home run hitters,
leaving Glaus ahead with 22. Vaughn is second on the team with 21
and Garret Anderson third with 17.
</P>
<P>
   This season is Glaus' first full year in the majors, but he
played in too many games in 1998 to be eligible for Rookie of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   If Glaus continues at his current pace, he'll finish with 29
homers. But he says it wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never satisfied,'' said Glaus, 22. ``The day I'm
satisfied is the day I drive in every baserunner that's out there.
That's not realistic, I know. I'd be satisfied right now if we were
in first place and going to the playoffs, because if we're in first
place and going to the playoffs, I'm doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost doesn't count: Ramon Ortiz will not face his idol, Pedro
Martinez of the Boston Red Sox. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz and Martinez, who were teammates on a winter-league team
in their native Domincan Republic, will pitch tonight _ Ortiz
against the Blue Jays and Martinez against the Twins. On a normal
five-day rotation, that means a head-to-head matchup Sunday in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Thursday's off-day, Angels manager Terry Collins
decided to push everyone back a day, meaning Ortiz will start
Monday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   On the injury front: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina made about 10-12
throws to first base during batting practice Monday, but his sore
right shoulder prevents him from throwing with any zip.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina will probably need a couple of more days before
returning to the lineup. He was hit by a pitch on the right side of
his back and also was hit on the right shoulder by a pickoff throw
while diving back to first.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that an off-balanced throw after fielding a grounder and
the combination forced him to change his throwing mechanics to
compensate.
</P>
</TEXT>
