<HEADLINE>
MULTIPLE-CHOICE QUERIES FOR MULTIPLE-MILLIONAIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Job Seeker,
</P>
<P>
   The sports fans of Southern California thank you for your
interest in the position of Team Owner. We have an opening in our
Professional Football division and might soon be making changes in
our Professional Basketball, Professional Hockey and Professional
Baseball divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Our Human Resources Department is eager to consider any
applicant with a billion dollars and a desire for fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   As you might know, if you happen to follow sports, we have
endured some bad luck with owners recently, marked by chronic
absenteeism (Rupert Murdoch), lack of commitment (Michael Eisner),
meddlesomeness (Jerry Buss) and what have you (Donald Sterling).
Also, there were a couple of petty thefts, perpetrated by Al Davis
and Georgia Frontiere, who stole the Raiders and Rams from us.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to improve our hiring practices, we are now
requiring each applicant to fill out the following questionnaire,
so we can better judge whether you possess the necessary skills,
character and ambition. Please use blue or black ink.
</P>
<P>
   _My principal residence is (a) in the Los Angeles area; (b) in
the Anaheim area; (c) in a city I named after myself.
</P>
<P>
   _My annual income is (a) $1 to $99 million dollars; (b) more
money than God; (c) more money than Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   _When my team is in action, I prefer to sit (a) among the
everyday fans in the bleachers; (b) among the major sponsors in the
luxury suites; (c) in the boardroom of one of my more important
companies.
</P>
<P>
   _I like to spice up my hot dog with (a) mustard; (b) mustard,
ketchup, relish, onions and hot peppers; (c) what is this ``hot
dog''?
</P>
<P>
   _Turn me loose in a sporting goods store, and I'll make a
beeline for (a) the skull-cracking rubber of the hockey pucks; (b)
the hardy leather scent of the new baseball mitts; (c) the
squeezeably soft fleece of the ski jackets.
</P>
<P>
   _My favorite sports memory involves (a) Kirk Gibson's home run;
(b) Magic Johnson's first NBA title; (c) a cheerleader, Dad's best
bottle of scotch and the back seat of Dad's Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   _Just the word, ``ballpark,'' puts me in mind of (a) the
carefree days of my youth; (b) a cathedral, a museum and a national
park all rolled into one; (c) revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   _My guiding principle when it comes to sports management could
be summed up as (a) ``there's a lot to be said for tradition''; (b)
``if sports guys knew anything, they wouldn't be in sports''; (c)
``whatever the boys in Marketing tell me today.''
</P>
<P>
   _The most important thing a team provides for its community is
(a) something to rally around in an era of ethnic, political and
economic division; (b) an infusion of money and jobs; (c) an
infinite variety of colorful hats to buy.
</P>
<P>
   _It's vital to preserve (a) the history of the franchise; (b)
the continuity that creates organizational pride; (c) tonight's
wieners so they can be served tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   _Any owner who really wants to win a championship (a) had better
be in it for the long haul; (b) must be willing to lose money; (c)
ought to look harder at more profitable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   _An owner smart enough to put proven experts in his
player-personnel office (a) is going to be a winner; (b) is an
idiot if he doesn't listen to them; (c) needs to remind them who's
the billionaire around here or pretty soon they'll believe they run
the place.
</P>
<P>
   _I vow to bring my team (a) a superstar player; (b) a superstar
coach; (c) a superstation.
</P>
<P>
   _I promise never to (a) quibble over a few thousand dollars if
the superstar is going to leave town as a result; (b) hold up the
taxpayers for the cost of a new stadium; (c) make promises.
</P>
<P>
   _A family of four (a) will never forget an evening together at
the ballpark; (b) should be able to go to a game without it costing
an arm and a leg; (c) is missing something if it doesn't top off
the experience with a stretch limo ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Please drop off your completed questionnaire with our
receptionist or mail it in the enclosed envelope. Applicants
listing annual incomes of only $1 to $99 million might be
redirected to our College Sports Boosters division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
