<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMER MIGHT MISS SEASON OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When All-American receiver Danny Farmer left
Saturday's scrimmage in a wheelchair, his injured ankle wrapped
like a mummy's limb, the Bruins termed it a mild sprain and listed
Farmer as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   They should have said game-to-game.
</P>
<P>
   Further examination revealed Farmer has a badly sprained left
ankle and might not play in UCLA's season opener Sept. 4 against
Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be a couple weeks,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
``He'll be back, but when we're not sure. I'm being very optimistic
in saying two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer injured the ankle on the sixth play of the scrimmage when
DeShaun Foster accidentally blocked Jason Stephens into Farmer's
leg, and his ankle rolled. He jogged off the field, but the pain
increased after icing. At that point, he requested a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   The examination showed a high sprain _ above the ankle bone _
and those take longer to heal than sprains on/below the bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident I'll play, but I'm always a positive
person,'' Farmer said. ``I think it'll heal fast, but I'm not the
doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   With Freddie Mitchell, Brian Poli-Dixon and Brad Melsby, the
Bruins are deep enough at receiver to absorb Farmer's injury for a
game or two. But they are not deep in the secondary, which makes
safety Jason Stephens' sprained right knee potentially more
troublesome than Farmer's ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to put it that way, but (the secondary) is a weakness
as opposed to a strength,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens is questionable for Boise State. If he can't play, the
two options at strong safety are sophomore Julius Williams, a
converted cornerback, and junior John Hall, a hurdler who recently
joined the football team.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup changes: After shuffling the lineup in response to the
disabled parking suspensions, Toledo released his first depth chart
Monday. Of the 44 players listed (excluding suspended players),
only seven are seniors.
</P>
<P>
   At outside linebacker, true freshman Asi Faoa has moved ahead of
junior Santi Hall, a converted defensive end who was suspended from
spring practice for violating team rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with Asi, and Santi did not participate in
spring,'' Toledo said. ``He was working on academics, and I'm
trying to make a point with him. He'd better buckle down.''
</P>
<P>
   Melsby, a senior, is the No. 1 split end. Last year's starter,
junior Poli-Dixon, had a shoddy first week but played well in
Saturday's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Other depth-chart developments: Freshman Mike Seidman, from
Westlake High, is the No. 4 tight end, although that could change
when Seidman learns the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is starting over Jermaine Lewis at tailback, and with
Durell Price suspended, Matt Stanley is the No. 1 fullback.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension-depleted offensive line features (from left
tackle to right tackle) freshman Blake Worley, senior Matt Phelan,
sophomore Troy Danoff, freshman Mike Saffer and junior Brian Polak.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Joey Strycula, the holder, is starting at free safety,
while freshman Joe Hunter and senior Jason Bell are the first-team
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Holland and Ken Kocher are the No. 1 defensive tackles,
with Anthony Fletcher and Steve Morgan in close pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Rusty Williams is starting at Hall's defensive end spot
opposite Kenyon Coleman. Williams' performance may determine
whether Hall moves back to end when the suspended linebackers
return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
