<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONGRESSIONAL-MYOPIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONGRESSIONAL MYOPIA ON FOREIGN AID
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Foreign aid is not among Washington's most popular causes. But
it happens to be one of the more effective investments in long-term
global security that America can make. Yet Congress now proposes to
cut some $2 billion from President Clinton's already modest $14.6
billion foreign aid request for next year, much of it from crucial
crisis prevention programs. When the foreign aid bill goes to a
House-Senate conference committee next month, the Republican
congressional leadership should work to reverse these shortsighted
cuts. What cannot be restored then should be included in a
supplemental foreign aid bill later this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Today's foreign aid dollars can help prevent tomorrow's wars, as
Clinton noted in a speech to the Veterans of Foreign Wars earlier
this month. That surely applies to $1.3 billion promised to Israel
and the Palestinian Authority for meeting the security costs of the
Wye peace agreement and improving the living standards of the
Palestinian people. Yet for the second budget year, Congress has
withheld financing for this program.
</P>
<P>
   There are also obvious dividends for American security in
programs designed to help Russia dismantle its Cold War nuclear
arsenal, safeguard bomb plutonium and employ former weapons
scientists in new fields. Yet both the House and Senate want to
impose steep cuts in these areas and would also trim money for
supporting reform in other former Soviet states. The House would
also cut appropriations for World Bank aid to the very poorest
countries and continues to hold up paying America's back dues to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Some American foreign aid money has been wasted in the past. But
that is no reason to starve the entire program. congressional
opponents argue that approving Clinton's full request for foreign
aid would violate current budget caps. But such arguments never
stop legislators eager to add defense funding or vote unwise tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing nuclear dangers in Russia, supporting peace agreements
in the Middle East and Africa and helping the poor emerge from
poverty are sound investments. Congress should heed Clinton's
appeal and providing adequate money for these programs this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
