<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS BACK HATE CRIME UNITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Reacting to the racist shooting rampage in the
San Fernando Valley, state legislators, district attorneys and
religious leaders threw support behind a bill Monday that would
earmark $5 million to add and train hate crime prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Under AB 741, the money would be used to assign individual
prosecutors to handle every stage of a hate crime case. In small
counties plagued by hate crimes, the money could be used to
establish hate crime prosecution units and training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate crimes are an assault on an entire community _ they
injure every one of us,'' Assemblyman Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys,
said after a news conference to rally support for the legislation.
``That's why we all must work together to combat crimes of hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles District Attorney Gil Garcetti also urged bipartisan
support for the bill, authored by Assemblyman Rod Pacheco,
R-Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This funding could significantly help the Los Angeles County
DA's office expand its hate crime prosecution unit,'' said Jim
Provenza, Garcetti's legislative liaison in Sacramento. ``Our five
DAs in the unit now are overworked. We have one-third of the
state's population in Los Angeles and a proportionate amount of
hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely need this funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco said the arson fires at three synagogues in Sacramento
this year, the killing of two gay men in Redding and, most
recently, the Valley shooting rampage are the types of ``horrors''
that inspired the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As racial acts of violence continue, we must better equip our
police and prosecutors, ensuring these criminals are punished to
the fullest extent of the law,'' Pacheco said.
</P>
<P>
   Provenza said the success in such legislation in the past is an
indication that the funding is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill really addresses the fact that you can better
prosecute cases with a specialized DA,'' Provenza said. ``It has
worked dramatically on sex crimes and domestic violence. There's no
question it will work here.''
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting the bill was Sacramento County District Attorney
Jan Scully, rabbis from the Congregation Beth Shalom, and members
of Crime Victims United of California.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
