<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE IS FEELING DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC's defense is fed up with hearing that it is
the team's question mark, especially after stuffing the offense
during much of last weekend's first scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are mad,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno said. ``We have
a lot of guys returning and people say the defense is the
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, one of those is USC coach Paul Hackett, who said the
defense had ``flip-flopped'' roles with the offense, which now has
the most experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been saying the defense is the weakness, but still the
offense can't do much on us,'' Moreno said. ``We hope we can
continue that in (the season opener against) Hawaii. We have
something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell update: Although Hackett hopes to hear some news today,
there is a growing feeling that USC might not get junior college
transfer Craig Mitchell at all this season.
</P>
<P>
   USC needs the wide receiver's JC transcripts before the school
year starts next week, and nothing happened Monday that got
Mitchell any closer to completing the necessary paperwork. If the
paperwork is not completed this week, Mitchell will be ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he does show up, it will be nearly impossible for him to
crack into the top-five receiver rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Nazel to play: Hackett announced that freshman Omar Nazel of
Oakland has moved from linebacker to defensive end and will not
redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he will contribute immediately,'' Hackett said.
``If a guy like Omar can rush the passer and play special teams,
that's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The news wasn't all good for Nazel. He sprained his foot in
practice Monday and underwent X-rays. His status for the rest of
the week was not determined.
</P>
<P>
   Man of Steele: Linebacker Markus Steele had his first day of
contact and didn't look too rusty, shutting down several running
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of plays I was happy with,'' Steele said. ``It
felt real good to go out there and make contact with a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele has set his sights on winning the starting weakside
linebacker position by the season opener Sept. 4 against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the main goal,'' Steele said. ``To get a starting
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele is contesting sophomores Henry Wallace and Darryl Knight
for the starting weakside position. Knight has been suspended from
the Hawaii game, however, for poor academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Scrimmage time: USC will hold a closed scrimmage at the Coliseum
today, its final scrimmage of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said a focus from an offensive standpoint will be wide
receivers Windrell Hayes and Marcell Allmond, who were injured and
missed all or most of the first scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Frank Strong, who sat out the first scrimmage with a
bruised thigh, will also play today.
</P>
<P>
   The defense will also be put to the test, practicing a majority
of time against only the first-and-second string offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0101EDT &QL; 
