<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Some four hours before Monday night's series opener at
Shea Stadium, Jeff Bagwell had a bitter, painful flashback.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bagwell opened the Astros' clubhouse door at Shea only to find
the small, dank visitor's locker room overcome with what looked
like more reporters than there were fans at Pro Player Stadium in
Florida only two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this, 1986 all over again?'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the night looked something like it. It felt something
like it. It sounded something like it.
</P>
<P>
   And unfortunately for the Astros, at least in the opener of this
potentially huge three-game set against the Mets, it ended
something like it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came up clutch, while the Astros let one slip away in
the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have a prejudiced point of view, but they hit two
balls off the handle that happened to fall fair in the inning,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said of the 3-2 Mets win. ``It was
lucky. That's all it was, really.''
</P>
<P>
   And, really, luck might well have had something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Astros starter Scott Elarton wiggled out of a few
jams through eight innings, while Matt Mieske slammed a long ball
and Carl Everett added a practically Hatcher-esque clutch shot in
the seventh to send the game into the ninth tied at two.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were in a good spot, and reliever Jay Powell seemed
to be hitting his spots well enough. Better still, by the time the
Astros stepped to the plate in the ninth, the outfield scoreboard
showed a 6-2 Braves win over the division-contending Reds, and the
Astros seemed to have the incentive to do something huge.
</P>
<P>
   Things hardly could have looked better. There were two Astros on
and two out, but then Lance Berkman struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to be tight against those guys,'' Bagwell
said. ``How much tighter can it get than 2-2 in the bottom of the
ninth? We were right there.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, oh, the luck. Mets center fielder Darryl Hamilton got
the Mets going when he doubled down the line after getting jammed
and breaking his bat on the pitch from Powell. Two batters later,
pinch hitter Matt Franco blooped a two-out single between Mieske
and diving shortstop Tim Bogar in short left field.
</P>
<P>
   Ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's like we always say: You don't want to be good;
you just want to be lucky,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said.
``There was a weird, weird set of events in that inning.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed weird. You might even want to call it lucky.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros have to realize that they have been the
unluckiest and seen the weirdest of occurrences happen in the games
they most needed to win. That perception needs to change, and time
is running out if it's going to happen before the playoffs _
assuming there is a postseason for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Astros' first try against one of the other
contending NL teams _ Cincinnati, Atlanta, Arizona and New York _
since getting swept in three games at Atlanta two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   This was a chance to begin turning things in their favor against
the good teams. But it ended much the same way as so many others.
Since June 14, the Astros have dropped 17 of their last 21 games
against the Reds, Diamondbacks, Braves and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it has just been bad luck. But with only 26 games
remaining in the season and seven of those against the Mets and
Reds, the Astros not only need to find a way to start changing
their luck, they need to secure a playoff berth, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we just want to get in,'' Biggio said. ``We're not
looking at who we're playing. We just want to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not a bad Astros performance by any stretch. But it was
not good. This was not a self-inflicted loss like pretty much all
three were in Atlanta two weeks ago. But it was a loss nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, given the electric atmosphere and hostile crowd, the
Astros handled the conditions well.
</P>
<P>
   There were at least as many fistfights in the stands as there
were runs scored. The tone of the night was set early, when a
tribute to Mets outfielder Bobby Bonilla played on the big screen
and it was was resoundingly booed.
</P>
<P>
   The 39,292 fans were on their feet for every pitch in the final
innings and shouted more than a few obscenities in the Astros'
direction. Tensions were high.
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, the Astros looked unshakable, coming back
from the 2-0 deficit, getting the strong effort from Elarton and
playing solid defense throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how it gets when they have winning teams here,'' said
Biggio, who grew up within shouting distance of the big city.
``This is what you get. This is getting to be like it was in the
mid-'80s.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like it. It was the perfect stage on which the Astros
could have made a big statement. Instead, they just had an ugly
flashback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
