<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BLAST RANGERS, 21-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This could be the Texas Rangers' best team in
their 28-year history, and yet their public _ especially the
gathering who attended Monday night's embarrassment at The Ballpark
in Arlington _ seems to have a hard time getting excited about this
ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, the Rangers simply won't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees applied yet another good, ol'-fashioned
country beating to the Rangers, and this 21-3 eyesore likely
convinced more of the masses that this postseason will be no
different than the previous two for Arlington's best.
</P>
<P>
   Must the Rangers offer their public some hope of beating the
defending World Series champions in the postseason to gain better
support than Monday night's gathering of 38,024?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Rangers left fielder Rusty Greer said.
``You're asking the wrong person there. All we can do is go out and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who eliminated the Rangers' during the 1996 and '98
Division Series, wasted no time establishing their superiority with
a six-run first inning against right-hander John Burkett (4-7).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the evening was only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost to the Yankees for the 18th time in 26
regular-season games since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees amassed a season-high 23 hits en route to 21 runs,
which were the most ever allowed by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Nos. 8 and 9 hitters _ third baseman Scott Brosius
and catcher Joe Girardi _ experienced their most explosive evenings
in terms of run production. Girardi went 4-for-6 and drove in a
career-best seven runs. Brosius went 4-for-6 and drove in a
career-best six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett surrendered as many runs (eight) as outs recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Mike Venafro and right-hander Danny
Patterson each surrendered five runs on five hits during their
one-inning appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I don't have any answers,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``I know we made a lot of bad pitches, and they put a
lot of good swings on the ball. That's a bad combination. You put
it to bed and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers provided few highlights.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro hit his eighth home run in as many
games with his two-run, second-inning blast off left-hander Andy
Pettitte (11-9), and right-hander Tim Crabtree pitched a 1-2-3
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers _ one and all _ displayed their best short-term
memories in the clubhouse afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored 21 runs,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``It was
over awhile ago. We'll just come back tomorrow. We've done it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Monday night's events put a temporary halt on the
Rangers' recent run, which included a three-game sweep of Boston
and winning three of four from the Central Division-leading
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be asleep in an hour,'' Oates said after the game.
``We've played good baseball. We know we've got a good team. We'll
come back tomorrow and tee it up again. This wasn't the first time,
and it won't be the last time.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
