<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENA SUSPENDED WHILE DOWN IN ALBUQUERQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Angel Pena is hailed as the future catcher of the
Los Angeles Dodgers, but he was sent to the minors earlier because
of lackadaisical play and a poor work ethic. Now, he's been
suspended for seven games from Triple-A Albuquerque for violating
team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he hasn't had a chance to
talk with Pena, nor Albuquerque manager Mike Scioscia, so he didn't
want to discuss how this could affect a Sept. 1 call-up.
</P>
<P>
   Pena, 24, is considered one of the top catching prospects in
baseball. But he raised some eyebrows when, with the Dodgers'
backup job on the line, he arrived at spring training overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball officials have expressed concern whether Pena will
be anything more than a major-league backup because they don't
think he has the work ethic necessary to develop into an everyday
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension went into effect Sunday and limits Pena's
involvement with the team. Bill Geivett, Dodgers assistant to the
general manager/director of player personnel, handed down the
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel Pena violated team rules that are consistent with the
major-league rules,'' Geivett said. ``It's something we're going to
handle internally.''
</P>
<P>
   Geivett and Dodgers senior vice president Tom Lasorda went to
Albuquerque and talked with Pena. He hasn't played since Aug. 10,
when he strained his elbow making a throw. Geivett wouldn't
elaborate on the situation, but sources said Pena's talking back
wore on the coaching staff while general manager Kevin Malone was
in town to watch Albuquerque in preparation for Sept. 1 call-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Malone and Johnson said earlier this season they were confident
Pena could be the Dodgers' everyday catcher if Todd Hundley was
injured, and Pena got that chance when Hundley spent 11 days
working with coach Rick Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   Pena didn't impress. He hit .208 and struck out 24 times in 120
at-bats. He also rarely came to the ballpark early for extra
hitting with the other backup players. Pena also committed three
errors and had four passed balls.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing Pena's demotion earlier this month, Johnson said,
``I was seeing balls get by him and I saw him dropping balls. I
said, `I have a higher set of standards for you.' I said, `Go out,
come back and be the kind of catcher you can be. You showed signs
you can do things up here, but you also showed signs you're not
ready to be one of the most valuable players on the field. ... It
looked like you didn't want it that bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hair-raising experience: How revered is Dodgers right-hander
Chan Ho Park in his native Korea? Well, Park had his head shaved by
his brother last week, but it wasn't done until 4 a.m. because the
two were debating the ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut my hair off to show I have control of myself,'' Park
said. ``So many people look at me back in Korea. I couldn't cut it,
but that's the wrong thinking. I thought that before I did it. I
was scared to cut my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end: Johnson said right-hander Robinson Checo, on the
disabled list since July 29 with a right groin strain, will be
re-examined because he's still experiencing discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're talking that it could be some kind of rupture,
real mild,'' Johnson said. ``It's not healing. I was hoping we'd
had him back. I'd like to look at him again.'' ... The Dodgers and
Albuquerque signed a one-year player development contract to keep
the Triple-A affiliate in New Mexico.... Johnson said the Dodgers
may promote minor-league pitcher Greg Gagne or Jeff Williams later
this week. ``We can look at all the options available to us this
year that might impact us next year,'' Johnson said.... Monday's
game was delayed 2 hours, 10 minutes by rain.... For the second
straight day Jose Vizcaino started at third in place of ailing
Adrian Beltre (ankle).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
