<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOND-ACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BOND ACT MISCHIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   The mass confusion caused by Albany's annual last-minute budget
scrambles often provides camouflage for mischievous legislation
that nobody notices until well after the deed is done. This year
was no exception. The budget passed earlier this month includes
subtle changes in the rules governing the disposition of certain
money under the 1996 environmental bond act.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the changes are fundamentally at odds with
the spirit of the act because they would divert money that was
originally aimed at fighting water pollution to economic
development. Spokesmen for Joseph Bruno, the Senate majority
leader, who inserted the new language, say the changes are minor.
Even the most cursory textual analysis suggests that the
environmentalists are right.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is $30 million in money earmarked under the bond act's
implementing legislation to help small businesses attain
``compliance with environmental laws and regulations or other
pollution avoidance activities.'' In plain language, this meant
that the purpose of the money was to help small businesses remove
pollution from their wastewater, through new technology or other
means. Bruno's revision deletes any reference to ``small
businesses'' and adds a provision allowing the $30 million to be
spent on ``water or wastewater infrastructure.'' Again, in plain
language, this means that the money could now be used by cities and
towns to expand their water supplies to accommodate new business
activity by large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's main motive is to encourage economic development in
upstate New York by providing industry with a secure water supply,
a commendable and defensible objective. What is neither commendable
nor defensible is the fact that he wants to pay for new water
supplies with money that was designed to clean up existing water
supplies. Furthermore, when the citizens of New York approved the
$1.75 billion Clean Air, Clean Water Bond Act three years ago, they
were voting to clean up the environment, not to subsidize new
industry. There are other programs for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the State Assembly nor Gov. George Pataki objected to
the new language, though they should have. Both felt bound by an
unofficial agreement giving the Republican Senate, the Democratic
Assembly and the governor discretionary authority over slices of
the bond act money. The Assembly has so far spent much of its slice
to replace old coal-fired boilers in New York City's public
schools. That is clearly consistent with the bond act's
environmental purposes. Bruno's disposition of his slice of the pie
is not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
