<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-EXPANSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. BID UNDER NFL'S REVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NFL expansion committee is scheduled to meet
Sept. 9 in Washington, D.C., to review Los Angeles' mired bid to
acquire the league's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is not expected to take any formal action six days
prior to the deadline the NFL gave Los Angeles to finalize its
expansion bid. But it hopes to evaluate the process on the
deadline's eve so it can later make a recommendation to the full
ownership at an Oct. 6 meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The committee could meet again before, or simply have a
conference call, to finalize its recommendation prior to the full
membership meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated because of a lack of public funding to assist the
Coliseum expansion bid, the NFL announced earlier this month it
would no longer deal exclusively with the Exposition Park site
prior to the Sept. 15 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   That gave new life to former prospective sites at the city of
Carson and Hollywood Park, if little opportunity to finalize
11th-hour bids prior to the deadline. In Orange County, there has
been discussion of a stadium in the El Toro area, and Padres owner
John Moores has approached the league about a possible stadium in
the Irvine area.
</P>
<P>
   No longer maidens when it comes to dealing with the NFL, Carson
city officials are taking a guarded approach to their latest
contact with the league.
</P>
<P>
   With the L.A. Coliseum proposal for an expansion team teetering
over public-money demands, league officials have asked Carson for a
letter of interest regarding an expansion franchise and stadium
site. The league has made the same request of city officials at two
other possible sites, in Inglewood (Hollywood Park) and Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Carson city councilman Daryl Sweeney said the city will submit a
letter of interest, ``but no one plans to get optimistic,'' he
said. ``There has been contact, but it's just been generalities.
They want to know if we're still interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the Coliseum is remotely close to a comprehensive, final
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles area and state officials have been trying to rescue
the Coliseum bid with a new plan for subsidizing parking
construction at Exposition Park. The plan now being discussed would
allow the team to keep parking revenue, with the parking structures
being paid off by incremental taxes generated by the team and games
played at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, bonds were proposed for the structures that would be
paid off largely from game-parking fees. NFL Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue said the league was concerned if the team was not allowed
to collected the parking fees _ in addition to paying a proposed $5
million-per-year stadium lease _ it would be difficult for it to be
financially successful in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   When the league established the Sept. 15 deadline for Los
Angeles, it said if the city failed to finalize an acceptable bid
that Houston would be awarded a team. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Long Beach Press-Telegram staff writer Bob Keisser contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
