<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BLAST RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This series between the New York Yankees and
the Texas Rangers is being touted as a possible playoff preview. If
that's the case, the Rangers might want concede the baseball and
challenge the Yankees to checkers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees crushed the Rangers Monday night, 21-3, while
totaling 23 hits, the most hits by the Yankees since Aug. 25, 1984;
it was the most runs ever allowed by the Rangers. Joe Girardi drove
in seven runs on four hits, Scott Brosius had four hits and six
runs batted in, and Tino Martinez had four hits and four RBI. No
Texas pitchers were hurt, but all were thoroughly embarrassed,
combining for 199 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of those games when everything steamrolls and
every ball you hit finds a hole,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Joe Torre, ``It's not like you're trying to rub it
in, but you just can't go up to the plate and stand there.''
</P>
<P>
   This region recorded 24 consecutive days of temperature over 100
degrees, a phenomenon manifested in the hardness of infield within
the Ballpark in Arlington. The dirt has been baked, and ground
balls skitter along the infield as if bouncing on a polished
gymnasium floor. Most rollers skip through the infield for hits, a
partial explanation for the 33 hits posted by both teams Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas pitching staff can take most of the credit, however,
for it succeeded in revitalizing the Yankees' offense. The Yankees
had averaged about three runs a game for a week and a half, most of
their regulars imbedded in offensive slumps. ``We better start
scoring some runs,'' Shane Spencer said Sunday, looking ahead to
the Texas series, ``or the Rangers are going to kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are a great offensive team, ranked second in the
league in runs scored, and over all they are better than last year,
Torre said before the game. ``It's because they're playing
defense,'' he said. ``Yesterday, I investigated it a little bit,
and that's the difference; it makes the pitching better.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the additions of first baseman Rafael Palmeiro and
the All-Star reliever Jeff Zimmerman, even with the luxury of
having Todd Zeile and Royce Clayton for a full season, there is a
basic truth at the heart of any series between Texas and the
Yankees: the Rangers' starting pitching, stacked with right-handers
possessing mediocre stuff, creates a feeding frenzy among the
Yankees' left-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Even their right-handed batters feasted on the slop John Burkett
threw Monday night. After Chuck Knoblauch walked to lead off the
game, Paul O'Neill, Bernie Williams and Martinez singled, Martinez
driving in two runs. Ricky Ledee walked before Brosius and Girardi
_ the Yankees most deeply mired in slumps _ hit back-to-back
singles, Brosius driving in a run, Girardi two.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brosius' first hit with a runner in scoring position
since Aug. 8, Girardi's first since July 28. The Yankees led, 6-0,
after a half inning, and if the Rangers had carried over any
confidence from their consecutive victories against the Yankees in
June, it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte (11-9) gave up a two-run home run to Palmeiro in
the second inning and began pitching tentatively; admittedly
distracted by the presence of family when he pitches in Texas,
Pettitte had never beaten the Rangers in this park before,
compiling an 0-3 record with a 16.05 earned run average. But the
Yankees' hitters kept slamming away at Burkett and the relievers
who followed. ``It only took 21 runs and five years for me to get a
win here,'' Pettitte joked later.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee and Girardi drove in runs in the second inning, Burkett
departing after Girardi's hit. So began a parade of Texas
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi drove in another run in the fifth; Yankees 9, Texas 2.
In the sixth, Brosius bashed a three-run home run to cap a five-run
rally; Yankees 14, Texas 2. In the seventh, both teams began using
bench players, but that didn't slow the flood of Yankee runs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams doubled home a run, and after a walk and another
run-scoring single by Brosius, the bases were loaded for Girardi _
who smashed a line drive into the right-center-field gap, his
triple clearing the bases. The day after catcher Jorge Posada had a
double, triple and home run and came within a single of having the
first cycle by a Yankees catcher in 59 years, Girardi had a single,
double and triple. Yankees 19, Rangers 2.
</P>
<P>
   There would be one last outburst. Luis Sojo doubled to open the
top of the eighth, and with two outs, Martinez blasted a two-run
homer, accounting for the last hit and runs for the Yankees. They
went down in order in the ninth, the last out made by Knoblauch,
who had seven plate appearances, drawing two walks while going 0
for 5 and making the last out in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, scheduled to start Tuesday, rolled his eyes at
Knoblauch to make a facetious pitcher's lament: you scored all
those runs on a night I didn't pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only one thinking about you,'' Knoblauch said. ``I'm
getting my five hits tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
