<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-JULIE-FIRED-AZR &LR;      08-24 2826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIE-FIRED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REPUBLIC' COLUMNIST'S DISMISSAL A STORY OF UNTRACEABLE SOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID PARRISH, MICHAEL MURPHY  and MAUREEN JENKINS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For five years, Julie Amparano was one of the most
respected writers at ``The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   When she became the paper's Life section columnist in July, she
quickly wrote a string of poignant and compelling true-life stories
about people in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   There was the White racist who at 25 discovered he was half
Hispanic. The gay man living in an intolerant neighborhood. The
upscale woman visiting the downscale restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly, Amparano was fired last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a front page note to its readers on Saturday, ``The
Republic'' revealed that some of the people quoted in Amparano's
column were untraceable.
</P>
<P>
   During two days of searching last week, ``Republic'' editors
reviewed 11 out of 17 of Amparano's thrice-weekly columns she wrote
since July. A total of 65 people were identified in the columns.
The editors had questions on about 40 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 24 had uncommon names and were checked out. Four were
found.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the people named in the columns couldn't be traced,
including the former racist, the gay man and the upscale diner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel embarrassed and chagrined about this,'' Deputy Managing
Editor John D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How on earth could these columns have gotten into the paper?''
Senior Features Editor Susan Felt asked herself.
</P>
<P>
   Felt oversees the paper's Life section, and D'Anna is her
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano, 39, denied that some of the people in her column were
fictional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there; I went to different places of the town,
looking for people from different walks of life, and they're
real,'' Amparano said Monday morning while being interviewed on
KTAR-AM radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're saying that I should have seen the driver's license
. . . well, that changes the rules of the game. But I did what I
was told to do. I was told to be a fly on the wall, get
conversations, bring them into the paper, and that's what I've
done,'' Amparano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken people's names down, what they told me they did,
and put them in the pages of `The Republic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has just been very unfair, very unfair to my name
and credibility, and I'm out to prove it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano later issued a statement saying she was given
inadequate time, less than 24 hours, to produce the requested
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the demand was unfair from the onset,'' she
said. ``Nonetheless, all of my sources were credible and real
individuals with firsthand knowledge about the subjects they
discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   While being questioned by editors last week, Amparano
steadfastly denied any fabrication of people or events,
``Republic'' Managing Editor Julia Wallace and D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people quoted in her column, she told the editors,
were found while she was out in the community _ at parks,
bookstores or on street corners _ and could not be readily traced.
</P>
<P>
   D'Anna said he now views in a different light Amparano's
stories, which were filled with insightful quotes from everyday
people and powerful tales of injustice and racism in the Phoenix
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read things that were too good to be true,'' said D'Anna,
a friend of Amparano's for nearly 20 years. ``In hindsight, the
fact we were getting something that was so new and different and
fit so well into our goals, yeah, it clouded my judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations leveled against Amparano also raised concerns at
``The Republic'' about how well editors and reporters adhere to
journalistic procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who joined the ``Republic'' last December, said the
newspaper's staff needs to have a long conversation about ethics,
standards and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say we do not have enough safeguards in place to
prevent something like this from happening,'' Wallace said. ``Every
time something like this happens, it eats away at what we all
do.'' &QL; 
MEDIA EMBARRASSMENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amparano's firing is the latest in a string of embarrassments
for the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, ``Boston Globe'' columnist Patricia Smith was fired
for making up people and quotes, and another ``Globe'' columnist,
Mike Barnicle, resigned under suspicion that he had fabricated a
column about two children hospitalized with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Republic'' magazine writer Stephen Glass was fired because
of allegations that his articles contained 47 fabrications. The
``Cincinnati Enquirer'' fired a reporter who used stolen voice mail
to create what the paper later called ``untrue'' stories about
Chiquita Brands International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Arizona Republic,'' the accusations against Amparano
represent perhaps the biggest public embarrassment since publisher
Darrow ``Duke'' Tully was forced to resign in 1985 after it was
disclosed that his 30-year military career was bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Deni Elliott, director of the practical ethics center at the
University of Montana, said the news industry is largely to blame
for fabrications because of what gets rewarded and noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pressure in every newsroom to find the right quote,
to create stories, columns that fit together in a way that is
aesthetically pleasing,'' said Elliott, who has been a reporter and
ethics coach at the ``Philadelphia Enquirer.''``'' &QL; 
REASSESSED SYSTEMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last June, after Glass and Smith were fired by their
publications, ``Republic'' Reader Advocate Richard de Uriarte wrote
that the paper was reassessing its internal systems of
fact-checking and editorial review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we let some things slide into the newspaper, perhaps
because the writing was so compelling, so entertaining, that it
just had to be shared?'' de Uriarte asked in his 1998 column.
</P>
<P>
   After Wallace joined the paper last December, she started a
credibility committee. Reporters and editors have so far reviewed
the paper's corrections policy and discussed issues such as
stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   De Uriarte said the committee has been developing feedback
surveys that will be sent randomly to people quoted in the paper,
asking whether they were quoted correctly and whether the story was
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped to get it started this summer,'' de Uriarte said,
``but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With any safeguard system, editors still have to trust reporters
to act professionally, D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's practical for editors to re-report and
fact-check every story,'' he said. ``Editors do, however, have an
incredible responsibility to make sure _ and this is for the
reporter's protection, too _ that the facts are there as they
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Amparano had been one of ``The Republic's'' stars. Editors raved
about her work _ the ability to tell human stories through the eyes
of everyday people. Being Hispanic made her success all the more
sweet for the newspaper as it tried to appeal to more of the area's
growing Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was getting such good stuff,'' Wallace said. ``She was
really connecting with people, especially in the minority
community.'' &QL; 
A SOLID CAREER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining ``The Republic'' five years ago, Amparano had
put together a solid journalism career, including working at the
Associated Press, the ``Philadelphia Daily News'' and the ``Wall
Street Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   Amparano is Region 7 director of the National Association of
Hispanic Journalists _ an organization with 1,700 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street Journal'' editor Roger Rickless supervised
Amparano _ then Julie Amparano Lopez _ when she wrote on management
and workplace issues from the paper's New York bureau in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly were no ethical issues (that) arose during
that time,'' said Rickless, now Canada editor.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Schiffman, who edited Amparano's stories when she worked
for the Associated Press's San Francisco bureau in the mid-1980s,
said he didn't recall any questions being raised about her work.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is Amparano's hometown, and she returned to be closer to
her family, D'Anna said. &QL; 
COWORKERS REACT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A popular and engaging person, Amparano's dismissal was greeted
by editors and reporters with a mixture of shock, disbelief and
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed because I had high hopes for her
column and future work,'' said Pam Johnson, executive editor and
vice president for news at ``The Republic.'' ``What a
disappointment to the newspaper and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Graciela Sevilla said she hasn't seen any proof that
convinces her that Amparano made up people in her columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known and worked with her for five years, and I can't
think of another reporter I know who has higher ethical standards
than Julie. So this seems incredibly far-fetched to me,'' Sevilla
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Amparano is involved in local and national journalism
organizations, and has frequently talked to younger reporters about
the importance of journalistic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that she's a very capable and talented
journalist. So I don't see why she would have a need to do
something like this,'' Sevilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Richard Ruelas, who belongs to two Hispanic
journalists' organizations with Amparano, wasn't sure what to make
of the paper's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're completely out of character to the person I know _ In
my dealings with her, she was always professional and
hard-working,'' Ruelas said. ``I would like to think the paper I
work for did the right thing.'' &QL; 
``Republic'' photographer Paul F. Gero said he was shocked by
Amparano's firing: ``I've always known Julie to be a total
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Jodie Snyder said that in working with Amparano on at
least one story she had ``small doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the quotes did sound too good to be true.`` &QL; 
CONCERNS SPUR INQUIRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Republic'' editors began investigating Aug. 16 when a senior
newsroom staff member reported that there were rumors that Amparano
was making up some parts of her column. Reporters for other media
were possibly working on a story about it, the editors were told.
</P>
<P>
   The editors had their doubts, but decided to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I was still a believer (in Amparano),'' Wallace
said. ``I know there were a lot of people who were jealous that
Julie got the column. Maybe it was a smear job.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday afternoon, Wallace called Senior Editor David
Fritze to a private conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me her columns and pointed out that `Jennifer
Morgan' had appeared twice this year and a couple of times in (her)
stories several years ago,'' Fritze said. ``I was told to take
these columns and locate these people and see if they existed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fritze was metro editor, Amparano had been one of his
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired her and thought she had a lot of talent,'' Fritze
said. ``I had not seen anything in her columns to give me any
indications to question the integrity of her reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   That would quickly change.
</P>
<P>
   Fritze said he went through the columns and divided the names
into two groups.
</P>
<P>
   He bypassed investigating the first group, family members and
persons fully identicied by their organizations, reasoning that no
one would attempt to fabricate such people.
</P>
<P>
   The second list was of people who were identified only by a name
in the columns or with a vague job description.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Morgan _ both of them _ made the second list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to locate about 20 people,'' Fritze said.
</P>
<P>
   Fritze said he used phone books, operator directory assistance
and online services such as CDB Infoteck and AutoTrack that people
can be traced through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, well, worst case scenario, I run across some names
we can't track, but we find most people,'' Fritze said. ``As I went
along, I was stunned. I'd run name after name without getting any
hits.'' &QL; 
MISSING PERSONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because private investigators have broader access to state
government data, ``The Republic'' hired Scott Yeager of Faxon
Investigations to check 15 names through Motor Vehicle Department
records and voter registration files.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the investigations proved inconclusive. For example,
there were 31 other possible matches found for the name Susan Hall
_ identified in Amparano's Aug. 9 column as the down-and-out mother
of the 5-year-old boy who goes hungry every day.
</P>
<P>
   Fritze said he didn't have enough time to track down each of
those 32 Susan Halls, or other common names with multiple matches.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the 15 names submitted to the private investigator, no
matches were found for 11 of them, ``Republic'' records show.
</P>
<P>
   That included Luis Adler Varela, the White racist who discovered
he was Hispanic, and Gus McDougal the gay man who was being
harassed by intolerant neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts also were raised about some names with numerous matches,
Fritze said.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano's July 19 column quoted a Jennifer Morgan, identified
only as someone outraged by the increased bombardment of commercial
advertisements at her dentist's office.
</P>
<P>
   Then in an Aug. 11 column, Amparano quoted a Jennifer Morgan,
identified as an attorney. The Arizona Bar Association lists no
such member.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in 1995, Amparano quoted in news stories individuals named
Jennifer Morgan. One was identified as an owner of a telephone
answering service, and another Jennifer Morgan was listed as an
advertising representative from Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republic'' editors said Amparano could not provide them with
any way to contact any of the four different Jennifer Morgans.
</P>
<P>
   Editors said their doubts grew about the Aug. 9 column featuring
the hungry 5-year-old boy after reviewing a series of e-mail
messages that Amparano sent to readers inquiring how they could
help the family.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano said she could not locate the boy's mother, Susan Hall,
after the column ran, Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   To readers, Amparano gave conflicting responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family received tons of assistance. But if you still like
to help others, please call the Thomas Pappas Elementary School for
homeless children,'' Amparano e-mailed one reader on Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 minutes after the first message, however, Amparano sent
this e-mail to another reader: ``The community outpour (sic) has
been overwhelming. I am trying to get a hold of Susan Hall, her
phone has been disconnected. I will let you know what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Amparano's e-mails were acquired as part of ``The Republic's''
internal investigation. &QL; 
OTHER QUESTIONS &QL; 
D'Anna said other questions surfaced while questioning Amparano.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano did not know the location of Crossroads Park in Gilbert
where she said she found and interviewed the gay man, Gus McDougal.
She told editors that she did nothing to verify that the man was
who he said he was, including getting his home address or phone
number, D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   She gave vague and varied answers on a Patricia Anderson, who
was identified in a column as a banker, D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   The editors said they were told by Amparano that the interview
with Anderson took place at Bank One Plaza in downtown Phoenix.
When told no such person worked at Bank One, Amparano said that she
might have been mistaken and that Anderson could work for another
bank, D'Anna said.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano could provide no phone number or address for Anderson,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republic'' editors said they had several meetings last week
with Amparano, during which she was asked to prove phone numbers
and other details.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano did turn over some phone numbers, such as those
belonging to women quoted in a column about a Girl Scout trip that
Amparano and her daughter attended.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano also produced a phone number for Luis Adler Varela, the
White racist who belatedly discovered he was half Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Fritze said he called the number several times, and finally a
woman answered who said she didn't know a Luis Adler Varela.
Further checking showed that the phone was listed to Amparano's
niece, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, Amparano met again with ``Republic''
management to go over the columns. D'Anna said she still could not
provide evidence that many of the people existed.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano asked for the weekend to locate people.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said she was inclined to grant that request. But as the
questioning proceeded, Wallace mentioned the niece's name and asked
Amparano whether she knew that person.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano hesitated, then denied she knew such a person, Wallace
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she is telling us her niece is not her niece, what's the
point? You can't believe anything she's saying,'' Wallace said. ``I
said `Julie, you're fired.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace gave three reasons for the firing: irresponsible
reporting; contradictory statements to editors during the
investigation; and inability to substantiate multiple people in her
column.
</P>
<P>
   Amparano said through her attorney, Stephen Montoya, that she
stands by all her stories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
