<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ An evening full of electricity ended with all the spark
of a match flame, and the Astros wound up getting burned.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Franco lifted the New York Mets to a 3-2 victory over the
Astros with a ninth-inning bloop single into shallow left field
Monday night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the most intriguing development of the inning occurred one
batter earlier, when Astros manager Larry Dierker directed reliever
Jay Powell to pitch around .263 hitter Rey Ordonez, thereby
bringing the pinch-hitting Franco to the plate and forcing
hard-throwing righthanded reliever Armando Benitez out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those situations where if Ordonez was willing to
swing at balls low and away, fine,'' said Dierker, who had Powell
intentionally walk Ordonez once the count got to 3-0. ``We wanted
to get Benitez out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After Franco's single, the Astros didn't have to worry about
facing Benitez or any other reliever, because the Mets had pulled
off their 13th last-at-bat victory and improved to 24-15 in one-run
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a little cat-and-mouse going on there,''
said Franco, who leads the Mets with 13 pinch hits and 10 RBIs off
the bench. ``It was fine managerial strategy from Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who offered his
opinion on the most talked-about decision of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a bad move,'' Valentine said. ``But it
didn't work out. He (Dierker) had (Jeff) Bagwell leading off the
next inning. I've got (Dennis) Cook warmed up, and he has Bagwell,
(Ken) Caminiti and Carl (Everett), who has been swinging a great
righthanded bat.''
</P>
<P>
   If the decision had been totally up to Powell (4-4), he probably
would have preferred facing Ordonez, who has only one hit in five
career at-bats against the Astros reliever. Franco is now 2-for-2
against Powell, despite the fact Monday's game-winner was no more
than a flare off the end of the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franco's a good hitter,'' Powell said. ``He did his job, and I
can't take anything away from him. With Ordonez up there, the odds
of getting him out are better than with Franco, but at the same
time, I understand Dierker's logic of wanting to get Benitez out of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The National League Central-leading Astros remained a half-game
ahead of Cincinnati, which lost at Atlanta on Monday night. The
Mets trail Atlanta by the same margin in the NL East, but the New
Yorkers have the best record in the majors (50-21) since June 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets and the Reds seem to score late in games,'' Astros
shortstop Tim Bogar said. ``They're beating closers and good setup
men. They just keep getting hits when they need them, and it's
contagious. I wish we would catch that bug.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros do seem to have caught a case of home-run fever.
After falling behind 2-0 in the first four innings, they tied the
score on a pair of solo homers _ one by Matt Mieske in the fifth
and the other by Everett in the seventh. The Astros have hit nine
home runs in their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's home run was his ninth in 16 games since returning
from the disabled list. He has 27 RBIs during that stretch and is
hitting .422 with an unreal .938 slugging percentage in that span.
</P>
<P>
   The loss overshadowed a strong effort from Astros starter Scott
Elarton, who worked a career-high eight innings, allowing just two
runs on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott pitched quite well,'' Dierker said. ``He neutralized a
good lineup, and you don't do that by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets struck first on Edgardo Alfonzo's solo home run to left
field in the first inning, and Roger Cedeno's fourth-inning
sacrifice fly scored Robin Ventura to push the lead to two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros didn't have an abundance of scoring opportunities
against Mets starter Al Leiter, who held them to two runs in seven
innings, but there were a couple of close calls.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio was stranded at third base after leading off the
game with his major-league-leading 50th double. Leiter escaped
another tight spot in the seventh when he intentionally walked
Biggio with two out to load the bases and coaxed an inning-ending
grounder from Lance Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie left fielder also found himself at center stage with
runners on the corners and two out in the ninth inning. He struck
out against Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you leave that many guys on base, it's tough to
win,'' Berkman said. ``I like being in those situations when guys
are on base and you can influence the outcome with one swing of the
bat. I've always been a guy who drove in runs; I just have to learn
to do it here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' winning rally was set up by center fielder Darryl
Hamilton, who reached on a one-out double, moved to third on a fly
ball to left field and scored on Franco's blooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have a prejudiced view,'' Dierker said, ``but they hit
a couple of balls off the end of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, that's all it takes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
