<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      08-24 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-ABORTION GROUP ACCUSES MCCAIN OF FLIP-FLOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the nation's largest anti-abortion groups
accused GOP presidential candidate John McCain on Monday of
executing ``a drastic flip-flop'' on legal abortion that it said
``demonstrates that McCain will sacrifice any principle'' for
political gain.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee, once a McCain ally but
more recently a bitter foe, seized on comments made by the Arizona
senator in San Francisco last week that he would not support ``in
the short term, or even the long term'' the repeal of ``Roe vs.
Wade,'' the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Repealing the landmark ruling now ``would then force X number of
women in America to (undergo) illegal and dangerous operations,''
McCain told a private meeting of the ``San Francisco Chronicle''
editorial board.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, an umbrella group for about 3,000 local
anti-abortion organizations in all 50 states, said in a news
release Monday that the remark was directly contradictory to many
past statements by McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The group produced a copy of its 1998 congressional candidate
questionnaire in which McCain had checked ``Yes'' in response to,
``Do you support complete reversal'' of ``Roe vs. Wad''e?
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in a statement released by his campaign, defended his
anti-abortion record and said he favors repealing ``Roe vs. Wade''
in the right environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point that I have consistently made is that a repeal of
``Roe vs. Wade'' must occur, but that it must take place in
conjunction with a sustained effort to reduce the number of
abortions performed in America,'' McCain's statement said. ``If
``Roe vs. Wade'' were repealed tomorrow, it would force thousands
of young women to undergo dangerous and illegal operations.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign spokesman, Howard Opinsky, said Monday that
the senator's position has been consistent because he has long
favored repealing the decision while simultaneously curbing
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been his commitment throughout his congressional
career,'' Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   But the anti-abortion group's legislative director, Douglas
Johnson, was quoted in the press release saying that McCain ``will
sacrifice any principle in order to curry favor with certain
political elites, in an attempt to further his personal political
ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, like front-running Republican presidential candidate
George W. Bush, has said he would not use a ``litmus test'' to
screen out potential Supreme Court justices who support abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Their positions have angered the party's religious
conservatives. New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith recently bolted the
GOP, saying it had abandoned its principles on abortion and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee was once an ally of McCain,
who has had a 17-year record opposing abortion, partial-birth
abortion and federal funding of abortion. The organization's
political action committee donated to McCain's Senate campaign in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship soured in 1997 when Johnson, the
legislative director, began to criticize McCain in the Catholic
press and in New Hampshire and Iowa, site of early presidential
contests next year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was angry with McCain for voting against a bill that
would have banned Parkinson's disease researchers from using fetal
tissue taken during abortions. But the main reason for his ire was
a provision in McCain's campaign-finance reform bill that was later
shelved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The provision would have subjected the Right to Life Committee
and other interest groups to full disclosure requirements and other
federal campaign-finance rules when they broadcast political
advertisements mentioning members of Congress by name. Johnson said
at the time that the new rules ``would cripple the pro-life
movement'' and stifle political speech.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was behind a series of ads airing in Iowa and New
Hampshire late in 1997 that attacked McCain and his campaign-reform
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, Mark Salter, McCain's top aide, told ``The
Arizona'' ``Republic:'' `'I consider Douglas Johnson to be a
thoroughly dishonest man.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign aides believe the intensity of Johnson's
latest attack Monday may be related to this recent, stormy history.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said in an interview, ``This is completely aside
from the campaign-finance, free-speech issue. Other candidates who
have flip-flopped on ``Roe vs. Wade,'' we have certainly had the
same reaction.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
