<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MCGWIRE-SOSA-NYT     08-24 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCGWIRE-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A THUNDEROUS ENCORE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire often says (and no doubt Sammy Sosa feels the same
way) that he would much prefer to be playing for a team with a
chance to win the pennant, which he isn't, than to be chasing his
own record of 70 home runs, which he is. Still, both he and Sosa,
who hit 66 last season, must be deriving some private pleasure from
the fact that they are once again lighting up the major leagues
with a home run race that may not have quite the electricity of
last year's chase but, statistically speaking, is every bit as
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, Sosa had 51 homers and McGwire 50. At this
rate, both will again exceed Babe Ruth's mark of 60 home runs for a
154-game season and Roger Maris' total of 61 for the modern
162-game season.
</P>
<P>
   Those standards are beginning to look a bit like the four-minute
mile. Once Roger Bannister broke that seemingly impenetrable
barrier in 1954, a lot of runners broke it. But for now, the only
people with a shot at 60 or more homers are the same two who did it
last year. Their nearest pursuer in the National League is
Houston's Jeff Bagwell, with 37 homers through the weekend. In the
American League, Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. had 38. McGwire and
Sosa, like Babe Ruth before them, are plainly in a league of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   What is not clear is why. The pep pill theory is no longer
available. McGwire, who last year took a controversial supplement
called androstenedione, says he gave it up at the start of the
season. Both men are strong and quick with the bat, but so are
others. A more intriguing explanation, which McGwire does not buy,
is that since he and Sosa are on out-of-contention teams, they can
swing from the heels without worrying about niceties like simply
getting on base.
</P>
<P>
   One other possibility, which we like, is that the competition
between the two _ an athlete's sense of occupying a space shared by
only one other person, and perhaps wanting to claim it for himself
_ has helped elevate them above the pack. They certainly do seem to
respond to one another's heroics. After Sosa hit four home runs on
Thursday and Friday to grab the lead, McGwire answered back with
two against the Mets on Sunday, including a shot that measured a
mere 502 feet only because it hit the scoreboard while still in
full flight. Whatever the reason, it is still a great and special
show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
