<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LAD     08-24 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT TIGERS IN BATTLE OF THE BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was giveaway night at Edison Field Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   That should come as no surprise _ the Anaheim Angels and Detroit
Tigers have been giving away games all season. Going into the game,
the Tigers were tied with the Kansas City Royals for the worst
record in the majors, and the Angels were only one game better.
</P>
<P>
   So right on cue, the two last-place teams gave 17,145 brave fans
what they should have expected all along _ bad baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Through 7{ innings, appropriately enough, neither team had a
lead. Eventually, the Angels prevailed, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck hit a one-out single in the eighth inning to drive
in the go-ahead run. Garret Anderson began the rally against Doug
Brocail (4-4) with his fourth single of the game. Troy Glaus drew a
one-out walk and Walbeck lined a single to right to drive in
Anderson, who scored for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival (3-2) blanked the Tigers in the final 11/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Tigers pitcher Dave Borkowski wasted no time getting started.
Borkowski committed three errors _ all in the first two innings _
to tie a Tigers club record. The errors led to three unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Borkowski's problems started when Angels leadoff hitter Trent
Durrington began the first inning with a comebacker that Borkowski
couldn't handle _ error No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Borkowski then threw the ball away on a pickoff attempt,
allowing Durrington to take second _ error No. 2. Durrington came
around to score in the first inning on Mo Vaughn's RBI groundout.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, the Angels had runners on first and second
with nobody out, but Troy Glaus hit a one-hopper back to Borkowski,
setting up a certain double play.
</P>
<P>
   Only Borkowski's throw to second sailed wide of the bag and into
center field, allowing Anderson to score from second _ error No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds' RBI double in the fourth inning gave starter Tim
Belcher and the Angels a 4-1 lead, but in the sixth the Angels
began giving back the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Dodger Karim Garcia hit an opposite-field home run to left
field, his eighth of the season, driving in ex-Angel Damion Easley
in ahead of him to cut the Angels' lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels responded in their half of the sixth after Tim
Salmon's leadoff triple. It was Salmon's first triple in more than
a year. His last triple was Aug. 5, 1998 at home against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson followed with his third hit of the night, a single to
right field for a 5-3 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who gave up three runs and eight hits in six innings,
was in line to get his first victory in more than two months. His
previous victory came in a 4-2 win over the Yankees June 20 in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But Angels reliever Lou Pote entered the seventh and failed to
retire anyone. He walked the first two batters he faced, then
allowed an RBI double to Tony Clark before getting the hook. Juan
Encarnaicion's RBI groundout off Mike Magnante _ the run charged to
Pote _ tied the game at 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
