<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7407 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AIMSSCORES-AZR &LR;      08-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIMS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEASE OF ARIZONA EDUCATIONAL TEST SCORES IS OPPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
 SCORES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The president of the state Board of Education isn't so
sure she wants the public to see the first round of scores for
Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards.
</P>
<P>
   Results of AIMS will be released in October to today's high
school juniors, 60,000 of whom took the reading, writing and math
exam last spring. But Mary Garcia voiced concerns during the
board's Monday meeting about announcing to everyone how many
students conquered the state's academic standards and how many
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Move slowly, she cautioned, AIMS is still in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is how we treat the results,'' Garcia said. ``We
didn't give the test to get high-stakes feedback. We did it more to
inform us.''
</P>
<P>
   She called releasing school, district and state test-result
trends an unnecessary reaction ``to something before we're ready to
hit it head on.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel it's the public's right to know,'' said Holly
Craw, who provides home schooling for two daughters embarking on
their senior year. Craw was one of 15 who took a mock version of
AIMS administered by ``The Arizona'' ``Republic'' last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much hype about the AIMS test,'' said the
north Phoenix mother, whose daughters don't have to take it but has
been following the exam's life. ``So let's see it. This will give
us a base line.''
</P>
<P>
   Although results will appear in juniors' transcripts, educators
and parents alike have questioned how much motivation the first
batch of pupils had to do well on AIMS. &UR; The test won't be a
graduation requirement until today's sophomores _ the Class of 2002
_ take it next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, those students who didn't meet the standards will be
retaking the test in the spring. The exam includes concepts that
the students likely will learn later in their high school career.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Monday's discussion, Garcia said the board would
address whether to make the results public _ and possibly take a
vote _ during its next meeting in September.
</P>
<P>
   However, state Department of Education officials, who had been
poised to release AIMS results to the masses, have their own
concerns. Department number crunchers want to analyze and compare
the results. But that might conflict with a decision to keep the
test scores under wraps, because any such analysis likely would
have to be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction,
is in favor of making the data public. She was out of town and not
privy to Monday's conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we really want to get the most out of the test, then we
want to pull together the numbers to see how schools did and how
districts did,'' said Patty Likens, an Education Department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   AIMS, crafted to ensure that Arizona students are grasping the
state's academic standards, has spent much time in the news. For
awhile, parents and educators worried that the test was debuting
before students had adequate time to digest the standards,
especially those revolving around math. In the end, the Board of
Education decided to wait until the Class of 2002 to tie AIMS to a
high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   They also feared that Spanish-speaking and special-needs
children would have difficulty on the exam. The test remains in the
shadow of a 7-year-old lawsuit that claims it's discriminatory
against limited-English students and that the state doesn't do
enough to bridge the language gap in education.
</P>
<P>
   State educators are moving forward with AIMS, nonetheless. In
April, the Board of Education approved an outline of how to gauge
students' performance on the test.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's meeting, the board picked a common number, 500,
that will be used as the cutoff score to determine who meets the
standards in reading, writing and math. It also decided to ask a
group of educators who helped define the cutoff score descriptions
in math to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was the board's discussion about whether to make the
first round of scores public that seemed to spark the most debate.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tom Haladyna, a professor and testing expert at Arizona
State University West, has been critical of AIMS, he does
understand why Garcia of the state board is hesitant about
releasing scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go carefully and make sure the test is really good,'' he said,
adding that comparing students' test scores isn't necessarily the
best thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Kotterman, president of the Arizona Education Association,
agreed, saying that it's not fair to put undue pressure on students
and worry parents before the wrinkles of the exam are ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   Providing AIMS scores to each student and teacher will help
improve the test, pointing out strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they (Board of Education) decide to do, they need to
be cautious,'' Kotterman said. &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at (602) 444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
