<HEADLINE>
BENNETT WINS UCLA DERBY EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bad plays decided UCLA's preseason quarterback
competition earlier than expected. Junior Drew Bennett avoided them
better than everyone else, and for that reason he'll start the
season opener Sept. 4 against Boise State in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tentative plan is to go the first two games, and possibly
three, with the two guys and maybe a third (Scott McEwan)
playing,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``At that time, I'd like to
make a decision on one. But we'll have two ready to play if one
struggles or gets hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   As planned, Toledo announced the quarterback cuts Monday
morning, with Bennett and redshirt freshman Cory Paus surviving.
(Thousand Oaks native McEwan is third string and Agoura High's Ryan
McCann is fourth.) However, no one expected Toledo to name a
starter this early. Even Bennett, the front-runner, was prepared to
compete for two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would be one of the two battling it out,'' Bennett
said. ``But when he said I would be starting against Boise State, I
was shocked. It was like, `Wow, all right.'... I called my parents
and told them they have to make it to at least one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo didn't stop at the starter. He named Paus the backup and
proffered a basic plan for using Bennett and Paus in the opening
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure what we're going to do yet, whether (Paus will
play) two series, three series, first quarter or second quarter,''
Toledo said. ``But both guys will play when the game's in doubt...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking not just at the nonleague (games), but at the
league and the future. The guy that does it will be the quarterback
of the future. That's a big investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice plan reflected it. Toledo and offensive coordinator
Al Borges split repetitions equally among the four candidates. They
tracked every pass thrown in one-on-one drills and scrimmages. They
analyzed statistics and took input from their assistants. In the
end, the answer was fairly obvious:
</P>
<P>
   Although Paus had a higher completion percentage, he could not
overcome Bennett's two-year edge in experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves to be the starter,'' Paus said. ``For me, this is
just the next step on the ladder. I've made the next jump: I get to
play in the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has a better grasp of the offense than Paus. He knows
which plays work against specific defenses and, more importantly,
which plays won't work. That enables him to audible (change the
play) efficiently at the line of scrimmage _ a crucial component to
UCLA's dynamic attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew didn't let us run bad plays, and he got us out of bad
plays and into good plays,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   McEwan and McCann were disappointed but not surprised by the
decision. As a redshirt sophomore, McEwan now faces an eligibility
bind. He has three years remaining after this season, so if he
wants to transfer, this is the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely sticking around,'' he said. ``I'm two injuries
away from playing, but I'm not hoping that happens. Transfers are
for guys who don't feel they're good enough to stick with the
program. And I love it here. I live 30 minutes away.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann, a redshirt freshman who suffered a concussion in
Saturday's scrimmage, said he has no plans to transfer and repeated
the Cade McNown story: McNown was the No. 4 quarterback when
training camp began in 1995, then became the starter six weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get back from this injury and start working
hard,'' McCann said. ``You never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
