<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-TWINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The long ball has been missing lately from the Red
Sox' arsenal. So has the so-called quality start. Pity. Life can be
such fun for the members of the Olde Towne Team when they remember
how to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case Monday night in a 4-1 victory over the
Minnesota Twins before 14,331 at the Metrodome. The game was
decided by bombs off the bats of outfielders Trot Nixon and Troy
O'Leary, as Boston ended a four-game losing streak. With Pat Rapp
working six innings, followed by three more from closer Derek Lowe,
you wonder why the Red Sox can't do this every night.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's drive in the second inning gave the Red Sox a 2-0 lead.
After Minnesota pushed across a run in the third, O'Leary came
through in the fifth inning with another two-run shot, his 25th
homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston moved back into a tie with Oakland in the American League
wild-card chase. The teams have identical 68-57 records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to help the team win ballgames,'' said Nixon,
the No. 9 hitter most nights. ``Most times, I just want to get on
base for the top of the lineup. The home run is just a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is crunch time _ the last part of this month and
September. I feel like I need to hit the ball, too, so there is no
weak link in our lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary felt the same way. The three-game sweep by the Texas
Rangers over the weekend had left a bitter taste in his mouth. The
Sox had an early-morning arrival in the Twin Cities. Their charter
plane from Dallas Sunday night had a flat tire and was delayed four
hours. The players arrived in their downtown hotel late enough to
read the morning papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trot picked us up with his home run,'' said O'Leary. ``It made
everybody relaxed out there. Things started going for us. I don't
even know what to call it. I don't care what I do as long as we
came up with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four losses, the Red Sox had hit only two home runs. On
Sunday, they were shut out by former Sox righthander Aaron Sele,
6-0. Monday night, the offense put together 10 hits, including two
each by O'Leary, Jose Offerman, and Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp played a key role, even though he had runners on base in
each of the six innings he worked. His concentration was admirable
considering that his pregnant wife is having troubles some two
months before the baby is due.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp struck out six and walked three. Lowe registered his
seventh save with three innings of two-hit, five-strikeout work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be out there, do my job,'' said Rapp. ``Keep
us in the game and give our bats a chance to come alive. I couldn't
get my curveball over early, and it got me into a couple of jams.
Once I got the guys on, I made the right pitches to get us out of
the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp said he will stay with the club at least until it returns
to Boston and then decide what to do. ``Things really haven't
changed at home with my wife,'' he said. ``Her blood pressure has
stabilized more or less, but they still want her in the bed on her
back. It's tough with two boys in the house running around. The
baby will come sooner than later. But she's fighting through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams said Rapp and his teammates did well
Monday night. ``Overall, we pitched and played a clean game out
there,'' said Williams. ``That was important. Don't forget that
Rapp was with us in Texas and on that deluxe flight. He was the key
because he got us through the sixth inning. Lowe had plenty of time
off. You knew he was rested from the standpoint of giving you more
than 1-2 innings. Fortunately, it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lowe, ``I know the long layover affected me. I didn't feel
good but I told myself, `One pitch at a time.' I made it through it
and Pat got a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of strikeouts but there were balls out of the
zone. I don't try to strike people out. I try to get hit the ball
on the ground every time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
