<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS REMAIN HIGH AS MARINERS TRY TO THWART DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What's the most hackneyed expression in sports that
describes an aging athlete?
</P>
<P>
   He's lost a step.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't apply to Lou Piniella. In fact, just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner manager, before the ESPN nation Sunday night, found
a step.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the step was at the top of the dugout. In failing
to clear it as he charged onto the field to protest a call,
Piniella launched himself into a stumbling faceplant that was so
rich in seasonal metaphor that space does not permit a full
recitation.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Piniella executed a full '99 Mariner: A
futile plan made worse by faulty execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I've ever done that,'' he said Monday, chuckling at
himself. ``I just don't have the first-step explosion any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to laugh at himself has always been one of
Piniella's endearing traits. But Sunday, as he bounced up from the
dirt and engaged in a fiery tantrum that drew his fourth ejection
in less than a month, Piniella seemed to drift across a line that
separates laughing with him to laughing at him.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was absolutely right in his argument _ if the
Indians' Carlos Baerga had slid any further outside the baseline,
he would have been hit by the trains just beyond right field _
Piniella's histrionics were so overwrought, and so familiar, that
it evoked only the weak courtesy laugh offered for a fading
nightclub comedian.
</P>
<P>
   After a placid half-season, Piniella was booted from games on
July 25, Aug. 8 and Aug. 14 as well as Sunday. At this rate,
Piniella by Labor Day will be a tattoo and two nose rings short of
the Rodman threshold of terminal foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, in the (four disputed calls), except for one, the film
proved I was dead right,'' he said. ``Sure, you can say I should go
out and argue and handle it. But I'm not doing this for me, I'm
doing it for the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the ballclub. That's the one that has had two brawls in the
last five weeks. The fights resulted in injuries and suspensions
for which the Mariners are still paying.
</P>
<P>
   No suggestion will be made here for some dignity and decorum.
This is, after all, baseball, where a public scratch of the groin
is considered an inalienable right.
</P>
<P>
   But an observer of national TV highlights recently cannot escape
the conclusion that the Mariners, despite Monday night's 4-1 win
over Cleveland that thwarted a four-game sweep, are little more
than higher-paid rasslers more skilled at pile drivers than driving
in runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the chair-breaking has happened since the team
moved to the Guilty Pleasure from the Kingdome. As much as the park
has been a delight for fans _ as long as they don't have need of a
parking space, safe food or a clean bathroom _ it seems that team
tensions have been ratcheted up significantly.
</P>
<P>
   What it has produced is men behaving badly.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to quantify, but it's also hard to miss _ this team is
nowhere as good as its yard, nor deserving of nightly sellouts. The
players, as well as Piniella, are embarrassed by what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   As Alex Rodriguez put it after the Sunday loss, ``We suck.''
</P>
<P>
   An inelegant description, yes, but apt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't deny that it's been tough, what we've been going
through,'' Piniella said. ``We're going with seven rookie pitchers
(five actually, but Todd Williams and Jose Paniagua have limited
major league experience), and we've moved from a smaller park to a
bigger park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, we had to play in a new park to see what we
needed, instead of thinking we knew what we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella has always been a win-now guy, from his playing days as
well as his first managerial job with the Yankees. But the Yankees'
financial clout makes them a win-now team by definition.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, for last season and this one, are not a win-now
team, having sunk to the bottom half of the major league payroll
ladder. For a variety of reasons already well-chronicled, the
Mariners are in decay and Piniella has been forced to play for the
future, not the present.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he arrived, Piniella's expansive
in-season conversations are almost exclusively about what's ahead,
not what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching-wise, we're in a lot better shape than we've been for
many years,'' he said. ``If we can get a couple more key guys, we
can put together a staff that will be around awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   If ... if ... if ... this kind of talk must be eating him. But
he has been a stoic keeper of the team faith. He has a team in
transition ill-suited for its new surroundings, yet he can't
complain or lament without jeopardizing his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shoulder it, rightfully so,'' he said. ``I can take the
heat. Always have. I'm no different a manager now than when we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true. But when he is losing while 45,000 fans a
night _ as well as Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr. _ are staring
impatiently, the heat is unusually intense, with no reasonable
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an umpire makes a bad call, or an opposing pitcher hits a
Mariner. Then, these guys swing with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
