<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JOEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT TALKS WITH GALLOWAY GET TESTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ The Seahawks' contract talks with leading
receiver Joey Galloway have become a test of wills.
</P>
<P>
   And both sides are getting a bit testy as Galloway's holdout
enters its 26th day Tuesday, with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The club has drawn a line on the negotiating table, tweaking its
seven-year, $35 million offer by moving almost $1 million from the
final two years of the deal into the first five years, and adopting
a take-it-or-leave it stance.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway and his agent, Eric Metz, consider the new $4.6 million
average over the first five years and the club's offer of a $7
million signing bonus to be below market value.
</P>
<P>
   For this deal to get done, something _ or someone _ will have to
give.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're new like we are, it was bound to happen with
somebody,'' said Holmgren, who was hired as general manager and
coach in January and then hired Mike Reinfelt to be his chief
contract negotiator. ``I have to establish how we're going to do
business. We're going to be fair. If I say something, that's the
way it's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is under contract. He should be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Galloway not at the team's Eastern Washington
University training camp, but talks have broken off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to get hold of Joey's agent ... we've phoned
every day,'' Holmgren said. ``He won't return our calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of that comment Monday, Metz offered, ``Haven't they made
their final offer? What is there to talk about?''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Galloway say he is prepared to sit out the
entire preseason and even miss some regular-season paychecks rather
than accept a deal he deems less than fair.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway has a year remaining on the five-year deal he signed in
1995 after being the team's first-round draft choice. But he
accepted the fifth year, at a reduced salary of $1.585 million,
with the understanding a new deal would be done before it ever
reached this point. That deal, however, was signed when Ken Behring
owned the team and Mickey Loomis was the primary contract
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren called Galloway over the weekend and Monday discussed
his reason for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things get lost in the interruption when you've got
five people kind of doing it,'' Holmgren said. ``When I talked to
him, I just wanted to make sure he knew what we, as an
organization, were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Listen, we want you here. But this is our offer. It's
a fair offer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway and Metz obviously don't agree, pointing to recent
contracts signed by Green Bay wide receiver Antonio Freeman and New
England cornerback Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman got a $5 million average over five years and a $10
million signing bonus as part of his seven-year deal that will void
to five years. Law got a $14 million signing bonus as part of a
seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals have Galloway and Metz expecting a signing bonus
that averages $2 million over the length of the contract and, at
the very least, incentive clauses that could bring the average of
Galloway's deal in line with Freeman's contract.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, incentive clauses have not even been discussed,
and the Seahawks have told Metz they will not include voidable
years in any deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this: what we're trying to do with Joey _ and what I
will try and do with every player on this football team _ is be
fair,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness is the one thing Galloway is after. He doesn't consider
the Seahawks' offer to be fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's their final offer, we can't control that,'' Metz
said. ``If they're trying to portray it as fair, we feel that's
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
