<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-INDIANS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' ABBOTT SHOWS HIS OLD TEAM SOME NEW TRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Four teams and six years ago, Paul Abbott made five
forgettable starts for the Cleveland Indians. He walked more than
he struck out, allowed more than a hit an inning and was not
brought back the next season.
</P>
<P>
   His attitude was worse than his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how different I am?'' Abbott said Monday night, after
spinning eight shutout innings in the Mariners' 4-1 win over
Cleveland. ``Before games, I was the first guy to look outside for
clouds, because that meant it might rain and we wouldn't have to
run. Now, I cry if I can't run. When I was in a game back then, it
was a job. I love to pitch now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a love made stronger by so many heartaches. Abbott was 25
when he pitched for Cleveland, up from Class AA, uncomfortable with
his delivery and his routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for negative things to happen,'' said Abbott,
who didn't have to wait long.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched in five Class AAA towns after the Indians sent him
down, injuring his shoulder, his elbow and, last winter, his knee.
He did not re-surface in the majors for five years after his
Cleveland stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ever saw him like this,'' said Indians
manager Mike Hargrove. ``We probably wouldn't have let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott (5-0) was masterful Monday, mixing a low-90s fastball
with a devastating tailing changeup to strike out 12 batters, the
most by a Mariner since Randy Johnson's last start in '98. He
allowed only three hits, two to Einar Diaz and an infield single to
Roberto Alomar. No runners advanced past second off him.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Mariners from being swept by the Indians in
this four-game series. Seattle got all the offense it needed in the
first inning, when Ken Griffey Jr. hit his 39th homer and Alex
Rodriguez followed with his 33rd. Griffey's homer was his 200th
over the past four seasons, and he joined Mark McGwire and Babe
Ruth as the only players to accomplish the feat.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Abbott's night. Starting for the third time since
replacing Jeff Fassero in the rotation, the right-hander took
another step toward earning a spot in the Mariners' 2000 rotation.
</P>
<P>
   It was one false step that kept him from the rotation this
spring. Abbott tore his anterior cruciate ligament covering first
base in winter ball and didn't make his debut until late June. An
effort like Monday night's was what the M's envisioned after he
went 3-1 last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really hoping he'd be the fourth or fifth starter,''
said pitching coach Stan Williams. ``It took a long time to get to
him, but what you saw tonight was not a mistake _ he's capable of
that. I thought he was better the last two innings than he was the
rest of the ballgame. The way he was throwing the ball the last two
innings, the hitters were overmatched.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said he didn't feel especially sharp early in the game,
when he fell behind often and struggled with his release point. But
something clicked in the fifth inning, he said, and he executed
whatever pitch catcher Dan Wilson called.
</P>
<P>
   His command was so exceptional that Abbott threw effective
backdoor sliders to left-handers for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a little bit of a lead and have that luxury, you
can kind of experiment a little bit,'' Wilson said. ``It seemed
like all of our experiments were working. It was kind of nice. He
threw some sliders when maybe he wouldn't have in other situations,
and even then, he threw great pitches. What a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians admitted they were baffled, to use shortstop Omar
Vizquel's word. Vizquel, the Indians' leading hitter, was 0-for-3
with two strikeouts, flinging his bat to second as he lunged and
fanned in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a dominating changeup,'' Vizquel said. ``It didn't have
any rotation. It looked just like a fastball, only it would die at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was cheered warmly by a sold-out Safeco Field crowd of
44,689 after fanning Alomar on a 92-mph fastball to strike out the
side in the eighth. Abbott, who also struck out the side in the
first inning, gave way to Jose Paniagua after throwing 128 pitches,
35 more than he'd thrown all year.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua loaded the bases on two singles and a walk, and with
two outs walked Diaz to force in a run. It was the Mariners' major
league-high 23rd bases-loaded walk this year, and it brought Jose
Mesa in from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa was roundly booed as he strode to the mound, but hee struck
out Richie Sexson _ who hit the game-winning homer off him Sunday _
on a wicked curveball to earn his 28th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
