<SLUG> BC-FBN-EXPANSION-CARSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARSON BACK IN RUNNING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No longer maidens when it comes to dealing with
the NFL, Carson city officials are taking a guarded approach to
their latest contact with the league.
</P>
<P>
   With the L.A. Coliseum proposal for an expansion team teetering
over public money demands, league officials have asked Carson for a
letter of interest regarding an expansion franchise and stadium
site. The league has made the same request of city officials at two
other possible sites, in Inglewood (Hollywood Park) and Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Carson city councilman Daryl Sweeney said the city will submit a
letter of interest, ``but no one plans to get optimistic,'' he
said. ``There has been contact, but it's just been generalities.
They want to know if we're still interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson was actively interested for more than a year after being
wooed to the idea by Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz. But when the
league chose the Coliseum as its preferred site, Ovitz moved on.
</P>
<P>
   All of the plans for developing the Carson site, a former
landfill off the San Diego and Harbor Freeways, remain in place.
The city has access to $180 million for development of a
stadium/mall complex ($30 million cash, $150 million in bonds) and
is continuing to move on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said there have been several new inquiries for
developing the site. The city has also been proactive in getting
the site included in an environmental appropriations bill that
would make federal money available for cleanup. Sweeney said other
Southern California municipalities already named in the bill will
receive as much as $12 million if it is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thinking this time is that we don't want to get in a
position where we're leverage for someone else or backed into a
corner,'' said Sweeney. ``If the ball gets thrown back into the
air, I think we'll want to work more directly with the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 days remain before the league's self-imposed deadline
(Sept. 15) to put an expansion team somewhere in Los Angeles
expires. The league's expansion committee will meet Sept. 9 to
discuss the status of L.A. in advance of the deadline and a general
owners meeting Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still looking at the alternatives to the Coliseum, and
that includes the Carson site,'' said NFL spokesman Joe Browne.
``We're working as hard as we can to work something out in L.A.,
but we're not discussing anything beyond the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the league's deadline, which means the owners could
change it. Even if the expansion opportunity goes to Houston, that
wouldn't preclude the league from nurturing a stadium site in L.A.
should an existing team, such as the Raiders, want to move.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he wasn't surprised the Coliseum deal hit a snag
over public money. ``From day one, the NFL said two issues were
crucial to an expansion team, a public subsidy and parking. If I
knew this, why didn't the Coliseum and its supporters? This (the
collapse) was totally predictable. The only people who didn't know
it were those saying they'd already won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 0252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7433 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON &LR;      08-24 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR CUAUHTEMOC CARDENAS IS FAILING IN BATTLE TO TAME
MEXICO  CITY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
(Eds.: Photographs accompanying this report may be purchased from
the Chronicle. Call the Photo Dept., 415-777-7077 for details.)
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On one all-too-normal day not long ago, Pedro
Martinez and Dario Jimenez were reminded just how ungovernable
Mexico City is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scum!'' and ``Sons of whores!'' were the mildest of the
epithets shouted at Martinez when he screeched up in a convoy of
patrol cars into the middle of a neighborhood riot. A dozen
policemen desperately pulled two accused purse-snatchers away from
local residents who were defending them.
</P>
<P>
   The teenage suspects were thrown into another car, and the
convoy spun frantic U-turns and raced away down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people sympathize with the criminals, they hate
authority,'' Martinez said as he drove away, sweating.
</P>
<P>
   At the other side of the city, Jimenez, a city planning
official, didn't get far with locals he was trying to persuade to
move off the parkland they were squatting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to steal our land,'' one squatter replied in his
small shack, his family scowling behind him. ``No way we'll move.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez left the neighborhood, spluttering and hanging his head.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half after sweeping into office as the most
powerful leftist elected politician in Latin America, Mayor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas has failed to bring substantial reform to
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   He has been stymied by immense problems: an endless crime wave,
rampant corruption, chaotic citizen protests and an unruly
bureaucracy controlled by the long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI). But many observers say that no one, not
even Cardenas, who is recognized even by his enemies as stubbornly
incorruptible and pro-reform, could solve them.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City, with a metropolitan area population of 20 million,
is the biggest metropolis in the hemisphere and one of the largest
in the world. It is so gargantuan that it dominates Mexico
politically and economically in the same way as Washington, New
York and Los Angeles would the United States if they were one
mega-city.
</P>
<P>
   The intractability of Mexico City's problems indicates just how
difficult it would be for any opposition politician to govern
Mexico if the PRI is defeated in next year's presidential elections
_ a growing possibility.
</P>
<P>
   As the PRI's well-greased political machine is dismantled, it is
being replaced by a power vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came to government, we expected that we would be able
to make concrete progress in resolving the city's problems,'' said
Jorge Legorreta, a former academic who is Cardenas' top official
for the large, crime-filled downtown district.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were quickly confronted by the subterranean actors, the
hidden power players in the city. These problems are much more
difficult to resolve than we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest roadblocks include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Urban sprawl. The capital has grown uncontrollably into the
extensive ``green areas,'' or designated parklands, climbing the
mountains on the city's south and west edges. Growth is propelled
by the annual arrival of 180,000 people from the countryside and by
corrupt officials who ignore zoning regulations _ and by Cardenas'
insistence on negotiations, rather than force, to dislodge
squatters.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hardball citizen politicking. Grassroots groups and average
citizens often adopt an aggressive, take-no-prisoners stance in
lobbying the government for services such as housing, utilities and
new schools. Sit-ins, land squatting and threats of violence have
long been standard for groups on all sides of the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many social groups are extortionist, demanding money and
services from the government,'' said Elio Villasenor, an
urban-policy expert at Equipo Pueblo, a Mexico City think tank.
``There's no shared civic responsibility, no respect and lots of
low blows.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Pollution. Mexico City remains one of the world's most
polluted cities, with a yellow-brown haze that leaves residents
with seared nasal passages and watery eyes. The problem is defying
all efforts at remediation. Although emission rules have been
toughened for the city's 2.5 million vehicles, which have an
average age of about 10 years, corruption among smog-check centers
has made a mockery of the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   New forms of corruption have been invented to allow average
citizens to escape compliance _ for example, a sleight of hand
nicknamed the  &UR; caballito,  &LR; or little horse, in which a new car's
papers are substituted for those of old, smog-belching vehicles,
producing a clean bill of health for the latter.
</P>
<P>
   -- Underpaid, corrupt cops. The city's 158,000 police officers
receive an average salary of only about $310 per month, barely
one-half of what a street vendor makes. As a result, corruption
continues under Cardenas despite several major purges, including
the firing of thousands of officers suspected of graft.
</P>
<P>
   -- Growing economic inequality and desperation among the poor.
``The lack of security is largely the result of a devastating
social crisis and worsening poverty,'' Legorreta said. ``The number
of delinquents has grown disproportionately.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Hostile, old-guard unions. About one-half of the 240,000
municipal workers are member of PRI-controlled unions, which manage
a complex web of corruption and exercise iron-fisted control over
their workers. Wildcat strikes _ more than 20 so far this year _
have shut down entire municipal departments and even cut water
supplies to large sectors of the city.
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials, for their part, say the Cardenas administration
is simply in over its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardenas hasn't shown the experience or the efficiency needed
to manage the city,'' said Esteban Moctezuma, who resigned earlier
this month as the federal Minister of Social Development to manage
the presidential campaign of the PRI front-runner, Francisco
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``His government has been more than a bit disorganized and
chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all has been failure. By most accounts, Cardenas has had
some low-profile yet significant successes. He has rooted out
corruption in the middle and upper administrative levels. City
services, such as the oft-overflowing sewage system, are more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crime has been reduced, and a wave of bank robberies has
stopped, although routine muggings and purse-snatchings are more
frequent than ever. At the same time, citizen complaints of police
brutality are less frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most ambitiously, Cardenas has given city government a
whiff of real grassroots democracy, allowing increased citizen
participation in decision-making at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the extra democracy hasn't worked well. The
first-ever elections in June for a new system of nonpartisan
neighborhood councils were a failure. Only 15 percent of voters
went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   On the crime front, Citizen Security Committees _ sort of a
neighborhood watch program _ have been formed to help the police.
But as policeman Martinez found out, sometimes the good citizenry
take a dim view of law and order.
</P>
<P>
   And on city planner Jimenez's recent visit to the Tierra
Colorada shantytown, he got an earful when he met with local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of dozens of meetings that he's been holding since a
year ago, when he announced the city's plan to move the
neighborhood's 1,500 residents out of the formerly forested ``green
area'' that they had turned into a full-scale urban neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But Jimenez's mission was daunting. Tierra Colorada is like most
of the city's 600-plus illegal squatter settlements, which hold
about 250,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   It was formed gradually since the early 1980s by migrants from
the countryside. Over time, through an anarchic process of
vote-selling and hardball negotiating, the residents acquired
scraps of paper that they said were legal property titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local PRI officials would give them information on what
parcel to squat on, then they would help them squat on it and
pretend to legalize their situation and give access to city
utilities, all in exchange for votes,'' said Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what they call titles aren't legal either. So what can we
do? We can't just throw them out. We have to negotiate. That's very
slow, and people want results a lot faster than we can give them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez should know. A former student radical, he was an adviser
to leftist squatter groups for nearly 20 years. He fought the PRI
vote-buying system, with mixed success _ until Cardenas' triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering the bureaucracy last year, Jimenez has found out
just how tough it is to govern honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to move most of you to a smaller area where we'll
build you proper houses, with all the utilities,'' he told Carmelo
Guerrero, whose extended family looked on stony-faced. ``For
others, we're teaching solar energy and dry latrines. But it's
difficult because the people are suspicious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, we don't trust the government,'' Guerrero
replied. ``We've learned not to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
