<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7437 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CASINO-RULING-SFCHRON     08-24 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-RULING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA HIGH COURT TOSSES OUT INDIAN GAMING RULING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Proposition 5, the high-stakes initiative to
expand legalized gambling on Indian reservations, was struck down
Monday by the California Supreme Court in a decision that tribes
say will be financially devastating.
<P>
   By a 6-to-1 vote, the high court said the measure, which
received an overwhelming 63 percent of the vote in November, is
illegal under a state constitutional ban on Nevada-style casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is a lucrative victory for Las Vegas casinos and
voids the most expensive initiative battle in state history _ the
two sides together spent more than $91.3 million. It also raises
the specter of federal gambling raids on Indian casinos and sets
the stage for another costly election. One tribe is circulating an
initiative similar to Proposition 5 that would legalize gambling
through a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian people throughout California will suffer at the hands
of Nevada casinos,'' said Anthony Pico, tribal chairman of the
Viejas Band of Kumeyaay Indians, located near San Diego. The tribe
was one of several that had backed Proposition 5.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis released a statement promising to abide by the
court's decision. But citing the overwhelming voter approval, he
said, ``I intend to work diligently to find a constitutionally
acceptable means of implementing the people's express will.'' He
said he will work with the Legislature, the tribes and all other
interested parties to achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5 gave 40 of California's 107 American Indian tribes
the right to maintain and expand casino gambling on their
reservations. The initiative's implementation has been postponed
since December, when the state Supreme Court agreed to review two
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's decision, the court said the measure attempted to
legalize previously banned slot machines and ``banked table (card)
games,'' including blackjack, the most popular card game. Both are
popular features of the casino play in Las Vegas and Atlantic City.
And both are outlawed under a 1984 amendment to the state
constitution specifically prohibiting Nevada and New Jersey-style
casino gambling, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The court also rejected the tribes' claim that their ``gaming
terminals'' are legally different from traditional slot machines.
The justices said they are still slot machines, even though they
are operated with buttons instead of levers and dispense chips or
credit instead of coins. The tribes say that those machines account
for about 70 percent of the gambling revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5 ``authorizes what would amount to prohibited
casinos,'' wrote Justice Kathryn Mickle Werdegar in the court
majority.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Joyce Kennard accused her
colleagues of rejecting the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   She said only federal law can authorize Indian gambling, and the
state can only impose conditions on operations. Kennard also
concluded that the tribes were operating lotteries, where the house
has no stake in the outcome, not prohibited banking games.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires states to allow the same type of gambling
on reservations that is legal elsewhere in the state. Tribal
leaders sought ballot approval after former Gov. Pete Wilson
refused to allow the casino-style expansion most tribes wanted. But
backers qualified Proposition 5 only as a proposed statute because
they believed they lacked time to get the additional signatures
needed for a state constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5 had been challenged by a group of residents and
businesses financed by Nevada casinos who opposed the expansion of
casinos near their communities. A separate suit had been brought by
the Hotel and Restaurant Employees and Bartenders International
Union, which represents 3,500 employees at card clubs in the state
and 1,000 workers involved in Indian gaming. The union's main
objection is that Proposition 5 did not guarantee rights for union
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal chairman Pico said he hopes Monday's decision will prompt
the governor to step up continuing negotiations with the tribes,
which so far have been going at a slow pace. ``Now when we sit down
and talk, we won't talk about Proposition 5. I'm hopeful we're
still talking about allowing gaming on Indian land.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the initiative allowed tribes with gaming
operations to share their profits with other tribes.
</P>
<P>
   But Ted Olson, a Washington D.C., lawyer who represented the
residents and businesses, cautioned that the court's decision
imposes restrictions on those negotiations. ``The governor cannot
agree to casino-style gambling,'' Olson said. ``It's quite clear
what the Indians are doing and proposed to do is clearly illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the voters may have the final say on the
future of Indian gaming.
</P>
<P>
   On the March ballot is a referendum, which, if approved by
voters, would overturn limited compacts negotiated by former Gov.
Pete Wilson and eight tribes. It is backed by the Agua Caliente
tribe, a Proposition 5 supporter and opponent of the compact, which
the tribe says is too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   The same tribe is circulating petitions for a November measure
that would allow the same type of gaming approved under Proposition
5. But the initiative would be a constitutional amendment, which
would override the law the Supreme Court cited in striking down
Proposition 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribes will ultimately bring their case back to the
people, and the people will have the opportunity to amend the
constitution,'' predicted Mark Epstein, a Los Angeles attorney who
represented the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein said the tribes are still reviewing their options. But
it is doubtful that they will appeal the decision to the U.S.
Supreme Court, because the case turns solely on state law.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's decision, the court noted that the tribes had
advance warning that Proposition 5 would have trouble under legal
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   After it qualified for the ballot but before the November
election, the Legislative Counsel issued an opinion saying the
measure would be declared invalid under the state constitutional
prohibition on the type of casinos operating in Nevada and New
Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
