<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIRFORCE-WASTE25-COX     08-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-WASTE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL AUDITORS FAULT AIR FORCE PRACTICES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Air Force is taking incoming fire from
government auditors in two recent critiques, one for failing to
keep track of billings for flying VIPs and the other for
mismanagement that contributes to the shortage of military pilots.
</P>
<P>
   For passengers who travel as friends of VIPs, a federal study by
the General Accounting Office describes the ultimate bargain in air
travel: more than 4,500 flights a year to almost any spot on the
globe, and possibly no bill for six years, if then.
</P>
<P>
   But the taxpayers always get the bill, because the service is
provided by the Air Force's 89th Airlift Wing. The elite
20-airplane service operates Air Force One and provides air service
for diplomats, military brass, and members of Congress at a cost of
$357 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial guests who go along, as well as the news media, are
supposed to pay the equivalent of coach fare. The newly released
GAO report concluded that the Air Force kept such sloppy books that
it was impossible to tell who paid.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department accountants had no numbers, names,
billing records or collection records for the nonofficial
passengers, said the report. As a consequence, it concluded, ``no
one independently verified that all reimbursements were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the VIP air service were also noted in a GAO study
in 1992, after a controversy over use of the VIP fleet by
then-White House chief of staff John Sununu.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has since tightened rules on use of the aircraft,
but the latest report found little progress on collecting
reimbursements. ``It appears that the problem still exists,'' said
William Solis, one of the authors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, for example, non-defense agencies are
required to transfer funds to pay the Air Force for flying their
employees for official duties, but the study found the Air Force
took as much as six years to send bills.
</P>
<P>
   In its response, the Defense Department said it would reform its
bookkeeping on reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   In a second report, the GAO, which serves as the investigative
arm of Congress, traced the Air Force and Navy pilot shortage to
the doorstep of the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   As the services complain that they train pilots only to see them
lured away by private airlines, the GAO said the military has not
properly considered how many pilots it needs, why so many are
leaving, or what would keep them.
</P>
<P>
   A major cause of the current shortage was a decision to reduce
recruitment during most of the 1990s, the report said. And amid
stepped-up efforts today, training is hampered by the disarray in
the delivery of spare parts, which keeps planes grounded and delays
pilot graduation by as much as 40 weeks, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of pilots, the GAO also concluded that pilot
re-enlistment bonuses, which extend only through the 14th year of
service, will not be sufficient to hold them until retirement. Many
pilots complained that the cutoff at that point represented a pay
cut for the remainder of their career and an incentive to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot survey also found widespread dissatisfaction after
years of stepped-up deployments that have repeatedly mobilized a
relatively small percentage of Air Force personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Force pilots identified the frequency and length of
deployments and lack of clear mission objectives as their primary
concerns,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has projected that it would be short as many as
2,155 pilots between 1998 and 2007. The Navy problem reached a peak
last year, with a shortfall of 1,153 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the report, the Defense Department called
retaining pilots is ``a top priority'' and said that the department
would consider a GAO remedy of offering the option of a
``fly-only'' career to pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
