 Tuesday, Aug. 24, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLIFFS-NOTES (Lincoln, Neb.) _ Down the street from the Nebraska
State Penitentiary, across from Midwest Turf and Irrigation, stands
a corrugated tin building, the kind found in industrial parks
across America. Drab and tan. Utterly utilitarian. Except for the
vivid, black-and-yellow stripes on the awning out front, the bumble
bee motif that has evoked Pavlovian responses of relief in
generations of students. This building is ground zero for a
phenomenon called Cliffs Notes. By MELISSA FLETCHER STOETJE.
</P>
<P>
   CLIFFS-NOTES-SIDEBAR (Lincoln, Neb.) _ If you don't have time to
read the in-depth story about Cliffs Notes, a shortened, a la Cliff
Notes, version is provided. By MELISSA FLETCHER STOETJE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AUCTIONS (Albany, N.Y.) _ On-line auctions let you
window-shop 24 hours a day, seven days a week, without wearing out
your feet or car. But be aware of the caveats before you start
clicking on that bid box. ``Don't jump in and buy on impulse,''
says Hank Hudepohl, an e-commerce analyst in Lincoln, Mass.
``People can easily get caught up in the fun or competition. It's
almost like gambling. So try to keep your cool.'' By FRANCES
INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-FURNISHINGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Because of computers and
CD players, children are spending more time in their rooms. To that
end, designers have created entertainment centers, workstations,
comfortable upholstered chairs, plush pillows and attractive
accessories to make the rooms as friendly as possible. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CHILDREN (Undated) _ A look at some recent children's
books, including ``Princess Dress'' (Dial, $15.99) by Doris Dorrie,
Benedicte Guiettier's ``The Father Who Had 10 Children`` (Dial,
$15.99) and ``Red-Eyed Tree Frog'' (Scholastic, $16.95) by Joy
Cowley. By JANE P. MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   PEWTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Most pewter will not tarnish or require
polishing if given proper care. Always hand wash pieces in hot,
soapy water soon after use, and never put pewter in a dishwasher,
because the heat-drying cycle may darken the surface. Rinse in
clear, hot water and dry with a soft cloth. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``I have a hummingbird
bush that was given to me, but a friend has a different bush that
she calls a hummingbird bush. I only have a patio, so will mine
grow in a large pot?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AUTOS (San Francisco) _ The Internet is bringing change
to two more old world practices _ the kicking of tires on the auto
lot and the test drive. This year, more than 5 million new vehicle
buyers will use the Internet to gather information to help them
decide what vehicles to purchase, and as many as 5 percent of auto
purchases are expected to be made online by 2000, a new survey has
found. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-BUSINESS (San Antonio) _ Companies have always hired
ex-military officers and enlisted men and women. But it's only been
in recent years that companies have popped up that exclusively
recruit from the military ranks. Fueling their growth is a tight
labor market, a strong desire among an underpaid officer corps to
find a better life and the growing recognition among corporate
leaders that the military produces some excellent managers. By L.M.
SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-BANKING (San Francisco) _ Not long ago, technology
financing was a small market ruled by investment bankers in San
Francisco and led by a few visionaries. Not anymore. Today,
high-tech financing is the largest and fastest growing sector in
investment banking, with brawny Wall Street firms dominating
mergers and acquisitions as well as initial public offerings. By
EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   CIDER-BAR (Sebastopol, Calif.) _ Marilyn Renna tilts a pint
glass under the tap, fills the glass to the brim with an amber
liquid topped off by a slightly foamy head. She slides the pint
across the bar to a parched customer. It's a scene repeated
endlessly in bars and restaurants, but this pint is different: It's
brimming not with beer but with fermented ``hard'' cider. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-ROBOTS (San Francisco) _ Two summers ago, the world was
enthralled by the skateboard-sized Mars robot, Sojourner, venturing
like an excited puppy around the Red Planet. But Sojourner looks
like a lazy pooch compared to the futuristic robo-critters being
developed by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. By
KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SFO-PARKING (San Francisco) _ The civil grand jury has issued a
scathing report advocating the elimination of free VIP parking
privileges at San Francisco International Airport, saying the
system had become comparable to an ``old boy's network.'' The
report said the free parking program smacks of ``improper
favoritism'' and found that one airport commissioner doled out 27
of the passes, 12 more than commissioners hand out. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ The San Francisco Bay Area's
own Richard North Patterson once again proves that he is at the top
of his game. His latest richly textured legal thriller, ``Dark
Lady'' (Random House, $25.95, 371 pages), begins with the bizarre
deaths of two of Steelton's most prominent men _ ``the drug
dealers' lawyer of choice,'' Jack Novak, and Tommy Fielding, the
general manager of the firm building a baseball stadium for the
Steelton Blues. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-OUTDOORS (Freeport, Maine) _ Fly-fishing has been part of
the L.L. Bean business since its inception in 1912. Today, the L.L.
Bean Outdoor Discovery Schools offer instruction ranging from
introductory courses, such as a one-day workshop where anglers
learn the fundamentals, to an advanced trip to Western Maine. The
schools teach a little bit about the state's favorite recreations
and a lot about the outdoors. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ The travel mailbox is frequently
filled with tales of woes. But once in a while, we encounter
someone who walks that extra mile to make our trips more memorable.
Good samaritans do still exist all over the world. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BERKELEY-BEARS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ This year's football
team at the University of California at Berkeley includes six
players with deep roots in Nigeria. Already there is talk of a
poster for ``The Nigerian Connection.'' By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HOMER-DERBY (Oakland, Calif.) _ Two good things can come
from this season's Sosa-McGwire sequel. One is variety: Sammy Sosa
wins the home-run title this time, toppling Goliath, tying or
breaking Mark McGwire's record of 70. The other is monotony. The
two sluggers make the public numb and we start to look around at
the other boys of summer, and we notice something more interesting,
more important to the long-term well-being of the game. By GWEN
KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Don't just take my word that the
California Legislature's ban on ``junk guns'' is junk. The most
pro-gun person and the most anti-gun person in Sacramento _ Green
Party Assemblywoman Audie Bock and National Rifle Association
lobbyist Steve Helsley _ both think it's junk, too. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Religious conviction is a
wonderful thing. Frankly, though, I'm getting sick of being beaten
over the head with the religious views of other people. I'm also
disturbed at seeing those convictions take on the force of law, as
seems to be happening in Kansas, where the state school board voted
effectively to ban the teaching of evolution in public schools. By
DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ Recent hate crimes weigh
heavily on me. They are a reminder that no matter how American I
may feel, there are some Americans who will not see beyond my
so-called ``non-white'' features. They see me, and others like me,
and African Americans, and Latinos, and even ``white'' people who
are Jews and ``white'' people who are gays and lesbians, as
inferior or unworthy. They see us as targets of opportunity _ to
kill, to maim. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
