<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX     08-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fear of bugs makes Canada trip a nightmare
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELEE ISLAND, Ontario _ For the last two nights I've been
sleeping on a camp cot on the front porch of a defunct restaurant
on the southernmost inhabited port of entry to Canada. For the last
two nights I've slept with a cricket under my bed and I don't know
who's jumpier, Jiminy or me.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs and I don't get along well, so when my ex-sister-in-law
Sharon (we used to be married to brothers but now we're not) told
me to pack up and get on the plane, I dragged my feet a bit trying
to wring out some answers to a few basic
</P>
<P>
   questions.
</P>
<P>
   Me: Are there any bugs?
</P>
<P>
   Sharon: Hmm? (an obvious stall)
</P>
<P>
   Me: Is there a toilet inside?
</P>
<P>
   Sharon: Three of 'em. It used to be a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Me: Are there any bugs?
</P>
<P>
   Sharon: Hmm?
</P>
<P>
   I came anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The plane ride is cool because I've always been into anything
noisy with wings _ unless, of course, it's a bug. The trip lasts
only 10 minutes, so before I can say, ``I'm outta here'' and head
back to civilization, I find myself standing beside a grassy runway
with a change of underwear and a cooler full of hot dogs. Robin and
Pat are there to meet us. Sharon had told me I'd love them.
``They're as goofy as we are,'' were her exact words.
</P>
<P>
   The girls load us into ``Old Blue,'' a 25-year-old pickup with
cobwebs where the windows should have been, and head for the west
side of the island. They
</P>
<P>
   chit-chat while I check for spiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick a bed,'' Robin says, waving a hand in the direction of
the screened-in front porch. There are ten of them. I make like
Goldilocks and try a few,
</P>
<P>
   avoiding the corners where creatures with many legs might be
lurking. My first choice turns out to be full of sand. I complain.
Robin tells me to get over it
</P>
<P>
   and reminds me that I'm still on probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No complaining until you've been adopted into the family.''
</P>
<P>
   I ask when that might be. She just shrugs, picks up her ukulele
and breaks into raucous song.
</P>
<P>
   This clan to which I am being apprenticed does not fit the
standard definition of family. Rather, it is a collection of gently
worn, slightly over-the-hill broads who've known each other longer
than anyone cares to admit, hell-bent on enjoying life. Sharon
joined at the beginning of summer and has recommended me for
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Robin wraps up the second verse of ``Ain't She Sweet'' and
announces it's timefor a game of Skip-Bo. Never heard of it. Pat
pulls out the cards and Sharon
</P>
<P>
   begins clearing the round table. I beg off since I haven't
finished checking under my bed for crawly things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lizzie,'' Robin bellows, ``what in the hell are you doing?'' I
dust off my knees and confess. Robin shakes her head and reminds me
we're on an island and
</P>
<P>
   the bugs were here first. She also tells me where I can find
``sympathy'' in the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   It's well past the witching hour before the hotly-contested card
game ends and everyone settles down. ``Night, Pat.'' ``G`night
Sharon.'' ``Night, Robin.'' We
</P>
<P>
   sound like a rerun of the Waltons.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the night silence closes in, muffling all but the lapping
of the lake waves against the seawall just fifty feet from my bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chirrup!'' Silence. ''CHIR-RUP!'' It's stereophonic crickets
and they're homing in on me. I abandon my bed and somebody hollers
at me for jumping onto theirs. I try to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Robin's not buying it and tells me I'm being silly. ``You're
bigger than those bugs,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' I grumble, ``but they're uglier. They're waiting to
catch me off guard so they can eat my socks.'' Someone throws a
pillow. Somebody else groans.
</P>
<P>
   Robin reminds me I'm still on probation and that if I don't
shape up I won't be invited back next weekend for Thanksgiving
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In August?'' I whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just not getting it,'' Robin warns Sharon in the
darkness. Somebody else sighs regretfully. I may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night, Sharon.'' ``G`night, Pat.'' ``Night, Robin and Mary.''
``Shut up
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
