<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX     08-24 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students as warheads
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Odessa Permian High should have listened to
Dorothy. What you're searching for you can find right in your
backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The school went all the way to Sandia Laboratories, the nuclear
think tank in Albuquerque, N.M., for ways to make itself super
secure. Judging by the results portrayed in Time magazine, a
long-distance mission was unnecessary. All Permian High had to do
was toddle up to Texas's Wallace Unit, a minimum-to-medium security
prison for 1,500, and take snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, Texans having to ask New Mexicans how to make a high
school into a prison. Correct me if I'm wrong, but didn't Texas
invent prisons?
</P>
<P>
   Permian High is now a secure campus: A perimeter fence. Outdoor
security cameras. Cameras in every room. ID badges with bar codes
for scanning. Portable metal detectors. Drug and alcohol test kits,
and dogs at the ready for sniffing explosives or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Permian students are being schooled on a '90s version of the Red
Scare's ``duck and cover.'' In this case the drill is ``stop and
drop it,'' only it's no drill. School officials seal off a hall.
Every student puts down whatever he or she is carrying _ backpacks,
purses _ for a metal-detector swipe.
</P>
<P>
   We needed a nuclear scientist to advise us on this? Didn't
Stalin already write the book?
</P>
<P>
   At this stage _ hysteria, Code Blue _ we aren't supposed to be
pondering issues like whether students have any civil rights or
whether, in nuclear arms parlance, we have engineered a case of
mutually assured overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   We are to ignore the statistics that tell us that last year
nationwide school violence went down. Student drug use went down.
Weapon incidents went down.
</P>
<P>
   That can't be true, we say. We know what we saw on TV.
</P>
<P>
   What went up, of course, was ``incidents'' that involved pranks
and hoaxes. ``Incidents'' involving children questioned for saying
something scary. ``Incidents'' involving students acting out or
pushing someone's fashion envelope. (While most Columbine kids wore
white unity T-shirts back to school, a few wore black. Were SWAT
teams called?)
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the new school year brings an armory attitude and,
one worries, a quest for thought control.
</P>
<P>
   A lonely but welcome voice on this matter has been Diana Philip,
Texas director of the American Civil Liberties Union. She writes
not just about the legal aspects of civil liberties on campus but
also the human aspects of a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools can lead the way in teaching tolerance and respect and
demonstrating that 'different isn't dangerous,' '' wrote Philip in
the Dallas Morning News. Instead, too often now it's just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Katz, a contributor to Rolling Stone, wrote a commentary on
``geek profiling'' on the Web site SlashDot. The real Columbine
story wasn't about gunfire but about a nationwide conformity
shakedown, ``a nightmare for kids who are different.''
</P>
<P>
   His words struck a chord with young people who had stories to
tell of being psychologically brutalized by peers and by their
schools. Their e-mails, by the thousands, caused the SlashDot site
to crash.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dual dimension to what we saw last spring, and in both
dimensions we must proceed with more moderation than we're prone.
On one hand you have the physical oppression of a security
crackdown. On the other hand you have the psychological crackdown,
with too little opportunity for the average kid to express what
might be going on in his or her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to mass perceptions, students do have rights, including
free speech rights reinforced by the Supreme Court in 1969. It put
a burden on schools to demonstrate that prohibited expression is
disruptive or disorderly.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but if we can convince ourselves that these are not students
but warheads waiting to detonate, we can dispense with all that.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
