<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN25-CO     08-24 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEYTALK: Decide where to put your investment
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning investors have a number of choices to make as they
start building an investment plan.
</P>
<P>
   There are emotional questions, particularly regarding how much
volatility you can live with. There are knowledge questions,
involving how much you know about investing and how much time
you're willing to spend learning more.
</P>
<P>
   Another square-one decision is where you'll put your investment
money. Will it be in the comfort of mutual funds, or in the riskier
but sometimes more rewarding option of buying individual stocks?
</P>
<P>
   For some, the decision is already made.
</P>
<P>
   You may have a 401(k) plan that limits your choices to mutual
funds. You may work for a corporation that gives employees a
discount on company stock.
</P>
<P>
   But most people have room to make some decisions for themselves.
Lee Jenkins, an investment manager with Raymond James &AMP; Associates
in Atlanta, has been helping customers over this hurdle for 13
years. He has some interesting thoughts on the pros and cons of
mutual funds vs. stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds have important advantages. A major one is
diversification _ a basic need for all investors because it
diffuses your risk. ``The average mutual fund has about 100
stocks,'' Jenkins said. ``If one or two or three of them perform
very poorly, it won't affect the portfolio as negatively.''
</P>
<P>
   The second plus is that you are hiring a pro to manage your
portfolio. You don't have to pick all those stocks yourself, and
you don't need to worry about when to sell them or where the market
is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to look at it every day,'' said Jenkins.
``Someone else is doing the worrying for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds do have disadvantages, however. One is what Jenkins
describes as overdiversification. ``The problem is that there are
only so many good stocks out there,'' he explained. ``Your manager
may end up buying stocks he doesn't want to buy, just because he
has to put the money to work. No mutual fund manager has 100 great
ideas. He'll have 20 or 30 great ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem: You could take a beating in a down
market, even if you don't succumb to panic selling. Some investors
will panic, forcing money managers to make distress sales that
lower the value of shares held by less excitable investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Lynch said that the 1987 crash was a time he should have
been buying stocks for the Magellan fund,'' said Jenkins. ``But he
had to sell stocks to meet the redemption requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are a different matter entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The big advantage is that you can make a lot of money if you
pick the right stocks. If you bought Internet stocks in the last
few years, you were probably a winner.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes you picked the particular Internet companies that
prospered, rather than road kill on the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is imperative that you don't make a mistake buying one or
two or three stocks,'' Jenkins said. ``If you get it wrong, you can
lose big, and there's nothing else in your portfolio to offset the
decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, investing in individual stocks has other advantages that
mutual funds do not.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can control your tax liabilities if you buy
stocks. A mutual fund manager buys and sells stocks all the time,
and each of those decisions can create taxable profits.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Jenkins said, ``With an individual stock, if you
don't want to sell, you don't have to. You can let your gains run,
or you could rack up some losses to offset gains.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a psychological benefit to owning stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about owning a stock like Home Depot and
being able to drive down the street and see that big orange sign,''
Jenkins said. ``It makes you feel good. You've got more of a
feeling of security. It makes investing tangible.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's that one huge disadvantage _ picking
your own stocks. It can be a complex, intimidating process. Even
the experts don't get it right all the time. If they did, they
wouldn't be making a living by telling you what to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
