<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-PAWN-BUSINESS25-COX     08-24 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAWN-BUSINESS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong economy makes business difficult for pawnshops
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ These are tough days in the pawn business.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy and record-low unemployment means fewer people
are in hock _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   Pawnshops such as EZ Pawn, the nation's second-largest chain
behind Fort Worth's Cash America International, are feeling it.
</P>
<P>
   When it released its earnings recently, EZCorp., the
Austin-based parent of the EZ Pawn chain, said a ``soft pawn
economy'' and declining loan demand helped push down the company's
earnings in the fiscal third quarter ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's loan volume is still growing, same-store
increases dropped to 13 percent from 17 percent a year ago.
EZCorp.'s gross profit margin also slipped to 13 percent from 19
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Lambiase, EZCorp.'s chief executive, said the company
also is feeling price pressure from retailers selling new goods and
competition from more lax credit standards by credit-card issuers.
As a result, the company is lowering its price structure across the
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on current trends, we expect the slowdown in loan growth
and lower margins on merchandise sales to continue,'' he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pawn companies' stocks are hurting, too. Shares in both EZCorp.
and Cash America recently hit 52-week lows. EZCorp. closed at $5.68
Monday, down nearly 43 percent from its high of $9.88 on Oct. 27.
However, it has rebounded from a low of $4.50 on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bostwick, 21, now goes to pawnshops to buy things, not
pawn them, since he graduated from college seven months ago and
started working full time as an assistant manager at a local
grocery store called Mr. Grocers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used them more when I was in school, only working part time,
and needed money,'' he said, leaving Doc Holliday Pawnbrokers last
week after buying some Game Boy tapes. He and his wife, Kerrylynn,
have bought a television and air conditioner from pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels better,'' she said of being a buyer instead of a
borrower. ``We're not worried about how to get something out. We've
got a little money now.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, pawnshops have been regarded as a bad-times
industry that thrives on economic downturns, according to Tom Horn
of the National Pawnbrokers Association. Pawnshops generally make
most of their money on loans to borrowers who put up merchandise in
return. Loans can range in value from less than $10 to several
hundred dollars,
</P>
<P>
   Pawn companies charge higher interest than banks, generally 15
percent to 20 percent per month. If borrowers fail to make their
loan payments, the pawnshops sell the collateral merchandise,
usually after 90 days. About 75 percent of customers return for
their items.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its reliance on loans, Horn said pawnshops are not
part of a counter-cyclical industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're talking about a downturn in the economy, that means
people have a higher tendency to not come pay back the loans,''
Horn said, adding that the average loan is $72. ``Then the
pawnbroker ends up with no repayment and a floor full of jewelry
and electronics that he does not want,'' and which may not be sold
in times of recession, when customers avoid spending sprees.
</P>
<P>
   At EZCorp., the strong economy has Lambiase watching closely to
make sure his stores don't overextend credit now and suffer later.
</P>
<P>
   Lambiase calls the pawn business ``one of the most effective
barometers of the economy I've ever been involved with.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Nagle, an assistant manager at South Lamar Pawn, one of six
area pawnshops owned by Action Pawn, said he started noticing a
drop in loan activity in March or April 1998. A lot more people are
paying off their loans, too, he said _ and taking less time to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early '90s _ '93, '94 and '95 _ were the best times, when
the economy was still down and everyone was getting over the
recession,'' he added. Inventory on the sales floor, items sold
outright or forfeited on loans, also is down these days, he said.
``It's kind of a seller's market right now,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get him wrong, though. There still are plenty of people
coming to pawnshops for loans.
</P>
<P>
   There are always regular customers who depend on pawnshops to
help them make it to the next payday, said John Burch, manager of
an EZ Pawn store. ``And there are always emergencies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davidson went to an EZ Pawn shop one day last week to hock
his golf clubs for $150. The computer consultant, who pulled up in
a Porsche and wearing a tie, doesn't exactly fit the pawnshop
stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody wrote me a bad check,'' he said. ``I've got to get
some money in the bank to cover it. This is quick. This is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson promised he'd be back to EZ Pawn in two or three days
to pick up his clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pawn shop will charge me $15 interest,'' he said. ``That's
a lot less than the $75 the bank will charge.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pletz writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
