<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DNA-DADS25-COX     08-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-DADS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DNA tests sometimes help 'dad'
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Men challenging child support claims are
finding that genetic testing may be their best defense if they have
doubts about who's the father.
</P>
<P>
   The state uses DNA testing, a science of the 1990s, to identify
fathers; defense attorneys use it to contest paternity claims
brought against ex-husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Revenue, which enforces child support
payments, tested 1,025 fathers in Florida's Palm Beach, Martin,
Okeechobee and Indian River counties last year. A surprising number
had no genetic relationship to the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 36 percent of the cases, dad wasn't dad,'' said Dave Bruns,
a spokesman for the agency. He said the four-county region accounts
for about 10 percent of the DNA tests ordered across the state by
the department.
</P>
<P>
   DNA leaves no doubts, said Dr. Jerry Tankersley, who operates a
suburban West Palm Beach lab that collects blood or saliva samples
for genetic testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a definitive, black-and-white, yes-and-no kind of a test
that does resolve the question,'' Tankersley said.
</P>
<P>
   The science may be indisputable, but DNA may not get all men off
the hook if they wait too long to challenge paternity, said Matthew
Nugent, a West Palm Beach attorney who specializes in family law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cases where people have shown that they are not the
father, but because they didn't object at the time of the divorce,
they are stuck with that judgment,'' Nugent said. ``In civil cases,
you don't get a second bite at the apple.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 9, the 2nd District Court of Appeal issued an opinion
about a Central Florida man who suspected he was not the father,
but failed to raise the paternity question until nine years after
his divorce. The court said he could not escape child support
payments even though a DNA test proved he was not the father. The
man acted as legal father of the child for a decade and could be
obligated to continue paying ``as a matter of contract law,'' the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before that opinion, a Wellington man fared better in
Palm Beach County Circuit Court on his challenge of a 1986
child-support judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Murray, 40, had claimed he married in 1984 thinking that he
was the biological father of his bride's 2-year-old daughter. The
couple had another child during the marriage and divorced in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Murray says he did not know he wasn't the girl's father until
1994. During the first eight years after the divorce, Murray fell
$32,675 behind in child support for both the girl and his son.
</P>
<P>
   His ex-wife, Shelley Akins, has testified that Murray had ``full
knowledge'' when they married that the girl wasn't his and agreed
to raise her as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Akins' testimony in 1994, the courts wouldn't relieve
Murray of his obligations to the girl without a DNA test. Murray
said he waited until March to have the testing because he couldn't
afford the $500 fee.
</P>
<P>
   The test, which uses blood or saliva samples from the mother,
child and alleged father, showed Murray's probability of being the
father at zero percent.
</P>
<P>
   So Circuit Judge Roger Colton on June 25 erased Murray's debts
for the girl. The ruling left Murray with $15,057 in past debts for
his son. Murray says he cannot pay the debt or his continuing
$40-a-week payments to the son because he's unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Family-law attorneys say Murray probably would not have won the
ruling had the mother objected to DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   While the state spends $1.6 million a year on DNA tests to
determine paternity, it will not pay for tests to disprove
paternity, Bruns said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When fathers come to us, our position is that it's an issue
they need to take up with the court,'' Bruns said. ``Our job is not
to prove a man is not the father; our job is to collect child
support from the father.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the man accepts paternal responsibility in a divorce or
other court proceeding, the revenue department ``generally
opposes'' DNA testing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DNA paternity testing is booming, partly because states like
Florida require a woman applying for public assistance to name a
child's father. The American Association of Blood Banks, which
licenses genetic labs, estimates 250,000 DNA paternity tests were
done nationwide in 1997, compared to 75,000 tests using mostly
blood samples in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Men are wrongly named ars in about one third of paternity
tests, said Dr. Elizabeth Panke, director of Genetica DNA
Laboratories in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Panke said most of Genetica's tests are to establish paternity,
but not all for child support. Some unmarried couples want the test
so their children can qualify for the father's retirement and
insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Douthat writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
