A7594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HAIR-MAKEOVER25-COX     08-24 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-MAKEOVER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Solution to hairstyle conundrum is cut and dried
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Get this.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Fulp was so protective of her hip-length hair that when she
lived in Nashville, Tenn., she would fly to Ocala, Fla. to get it
cut. She trusted no one else. Even when she moved to Tequesta,
she'd drive the three-plus hours to her hometown for a trim.
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida heat got to her. Earlier this summer, Fulp
ducked into some nameless local salon and got 6 inches whacked off,
a stunning amount for her. ``My hair is part of me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her hairstyle hadn't changed since high school, but Fulp was
finally in the mood. If she left her hair down, her two kids pulled
it. If she put it in a top knot, she noticed hair loss at her
temples.
</P>
<P>
   So she went to the Babor Institute in Palm Beach for a makeover
_ on her 33rd birthday, no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what to do with it,'' she told stylist
George Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott listened to her hair history _ never any color, a perm
or two _ and learned that Fulp stays home to take care of the kids
and renovate the house. ``I want it to be easy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor: Fulp's husband, Bob, would pass out if she came
home with short hair. No problem. ``It's nice one length,'' Elliott
said. ``Long and pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   But heavy. Elliott immediately trimmed 3 more inches, and
suddenly Fulp had the shortest hair she'd had in years. For extra
bounce without extra time in front of the mirror, Elliott gave Fulp
a loose body perm.
</P>
<P>
   While she waited for the perm to set, Fulp plotted. Why not buy
a short blond wig on the way home and shock poor Bob into fits?
</P>
<P>
   Elliott put Fulp in hot rollers to give her hair some temporary
lift. Makeup artist Julia Holguin reached for earth tones _ light
brown and blue-gray on the eyes, natural beige foundation, and
maroon lipstick for Fulp's strongest feature, her lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warm is her most natural look,'' Holguin said.
</P>
<P>
   Once primped and spritzed, Fulp said she felt lighter and
fluffier already.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, she was happy to report that she could wear her
hair down, even while swimming, and it didn't get in anyone's way.
</P>
<P>
   And the wig?
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't find one in time to fool her husband, but she got
him anyway. ``I pulled back my hair so it looked short,'' she said.
``Boy, he had a funny look.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
