NYT-08-24-99 1120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOME-DECOR25-COX     08-24 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DECOR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    African decor centers on family, spirit
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Walk into Curtis Polk's Pflugerville home, and
you notices three things: Texas-size furniture, warm colors and
artworks by well-known African American artists Keith Mallett and
Albert Fennell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come into your home, you need to feel comfortable,''
Polk said to explaining the furniture and the sky-blue and
earth-brown colors. Yet it's the lithographs and radiographs that
broadcast the Polk home's soul, especially the work of Mallett.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first Mallett lithographs Polk purchased hangs over
the corner fireplace in the living room. The picture features three
black women with different shades of skin complexion, which Polk
said appeals to his sense of cultural diversity. On the connecting
wall is another lithograph of an African American father holding a
child with a swatch of multicolored Kente cloth. The lithograph is
hangs above an ample love seat that matches the room's textured,
multihued sofa and armchair. Across the room from the television is
Polk's favorite armchair and above it are two radiographs by Albert
Fennell. The black-background drawings, one of a man and one of a
woman, are mounted in a single frame. Polk said he wanted the two
artworks together to illustrate the importance of couplehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Mallett's artwork is related to the family, men and
women, relationships and children,'' Polk said. ``It makes me think
of my family, think of times back in the day. I always had the love
and care of my parents in the home.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Polk said, the artwork is about having beautiful images of
people who look like him and infusing his home with art that speaks
to his African American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't alone: Today, more people are permeating their home,
and sometimes office, decor with artworks and artifacts that
reflect the African American experience or connect them to Africa.
Polk and other Austinites speak of cultural heritage and
spiritualism when they talk of their desire to combine African
American and African art in their homes. They are taken by the
colors, intricacy of the handwork and form and shape of the pieces
they have acquired.
</P>
<P>
   And they are very much in step with a decorating sentiment that
has gained momentum since the 1980s among middle-class Americans,
who are making African motifs and palettes a style basic in
interior design.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 40 years, Bertha Means has regularly traveled the
African continent, visiting family and friends in several nations.
Each time she returns to her Northwest Austin home, pieces of those
journeys come with her in hand-crafted artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The most beloved piece is probably the Ethiopian pictograph
depicting the ancient legend of King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba
in the dining room. ``When I look at it now, it brings back family
memories,'' said Means' granddaughter Inning Khabele-Stevens, whose
parents had a similar pictograph hanging in their home.
</P>
<P>
   Through the decades Means' collecting included items such as an
old Benin bronze head of a man that sits on an ivory-colored
pedestal near the living room. Adorning the dining room table is a
Kenyan sculpture hand-carved from a single piece of mahogany that
features several interlocking human figures.
</P>
<P>
   But ``African art was never created for its own sake. It was
made to communicate or reinforce morals, values and principles,
such as respect for the ancestors or elders, motherhood or for the
kingship,'' said Khabele-Stevens, a local artist who grew up in
Botswana, Nigeria and Lesotho before moving to Austin as a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   To Western people, African art is beautiful and intriguing, said
Khabele-Stevens, who studied African art and history in college.
But to Africans, ``the purpose of art is a reminder of purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVonne Mason has a deep affection for old African masks and
antique European-style furniture. She has blended both aesthetics
in her Northwest Austin home. She said her attraction to the masks
started in the early 1970s when she purchased her first pieces,
such as the large, impressive black and gold tribal mask in the
living room. ``It has lots of character,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   A spiritual connection
</P>
<P>
   While Mason consulted with Jan Moss, an Arlington, Texas-based
interior designer, in selecting art and other furnishings, a source
for anyone wanting to incorporate the African-inspired design
aesthetic in their home is the book ``The Spirit of African
Design'' (Clarkson Potter, $35) by Sharne Algotsson and Denys
Davis, interior designers from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The African-inspired aesthetic isn't just about stylishly
placing artifacts, textiles and art in a room, Algotsson said, it's
about making a cultural and spiritual connection between the home's
decor and the people who live in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to express their love of Africa in their home,''
Algotsson said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the African aesthetic complements any decorating style,
whether it's traditional or contemporary, formal or funky,
Algotsson said it is becoming a design staple _ much like French
provincial or American traditional _ going into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people consciously keeping it a design
style,'' Algotsson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, art in the African aesthetic meant expensive,
rare pieces that were off limits to the average person. Those who
acquired it were in the high-end art market or worked for
museums,'' Algotsson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, African American and African art is in the mainstream.
Giant retailers, such as Pier 1 Imports and JCPenney, have these
home furnishings. ``These companies wouldn't be investing in
African design if they didn't see its staying power,'' Algotsson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Waly Faye, owner of Goui-Gui in Austin, said he has seen the
African-inspired design aesthetic grow in the 10 years he has
imported art, crafts and artifacts from his native Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Djembe drum, which is native to his homeland,
is often purchased because the buyer thinks it will look nice in
the home. But, Faye said with a smile, ``you never know when one
will start playing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to bring in things the people will appreciate,'' Faye
said.
</P>
<P>
   And at the end of the day, as Polk said, you must be comfortable
in your home. African American art and African-inspired design
makes that possible for many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when I look at the African masks, I think that could
be somebody I know, somebody I grew up with,'' Polk said. ``I like
Picasso, would love to own a painting, but his art doesn't look
like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: nmartin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   African design tips
</P>
<P>
   Design elements: The elements of African-inspired design are as
wide-ranging and multifaceted as the continent that inspired the
style, but most of the objects, artifacts and art have some
spiritual and/or cultural connection to Africa or the African
American experience. Some key points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Colors are usually warm and/or vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most patterns are intricately designed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Objects, such as quality sculptures and masks, are created by
hand and of natural materials, such as wood or clay.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive flair: Large pieces of hand-woven African textiles
can be expensive, but an affordable alternative is to buy a yard or
two for throw pillows as accents for sofas, chairs or beds.
</P>
<P>
   If original paintings or drawings are beyond the budget, most
well-known African American artists produce affordable prints of
their work that are suitable for framing.
</P>
<P>
   Books: ``Collecting African American Art: Works on Paper and
Canvas'' (Random House, $50) by Halima Taha.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spirit of African Design'' (Clarkson Potter, $35) by
Sharne Algotsson and Denys Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: nmartin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
