NYT-08-24-99 1120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTS-N-BOLTS25-COX     08-24 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-N-BOLTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NUTS &AMP; BOLTS: Ceiling-fan fix is a breeze
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ceiling fans help keep you cool inexpensively, and they're an
excellent supplement to air conditioning. But occasionally fans
develop wobbles that cut down on their efficiency and make them
noisy and annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Often you can correct a shimmying fan, but it may take a little
time and experimentation before the fan is running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspection
</P>
<P>
   You may be able to get an idea about what's causing your fan to
wobble just by observing it carefully while it's running. Turn it
on and watch how it operates at different speeds. Most fans have
high, medium and low settings, and you change from one speed to
another by pulling a chain.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the fan in motion, turn it off and get on a
ladder for a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   Manually move the blades around and look for obvious differences
in the blades. For instance, is one blade pitched at a different
angle or obviously warped?
</P>
<P>
   With a tape measure or yardstick, measure the distance from the
ceiling to the tip of a fan blade. Leave the tape measure in the
same position and rotate the next blade around to see if it is the
same distance from the ceiling. Repeat with each blade, noting if
any are out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Like a tire on your car, a fan must be balanced and perfectly
level or it can't spin in a smooth, level manner.
</P>
<P>
   Take a careful look at all the brackets (sometimes called blade
irons) that hold the blades of the fan to the motor housing. All of
them should be in good shape and affixed at exactly the same angle.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, inspect the hardware holding the fan to the ceiling.
Cut power to the fan circuit by disengaging the circuit breaker or
removing the fuse connected to the fan.
</P>
<P>
   With a helper supporting the weight of the fan, loosen the
covering over the support system at the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Ceiling fans should be attached to an electrical box affixed
securely to a cross bar or bracket attached between two ceiling
joists. An electrical box is a square or hexagonal box of plastic
or metal used to wire outlets, ceiling lights or fans.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases you may find the fan has been attached to an
electrical box screwed through one side to a single joist. In other
cases, you'll find the fan attached directly to a plaster or
drywall ceiling using bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these methods are adequate to keep a ceiling fan
steady and should be replaced. Consult a ceiling-fan retailer for
advice on rehanging your fan.
</P>
<P>
   If the fan is properly installed, tighten all the screws holding
it in place and reattach the cover. Also tighten the screws holding
the blades to their brackets.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring balance
</P>
<P>
   Earl Elworth, manager of Dan's Fan City in Miami Township, Ohio,
said tightening the hardware sometimes significantly improves the
fan's performance. But most often more tinkering is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to your observations from earlier and start working on
correcting any problems you noticed.
</P>
<P>
   A badly warped blade must be replaced, Elworth said. If you
suspect a blade is warped, remove it from its bracket by loosening
the screws. Place the blade on a flat surface to see if it is
level.
</P>
<P>
   If one or more blades on the fan are warped, Elworth suggests
replacing the entire set. The chances of finding one blade that
perfectly matches the shape, look and weight of the others on a fan
are fairly slim, and you should be able to find a whole replacement
set for about $15 to $30 where fans are sold.
</P>
<P>
   If the blades are all good, try adjusting the brackets to make
sure the blades are properly aligned. If the tip of one blade is
lower or higher than the others, firmly grasp the bracket and
gently try to bend it back into line.
</P>
<P>
   Elworth said this is easiest with inexpensive fans with
relatively lightweight brackets. Sturdier brackets are less likely
to get out of line, but when they do go bad they're very difficult
to correct.
</P>
<P>
   Sets of replacement brackets are also available for about $15 to
$25, Elworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this brings up a point I've made before: It doesn't
make a lot of sense to spend $25 on trying to fix a 10-year-old fan
that was only worth $50 in the first place. Sometimes it's better
to shop for a better fan.
</P>
<P>
   If the blades are aligned and the fan still wobbles, the problem
might be in the balance of weight between the blades. Correcting an
imbalance is basically a trial-and-error process.
</P>
<P>
   Try switching the positions of some of the fan's blades. Take
off two adjacent blades and swap their positions. Turn on the fan
at different speeds to see if there's any improvement, then repeat
the process with the other blades.
</P>
<P>
   If the fan still wobbles, you may need to add weight to one of
the blades. Dan's Fan City and other retailers sell inexpensive
balancing kits (about $2) that may help.
</P>
<P>
   The kits come with a plastic clip that is fastened to the rear
edge of a blade. You attach the clip and run the fan to see if the
added weight helps the performance. Repeat with each blade and
compare your results.
</P>
<P>
   If adding weight to a particular blade corrects the wobble, you
remove the clip and affix a small weight that comes with the repair
kit.
</P>
<P>
   You can accomplish the same thing without a balancing kit by
testing the fan with metal washers and tape. When you find the
blade that needs weight, permanently install the washer by slipping
it over the bolt holding the blade to its bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Once a fan is balanced, it should continue to run smoothly
without much maintenance. Consult your owner's manual for tips on
taking care of the fan, but an occasional dusting with a soft brush
or lint-free cloth is typically all they need.
</P>
<P>
   Elworth said many fan owners use dusting devices specially
designed for ceiling fans. The devices have poles with looped
brushes on the end that are slipped over the fan blades to clean
the tops and bottoms of the blades at once.
</P>
<P>
   Elworth said extreme care should be used when using such
devices. He said many customers have damaged fans by bearing down
too hard while dusting their blades.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE AN IDEA, question or concern? Contact James Cummings at
jamescummings(AT)coxohio.com; or write to the Features Department,
Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio 45402. This story
includes information from the Reader's Digest New Fix-It-Yourself
Manual.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
