<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-5THINGS25     08-24 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-5THINGS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five issues that might determine the success of the Cowboys
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ They talk a good game and still look
slick in those silver uniforms. The who's who list of NFL
superstars contains a fair share of Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   But just how battle ready is the 1999 Cowboys edition?
</P>
<P>
   A month of training camp in the unmerciful Texas sauna has
yielded more questions than answers. Dallas is the league's mystery
team. Depending on which voice you trust, the Cowboys will finish
the season anywhere from 6-10 to 12-4. They can be a Super Bowl
contender or a team that dies before New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Have these guys become a bore?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three weeks remaining before the opener in
Washington, here are five tough issues that might determine the
success of the NFL's most intriguing cast of characters:
</P>
<P>
   1) The Spellman factor
</P>
<P>
   For the record, defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban was the team's
first-round draft choice four months ago. In reality, the Cowboys
had an extra first-round pick, former Bears lineman Alonzo
Spellman. It isn't certain whether Spellman is a career bust or
someone who can rejuvenate a defensive line that has been ranked
30th out of 31 NFL teams by one magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The bipolar disorder that nearly ruined his professional life in
recent years appears under control. Spellman's arms and legs look
as strong as oak branches. His steely eyes seem fixed on
recapturing past excellence. When asked what he brings to the
Cowboys, Spellman offered a puzzled look before responding,
``You'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavika Pittman led the Cowboys with six sacks last season. Since
1964, no sack leader in Dallas has ever had fewer than six. Some
believe Spellman, who was shifted from end to tackle on Monday, is
capable of 10.
</P>
<P>
   But does he have the desire to play football again?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the best frame of mind he's been in for the last four
or five years,'' defensive coordinator Dave Campo said. ``I've
spoken many times about Alonzo to (Bears Coach) Dave Wannstedt and
people on his defensive staff. They describe him as humble, someone
who wants to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't take the Cowboys long to find out whether they still
are suspect on the line. In the second week of the season, they
will face Atlanta's Jamal Anderson, arguably the league's most
powerful insider runner.
</P>
<P>
   Will Spellman make a difference? We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   2) Rocket power
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin arguably are the
best 1-2-3 offensive combination in league history. They have led
the Cowboys in passing, rushing and receiving eight straight years,
the only time the same three players led their teams in those
respective categories.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the so-called triplets, the most
important piece to the offensive puzzle just e receiver
Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   The triplets are as predictable as a Julia Roberts movie, but
they no longer can carry a team by themselves. The only player who
can stretch opposing defenses _ giving more room for the triplets _
is Ismail. He had 69 catches for Carolina last year and has shown a
knack for catching deep passes in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail is the best deep threat in Dallas since Alvin Harper left
town four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   3) Troy's blind spot
</P>
<P>
   Ask any draft expert to name the team's most important _ and
perhaps best _ pick over the last five years, and Flozell Adams is
the overwhelming choice. The same player whose quickness and
hearing ability were questioned before the 1998 draft enters the
season with one of the team's most important duties _ protecting
Aikman's back.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has moved to left tackle, a position that has been filled
admirably by Larry Allen and the late Mark Tuinei for almost all of
Aikman's 10 seasons in the league. Aikman has been sacked fewer
than 20 times in five seasons, a remarkable number for someone on
the field as much as he is.
</P>
<P>
   Some have said the health of the team is only as strong as
Aikman's health. For now, the transition of Adams to left tackle
has been a success. Few defensive linemen have beaten him at
practice and, at 6 feet 7 inches and 335 pounds, Adams is among the
NFL's biggest men.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work as hard as Flozell works, and you have the pride
that he does, it makes you a hard man to beat,'' offensive line
coach Hudson Houck said.
</P>
<P>
   4) Behind closed doors
</P>
<P>
   One of the most confusing questions of the summer stems from the
status of Leon Lett. The most talented defensive lineman in Dallas
for a decade will serve a drug suspension at the start of the
season. But for how long? If you want an answer from Coach Chan
Gailey, look elsewhere. Gailey doesn't lie, and he claims to be
clueless on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Dallas questions whether it is fair for Lett to serve
a suspension. Many expect it will be four games, but it could be
six, eight, or even more. Commissioner Paul Taglabue's delay of the
case is not fair.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys expected a decision on Lett's status in July, just
before camp opened in Wichita Falls. That would have been fair.
Knowing how long Lett would be suspended would allow the Cowboys to
plan accordingly. If it's longer than four games, for example, team
owner Jerry Jones might choose to find a suitable tackle elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As camp prepares to close for the summer, the Cowboys are still
in the dark. Maybe Jones knows the length of the suspension and has
been told to stay quiet. A good poker player knows when he has a
good hand, and Jones does not seem overly concerned by the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Lett, by contrast, deserved to know the severity of his
suspension long before this.
</P>
<P>
   5) Confidence shaken
</P>
<P>
   The Aikman/Smith/Irvin era has been measured by Super Bowls,
something the Cowboys haven't sniffed since the end of the 1995
season. They have not made another serious challenge since then,
and it is becoming increasingly difficult to believe this year will
be any different.
</P>
<P>
   Some must wonder whether they believe it themselves. Arizona
embarrassed the Cowboys in the first round of last year's playoffs.
This summer the Cowboys haven't won a preseason game. They even
lost to the Browns. Such talk about the preseason has always been
dismissed, but it has been disturbing to see the first-team offense
and defense struggle through three games.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of reasons Dallas no longer resembles the team
that won with ease early in the decade. Only 10 players who were on
those three championship teams remain, and they do not have enough
help from their young teammates to make another run.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
