<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MUSLIM-PRISONERS25-CO     08-24 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSLIM-PRISONERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jail to add services for Muslim inmates
 &HT;    (EDS: For clarity, meeting between ACLU, prison officials was
held Friday, Aug. 20.)
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ As the rest of the Muslim world fasted
during daylight last December in observance of the month of
Ramadan, it was business as usual for Muslim inmates at the St.
Lucie County Correctional Center: Eat now or go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Now, changes are in the works, said Sieg Christman, president of
Florida's Treasure Coast chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union.
</P>
<P>
   After organization members met with St. Lucie County sheriff's
officials Friday, the jail has agreed to allow Ramadan observance
for the jail's eight Muslim inmates. It also has agreed to allow a
Jumu'ah prayer service once a month, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU officials, who asked for weekly services on Friday, said
they're thankful, but that the accommodations aren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of happy, but then we're sort of disappointed,
too,'' Christman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jeffries, an attorney for the St. Lucie County Sheriff's
Office who went to last week's meeting, said inmates had requested
services before but that scheduling Jumu'ah services was difficult
because of space constraints and jail schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholics only have Mass once a month,'' he said. ``Just
physically, it can't be done every week.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the jail would accommodate weekly services if it could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a very fruitful meeting and I think they were
genuinely surprised that we were doing all we did,'' he said,
explaining that inmate meals exclude pork, which can't be eaten
during Ramadan, an extended ritual of fasting believed to have been
commanded by Allah.
</P>
<P>
   He said inmates will be given bag lunches and dinners during
Ramadan _ which lasts either 29 or 30 days, depending on the year _
so that they can eat after sunset.
</P>
<P>
   But M. Zaman Marwat _ an imam who has been asked by ACLU
officials to lead services at the jail _ said that the religion's
worship practices cannot vary. He said he would not lead services
at the jail if Jumu'ah is allowed only once a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that we can't do it this way or that way,'' he
said. ``It's only one way it can be done. . . . It's not done for
the individual. It's done for our creator. It's his command and we
have to fulfill it.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Muslims are obligated to pray five times a day, he
said. On Jumu'ah _ the Muslim word for Friday _ one of the prayers
is replaced with a two-hour communal prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Marwat leads weekly services at the state prisons in Martin and
Okeechobee counties, he said. While inmate conversions to Islam are
a growing jailhouse phenomenon, ACLU officials said the St. Lucie
inmates were practicing Muslims before their incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteer from our board actually went out and talked to
mostly the inmates' mothers, sisters, and other relatives, who
confirmed that they had actually been practicing Muslims before,''
ACLU attorney Rosemarie Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
