<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ A look at cooling systems. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED SUNDAY.TESTDRIVE-TUNDRA _ A review of
the Toyota Tundra pickup. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Beginning investors have a number of choices to make
as they start building an investment plan. There are emotional
questions, particularly regarding how much volatility you can live
with. There are knowledge questions, involving how much you know
about investing and how much time you're willing to spend learning
more. Another square-one decision is where you'll put your
investment money. Will it be in the comfort of mutual funds, or in
the riskier but sometimes more rewarding option of buying
individual stocks? (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-CDC _ ATLANTA _ On Tuesday the CDC will release its
state-by-state report on tobacco use as well as its recommendations
on how to solve the public health problem, including funding
guidelines. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-DEEP _ ``In Too Deep.'' Cop vs. crimelord tale starring
Omar Epps, Jermaine Dupri, Pam Grier, Nia Long, LL Cool J. Grade:
B-. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-KAPLAN _ ATLANTA _ Two years into the reign of Rick Kaplan
at CNN/U.S., he has changed the corporate culture and the network's
on-air look, although not its ratings as much as he would like. Not
everyone at CNN likes the changes, but having survived Tailwind and
bested Lou Dobbs, it appears that Kaplan will continue to mold the
network the way he wants. A look at two years of changes, what's
coming in September, and what staffers are whispering about.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BUBBLY-2000 _ A lot of people may be staying home this New
Year's, but whether they're partying low-key or not, many are
snapping up the expensive bubbly. This isn't the year to settle for
Korbel, apparently. And it's not too soon to buy, if you want to
assure you get some of the good stuff. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HAIR-MAKEOVER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lisa Fulp was so
protective of her hip-length hair that when she lived in Nashville,
Tenn., she would fly to Ocala, Fla. to get it cut. She trusted no
one else. Even when she moved to Tequesta, she'd drive the
three-plus hours to her hometown for a trim. But the Florida heat
got to her. She whacked her hair. WITH PHOTOS. (Anna, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-DADS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ DNA testing is on the rise in
cases of contested paternity. Leon Murray of Wellington was stuck
with child support payments for 10 years before he decided to test
his suspicion that he was not the father of the little girl. Within
two weeks, he got a report from Genetica Labs saying the
probability that he was the father was zero. So a judge dismissed
$25,000 in child support debt owned by Murray, an unemployed
painter. Genetica and dozens of other labs are conducting about
250,000 DNA tests a year, most to settle child support disputes.
They have billboards and websites and Yellow Page listings and the
cost has dropped below $500 for the tests. (Douthat, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COLORS _ Roach brown. Blazer blue. Old parchment white. Green
No. 123. Whether gross, dull or pretentious, colors get their names
from somewhere. We check out color-namers for paints, cosmetics,
crayons, etc. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO
ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Like a fine professor for life, the garden
never stops teaching. Everlina R. Jackson grew one of the more
surprising lessons in her Southwest Atlanta space. Jackson planted
potato eyes in what she called her ``best garden ever.'' Then the
potatoes bloomed along with something that looked like cherry
tomateos. The strange growth _ ``pomato'' _ puzzled everyone,
except for one wise County Extension agent who explained the
mystery. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-DINNER _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta designers, 43 to be exact,
know how to send a table over the top, especially when they're
competing for the attention of 600 dinner guests _ and especially
when it's for a good cause. The tables will be unveiled during
Collection Rouge III: Dining by Design, a benefit for the Atlanta
chapter of the nonprofit Design Industries Foundation Fighting
AIDS, which is Monday at the Woodruff Arts Center. Unlike other
tabletop events, this one allows guests to actually dine in the
elaborate desplays and mingle to check out all the displays.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   THEME-TABLE _ If the thought of developing a dinner party theme
seems as mind boggling _ and expensive _ as buying your first home,
professional event planners have news for you: It doesn't have to
be. Three designers participating in the Collection Rouge III:
dining By Design, a benefit for the Design Industries Foundation
Fighting AIDS, share insider design secrets. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   NUTS-N-BOLTS _ Tips on keeping a ceiling fan running smoothly.
(Cummings' Dayton Daily News). MOVED.HOME-DECOR _ AUSTIN, Texas A
look at Afrocentric elements in Austin-area home decor. There are
design books out on the topic. There are some local places that
specialize in African textiles, art, and artifacts and such. WITH
African design tips box at bottom of story. (Martin, Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
