<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS TAKES A LEAP INTO THE DARK AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Not long after the Kansas Board of Education
voted effectively to ban the teaching of evolution in that state's
public schools, I went to work one day to find a book waiting for
me. It had been delivered by a guy I know _ a bright guy, a nice
guy and a guy with a firmly embedded set of religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   He'd included a note: ``Reading this book is probably the most
intelligent thing you have ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   So I read it. It's a book published by a religious group. The
title: ``Life _ How Did it Get here? By Evolution or by Creation?''
</P>
<P>
   For 250 slickly produced pages, the authors of this book argue
not only that evolution is bunk but that it's pernicious bunk
cooked up to ``serve the purposes of Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all a little much for me, frankly. Religious conviction
is a wonderful thing. It offers human beings comfort in times of
trial. It encourages us to behave in civilized ways toward others.
I understand why some people who derive deep, personal satisfaction
from their religious beliefs feel the need to pass along that gift
to others.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, though, I'm getting sick of being beaten over the head
with the religious views of other people. I'm also disturbed at
seeing those religious convictions take on the force of law, as
seems to be happening in Kansas. Once you permit people to write
religious conviction into law, you're only a step away from
confronting some updated version of Tomas de Torquemada or the
Ayatollah Khomeini. Those guys figured they'd cornered the market
on truth, too.
</P>
<P>
   What disturbs me most, though, about this divisive battle
between creationism and evolution is the determination of the
reactionary side to deny others the use of God's most precious gift
to humanity. That's our power to think.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for evidence of a divine spark that
distinguishes our species from all others, you can find it most
vividly in our ability to gather evidence, assess it and to form
conclusions from it. We can do that because we've been granted
unique cognitive skills.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can we solve problems _ the square peg in the square
hole stuff _ but we also have the capacity for abstract or symbolic
thought. That uniquely human ability is what permits you to look
upon the letters on this page, or to hear the sounds that these
letters represent, and to glean from them meaning that's denied
lesser creatures.
</P>
<P>
   The problem I have with creationism is not just the
anti-intellectualism it represents. I object to creationism because
it represents a desperate denial of our most basic human trait.
That's our ability _ our sacred duty, actually _ to draw rational
conclusions about what we see around us.
</P>
<P>
   Creationists are unwilling to accept any view of divine
direction that's not spelled out in a book that many people of
intense religious faith do not take literally. The creationists
simply are unwilling to look upon the vast evidence supporting the
theory of evolution as an indication that we thinking humans have
uncovered clues about one of the mechanisms by which a supreme
being carried out creation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that acceptance of evolution can't be part of a logical
system of devoted religious belief. The polls indicate that, for
most Americans, that's precisely what it is. For some, though, no
religious belief counts except the one they adhere to in each and
every minute detail. Not only are they determined to shove those
beliefs down everybody else's throat eery time the opportunity
presents itself, they believe it's their obligation to do so.
That's what happened in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   And, please, don't kid yourself that it can't happen where you
live.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S GUN LAW MISSES ITS TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You may have heard that the California Assembly
approved a ``junk gun'' ban last week. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   The only junk involved was the legislation itself, which Gov.
Gray Davis has promised to sign. After state Sen. Richard Polanco's
bill passed, Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa said, ``Now we
can say to the people of the state that we've kept our promise to
get rid of cheap and unsafe handguns.''
</P>
<P>
   That's complete bunk.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in the bill about the price of handguns. The
safety procedures it specifies will only benefit manufacturers who
want to sell lots of new guns, cheap or expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The bill might also benefit bad guys who want to be assured
their guns won't jam. Boy, do I feel safer now.
</P>
<P>
   Don't just take my word that this bill is junk. The most pro-gun
person and the most anti-gun person in Sacramento both think it's
junk, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Green Party Assemblywoman Audie Bock of Oakland agrees with
National Rifle Association lobbyist Steve Helsley, you know
something weird is going on. They made exactly the same points
about the junkiness of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite amazing, isn't it?'' Bock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go figure,'' Helsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bock and Helsley said the legislation serves the interests
of gun manufacturers because it lets them sell new handguns while
hindering private owners from selling used ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that gun manufacturers didn't oppose this
bill,'' Helsley said. ``Their job is to pump sales. Ours is to
protect rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers, even those who make cheap guns, can perform the
complex drop tests and test firings specified in the legislation. A
citizen can't afford the lab testing to sell a used gun. In fact,
there are no labs.
</P>
<P>
   Bock of the Green Party even expressed concern for gun store
owners: ``Legitimate dealers will be stuck with a stock of
expensive used guns they can't sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Where do used guns go? Bock and Helsley both said they may end
up on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Cops have an exemption to carry guns deemed unsafe by the
legislation. But if a cop shoots someone with such a gun, a city
will have hell and lawyers to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Both the NRA man and the Green Party woman mentioned this civil
liability issue.
</P>
<P>
   When I suggested that the Assembly has passed an omnibus law of
unintended consequences, Bock said, ``Gun legislation backfires a
lot, pardon the word. This is one of the worst examples.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA man saw some intended non-consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't really want to ban guns,'' Helsley said. ``The
political utility is to do it again and again and again, every time
saying, `Those gun folks have figured a way around our carefully
crafted bills.'''
</P>
<P>
   Helsley, a former assistant director of the state Department of
Justice, said the recently signed assault weapons bill allows
ownership of an AK-47 variant with a new kind of stock, but bans
cowboy-type Winchesters that hold more than 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bill and Annie Oakley used assault rifles? Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans vote against every gun-control bill, while
Democrats feel they all have to put in a gun bill of their own,''
Bock said. ``None of them know much about guns. We have a horrible
mish-mash of gun laws that's just impossible for anyone to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich Polanco knows as much about guns as he does particle
physics,'' Helsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so, but maybe politicians are looking out for their
own safety in future elections rather than Californians' safety.
</P>
<P>
   Bock said colleagues warned her that opponents will attack her
for voting against ``junk guns,'' even though she was voting
against junk legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Helsley said, ``The political consultants were circling,
advising their clients, as this bill was on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, Bock and Helsley respect each other, but they don't
agree on anything about guns except that California's gun laws are,
as Bock put it, ``a bunch of baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   Bock ultimately would like to see ``the Japanese model'' of
strictly controlled permits for guns, requirements to keep guns
locked in safes and random checks to see if gun owners are obeying
the laws.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as far from the NRA model as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing both the NRA man and the Green Party woman
mentioned. At the last minute, legislators exempted Glock
semiautomatic pistols, which otherwise wouldn't have met the safety
standards of their ``unsafe handgun'' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just decreed them safe,'' Helsley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because a lot of cops like the Glock,'' Bock said.
</P>
<P>
   A Glock is the type of gun a white extremist used to murder a
mail carrier in Los Angeles last week. It's this week's poster gun
for gun control, but somehow the Assembly failed to ban it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters. Nothing in this exercise should make people
feel safer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
