<HEADLINE>
PEWTER, AN OLD ALLOY, ADDS FLAIR TO MODERN DECOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Pewter is one of the oldest known alloys, thought
to have been used as early as 1500 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Pewter was commonly made into dishes, drinking vessels, spoons,
bowls and candlesticks in Europe since the Middle Ages. English
pewter was imported to America until its manufacture began here in
the mid-17th century.
</P>
<P>
   It was often a substitute for gold and silver in homes and
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Because pewter is made up of 90 percent tin, it is very soft and
is easily dented. Small amounts of copper and antimony help
strengthen it. Early lower-grade pewter also contained lead in
varying quantities. The lead proved fatal for many who ingested a
dose each time utensils scraped the surface. The lead also caused
tarnish.
</P>
<P>
   The blackish gray patina of pewter varies depending on the
amount of lead. Polished lead-free pewter can look almost as bright
as silver.
</P>
<P>
   Each piece of pewter is cast from a mold, then trimmed, filed
and polished. Shapes were often inspired by simple stylish silver
pieces, such as small trays and tea services. Pewter fell from
favor in the 19th century, when it was replaced by Britannia metal
(a cheaper, lighter non-lead substitute that did not tarnish),
electroplating, china and glassware.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1700s pewter has been made without lead.
</P>
<P>
   With proper care, most pewter will not tarnish or require
polishing. Always hand wash pieces in hot, soapy water soon after
use. (Never put pewter in a dishwasher, because the heat-drying
cycle may darken the surface.) Rinse in clear, hot water and dry
with a soft cloth. Air-drying can leave difficult-to-remove water
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Heat from an oven or burner can melt pewter, so don't use it for
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing usually depends on the amount of copper in a piece and
the overall weight. Candlesticks begin at around $30 for a pair,
drinking vessels at $20 and up, napkin rings for $11 each and an
11-1/2-inch plate for $60 to $75. Antique pieces will cost more.
</P>
<P>
   Most antique pieces are marked by the makers. Most pewter books
list early pewterers and their marks. Antique pewter is popular as
a display collectible today, but many reproduction pieces are
available in museum gift shops and specialty catalogs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
