<HEADER>
A7649 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-MAINE-OUTDOORS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-OUTDOORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE SCHOOL LURES ITS STUDENTS WITH BAIT AND TACKLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Sim Savage is CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Maine _ ``Did you really go to fly-fishing school?''
</P>
<P>
   We were riding a boat out to a scuba site in Jamaica and my
khaki cap caught the attention of the man across the aisle. The hat
emblem reads: L.L. Bean Fly Fishing School.
</P>
<P>
   I can wear it with honor, as it is my the closest thing to a
diploma for participating in a 3 1/2-hour June casting clinic, part
of Bean's Outdoor Discovery School.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I ever wanted to be a fly fisherman; my experience was
limited to a viewing of ``A River Runs Through It.'' That film
apparently has done more for fly-fishing than you'd think.
</P>
<P>
   Fly-fishing has been part of the Bean business since its
inception in 1912. Instruction ranges from the introductory
courses, such as a one-day workshop where anglers learn the
fundamentals ($175), to a four-day advanced trip to Western Maine
($1,795). In between, there are 2 1/2-hour ($40) advanced
fly-casting clinics and Women's Weekend courses ($300).
</P>
<P>
   There are three things that instructor Sim Savage hopes students
get from an introductory class: a wonderful time, the fundamentals
and that they leave ``tired as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Classes usually grasp the basics of casting, fly tying, knots
and strategies. The classes have become so popular that Bean has
expanded the introductions. There are 20 fly-fishing instructors on
staff, and all are required to be certified through the Federation
of Fly Fishers.
</P>
<P>
   The typical student is about 45 years old and ``has had a
lifelong dream to learn how to fly-fish,'' says instructor Ellen
Peters, a Master Maine guide and a fly-fisher since the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   The fly rod makes a whooshing sound as it slices through the
air. The yards of line floating off an 8 1/2-foot rod is quite a
sight and I can see the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of us are standing around a long, shallow ``wading pool,''
fly rods at the ready, as we practice over and over the four-part
cast. Tip down to the water, up, forward and tip back in the water.
</P>
<P>
   We learn the backcast and the roll cast, the water droplets hit
the top of the water, and the whoosh-whoosh is the only sound as we
practice over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 percent to 40 percent of participants will continue to
pursue fly-fishing, Savage says. He jokes that attending Bean's
fly-fishing school ``looks good on a corporate resume.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean's Outdoor Discovery School began in 1979. The school, which
operates year-round, is testament to how Mainers embrace the great
outdoors. Besides fly-fishing, summer classes include wing
shooting, wilderness skills, programs for children, sea kayaking,
canoeing and bicycling. Winter workshops cover cross-country
skiing, snowshoe courses, photography (harp seals and moose,
especially), Maine Guide courses and hiking.
</P>
<P>
   New this year is on-demand programs for day-trippers in
Freeport. If you happen to be in the L.L. Bean store, check out the
list of classes posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about people's recreation time and fun,'' says Mike
Verville, L.L. Bean's director of merchandise. You could say that
L.L. Bean sells both.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a wet suit, spray skirt and water shoes, I looked like a
demented ballerina carrying a pair of oars to the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour sea kayaking class was designed for those who
have some kayak experience, but they let me in, anyway. It was even
fun, once I overcame initial nervousness. And the kayak never
tipped.
</P>
<P>
   Bean uses Sebasco Harbor Resort, a 665-acre estate in the
protected waters of Casco Bay at the mouth of the New Meadows
River, for kayak and canoe workshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to have the same number of people who go out come
back,'' says kayak instructor Bob Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 11 students are from Maine or elsewhere in New
England and have canoe or kayaking experience; then there were the
two of us with no kayaking experience.
</P>
<P>
   We split into two groups and tackled the chilly waters of the
river. We learned how to get into a kayak, the strokes, paddling,
rolls and even how to rescue a kayaker. We paddled out to the mouth
of Casco Bay and then headed back to shore, a little tired and very
proud of our accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   After a rousing game of water bottle keep away, using our hands
instead of oars, we heft kayaks off the beach and trudge back to
the starting point, wash off the mud and hose off the wet suits.
</P>
<P>
   The Outdoor Discovery Schools teach a little bit about Maine's
favorite recreations and a lot about the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fondest wish,'' says Savage, ``is that (visitors) leave
here knowing why clean air and clean water are so important.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Contact your travel agent or L.L. Bean
Outdoor Discovery Schools, Freeport, ME 04033; 888-552-3261, or on
the Web at www.llbean.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
