<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-INTERNET-AUCTIONS-HNS     08-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AUCTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRENZIED WORLD OF ON-LINE AUCTIONS, BUYER BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On-line auctions let you window-shop 24 hours a
day, seven days a week, until you find what you want, without
wearing out your feet or car.
</P>
<P>
   But be aware of the caveats before you start clicking on that
bid box.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors in Lincoln, Mass., is a research company that
reviews, ranks and rates e-commerce sites using more than 100
criteria, from ease of use and customer confidence to on-site
resources and relationship services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the consumer's advocate,'' said Hank Hudepohl, an
analyst at Gomez. Even with a watchdog group, each shopper has to
be responsible and follow some basic advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't jump in and buy on impulse,'' Hudepohl said. ``People
can easily get caught up in the fun or competition. It's almost
like gambling. So try to keep your cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He recommended researching a site and previewing the
merchandise. Watch bidding and see how it goes. Read up on the
rules, which differ from site to site. Most require bidders to be
over 18. And, ``If something seems too good to be true, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are very interested in buying an item, check the bidding
action every hour or so. At eBay.com, for instance, potential
buyers offer as many as 600 bids per minute, according to Kevin
Pursglove, senior director for communications of the on-line
auction house. The site is currently the leading person-to-person
on-line trading community, with more than 1,600 categories and more
than 1.5 billion page visits per month.
</P>
<P>
   Although some on-line auction houses monitor their sites for
strange bidding behavior and unusual listings, the buyer should
still be cautious and savvy before starting to bid, according to
on-line auction specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites let you retract your bid if you accidentally hit the
wrong key or change your mind in a certain time span, while others
allow retracted bids until the last minute of the auction, Hudepohl
said. Know the value of the item you are bidding on and set a limit
for yourself, so you are not caught up paying more than it's worth
or you can afford. Sites like BiddersEdge.com, BidFind.com and
DealTime.com provide a historical record of what was paid for a
type of item at auction, as well as its current auction price and
which auction site has it for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are on-line shopping tips at many of the sites,''
Pursglove said. You can also check into tips produced by Internet
Fraud Watch unit of the National Consumers League based in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The league's Web site is http://www.natlconsumersleague.org/
</P>
<P>
   Know who you are dealing with. On-line auction sites involve
business-to-consumer trading, as with Onsale.com, or
consumer-to-consumer, like eBay and Yahoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers register with an on-line auction site of their choice
that caters to the type of inventory or item they plan to sell.
They then select how many days the item will be for sale, which can
be anywhere from three days to one month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are buying from a business, always look to the area of
their Web site that talks about who they are and how to contact
them,'' Hudepohl advised. ``A site can look very professional and
if you've never heard of it before, you should always verify the
seller.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests checking the feedback forum, where buyers write
their comments about transactions with sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said that even though the main responsibility is with
the seller, the buyer should always do the homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out how to contact the seller before you start bidding,''
said Pursglove, so you can ask any questions that may not have been
answered on the Web site. You can ask questions while the bidding
is going on, right up until it ends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said sellers write their own descriptions of the
items. Some include one to three photos, showing different angles,
while others have no photos. Hudepohl said that you should ask if
you can pay by credit card (with most cards, you are only liable
for the first $50 in case of a scam or fraud) and if there is an
escrow service for holding your money until you receive your
merchandise. Never send cash through the mail. Ask about the return
policy and if a high-value item has been or can be certified for
authenticity by a third party.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of shady dealings. Just because 25 people are actively
bidding on an item doesn't mean it's valuable. It could be an
instance of collusion between sellers and false bidders who are
trying to increase the sale price.
</P>
<P>
   Some bidders engage in sniping, timing their first bid for the
very last second to beat out all other people. At times, auction
companies will extend the bidding by an hour or more if they expect
that this is the case.
</P>
<P>
   Bid shielding is an unethical practice of trying to block others
from bidding. Here's how it works: One person bids $10 for a book
and a colleague quickly bids $500, assuming that no one will
overbid the inflated price. The high bidder retracts the bid at the
last minute, giving the first person a $10 deal.
</P>
<P>
   On-line auctions should be fun when they are conducted right and
if buyers are honest, Pursglove said. ``There's a great sense of
community when partaking in an on-line auction, where you can chat
with other people who have the same interests as you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudepohl also said to have fun, but as with anything, continue
to always be cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to product selection, there's almost an
unlimited potential for finding what you need,'' Hudepohl
said.``It's important to know that only the top 50 (sites) have 95
percent of the market. Many sites are just trying to get their feet
off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudepohl said merchandisers market and liquidate their products
much more efficiently in auctions.
</P>
<P>
   With 500 auction sites on the World Wide Web, there's something
for every interest. Even the venerable Sotheby's auction house went
on line this summer. Matthew Weigman, director of Sotheby's press
office in New York, said that the auction house is also in a new
joint on-line auction site with Amazon.com, best known as a book
retailer. This fall, Sothebys.amazon.com will offer memorabilia
from Secretariat, America's most beloved Triple Crown winner, and
baseball memorabilia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
