<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     08-24 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANOLA NEAR-EXTINCT, ITS PAST LOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANOLA, Texas _ Here along Matagorda Bay, between Port Lavaca
and Port O'Connor, lies a lonesome stretch of beach marked by a
makeshift barrier of broken concrete slabs, and long, decaying
piers that tumble into the brackish water.
</P>
<P>
   The lone, reclusive figure along these vacant shores is a large,
pink-granite statue of Rene Robert Cavellier, Sieur de La Salle,
the French explorer who first set foot here more than 300 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few fishing cabins across the road from the beach.
The official tally for Indianola is supposed to be 100 people, but
it would take a generous count on a busy day to get half that many.
</P>
<P>
   A sizable historical marker near a small group of covered picnic
tables goes largely unread. Indianola has been forgotten in Texas
history. Even now, with the dying fury of Hurricane Bret holding
the public's attention, this tiny town is never mentioned. It is
not known.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more than 100 years ago, Indianola was considered the
second-largest seaport in Texas. Second to Galveston. Hurricanes
blew it off the map, destroyed it twice and returned it to native
sand and rock. They all but erased its place in the development of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Carl of Solms-Braunfels picked this point of Matagorda
Bay as the landing port for thousands of German immigrants who
eventually populated the whole of Texas, particularly the Hill
Country.
</P>
<P>
   The port was called Indian Point for a while and it became a
deep-water port during the Mexican War. For 30 years it was the
primary Army depot supplying the frontier forts of western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It was through this port that the Army brought its first Camel
Corps, a herd of camels purchased as an experiment ordered by
Secretary of War Jefferson Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The town was established in 1847. Stagecoach service to the
interior of the state began the next year. By 1848, the name was
officially changed to Indianola. It became the county seat of
Calhoun County and was the primary port through which European
immigrants flowed into western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Union gunboats bombarded the city on Oct. 26, 1862. Troops
eventually occupied the town, then looted it. They left the
following month but returned nearly a year later and stayed until
1864.
</P>
<P>
   The Handbook of Texas says the ``first shipment of mechanically
refrigerated beef moved from Indianola to New Orleans on the
steamship Agnes in July 1869.''
</P>
<P>
   It is said that warehouses stored ice at Indianola. The ice was
cut on the Great Lakes and shipped south at great expense. The ice
was prized during the Texas summers.
</P>
<P>
   Indianola was at her peak _ between 5,000 and 6,000 residents _
in 1875 when the first hurricane struck. The town was crammed with
visitors attending an important trial. Two days later, about 300
people had died.
</P>
<P>
   The town was rebuilt. But on Aug. 19, 1886, a second hurricane
hit. This one was accompanied by a huge fire and the town was
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Those residents who did survive had no heart to rebuild again.
The county seat was moved to Port Lavaca and the memories of
Indianola were allowed to wash away with the debris.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
