<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE INSPIRED PHIL COLLINS' SONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've heard many versions of the story behind the Phil Collins
song ``In the Air Tonight.'' In each, Phil witnesses a drowning or
a murder. Is there any truth to any story related to this song?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.M., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The only troubling event Collins used as inspiration for the
song was the breakup of his first marriage. Collins and Andrea
Brett divorced in 1978, and she raised their children, Joely and
Simon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Collins told Parade that the song was written out of
frustration and bitterness after the split. ``You're putting your
private life out for all to see,'' Collins said. ``But I'm not
embarrassed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   More of his private life was on display in 1994, when People
reported that Collins sent a fax telling second wife, Jill
Tavelman, he wanted a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Collins wrote five songs on the ``Tarzan'' soundtrack and, with
his big band, has a new album, ``A Hot Night in Paris.'' On July
23, he married his former interpreter, Orianne Cevey, in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the significance of the lapel pin that Robert McCall
wore on the ``Equalizer'' TV series?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.C., Midland, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A: The lapel pin never figured into a story during the show's
four-year run.
</P>
<P>
   The pin was added to McCall's wardrobe by costume designer Linda
Wayne, according to a frequently asked questions list prepared by
``Equalizer'' fans. The list appears on the Web site
www.conubic.com/eqew/eq-ew/eq.html.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as an artist has their signature on their work of art, a
costume designer also has a signature when they are working on
something like a TV series,'' according to the site. ``When she
left the series in the fourth season, the pin went with her and was
never seen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Series star Edward Woodward, who played McCall, said in a TV
interview he always figured the lapel pin would be used in an
episode ``as a weapon or something important to the story,''
according to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a hot sauce that I would like to get to the
marketplace. What is the best way to market a recipe or the sauce
itself?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.I., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: One place to start looking is the International Chili
Society, a 32-year-old group that runs the World's Salsa
Championship each year.
</P>
<P>
   The society, which was founded with the 1967 World Champion
Chili Cookoff in Terlingua, Texas, sanctions chili contests around
the world. An estimated 300 cookoffs were held in 1998 for 1
million cooks, judges and tasters.
</P>
<P>
   Society members, who call themselves ``chiliheads,'' receive a
quarterly newspaper with 60 pages of chili-related news, recipes
and photos.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (877) 777-4427 or write to the
International Chili Society, 6755 Speedway Blvd., Las Vegas, NV
89115. The society has a Web site at www.chilicookoff.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. If you have a question, call 904-445-2009 or
e-mail him at trivia(at)prefect.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
