<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM WON'T EASILY GIVE UP SON'S FRIENDSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know the difference between a hat trick and a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   I know the difference between a nine-iron and a sand wedge _
even though I'm terrible with a sand wedge. This spring, I used one
to dig holes for my flower bed. I just put a practice ball on the
spot where I wanted to plant the bulb and pretended I was in a sand
trap. I never did hit that ball, but my petunias were gorgeous.
And, yes, I know the difference between a Mustang and a Corvette.
These are simple matters.
</P>
<P>
   But what is the difference between, ``Mom, you don't have to
come,'' and ``Mom, you don't need to come?''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch! That still hurts. Give me a moment please, OK? I'll be all
right. I really don't believe that my son meant to bruise my
feelings. He's a sweet man-boy. And, frankly, the singular idea of
spending another two hours of my life on the sideline of some
mom-forsaken field as fire rains from the sky, is not appealing. It
never was, really.
</P>
<P>
   I've done it time after time, field after field, bleacher after
bleacher, for years, however. I've lugged the coolers, yelled out
encouragement for the wrong mascot, and purchased thousands of
losing raffle tickets. And why have I been such a devoted, rabid
fan for so many teams? Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because of my son. Where he went, I went.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I sat on the sidelines of practice balancing my checkbook,
making phone calls and reading novels. Yes, I've spent the entire
halftime of soccer games in the women's restroom trying to escape
the merciless heat or Arctic cold. But when the team was in motion,
whenever my son moved, even if he was just scratching himself, I
saw it. It was recorded in my mind for all time. I battled entire
battalions of mosquitoes for my boy just because he asked, ``Mom,
you're coming to my game aren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   He said it like a sentence, though, like he expected me there
because he wanted me there. He needed me. So, as often as I could,
through headaches and heartaches, I went to his games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, he says, ``Mom, you don't need to come to
practice anymore.'' To soften the blow, he added that none of the
other moms come. Oh, so now it's a Dad thing. Dad can come, but I'm
not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   I'm cool. I don't wear goofy clothes or yell, ``Hit him again!''
at basketball games. I don't run on the field and do cartwheels
with the cheerleaders _ anymore. What happened? Why was I banished?
</P>
<P>
   I think it's this awful robber who keeps coming to e at
night. I used to call him the man fairy, but fairies are nice
people. They bring you cute little things like tooth money and
tiaras. This guy is a thief. First he took my son's fat baby cheeks
away. Then he stole his giggles and hugs. This summer he ferreted
away his little boy voice and left a voice box that rumbles like
thunder and sounds like my husband. Those things I expected. I was
sort of prepared for those losses.
</P>
<P>
   But I never dreamed he'd steal my son's desire for my company.
Gee whiz. That's been the hardest loss of all.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm fighting back. The thief can have my baby's adolescence.
The girls can even have his attention. But his friendship, our
friendship, is priceless. No one is taking our relationship away
without going through me first, and I just ain't having it! Not
today, not tomorrow, not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, I went to practice anyway. There were several
other moms there. I think my son even looked my way once, and
smiled. Later, he didn't complain, but he did say, ``Mom, when you
come to practice again, will you bring me some Gatorade?''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I suppose, the difference between us depends a lot
on me. See you at practice.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
