r e BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     08-24 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F. SCOTT FITZGERALD UNDERSTOOD MODERN AMERICAN LONGINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep coming back to the Modern Library board's selection of
the 100 best novels in English published in this century. I've
given recent reports on some of these ``best'' novels, and others
may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Today's focus is on F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``Tender Is the
Night'' _ which, if you've already read it, you may care to read
again, especially if you have a more than passing interest in its
author.
</P>
<P>
   The late Ken Millar, whose Lew Archer melodramas were bylined
``Ross Macdonald,'' once told me he rated Scott Fitzgerald as
America's greatest author of the 20th century for being ``the first
one to grasp the modern American experience.'' I've sifted that one
around, striving to understand, and perhaps I'm getting close.
</P>
<P>
   The modern American experience is love. It may be said as simply
as that, but love is never simple. In earlier centuries and in
other places, love was necessarily subordinated to more practical
considerations, but 20th-century America held more options _ and
love in all its considerations and forms became an ever more
powerful motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Fitzgerald wrote about these confusions in his own quest
for answers. Love isn't sex, but love without sex isn't love, and
one must fire the other. This theme is addressed in scores of
Fitzgerald short stories and in three of his four completed novels
_ ``The Beautiful and Damned,'' ``The Great Gatsby'' and ``Tender
Is the Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Side of Paradise,'' the novel that introduced the
24-year-old Fitzgerald in 1920, exists apart. It is a precocious
performance, but is essentially an invention that does not connect
to its author's own experience. ``The Beautiful and Damned'' does,
but it has never been held in high critical regard. ``Gatsby,''
though, has been in favor since its 1925 publication, its
reputation riding steadily upward until it placed second, right
behind James Joyce's ``Ulysses,'' in the Modern Library election.
</P>
<P>
   Its three principal male figures _ Jay Gatsby, Nick Carroway and
Tom Buchanan _ all reveal aspects of Fitzgerald's personality and
philosophy. But protagonist Dick Diver in ``Tender Is the Night''
is Fitzgerald absolutely, although Diver is presented as a
psychiatrist rather than as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   Composing the novel was a necessary catharsis for ``Diver.'' The
wealthy, schizophrenic Nicole Warren, whom he treats and with whom
he falls in love and marries, is a paraphrase of Zelda Sayre
Fitzgerald, whose mental instability was impressed upon her husband
when their marriage was fresh. Rosemary Hart, the young actress who
lures Diver into an extramarital affair, is Fitzgerald's literary
stand-in for Lois Moran, a Hollywood beauty of the period.
</P>
<P>
   That period, of course, is the Jazz Age 1920s, Fitzgerald's own
preserve. Although ``Tender Is the Night'' was not published until
1934, and sold poorly as late issue of a has-been author, it was
written on and off between 1925 and 1931 as Zelda's mental
condition worsened. Not until 1948, when a new edition was
introduced with Malcolm Cowley's commentary, was it clarified that
the novel was an ironic presentation of a true-life drama.
</P>
<P>
   The innately romantic Scott Fitzgerald was completely absorbed
in and dominated by his love for Zelda, and his failure to save her
was his awful defeat. He sensed Zelda would be his undoing, as
Nicole, whom he substantially cures, is the ruination of fictional
Dick Diver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tender Is the Night'' is tragedy of high literary order. It is
now available in several paperback editions as well as the Modern
Library hardback; and, along with ``Gatsby,'' it endures on library
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
