<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S CRYING OVER SPILLED MILK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No amount of ginkgo biloba will bring back the brain cells of my
youth. No catchy rap song will help me remember more than one of
the Pokemon monsters' names (Go, Pikachu!). Not even 10 hours of
sleep will keep me from bringing home stacks of Lean Cuisines
identical to the ones in the freezer while I forget the item that
prompted my urgent trip to the store.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of an aging intellect have come slowly but
comfortably, and I thought I was OK with time's march on my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Until last weekend, when I found myself turning into my dad.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday began like any other weekend morning. Innocent. Sweet.
With my two kids snuggled against each side of me, still heavy with
sleep, I reached for the remote control for the TV. And found it
caked with dried milk.
</P>
<P>
   The buttons were ringed with thick lines of white. A light film
covered the whole gadget. I pressed one of the buttons. It went
down. And stayed down.
</P>
<P>
   Frantically, I began pushing all the buttons. Fast forward for
the VCR. Rewind. Channel up. Power. They all stuck. Nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the TV didn't work either. Somehow, when the remote
went out, it turned off whatever it is that makes the VCR work,
which is what our cable box runs through, which means, in brief,
that suddenly we could only get Channel 3. Well, I like Pokemon at
3 p.m. as much as the next person (again, Go Pikachu!), but I like
``Ally'' on Fox, too, and this was our brand-new VCR and in the
split second that I took to think this whole thing through
carefully before I opened up my mouth, the most reasonable idea in
my head was Scream.
</P>
<P>
   Which I did, and as best I recall it was some incoherent
combination of how We Need to Take Care of Our Things, and What Do
You Think I Am, Made of Money?, two of my most tried-and-tired
refrains.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, neither of my children stepped forward at this
point to take credit for the milk spill I was so elaborately crying
over. Since Scream wasn't working as a parenting strategy, I sat
down on the hamper and took a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, let's figure out what to do,'' I seethed, trying now to
demonstrate problem-solving for my impressionable progeny.
Five-year-old Hadley giggled.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later I was at Best Buy with my milky remote, searching
for a replacement universal remote that looked similar. None of
them did, so 45 minutes later I selected one that fit in my price
range instead: $19.79, including batteries and tax. I went to the
office to catch up on some work, and promptly forgot about the
remote mess.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday began like any other weekend morning. Innocent. Sweet. I
installed the batteries in the universal, and followed the
directions. The remote worked. The volume button worked. Hey, it
never had with the other remote! I was a genius.
</P>
<P>
   I was an idiot. There was no button to change the Line In, which
meant no PlayStation capabilities. No Medieval or Croc. There was
no button to initiate programming for the VCR. No taped episodes of
``Ally.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperation led to an idea. I got out a Q-Tip and starting
cleaning the milky remote. Some of the buttons were working now.
The Line In worked. The programming worked. But the volume still
didn't work _ and neither did the fast-forward or rewind.
</P>
<P>
   And this is when I developed my System, and turned into my dad.
Why not have two remotes for several different purposes (OK,
technically three remotes; the original one for the TV _ the one
that the batteries fall out of every time you pick it up _ was
still the only one that could turn the 10-year-old set on and off)?
</P>
<P>
   My System worked, and the only possible drawback would be my own
death, in which case no one on the planet would be able to figure
the System out.
</P>
<P>
   That if-I-go, it-goes-with me System is exactly how my dad has
set up his own VCRs, including the one that has the illegible
handwritten instructions that he keeps in a drawer and has to drag
out every December when we all want to watch White Christmas again.
Every year he screams and seethes. And every year we giggle.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, I have a feeling I won't be laughing. Because
now, you know, I have become my dad, who I realize is a true
Problem-Solving Genius. So I'll be the one taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Newton writes a weekly column about parenting. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
