<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AUTOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AUTO BUYERS LET THEIR FINGERS DO THE BUYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Internet is bringing change to two more old
world practices, the kicking of tires on the auto lot and the test
drive.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 5 million new vehicle buyers will use the
Internet to gather information to help them decide what vehicles to
purchase, and as many as 5 percent of auto purchases are expected
to be made on line by 2000, a new survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   Auto dealers have not only recognized the potential of sales via
the on-line buying services that connect them to consumers, but
have established their own presences on the World Wide Web to sell
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where it's going,'' said Tom O'Leary, general manager of
Burlingame Ford in Burlingame, where a manager works full-time on
Internet sales. ``It's the computer age. Computers in this area are
as common as telephones.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of new vehicle shoppers using the Internet
increased from 25 percent in 1998 to 40 percent during the first
quarter of 1999 and is projected to be 65 percent by the end of
2000, according to a survey by J.D. Power and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power, based in suburban Los Angeles, is an international
marketing information firm that covers automobiles, tires,
airlines, health care, phone services and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   One popular site is Kelly Blue Book (www.kbb.com), the on-line
version of the venerable publication that began as a service
strictly for used car buyers, but which now carries information on
new models as well.
</P>
<P>
   Other on-line services take consumers some or all of the way
through the buying process.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Autoweb.com of Santa Clara, one of the pioneers
of the sector in 1995, consumers can find information on every make
and model of passenger vehicle made and a network of dealers in 50
states through which they can begin a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a process that used to take a few weeks _ getting
information about a car, driving around looking at cars, test
driving them _ and now in a couple hours you can get all the
information you need,'' said Dean DeBiase, the president and chief
executive of Autoweb.com. ``You can either schedule a test drive
or, quite frankly, just buy the car on line.''
</P>
<P>
   He said perhaps 40 percent of consumers who are using his
service may eschew the test drive because they are familiar with
the brand they are buying.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Denove, director of consulting operations at J.D. Power,
said the number of people buying a new vehicle through the Internet
rose from 12,000 per month in the first three months of 1998 to
nearly 30,000 per month in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is a growing, but still tiny, sector of overall auto sales.
About 13 million people buy a new car each year, Denove said.
Another 3 million new vehicles are purchased annually by
governments or large businesses for their fleets.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers that have relationships with on-line buying services
like Autoweb.com generally offer consumers firm prices, which the
industry says are competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes these are better prices than the best negotiator can
get walking in through the front door and dealing with the
salesperson directly,'' Denove said.
</P>
<P>
   He said consumers are becoming more informed and that dealers
and auto manufacturers ``have to find ways of doing business with
an informed consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Denove said the growing influence of the Internet is likely to
hit domestic manufacturers the hardest. The J.D. Power study shows
that the more time a person spends on line, the less likely he or
she is to purchase a domestic vehicle. Overall, domestic
manufacturers have approximately 70 percent of the share of the
market share; however, this share drops to 58 percent among
Internet shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Autoweb.com, other major on-line services include
Irvine-based autobytel.com; carpoint.msn.com, a service of
Microsoft; and cars.com of Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
