<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BROWNS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     08-24 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CLEVELAND: ... third and 1.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might have been mistaken for group dementia under the searing
sun. But a visit to the Dawg Pound revealed the true motives of the
crowd _ or ``guests,'' as they are termed in the new Browns'
parlance. In the new stadium, the Pound has been not only preserved
but expanded, from 5,000 to 10,000 seats spanning two decks, and
after three years of silence, its denizens were eager to woof. Some
had left work at 2 o'clock to be ready once the gates opened at
3:30, an hour and a half before the practice, and Aaron Eck, a
four-year Pound veteran _ or inmate _ explained why.
</P>
<P>
   Eck, a 28-year-old heavy-equipment operator, had been forced to
content himself with rooting against Modell's new team, the
Baltimore Ravens, ever since the owner pulled up stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to kill Modell; I hated him,'' said Eck, echoing a
popular sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Now he had something to root for, even if it was just pretend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited three years, and I don't care how I see 'em,'' said
Eck, hoisting his souvenir beer. ``If they're gonna be here, I'm
gonna be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns actually had been on initial display two weeks before
in the Hall of Fame exhibition game at Canton, a 20-17 victory over
the Dallas Cowboys, and those Clevelanders who didn't form part of
the record crowd of 25,156 at the game had welcomed back the team
on television.
</P>
<P>
   This presented a scheduling conflict for some, such as Dawg
Pounder Ed McCluskey III, a 26-year-old Ford Motor Company driver
from Sandusky. The game ran simultaneously with the wake for his
father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the first hour at the funeral home,'' said
McCluskey. ``No way was I going to miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clevelanders had been missing pro football something awful since
not long after the day Modell dropped his bombshell. Having cried
poor-mouth for a while, he waited to make his announcement until
the eve of a November election in which funds were approved to
subsidize the renovation of Cleveland Stadium he had sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like finding out that your best friend was terminally
ill,'' said John ``Big Dawg'' Thompson, a 38-year-old computer
parts salesman who founded the Dawg Pound 14 years ago and served
as its full-scale poster boy, wearing a $10 rubber hound dog mask,
a No. 98 Browns jersey, and white replica team pants with
orange-and-brown piping down the sides over his 375-pound frame
each game day. ``Then you find out you only have four chances to
visit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those represented the Browns' final four home games, and when
the death knell sounded the week before Christmas in a 26-10
victory over the Cincinnati Bengals, the atmosphere was one of
mourning and menace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't so much sadness for the players as for the
city,'' recalled Langham. ``It's tough to explain why you're moving
a team after a city and fans have supported you so well.''
</P>
<P>
   These fans had no interest in explanations. They expressed their
affection for Modell as the game wound down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered why people were standing through the fourth
quarter,'' said McCluskey, who didn't belong to the Dawg Pound at
the time but had obtained tickets for the game. ``Then I turned
around and saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Hacksaws were what he saw. Two of them were being used to carve
up the bleachers; one was confiscated, but security guards finally
gave up and the other remained in use. And in the higher-priced
sections, industrial tools were deployed to unbolt entire rows of
chairback seats. Some fans kept them as mementos; others bequeathed
them as a sort of bon voyage present for Modell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started about five rows behind me,'' said Eck. ``People
were passing down rows of seats to the front and throwing them onto
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   What remained on the field, really, was Cleveland's heart and
soul. The players', likewise. At the end of the game, the Browns
took a farewell lap around the stadium to shake hands with their
former patrons. Many shed tears, fans and players alike.
</P>
<P>
   But the surrender was temporary. The next morning, Thompson
awakened from the nightmare and said to himself, ``The hell with
it. We're going to let the league know they can't get away with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mayor's office, White was of a similar mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were finally convinced that we were heading down the
primrose path,'' he said, ``I went to New York with my attorney and
told the commissioner we weren't going to take this lying down. We
had done everything right, including giving Modell the choice of a
new stadium or renovation _ he chose renovation. I said to the
commissioner, `We're not going to let Art Modell kick us in the
teeth and put our tail between our legs and go home. There's going
to be a fight, and there's going to be blood on the floor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of paper, too. While White handled the political
football, Thompson galvanized the populace. The grassroots
groundswell proved overwhelming. Rallies were organized. Faxes
flooded the NFL offices. The group known as Save Our Browns _ its
pointed acronym SOB _ staged phone-ins, sent blizzards of postcards
to each NFL team, and jammed the Internet with e-mail pleas to
relocated club boosters around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a call from some college, either North Carolina or
North Carolina State,'' recalled Thompson. ``They said, `Who are
these Cleveland Browns to be shutting down the Internet? We're
trying to conduct classes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns diehards were busy teaching the NFL a lesson. It
culminated with a pilgrimage to the owners' meetings in Atlanta,
where Thompson and four busloads of fellow preservationists
delivered a massive scroll with 2.2 million signatures demanding
satisfaction for Cleveland. Thompson, initially banned from the
hotel where the owners were meeting, eventually gained entry and
buttonholed ``15 or 16 of them'' to make his case. White worked
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans' role was huge,'' said Policy, who at the time was
running the San Francisco 49ers and serving on the NFL's Finance
Committee. ``You had a tandem situation. Community leadership on
the one hand _ Mayor White and an extremely potent business
community in the form of Cleveland Tomorrow. On the other hand, you
had a huge, passionate fan campaign that did some things that are
historical footnotes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason the Browns aren't one. Soon after the Atlanta
avalanche, the landmark deal was struck in which Modell was allowed
to leave while the Browns, in spirit and fact, remained, though
they were put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the new stadium was built, and last Sept. 8, an
expansion franchise was awarded to local financier and
philanthropist Alfred Lerner, who had loaned his private jet to his
friend Modell to fly to Baltimore and seal the relocation pact some
three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are no hard feelings toward Lerner; there never were any
against the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really blamed the Browns,'' said veteran linebacker
Chris Spielman, an Ohio native. ``They think one person was to
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   With that person gone, the support for the new Browns is
unprecedented. For the first time, every home game, exhibition and
regular-season, is a sellout. There were 4,000 fans in Canton for
the expansion draft. Dawg Pound tickets, priced at $30, are in
demand for some $300 among people who want to do it up right for
the regular-season opener. Businesses are jostling one another to
get on the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different; we're a major league city now,'' said
Dennis Roche, general manager of Cleveland's Chamber of Commerce.
``Corporately, people want to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With that boosterism comes a heightened sense of responsibility.
The Browns are an expansion team _ as evidenced by a 30-3 humbling
by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in their second exhibition _ but they
aim to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of not wanting to disappoint people who have been
there 1,000 percent for you,'' said Policy, a Youngstown native who
returned home as a 10 percent equity partner in the Browns. ``It's
almost like you feel an obligation to them.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the mere return of the Browns is dividend enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, I wouldn't spend four or five hours of my afternoon
down here just to watch them scrimmage,'' said Eck from his Dawg
Pound perch Tuesday. ``But I want to see anything of them I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Woof, woof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
