<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTAS PLAYS SOME HARDBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Costas brought his A-game for an interview with Pete Rose
that aired Monday on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Costas gave a clinic on how to ask tough questions without being
mean-spirited or condescending. He never let Rose get away with
giving cute or nonresponsive answers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, of course, is whether Rose bet on baseball games.
Despite his denials, Rose was banned from the game by former
commissioner Bart Giamatti and has since applied for reinstatement.
Current commissioner Bud Selig appears reluctant to let Rose back
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose Bud Selig grants you a hearing . . .,'' Costas asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I would say to him?'' Rose answered. `` `Bud,
please, can I see the evidence? I want to see the evidence. I want
to comment on the evidence.' That's what I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You contest the evidence?'' Costas asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I would,'' Rose answered. ``Sure I would. Sure I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas went right after the evidence question.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that there are betting slips,'' Costas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are they at?'' Rose asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That there are phone records, including multiple phone calls
on several dates spread over at least a couple of years, an hour or
less before game time, into the manager's office . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Rose answered. ``That's not true. That's
not true at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your handwriting on a betting slip, including baseball
games,'' Costas said. ``Never against the Reds, but on the Reds and
on other baseball games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Rose answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they've got all that,'' Costas went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they . . . well, can I see it, please?'' Rose answered.
``Can you see it? Can America see it? I mean, don't you think that
baseball would come forward with that? They come forward with
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You deny that you ever bet on baseball?'' Costas asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to answer that question because I'm going to
live up to the agreement I signed,'' said Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Costas explained to ``Today'' host Matt Lauer that gambling is a
capital crime in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball makes a valid distinction between gambling and other
transgressions or character flaws that might be as bad or worse
outside the context of sports,'' Costas explained. ``But in sports,
gambling is in a separate category because it goes to the question
of the integrity of the contest or the perception of the integrity
of the contest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Football beats baseball
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI analyst Ron Meyer had mostly praise for the Patriots,
stating that they looked to be on a par with the other teams in the
NFL's toughest division. ``The Patriots looked very impressive,''
the former New England coach said. ``(Drew) Bledsoe played
extremely well and had a nice array of receivers. But the question
remains, will the Patriots be able to fill the void created by
Robert Edwards's injury?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Writes and wrongs
</P>
<P>
   Nick Charles blasted the hypocrisy of professional athletes
charging fans for autographs on CNN/SI's ``Page One.'' ``The
relationship between athlete and fan has been altered forever,
because sports stars are paid handsomely to appear at collectors
conventions and even more just to sign,'' Charles said. ``Celtics
great Bill Russell refused to sign autographs during his playing
and coaching days and once wrote that signing his name would rob
him of his own freedom. Now he'll sign your basketball for $350.''
. . . CNN/SI's Fred Hickman appeared on ABC's ``Politically
Incorrect'' last week and joined the growing chorus of opposition
to professional wrestling. ``When I was a kid, we looked up to and
followed sports heroes like Willie Mays,'' Hickman said. ``Now kids
are following pro wrestling and characters like `Wifebeater.' I am
a firm believer in if you follow something you soon will act or
model yourself after it. In this case, these kids are going to slip
through the cracks and into trouble. Hey, buy yourself a deck of
cards and stay away from wrestling.'' . . . Former Reds pitcher Rob
Dibble gave Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette a little spanking
last week on ESPN Radio. Dibble said that star players such as
Pedro Martinez deserve a little slack and should not be treated
like regular players. ``Dan Duquette, No. 1, is a scared weasel,''
Dibble said Friday morning. ``He is such a chicken guy that he
delegates other people to do his dirty work. Now Jimy Williams is
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another one on board
</P>
<P>
   There's always room for more NFL analysis on television. Mike
Francesa joins the pack this season with ``The NFL Now,'' debuting
Sept. 12 on MSNBC, essentially a televised version of his radio
show. It will be simulcast from the WFAN radio studios in Astoria,
N.Y., though only the first hour of the two-hour nationally
syndicated show will be picked up on TV . . . ``SportsCenter''
anchor Dan Patrick debuts a show Sept. 13 on ESPN Radio. It will
include the standard fare of celebrity interviews and appearances
by ESPN commentators. ``I love radio, especially the
free-to-express-ideas format that drives ESPN Radio,'' Patrick told
reporters. ``Now, instead of doing bite-sized portions of sports, I
will be able to take a little bigger bite each day, have some fun,
and express my opinions and feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
