<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILAN WILL FACE CHALLENGES AS SERIE A KICKS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Italy's Serie A season begins Sunday with defending champion
Milan in crisis. Club president Silvio Berlusconi criticized coach
Alberto Zaccheroni's ``tridente'' attack of Oliver Bierhoff, Andriy
Shevchenko, and George Weah after a 2-1 loss to Parma for the
Italian Super Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Zvonimir Boban suffered an abdominal injury while playing for
Croatia against Malta, Brazilian midfielder Leonardo is struggling,
and Weah has returned to his Staten Island home on ``personal
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milan, which opens the season at Lecce, overcame bigger
problems last season. And Zaccheroni deservedly received much of
the credit after returing Weah to an advanced position alongside
Bierhoff.
</P>
<P>
   This week will be a high-stakes antipasto to the season.
Juventus meets Rennes of France in the Intertoto Cup final Tuesday;
Fiorentina visits Widzew Lodz and Parma plays host to Rangers in
the Champions League preliminaries Wednesday; and Lazio meets
Manchester United for the European Super Cup in Monte Carlo Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers appears primed to upset Parma _ revenge for last year's
elimination. Parma clearly underestimated Rangers in falling, 2-0,
in the away leg in Glasgow two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers pounded another Scottish opponent, Dundee United, by a
score of 4-1 Saturday as Michael Mols and Claudio Reyna continued
to impress. Mols, though, is awaiting the birth of his first child
and could miss the match in Parma. Rangers president David Murray
will make his private jet available for Mols, but Rangers Dutch
coach Dick Advocaat said he is certain the birth will not occur
until next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid shakeup
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid president Lorenzo Sanz spent $82 million in the
offseason to reinforce the team, nearly half of that to acquire
Nicholas Anelka from Arsenal. But Real Madrid needed two holdovers,
Fernando Morientes and Raul, to score in the 92d and 93d minutes of
a 2-1 victory over Mallorca in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh coach John Toshack is expected to revive Real Madrid with
a ``dream team'' lineup, but he has been under extreme pressure
while awaiting the arrival of Anelka and feuding with Dutch
midfielder Clarence Seedorf. But in the opening game, Toshack
boldly removed Anelka late in the second half, and Real Madrid
rallied. And Monday, Sanz said Seedorf would be sold to Inter.
There is a dispute over the price, though, as Sanz wants nearly $30
million and Inter's Massimo Moratti has offered about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always known very well that I could be finished with
Real at any moment,'' Toshack said. ``It could fall apart in five
minutes, five months, or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barcelona is remaining relatively tranquil with the
addition of another former Ajax player, Finnish midfielder Jari
Litmanen. Barcelona lost to Valencia in the Spanish Super Cup but
appears to have adjusted to the 3-4-3 alignment of coach Louis Van
Gaal.
</P>
<P>
   And Atletico Madrid, eternally ambitious under the questionable
direction of Jesus Gil y Gil, suffered a 2-0 loss to city rival
Rayo Vallecano before a capacity home crowd at Estadio Vicente
Calderon. US national team goalkeeper Kasey Keller made his Liga
debut for Rayo Vallecano and performed well, though he apparently
was fortunate that Atletico missed an open goal with the score 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earning their keep
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara had a fast start in its first season in Portugal's
Primera. The Azoreans, the first club from the islands to win
promotion to the top division, held a 2-0 halftime lead over
Sporting on goals by Gamboa. A capacity crowd of 18,000 attended
the match at Estadio de Sao Miguel, nearly equaling the population
of Ponta Delgada, listed at 21,000. This was also a special
achievement for coach Manuel Fernandes, who played for Sporting and
Portugal's national team, and a shock for Sporting under Italian
coach Giuseppe Materazzi and with former Manchester United
goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel making his debut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Profitable farm crop
</P>
<P>
   Television rights to the Brazilian championship have been sold
for $120 million this year, with $50 million in foreign contracts.
These are significant figures for an entity with many minor league
traits.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 Brazilians are performing outside the country,
many with top clubs in Europe, which still exhibits a colonial
mentality about South American soccer. Brazil is considered a vast
farm system to supply a gigantic industrial machine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the soccer industry's estimated worth is more than $260
billion, and 80 percent of that value is European. With that
financial advantage, European clubs are going to be predominant.
But when it comes to quality of play, South America more than holds
its own: Argentina, Brazil, and Uruguay have won half of the 16
World Cups contested.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Brasilerao'' season, which began last month, involves 22
clubs and more than 500 players. A few are foreigners, most notably
Colombians Victor Hugo Aristizabal (Santos), Faustino Asprilla
(Palmeiras), and Freddie Rincon (Corinthians), and Paraguayan
Francisco Arce (Palmeiras).
</P>
<P>
   Though the national championship is billing itself as ``The Best
Championship in the World,'' and it produces a Copa Libertadores
entrant, the state championships are equally significant. The state
of Sao Paulo, for instance, has about the same population as
Argentina (30 million) and a greater economy. This illustrates the
scope of Brazil, and gives an idea of its human resources and its
sporting system's ability to produce top-level athletes, despite
the historic instability of economy and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Corinthians has emerged as the top team in San Paulo and the
Brasilerao, with seven national team players, including the
unpredictable Edilson, barred from the Selecao after igniting a
brawl when he began mocking Palmeiras's tactics by stopping to
perform a juggling act in the middle of the second half of the
state final.
</P>
<P>
   Wanderley Luxemburgo, coach of the Selecao, is doing a juggling
act of his own to prepare for friendly matches against Argentina
Sept. 4 in Buenos Aires and Sept. 7 in Porto Alegre. He has called
in both Ronaldo from Inter and Ronaldinho Assis, the latest
19-year-old sensation, from Gremio; Rivaldo from Barcelona, Roberto
Carlos from Real Madrid, and Juninho, who was dropped by Atletico
Madrid and is with Vasco da Gama; plus three Roma players, Cafu,
Antonio Carlos Zago, and Marcos Assuncao.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Argentina did not recall Gabriel Batistuta, who is
questionable for Fiorentina's season opener.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still in power
</P>
<P>
   Brazil built the original Maracana, a 200,000-capacity
megastadium, for the 1950 World Cup. The Yugoslavians constructed
an imitation in Belgrade on the site of the Crvena Zvezda (Red
Star) stadium in 1963. When the lights went out there at halftime
of the Yugoslavia-Croatia game last Wednesday, it was another black
eye for Slobodan Milosevic, but when the match finished 0-0, the
Yugoslavs were in command of Group 8 of Euro 2000 qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia next visits Ireland in a showdown for the group lead
Sept. 1 in a match that was postponed when the Irish refused to
issue visas to the Yugoslav delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Croatia edged Malta, 2-1, Saturday to overtake both
Ireland and Yugoslavia for the group lead. But the Croats will
likely be without Boban, the Milan midfielder who was injured
against Malta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
