<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PREMIER IS ADEPT AT PLAYING POLITICAL HEAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With his thinning hair, angular face, and tightly
pursed lips, Vladimir Putin might resemble a stern high school vice
principal _ the type that scares the living daylights out of even
the best behaved pupils.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin apparently hopes that his latest
prime minister will do just that to the Kremlin's political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, Russia's fifth prime minister in 17 months, is well-known
for playing hardball with his political foes. He was appointed Aug.
9 after Yeltsin and his inner circle _ known as The Family _
thought his predecessor, Sergei Stepashin, hadn't proved tough
enough in his 82 days in office.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin's sin: He allowed Yeltsin's arch foe, Moscow's
ambitious mayor, Yury Luzhkov, to lure most of Russia's regional
leaders into an anti-Kremlin alliance that could dominate this
year's parliamentary elections and next summer's presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, however, earned a reputation for leaning hard on
opponents as deputy mayor of St. Petersburg, as the Kremlin's point
man on corruption, and as director of the KGB's successor agency,
the Federal Security Service.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, for example, NTV commercial television reported
that the wife of St. Petersburg Governor Vladimir Yakovlev was the
subject of a criminal investigation. The report is still
unconfirmed, but politicians and journalists in St. Petersburg were
unanimous in suspecting that Putin's hand was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly a political provocation,'' said St.
Petersburg-based investigative journalist Alexander Gorshkov, who
said that he didn't exclude that Putin was involved. ``Putin will
do whatever he is told by the president and his people.''
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly enough circumstantial evidence from Putin's
past to suggest such a move. Earlier this summer, for example, when
Putin was director of the Federal Security Service, that agency
began probing the affairs of businesses allegedly tied to Luzhkov's
wife. When Russia's federal prosecutor was investigating corruption
in Yeltsin's inner circle, Putin reportedly furnished the media
with video tapes of a man resembling the prosecutor frolicking with
naked women.
</P>
<P>
   And even before this year's political battles began to heat up,
Putin was busy leaning on regional leaders. Last year the Federal
Security Service opened corruption investigations of uncooperative
leaders in several regions _ in some cases arresting high-ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the Voronesh region, for example, Putin's Federal Security
Service went after associates of that region's governor, Communist
Ivan Shabanov. As a result of a corruption investigation last year,
two of Shabanov's deputies were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Kremlin and in the (Federal Security Service) Putin
dealt with regional leaders by using blackmail,'' said Nikolai
Petrov, a specialist in regional policy at the Moscow Carnegie
Center. ``He would gather compromising material on them and
threaten to use it if they don't behave as the Kremlin wants.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Russia's regional leaders enjoy immunity from
prosecution, Putin's Federal Security Service went after their
closest associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an attempt to frighten regional leaders, to show them
that even though they may be well-connected and have immunity from
prosecution, they can't protect their closest associates,'' said
Petrov. The message was loud and clear: If you are loyal, be as
corrupt as you like; if you cross the Kremlin, watch it.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years as a KGB spy in Germany, Putin's political career
began when he joined the local government in his hometown of St.
Petersburg. There, as a deputy to that city's first elected mayor
Anatoly Sobchak, Putin won praise for bringing foreign investment
to Russia's second city. He also was known as Sobchak's heavy
trotted out to deal with uncooperative foes.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Belyayev, who served as speaker of St. Petersburg's
city council in the early 1990s, said Putin was a master at
``psyching out'' local politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he talked to you he understood your psychological
profile, your needs, your weaknesses,'' said Belyayev. ``He used
this all to his advantage politically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
