<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEC IS TEEMING WITH SUBPLOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ Count David Duval among those at Firestone Country
Club this week who will feel like they are in a familiar room with
new furniture.
</P>
<P>
   That's because what used to be the NEC World Series of Golf is
now the NEC Invitational, and while it's still a PGA Tour stop,
it's now also part of the World Golf Championships, a annual series
of mega-events put together by pro golf governing bodies in the
United States, Europe, Australia, South Africa, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The WGC made its debut in February (Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship for top 64 in world rankings), and another will
be held in November (American Express Championship for top 50). For
this event, the international golf braintrust came up with this
idea: Invite members of the Ryder Cup and Presidents Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, 40 other players are here to attempt to knock Duval from
the champion's throne. He is, after all, the defending champ,
correct? ``Not really,'' said Duval, one of the few players who
checked in at Firestone Monday. He was on the range _ per usual,
hitting soft wedges _ and afterward said the makeup of the field
made for a different feel. Still, he said, ``It's an elite field.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, especially since it includes Duval, Tiger Woods,
and the kid from Spain who has muscled into their 1-1A act in
recent weeks, Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   But the field does not include all the winners of PGA Tour
events (and various world-wide tournaments) in the past year, which
used to be the criterion for an invite. Among those who are not
here? David Toms, who birdied the last two holes Sunday to pass
Duval and win the Sprint International in Castle Rock, Colo.
Fifteen other PGA Tour winners (Brandel Chamblee, Billy Andrade,
Chris Perry, Jeff Sluman, Rocco Mediate, Gabriel Hjerstedt, Tim
Herron, Loren Roberts, Olin Browne, Rich Beem, Ted Tryba, Duffy
Waldorf, J.L. Lewis, Brent Geiberger, and Tom Pernice Jr.) are not
here. Conversely, there are many in the field (Fred Couples and Lee
Janzen among them) who have not won in 1999 but earned invites
based on last year's Presidents Cup berth.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, another change to this year's event, and
its color matches the fairways of this plush layout. Green. As in
money. Lots and lots of it. Last year's purse was $2,250,000, and
when he won, Duval earned $243,000. If he were to successfully
defend, his paycheck would be $1 million, since the purse for each
of these WGC parties is $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The argument has been raised that a berth on the Ryder Cup team
indirectly earns you pay, for it entitles you to a spot in this
tournament, in which last place (there is no cut) pays $25,000. And
it affords you the opportunity to win many times that.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the topic of $5 million aside _ if it is possible to do
so _ there is an intriguing backdrop to this week's tournament.
That is, a preview of next month's Ryder Cup matches, since all 24
players are here. It won't mean a thing, but if the Americans play
much better here than their European counterparts, expect to hear
more observers talking up a US walkover at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   That's down the line, though. First things first for players
such as Jose Maria Olazabal, who Monday got in a practice round on
a slow day here. Then again, if you have fond memories of a place
(Olazabal stormed to a 12-shot win here in 1990 and triumphed again
in 1994), why not rush to embrace it?
</P>
<P>
   ``The course played great,'' said Olazabal, who owns the record
here with a 61 during that 1990 triumph. ``I said in 1990 that it
was in perfect shape, and it's the same this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to know that some things haven't changed at this
event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
