<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     08-24 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN OAKLAND, A IS FOR ARGUMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They started it. It is important for you to remember that. One
of them called me a ``chump.'' Another called me ``Mikey.'' One
misspelled my last name (Hollie?). Most misrepresented my words.
And then, essentially, all dared me to step outside for a verbal
rumble.
</P>
<P>
   I'm too old for this, right? It's been 10 years since I taunted
someone about sports, and even then I didn't have to say much. My
roommate at the time was a mouthy Steelers fan. So after the
Steelers lost their 1989 opener to the Browns, 51-0, I simply
flashed the screaming headlines from the Pittsburgh dailies
whenever he looked my way.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do with these Oakland A's fans, who have serenaded
me with e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   They are upset because they believe I slammed their team in a
column last week. They are angry because I had the nerve to
conclude that a team that hasn't had a winning record since 1992 is
``painfully mediocre.'' They fixated on 1986, called the Red Sox
the ``Blowsox'' and labeled me a Sox homer (Dan Duquette would get
a chuckle out of that one). They are angry because I believe that
playing for the wild card in August is silly. I know Sox fans can
point to 80 years of history to justify their belief in collapses
rather than comebacks, but I still think aiming for the consolation
prize is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   Responsible Option: Michael, be an adult. Stop this foolishness
and write about Brian Rose being sent to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Old-School Option: My man, they called you Mikey? What? Man,
dust off your Yo' Mama jokes right now. Like: Yo' Mama is so small,
you don't even call her ``Mama''; you call her ``A's attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe I should start.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I was surprised to learn that the A's even had
fans to taunt me. Oakland is the last team to win three consecutive
World Series titles. From 1972 to 1974, Oakland was the center of
the baseball universe. Except people in Oaktown were the only ones
who didn't pay attention. The average attendances those years were
13,164, 12,668, 11,124. In some cities, your attendance improves
when you get better. But East Bay logic is that fans decline the
more you win. I bet you could go to the middle of downtown Oakland
right now and yell, ``Hey, the A's won the '74 Series,'' and people
would start celebrating as if it were breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of all this is that I actually like the Bay Area. It
is the ultimate yin-yang setup, with artsy San Francisco on one
side of the Bay and gritty Oakland on the other. A brilliant writer
named Ishmael Reed spent a lot of time in Oakland (but native
daughter Gertrude Stein couldn't stand it). The Black Panthers and
an afroed Angela Davis made history in Oakland. When heiress Patty
Hearst was kidnapped in the '70s, her captors demanded an unusual
and honorable ransom: They wanted the city's poor to be fed. The
Celtics have Oakland's basketball team _ the Warriors _ to thank
for Robert Parish and Kevin McHale. Hip-hop fans have Oakland to
blame for MC Hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it chump,'' wrote an A's fan named Paul, ``the A's aren't
going away . . . Have fun scrambling for the wild card, it's the
only chance your scrappy little team has.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, maybe I shouldn't have said anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are not my team, but Paul may have a point. While
everyone focused on Pedro Martinez's outburst last week, no one
mentioned that he and the Sox failed on a chance to slug the A's
and reduce the Yankees' lead in the AL East to 5 1/2 games. That
would have happened if Martinez had beaten an impressive Oakland
rookie named Tim Hudson. Instead, the A's got a split of their
four-game series and the Sox didn't take advantage of the shaky
baseball/hint of turmoil coming out of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember an A's dynasty a few years back,'' wrote Bill,
``but I don't remember much from the Red Sox since the Mets
outclassed them. Was that in '86?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe I should start.
</P>
<P>
   These people really do have low expectations. Dynasty? I hope
Bill isn't talking about 1988-1990. During that time, the A's
appeared in three consecutive World Series and had a regular-season
low of 99 wins. They beat the Sox twice in the American League
Championship Series. They lost to the Dodgers in the '88 Series and
were swept by the Reds in '90. The '90 loss is still, I think, the
second-most disappointing sweep in Series history (the '54 Indians
have the top award all to themselves). But Oakland did win the
title in '89 _ the same year that the region was thinking more
about an earthquake than baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about Oakland is that educators aren't afraid to
experiment. A few years ago, the Oakland School Board brought the
world something called Ebonics. They tried to make the argument
that black English should be taught, as if it were an African
language such as Wolof or Ga. Ebonics from the East Coast to the
West: Is y'all fools crazy?
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans talk about being cursed, but they have competition from
A's loyalists. There will never be anything worse than building the
Yankees' dominance by giving up Babe Ruth, but in 1976, the A's let
the following players walk and received no compensation: Don
Baylor, Bert Campaneris, Joe Rudi, Sal Bando, Gene Tenace, Rollie
Fingers, and Willie McCovey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee,'' Bart writes, ``how many World Series have the Sox won,
ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Joan adds, ``It's soooo nice that the Red Sox have soooo many
World Series trophies. How many? Let me see. Two? No. One? No. Let
me guess!! None. Wow, they really have something to be proud of . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll get to that soon. But I will say that the A's have a cushy
September. They have 20 games against the Tigers, Devil Rays,
Royals, and Angels. A decent team easily wins 14 of those games.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Sox, all they can do is beat up on the bad teams in
front of them and hope that the A's handle the baseball the same
way their fans handle history. It's been a long time, but the Sox
do own some World Series titles. Five of them. The first one was in
1903. And there were even some fans there to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0119 </DOCNO>
