<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-WARREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS A RUNNER, WARREN IS STILL BACKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ How should we categorize the tale of one
Lamont Warren?
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy? Maybe. Comedy? Depends on how you look at it. Irony?
Yeah, that's it. Definitely some irony here. Or, better yet, this
may be a mixture of all three.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of our story is a running back who spent the first
five seasons of his NFL career backing up perennial Pro Bowler
Marshall Faulk in Indianapolis. After being released by the Colts
in April, Warren signed a free agent contract with the Patriots on
draft day. Now he could, potentially, spend the next five years of
his career backing up another Faulk, Marshall's cousin Kevin.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Warren was drafted by the Colts in the
sixth round the same year (1994) they took Marshall Faulk with the
second overall pick. Warren signed on for five years with New
England the same day the team drafted Kevin Faulk in the second
round. Both Faulks are from Louisiana, they're about the same size,
and they're the same type of running back _ shifty and elusive with
good receiving skills.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing they don't wear the same number, or we could be
talkut ``Twilight Zone'' material.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little ironic,'' Warren said. ``Just can't get away
from 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   With two games remaining in the exhibition season, it appears
that Kevin Faulk has a firm grip on the running back spot left
vacant by the offseason injury to Robert Edwards. Warren did start
the first game of the exhibition season against Washington but was
ineffective and quickly gave way to Faulk, who staked his claim
with an impressive debut. This past Saturday night against the
Cowboys, Faulk didn't fare as well, gaining only 17 yards on 11
carries, but that was against Dallas's first-team defense. He did a
commendable job making the most out of very little running room.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, on the other hand, gained 46 yards on nine carries
against Dallas, including an 18-yarder in the fourth quarter. Most
of that yardage, though, came against second- and third-stringers.
But the action Warren saw was probably a preview of his role for
the regular season. The former University of Colorado track star
entered on third downs and twice lined up in the slot in a
four-receiver set. He ran precise out routes and caught two passes
for 18 yards. Against the Redskins, he caught a 17-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   If Faulk can carry the ball 20-25 times a game, Warren would be
the primary pass catcher out of the backfield. But with Derrick
Cullors and now Harold Shaw in the mix at halfback, Warren's
carries may very well be few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Is this why he chose New England over such suitors as Cincinnati
and Green Bay? Did he come to the Patriots to do the same thing he
did in his native Indianapolis?
</P>
<P>
   ``(A starting job) is pretty much the reason why I came, because
of the opportunity,'' said Warren, who rushed for 603 yards and
five touchdowns in his career as a Colt. ``I've been around for a
long time. I just wanted to at least get that opportunity to start
one time. I'm not worried about it. Here I'm getting a chance and I
think they'll find a way to get me on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going out there and playing and doing my job. We've
got a few more preseason games to go, so I'm really not thinking
about (starting) right now. I'm just trying to make sure my
performance is good. I think that as long as I'm sound in my
assignments, all of that will take care of itself. Whatever the
role is, I'd be willing to play it. However it unfolds, I'd be
willing to do whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy, comedy, irony. Someday it'll make for an excellent
trivia question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-PUFF-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     08-24 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PUFF-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Puff Daddy lives large. He entertains fellow celebs and high
rollers at his house in the Hamptons. He owns a clothing line, Sean
John, a magazine, Notorious, and a restaurant on New York's Lower
East Side, Justin's. He was to play a quarterback in the movie ``On
Any Given Sunday,'' but the production kept getting delayed and he
had to bail. He has a deal with Miramax for a movie called ``King
Zuckerman.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles, not one of his frequent gestures, when a reporter
checks his fingers to see how many he has, the (lame) joke being
that he has his fingers in so many pies, you wonder if he's got
more than 10. ``Music is the number one priority,'' he asserts.
</P>
<P>
   He travels with an entourage that fills a van. He sports two
thick chains around his neck, one dangling a large
diamond-encrusted crucifix, the other an equally large and
diamond-encrusted madonna and child. He was raised Catholic and was
an altar boy. He's not a churchgoer today, but he says, ``I'm
definitely a 100 percent believer, I just don't practice. I
consider myself nondemoninational, but say I was baptized Catholic.
I turned out OK. I can't denounce it. I just couldn't get with the
whole idea of `Kneel here and do this.' It's not just Catholics,
but men making the rules, men with egos.''
</P>
<P>
   Puff Daddy, of course, is not without ego. And he can be more
than a little ostentatious, which some folks might see conflicting
with his professed spirituality. Case in point: His luxury car, the
chains around his neck. ``I can at times be ostentatious about
it,'' Puffy admits. ``You know, I'm human. Being a man, I can't be
judged by people. What you see is what you get. Because I worked
hard and made money, that doesn't give you any right to have
something against me. I found a lot of support from my fans and
people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Puffy supports a charity, Daddy's House, which supports programs
for low-income kids to which he says he's donated $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that seems to eat at Puff Daddy, at least to a degree,
is the suspicion that his fame comes at the expense of tragedy. In
1991, an oversold charity basketball game he organized resulted in
a stampede and the death of nine people. And there's the death of
the Notorious B.I.G., a shooting many think was done in retaliation
for the killing of Tupac Shakur, in a West Coast-East Coast rap
war. (No one has been charged in either killing. Puff Daddy says he
has no idea who killed Shakur or B.I.G.)
</P>
<P>
   With ``Forever,'' Puffy says, ``I definitely turned a corner,
but you know you have to handle whatever ball is thrown at you,
that's just the way some people got a hold of my name after what
happened. Of course, everything is magnified and that comes with
it. It's nobody's fault. The good things are magnified, too, and
you gotta take the good with the bad. . . . You go through them,
and when I went through them I had nobody around but God, so my
spirituality is so much stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the van, Puff Daddy juggles multiple mobile phones like a
Karamazov brother; during a rare moment when he's not on the phone
or talking to an interviewer, his eyes shut behind his dark
glasses, as he catches maybe a 30-second catnap, before the phone
beeps and the process starts up again. He apologizes for the
seeming rudeness _ ``family business'' _ but Puff Daddy is the
consummate multitasker. Cell phones are his lifeline to the world
outside his immediate physical orbit, and there are a lot of folks
he needs, or wants, to be able to reach out and touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like everything I have asked for will get done
wrong, so I just started making sure it got done right,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Puff Daddy admits he got wrong was agreeing to appear
in a video of a song called ``Hate Me Now,'' made by a friend, Nas,
that had Puffy up on a cross, Jesuslike, perhaps raising the aura
of Puff Daddy as a persecuted Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   What was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask myself that question,'' Puffy says. ``When I get in
trouble: Why the hell did I do that in the first place? I mean,
when we did this I didn't think that I tried to portray Jesus, but
it looks like I did. . . . People (would have thought) my
relationship with God was just a joke. I love God and would never
do that. I got myself into a situation and had to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not in the best way. There was an altercation between
Puffy and Steve Stoute, an executive at Nas's label, Interscope,
about the video. Puffy wanted out; Stoute held his ground. Stoute
alleged that Puffy turned over his desk, broke his arm and jaw, and
assaulted him with a champagne bottle. No bottles, no broken bones,
says Puffy. In June, they came to a settlement, though Puffy says
no money changed hands. The video never aired. (A Manhattan
district attorney is still pursuing the case even though Stoute is
not pressing charges.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be a learning lesson,'' Puffy says. One of his
flaws, he adds, is ``I have to take time to appreciate certain
things. Sometimes I don't realize the stuff I say, because of who I
am, they may take it in a different way. If I say `shut up' to
somebody, it's like, I gotta watch stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to join Puffy's crew, well, sorry, the spaces are
filled. ``I don't make no new friends,'' he says. ``I got my boys
right here and besides that, I don't need no new friends.'' A line
from ``P.E. 2000'': ``A lot of strange faces, I can only trust
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Romance? The CEO is single, recently broken up with his
girlfriend, Kim. A rough breakup? ``No,'' he says, ``100 times less
than yours (would be). I'm a cool cat.'' And what about the rumors
he's dating Jennifer Lopez? She's just a friend. ``We just be
kicking it,'' he tells the WJMN afternoon audience. ``You know,
everybody tries to assume. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing, and one thing only, Puff Daddy would like
you to take away from this story, it is this: His album is out
today (Aug. 24) And you should buy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
