<HEADLINE>
THE BASEMENT WASN'T AMONG THE FITTEST RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do retailers fail?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is pretty basic: There are too many of them to begin
with and they are all trying to expand at the same time. Even in
terrific economic times like these there simply aren't enough
dollars to support all of them. The laws of mathematics guarantee
some chains aren't going to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition has never been fiercer,'' says Eileen Leary,
an analyst with State Street Research.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement is just the latest casualty in the Darwinian
struggle that American retailing has become. The Basement filed for
bankruptcy Monday after years of poor financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation, the Basement is part of a good-sized
club. Fedco, a Southern California retailer, filed for bankruptcy
in July; Loehmann's, a popular New York discounter, filed for
Chapter 11 in May. Over the past few years, New England chains,
including Bradlees, Caldor, and Ames, have operated for a time
under the protection of the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   New England chains have been particularly vulnerable because the
region's population doesn't grow very fast yet the supply of stores
does. Some of the nation's biggest retailers have just arrived in
New England in the past few years, making an already tight market
even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart now has 95 stores in New England, up from 45 just four
years ago. Target, a subsidiary of Dayton-Hudson, has just begun
opening stores in Massachusetts; the company says it could have two
dozen stores in New England within the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the new entries literally take over the locations
vacated by the competitors they have vanquished. Life doesn't get
much more Darwinian than that. Both Wal-Mart and Target have made
bids for some of the sites Caldor once occupied. Caldor was forced
to liquidate when it couldn't come up with a viable recovery plan.
</P>
<P>
   What separates the winners from the losers?
</P>
<P>
   Size is one thing. The big national chains can take advantage of
scale to win lower prices from their suppliers. In the current
environment, where it is difficult if not impossible for stores to
raise their prices, those lower costs translate into bigger profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   The big chains can also make the investments necessary to build
state-of-the-art computer systems. According to Steve Paspal, a
money manager with Sovereign Asset Management, Wal-Mart has used
its computers both to keep precise track of what its customers are
buying and to keep its inventories as lean as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The deep pockets that come with size have allowed the national
chains to build bigger, more attractive stores where the
merchandise can be displayed in eye-catching ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger stores are easier to shop in,'' says Leary. ``You
can find what you want and get in and out fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But size isn't everything. Giants such as Sears, J.C. Penney,
and Kmart have all struggled. Their problem? Poor positioning, says
Susan D. Sampson, director of the Prince Program in retail
management at Simmons College.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a clear message,'' says Sampson. ``The
customer doesn't know where to put them in his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners, says Sampson, have a distinct identity: Wal-Mart is
the place to go for low-cost hard goods; Target is the star in soft
goods; TJX, a Framingham, Mass. chain, is a leader in family
apparel. Ames, which has twice gone through bankruptcy, has
prospered by becoming a chain that appeals mainly to low-income
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The losers aren't bad stores. They simply aren't special enough.
Their me-too message gets lost in he clutter and their customers
vote with their feet for competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Basement falls into this category. It is cheap, but not any
cheaper than many other stores. It sells clothes with well-known
lablels, but again, so do others. It may be special in downtown
Boston because of its history, but elsewhere it is one more
discounter trying to find a spot in a crowded market.
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't about to get any easier for retailers. The rise of
the Internet guarantees a whole new group of rivals for existing
players. If only a small piece of the pie goes to Internet
start-ups, there will be that much less for the bricks and mortar
companies to divide.
</P>
<P>
   And the economy isn't going to get better. Consumer confidence
is at record levels; the unemployment rate is near a 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have rarely been this good for retailers,'' says Mark
Zandi, chief economist at Regional Financial Associates, a
Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   When and if the economy weakens, the glut of stores will be more
pronounced and the competition will get fiercer still. At that
point, as Charles Darwin might have put it, only the fittest will
survive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
