<HEADLINE>
I HEARD IT THROUGH THE BOVINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGTSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McDonald's, the world's largest user of beef, is feeling the
heat again for its treatment of cattle. In the past few weeks,
militant animal-rights activists have been suspected in the burning
of a McDonald's in Antwerp, and a leading US animal rights group,
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, angrily abandoned
talks with the restaurant chain, charging the company viewed animal
welfare merely as a public relations issue.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, for its part, has offered some dramatic pledges. At
the company's annual meeting in May, Jack Greenberg, the chairman
and chief executive, vowed: ``We want to take industry leadership
in animal welfare.'' And recently, a McDonald's spokeman said: ``We
are sincere in this area and we have a big stake in the whole
issue. We want to make a positive difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you hadn't heard, McDonald's has moved swiftly on the
issue. The improvement in the animals' circumstances has been
nothing less than breathtaking. On a recent inspection tour, I
walked _ gingerly _ among the cattle becoming, you might expect, a
fly on the wall, and jotted down the following conversation. But
despite all I saw I am still no closer to answering the crucial
question: Are the cows happy?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, Patty, sometimes it all seems so futile,'' said
Chuck. ``Sure we've got it good _ it's great now. But what's the
point?''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck stretched his hooves out on the lounger, closed his runny
bovine lips around a fat Cuban cigar, and sighed the sigh of an
existential Holstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck, enough of the gloom, the despair. It doesn't do anybody
any good,'' Patty told him. ``Our parents and our parents' parents
and their parents' parents way back all suffered so we could enjoy
the good life.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a dreadfully hot August day, and a steaming rain pounded
on the roof. Chuck and Patty were dry and cozy in their single,
detached pen cooled by the breeze of a high-powered air
conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure they suffered,'' Chuck said, ``and I live with the
guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh brother,'' Patty moaned. ``Listen to me. Would you rather
be herded by the thousands like . . . like . . . cattle, and live
day in and day out with no room to breathe, let alone move, with
little light, have chemicals shot into you and feel all painfully
fattened up, and get diseased or go lame, have your liver fail on
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the same in the end,'' Chuck reminded her. ``But go
ahead and call the folks at McDonald's if you insist. They'll take
care of it, you know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't pretend you don't want cable TV too. Is it so much to
ask?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it makes it easier for you,'' Chuck said. ``But have a look
at me, Patty. What's there before you? That's right: a Big Mac. A
whole afternoon of Big Macs on the griddle. That's what it's all
about, Patty. We know exactly what we were put here on earth for.
So what's the use of everyone making a fuss whether or not we have
ice for our Cokes and all-cotton bed sheets?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck, can't you just enjoy what we've got?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, Patty, it's the good life that makes it all worse.
Cramp me in a stall. Inject me with strange drugs. Torture me any
way you like. I'll be a happier Chuck when my time comes to be
burgered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Utter nonsense, you old bull.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a rap at the door, and two men entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you here for the cable?'' Patty inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, ma'am. We're here for Chuck. Let's go _ hoof it, big
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But _'' Patty stammered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get philosophical,'' Chuck said. ``Just MOOOOO your
lungs out!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
