<HEADLINE>
IT'S HER RACE TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Silverbulletday win Horse of The Year honors?
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old filly put on an awesome display in winning the
Alabama by 9 lengths at Saratoga last Saturday, and, with
Charismatic, Silver Charm, Free House, Victory Gallop, and Real
Quiet lost to injury, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   This is beginning to shape up as one of those years when the
oldest, strongest male does not capture racing's biggest prize.
Behrens, the last legitimate handicap horse left, lacks charisma,
and though he is a gem of consistency, he has lost three races
(7-4-3-0). The Golden Eclipse is probably his to lose, but it won't
take much more than one more defeat for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday's record is sensational. She has won seven of
eight starts this year, 13 of 15 in her career. There is precedence
for a 3-year-old filly to be top horse, as the great European grass
filly All Along won it in 1983 after making an undefeated tour of
North America. And Lady's Secret was a worthy winner in 1986 at the
age of 4, proving that if females are popular enough, they can get
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, who is ridden by Jerry Bailey, trained by Bob
Baffert, and owned by Mike Pegram, proved she has the quality to
run long, which is important. She handled the mile and one-quarter
of the Alabama with ease, running away through the stretch even
though the pace was slow. ``She was a little wide and had to run
down a soft pace,'' said Bailey. ``She surprised even me, she's
that good.''
</P>
<P>
   What Silverbulletday hasn't done, something both All Along and
Lady's Secret did do, was beat males. Her only flop this year came
in the mile and one-half Belmont Stakes, when she tired after a
mile and one-quarter of battling the boys and faded to seventh. At
the time, Baffert offered several rationales for entering her in
such a tough spot, none of which made any sense.
</P>
<P>
   But Pegram came right out and said: ``If Charismatic (who had
already won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness) wins the Belmont,
there's no way he won't be Horse of the Year.'' Pegram, who also
owns Real Quiet, figured if Charismatic could be stopped, either
one of his two horses had a shot at Horse of the Year. If
Silverbulletday, who was sent right to the lead, happened to do the
stopping, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Pegram say they have no further plans to take on
males. Their next assignment for Silverbulletday, a meeting with
filly handicap standout Banshee Breeze in the Spinster Stakes at
Keeneland Oct. 16, is almost as daunting. Undefeated this year at 4
for 4, Banshee Breeze is herself a Horse of the Year candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If the voters are not inclined to vote for a female who has not
beaten males, that projects 2-year-old colt More Than Ready into
the big picture. Impressive from the start, More Than Ready is 5
for 5 and could be the real deal. Secretariat (1972), who was
worthy, and Favorite Trick (1997), who was not, both won Horse of
the Year as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   In an open year such as this, star quality counts for a lot.
And, right now, there's no bigger star than Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baez begins rehab
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Rudy Baez, who suffered paralysis from the waist down in
a spill at Rockingham Park Aug. 4, has begun an intensive
rehabilitation program at the Keeler Institute in West Orange, N.J.
The Keeler Institute specializes in spinal cord injuries and
treated actor Christopher Reeve, who was injured in a show jumping
accident and has become a spokesman for the cause. Baez, who
underwent surgery at Massachusetts General Hospital before being
flown to the Keeler Institute last Thursday, is scheduled for two
months of rehabilitation. ``He's doing well right now,'' said Mike
Szpuk, Baez's agent. ``He's getting ready for rehab.'' Noted for
his tenacious style, Baez, 47, was long the leading rider in New
England and won 4,878 races to stand 17th on the all-time list. His
wife, Judy, and their children, 16-year-old Jessica and 10-year-old
Christopher, appreciate the efforts of those who have offered
support, as cards and letters, including one from Reeve, have
poured in. Donations can be made to The Rudy Baez Fund, c/o Eastern
Bank (attn. Rachel Sosnowski), 125 Washington St., B309, Salem,
01970. The Internet site is www.rudybaez.com . . . Jockey Gary
Stevens, who has been riding in Great Britain, will return to the
United States in time to ride on the Travers Stakes program at
Saratoga Saturday. He will now ride first-call for the powerful The
Thoroughbred Corporation. Stevens, who went to England May 29, rode
46 winners overseas, his last being Maramba at Sandown Park last
Saturday. ``The entire stay has been fun, and the whole of Royal
Ascot was very pleasing,'' said Stevens. ``The variety of courses
keeps your mind fresh and keeps an extra hop in your step.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walden's double
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Elliot Walden will send out a powerful duo in the $1
million Travers, as he'll be represented by both Menifee, who won
the Haskell at Monmouth, and Ecton Park, who took the Jim Dandy at
The Spa, both on Aug 8. Both horses drilled over the Oklahoma
training track Saturday, with Menifee going 5 furlongs in 1:00 4/5,
and Ecton Park the same distance in 1:01. ``I was very pleased with
the works,'' said Walden. ``They both look like they came back good
and happy.'' Also working for the Travers was Lemon Drop Kid, who
won the Belmont but ran second to Ecton Park in the Jim Dandy. The
big colt went 5 panels over the main track in 1:00 2/5 . . . Malek,
a key contender for the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar
Sunday, went 6 furlongs in 1:10 4/5 Friday, raising the eyebrows of
trainer Richard Mandella. ``It's the best work I've ever seen him
do,'' said Mandella. The former champion of Chile finished third
four straight times this year, before Mandella dropped him into the
Viking Spirit Handicap July 29, which he won.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1310EDT &QL; 
