<HEADLINE>
PUFF DADDY'S NEW CD MEANS A CHANCE FOR PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The switch is flipped and the thin figure dressed in white,
wearing a cap and dark glasses, sporting thousands of dollars'
worth of jewelry and sitting quietly in a suburban radio station
studio, snaps to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whassup, whassup, whassup, whassup, Beantown, Boston, what's
goin' on?'' Sean (Puffy) Combs, a.k.a. Puff Daddy, asks the WJMN-FM
(``Jam'n'' 94.5) audience. ``I got a new album I'm promoting after
two and a half years. I'm gonna drop this new bomb on y'all. It's
called `Forever' and it comes out to the stores August 24.It's the
sequel to `No Way Out.' If you liked `No Way Out,' if you liked the
tour, get ready, we coming with a hotter album, a hotter tour, a
hotter everything.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got a glass of champagne by his side. He hopes _ believes _
he still has the world on a string.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity juggernaut that is Puff Daddy _
multiplatinum-selling hip-hop act, CEO of the Bad Boy Entertainment
label _ is on a roll. ``It's not wack, it's worth buying, you
know?'' he says, of ``Forever.'' It's the first week in August and
Puff Daddy is in the early phase of a 28-city promotional tour
where he will yak up his album, and its first single, ``P.E.
2000,'' all over radio. Here, he touches down at Logan, phones WJMN
in Waltham to say he's in the tunnel, running late. After he leaves
the station _ where he mentions the day of album release a dozen
times in under an hour _ he's spirited over to WILD-AM (1090) in
Roxbury where he yaks the yak again, dropping the names of his
costars on the album, R Kelly, Jay Z, Nas, Bizzy Bone of Bone
Thugs-N-Harmony, Lil' Kim, Twista, Busta Rhymes, Mario
``Yellowman'' Winans and others. The late Notorious B.I.G., Puff
Daddy's pal and Bad Boy cash cow, gunned down in March 1997 by an
unknown assailant, appear as well.
</P>
<P>
   A Puff Daddy album is very much about collaboration. He is more
the ``organizer'' than the star performer. He has referred to
himself as not ``an MC, but a vibe giver.'' During the
station-to-station journey, he talks to a reporter in the van. He's
less effusive, more laconic, and more serious in this mode.
</P>
<P>
   You can call him Puffy, Puff Daddy, P-Diddy, or he says,
``whatever you want to call me.'' He says he won't tell where he
got his nickname. ``Nobody knows that,'' he says, implying that
nobody ever will. The only person who calls him by his given name,
Sean, is his mother, or, he says on the radio, the police. ``When I
hear `Sean,' that is a serious, serious thing, like, you know,
somebody giving you a ticket.'' Famous for driving around in a
$375,000 1999 Bentley Azure, Puff Daddy won't be behind the wheel
for a while. License suspended, he says, long story. He has to take
a road test to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   But don't feel too sorry for him. You can spot Puff Daddy at No.
16 on Forbes magazine's list of top moneymaking entertainers, with
last year's income estimated at $53.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't bad,'' Puffy, 29, says, but he goes on to note that
real wealth is Rockefeller wealth, generations of it. Puff Daddy is
always looking at the next level up. ``When people talk about being
overly wealthy, that's like $500 million and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Offstage, Puff Daddy projects a serious mien. He's very much
about the business. Bad Boy Entertainment, a label that employs 300
people, grossed $200 million in 1997, $35 million last year. Puffy
stepped out from behind the producer's console _ where he launched
the Notorious B.I.G., Mary J. Blige, MA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
