<SLUG> BC-POP-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODING'S IN NEED OF A REAL ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1997, when he won the best supporting actor Oscar for his
role in ``Jerry Maguire,'' Cuba Gooding Jr. gave one of the most
exuberant, buoyant acceptance speeches in Academy Award history.
Who could have guessed then that, nearly three years later, we'd
still be waiting for him to do anything as memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding will soon be seen in the formulaic action film ``Chill
Factor,'' in which he shares above-the-title credits with Skeet
Ulrich. Yes, folks, that's Skeet Ulrich _ not to be confused with
Metallica drummer Lars Ulrich _ whose best known role is probably
as the skanky thug who beats up Greg Kinnear in ``As Good As It
Gets.'' Say what? When did Ulrich become enough of a star to merit
equal billing with the Oscar-winning Gooding, and how has Gooding's
post-Oscar path landed him in a movie with a bland young actor
named Skeet?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is yet another case of Hollywood racism rearing its
head. Everyone knows that most black actors are on the pay-no-mind
list when it comes to getting A-list roles. But when he snagged the
coveted statuette, Gooding looked good to defy the odds and break
big as a leading actor. Even though his greatest recognition came
in a supporting role, Gooding had already proven his star skills
with his debut (and still best) role as Tre Styles in John
Singleton's ``Boyz N the Hood.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's tough to name anything _ let alone anything
worthwhile _ Gooding has done in recent years other than those
stupid Pepsi commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he had a small role in ``As Good As It Gets.''
Last year, he played second fiddle to Robin Williams and
breathtaking art direction in the little-seen ``What Dreams May
Come.'' Earlier this year, he basically played the Jodie Foster
role to Sir Anthony Hopkins' hammy riff as a Hannibal Lecter-like
killer in the widely-panned ``Instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for ``As Good As It Gets,'' which, let's face it,
belonged to Jack Nicholson and Helen Hunt, none of his films have
been hits. So now Gooding is trying to trod the big dumb action
film route paved by his fellow Oscar recipient Nicolas Cage, who,
after proving his acting mettle in ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' turned
his attention to $20 million paychecks with dreck like ``Con Air,''
``The Rock,'' ``Eight Millimeter'' and ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Chill Factor'' _ which sounds like a cross between
``Speed'' and ``Broken Arrow'' _ Gooding and Ulrich play a couple
of guys trying to keep chemical weapons away from the bad guys. No
matter what spin Gooding may try to put on this, it can hardly be
viewed as a career-boosting move, and make no mistake, his career
needs a boost. After all, when he won the Oscar, he was mentioned
alongside such past winners as Denzel Washington and Sidney
Poitier. At the rate he's going, he may soon find his name in the
same category as F. Murray Abraham, who won a best actor Oscar in
``Amadeus,'' and went on to appear in such forgettable fare as
``Mobsters,'' ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' and ``National Lampoon's
Loaded Weapon I.'' Here's hoping we won't soon see Gooding in part
II.''
</P>
<P>
   Random thoughts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone know why Claire Danes, who has starred in two
stinkers this year _ ``The Mod Squad'' and ``Brokedown Palace'' _
is considered a major talent? Neither do I . . . Will someone,
somewhere please give the multitalented Lea DeLaria her own TV show
(she could easily revive the long-dormant variety format) or cast
her in a big, juicy part in a major film? She can sing, having
wowed critics in an off-Broadway production of the classic musical
``On the Town;'' she can act, having recently played Audrey in the
Williamstown Theatre Festival's production of William Shakespeare's
``As You Like It;'' and she's a ribald, take-no-prisoners comedian,
whose sharp comic tongue will be on display Thursday in her show,
``It's Delicious, It's Delightful, It's DeLaria,'' at Town Hall in
Provincetown. She has the same whip-smart, offbeat charm as Janeane
Garofalo, and certainly room should be made for bold,
think-for-themselves women who shun the Hollywood cookie-cutter for
their own quirky rhythms, which shatter every stereotypical female
mold . . . Boston, which for better and probably worse all but
invented the boy group phenomenon in the 1980s with New Edition and
New Kids on the Block, is again making its mark in the current wave
with LFO, which stands for Lyte Funkie Ones. Their hip-hop flavored
``Summer Girls'' is currently No. 3 on the Billboard's Hot 100
chart. Pop pablum rules!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
