u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-24 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS ON USAGE: WHOM DO YOU TRUST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's your favorite usage authority? I asked last week, having
concluded that Strunk &AMP; White's ``Elements of Style,'' almost
unrevised in its new edition, was doomed, left to fossilize by the
road as history marches past.
</P>
<P>
   I vaguely expected some consensus _ perhaps a plurality for
``Woe Is I,'' Patricia O'Conner's 1996 usage guide. But just as
Boston women don't buy their hats, but have their hats, usage-book
lovers seem to stand by their old reliables. Readers named books
from the '90s and books from the '50s, books familiar and obscure,
but only a handful of titles got more than one mention. One of them
was indeed ``Woe Is I,'' a modern Strunk &AMP; White with a sense of
humor and a dose of historical perspective. O'Conner knows when to
break the reductive Strunkian rules and when to admit that a
once-banned usage has become standard. Her chapter laying to rest
``The Living Dead'' _ those injunctions against hosting parties,
splitting infinitives, and using since for because _ is a model of
common sense. ``O'Conner makes you laugh, even if you're not
agreeing with her,'' wrote reader Beth David.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Conner shares the field with an even newer contender,
Becky Burckmyer's ``Why Does My Boss Hate My Writing?'' This is a
fine little book, despite the subtitle (added, no doubt, by some
marketing genius) that promises to help ``improve your writing 100
percent.'' Ignore it: Despite her utilitarian goal, Burckmyer
writes easily and winningly, though always erring on the side of
caution. You may know it's OK to split an infinitive, but if your
boss _ or your customer _ is less enlightened, you'll lose points
for it anyway, she notes. Burckmyer also gives some basic rhetoric
lessons _ how to compose an apology, how to deliver good news or
bad _ that are handy for real life as well as office life.
</P>
<P>
   There were good reviews, too, for William Zinsser's ``On Writing
Well'' and Claire Kehrwald Cook's ``Line by Line: How to Edit Your
Own Writing.'' ``Extremely well organized, with a good index,''
wrote Susan Shipley of Jamaica Plain of Cook's book. (The newer
edition, presumably seeking a wider audience, has changed ``Edit''
to ``Improve'' in the subtitle.) I have only a nodding acquaintance
with Zinsser, and hadn't heard of Cook, but I'll be taking another
look at both.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I've seen enough of Karen Elizabeth Gordon,
who writes the kind of books for which the term ``flight of fancy''
was coined. ``The Deluxe Transitive Vampire,'' for instance, is a
sampler of English constructions, dense with gargoyles and puns,
showing . . . I'm not sure what. But Philip Madell, who sent along
his glowing published review of ``Vampire,'' is a fan, and you
might be too.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might not _ and that's probably one reason so many people
stick with the guidebooks they know. Most usage writers are
covering the same territory, after all; what you're looking for is
someone whose voice you like, whose judgment you trust, whose
indexer has corralled all the references to issues you care about.
</P>
<P>
   But checking out the candidates is no easy proposition. Even a
good bookstore will have only a few usage books at any given time.
The online booksellers have dozens, but the reviews _ when they
exist _ aren't very helpful: You may despise a title beloved of
Arlene in Arkansas or Patience in Philly. (One new usage book, well
and widely reviewed, turned out to have long passages in blindingly
tiny sans-serif type; worse, its author used the phrase ``wax on
about'' as if it were standard. Say it isn't so . . .)
</P>
<P>
   What on-line customers really need is not reviews but a sample
page from each offering on the seller's Web site. One of the more
pretentious of the pretenders to Strunk &AMP; White's throne _ a book
called ``Adios, Strunk and White'' _ does have a long excerpt on
Amazon.com, and it's a revelation. The blurbs promise ``a mosaic of
brilliant techniques'' and _ more ominously _ an explanation of
``how to achieve writing notions.'' But the authors' own words tell
all: Their prose is pedestrian, their terminology gimmicky
(Time-warping! Layering! Uncorking!) and their grasp of etymology
shaky (``ossified in stone''). After a minute, it was adios forever
to ``Adios, Strunk and White.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were always that easy, I would buy _ I hope _ a lot more
usage books. But until the booksellers figure it out, I'll be
relying on your recommendations, and waiting eagerly for more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CULTURE-YIDDISH-ART-B     08-24 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-YIDDISH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OY AND THE JOY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's not easy to raise your kids in a language that
few people speak. But Michael Katz and Linda Gritz reaped their
reward this summer. When their 10-year-old daughter, Pauline, wrote
them a letter from overnight camp, they could hardly believe what
they were reading. Ikh hob geshriben tsu buba. Kenst du shriben tsu
mir, zizegute? (``I wrote to Grandma. Can you write to me please?''
Pauline wrote, using an English-based alphabet and a confident if
not word-perfect Yiddish, and signing it with her Yiddish name,
Perl.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited!'' exclaimed her mother, a scientist at a
biotech company. ``I was kvelling (beaming with pride) the rest of
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz and Gritz are among a tiny handful of English-speaking
couples in Massachusetts teaching their children to speak Yiddish,
the language of their East European Jewish forebears.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching children a second language might not seem remarkable _
except in the case of this particular second language. It is true
that Yiddish _ whose components are German, Hebrew, Aramaic,
Slavic, and the Romance languages _ has a lot to offer, as
languages go. It is rich, evocative, and colorful. With a
1,000-year history, it holds the key to a lost Eastern European
lifestyle and its traditions and culture. It's great for imitations
and punch lines, lending it a ``tremendous non-Jewish appeal,''
says Hankus Netsky of the Boston-based Klezmer Conservatory Band.
``It's ironic, it's catchy, it's exotic.''
</P>
<P>
   But useful Yiddish is not. The reality is that Yiddish, which
was spoken by nearly 10 million people before World War II, was all
but eradicated as a daily language by the Holocaust and by the
assimilation of Jewish immigrants. Few would dispute that its
heyday has come and gone, despite a recent revival of interest by
academics and performers. (Witness the recent release of the album
``Mamaloshen'' by performer Mandy Patinkin, featuring a Yiddish
version of ``Take Me out to the Ball Game.'')
</P>
<P>
   Still, you won't see street signs in Yiddish very often, or find
a ``recent Yiddish titles'' section at your local bookstore, or
overhear a fluent Yiddish conversation in the neighborhood _ unless
the speakers happen to be elderly, or are among those Hasidic Jews
who have held on to the language as the vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Katz and Gritz and other like-minded parents, raising their
children to speak Yiddish is not about nostalgia.We're not talking
about parents passing along a Yiddish phrase here or there, or
teaching the kids how to differentiate between a schlemiel and a
schlimazel. These parents are establishing Yiddish as the dominant
language of their homes, or making it at least as important as
English.
</P>
<P>
   They may send their children to a Yiddish-oriented summer camp
(Camp Kinderland in Tolland, which Pauline Katz is attending) or
plan their vacations around organized Yiddish events, with other
families: Next week, for example, the Katz-Gritz family will spend
time at a weeklong annual Yiddish retreat in Copake, N.Y., called
Yidish-Vokh (Yiddish Week). They may organize Yiddish play groups
for their children and get creative about inventing games,
converting ``Duck duck, goose,'' for example, to katchkele,
katchkele, genzele. They may even give the family pet a Yiddish
name, as have Mark David and Debbie Ellerin parents of two children
and a pug they call Zisi (``Sweetie'').
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course, is: Why? The answer would seem to
be: Why not? Some parents, like David and Ellerin, say they want
their children to be multilingual, and one reason they favor
Yiddish is because it is ``a great key to so much culture that's
normally encoded,'' says David, a software developer who also hosts
a weekly Yiddish radio show in Boston called ``The Yiddish Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Others grew up with Yiddish and want to keep it alive in their
families. ``My parents spoke it when they didn't want me to
understand, and then I understood,'' says Shifra Rosenthal, a nurse
and mother of two children, aged 4 and 16 months. ``I just love the
language.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yiddish is the major language of our families and was the most
beautiful aspect of our childhoods,'' says Rakhmiel Peltz, formerly
of Northampton, Mass. and more recently of Philadelphia. He and his
wife, Hannah Kliger Peltz, have taught Yiddish to their children,
now 8 and 6, ``to make sure they had the same jewels as we had.
When I hear Yiddish, that is what beauty is.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are also ideological. Katz and Gritz, parents of
Pauline and Ben, 8, were first exposed to Yiddish as children in
New York Jewish schools and summer camps. Katz says he was
influenced by the work of Yiddish labor poets and fiction writers,
with their commitment to social justice. ``It's given me moral
guideposts'' in life, he says. And teaching the children Yiddish is
a way ofsmitting our culture, which happens to have skipped
a generation,'' says Katz, a theater technical director at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Neverthless, trying to raise modern kids to speak Yiddish is
``very challenging,'' David says. One reason is that there are few
people with whom to speak it. ``You really have to make an
effort,'' says Peggy Davis, who, together with her klezmer musician
husband, Joe Kurland, are raising their son, Aaron, 5, to speak
Yiddish. ``But in rural areas, it's twice as hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another impediment to speaking Yiddish is that the language
stopped evolving about 50 years ago. How do you translate phrases
like ``disposable diapers?'' What's the Yiddish word for ``Burger
King''?
</P>
<P>
   (There are answers to these vocabulary dilemmas. New York
Yiddish scholar Mordkhe Schaechter has compiled a Yiddish-English
dictionary of childbirth and early childhood words. Entries include
the Yiddish words for ``breast pump,'' ``unwed mother,'' ``blow
bubbles,'' and ``don't take candy from a stranger.'')
</P>
<P>
   As far as Burger King goes, there are several solutions, David
says. You can be literal (cutlet meylekh, i.e., hamburger king);
make up a word; switch to English; or ``use English words lightly
Yiddishized,'' that is, speak the English words, but with a Yiddish
accent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there are other quandaries: Is it fair to expect a high
level of Yiddish from children, given that few people will
understand them? Is the occasional Yinglish word permissible?
Should a parent let poor grammar slip by?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a different opinion. For Gritz and Katz, whose own
mostly textbook Yiddish is less than fluent, ``better a broken
Yiddish than no Yiddish'' is a reasonable rule of thumb. Others,
like Ben Schaechter of New York _ a native Yiddish speaker who runs
the Yidish-Vokh _ insist that children speak with perfect grammar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak only Yiddish to my kids, period,'' says Schaechter,
composer, pianist, and conductor of a Yiddish chorus who grew up in
a Yiddish-speaking home in New York. ``It's very important to
establish a language as the language of the home, and not speak it
just on Thursday or Shabbos or if it rains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If my daughter speaks English, we don't answer her, or we say,
redt af yidish,'' which means ``speak Yiddish,'' concurs Shifra
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   What if a child doesn't want to speak Yiddish? There's not much
you can do, parents say. Linda Gritz acknowledges that Pauline
``uses Yiddish mainly when I push her to, or when she wants
something special and knows she can soften my heart more'' if she
asks in Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been successful in being vigilant enough in
getting our kids to speak Yiddish,'' says Rakhmiel Peltz. ``When
our son started speaking, he answered us in English, and we
accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are the occasional rewards for all this effort,
such as that described by David. Noting that Yiddish was the secret
language for an earlier generation of Jews who didn't want their
American children to understand them, David spoke proudly of a
recent incident in his own family that showed how much things have
changed in just a few years. His children were in a car with their
aunt and were overheard plotting in Yiddish about how they were
going to get her to buy them a toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they speak Yiddish so the older people won't understand,''
laughed David. ``My sister came home and said she was kvelling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
