<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7717 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BROWNS-2TAKES-BOS     08-24 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAWGS HAVE THEIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The cop at the intersection of Carnegie and East 9th
looked as if he were escorting a prisoner to life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland Browns Stadium?'' he repeated an unsuspecting
motorist's question. ``Just keep going straight.''
</P>
<P>
   He shook his head, and his voice assumed a tone of utter pity.
``Good luck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you say that?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' replied the officer, gesturing to the gridlock that
extended to Lake Erie on the horizon, ``that's where they're all
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 25,000 of them. Leaving work early last Tuesday afternoon
so they could be on hand by 5 o'clock sharp. For a preseason
practice. For their first look at the new Cleveland Browns, who
they fervently hope will be mistaken for the old Cleveland Browns,
a National Football League institution for 46 years before their
owner, the locally loathed Art Modell, uprooted them at the call of
a siren's song of riches and perks from Baltimore after the 1995
season.
</P>
<P>
   This franchise is truly a phenomenon, ``probably a one-time
situation,'' in the words of president and CEO Carmen Policy.
Indeed, it is doubtful any professional sports entity before or
after these Browns could describe itself as does director of
communications and public affairs Alex Martins: ``An expansion team
with a history.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because when Modell finally was bid good riddance on Feb.
8, 1996, all he got to take with him were the players who
constituted the previous Browns. Everything else belonged to
Cleveland: the name, the orange and brown team colors, the legacy
of a franchise that had sprung from Paul Brown's genius into the
short-lived All-American Football Conference in 1946 before
becoming an instant NFL dynasty four years later, and, most
important, a commitment from commissioner Paul Tagliabue that the
city would have a replacement, via either expansion or relocation,
within three years.
</P>
<P>
   What they were unveiling Tuesday was the result of the
unyielding leadership of Mayor Michael R. White, the cooperation of
the local business community, and, most of all, the ruckus raised
by a people's revolution that proved the big dog doesn't always
win, at least not against the Dawg Pound.
</P>
<P>
   So Chris Palmer, the 49-year-old former Boston University head
coach and Patriots assistant who was chosen as the field boss of
the new Browns, wasn't paying lip service when he observed, ``I'm
just a small part of what's happening. Really, it's the fans who
brought the team back.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that a sense of accomplishment and
self-congratulation engulfed Cleveland Browns Stadium _ such an
infant that its lakefront marquee proclaimed it the home of the
``CLEV LAND BROWN'' _ for the fans' first glimpse at the fruits of
their protest. The ballpark was the most obvious sign of revival
for those who survived the hourlong, 13-block, bumper-to-bumper
exhaust festival from Carnegie and East 9th and were lucky enough
to find a parking space in the municipal lots behind the Browns'
new digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put 6,700 cars in here,'' said Port of Cleveland
compliance manager Bob Dean as he manned a walkie-talkie along the
macadam shoreline. ``And we'll turn away twice that many: people
who don't have season tickets, curiosity seekers, and a few who
aren't even sure why they're down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they locked their vehicles, the patrons were dazzled by the
sight of the gleaming, $283 million, 73,200-seat steel-and-glass
oval that has sprouted on the very spot where once stood Cleveland
Stadium, the mausoleum that served as the foundation for Modell's
argument that he could no longer stay financially competitive with
his more lavishly housed rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The lie was put to that as the crowd streamed through the gates,
unable to wait for Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's more competitive introduction,
when the new Browns played their first game in Cleveland, a 24-17
exhibition loss to the Minnesota Vikings before a capacity crowd of
71,398.
</P>
<P>
   That was preceded by Friday's Welcome Home Browns parade along
Euclid Avenue in Public Square and a pep rally later in the
afternoon, the highlights of what the mayor declared to be Browns
Spirit Day. A crowd estimated at more than 30,000 saluted Browns of
the past ranging from Lou Groza to Bernie Kosar, hailed Browns of
the present such as Jerry Ball, paid tribute to their own efforts,
and trashed the preceding administration by purchasing the ``MODELL
SUCKS!'' T-shirts that were in abundant supply.
</P>
<P>
   And when darkness descended Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, downtown became an
enormous beacon, the skyline lighting up, per request of the mayor,
to illuminate the fact that the Browns are back.
</P>
<P>
   Some had been ready to trumpet that fact since the night before.
Municipal parking lot attendants reported that tailgating among the
particularly ravenous began at 1 a.m. _ 17 hours before game time _
while others started early Saturday serving as joyous counterpoint
to the Ku Klux Klan rally that commandeered several nearby city
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Latecomer Tim Franck was among a woozy crowd from Wooster, an
hour south, that had set up grills and coolers in a lot a
quarter-mile from the stadium at 9:30 a.m. Franck, a 48-year-old
paintbrush salesman, surveyed the vehicles _ many of them done up
in Browns colors and sporting some form of team insignia _ in the
lot and said, ``You want to know how you can tell the Browns are
back? You look around here and it's the same people in the same
places who've been here for 15 years. It's one big reunion. Three
years seems like two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Group leader Roger Veberba, a 38-year-old construction worker
from Maple Heights who bills himself as the Mayor of the Muni Lot,
had been partying since before 8 a.m. but promised not to wait
until the last minute to toast the regular-season opener against
the Pittsburgh Steelers on Sunday night, Sept. 12. ``We'll be here
Friday,'' he said. He was serious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of these revelers had been among Tuesday's faithful, most
of whom were getting their first taste of the new building's
innards, though some had been here the previous weekend for the
debut tour, part of a drive against hunger that required a can of
food as the price of admission. Motivated as much by anticipation
as altruism, some 100,000 donors passed through the turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   For Tuesday's workout, which featured a bare minimum of all-out
contact, special deluxe-sized tickets labeled ``Sneak Preview'' _ a
misnomer if ever there was one _ were mailed to the club's 62,000
season ticket-holders. Those who partook were advised to keep their
tickets for posterity; the ushers were tearing no stubs from the
sacred artifacts. There were, however, plenty of chances to spend
money. Merchandising stands throughout the stadium were doing a
land-office business; the No. 2 jersey of the Browns' _ and the
NFL's _ first draft choice last spring, quarterback Tim Couch, was
a particularly hot item in the 87-degree weather. Extra-large $5
beers, in keepsake plastic mugs with a Browns helmet on the front
and schedule on the back, were available at the swamped concession
stands, and some thirsty supporters carried around stacks of them,
like babushka dolls.
</P>
<P>
   But the product that had brought out the masses was down on the
field. The Browns players, dressed in their Halloween-treat
uniforms, were accorded a standing ovation, the three-year hiatus
finally over, once they could be coaxed out of their plush
surroundings. ``The players were in awe of the locker room,'' said
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   They were in awe of the support, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' said Couch, gazing around at the
adulation sprinkled through every section and in some of the 148
luxury boxes priced at $50,000-$125,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Browns set foot on the Kentucky bluegrass, their first
act was to return the favor. Like the cavalry, they trooped behind
the south end zone to the Dawg Pound, that notorious section where
kennelmates in years past would cheer the home team and rattle the
visitors with mock barking, throwing their passion and occasional
projectiles into each well-lubricated Sunday afternoon. Defensive
backs Corey Fuller and Tim McTyer applied the touchy-feely theme of
the day literally, leaping the 7-foot barrier in front of the
stands to slap five with some of the Dawgs in the front row of the
orange aluminum bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally different,'' said cornerback Antonio Langham, a
once and present Brown who had worn the team colors for the
surreal, funereal farewell of the Modell regime on Dec. 17, 1995.
``It feels so good to hear the screaming and the hollering.''
</P>
<P>
   All for an otherwise routine scrimmage, offense against defense,
in which each numbingly regimented and repetitive exercise was
announced over the public address system: ``The next segment will
be nine-on-seven drills consisting of 15 plays.'' The only
semblance of combat occurred during full-contact goal-line plays
for the final five minutes of the two-hour session, and a
high-decibel roar arose when former Patriots afterthought Sedric
Shaw cracked through the middle for the first touchdown on third
and 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
