<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-GREENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S GREENS TAKING POWER, SET CENTRIST COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Last month, when Belgium's newly installed
transportation minister, Isabelle Durant, was informed that she was
entitled to a sporty BMW sedan, she politely declined the perk.
</P>
<P>
   Like other environmentalists who have taken power across Europe,
Durant has compromised on some things but she draws the line at
driving a gas-guzzler, even if it comes free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly but inexorably, the so-called ``Green'' parties of
Europe, once considered part of the radical fringe, are becoming
more mainstream and gaining power throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the so-called 68'ers, radicals who led and took part in
the student uprisings of the late 1960s, have left the communes of
yesteryear for the committee rooms of today. Leaving behind an
uncompromising ideology, often born of youthful idealism, they have
found influence by engaging in the give-and-take of pragmatic
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what was most responsible for the change, Niki
Kortvelyessy, a leading member of the Brussels-based European
Federation of Green Parties, said, only half-jokingly, ``It's
called reaching middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aims have not changed. The strategies have changed,'' she
said. ``If the Greens have been about anything, it's about change.
You can make more change in government, but there's a price to be
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that price is compromising when the bigger coalition
partners balk at shutting down nuclear power plants or lowering
speed limits. By agreeing to compromise, however, more Greens are
gaining positions of authority rather than being consigned to the
margins of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Greens are primarily environmentalists, their
platform encompasses pacifism and a social agenda that is decidedly
to the left.
</P>
<P>
   And their ascent has been relatively swift. The British Green
Party, Europe's first, was founded in 1973, but most European
environmentalist parties were not formed until the 1980s. It was
not until 1984 that European Green parties organized themselves in
a loose federation, and it was not until 1993 that a Green party
member sat in a government Cabinet. Today, 12 countries in the
15-member European Union have Green parties.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they sit in five coalition governments _ Finland, the
first country to have a Green Cabinet member, Belgium, France,
Italy and, most prominently, Germany, Europe's biggest country.
Outside the EU, they have made gains this year in eastern Europe,
with Cabinet ministers in Poland and Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Greens upped their numbers in the 626-member European
Parliament from 27 to 47. In the elections, the Greens doubled
their vote in Britain, France, and the Netherlands, and they
dramatically increased their share of the vote everywhere except in
Germany and Italy, where it fell slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Michaele Schreyer, a German environmentalist, is
expected to be confirmed as the first Green to sit on the 20-member
European Commission, which oversees the administration of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   As they leave the fringes, however, the Greens have had to
compromise on some sacred tenets. In Germany, for example, the
Greens had to swallow hard when Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
refused their demands for the immediate mothballing of all nuclear
power plants. Instead, they settled for vague commitments from
Schroeder to phase out nuclear power. Greens have had to be
similarly patient in France, where their newfound clout has led to
the closing of just one of the country's 57 nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   But it was NATO's war against Yugoslavia that presented the
pacifist Greens with their biggest dilemma, and also showed just
how much the 68'ers and other former radicals who now lead the
Green parties have changed.
</P>
<P>
   One of those 68'ers is Joschka Fischer, who as Germany's foreign
minister is arguably the world's most powerful Green. Hitherto a
pacifist, Fischer said his attitude about using force changed after
the Serb massacre of civilians at Srebrenica in Bosnia in 1995. He
emerged as one of Europe's staunchest defenders of using force
against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. But he barely
managed to hold his Green Party together over the war, which marked
the first time since the end of World War II that German forces
were engaged in combat.
</P>
<P>
   If Fischer's personal journey personifies how former radicals
have become current establishment figures, so, too, does the
odyssey of Daniel ``Danny the Red'' Cohn-Bendit. A leader of the
student revolt of May 1968 in Paris, Cohn-Bendit has mellowed with
age and since 1994 has served in the European Parliament as one of
Germany's Green representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years after he was expelled from France for his
activism, Cohn-Bendit coordinated the Green campaign in France for
the European election, which saw the French Greens double their
vote. At 54, he still insists nuclear power must be phased out, and
that some drugs should be legalized. But he speaks approvingly of
the European Central Bank, accepts the necessity of immigration
limits, and advocates raising the retirement age to 70.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of former radicals mellowing, the Greens are
also throwing their weight around. Earlier this month, after the
European Union lifted a three-year ban on British beef imposed
because of ``mad cow'' disease, German Health Minister Andrea
Fischer, a Green, refused to lift that country's prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, a Green parliamentarian, Magda Aelvot, was named
health minister last month and promptly launched a crackdown on
contaminated food. The lack of decisive action by the previous
government in the face of a report of cancer-causing dioxins in
animal feed was widely cited as the reason Jean-Luc Dehaene was
booted out as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The growing influence of Greens in government makes it likely
that trade wars between the United States and the European Union
will become more common. The Greens have led European opposition to
the import of US beef from hormone-treated livestock and to the
testing of genetically-modified crops, most of them produced by
US-based multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   There are limits to Green power, however, as the German Greens
learned when they tried to muscle their much larger coalition
partners, Schroeder's Social Democrats. And France's Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, a socialist, refused to give in to demands from his
Green environment minister, Dominique Voynet, for a general amnesty
for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the Greens had to decide whether to withdraw
their support from the government on principle, or retain their
influence and fight another day. Increasingly, Greens are choosing
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   To some, that means sellout. Green party officials believe the
drop in their vote in Germany and Italy in the European elections
was a rebuke from longstanding supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are grass-roots fundamentalists who expect the world to
change overnight because the Greens have gotten into government,''
said Kevin Saunders, a leading member of the British Green Party.
``They don't understand why they're not living in a green utopia.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders says most European Greens have a more patient,
realistic view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compromise has got to be part of politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For all their newfound pragmatism, Greens are still prone to
stand on principle, no matter how much it embarrasses the
government. In Austria last week, a leading Green, Peter Pilz,
lambasted the government for allowing a top aide to Iraq's
President Saddam Hussein to obtain medical treatment in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   While Pilz catalogued Izzat Ibrahim al-Durri's alleged
involvement in mass killings of Kurds in northern Iraq, and filed a
complaint seeking his arrest, an embarrassed Austrian government
acknowledged it had granted a one-month visa for humanitarian
reasons and said Ibrahim had diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ashamed of the Austrian government,'' Pilz said. ``The
country is becoming a paradise for mass murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   As Europe increasingly becomes a region without economic
borders, the Greens are also emerging as the leading opponents to
the creation of large markets that exploit economies of scale,
seeing the movement of food and products over long distances as a
needless waste of gasoline and a threat to the small, local shops
where most Europeans do their shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a turning point,'' said Saunders. ``One of the things
Green parties across the world are working for is a closer
relationship between the consumer and the producer, the whole idea
of getting markets closer to people. Why ship cauliflower halfway
across Europe when you can get it grown locally? This is about
revitalizing communities, it's about saving the local shop from
being swallowed up by the supermarkets. It's moving back 40 or 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that sounds more reactionary than radical, he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now we're radical conservatives,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
