u a BC-PENNY-ENEMY-BOS &LR;      08-24 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNY-ENEMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THOUGHTS FOR YOUR PENNIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The penny has many enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Bot, 32, a psychologist from Toronto, occasionally
drops a penny and chooses not to pick it up because it ``isn't
worth the trip.'' Eighteen-year-old Eben Ellertson, a college
student, blithely listens to them rattle up the vaccuum cleaner
tube. And then there is Melissa Ceurvels, 25, who has been known to
throw out a penny because it was ``sticky.''
</P>
<P>
   It's characters like these _ capricious youngsters striding over
pennies, building up 10-year stockpiles or tossing them out car
windows _ who have taken so many coins out of circulation that the
US Mint this spring was forced to increase its penny production by
33 percent over 1997 rates.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston sent letters
to banks asking them to drop surcharges for customers who want to
redeem unrolled pennies for more substantial denominations, said
bank spokesman Thomas Lavelle.
</P>
<P>
   While laypeople typically refer to this as a ``penny shortage,''
the US Mint prefers to call it a ``unusually high penny demand'' _
evidence, in other words, that the penny remains a crucial part of
the economy. But critics of the penny say the circulation crisis,
like the ``take a penny'' dishes that have proliferated next to
cash registers across the nation, is a sign that the coin is
becoming more trouble than it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a penny is used in a transaction, it's a one-way
transaction,'' said James Benfield, executive director of the
Washington-based Coin Coalition and a longtime penny critic. ``In
other words, it sits in a jug at home. If there were really a need
for a penny on the market, it wouldn't be there.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer's penny crisis hit New York City hard after a flood
of cash transactions over the Fourth of July weekend. During the
worst of it, some desperate New York retailers were rounding off
all purchases down to the nearest nickel. By comparison, New
England has not been seriously affected, and in the days since the
letter went out to New England banks, coin supply has already begun
to build back up to normal levels, Lavelle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an ebb and flow to these things. I know I, and perhaps
you, on occasion get lethargic about pennies,'' he said. ``It's an
interesting, quirky situation, but this is not problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   But this summer penny crunch, like earlier ones in 1981 and
1994, suggests that hoarding can cause serious problems for the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Coinstar, a Bellevue, Wash. company that
manufactures coin-counting machines, suggests that the lack of
respect for the penny is generational. The June survey found that
47 percent of Americans between the ages of 18 and 34 had thrown
away a penny at least once in their lives, compared to only 11
percent of Americans over 65. Twelve percent of Americans surveyed
said they would not pick up a penny from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   That the penny has become a lowly-regarded currency was brought
home recently to Gerry Noonan a spokesman for the Connecticut
Bankers' Association, when he bragged to his 22-year-old son about
finding some coins on the floor of his garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Oh, Dad, nobody picks up pennies anymore. I only
pick up dimes and quarters,''' Noonan said. ``And I think when the
members of the Federal Reserve are a little younger, they might do
away with the penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Coinstar, an 8-year-old company, has capitalized on America's
hoarding ways. The company was founded by a business school
graduate who had stared too long at his own jar of unsorted coins.
</P>
<P>
   For an 8.9 percent service fee, Coinstar machines located mostly
in supermarkets will roll coins into the paper wrappers banks will
accept _ a time-consuming task usually foisted on young children.
</P>
<P>
   Working from their estimate that Americans are hoarding $7.7
billion worth of change, the company has capitalized to the tune of
$142 million in commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a service that's taken off,'' said Michelle Avila,
a spokeswoman for the company. ``Sometimes people balk at the
service fee, but if your time is worth more than $1 or $2 an hour,
it's probably worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over the penny's future came up in 1989 when Congress
considered legislation to abolish the penny, but never acted on it.
</P>
<P>
   Benfield, whose Coin Coalition is backed in part by the
vending-machine industry, says the main proponents of keeping the
penny come from the zinc industry and the US Mint, which still
sells pennies to the Federal Reserve for more than it costs to
manufacture them.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the penny say doing away with it would nudge up
prices for everyone and especially hurt the poor, who are more
likely to perform frequent small cash transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But Benfield calls himself ``a strong advocate of cent
pricing,'' and recommends that final trasactions ending in 1 or 2
cents be rounded down and those ending in 3 or 4 cents be rounded
up _ already common in US military stores overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in the future, Americans will say `We've had
enough of this silliness,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to phasing out the penny is as much emotional as
practical. Americans unlike many foreigners have never seen a coin
eliminated because of inflation, said coin experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it's a great testimony to the political stability of
our country,'' said Bob Fichter, a spokesman for the Massachusetts
Bankers' Association. ``For years and years, we've had this coin,
whereas in places like Russia and Brazil they're deciding to reduce
the 100,000 ruble note to one ruble.''
</P>
<P>
   But symbolism doesn't mean much to the 20-somethings who pass
pennies by because they don't feel like bending overockets. Erik
Geagan 27, rendered swift judgment on the coin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Useless,'' he said, without pausing. ``It's a currency I feel
you should do without.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
