<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HURRICAN-SEASON-ART-B     08-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICAN-SEASON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECASTERS PREDICT SURGE IN HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Bret was just the beginning. Specialists in hurricane
forecasting agree that this year is likely to produce more
hurricanes than average, and perhaps four severe ones (those at
least as powerful as Bret) instead of the two seen in an average
year.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the specialists say next year may be just as bad. In
fact, people on the Atlantic Seaboard may have been lulled into a
false sense of security by three decades of unusually low hurricane
activity _ during which construction along vulnerable coastlines
has boomed as never before. As a result, the nation could be in for
coastal devastation that might dwarf that of any storm in history.
</P>
<P>
   But, the meteorologists stress, such long-term forecasting deals
with averages, and it is still impossible to be sure what kind of
hurricane activity will really occur in any given year. ``The
statistical indicators are mostly positive this year,'' said Kerry
Emanuel, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology atmospheric
scientist and hurricane specialist, indicating that it is likely
there will be more than the annual average of six hurricanes, with
two of them major (winds over 111 miles per hour).
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June through November.
</P>
<P>
   William Gray, a Colorado State University meteorologist whose
team makes one of the few detailed, annual predictions of hurricane
activity, expects that this year there will be nine hurricanes,
four of them major. Forecasters at Florida State University, headed
by climate scientist Jim Eisner, agree with that prediction, and
say that next year will produce similar elevated numbers; as part
of an experimental five-year forecast, they say the following two
years will be below average, followed by another highly active year
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   While no other groups are willing to go as far out on a limb
with long-term predictions, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration's National Hurricane Center also agrees with the
forecast that this year will produce more hurricanes than average.
</P>
<P>
   But, Emanuel cautioned, in all such predictions ``there is a
large margin of error. It could be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the expectation of high activity in the Atlantic
this year is the fact that the El Nino/La Nina cycle, which relates
to the amount of warm water in the eastern equatorial Pacific, is
now squarely in the La Nina phase. This part of the cycle,
characterized by cooler than usual Pacific water, is typically
associated with heavy hurricane years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this correlation is quite strong, according to a new
analysis by Roger Pielke of the National Center for Atmospheric
Research and Christopher Landsea of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, which will be published in October in
the Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows that in most La Nina years (17 out of 22, or 77
percent), hurricanes have struck the US coast to produce over $1
billion in damage. Far fewer El Nino years (only 7 of 22, or 32
percent) have had storms that did so much damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some climate scientists say this association arises because in
El Nino years, high-level winds tend to be stronger, causing the
tops of storms to be sheared away before they can strengthen, while
in La Nina years such winds are weak. But Emanuel said that while
the statistical connection is clear, the reasons for it are ``a lot
of speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Pielke said that such statistics are unlikely to be
of much value for coastal dwellers: Nobody should cancel insurance
or move away just because of such statistical differences. But this
analysis could be significant both for the reinsurance industry and
for emergency planning officials, who can take extra steps to
prepare for the possibility of major storms.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in anticipation of a heavier-than-usual hurricane
year, officials might set aside more money in emergency response
budgets. But, Pielke said, in years forecast to have low activity,
``I wouldn't do the opposite, because large losses are possible in
any year.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the total monetary damages, Pielke said, the
four-year period from 1991 to 1994 _ during which the devastating
hurricane Andrew struck Florida _ was actually the quietest such
period in this century. But the peak of recorded activity came just
on the heels of this quiet period. The total number of Atlantic
tropical storms from 1995 to 1998 was greater than any other
four-year period since records have been kept: 53 named storms,
with 32 hurricanes, even though 1997 was one of the quietest years.
</P>
<P>
   But the impacts vary by region. In Florida, Pielke said,
hurricanes from 1944 through 1950 produced more damage (adjusted
for inflation) than all the storms in the nearly half-century since
then _ including Andrew. And while the '95-'98 period spawned many
intense hurricanes, the strongest ones struck in the Caribbean or
in Central America, leaving US coastal dwellers unshaken in their
complacency.
</P>
<P>
   Bearing in mind that many people living in coastal communities
have lived only in this unusually benign period and are not
accustomed to the kind of hurricane devastation that is typical
over the long term, Pielke recommended they ``prepare for the
past.'' In other words, people should expect an eventual return to
the stronger hurricane conditions that prevailed in the earlier
part of this century _ although Pielke himself is unsure of whether
the recent four-year period of intense activity represents the
beginning of that return, or just an anomalous break from the calm.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups support the forecast of a strong hurricane season
this year, as well as in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Joe D'Aleo, chief meteorologist for Weather Services
International in Billerica, Mass., noted that many of the major,
most memorable East Coast hurricanes of the past have come in La
Nina years like this one: The ``Great Hurricane'' of 1938, and
hurricanes Carol and Hazel in '54, Diane in '55, and Hugo in '89.
</P>
<P>
   Pielke stressed that people in coastal areas should prepare
themselves for a return to the conditions of greater hurricane
activity that occurred in the 1940s and '50s. ``We undoubtedly will
find that there are cycles and relationships'' that bring about
greater and lesser periods of hurricane activity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, we've been lucky in recent years in the US,'' he
said. ``If it happened before, that's a pretty good indicator that
it can happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
