<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Shanghai) _ The Chinese government announces it will
prosecute leaders of Falun Gong sect. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ACCORD (Nairobi, Kenya) _ After weeks of delay, rival
rebel factions are expected to sign a Congo peace plan, raising
hopes for actual peace. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ACHEBE (Lagos) _ Chinua Achebe, the Nigerian writer and
critic of military rule, has come home for the first time in nine
years. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC (Dateline to kum) _ Developments outside the
town of Orahovac, as Russian peacekeepers and Albanians negotiate
after the Russians were blocked from the town on Monday. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-NKOREA (Almaty) _ Kazakhstan sells 40 MiGs to North
Korea, prompting the U.S. to consider sanctions. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR (Berlin) _ Story about the continuing
negotiations on compensation for those forced into slave labor by
the Nazis. Talks were conducted Tuesday in Bonn; the goal, unlikely
to be met, is to wrap up by Sept. 1, the anniversary of the
invasion of Poland. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Dateline to kum) _ In the wake of last week's
earthquake, even major issues like the Kurdish conflict have been
blown off the national agenda. Debate over the government's
proposal to offer amnesty to guerrillas who surrender, for example,
has been postponed indefinitely. And although Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit had announced his support for large investments to combat
poverty and unemployment in the mostly Kurdish southeast, there
will probably be no money to pay for such programs now. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ANCIENT-BODY (Whitehorse) _ Scientists announce finding
the body of a frozen hunter that may be 5,000 years old. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SWISSAIR-BURIAL (Washington) _ New technology collides with old
religious principles on the tricky question of how to handle the
remains of people killed in the SwissAir crash a year ago. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHAT-ROOM-SYPHILIS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco health
officials, tracking an outbreak of syphilis cases, found that as
many as 99 men met each other on the same AOL chatroom, then had
sex, perhaps infecting each other. Although people have met each
other for sex on the Internet before, this is the first big cluster
of sexual activity that started in cyberspace and has now been
documented to have lead to an outbreak of sexually transmitted
disease. One man had as many as 47 partners. Many of the men knew
each other only by made-up chatroom names and the health department
is using the Internet to track them down. In addition, some of the
men are HIV positive. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   HEMP-SEIZED (Detroit) _ Officials have seized 40,000 tons of
sterilized hemp in Detroit, on its way from Canada, where it is
legal, to farmers in U.S., where it's not legal. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Federal Reserve policy makers meet to
consider interest rates; a quarter-point raise has been expected.
The announcement is expected at 2:15 p.m. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS-AIRLINE (Minneapolis) _ Many cities root unabashedly
for the home-town business. But here, where Northwest Airlines has
its headquarters, employs tens of thousands and controls 80 percent
of the airline seats out of the city, many people are rooting for
Sun Country Airlines, a small charter airline that started flying
to 15 destinations in June. Still, Sun Country's experience shows
how difficult it is for a small airline to make it in head-to-head
competition with an industry giant at its so-called fortress hub.
By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AUTO-WORKERS (Detroit) _ Looking at the state of
negotiations between the Canadian Auto Workers union and auto
makers and what that may mean for the UAW. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AIRLINES (Undated) _ A Canadian investment firm, with
backing from American Airlines, offers $3.8 billion to acquire Air
Canada and Canadian Airlines and merge the two.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:15 p.m., stocks were little changed.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 12 points, but the S&AMP;P
500 was up 4 point and the Nasdaq was up 39 points. At midday, the
30-year bond was yielding 5.97 percent. In Europe, markets were
mixed, with London down 0.35 percent and Frankfurt up 0.42 percent.
Tokyo closed down 0.76 percent; Hong Kong, up 0.44 percent.
</P>
