<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-VENTURA-BEATTY-POLITI     08-24 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURA-BEATTY-POLITICIANS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITIES FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
  
 WARREN BEATTY SOUNDS LIKE POTATO CHIPS and OTHER POLITICAL &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   What a stupid year this has been for American politics.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic was launched this spring when Minnesota elected
former wrestler and professional bigmouth Jesse Ventura to the
governor's chair _ thus rendering Garrison Keillor impotent as a
satirist.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to chuckle about cute little Lake What's-It's-Name
when the real citizens of the region are being captained by a
chrome-domed trash-talker in a fringe jacket?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more ridiculous than the election of Ventura was
the reaction from the media. Sure, a cartoon character winning a
gubernatorial slot in a big cold empty state made for an
interesting feature story _ but the press acted as if Batman had
been elected president of the free world. I mean, how much power
does the governor of Minnesota wield, even in Minnesota?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the tone was set for '99. Nothing was too silly to
be taken seriously. When Ventura's former adversary, the aging and
frighteningly oily-trunked Hulk Hogan, made noises about running
for president, he garnered an inordinate amount of attention _ as
if the guy could actually wrestle the electoral college majority
away from George W. Bush or an Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another wrestling match has been dominating headlines
for weeks _ make that months. Even though the residents of at least
49 states couldn't care less about the Senate race in New York _
which is still more than a year away _ the Time and Newsweek
magazines and ``Hardballs'' of the world have been breathlessly
covering the Rudy Giuliani-Hillary Clinton matchup as if it were
the ultimate in Wrestlemania excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Both potential candidates have been acting like goofs _ Hillary
with her Yankees cap and her coy interviews and her pompous
``listening tour,'' Giuliani with his grandstanding campaign jaunt
to Arkansas and his acerbic remarks about the first lady. Gosh, New
Yorkers will be lucky to have either of these dignified greats
representing them in Washington, won't they?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the press is dying for this fight to happen. The
talking heads keep telling us that if Giuliani and Clinton do
square off, it'll be the most fascinating political race in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that Kennedy squeaker over Nixon in 1960 didn't contain
any drama or change the course of world events or anything.
</P>
<P>
   If the above follies aren't stupidity enough for one year,
consider that Jerry Springer's name was floated as a potential
candidate for the Senate in Ohio _ until Springer's office issued
an official denial last week.
</P>
<P>
   Could I be dreaming, or did I actually hear Springer say: ``Of
course I won't be running. I've spent the better part of this
decade overseeing the worst carnival freak show this country has
ever known, and I'm too ashamed of myself to take a walk in public,
let alone run for office. What's wrong with you people!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe imagining things. Just kidding. What Springer
actually said was that it was ``impractical if not impossible for
me to make a run for the Senate at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't count me out in the future, America.
</P>
<P>
   And even as Springer was issuing his denial, the media was
working itself into a lather over the possibility of Warren Beatty
running for president _ perhaps the stupidest of all the stupid
stories of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I love Warren Beatty's work as a Hollywood hyphenate. When
not seducing just about anyone worth seducing in the 213 and 310
area codes, he has produced an incredibly versatile and compelling
body of work, from ``Shampoo'' to ``Heaven Can Wait'' to ``Reds''
and ``Bulworth.'' But have you seen this man try to communicate
without a script? He's about as articulate as a bag of potato
chips. This guy couldn't win a debate with a mime.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty reportedly won't make a final decision until next month.
If he does decide to throw his charm into the ring, it'll be
interesting to see how he responds to the ``Have you ever used
cocaine?'' question the New York Daily News has thrown at all the
candidates. (George W. Bush refused to answer. Everyone else has
replied in the negative.) One imagines the elliptical Beatty
replying, ``For what purpose?''
</P>
<P>
   Topping off all this nonsense: the always-irrelevant Iowa straw
poll, a non-binding popularity contest in which candidates can
legally wine and dine their supporters and then either embrace the
poll as proof of their momentum or dismiss it as a fund-raising
gimmick, depending on how they finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa straw poll is like a strip club _ whoever spends the
most money gets the most attention from the regulars. But it's also
like a strip club in that you'd have to be a fool to interpret that
affection as genuine.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to believe we've had our fill of stupid political
stories for 1999 _ but we're only two-thirds of the way through the
year, and Matt Drudge, your favorite mainstream-media basher, is
reporting that another famous politician might have been caught on
tape cooing to his mistress.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost enough to make one long for the days of Ford vs.
Carter, when the biggest question was who was more boring.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times, a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
