<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CIDER-BAR-HNS &LR;      08-24 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDER-BAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLICAN'S CORE SALES RELY ON FERMENTED CIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEBASTOPOL, Calif. _ Marilyn Renna tilts a pint glass under the
tap, pulls back the tap handle, fills the glass to the brim with an
amber liquid topped off by a slightly foamy head and slides the
pint across the bar to a parched customer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene repeated endlessly in bars and restaurants
everywhere, but this pint at the Ace in the Hole pub is different:
It's brimming not with beer but with fermented, hard cider made on
the premises. Proprietor Jeffrey House touts Ace in the Hole as the
first cider pub in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   House, an entrepreneurial Englishman who moved to the United
States in 1977, says the new pub, which opened July 29, is designed
``to be a showcase for the Ace brand.'' Ace features a line of
smooth, carbonated apple ciders with 5 to 6 percent alcohol that
House has been making since 1994. It is distributed to liquor
stores and supermarkets in the Western states and served in bars
and restaurants in several cities.
</P>
<P>
   House says he envisions Ace in the Hole, the latest venture of
the privately held California Cider Company Inc., as a tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see Japanese tour buses,'' he says of the pub,
located outside of downtown Sebastopol in the heart of Sonoma
County wine country.
</P>
<P>
   A spacious place boasting a pleasant patio with picnic tables,
picture windows, an interior fireplace and handsome bar made of
wood from a vintage water tower, the pub is quiet on a recent
Monday, though House says it is doing well on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   A former advertising executive with Ogilvy &AMP; Mather in London,
House has ambitious promotional ideas for the pub. ``We plan to
have concierges from the San Francisco hotels come up for an event.
We will be inviting wholesalers and bartenders and working with
this area's tourist promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it may seem sacrilegious to speak of cider as a tourist
draw in prime wine country, Sonoma County was apple territory for
generations before the grape became so popular. It still produces
fine apples for eating, food processing and commercial
cider-making.
</P>
<P>
   Ace uses Granny Smiths, Gravensteins and ``a melange of others''
to make cider, House said. Most of the apples are grown in Sonoma
County.
</P>
<P>
   Through another company House owns, Thames America, he exports
California wines and imports European craft beers and speciality
ales to the United States. But House has taken a fancy to cider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider is refreshing,'' House says. ``It is less bitter than
beer and has less calories. And it has a lower alcoholic content
than wine.''
</P>
<P>
   House's competitors in the bottled fermented cider business
include Gallo Wine, which markets cider under the Hornsby brand,
Boston Beer's Hard Core, Vermont-based Woodchuck and a Canadian
cider called Whyter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House describes fermented cider as a small but growing niche in
the huge beverages market. In the United Kingdom, he says, cider
holds 10 percent of the market for alcoholic drinks, and is served
in most pubs.
</P>
<P>
   But fermented cider is such a small, new category in this
country, Beverage Industry News publisher Dave Page says his
national trade magazine does not track the drink in detail.
</P>
<P>
   At Celebrator Beer News, a bimonthly national magazine that
mainly covers the microbrew and craft beer industry, publisher Tom
Dalldorf estimates there are maybe two dozen fermented cider
operations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of little cideries popping up everywhere,
wherever wonderful apples are grown: upstate New York, New England.
If it ever gets to be half the size here that it is in England,
it'll be huge. There, if you go into a bar and order a cider, no
one thinks you're weird,'' Dalldorf says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
