<P>
   EGGPLANT (Undated) _ In the eastern Mediterranean, the eggplant
is a beloved staple. It replaces meat in stews; it is sliced thin,
grilled and drizzled with fruity olive oil; it is charred, peeled
and blended into a silky, garlicky puree; it is layered with
tomatoes, onions and oil and baked until it is creamy and
caramelized. Eggplants are even cooked in sugar syrup and eaten as
a sweet. Such potential has not quite been realized in American
kitchens. And yet we now have more varieties than ever. Chefs use
all of them regularly _ especially this month and next when
eggplant are at the height of their season. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
