<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIFFS-NOTES-SIDEBAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELISSAS NOTES ABOUT CLIFFS NOTES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Editor's note: If you don't have time to read the in-depth story
about Cliffs Notes, a shortened, a la Cliffs Note, version is
provided. 
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, students everywhere have depended on Cliffs Notes _
the popular yellow- and black-striped ``condensed classics'' _ to
get through English class. Started in 1958 by Cliff Hillegass, the
Cliffs Notes publishing house is in Lincoln, Neb. But changes are
brewing. In December, Cliffs Notes was bought by IDG Books
Worldwide, maker of the ``For Dummies'' books, which plans to
expand the Cliffs Notes line into such areas as personal finance
while continuing production of the literary guides. The guides _
280 titles, from classics to contemporary works _ draw mixed
feelings from teachers. Some say students use Cliffs Notes to
cheat. Others fear they prevent students from thinking
independently. Still others say Cliffs Notes are OK as long as
they're used properly. Here's a surprise: Cliffs Notes are written
by English teachers, who view them as a way to earn extra money
while doing what they love _ dissecting good literature.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 80s and retired, Hillegass has never condensed a
classic in his life. But he did invent the official Cliffs Notes
mantra: The Notes are no substitute for the book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-CLIFFS-NOTES-2TAKES-H     08-24 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIFFS-NOTES-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS AFRAID OF TAKING THE LITERARY PLUNGE FIND A SAFETY NET IN
CLIFFS NOTES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Cliffs Notes is cq) 
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Down the street from the Nebraska State
Penitentiary, across from Midwest Turf and Irrigation, stands a
corrugated-tin building, the kind found in industrial parks across
America. Drab and tan. Utterly utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   That is, except for the vivid black and yellow stripes on the
awning out front, the bumble-bee motif that has evoked Pavlovian
responses of relief in generations of students baffled by
``Beowulf,'' stumped by Steinbeck, flummoxed by Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't guess it, but this building is ground zero for a
phenomenon that has thrown countless teachers into fits of apoplexy
and sent innumerable students running, hearts racing, to the
nearest bookstore, to racks near the back, to the oeuvre of a man
whom they've never met but who promises to deliver them from that
quagmire known as English class. A man said not only to know but
also to willingly divulge the meaning of the white whale, the
secret of the red letter, the reason why the caged bird sings.
</P>
<P>
   A man named Cliff, whose stock shoots up when school bells start
ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this the author room,'' says Greg Tubach, acquisitions
editor for Cliffs Notes, who's leading a tour of the birthplace of
that consummate oxymoron, the ``condensed classic.'' The author
room doubles as the smoking room; a faint whiff of tobacco hangs in
the air. All along the walls are stenciled authors' names:
Shakespeare, Wolfe, Chaucer, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to call the kitchen the novel room,'' says Tubach.
</P>
<P>
   Here the stencils list book titles: ``The Grapes of Wrath,''
``As I Lay Dying,'' ``Wuthering Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Cliffs Notes Country, all right. The kitchen is yellow.
The chairs in the smoking room are yellow. The hard hats in the
warehouse are yellow. Oversized yellow wristwatches hang on the
walls. So do posters urging you to ``Get the Cliffs Notes Edge!''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what legions of students do every year, especially
around finals. Competitors exist, sure, but it's Cliffs Notes that
has slipped into the American lingo, Cliffs Notes that has become
as generic as Kleenex or Coke, Cliffs Notes that works as a handy
shorthand for any act undertaken in haste or half-measures (``I was
pressed for time, so I did it the Cliffs Notes way'').
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the 21st century dawns, Cliff stands poised to move
beyond the windy domains of William Shakespeare, John Milton and
James Joyce into the post-college realm of mortgage-hunting and
resume-writing. Cliffs Notes Inc., founded 41 years ago by a
bookstore rep named Cliff (that's him) Hillegass, was purchased in
December for $14 million by California-based IDG Books Worldwide,
maker of those ubiquitous ``For Dummies'' self-help books.
</P>
<P>
   Under IDG, Cliffs Notes will continue to produce the popular
``literary study guides,'' test-prep manuals and reference books,
but that's not all. Soon to come: yellow-and-black primers on
everything from getting out of debt to playing the stock market.
And that's just a start. IDG honchos say Cliffs Notes will venture
deeper into the ``university of life,'' offering quickie treatments
on everything from self-help to pet care to spirituality. (``Yes,
you too can learn Buddhism in your spare time!'')
</P>
<P>
   After that, IDG plans to take Cliffs Notes to foreign lands,
anywhere students puzzle over the ghost in ``Hamlet'' or the role
of the journey in ``Song of Solomon.'' We're talking total Cliffs
Notes world domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, absolutely,'' says bigwig Roland Elgey, confirming IDG's
plans to turn the homey little Lincoln outfit into an international
publishing juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   So as we stand on this precipice _ this cliff, if you will _ the
time seems ripe to visit this slice of Americana. To parse its
themes, explore its roots, before it's sucked forever into the
corporate maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   First, the party line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, Cliffs Notes are a supplement for when a kid is
having a hard time understanding the novel,'' Tubach says.
``They're used in tandem with the novel. A student will read a
chapter in the novel, go to that chapter in the Note, and so on,
back and forth. It's almost a symbiotic relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Tubach and his co-workers at the Lincoln office to admit
to Cliffs Notes' near-sacred status as a convenient cheat sheet _
as a way to slink through sophomore English without ever cracking a
spine _ is close to impossible. Wink all you want. You encounter a
great Cliffs Notes Wall of Denial.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they sort of admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be students who use (Notes) as cheat sheets, but
they're most likely D students,'' says Tubach. ``It might help them
pass the course, but it won't get them a good grade. Students who
use them the right way tend to be the A and B students.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the official Cliffs Notes mantra: The Notes are no
substitute for the book. That's how founder Hillegass (a retired
octogenarian who, incidentally, has never condensed a classic in
his life) intended it. A stern disclaimer at the start of every
Cliffs Notes states as much.
</P>
<P>
   As for all those fuming English teachers who resent Cliffs
Notes, viewing them as roadblocks to true learning, as leeches that
suck the lifeblood from literature _ well, that's a myth, Tubach
says. Every year, Cliffs Notes staffs a booth at the National
Convention for Teachers of English, and the reception is invariably
warm. ``Ironically, teachers are often more willing, more
comfortable teaching a novel if they know there's a Note (on it)
out there,'' Tubach says. ``They, too, view it as a helping hand, a
supplement.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers began to chill out in the '80s, he claims, when Cliffs
Notes changed its emphasis from ``summary'' (what happens) to
``commentary'' (what it means). Cliffs Notes differ some in
structure, but all have common features: a life of the author,
historical context, character analysis, synopsis, commentary and
sample essay questions, sometimes maps, genealogies and glossaries.
All address such English-teacher topics as theme, symbolism and
character.
</P>
<P>
   Tubach, 34, holds an almost-doctorate in English from Texas A&AMP;M
University (all he lacks is his dissertation). He has written two
Notes: ``Mutiny on the Bounty'' and ``The Hunchback of Notre
Dame,'' which joined the Cliffs Notes canon of 280 titles ranging
from the hoary (``The Iliad'') to the contemporary (``A Raisin in
the Sun'').
</P>
<P>
   Before IDG bought the company, he worked with a stable of about
15 writers scattered across the country, helping them shorten
literature into ``literary guides.'' That function has moved to
IDG's editing house in Indianapolis. These days, Tubach focuses on
selecting which books will get ``noted'' _ a process that involves
poring over catalogs and asking teachers what they plan to teach,
since only those tomes get noted _ and finding new people to churn
out Notes.
</P>
<P>
   These people turn out to be _ apostasy! _ English teachers. They
view writing Cliffs Notes not as an act of betrayal but as a way to
earn extra money doing what they love: pulling apart the dense,
delicious threads of good literature. People such as Durthy A.
Washington, a part-time English teacher at the University of
Colorado at Colorado Springs who did the Cliffs Notes job on ``Song
of Solomon,'' Toni Morrison's mythic tale about cultural identity.
The booklets serve as ``road maps'' for befuddled readers,
Washington says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soul and texture is in the novel, of course, never in the
Cliffs Notes,'' says Washington, who shrank Morrison's 337-page
opus to a breezy 112 pages. ``The trouble comes when they're used
the wrong way. But there will always be students who look for
shortcuts. I can't control that.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wasowski, a high school English teacher in Mansfield,
Ohio, wrote the Cliffs Notes for David Guterson's ``Snow Falling on
Cedars,'' which he teaches in an honors English class. Sure, Cliffs
Notes can be abused. But there's worth in them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students use them to get additional ideas or to find
thought-provoking questions,'' Wasowski says. ``Any type of
resource that teaches students more about the author, more about
what's in there, is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he occasionally receives essays bearing the obvious marks
of Cliffs Notes plagiarism, but they're few and easy to spot.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was paid $3,500 for her shrinking act. (Most writers
get $2,500-$4,000 to abridge a work, depending on its complexity
and length, says Tubach.) What she didn't get was input from
Morrison, despite her efforts. Living authors don't take kindly to
being shrunk, it seems. (Note Amy Tan's famous reply upon learning
that ``The Joy Luck Club'' had been Cliff Noted: ``But I'm not dead
yet!'') Washington attended a college-campus lecture at which
Morrison spoke and afterward tried to approach her to schmooze
about her efforts with ``Solomon.'' The literary lioness gave her a
frosty brushoff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disappointed,'' Washington says, still sounding
crestfallen. ``I can understand it, though. If I had put my
lifeblood into a novel and then had someone come along and try to
dissect it, I guess I would be a little hesitant.''
</P>
<P>
   We pause here for the Cliffs Notes history.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry: It's the condensed version.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when Cliff Hillegass, native son of Rising City,
Neb., became head of the wholesale division of the Nebraska Book
Co. He traveled across the country, getting to know
college-bookstore owners everywhere. One day he was chatting with
his buddy and business associate, bookstore owner Jack Cole, who
had introduced a line of condensed classics in Canada called Cole's
Notes. Why don't you try to make it fly in the United States? Cole
asked Hillegass.
</P>
<P>
   Hillegass tapped into his network of bookstore owners and took a
temperature reading: Would something like Cliffs Notes sell in the
United States? Could be, they said. So, in 1958, he got busy. On a
handshake deal with a Lincoln printing company, he put out 2,000
copies of Notes on each of the 16 major plays of Shakespeare, with
1,000 extra copies of the Notes on ``Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, critics have decried Cliffs Notes as literary
butchery. They note, for example, that Herman Melville's ``Moby
Dick'' is 595 pages; the Cliffs Notes version totals 96. Cliffs
Notes dispatch Chapter 1 in two paragraphs; it takes Melville that
long to introduce his main character, Ishmael.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Pennsylvania's Villanova University went so
far as to ban Cliffs Notes from its bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that in their birthplace, at least, Cliffs Notes
would get a little respect. Think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't carry them, and if we did, I wouldn't tell a
soul,'' says Paul, a reference librarian at the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln who doesn't want to give his last name. This is a
scholarly place, he says; there's no room for Notes. He punches in
the computer coordinates for the Bennett Martin Public Library and
finds that, yes indeed, you can find Cliffs Notes there, 254
titles, everything from Tan's ``The Joy Luck Club'' to the New
Testament. (``Ooh, don't tell me how it ends!'' Paul jokes.)
</P>
<P>
   One sector where Cliffs Notes get plenty of respect is among
students in this Midwestern college town, where Cornhusker football
reigns, the airport boasts four gates and everyone has a sturdy,
corn-fed, vaguely Nordic look. At the college bookstore, employee
Joyce Jensen has seen plenty of panic in the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Students) come running in here all desperate,'' Jensen says.
``They get all disappointed when they find we've sold out of a
certain (Cliffs Notes). And they think there's a Cliffs Notes for
every single book ever published. There's not.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tubach assures such students that almost any title can be
downloaded for $6 off the Internet at www.cliffs.com. Regular Notes
cost between $3 and $5.)
</P>
<P>
   The use of the primers seems to have increased in recent times,
says Jensen. ``Sad to say, kids aren't reading as much,'' she says.
``I think maybe they have too many activities, too many things
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, things are quiet in the Lincoln office.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who have worked here 15, 20 years are being ``transitioned
out,'' as Bob Covolik puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Covolik has been around since the beginning. A friend of
Hillegass' sons, he started out in the basement 36 years ago,
stuffing Cliffs Notes into boxes, driving them to the post office.
He has fond memories of working with the old man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd get in there himself and pitch in,'' says Covolik.
(Hillegass was a big art collector; the hallways of the Lincoln
office are lined with furniture-showroom-quality art.) It was all
about customer service, says Covolik, 55, who worked his way up
from part-time errand boy to president. Over the years, the company
expanded from college bookstores to regular bookstores to bookstore
mega-chains to grocery stores. He's always loved his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up to me and smile and say, `I couldn't have
gotten through school without you,''' Covolik says. Everyone who
works for Cliffs Notes has a story like that.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed over time.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with spelling. Cliffs Notes originally had the correct
possessive apostrophe in its name (Cliff's), but people never used
it, so 10 years ago the company took it out.
</P>
<P>
   Sales took a dramatic dive in the '60s, says Covolik, when
``those flower people, do-your-own-thing types,'' tossed
establishment constraints such as plot and theme out the window.
Sales took a strong upswing in the '90s, when the literary canon
exploded and teachers broadened their scope beyond the DWM (or Dead
White Male) perimeters.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never change. The top-selling Cliffs Notes have
always been ``The Scarlet Letter,'' except for 1984, when teachers
everywhere taught (you guessed it) George Orwell's 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But now things are really changing. The Cliffs Notes operation
is moving to Indianapolis and California, except for a small
educational division in Lincoln. Covolik will stay on as general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know for how long,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the warehouse, Charlie Lehl has overseen Cliffs Notes
shipping for 20 years. A big, burly Grizzly Adams of a man with a
pack of smokes in his pocket, he thought he'd work here forever.
Now it's back into the job pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they say,'' he says, grinning sheepishly. ``The
big guys eat the little guys.''
</P>
<P>
   A classic theme.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
