<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BOOKS-CHILDREN-REVIEW     08-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CHILDREN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS BRIGHTEN END OF SUMMER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: An odiaeresis, or two dots, needed over o in Dorrie; accent
marks needed over first two e's in Benedicte) 
 
By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today isn't a plain school-clothes day, Lottie decides. It's a
Princess Dress day. Mom doesn't think so, and the two get into a
familiar row involving accusations such as, ``You can't wear that''
and ``We're going to be late.'' So begins Lottie's ``Princess
Dress'' (Dial, $15.99) by Doris Dorrie with illustrations by Julia
Kaergel. The picture book was published originally in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A determined Lottie puts on her gold princess dress, brushes her
teeth and polishes her crown. She's ready.
</P>
<P>
   But something is wrong. Mom looks, well, boring. Lottie
convinces Mom that if today is a Princess Dress day, it is also a
Queen Mom day. ``Today is special,'' Lottie exclaims, ``and you
will look like a beautiful queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom, with reluctance, puts on her red and gold party dress and a
crown.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody they pass on the way to school and to work smiles and
says, ``Today must be a very special day,'' which, when a daughter
and her mom are wearing royal dresses and crowns, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Dorrie's delightful grin-inducing book reminds us that
unconventional daughters and flexible moms can make every day
special. Matching crowns help.
</P>
<P>
   Lottie's story is only one of a wheelbarrow full of delightful
new children's books that can help ease the angst of bidding
another speedy summer goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving wacky but cool fathers equal time is Benedicte
Guiettier's ``The Father Who Had 10 Children`` (Dial, $15.99),
recommended for 3- to 4-year-olds and for all fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Primitive, boldly colored drawings add solidity to the father
who every morning before work makes 10 breakfasts and every evening
after work prepares 10 fried eggs, 10 bowls of spaghetti, 20
meatballs, 50 broccoli spears and 100 raspberries with whipped
cream.
</P>
<P>
   He is one pooped papa. One day he leaves his 10 children with
their grandmother and sets sail for a vacation of maybe 10 days,
maybe 10 months. The second morning he gets out 10 cups and
realizes something is missing.
</P>
<P>
   What does he do? You're right. Gotta love this dad. There's a
bit of the father in all parents, even those who don't have 10
children but who have felt a similar pull between the desire for
serenity and the need to be in the midst of their children.
</P>
<P>
   The book brims over with sweet feelings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Red-Eyed Tree Frog'' (Scholastic, $16.95), with story by Joy
Cowley and photography by Nic Bishop, will turn tiny children into
instant crusaders to save rain-forest homes of these 2-inch-long
Central American frogs.
</P>
<P>
   The astounding photos show a bigger-than-life frog looking for a
meal, escaping danger, taking little naps. With big red eyes that
help him see in the dark, a bright green body and tiny suckered
toes, this buddy stars in his own simple, clear and informative
story. He's cuter than anything Disney could have dreamed up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Rohmann's ``The Cinder-Eyed Cats'' (Crown, $17) is
reminiscent of the wonderful ``Dream Child'' by David McPhail. With
few words and magical art, Rohmann takes a small lad in a flying
boat to a faraway land where ``cats like velvet shadows move.'' The
rest of the world sleeps. But not the boy and his world of dancing
fish and gentle tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut your eyes, go to sleep, you have nothing to fear,''
Rohmann tells his young readers. His soft colors and sweetly
creative paintings continue the comfort, wrapping the youngster in
a cozy security blanket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``William Shakespeare &AMP; the Globe'' (HarperCollins, $15.95)
Aliki leads children on a tour of Shakespeare's life and times. No
Gwyneth Paltrow or Joseph Fiennes, but everybody keeps their
clothes on, and Aliki sticks closer to fact that did ``Shakespeare
in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   She tells the story as a play, mixing narrative with pictures
that could pass for peopled sets. The story is a circle, beginning
with the Bard and the theater for which he wrote his plays. Then it
eases into the present-day reconstruction of the theater. The
author lives near the Globe theater in London.
</P>
<P>
   The book is so lively and enticing that children won't mind the
history and literature lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But they'll still mind the fact that summer is over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
