<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MILITARY-BUSINESS-2TA     08-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-BUSINESS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITERS HAVE A MESSAGE FOR OFFICERS LEAVING THE MILITARY:
CORPORATE AMERICA WANTS YOU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ ``Let's try it again,'' said Jon Petrucelli,
leaning toward the U.S. Air Force officer sitting across from him
on the sofa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is the answer to a question _ the old ``tell me about
yourself'' that comes up 40 to 50 percent of the time in job
interviews, and it's a real stumper if you're not prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Ruben Silva looked a bit ill at ease and stared back at
his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' he said, and took a deep breath, launching into a
halting five-minute monologue, starting with his birthplace in
Brownsville, Texas, and ending with his current job as special
assistant to the jet maintenance academy commandant at Lackland Air
Force Base in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' said Petrucelli, who was leading this mock job
interview in a suite at the Sheraton Hotel. ``You need to lock it
up, trim it up and make it smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli is a recruiter who, like the Marines, is looking for
a few good men and women. But unlike the Marines, his recruits are
already in uniform. He works for Bradley-Morris, a company that
serves as a middleman linking employers with former military
officers and enlisted personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli's job is to find junior military officers and line
them up with employers who need operations, logistics and
engineering experts. Other recruiters in his company focus on
finding jobs for enlisted personnel, especially electricians,
mechanics, machinists and electronic technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Companies always have hired former military officers and
enlisted men and women. But only in recent years have companies
popped up that recruit exclusively from the military.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling their growth is a tight labor market, a strong desire
among an underpaid officer corps to find a better life for
themselves and their families, and the growing recognition among
corporate leaders that the military produces some excellent
managers.
</P>
<P>
   The former soldiers, sailors and airmen bring to the table
leadership experience and rigorous training that most recently
minted college graduates don't have, said Amy Zimmerman, operations
manager of Orion International in Austin, Texas, another company
specializing in recruiting from the military.
</P>
<P>
   Like many who work for these specialized recruiting companies,
Zimmerman is a former military officer, a graduate of the U.S.
Military Academy in West Point, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   One employer that is finding its best managers from among the
ranks of the military is Banta Corp. It recently hired two former
soldiers and is considering a third.
</P>
<P>
   The military is a great source of committed, disciplined workers
who can focus well on goals, said Rob Michel, corporate director of
human resources for the Wisconsin book, magazine and catalog
printer. Banta is launching a Houston office to assemble computer
hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   Michel, however, is a little reluctant to talk about his
new-found source for employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep it a secret,'' he said. ``It's like
fishing. You don't tell anyone your hot spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite how good he has found his new labor source to be, Michel
has encountered some trepidation at Banta.
</P>
<P>
   Michel said there was some resistance from supervisors because
they expect the former military officers to have a ``management by
yelling'' philosophy. They're also worried the former officers
won't be able to adapt quickly, that they'll be stuck in a rut. But
the company's recent military hires have put those stereotypes
largely to rest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The perception that military officers get things done by
ordering others around is a hurdle to hiring, said Shaun Bradley,
president of Atlanta-based Bradley-Morris and a graduate of the
U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   However, that's an outdated image. Today's military focuses on
coaching, mentoring and training _ all management buzzwords of the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use `please and thank you,''' Bradley said. ``Very few
situations require an on-the-spot order except maybe getting shot
at.''
</P>
<P>
   General Electric Co., credited with being the first major
company to foresee the benefits of hiring former military
personnel, began recruiting three years ago _ mostly as an
experiment _ at the behest of Jack Welch, GE's chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment went well, and today GE has more than 1,000
former junior military officers on its payroll, said Jennifer
Whiting, spokeswoman for GE in Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   When news leaked out that Welch, well-respected by other CEOs,
was hiring junior military officers, other companies followed suit,
making the field more competitive. To compete with other employers,
GE tries to get its offer on the table first, Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   That approach fits with Petrucelli's experience. At a recent job
fair in Chicago, GE made a job offer to one candidate in less than
four days. He doesn't usually see that kind of speed.
</P>
<P>
   It's Petrucelli's job to make sure the recruits look and sound
as good as they can when they interview for jobs. So, he starts
working with them a year or two before they plan to leave the
military, helping them write a resume and learn to answer interview
questions.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, he spent an afternoon in a hotel suite
individually coaching a group of officers who have done well in
their military careers but want something more from the private
sector. Sixty-five percent of the clients had graduated from
military academies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you separating from the military?'' Petrucelli asked
Air Force Capt. Phil White, a young officer wearing a uniform so
starched it looked like it could stand up by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My core values and the military's core values don't match,''
White shot back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli frowned and shook his head during the mock interview:
``Never give a negative answer.'' Sugarcoat it a bit, he suggested:
``I completed my commitment, re-evaluated my life after five years
and now am seeking more of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Petrucelli speculated that White _ a graduate of the U.S.
Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo. _ will be much in
demand when he lands on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a super stud. I'll probably put him in front of McKinsey
and Andersen,'' said Petrucelli, referring to the blue chip
management consulting firms McKinsey &AMP; Co. and Arthur Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   All this coaching is designed to make the officers look
irresistible to employers during The Conference. That's the roving
job fair Bradley-Morris sponsors every few weeks that tries to
match soon-to-be former military officers with employers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rigorous two-day experience. On the first day, the
candidates attend briefings to tell them everything they'll need to
know about the employers to get through a half-hour interview. Then
they go through a series of mock interviews, to really polish their
``tell me about yourself'' answers.
</P>
<P>
   The second day is crammed with interviews. Some candidates, who
are advised to dress in navy pinstripe suits with red power ties,
interview with as many as 10 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Silva is a little nervous about going into an interview with
just a briefing to back him up.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, Petrucelli assures him. The first interview is all
about you. ``Dell won't ask,'' he says, ``what do you think about
our computers?''
</P>
<P>
   For the recruits, getting in front of a company such as Round
Rock, Texas-based Dell Computer Corp. is what they hope will be
their ticket out of what is becoming an increasingly difficult
lifestyle that doesn't allow much room for a family.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Keith Hughes said he is scheduled to spend three of the
next five years aboard a Navy ship, but the naval flight officer
doesn't want to be gone for six months at a time because his wife
is pregnant with their first child.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said his last departure affected him deeply when he saw
another officer say goodbye to his 2-week-old infant before
boarding for a six-month journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible to see,'' said Hughes, who is thinking of
resigning next year. ``It's a life for some but not for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Others want to move ahead faster than the military will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stafford, a 1978 graduate of the Citadel in Charleston,
S.C., decided to leave the Army in 1986 after serving seven years,
because of the frustration of not getting ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Your promotions aren't totally tied to merit, he said. If your
performance is good, you'll be promoted along with your peer group,
but not before.
</P>
<P>
   So, Stafford spent a year researching possible employers and
narrowed them down to a list of 10 for their advancement potential,
training assistance and challenge. He ended up taking a sales
representative job with &UR;  &LR; Pfizer, one of his target companies. He is
now regional accounts manager in Houston for the pharmaceuticals
company.
</P>
<P>
   Low pay is another issue that is pushing some officers out the
door. Similar jobs in the private sector pay two to three times as
much as they do in the military, estimated Lt. Col. Cornell T.
McGhee, commander of U.S. Army recruiting in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in pay has widened in the past six years because
the economy is doing so well, he said. To fight the brain drain and
loss of experience, military employees will receive a 4.8 percent
raise in January. Six months later, another raise will boost wages
an average of 5.5 percent, depending on years of service and grade.
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli understands why people want to leave the military. He
graduated from West Point in 1994 and left active duty two years
later, he said, because he had done what he set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been a platoon leader,'' he said. ``I knew I didn't want
to stay in for 10 years and be a commander.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers are a hot commodity and recruiters such as Petrucelli,
who are paid strictly on commission, try to lure the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Navy nukes'' _ they're the top guys to place, he said,
referring to the people who work on Navy submarines. ``We get them
very good offers.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the best job candidates, Petrucelli hosts a ``seminar''
every few weeks in a hotel conference room near a military base.
It's a low-key affair _ no fancy hors d'oeuvres, just pitchers of
ice water and small bowls of hard candy. It's part sales talk and
part pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   The offers are coming, Petrucelli tells the eight men sitting
around the conference table, recalling the recent conference in
Chicago that produced the job offer from GE.
</P>
<P>
   They all nod appreciatively.
</P>
<P>
   Dell and Applied Materials will be at the next conference in
Austin, Petrucelli tells them. The officers all nod their heads
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much money can I expect to make?'' asks one of the
officers who has come to listen to Petrucelli at the suggestion of
a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   It depends, of course, on location and interviewing skills,
Petrucelli said, but candidates can expect to start at between
$50,000 and $80,000. Again, the officers nod.
</P>
<P>
   A few, however, are still worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we really that desirable?'' one asks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, Petrucelli said soothingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all into goals, and corporate America loves goal-driven
people,'' he said, warming up to his closing. ``Four hundred and
fifty companies come to us for leaders. The best thing you can do
is work with me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Information: Bradley-Morris has a Web site at
www.bradley-morris.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
