<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMMINGBIRD BUSH IS A COMMON NAME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I have a hummingbird bush that was given to me, but
a friend has a different bush that she calls a hummingbird bush. I
only have a patio, so will mine grow in a large pot?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not unusual for a common name to be shared by more than
one plant. The clipping from your hummingbird was considerably
damaged in the mail, brown and broken, but appears to be from a
``Hamelia patens,'' a sun-loving shrubby perennial that produces
red-orange tubular blooms. The foliage has a red coloring.
</P>
<P>
   It should be fine in a large pot filled with a well-draining
soil. You will likely need to transplant to a larger pot in the
future. Protect the plant during freezing weather. The top growth
will freeze, but a thick layer of mulch will help ensure that new
growth emerges from the roots in spring.
</P>
<P>
   This year, thanks to such a mild winter, hamelias are giant
10-foot billows. Given freezing weather, they may obtain a height
in the 6-foot range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anisacanthus wrightii,'' a small shrub native to Texas, is
another plant commonly called hummingbird bush. It produces 2-inch
orange blooms summer and fall, has glossy 2-inch leaves and matures
to a height of about 3 feet. It is a good container plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When is the best time to prune 10-year-old live oak trees
around the bottom of the branches? When is the best time to prune
crape myrtles and wisteria?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not sure I know what you mean by ``around the bottom of
the branches.'' Perhaps you are referring to the idea that leaving
small limbs close to the ground on young live oaks (as with pecans)
encourages the trunks to thicken at a faster rate. The general rule
of thumb is to leave such limbs until the tree has gained some
height, then the lowest branches are removed.
</P>
<P>
   The optimum time to prune a live oak, many experts say, is late
winter to early spring, although I see pruning done at other times
of the year. I always turn to a professional arborist for major
pruning as well as health checks.
</P>
<P>
   Prune crape myrtles while dormant. If I don't get around to
pruning in January, I do so the first half of February. Prune
wisteria after it has bloomed in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been fighting Virginia buttonweed in my lawn. I have
not had much success with broadleaf weedkillers. Consequently, I
have tried other methods of control: pulling the weeds and growing
shade trees.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, one corner of the lawn was severely infested, and
I laboriously pulled every one by the roots. Last year I found no
buttonweeds in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Last year I attempted to pull every weed that was mature enough
to blossom. This year I have pulled seedlings just beginning to
grow. In April, I collected about 100 with at least part of the
root system. Every few days following, I pulled 10 to 50 weeds. In
July, I found that I had missed some that had branched under the
leaves of the grass. I hope that I will have few weeds next year.
</P>
<P>
   I observe that buttonweeds do not grow in shady areas, so for
long-term control I have planted two elms that should give open
shade in areas that now get full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a pre-emergent that can be used in a St. Augustine
lawn?
</P>
<P>
   A: I, too, pull buttonweed. I think it's the most effective
control for this warm-season perennial that begins to show growth
in early spring. Virginia buttonweed spreads by seeds, rhizomes and
rooting stems. You do have to search for the weed among the blades
of the grass to catch it before it flowers, then seeds. The
leathery, dark-green leaves can be difficult to detect in St.
Augustine. If you see the star-shaped white flowers, grab and pull
before these become rows of green seedpods. If you mow the weeds,
they'll simply grow back. Since it is a perennial that can produce
an extensive system of rhizomes, you have to get this underground
network for your hard work to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   I've found that this weed particularly likes moist soil.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your lawn thick and healthy to discourage this pest. This
means proper mowing, fertilization and aeration. I do not know of a
pre-emergent that will do you any good. A post-emergent that
contains dicamba, such as Image, may help. But get ready to apply
more than once in spring and summer. And, as you know, it's most
important to follow instructions as St. Augustine and herbicides
don't always mix.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My bay leaf tree has bugs. Can you identify them? What can I
do for my fig? This year it shed its leaves, and the figs cracked
open before they could ripen.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your bay tree has scale. You can treat with a horticultural
oil. Ask your nurseryman about such products. You can also attempt
control by dabbing on rubbing alcohol, but this can be tedious. If
you're not squeamish, you can actually slide your thumbnail across
the pests. If they flake off easily, they're already dead.
</P>
<P>
   Scales attach themselves to leaves and stems, drinking sap from
the plant. Some ladybugs and parasitic wasps are natural predators.
</P>
<P>
   Figs need a great deal of water during the summer and a thick
layer of mulch. They also need abundant sun, a well-draining,
organically enriched soil, and little or no pruning.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My aunt gave me a plant 45 years ago. Can you identify it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The plant you have appears to be a rockrose, or ``Pavonia
lasiopetal,'' a tough native that may range in height from 2 to 5
feet. It produces its 2-inch pink blooms late spring to frost.
Rockrose is a member of the mallow family, a hibiscus relative, as
you can see from the flowers. The blooms open in the morning and
close in the afternoon. Plants that receive afternoon shade hold
their blossoms open longer. Rockrose is almost evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   This pretty little native likes sun or partial sun and a
well-draining soil. Prune for legginess.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is a weed that has begun to overrun my garden. It grows
on top of pine needle mulch, on bare ground and in unused flower
pots. Do you know of a way to get rid of it beyond pulling it out
by the roots? I have tried broadleaf weedkillers to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   A: The weed you sent appears to be one that goes by the
unfortunate common name annual jewgrass, or ``Microstegium
vimineum.'' This is a summer annual that is mostly prostrate and
runs along the top of the ground seeking shade. I pull it from
beneath azaleas and large perennials in an attempt to nab it before
it seeds. Because it's so shallow-rooted, it's not difficult to
pull, and because it grows near desired plants I do not use a
herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   This pest is a grassy weed rather than a broadleaf type.
</P>
<P>
   You might check the herbicide labels at a garden center to see
if there is one that targets this grassy weed. Be aware that many
herbicides cannot be used on St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The volume of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
