<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODWILL TRAVEL GESTURES STILL EXIST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over u in Cancun and a udiaeresis, or two
dots, needed over u in Kitzbuhel) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The morning mail was taking on an all-too-familiar tone.
</P>
<P>
   One reader, who had eagerly anticipated a vacation with his wife
and quadriplegic son, related his dismay at the tour packager's
failure to fulfill a promise of providing wheelchair-accessible
facilities at Florida lodgings.
</P>
<P>
   A second letter focused on itinerary ``diversions and delays''
during a youth group's trip to Cancun. Another derided ``price
gouging'' for millennium promotions. Still others reported
frustrations over flight delays, excessive rental-car charges and
hotel discomforts.
</P>
<P>
   I read each missive with empathy and wished anew that I could
push some magic button to right all wrongs. Have travel-service
providers forgotten, I wondered, that we invest our time and money
in vacations to get away from problems and pressures, not to
compound them? What happened to basic human compassion and
understanding?
</P>
<P>
   Then I opened Houstonian Jo Anne Courtney's letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HANDLING ADVERSITY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She had called a couple of days earlier to tell me about her
experience this summer at the Kona Village Resort on the Big Island
of Hawaii. As she talked, I asked if she would put her thoughts in
writing so I could share them with fellow travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Selfishly, I knew she would cheer me up, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``To celebrate our 47th wedding anniversary,'' her handwritten
letter began, ``my husband and I took our teen-age grandchildren
with us on a very special vacation _ to a resort with no air
conditioning, no telephones, no television and no clocks.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to describe some of the resort's appeals: spacious
cottages built on stilts, with thatched roofs; winds sweeping
through the property; meals included in the basic room rate;
children's activities; a full recreational program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just one thing wrong with this plan,'' she wrote.
``I didn't get to do it. Two hours after arrival, my clogged
arteries decided to quit working. The classic pains in my left
shoulder radiating to my arm, jaw and chest let me know that I
needed the manager, fast!''
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance was called to take her to the nearest hospital, 45
minutes away. Jack Terry, the resort's resident manager, ``held my
hand and comforted me until it came,'' she wrote, ``and he said
that he would bring me home when I was released.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE THOUGHTFULNESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After tests, Courtney was flown by air ambulance to a hospital
in Honolulu for further treatment. As she was about to be released,
a business trip took Terry to the state capital, and, the letter
continued, ``This kind man met me at my hospital room, drove me to
the airport, got a wheelchair for me and arranged for a taxi to
meet me at the Kona airport. He had even bought my airline ticket
and had it waiting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving back at the resort, the dining room was closed,
but a feast had been arranged for Courtney and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thoughtfulness didn't stop there,'' she wrote. ``The
resort took $200 a night off the room/meal rate for the nights when
I wasn't there. They have since written to find out how I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after I received that letter, a colleague told me of her
experience during a recent Holland America cruise in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call in the middle of the night brought word that
her mother was seriously ill back home. She was advised to return
as soon as possible. Still at sea, the ship's staff set to work,
and by the time the vessel docked in Seward shortly after dawn,
flights home had been arranged _ no routine matter in such a small
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really appreciative,'' the colleague said.
</P>
<P>
   Even small gestures of goodwill can nourish us for years. I
remember a vacation in Kitzbuhel, Austria, in the dead of winter,
when my wife took ill and a housekeeper secured an extra blanket
and wrapped it around her, then set up a makeshift bed in front of
a warm fireplace. Just this summer in Australia, when I tarried too
long at the new Olympics complex 12 miles from downtown Sydney and
missed the last scheduled public transportation, a tour-bus driver
whose daily rotation had just ended sensed my predicament, said
``Hop aboard,'' and detoured four miles to a taxi stand. When I
offered a monetary thank-you, he refused.
</P>
<P>
   These people didn't know me. They had no idea what I do for a
living. They were just being nice.
</P>
<P>
   I never take it lightly when readers express their frustrations
at travel ills. I can only hope that next time they'll encounter a
Jack Terry in Kona, a concerned housekeeper in Kitzbuhel or a
gracious bus driver in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Good Samaritans do still exist all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
