<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUD     08-24 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHICAGO-HOPE (Los Angeles) _ ``Chicago Hope'' gets a
transfusion and one last chance to succeed. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TOURING-SMALL-TOWNS (Bishop, Calif.) _ Arts in America: Laura
Spitzer, a classical pianist who plays far off the beaten path. By
Martin Forstenzer.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-FOUNDATION (New York) _ Judging by the experience of a new
cultural support foundation, many of the nation's artists are eager
to apply for financial aid even in these prosperous times. By last
week's deadline for the Creative Capital Foundation's first round
of grants, applications from 1,810 visual, performing and media
artists had flooded into the Greenwich Village office of the new
group, formed to fill the gap created when the National Endowment
for the Arts ended most grants to individuals in 1995. By Judith H.
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television. By Bill
Carter and Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
