<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOMER-DERBY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOMER DERBY DETRACTS FROM THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Two good things can come from this season's
Sosa-McGwire sequel.
</P>
<P>
   One is variety: Sammy Sosa wins the home-run title this time,
toppling Goliath, tying or breaking Mark McGwire's record of 70.
</P>
<P>
   The other is monotony. The two sluggers make the public numb.
</P>
<P>
   Like a child gorged on cotton-candy, we lose our taste for the
home-run chase. We start to notice that all those dingers haven't
done much for the Cubs and Cardinals in the wins column. We still
like Sammy and Mac, but we start to look around at the other boys
of summer, and we notice something more interesting, more important
to the long-term well-being of the game.
</P>
<P>
   We notice the Oakland A's, aka The Team That Traded Mark McGwire
The Year Before He Broke Roger Maris' Home Run Record. They are
playoff contenders who look remarkably like baseball's salvation.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it was Sammy and Mac to the rescue. They pulled so
many baseball expatriates back into the stands, back in front of
the televisions, back to the newspaper box scores. But the season
ended with a fizzle, a World Series sweep by the Yankees, a
franchise with a payroll bigger than McGwire's biceps.
</P>
<P>
   The little guy, it was clear, didn't have a chance. Rupert
Murdoch's minions dropped his millions on Kevin Brown at the winter
meetings, and baseball had three staggering record numbers for the
year: 70 for McGwire, 66 for Sosa, $105 million for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are the antidote to Murdoch's excesses. Their entire
team makes $22 million. Fewer people come to their games than show
up early for McGwire's batting practice. They aren't an attraction.
They are just a team, a winning team. They are, whether they
realize it or not, pushing aside Murdoch the way McGwire and Sosa
tracked down Maris. The difference is that Maris had a worthwhile
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   That is the story of this season: The pricey Dodgers stink.
</P>
<P>
   The bargain A's are amid the elite. So are the Cincinnati Reds,
another of baseball's discount squads.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that better, in the long run, than the individual glory of
a home-run record, especially one that may not hold up an entire
year? When they come and go so easily, records mean a whole lot
less. It's like caviar: If everyone could afford it, we'd just
spare the pretense and call the stuff fish eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a fair number of people are starting to agree that a
home-run fixation could hurt the game more than help it.
</P>
<P>
   I've argued this ever since Ken Griffey Jr. took so much flak
for vowing to skip the 1998 Home Run Derby at the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thought he was showing disrespect for the fans. I
thought he was showing respect for his sport.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's All-Star dunking competition started out as great fun,
just like the homer derby. After a while, it became the emblem of
everything wrong with the league. The NBA finally canned it. Too
many players had the style to dunk but not the substance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, everyone proclaimed baseball reborn, because of the
home run. I remembered the tedious playoff races and thought: Five
more years like this, and no one will ever want to watch baseball
again.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and McGwire were special last year. They could even be
special this year. But the A's and Reds' attack on free-spending
franchises is even better. If this happened every season, we would
never grow tired of it. In fact, we might become more entranced by
baseball than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the assumption is that free-agent spending dictates
success. At the beginning of the year, fans see white handkerchiefs
flying over small-market stadiums, and they turn off to the team
from the very beginning. The Giants helped counter that somewhat,
but even they have a generous payroll compared to the A's.
</P>
<P>
   If fans started to believe that every season, any team has a
chance to compete, there's more reason to start following any club
from spring training onward.
</P>
<P>
   And think of the lesson that an A's playoff appearance would
impart this season. A national television audience would hear how
this was the team that didn't have enough money to keep Mark
McGwire, traded the superstar and still found a way to become a
winner again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far better lesson than youngsters will glean from
watching how teams treat Sosa and McGwire these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't understand is why anyone's throwing them
strikes,'' said Matt Stairs, one of McGwire's former Oakland mates.
``Maybe it's just macho, the pitchers don't want to look like
they're backing down against them. But if I were up against them,
I'd throw in the dirt, four straight balls in the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because he wants to win more than he wants to please a
stats-hungry crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker sounded like a rebel when he declared last weekend
that he would intentionally walk Sosa any time the Cubs slugger had
a chance to beat the Giants in this week's series at Wrigley Field.
He's not interested in being popular with the fans. He'll happily
walk McGwire, too.
</P>
<P>
   And the two sluggers have to know that Baker is showing them the
utmost respect with that approach. He fears their bats, and he
insists on treating them as ballplayers, not sideshow attractions
conducting glorified BP in the middle of a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
