<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Aug. 25,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-HORSES _ DUBLIN, Ireland _ City officials and landlords
here are struggling to cope with a growing problem of people buying
horses cheaply at auctions and taking them home as pets or a means
of basic transportation. This is particularly a problem in
high-rise apartment buildings where a horse in an elevator is
becoming a familiar sight. (Roughton, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-POLL _ WASHINGTON _ Dismay at last spring's school
shootings in Colorado and Georgia has not shaken the faith of most
adults in the safety and orderliness of their own community's
public schools, especially if their kids attend them. That and
other findings are in a national Gallup poll released Tuesday by
Phi Kappa Delta International, the fraternity for professional
educators. With Q&AMP;A data for a graphic or textbox. (Mollison, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Air Force is taking flak
from federal investigators in two reports detailing waste and
mismanagment. One says that amid talk of more pay and bonuses to
keep pilots in the military, the Pentagon doesn't know how many
pilots it needs nor what it would take to retain them. Annother
says the Air Force's VIP wing, which flies the president and other
top officials, sometimes takes six years to send a bill _ if any is
sent at all. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENDORSE _ ATLANTA _ GOP presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, who's planning to visit Atlanta on Friday, is putting out
campaign literature that says he has endorsements from most of the
Republicans in the Georgia Legislature. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ ATLANTA _ Marianne Gingrich says her husband
absconded with ``a substantial portion'' of the couple's joint
assets before filing for divorce. Also: Three days prior to the
world learning that he'd had an affair, Newt was to launch a radio
commentary series. Checking to see if that's been held. (Stanford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHAIR _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The Florida Supreme Court has
more than words to consider in deciding the future of the state's
electric chair: The justices have color photos of Allen Lee
``Tiny'' Davis, still strapped in the chair minutes after his
bloody execution last month. (Date, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BAILEY-CONTEMPT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Contempt hearing today
for F. Lee Bailey, who refuses to turn over $2 million of
ex-stripper and infomercial king William Crocker's money, hidden in
the Cayman Islands. Bailey says it rightfully belongs to him for
legal fees, and besides, he's spent most of it any way. (McLachlin,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   STAROFDAVID _ GULFPORT, Miss. _ The Harrison County School Board
has abruptly overturned a controversial decision that had prevented
a Jewish student from wearing a Star of David necklace to school.
Board members, who had planned to hold a public forum on the issue
next Monday, decided just before a meeting Monday to vote on the
matter. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MUSLIM-PRISONERS _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ As the rest of the Muslim
world fasted during daylight last December in observance of the
month of Ramadan, it was business as usual for Muslim inmates at
the St. Lucie County Correctional Center: Eat now or go hungry.
Now, changes are in the works, said Sieg Christman, president of
Florida's Treasure Coast chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union. After organization members met with St. Lucie County
sheriff's officials Friday, the jail has agreed to allow Ramadan
observance for the jail's eight Muslim inmates. It also has agreed
to allow a Jumu'ah prayer service once a month, officials said.
ACLU officials, who asked for weekly services on Friday, said
they're thankful, but that the accommodations aren't enough.
(Collins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-CDC _ ATLANTA _ On Tuesday the CDC will release its
state-by-state report on tobacco use as well as its recommendations
on how to solve the public health problem, including funding
guidelines. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
