<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOLS-POLL25-COX     08-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-POLL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS THINK THEIR OWN CHILD'S SCHOOL IS SAFE
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's school shootings did not shake parents'
faith in the safety of their local schools, according to a national
Gallup poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An overwhelming 92 percent of parents with children in their
local public schools and 84 percent of other adults described the
local learning environment as ``very'' or ``somewhat'' safe and
orderly.
</P>
<P>
   When parents were asked specifically about the public school
attended by their oldest child, only 7 percent said they were
sending their son or daughter to an unsafe school. Instead, 42
percent described it as ``very safe and orderly'' and 50 percent
called it ``somewhat safe and orderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Local pride in the overall quality of schools also remains
strong, according to the poll, the 31st annual public education
survey conducted for Phi Delta Kappa International, an
Indiana-based association of more than 100,000 professional
educators in 15 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Offered a chance to grade schools, 56 percent of the
public-school parents and 47 percent of the other adults gave an A
or B to their local schools. But only only 21 percent of the
parents and 26 percent of others awarded an A or B to schools ``in
the nation as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
occurred April 20. The poll of 1,103 adults, which had a sampling
error of plus or minus two percentage points, was conducted from
May 18 to June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there is nothing in this poll to suggest that there
was a significant change in public attitudes as a result of the
Columbine shootings,'' said the poll's director, Lowell Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of parents came to the schools right afterwards and
said, 'How are you ensuring the safety of our children?''' said Jim
Fogarty, a school official in Suffolk County, N.Y., who is the
incoming president of Phi Delta Kappa International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many visitors were reassured by what they saw of the safety
net features that were in place,'' he said. ``Some programs were
tightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the public wants schools to be even safer, said Jack
Jennings, executive director of the Washington-based Center for
Education Policy.
</P>
<P>
   That desire showed up in the answers to an open-ended question
in which the pollsters asked people to name ``the biggest problems
with which the public schools of your community must deal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the top two concerns were lack of
discipline or need for more control (mentioned by 18 percent this
year and 14 percent last year) and fighting, violence or gangs (11
percent this year, 15 percent last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, people still want more discipline within the
schools,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters asked parents of public-school children and other
adults two multiple-choice questions on school safety.
</P>
<P>
   All were asked the first question: ``Thinking about the public
schools in your community, how would you describe the learning
environment?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers were ``Very safe and orderly,'' parents 30 percent;
others, 22; ``Somewhat safe and orderly, parents 62, others 62;
``Not very safe and orderly,'' parents 5, others 8; ``Not at all
safe and orderly,'' parents 2, others 3; ``Don't know,'' parents,
1; others, 5.
</P>
<P>
   The one-third of the respondents who had children in public
schools then were asked: ``How about the learning environment in
the public school your oldest child attends?''
</P>
<P>
   The percentages were ``very'' (42 percent), ``somewhat'' (50),
``not very'' (5), ``not at all'' (2) and ``don't know'' (1).
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the poll can be viewed on the Web site of Phi
Delta Kappa International (http://www.pdkintl.org).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
