<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERI     08-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OF THESE THREE MYSTERIES ARE GOOD READS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco Bay Area's own Richard North Patterson once
again proves that he is at the top of his game. His latest richly
textured legal thriller, ``Dark Lady'' (Random House, $25.95, 371
pages), begins with the bizarre deaths of two of Steelton's most
prominent men _ ``the drug dealers' lawyer of choice,'' Jack Novak,
and Tommy Fielding, the general manager of the firm building a
baseball stadium for the Steelton Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding had been found naked in his bedroom, next to a black
prostitute. Both apparently died of drug overdoses. But Fielding's
mother insists that her son was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Novak had been found hanging from his closet door, wearing a
garter belt and stockings. It could have been a sex act that went
wrong, but Novak had been castrated, making it a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases will prove to be the ultimate test for Assistant
County Prosecutor Stella Marz.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last six years, she had won every case but one _ a hung
jury following the murder trial of a high school coach who had
gotten one of his students pregnant and who, devastated by Stella's
particularly ruthless cross-examination, had committed suicide. It
was this which had led a courtroom deputy to give Stella a nickname
which now enjoyed wide currency among the criminal defense bar: the
Dark Lady. But only recently had they become aware of her ambition,
long nurtured, to become the first woman elected prosecutor of Erie
County.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve her goal, she must help her boss, Arthur Bright, win
the mayoral race against the hugely popular Mayor Krajek. And to do
this, she must distance Bright from his ties to Novak _ his old
classmate, friend and campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her investigation begins, an anonymous caller
tells a reporter that Stella had been Novak's lover. However, the
affair occurred 13 years before when Stella worked for Novak while
she was going to law school.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Stella plunges ahead with the cases. When one of
Stella's witnesses is killed, Stella is convinced that Fielding was
murdered and she begins an investigation of the money behind the
baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Stella's life will be threatened, her beloved cat killed, and
eventually she will begin to trust no one.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Patterson's character development is first rate. He
deftly defines the complexities of a declining city's politics and
the underhanded maneuvers in getting a stadium built. The plot is
well- paced, and the dialogue rings true.
</P>
<P>
   In his acknowledgements at the end of the book, Patterson says
``Steelton is not Cleveland _ it's what Cleveland might have become
had its people not decided otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard for the reader not to substitute Cleveland for
Steelton throughout the book because Patterson ``borrowed'' so much
of that city's history in creating Steelton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Lady'' is sure to be a bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``High Time to Kill.'' By Raymond Benson. G.P. Putnam's Sons.
$23.95. 255 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Benson is no Ian Fleming, but he captures the spirit and pluck
of Fleming's OO7 in this high-flying spy thriller.
</P>
<P>
   While on vacation in the Bahamas with his latest lover, Bond
saves the life of the governor, who has been targeted by a new
terrorist group known as the Union.
</P>
<P>
   In a secret British lab, scientists are developing Skin 17, a
material for the frame of an airplane that will allow it to reach
previously unattainable airspeeds. A member of the British Secret
Service kills the head of the scientific team and gives the Union a
microdot containing the formula for Skin 17. MI6 learns that the
courier carrying the microdot was on a plane that crashed in the
Himalayas, and Bond is sent to recover the microdot.
</P>
<P>
   I started reading ``High Time to Kill'' just after seeing the
IMAX film ``Everest,'' and I'm sure that influenced the fun I had
reading the parts of the book that dealt with scaling a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Benson provides lots of blood and guts, sex and derring-do.
``High Time'' is a perfect read for a plane ride or an afternoon at
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra's Needle.'' By Steven Siebert. Forge. $23.95. 168
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert's debut thriller could have been top-notch. But the
intriguing plot goes awry due to terrible construction.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologist Dan Rawlins is doing research at New York's
Metropolitan Museum of Art. One day he gets a visit from Liam
McKay, who says he works for Sotheby's. McKay shows Rawlins a photo
of a damaged ankh and asks if the Met's collection has the other
half.
</P>
<P>
   Checking the museum's catalog, Rawlins finds a match to the
damaged ankh. But when McKay offers to buy the museum's half,
Rawlins knows McKay has a hidden agenda and brushes him off.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlins later sends his assistant, Marce, to retrieve the ankh.
The next day, Marce is found mutilated at the base of Cleopatra's
Needle in Central Park. Rawlins' father is found brutally murdered
near his beach house, and the younger Rawlins also is attacked.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle East, Mossad agent Jacinda El-Bahri has retrieved
the damaged half of the ankh from a terrorist group planning to use
the relic's legendary power to further its cause.
</P>
<P>
   After her hideout in Cairo is bombed, Jacinda flees to Port Said
and books passage on the first departing merchant ship. After a
brief nap, she awakens to find the ship dead in the water and only
one other person on board.
</P>
<P>
   Then the story moves back thousands of years to ancient Egypt to
tell the tale of the ankh. And after 119 pages, the story returns
to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother with ``Cleopatra's Needle.'' It's a mess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
