<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SPIRITUAL-LISTENING-N     08-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-LISTENING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOUSE IN THE WOODS WHERE BUSY PEOPLE DEVELOP `A LISTENING
HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the Minnesota woods, there is an unusual little house-- a
place called the House of Prayer. It is, like thousands of other
such places, a church retreat center.
</P>
<P>
   Its unique mission, however, is to cultivate contemplative
prayer and help busy people develop ``a listening heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, I discovered the House of Prayer and was drawn
by its simplicity. Owned by the Episcopal Church and situated on
the grounds of St. John's Benedictine Abbey, the House of Prayer
sits at the juncture of farmland and woods 90 miles north of the
Twin Cities.
</P>
<P>
   Its peace served as a counterbalance in my life during a hectic
year of commuter-marriage. Since then, especially during stressful
times, I find myself thinking of the house in the woods and wishing
I were there.
</P>
<P>
   When business recently took me to Minnesota, I returned for an
afternoon at the House of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, there was a new addition to the little house: an
Oratory. An oratory is a small chapel devoted to personal prayer.
But this particular oratory was unlike any I have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   The outside looks like a tiny church and forms the shape of the
cross. But the cruciform is not obvious on the inside. Instead, the
oratory's main room is round. The ceiling is low around the edge of
the room and then soars in a teepee-shaped vault to skylights.
</P>
<P>
   The space is very plain-- only a few removable icons-- its
austerity relieved by texture, color and light. Traditional
Christian symbols are absent. Less traditional onesborrowed from
Buddhist and American Indian sacred traditions help furnish the
oratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are unapologetically Christian in our life,'' says the Rev.
David Keller, director of the House of Prayer, ``but we welcome
others.''
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, the word ``oratory'' conjures images of
speech and speech-making. But in this place, I fell into hushed
silence knowing I had found sacred ground. I did not want to talk.
I wanted to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``An oratory is a place to speak and listen,'' explained Keller.
Here, speaking and listening to Godand the inner prompting of one's
soulthrough meditation is the goal. As Keller said, the building
``leads beyond itself into the heart of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oratory is grounded in a particular tradition-- that of
Benedictine spirituality. Although it originated fifteen hundred
years ago, many contemporary churchgoers have picked up Benedictine
ideals and found them helpful for modern spiritual concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Norris's best-selling books exude Benedictine
spirituality. Less well-known writers, such as Joan Chittester and
Esther deWaal, have found devoted audiences for their books on
practical Benedictine life.
</P>
<P>
   Popular author Thomas Moore described the Benedictine vision as
``profoundly contemplative and thoroughly communal.'' Perhaps the
balance between private meditation and life in the world is
precisely its appeal in its current revival.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Benedictine spirituality comes from the first word
in St. Benedict's Rule: ``Listen.'' Benedictine life assumes there
is a God who is speaking, a presence who wants human beings to
listen: ``What is more delightful than this voice of the Lord
calling us? See how the Lord in love shows us the way of life!''
</P>
<P>
   That Benedictine spirituality, with its emphasis on listening,
should be finding its way into American religion strikes me as
oddly hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   It is odd, of course, because American religion has never been
particularly good at listening. Preaching, yes. Good deeds, yes.
Talking and doing have been the hallmarks of American piety.
Americans are quick to tell others what to believe and slow to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, and in the strangest places, we hear of listening.
Politicians are not making speeches. They conduct ``listening
tours.'' Some denominations have declared moratoriums on talking
about issues and have instead proclaimed ``Jubilee'' years to
listen to concerns in their midst. Management professionals urge
executives to spend up to a year listening to their employees
before implementing new policies.
</P>
<P>
   There's something spiritual in all this-- largely unnoticed, but
very real. Perhaps we have discovered that noise, the shouts of our
preachers, pundits, and politicians, have done nothing to solve our
deepest problems.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if we stop and listento God, to ourselves, to one
anotherwe can chart a new course for our society.
</P>
<P>
   We have discovered we do not need oratory as much as we need the
Oratory.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the Oratory, one of the carpenters on the
project remarked, ``I'm not looking forward to going back to
working on strip malls.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when we finally listen, that is what we will all hear.
There is more to our work and our lives than strip malls.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7862 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SPIRITUAL-LISTENING-N     08-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-LISTENING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOUSE IN THE WOODS WHERE BUSY PEOPLE DEVELOP `A LISTENING
HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
