</P>
<P>
   The Oratory is grounded in a particular tradition-- that of
Benedictine spirituality. Although it originated fifteen hundred
years ago, many contemporary churchgoers have picked up Benedictine
ideals and found them helpful for modern spiritual concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Norris's best-selling books exude Benedictine
spirituality. Less well-known writers, such as Joan Chittester and
Esther deWaal, have found devoted audiences for their books on
practical Benedictine life.
</P>
<P>
   Popular author Thomas Moore described the Benedictine vision as
``profoundly contemplative and thoroughly communal.'' Perhaps the
balance between private meditation and life in the world is
precisely its appeal in its current revival.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Benedictine spirituality comes from the first word
in St. Benedict's Rule: ``Listen.'' Benedictine life assumes there
is a God who is speaking, a presence who wants human beings to
listen: ``What is more delightful than this voice of the Lord
calling us? See how the Lord in love shows us the way of life!''
</P>
<P>
   That Benedictine spirituality, with its emphasis on listening,
should be finding its way into American religion strikes me as
oddly hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   It is odd, of course, because American religion has never been
particularly good at listening. Preaching, yes. Good deeds, yes.
Talking and doing have been the hallmarks of American piety.
Americans are quick to tell others what to believe and slow to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, and in the strangest places, we hear of listening.
Politicians are not making speeches. They conduct ``listening
tours.'' Some denominations have declared moratoriums on talking
about issues and have instead proclaimed ``Jubilee'' years to
listen to concerns in their midst. Management professionals urge
executives to spend up to a year listening to their employees
before implementing new policies.
</P>
<P>
   There's something spiritual in all this-- largely unnoticed, but
very real. Perhaps we have discovered that noise, the shouts of our
preachers, pundits, and politicians, have done nothing to solve our
deepest problems.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if we stop and listento God, to ourselves, to one
anotherwe can chart a new course for our society.
</P>
<P>
   We have discovered we do not need oratory as much as we need the
Oratory.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the Oratory, one of the carpenters on the
project remarked, ``I'm not looking forward to going back to
working on strip malls.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when we finally listen, that is what we will all hear.
There is more to our work and our lives than strip malls.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
