<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7879 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-LIFETIME-REVIEW-SPI &LR;      08-24 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFETIME-REVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MAY BE TOO MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look out, Judge Judy. Judge Othniel is in the house. And he's
not dealing in small claims.
</P>
<P>
   Othniel, fresh from the Old Testament's Book of Judges, is a
featured player on ``Twice in a Lifetime,'' a new Pax TV series
premiering Wednesday night at 8 on KWPX. In Othniel's courtroom,
supplicants on their way to the hereafter get a hearing to
determine if they deserve a second chance at life. Thus, a ``life
sentence'' from Othniel (played avuncularly by Al Waxman) is a good
thing, assuming the plaintiff isn't thrilled with the idea of being
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to each case is a ``caretaker of souls,'' a sort of
celestial public defender who argues on behalf of the plaintiff and
then, back on Earth, acts as a guide to help the person see where
he went astray. One such caretaker is young Mr. Jones, the main
facilitator on ``Twice in a Lifetime.'' Each week, in the manner of
a latter-day Mr. Roarke from ``Fantasy Island,'' he guides a new
character on a return trip to real life and a chance to get it
right the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   A syrupy combination of ``Touched by an Angel'' and ``Quantum
Leap,'' ``Twice in a Lifetime'' moves more slowly than a line at
the DMV. If this is family viewing, America's families will have to
be treated for early-onset drowsiness on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's episode is about a woman (Gwyneth Walsh) who gave up
her first child for adoption when she was 16. Now 46 and an
alcoholic who's a rotteand mother, she gets a second chance
to confront her teenage decision. There's just one twist: She
doesn't go back as herself at 16; she goes back as an adoption
counselor, coming face to face with herself.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting contrivance, but not even a surprise ending
can keep ``Twice in a Lifefrom overcoming its own sluggish
pace. Walsh is pleasant enough as the first plaintiff in Othniel's
court, and Gordie Brown, who is a Las Vegas comedian when he's not
playing Mr. Jones, is youthful and charming as a world-wise
guardian angel. The writing isn't even particularly heinous. But in
its first incarnation, ``Twice in a Lifetime'' is just plain
boring, which is interesting in a way, because Pax TV rejected the
original pilot as being too dark.
</P>
<P>
   In that version, the judge was Jephthah, also played by Waxman,
but he was meaner and his court was a scary place. It also had a
nasty prosecutor who fought against a second chance for the
plaintiff (and in one instance succeeded in getting a person
dispatched to hell).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's not family viewing, but, trust me, it's a lot more
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in a Lifetime. Hourlong anthology series about people
getting a second chance to shape their own destinies. Starring
Gordie Brown, with special guest performers each week. Season
premiere Wednesday night at 8, KWPX. Parental guideline rating:
TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TAX-STAKES-$ADV29-COX     08-24 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-STAKES-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAX CUT PLAN COULD HAVE BROAD ECONOMIC EFFECT
 &HT;    840&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, Aug. 29.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Democrats and Republicans battle over how much
to cut federal taxes, analysts disagree over whose plan is better
for the economy. But they do agree that the cuts could have a
tremendous long-term impact on the country.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns to work after Labor Day, Republicans plan
to send President Clinton their already-approved plan to cut taxes
by $792 billion over 10 years. It would trim income tax rates
across the board, as well as estate taxes, capital gains taxes, and
the ``marriage penalty'' that causes some couples to pay more tax
than if they filed as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly promised to veto the GOP plan. His own
proposal is for $320 billion in tax cuts aimed at low- and
middle-income workers. That would be partly offset by $70 billion
in new revenue from closing loopholes in the corporate tax code, a
strategy businesses call a tax hike.
</P>
<P>
   The president also wants to set aside $374 billion over 10 years
to shore up Medicare, the federal health insurance program for the
elderly, and to spend roughly $100 billion more on education,
worker training and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would tap $1 trillion in projected budget surpluses
over the next decade _ if they actually appear, which many experts
doubt _ while agreeing to save another $2 trillion in excess Social
Security and Medicare taxes for future spending on those programs.
</P>
<P>
   With the tax dispute coming to a head, advocates for each
approach are pointing to the potential economic benefits _ and
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for the larger Republican plan is that ``tax cuts
do create, or do free up, capital and investment and spending in
ways that do stimulate the economy,'' said Glenn Yago, director of
capital studies at the Milken Institute, an economic research group
in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Economic stimulus, in turn, helps create jobs and raise incomes
across all socio-economic levels, Yago maintained.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent the economy needs better educated workers, he
said, private industry can do a better job than government, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that do require a higher level of
investment currently, particularly in the education area,'' said
Yago. ``The temptation (in Washington) is to fund it through the
enormously inefficient mechanisms of government, which would
squander that wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Others counter that the stimulus of a large tax cut might better
be applied in times of recession than in times of economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you would want to do a tax cut. This is
not one of them,'' said Robert Bixby, policy director for the
Concord Coalition, a Washington research and advocacy group
dedicated to reducing the national debt. ``The economy doesn't need
a tax cut right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Another argument against big tax cuts is that they threaten to
scuttle debt reduction and force needed government programs onto a
deficit-era austerity diet, said Michael Calabrese, director of
domestic policy programs for the Center for National Policy, a
liberal-leaning research and advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall impact will be to starve government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the tax cut debate might have less effect on
the economy than on congressional and presidential politics next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even the larger Republican tax cuts, for example, would amount
to less than $5 billion when they start phasing in next year _ less
than one-tenth of 1 percent the size of a U.S. economy expected to
produce a gross domestic product (GDP) of $8.5 trillion in goods
and services this year.
</P>
<P>
   But ``by the time you get to the year 2008, you're looking at
cuts of $168 billion,'' said Henry Aaron, senior fellow for
economic studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington
research group.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, ``it's a tax cut of a percent and a half of
GDP,'' said Aaron, ``which is a significant change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican tax cut gets into really serious money _ $3
trillion, the Treasury Department estimates _ over the second
decade of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The current debate brings the Republican philosophy of lower
taxes and less government into direct conflict with Democratic
preferences for a higher level of government services.
</P>
<P>
   How the dispute is resolved could have a tremendous long-term
impact on the country's economic prospects, analysts from both
sides of the political spectrum agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate over the tax bill,'' said Aaron, ``is one of those
watershed debates on the direction in which budget policy will go
over the next decade or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar turning points in the past have had profound effects on
the economy. President Reagan's tax cuts and military spending
increases in the early 1980s are credited with providing a powerful
boost to the national economy _ and record federal budget deficits
a few years later. President Bush's unpopular tax increases in the
early 1990s are seen by many as setting the foundation for the
decade's long economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   With the stakes so high and the prospects so uncertain, many
analysts say neither Clinton's approach nor the Republicans' is all
that attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Simply holding the line on spending and taxes would do far more
for the country than either large spending hikes or sizable tax
cuts, said the Concord Coalition's Bixby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that there's so much partisan bitterness that they
won't be able to make a deal,'' said Bixby. ``They should dare to
do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   If taxes and spending are left largely unchanged, whatever
surplus does accrue in the years ahead would go mostly toward
reducing the $3.6 trillion the federal government now owes to banks
and other investors, the so-called public portion of the country's
$5.6 trillion debt.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) estimates that if
Congress and the White House simply stick to the spending caps set
forth in the 1997 balanced budget agreement, and leave the tax
structure as it is, public debt would fall to $865 billion by the
year 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of 40 percent of today's GDP, the public debt would fall
to 6.4 percent of GDP in 2009, the CBO figures.
</P>
<P>
   For a country that spent an entire generation racking up the
largest national debt in world history, that would mark a stunning
achievement. In addition to driving down the amount the government
pays in interest costs _ $229 billion this year alone _ many
economists contend it would substantially boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the reduction that is occurring in the federal
debt at this stage, as a consequence of the ongoing surplus, is an
extraordinarily effective force for good in this economy,'' Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan told the House Banking
Committee in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a major factor in expansion of economic growth,''
said Greenspan, who went on to plead with the panel's members not
to do anything to impede the trajectory of the long-awaited deficit
relief. ``Let the surpluses run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming, of course, that the projected surpluses
actually materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no surplus that we can really count on,'' claims
Calabrese of the Center for National Policy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the projections of a $1 trillion surplus over 10 years,
not counting excess Social Security and Medicare taxes, depend on
three rather shaky assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   _ First, that the economy _ already eight years into one of the
largest peacetime expansions in the nation's history _ will
continue to grow at better than 2 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Second, that Congress and the White House will stick to the
spending caps set by the 1997 balanced budget deal. The Center on
Budget and Policy Priorities, a Washington research and policy
group, estimates that holding to the caps would require $775
billion worth of spending cuts over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of $775 billion over 10 years in cuts is utterly
unreal,'' the center's executive director, Robert Greenstein said.
``Neither party has the stomach for deep cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Third, that Congress won't break the bank with bookkeeping
gimmicks such as so-called emergency spending _ like the $4 billion
Republicans have called for to pay for next year's national census.
</P>
<P>
   In short, history and political horse sense suggests that the
projected surpluses may not survive the budgeting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were telling me you were going to lose 20 pounds by
Christmas, and you were eating a banana split in front of me,''
explained Bixby, ``I might not believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
