</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) estimates that if
Congress and the White House simply stick to the spending caps set
forth in the 1997 balanced budget agreement, and leave the tax
structure as it is, public debt would fall to $865 billion by the
year 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of 40 percent of today's GDP, the public debt would fall
to 6.4 percent of GDP in 2009, the CBO figures.
</P>
<P>
   For a country that spent an entire generation racking up the
largest national debt in world history, that would mark a stunning
achievement. In addition to driving down the amount the government
pays in interest costs _ $229 billion this year alone _ many
economists contend it would substantially boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the reduction that is occurring in the federal
debt at this stage, as a consequence of the ongoing surplus, is an
extraordinarily effective force for good in this economy,'' Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan told the House Banking
Committee in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a major factor in expansion of economic growth,''
said Greenspan, who went on to plead with the panel's members not
to do anything to impede the trajectory of the long-awaited deficit
relief. ``Let the surpluses run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming, of course, that the projected surpluses
actually materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no surplus that we can really count on,'' claims
Calabrese of the Center for National Policy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the projections of a $1 trillion surplus over 10 years,
not counting excess Social Security and Medicare taxes, depend on
three rather shaky assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   _ First, that the economy _ already eight years into one of the
largest peacetime expansions in the nation's history _ will
continue to grow at better than 2 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Second, that Congress and the White House will stick to the
spending caps set by the 1997 balanced budget deal. The Center on
Budget and Policy Priorities, a Washington research and policy
group, estimates that holding to the caps would require $775
billion worth of spending cuts over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of $775 billion over 10 years in cuts is utterly
unreal,'' the center's executive director, Robert Greenstein said.
``Neither party has the stomach for deep cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Third, that Congress won't break the bank with bookkeeping
gimmicks such as so-called emergency spending _ like the $4 billion
Republicans have called for to pay for next year's national census.
</P>
<P>
   In short, history and political horse sense suggests that the
projected surpluses may not survive the budgeting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were telling me you were going to lose 20 pounds by
Christmas, and you were eating a banana split in front of me,''
explained Bixby, ``I might not believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
