<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Everything's OK in Prague
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ The worst thing in the world is to
offend folks when you had no intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   So it has happened, all because of a story I wrote from the
capital of the Czech Republic a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the first few paragraphs to give you an idea:
</P>
<P>
   ``Prague is a city intoxicated on freedom, and that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual to meet someone along the street smoking a
joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the finest restaurants in Prague is just a block from
an open drug market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be sitting in a restaurant and, instead of a waiter,
it's a drug dealer who comes to your table to ask what he can bring
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then, so does the weather girl on TV, who appears totally
nude and then begins to dress herself accordingly for the next
day's weather. On occasion, it's an equally naked weather boy.''
</P>
<P>
   And it goes on from there.
</P>
<P>
   I have since received e-mail correspondence informing me I have
caused great consternation among a number of people, two or three
at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   The writer notes, ``I am not a reader of yours,'' which is as
good a way as any to get a writer's attention, ``but was sent one
of your opinions by my sisters ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Prague is by no means what you have described by your column.
... We have been living here for seven years and are very happy to
have joined this community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here have gone out of their way to assist us in
some of the worst times of our lives and we are thankful for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer goes on to ask that if I could clarify my earlier
comments, ``I and my fellow townspeople would appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not think your column is widely read,'' a further
attention-grabber, ``but you never can tell what gets around to
where.''
</P>
<P>
   She concludes on a conciliatory note: ``We host the Prague
Kolachi Festival every year the first weekend in May. You may want
to join us next May and become familiar with our people.''
</P>
<P>
   What can I say? I apologize to the writer, to her sisters and to
all the good people of Prague, Okla., for any misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   One other item from the mail. I had written about the little
hotel where I always try to stay when I'm in Paris, a delightful
spot on the Left Bank, just around the corner from the Pantheon, a
short way from the Sorbonne and an easy walk to Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   With a bistro on most every corner, a bakery right across the
street and even a coin-operated laundromat in the next block, it's
very much a neighborhood in itself.
</P>
<P>
   What I forgot to include, and any number of readers have written
asking, was the name of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Hotel Claude Bernard, 43 rue des Ecoles. You can find
detailed information on the Claude Bernard and scores of other
small hotels in Fodor's ``Hotels of Character and Charm in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   I hasten to add, that's Paris, France, not Paris, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address, P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
