<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-IRELAND-HORSES-0825-C     08-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-HORSES-0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DUBLIN'S URBAN COWBOYS FIGHTING TO KEEP THEIR HORSES, WAY OF
LIFE
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ On a patch of green beside the dreary gray
Ballymun towers here, horse and rider leap effortlessly over an
obstacle fashioned from a discarded plank resting on two stacks of
old tires.
</P>
<P>
   Cairin McElligott, 15, rides Jasmine bareback with little effort
and much grace. He tugs the reins to turn Jasmine for another
attempt and taps her flanks with the sides of his sneakers. Again,
horse and rider are flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a large van parked on the road by the narrow grassy
strip enjoys a steady flow of people through its side door. It's a
mobile methadone clinic making a stop to serve the heroine addicts
among the vast government housing complex's 20,000 inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people emerging from the van stop to take in the
free display of equestrian skills.
</P>
<P>
   It is a show whose days may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the poor people of Ballymun and other government
housing complexes around Dublin have had their horses. But growing
concern about the welfare of Dublin's urban horses has placed the
Ballymun riders on the road to extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of owning a horse and keeping it in a play yard, a
football pitch or in the back garden are over,'' said Maurice
Byrne, the chief inspector for the Dublin Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. ``There's no place for it in this
day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vicky McElligott, Cairin's mother, is vowing to fight to
keep the horses at Ballymun.
</P>
<P>
   McElligott admits that this bleak, litter-strewn place is less
than an ideal home for the horses, but she is equally aware of the
ugly realities represented by the methadone van.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horses are a way a boy can raise his expectations,'' says
McElligott, the mother of nine. ``Maybe the horses don't keep them
from the selling or using of drugs, but they do give them a focus:
Taking care of an animal as big as a horse is a responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   She worries that horse protection laws passed in recent years on
the national and local level soon will bring an end to ownership by
poor and working-class people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be just for the rich,'' she says.
``Multi-million pounds are spent on those horses. The manure from
those horses is worth more than our horses.''
</P>
<P>
   The laws, which date to 1996, require horse owners to license
their animals. They make it illegal for anyone under 16 to own a
horse, and authorities can impound horses not kept in stables.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that animal control officers will carry off their horses
at night, Ballymun residents keep vigilant watch over the horses
from the high-rise windows. About 120 horses live in and around
Ballymun, less than half the population of five years ago. Across
Dublin, there may be 3,000 urban horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're illegal, there's no denying that,'' McElligott says,
glancing at the half-dozen horses tethered to stakes in the green
patch. More horses graze on a nearby soccer field, and even more
are kept in a stand of trees near the towers.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of the horses at Ballymun varies from well-fed
and groomed _ generally those kept at the stable _ to rangy and
unkempt. Some are shoeless.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The urban horses have received a good deal of attention in the
local and national media and have been portrayed _ some say
romanticized _ in the films ``The Commitments'' and ``Into the
West.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most unforgettable scenes in the latter featured a
horse, a small boy and, an erratic elevator servicing one of
Ballymun's towers. ``You're not bringing that in here,'' complains
one of the film's main characters to the boy standing with his
horse. ``The stairs would kill him,'' the boy replies indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   To McElligott, this struggle is more than a battle over the
right to ownership. She depicts it as a battle over culture and her
right to retain her heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Horses long have had a special place in the Irish psyche, so it
is not surprising that people held on to them when they began
taking up residence in places such as Ballymun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you. Look at the tower blocks,'' she says. ``Irish
people were never meant to live in the sky. That's half the problem
here.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of staving off official action, the Ballymun residents
have organized the Ballymun Horse Owners Club. Members must
contribute a few pounds and attend meetings, and they board their
horses in a hastily converted pub that lay abandoned for years. The
club has shows and races in which it competes with clubs from other
housing projects. The races often generate kitties of more than
$20,000.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside the former pub, horses poke their heads out through holes
knocked through the cinderblock walls. A cat with a mouse in its
mouth hunts for privacy as chickens and ducks squabble in a corner.
A half-dozen kids between 11 and 15 clean the stall floors, which
are covered with straw and sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Barnes, 36, instructs 11-year-old Brian Boyle on the finer
points of cleaning mud from a shoed hoof. ``Mind the quick,''
Barnes says. ``That's it. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who loves to race his horses, says he's taught himself
how to care for the animals. ``The horse will teach you,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Byrne, the DSPCA chief inspector, has no doubt that many people
in Ballymun love their horses and do their best for them. However,
he believes the horses in the stable are not representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are horses that are left tethered on a rope in the
football pitch in the open, even in winter,'' he says. ``The boys
ride them bareback, not realizing that this is very painful to the
horse, with the hard seams in their jeans. They will get up in the
morning and ride their horses have dinner and go and ride them
again like the hammers of hell. And then at night others will ride
them too. The horses are exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   McElligott acknowledges that there are problems, but she insists
that people who treat their horses well should not be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she knows that the situation as it is, cannot last.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could come in today and close us down and take the horses
away,'' she says, watching her son and his horse make one more
jump. ``They want to annihilate this way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
