<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mount Horrocks Clare Valley Late-Harvest Riesling 1998,
Southeast Australia. About $18.
</P>
<P>
   No one can resist a sweet dessert wine. I'm not talking about
some sugary plonk fortified with 20 percent alcohol; it's easier to
knock yourself out with a hammer. No, I'm referring to the viscous,
golden late-harvest wines made entirely from overripe grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The best are the sauvignon-semillion blends of Sauternes and the
rieslings of Germany, Alsace and Austria. American versions often
lack the acid needed to balance the sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   This riesling from Australia is the nearest thing I've come to a
great German beerenauslese, a rare late-harvest wine that usually
commands a high price. The winemaker, Stephanie Toole, achieves a
balance of high sugar and intense acid that they'd be proud of in
the Rheingau. A connoisseur's confection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
