<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      08-24 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FITTING END FOR SUMMER'S VIVID FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the sixth of eight columns by Waldy Malouf, the chef and
an owner of Beacon in Manhattan. His collaborator on these columns
is Melissa Clark.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the time of year for straightforward tomato dishes, ones
that take advantage of the fantastic spectrum making its way to
farm stands and produce markets in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the best of these dishes are barely cooked, or not cooked
at all. The less you cook a peak-of-summer tomato, the more you can
appreciate its marvelous, fruity flavor. A vivid yellow tomato
soup, simmered for just a few minutes, then pureed and chilled, is
a perfect example. The brief simmering helps the tomatoes release
their juices and meld the ingredients. But the flavors remain pure
and sweet, without that vague cold spaghetti sauce taste of many
tomato soups.
</P>
<P>
   While you can use any color of tomato for this soup, I like the
look of the yellow ones. They are also milder and less acidic than
their red cousins, and make a better match for herbs and spices.
But this soup is really about the tomatoes, so I use a light hand _
just a touch of toasted whole coriander and cumin.
</P>
<P>
   The coriander shows up again as an herb in the garnish _ a
relish inspired by Mexican salsa. The relish is uncooked, and it
brings a crunchy texture to the smooth soup. Bits of jalapeno are
like sparks on the tongue, contributing just enough heat to
accentuate the coolness of the soup. I use red tomatoes in the
relish, for their more assertive flavor, which stands up to the
jalapeno, and for a contrasting color.
</P>
<P>
   This soup couldn't be simpler to prepare. Since it's strained
after being cooked, you don't have to peel or seed or even core the
tomatoes _ just cut them into chunks and throw them into a pot. The
soup needs to be made several hours in advance so it can chill and
the flavors can develop. Prepare it in the morning, or even the day
before serving, but not any further ahead or it will lose its
freshness. The relish, too, can be made a few hours before serving,
but not more than three, or the tomatoes will turn flabby. Not a
fitting end for the tomato you've been waiting for all year.
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW TOMATO SOUP WITH CILANTRO-ONION RELISH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 4 hours' chilling
</P>
<P>
   For the soup:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   6 large yellow tomatoes, cut into rough cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon whole coriander seed
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon whole cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly ground black pepper For the relish:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red tomato, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   { cup finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make the soup, heat olive oil in a large pot over medium
heat. Add the onions and garlic, and saute until they are
translucent, about 5 minutes. Do not let them brown (if they start
to color, add a tablespoon of water). Add the tomatoes and saute
for 5 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, in a small skillet, toast the coriander and cumin
over medium high heat until they are fragrant and lightly browned,
about 2 to 3 minutes. Add them to the tomatoes, along with 2 cups
water.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring the tomato mixture to a boil, then reduce the heat and
simmer for about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn off the heat, and let the soup cool slightly. Puree with
an immersion blender, or in batches in a food processor. Strain,
and discard the solids. Chill the soup until cold, at least 4
hours. 5. When ready to serve, make the relish: in a small bowl,
mix together all the relish ingredients. Season the soup with lemon
juice, salt and pepper. Garnish with relish, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
