<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CULTURE-BOOK-REVIEW-(     08-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-BOOK-REVIEW-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN CULTURE, AMERICAN TASTES': WHEN LOWBROW BUMPS INTO
HIGHBROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Kammen is one of the better-known historians practicing
these days. His book ``People of Paradox'' won the Pulitzer Prize
in 1973; his later ``Mystic Chords of Memory,'' in which he teased
out the various uses and misuses of the American past, was greeted
with reverential reviews. Kammen, in other words, has the sort of
reputation that makes one expect something complex and strong from
his books, and this expectation certainly holds for his new one,
``American Culture, American Tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways a natural continuation of ``Mystic Chords of
Memory,'' the new book is an extended commentary on the fate of
culture in a modern democracy. As always with Kammen, it is
prodigiously researched and impressively erudite. Its main topic is
the transformation of American culture from the time when what
Kammen calls popular culture was dominant to the present ascendancy
of mass culture. It covers other matters as well: the relationship
between the ``high'' culture and the ``low,'' the way the two have
permeated each other, and how their intimate relationship has been
proclaimed and denounced by various historians and critics over the
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kammen's learned treatment of a good topic, there is
something off about this new book, something vague and ungraspable
about its themes, beyond the requirements of serious scholarship.
Much of it, despite Kammen's frequent reminders about how
``complex'' things are, seems rather familiar.
</P>
<P>
   There is a great deal of rather solemn throat clearing in this
book, as if Kammen himself hesitated to get to the point. He so
laboriously cites what prior writers have said on his subjects that
whole chapters seem more compilations of researched tidbits than
fully developed arguments of his own.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Kammen's writing elsewhere has been praised for
its elegance, here it has a wordy, repetitive, glutinous quality
that makes it difficult to get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a fairly broad consensus, encompassing
people with otherwise divergent perspectives, that ever since
mid-century, and especially since the dominant role of television
became evident around 1960, cultural stratification and the
existence of distinct brow levels have become blurred where they
haven't been overtly blended,'' Kammen writes in a typically
cumbersome sentence. Ask yourself as you read it exactly what has
been ``blurred'' or ``overtly blended.'' You can guess what Kammen
means here, but it isn't what he has said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kammen treats culture in the broad sense as referring to all the
elements that go into a way of life: habits, customs and behavior
as well as art, music and literature. Culture is baseball as well
as Beethoven, the way you shop and the books you read. As he treats
this vast subject, he is at his best when he departs from concept
and delves into concrete example.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with an assertion that popular culture is not at all
the same thing as mass culture, and that ``definitional clarity''
(another fancy locution; ``clear definitions'' would be simpler and
more accurate) is essential. It is about 50 pages later that the
differences between these two categories begin to emerge, but when
they do, Kammen provides a bracing shock of recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis here has to do with the elements that made up
American popular culture from about 1880 to 1940, when it was the
centerpiece of American culture in general. Kammen talks about the
Sears, Roebuck catalog, self-help books, minstrel shows, newspaper
comic strips and the emergence of supermarkets as artifacts of what
he calls proto mass culture, or ``PMC.'' Later he provides some
illustrative elements of ``MC,'' mass culture itself: not Sears but
McDonald's, not syndicated comic strips but MTV, not urban parks at
the end of trolley lines but Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, one of the most basic differences between popular
and mass culture hinges upon the more participatory and interactive
qualities of the former in contrast to the more spectatorial and
passive qualities of the latter,'' he writes. The supposedly active
popular culture versus the passive mass culture (in fact, later in
the book Kammen cites opinions that the most recent artifacts of
mass culture, like computer games, are not passive at all) is not
the only difference.
</P>
<P>
   He also cites the transformation from what he calls a
commercialized culture to a commodified one. In one, he writes,
companies find new ways to market goods that people actually need.
In the other, companies use advertising to create the need.
</P>
<P>
   The reader will find in these pages brief histories of cultural
criticism, of the growth of corporate power in creating the mass
culture and the near destruction of the boundaries between the
middlebrow culture and the highbrow one. There are also compelling
passages that trace the decline of traditional cultural authority,
a decline hastened by corporate power: ``The entrepreneurial power
of commerce totally crushed the recommendations of such cultural
authorities as John Crosby, Jack Gould and Gilbert Seldes _
prominent television critics who pleaded for diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not exactly new points, but they are elements in a
compelling and even thrilling American story: of the brilliant,
beleaguered popular culture and its partial eclipse by the rise of
the mass culture. Kammen tells that story topic by topic rather
than time period by time period, perhaps not the right approach.
</P>
<P>
   His presentation thereby loses narrative force and results in a
confusing overlapping of subjects and illustrations. Paradoxically,
this author's encyclopedic knowledge of his subject gets in the way
of the story he had to tell. Kammen seems compelled to put
everything in, when a more fully developed less might have been
more.
</P>
<P>
   What Kammen has done, in short, is reflect on the popular and
mass American cultures from a highbrow academic standpoint, but
highbrow in an unnecessarily eggheadish, inaccessible way. There is
marvelous information and interpretation here for those who have
the patience to dig it out, but patience will surely be needed.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN CULTURE, AMERICAN TASTES: Social Change and the 20th
Century'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Kammen  &UR;  &LR;  Illustrated. 322 pages. Alfred A. Knopf.
$30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-ART-2T     08-24 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC BUT ACCESSIBLE, COCONUT MILK EARNS ITS SHELF SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time has come to give coconut milk a permanent place in your
pantry. One of the keys to the flavors of Southeast Asia, India and
much of the Caribbean, this no-frills liquid could hardly be easier
to use: just open and pour. Like canned tomatoes, it is the
foundation of some essential dishes. Like canned chicken stock, it
can turn a dry dish into a pleasantly saucy one in about two
minutes. Like both, its usefulness and versatility transcend the
stigma of canned food.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut milk is not the anemic fluid found inside a coconut;
that's coconut juice, which is drunk as if it were water in the
tropics. And it's not the thick and heavily sweetened mass also
sold in cans that is used to make pina coladas and other drinks;
that's cream of coconut, which is coconut milk laced with loads of
sugar. Instead, it is the essence of coconut meat made liquid, with
all of the flavor and none of the grittiness.
</P>
<P>
   Although coconut milk may be a new ingredient to many Americans,
it is common in everyday cooking throughout the tropics, in both
sweet and savory preparations. It is, for instance, a fast dessert
sauce in Vietnam and the basis for the Puerto Rican coconut pudding
called tembleque. It is also used in many Caribbean rice and bean
dishes and soups, as a luxurious finish in stews in parts of India
and as a major ingredient in many Thai soups and curries. In South
America, it is used like (or with) broth in lobster and chicken
stews.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut milk is also the backbone of dozens of ``creamy'' meat
dishes in countries where refrigeration is uncommon or where dairy
products are shunned for practical, traditional or religious
reasons. (It is not a dieter's substitute, though: coconut milk is
just as high in saturated fat and calories as coconut and coconut
oil. If this concerns you and you want to cut back on calories and
fat, just cut the coconut milk with water or chicken stock; the
flavor is so strong that it will still come through.)
</P>
<P>
   But coconut milk does more than add distinctive flavor. It acts
as a thickener as well. Stirred into simmering dishes in the last
few minutes of cooking, it has much the same effect as heavy cream,
as in the curry recipe here. Used as a substitute for water to cook
rice or rice pudding, it turns the ordinary into the sublime. It
has the same effect when fresh corn kernels are simmered in it. It
can even be used as wine or brandy is to deglaze a skillet, or to
finish cooking noodles; both of these techniques are used in the
stir-fried noodle recipe here.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, coconut milk needs only sugar to make one of the
world's greatest sorbets. Just thoroughly mix two cans (three to
four cups) with three-quarters of a cup of sugar (or more to
taste), plus a teaspoon of vanilla, and freeze in an ice cream
maker. This sorbet is best served the day it's made.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any supermarket carries coconut milk these days, in
either the Asian or the Hispanic section, but you can make your own
quite easily. Start with dried, unsweetened coconut flakes, sold in
bulk in natural-food stores. Place a couple of cups of coconut in a
blender with an equal amount of boiling water, and blend. (Do this
very carefully, since few things are worse than airborne boiling
water.) Let the mixture sit for a few minutes, then strain through
a sieve, pressing down to extract as much liquid as possible, and
you have coconut milk.
</P>
<P>
   You can make it thicker or thinner by varying the proportions.
(You can also start with a fresh coconut, but that is much more
complicated, since the coconut has to be roasted, shelled and
grated. The process is not much fun.)
</P>
<P>
   Twelve- to 18-ounce cans of coconut milk, usually from Southeast
Asia, are always cheap, about $1.50 each and sometimes less. Some
milks are thicker than others _ so thick that you may have to add
water to work with them _ and it's worth trying to find one of
those brands and sticking with it. Thicker is better because you
can thin the milk, which means you get more for your money. Often
the liquid will have a thick, almost clotted top, but it can just
be shaken to emulsify it.
</P>
<P>
   Most cans contain a single preservative, potassium
metabisulfite, which is generally considered harmless except for
those with sulfite allergies, especially asthmatics. Other than
that, the label should list no ingredients other than coconut and
water.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut milk is perishable. Once a can has been opened, it
should be refrigerated immediately and used within two days, or it
can be frozen indefinitely. In the cabinet, it's as shelf-stable as
tomatoes or broth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COCONUT RICE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cans unsweetened coconut milk, 3 to 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups rice, preferably jasmine
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine coconut milk and rice in a saucepan, and bring to a
boil over medium heat, stirring occasionally. Add some salt, reduce
heat to low, and cover. Cook for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally
to make sure the rice does not stick or burn.
</P>
<P>
   2. Uncover, and continue to cook, stirring, over low heat until
rice is tender and mixture is creamy. If liquid evaporates before
rice is done, stir in water, about { cup at a time, and cook until
done.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: For coconut rice and beans: Stir 1 cup of moist
cooked kidney, pinto, pink or black beans into the rice about 5
minutes before it finishes cooking.
</P>
<P>
   For rice pudding: reduce rice to 1 cup; add } to 1 cup sugar.
(Start with the smaller amount.) Cook as above, leaving the mixture
very creamy. Serve warm or cold, with a little more coconut milk
stirred in; garnish with a sprinkle of cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STIR-FRIED COCONUT NOODLES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   } pound linguine-style rice noodles, or Italian linguine
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons canola, corn or other neutral oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound minced or ground boneless pork or chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow or red bell pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 eggplant, about { pound, cut into {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 can (1{ to 2 cups) unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   Nam pla (fish sauce), soy sauce or salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Minced cilantro for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. If using rice noodles, soak them in very hot water to cover
until ready to add to stir-fry in Step 4. If using linguine, bring
a large pot of water to a boil, salt it, and cook pasta until it is
nearly but not quite done. Drain, and rinse in cold water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, place 1 tablespoon of the oil in a large skillet
or wok; turn heat to high. A minute later, add meat, and cook,
stirring occasionally, until browned, about 5 minutes. Remove with
slotted spoon; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add another tablespoon of the oil to skillet, followed by
bell pepper and eggplant. Cook over medium-high heat, stirring
occasionally, until both are browned and tender, about 10 minutes.
Remove with slotted spoon; combine with meat.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add remaining tablespoon of oil, followed immediately by the
garlic and about 30 seconds later, the coconut milk. Cook over
medium-high heat, stirring and scraping with a wooden spoon, for
about a minute. Add drained noodles along with meat and vegetables,
and cook until noodles absorb most of the coconut milk, about 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   5. Season with nam pla to taste, then add plenty of black
pepper. Garnish with cilantro, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHRIMP OR CHICKEN CURRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola, corn or other neutral oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 can unsweetened coconut milk (1{ to 2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds peeled shrimp or boneless chicken, cut into }- to
1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled, seeded and diced tomato (canned is fine; cut up
and drain before using)
</P>
<P>
   Chopped basil or mint for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place oil in a large skillet; turn heat to medium-high. A
minute later, add onions, along with a generous pinch of salt and
some pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until onions are very
soft and almost falling apart, 15 minutes or more. Stir in curry
powder, and cook, stirring, for another minute or so.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add coconut milk, and cook until it thickens, about 2
minutes, stirring occasionally. Add shrimp or chicken, and stir,
then cook until done, 3 to 6 minutes. (Shrimp cooks a little faster
than chicken; if you are in doubt about whether chicken is done,
cut into a piece.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Add tomato, and cook another minute; adjust seasonings as
necessary. Serve over rice, garnished with basil or mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; As Fast as Your Can Opener &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Combine canned coconut milk with canned Thai curry paste, and
you have the equivalent of Campbell's soup for the '90s: the sauce
that launched a thousand dishes. Add about a pound of cubed duck,
turkey or firm fish, lump crab meat, beef strips or whole shrimp to
a can of the milk, along with a couple of tablespoons or more of
the curry paste. Simmer, and serve over rice for a main course for
four.
</P>
<P>
   Simply mixed with equal parts coconut milk and broth, a canful
also makes a soup almost faster than Campbell's. The paste comes in
green or red versions, both hot from the chilies used to make them
and both good with anything from fish to potatoes. Four-ounce cans
sell for $1 or less at Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
