<HEADLINE>
WHERE WAITERS TELL ALL ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every bartender, busboy, hostess or waiter has a collection of
horror stories from the front lines. Behind ``the customer is
always right'' and ``service with a smile'' lurks backlash of epic
proportion beyond the swinging doors.
</P>
<P>
   Just what does your waiter think of you? A handful of Web sites
catering to members of the service industry offer a hint,
cataloguing their peeves and posting information, anecdotes, advice
and the tipping habits of the rich and famously cheap. Some sites
are essentially cyber support groups; others offer advice for the
customer as well as the help. In either case, be forewarned: all of
them include language that isn't appropriate for the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in celebrities and what they tip, the
Stained Apron (wso.net/apron) is the spot. According to postings on
the site, Kevin Costner, Johnny Depp and Bernadette Peters are
stellar tippers (20 to 50 percent), while Dan Quayle and Ice-T are
less generous (the rapper is said to have tipped less than 10
percent at a Sizzler).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the site is dedicated to venting, like the rant from the
waiter who had to pick through the trash to find a child's
retainer. Other sections include Why Tipping Properly Is So
Important (Bad Things May Happen) and Menu Manglings, which are
tales of customer confusion during ordering (a car-ah-fay of
shab-liss, anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   The Waiter's Revenge (www.geocities.com/soho/1227) is an
extensive site organized like a menu with entrees including Stories
From Under the Table, yarns about customers like the man who
ordered fish baked in parchment, then ate the paper and complained
that the fish was tough and crunchy. There is also Your Dream
Revenge on Bad Tippers, a section for waiters' anxiety dreams, and
a selection of waiters' haiku: Flies found in my soup, Guarantee a
free dessert, Top with a cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Bitterwaitress (bitterwaitress.com) is a newer site along the
same lines. A large part of it is still under construction, and
there are plans to include gossip and rantings about restaurant
owners, which none of the other sites do. There are departments
like Celebrity Gossip and Industry Dirt. A glossary includes terms
like Discover Card, defined as a sure sign that a person is cheap,
a bad tipper and out of his league. The only celebrity tidbit is
from a server at Ocean Grill on New York's Upper West Side, who
reports Pierce Brosnan left 10 percent and a dollar for the coat
check.
</P>
<P>
   The Hostess Gripe Page (www.geocities.com/napavalley/8691) is a
spinoff of the Waitress Gripe Page, which is no longer up and
running. It opens with: ``This Web page was solely created to
enlighten people about what a hostess in a restaurant actually does
and what she has to go through.'' This consists of anecdotes under
the heading Hall of Stupid Customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Disgruntled Ex-Burger King Employees page
(www.geocities.com/capitolhill/lobby/2645) caters to an apparent
legion of former Burger King employees seeking solace. The site's
manifesto begins: ``My pain runs deep. My acne has never left my
face.'' It is large, somewhat frightening and has a message board
and mailing list, with sections like the Evil Customer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
