<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-DIMSUM-BOOK-REVIEW-AR     08-24 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMSUM-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIM SUM': YES, HOMEMADE DIM SUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The very thought of preparing dim sum from scratch stops most
home cooks before they start. All that painstaking slicing,
chopping, wrapping, steaming and frying, just to produce six or
eight of these assorted Chinese dumplings and other tidbits, often
served for brunch, usually leads to one thing: opting to let a
restaurant cook these tasty morsels for you.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dim Sum: The Essential Kitchen'' by Vicki Liley (Periplus
Editions, $17.95) changed my mind. Once the marketing was done,
including a side trip to an Asian grocery for wonton, I was able to
whip up six dishes in about an hour. The payoff? An impressive and
delicious array of hot appetizers for four people.
</P>
<P>
   It did take planning, though. A pork fillet had to marinate
overnight in hoisin, garlic, five-spice powder, soy sauce and
sugar. It went into the oven first, and in the half-hour it took to
roast, I made a spinach stuffing for dumplings, assembled an oyster
sauce for blanched bok choy and simmered a black bean sauce for
steamed clams. When the pork was done, I tossed shiitake mushroom
caps in a soy and sesame marinade and broiled them. Then, I
stir-fried squid with garlic and chilies, and steamed the
dumplings. None of these tasks required a cooking school education,
just the ability to watch two pots at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The spinach and ginger dumplings were a breeze, with four
quickly stir-fried ingredients going into wonton wrappers sealed
with a quick twist at the top, without elaborate pleating. But the
instructions should have specified putting the spinach mixture in a
strainer first to drain off excess liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ms. Liley's recipes, like deep-fried stuffed crab claws,
sauteed shrimp pancake rolls, and steamed lotus leaves filled with
sticky rice, chicken, shrimp, sausage and seasonings, present a
daunting list of ingredients and demand an afternoon's
concentration. Others, like salmon beggar's purses, are more
creative than what you may find on the carts in a dim sum palace.
</P>
<P>
   The book gives advice on serving dim sum and tea _ never serve
sugar and milk with the tea _ and on what place settings are best
with what dishes. Beautiful photographs accompany each recipe,
though the ones for shrimp balls and clams in black bean sauce were
reversed. But unfortunately the names of most of the dishes are
given only in English, not in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   You get much more help with Chinese names and pronunciations in
``Have Some Dim Sum'' by Evelyn Chau (Hushion House, $19.95). While
Ms. Liley's book is definitely for the home cook, this book is
meant for restaurant-goers. It provides the name of each dish in
Chinese _ with a guide to pronunciation _ and in English, and gives
a good description of each one, but has fewer photographs. It is
clearly organized, grouping steamed, fried and sweet dim sum
dishes, with a small section of specialties like tripe and congee,
a hot rice porridge.
</P>
<P>
   The history of dim sum, which is thought to date from the Tang
dynasty (A.D. 618 to 906), is explained, along with how the various
dishes are served, when to use dipping sauces and what you have to
know about the tea-drinking protocols. (Tipping the lid of the tea
pot alerts the server to refill it.)
</P>
<P>
   Recipes, many of which rely on chicken bouillon powder, a
shortcut ingredient, are included for only about a third of the
dishes. In general, the recipes here are not as appealing as those
in Ms. Liley's book. The steamed spare ribs in black bean sauce,
one of very few dishes that were in both books, were a bit gummy
and not as well seasoned as the ribs made according to the recipe
in ``Dim Sum: The Essential Kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIZZLED MUSHROOMS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Dim Sum: The Essential Kitchen''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   13 ounces shiitake mushrooms, preferably medium-large, stems
discarded
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mirin (Japanese cooking wine)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra fine granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons black sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler. Line a baking sheet with foil, and brush
with oil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place mushrooms in a shallow dish. Mix soy sauce, mirin,
sugar and 3 teaspoons chives together, and pour over mushrooms,
turning them to coat well. Allow to marinate 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Arrange mushrooms on baking sheet, and broil very close to
source of heat about 3 minutes on each side, until softened and
lightly browned. Brush with marinade during broiling.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer mushrooms to a serving dish or 4 individual bowls,
and sprinkle with sesame seeds and remaining chives. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
