<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, Aug. 25. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Shanghai) _ Chinese authorities announced on Tuesday
that they are preparing to prosecute top leaders of Falun Gong, a
signal that China has reached the final stage of its broadest
political mobilization campaign in a decade. Falun Gong, a
spiritual movement of more than 20 million members that badly
spooked China's leaders with its ability to organize potent
anti-government protests, was banned last month as the Communist
Party galvanized its vast apparatus in a sweeping crackdown aimed
at snuffing out political dissent. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ACCORD (Nairobi, Kenya) _ The peace process in Congo took
a major step forward on Tuesday when two rival rebel factions
agreed to sign a cease-fire document already approved by other
combatants in the yearlong civil war. But like almost everything
else about the war, the compromise between the two groups is
decidedly complex. Rather than have two or three rebel leaders sign
the peace document, as originally envisioned, the compromise calls
for some 50 rebel officials from all three rebel groups to sign. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul) _ In the wake of last week's earthquake,
even major issues like the Kurdish conflict have been blown off the
national agenda. Debate over the government's proposal to offer
amnesty to guerrillas who surrender, for example, has been
postponed indefinitely. And although Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
had announced his support for large investments to combat poverty
and unemployment in the mostly Kurdish southeast, there will
probably be no money to pay for such programs now. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ANCIENT-BODY (Whitehorse) _ Scientists announce finding
the body of a frozen hunter that may be 5,000 years old. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EXTRADITE (Washington) _ A Maryland teenager who has been
the subject of a 17-month extradition battle between the United
States and Israel has agreed to plead guilty to murder and accept a
24-year prison sentence in Israel, state prosecutors in Maryland
announced on Tuesday. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHAT-ROOM-SYPHILIS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco health
officials, tracking an outbreak of syphilis cases, found that as
many as 99 men met each other on the same AOL chat room, then had
sex, perhaps infecting each other. Although people have met each
other for sex on the Internet before, this is the first big cluster
of sexual activity that started in cyberspace and has now been
documented to have lead to an outbreak of sexually transmitted
disease. One man had as many as 47 partners. Many of the men knew
each other only by made-up chatroom names and the health department
is using the Internet to track them down. In addition, some of the
men are HIV positive. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Federal Reserve policy makers meet and
raise rates one-quarter of a point. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
