<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CNN-KAPLAN25-COX     08-24 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-KAPLAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changing News Network: Kaplans take on CNN
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The view from Rick Kaplan's office, six stories above the CNN
Center atrium, is somewhat Godlike. From the window near his desk,
he can look down on the CNN newsroom (he spear-headed the redesign)
and the anchor desk (he booted some people out, elevated others).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's omnipresent,'' says morning anchor Daryn Kagan, one of
those who has flourished under Kaplan's reign. ``He's very
hands-on. It's not like some far-away executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, 52, has been president of CNN/US for two years, a tenure
that has seen the Operation Tailwind debacle, intensive coverage of
the Columbine High School shootings, the war in Yugoslavia and the
impeachment proceedings of President Clinton; the launch (and soon
the re-launch) of ``NewsStand''; and controversy, gossip and
sometimes division within the ranks of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's modification of CNN rolls on, with the biggest plans
still to come. On Sept. 13, the network will unveil a new version
of ``The World Today,'' a title it has already been using, as an 8
p.m. hourlong newscast it intends to be definitive. Larry King will
continue at 9 p.m. (the slot is essentially his as long as he wants
it), and then the revamped ``NewsStand'' will move back to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes for daytime hours, rolling out in September and
October, will turn the network more toward finanical and business
news, which Kaplan says have assumed a priority in viewers' minds
that the Cold War once had.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the changes Kaplan has wrought inside CNN _ the
corporate culture, the way it works _ have been more significant
than what appears on the air. Some longtime CNN veterans haven't
liked it; some acknowledge, grudgingly or enthusiastically, that he
has made the newsroom sharper. Executive producers have more power
(and pressure), anchors come in earlier and do more reporting, and
there's more centralized planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an organization that has conquered the world,'' says
Kaplan, an out-sized presence at 6-foot-7, ``and when you want to
change it, some people will get their back up and say `That's not
the way we do it.' I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I think I've gotten past the point where I need a
food-taster.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the concerns of CNN employees aren't necessarily
directed at Kaplan. The merger of CNN and Time Warner Inc., which
was finalized 10 months before Kaplan was hired, but which has had
fallout ever since, changed some of the ways CNN employees view
their workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Before, many CNN employees had the sense that they worked for
Ted Turner personally; one occasional refrain was that Turner ``may
be an s.o.b., but he's our s.o.b.'' Now, staffers who considered
themselves close to Turner note that he rarely just walks through
the newsroom any more to say hello. They feel as if they work for a
corporation headquartered in New York, which they do, rather than
one whose heart is in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan himself recognizes the issue, a combination of regional
pride and scrappiness; he refers to CNN as formerly being known as
``this Chicken Noodle Network down here in the South'' that ``beats
up regularly on those Yankees up North,'' meaning the network
competition. The irony is that Kaplan is a Yankee (a Chicago native
who worked for years in New York City) who came to CNN from ABC
News. The man who hired him, CNN News Group Chairman Tom Johnson,
is a Macon native and University of Georgia grad. In some ways,
Kaplan is a result of changes at CNN as much as he is the cause of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are being driven in large part by a need for stable
ratings, which means getting viewers to habitually tune in even
when there is no major news event. While other cable networks are
enjoying unprecedented ratings growth, CNN continues to be a
network of peaks (big news events) and valleys (the rest of the
time).
</P>
<P>
   Enormous graphs hang in hallways in the executive suites showing
CNN's ratings spikes for the Persian Gulf War, the O.J. Simpson
trial, etc., but those graphs don't hang in Kaplan's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually detest those graphs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fall is probably crucial, the major test,'' says Larry
Gerbrandt, a cable analyst for the media research firm Paul Kagan
and Associates. ``These are probably the biggest changes we've seen
so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8 p.m. ``World Today,'' anchored by Wolf Blitzer (who's
first among equals), Joie Chen and Jim Moret will be what Kaplan is
calling ``our flagship program, the place where we expect CNN to
makes its statement about the news.'' The big guns are being
readied: Christiane Amanpour will appear, as often as possible,
from whatever international trouble spot she's in, and Jeff
Greenfield will offer analysis and finally find a home for his
tongue-in-cheek ``Looking Glass'' essays.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger change will be at 10 p.m., where ``NewsStand'' moves
to five nights a week. Instead of being anchored to a specific
magazine such as ``Fortune'' or ``Entertainment Weekly,'' the
newsmagazine will start off with breaking news and then run a mix
of magazine-style segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the news of the moment is going to take up the whole
hour of 'NewsStand,' and sometimes the news of the moment might
only take up the first couple of minutes,'' Kaplan says.
</P>
<P>
   The change was necessary because CNN was frequently having to
pre-empt ``NewsStand'' for breaking news, ranging from the war in
Yugoslavia to the death of John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best way to look at Kaplan's first two years running
CNN/US is as a balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In his favor:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The news. Two years ago, most anchors were essentially
news-readers with little input; now they're more involved, and are
considered to be reporters (Kagan was first on the scene for CNN at
the Buckhead shootings in July, reporting via her cell phone).
Video footage was repeated frequently during the day; those repeats
have been cut back. When CNN isn't in what Kaplan calls ``rolling
coverage'' (such as the search for JFK Jr.'s plane), it usually
packs more news into 24 hours than it used to.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The newsroom. The $7.5 million re-built newsroom and anchor
set, unveiled last October, certainly gives CNN a much sleeker and
classier on-air look. It also alleviated the feeling journalists
had in the old newsroom of being ``15 pounds in a 10-pound bag,''
as Turner Properties project manager Chuck Burleson put it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jeff Greenfield. Kaplan, a former ABC News executive producer,
brought Greenfield from ABC to CNN, and both have benefitted.
Greenfield gets much more air time, and CNN has an analyst who is
thoughtful, fresh, and free of the easy, off-the-cuff soundbites
that are the life's blood of so many commentators on TV (including
CNN).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His temper. Or lack of it. At ABC, Kaplan was legendary for
being a rough taskmaster with a tendency to sometimes berate
others. He's still nobody's idea of a softie, but when the staff
gossips, it's not about Kaplan eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cash flow. CNN's cash flow (revenue minus certain costs, such
as interest) is climbing, according to analyst Gerbrandt. After
being flat in 1998 at $276 million, Gerbrandt says, CNN's cash flow
will rise this year to about $310 million and is projected to rise
in 2000 to about $363 million. ``If that's the scorecard for
Kaplan, he's definitely ahead,'' says Gerbrandt.
</P>
<P>
   And on the negative side of the Kaplan balance sheet:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Operation Tailwind. The blackest mark against CNN ever, this
story alleging U.S. soldiers used sarin nerve gas in Laos in 1970
led to a retraction, an apology and lawsuits for millions of
dollars that are still pending. Two producers were fired and one
executive resigned, but many staffers blamed Kaplan, because the
Tailwind story ran on the premiere of ``NewsStand,'' which he had
created and championed. At stormy meetings, CNN staffers vented
against Kaplan, and resentment still simmers among some that Kaplan
was never held responsible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``NewsStand.'' Kaplan intended this newsmagazine to be
``appointment television,'' but it never has been. Although there
was some solid journalism, CNN kept having to pre-empt it. ``It's
my fault,'' Kaplan now says. ``I tell people unashamedly that I
learned a lot. When you have a news program that has to be
pre-empted for news, you have to sit back and say, 'There's
something wrong with the way we're set up here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Division in the newsroom. There is still a strong sense of
``ins'' and ``outs'' within CNN. Many long-time veterans are
particularly anti-Kaplan, and view him as someone who is too
ratings-oriented, who is making CNN too slick and packaged, too
much like ABC, CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Even the nature of newsroom gossip has changed. Before Kaplan,
gossip tended to be personal: Who was in rehab, who was sleeping
with whom. Now it tends to be professional, sometimes with a
paranoid edge: Who's climbing the ladder, and who's fingers are
getting stepped on?
</P>
<P>
   CNN staffers in bureaus, such as New York, Los Angeles and
Washington, D.C., monitor the intense rumor level at CNN with some
bemusement. Greenfield, who's based in New York, allows that
journalists are perhaps worse gossips than some other professions,
but says he's seen it at other networks and in government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest on-again, off-again rumor at CNN has apparently
finally died. For a year after Operation Tailwind, Kaplan was
repeatedly rumored to be on the way out _ forced to resign or
fired. Then in June, Lou Dobbs _ longtime anchor, CNNfn president
and close friend of Ted Turner _ resigned suddenly after clashing
with Kaplan. Almost everyone inside CNN saw it as more than just a
victory for Kaplan _ that by vanquishing the well-connected Dobbs,
Kaplan's power base was more secure than anyone else's at the
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I subscribe to Harry Chapin,'' Kaplan says, citing the '70s
singer-songwriter. ``It's the going, not the getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and CNN may still be going through some changes in the
future, but in terms of sealing his hold on the network's future,
he's gotten there.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
