A8047 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DESIGNER-DINNER26-COX     08-24 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-DINNER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dinner for 600? No problem, when designers set the table
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next time you want to wow your dinner guests,
forget the Wedgwood, the sterling, the roses.
</P>
<P>
   Try a chandelier that's painted hot pink. A vine-shrouded arbor
that seats 10. A lush carpet of wheat grass. A gurgling fountain
for a centerpiece. Instead of candles, how about a fog generator to
create an air of mystery and romance? And the music? No need to
hire a musician _ just position a model in the center of the table
for live entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Sound far out? You bet. But those ideas are among the bag of
tricks used by 43 Atlanta designers who know how to send a table
over the top, especially when they're competing for the attention
of 600 dinner guests _ and especially when it's for a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   The tables will be unveiled during Collection Rouge III: Dining
by Design, set for Monday at the Woodruff Arts Center to benefit
the Atlanta chapter of the nonprofit Design Industries Foundation
Fighting AIDS. Unlike other tabletop events, this one allows guests
to actually dine on the elaborate displays and mingle to check out
all the displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our favorite thing to do as far as charities go
because we get to be creative and do exactly what we want,''
interior designer Wendy Edwards said. ``It's so much fun to walk
around and see what everyone else has done, and that makes it not
stuffy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the creations by designers working in the
interiors, fashion, floral and hair industries will be two
tabletops by New York designers that are traveling to eight cities
where DIFFA chapters are sponsoring similar benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A new twist this year is 10 traveling champagne buckets
(Champagne Mumm is the national sponsor) that have been decorated
by or for national celebrities and will be raffled off at the end
of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Another 25 buckets will be filled with prizes by local artists,
designers and retailers and sold during a silent auction.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsorships of tables as well as the $300 tickets to
the event, which sold out three months ago, benefit local AIDS
organizations. Last year, more than $150,000 was raised, said Carey
Carter, the 1999 chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For designers, the rules are simple: Their displays must fit a
72-inch round table, accommodate 10 guests and contain something
red, a color associated with the fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a taste of what designers are planning:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Glorious gardens: The heat index may still be high, but guests
can enjoy the great outdoors inside the Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Long Flora Design is creating an intimate garden setting,
placed under an arbor in tribute to Madame Pompadour. ``Instead of
using a carpet, we're having a French carpet faux-painted on a
raised platform,'' Long said. Under the glasstop table, however,
the designer is ``planting'' wheat grass. And just for fun, Long's
attaching oversize pompadour wigs to the backs of the chairs.
``It'll look like you're sitting under a big hair dryer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Events, caterers for the affair, is creating a garden
oasis amid the room's sea of red displays with an all-green table
placed in a vineyard setting. Strawberries will provide the dash of
red, designer Teresa Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing draws attention like the sound of water, and Atlanta
Water Gardens had guests gushing at last year's table with its
6-foot-tall copper fountain. This year, owner David Robinson plans
a modern encore, set in an Asian garden filled with tropicals and
with mist floating over the table.
</P>
<P>
   For a touch of whimsy, garden designer Brooks Garcia is up to
some monkey business under a tent filled with tropical fruits and
flowers and decorative monkeys dressed in red waistcoats, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rooms totow: When table coordinator John Williams says
designers have gone over the top, he's not just talking about the
look of their displays. Many have requested ``vertical space'' for
creating entire rooms _ some under tents and canopies, others as
free-standing structures.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stewart has developed a 12-foot-high ``hot weather
pavilion'' with a beamed roof, columns and chandelier made of
branches, all painted hot pink.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Zuber of Corporate Environments is moving his guests
into a living room set on a platform. ``We're passionately
recalling the 20th-century cocktail hour by camping it up with a
bar from the '50s and classic modern furniture such as Knoll,'' he
said. The room also will include television monitors showing
footage of '50s propaganda and films such as ``Breakfast at
Tiffany's.'' Guests are asked to dress as '50s stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saluting the centuries: Futuristic technology and time in
general are sure to factor heavily in this year's themes.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Miner secured permission to seat 12 at his table so that he
could create the face of a clock, with Roman numerals placed inside
each plate. A lamp, instead of flowers, will claim the centerpiece,
from which clock hands made of lightweight balsa wood will extend.
``It's kind of goofy but kind of different, too,'' Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vantosh can identify. She and associate Patrick Delaney
have come up with a Y2K theme. Under each end of their table will
be metal restaurant-style shelves stocked ``with things you've been
hearing and reading you'll need during this outburst of fear
they're predicting _ flashlights, money, potatoes, powdered milk,
bottled water _ and, of course, plenty of champagne,'' Vantosh
said. ``We're really trying to keep it pretty simple.''
</P>
<P>
   At this event? Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   THE TABLE DESIGNERSAtlanta Water Gardens
</P>
