<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE26-COX     08-24 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A mystery crops up in `best garden ever'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like a fine professor for life, the garden never stops
teaching. Everlina R. Jackson grew one of the more surprising
lessons in her southwest Atlanta space.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, as in some 30 previous springs, Jackson planted
food, including pepper, corn, beans, cabbage, beets, squash,
cucumbers. And ``Irish'' potatoes. She bought the white eating
potatoes from the store, cut out the eyes and planted them _ one
per hill, or mound. ``I've done that before,'' she said recently,
referring to that pleasing practice of getting fresh vegetables or
fruits and finding ways to plant them.
</P>
<P>
   (I have enjoyed buying lemon grass from the farmers market and
putting the plant, bulb intact, in the ground _ where it grows
strap leaves lush and aromatic, recalling the incomparable taste of
a good Thai soup.)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson planted the potato eyes in what she called her ``best
garden ever. One to remember.'' The potatoes ``bloomed so pretty,''
Jackson recalled. ``White blooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day, as she went out to dig up some of the potatoes,
``I saw those little things on them, looking like tomatoes, green
cherry tomatoes. I just couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The strange growth _ let's call it ``pomato'' _ puzzled
everybody, including friends, neighbors, her husband, Willie F.
Jackson, and her daughter, Notosha Wilson. During a visit to
Detroit, Jackson mentioned her surprising crop, and people there
were as amazed as Jackson was. As amazed as I was when I saw the
pictures and heard the description.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``Everybody I told about it said, `I didn't know
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   I got the same reaction _ until I told Wayne McLaurin, professor
of horticulture at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aren't tomatoes,'' he said. ``They're seedpods.''
</P>
<P>
   Seedpods that go around fooling people into thinking they're
green tomatoes growing on potato vines are old fruit to McLaurin.
``I get a number of telephone calls about them every year,'' he
said, adding that, ``We have seen a number of these this year''
because the relatively cool spring was conducive to their growth.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1970s, when he was studying at Louisiana State
University, McLaurin became expert in the ways of potatoes, quickly
learning that the little round fruit tastes nothing like the
seductively sweet cherry tomato it imitates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a bitter taste to it,'' said McLaurin, explaining
that a poisonous alkaloid called solanine is concentrated in the
seedpods. Alas, yet another sweet surprise that turns out to be a
bitter disappointment. Eat enough of these pods, and you could get
sick, but, fortunately, the unpleasant taste would stop you _ if
you got past the green color.
</P>
<P>
   While the pods aren't edible, they are plantable. Cut them open,
and you'll find a lot of seeds, which can be sown in the early
spring. The resulting potatoes will be smaller, said McLaurin, but
beyond that there's no telling what you'll grow: ``You might get
whites and reds. Goodness only knows. It's like a Christmas
package.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be just fine with Jackson, who welcomed McLaurin's
analysis with calm interest. ``I had never seen it before, and I
had never heard of it,'' she said of the ``pomato,'' ``but if it
happens like that again, I'm going to plant those seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yet another lesson will grow in her garden.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
