<HEADER>
A8049 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-THEME-TABLE26-COX     08-24 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-TABLE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secrets to tackling a theme table
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 26.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the thought of developing a dinner party theme
seems as mind-boggling _ and expensive _ as buying your first home,
professional event planners have news for you: It doesn't have to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just be different. Be daring,'' said Tony Conway of Legendary
Events, an Atlanta catering company.
</P>
<P>
   Once you allow your mind to reach beyond the predictable, beyond
the so-called rules of entertaining, you'll discover ideas that can
result in creative and inexpensive tabletops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to turn to yourself and see what you already have at
home,'' said David Tutera, a New York event designer who often
works in Atlanta. ``A lot of hosts have more than they think when
it comes to linens and fabrics.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Tutera and Conway, along with partner Teresa Day, are among
the designers creating tabletop displays for Monday's Collection
Rouge III: Dining by Design, a benefit for the Design Industries
Foundation Fighting AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming up with a theme, you need to think about it for a
few minutes, then step away from the idea and think of the most
unrelated things about it,'' Tutera said. ``Think of the least
obvious, go with the understated.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 tips shared by the pros:
</P>
<P>
   1. Clean up the garage: If you're looking for space for a large
dinner party and don't want to rent a hall, consider the garage.
``Clear it out and set up four or five tables with lots of
candles,'' Conway said. ``For any room that's boring, play up the
table and make it wow. Spend money on the table, not the decor.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Try unusual table sizes: Most homeowners have rectangular
tables. Conway suggests renting two 3-foot-by-6-foot tables and
placing them together to form a square, a shape more conducive to
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   3. Think beyond linens: Tablecloths are difficult to find for
large tables, so consider other coverings, such as inexpensive
12-inch-square ceramic tile placed over felt. Another option is to
cover a plywood tabletop with wallpaper or fabric, Day said.
</P>
<P>
   4. Edgy appeal: Instead of using table skirting, Day recommends
buying 54-inch-wide fabric that picks up the colors in the room and
attaching the fabric to the table's edge.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mix 'n' match fabrics: Don't be afraid to use more than one
fabric and pattern. Mix florals and checks that have common colors.
Old shawls and throws also can be used. Day crisscrosses linens to
add depth to a table and dresses up the corners by attaching
ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   6. Color wheels: Bring a balance to a riot of color on the table
by repeating one of the colors in the candles, napkins or plate
chargers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   7. Flower power: Flowers can be the table's greatest expense,
but they don't have to be. Homeowners often can collect cuttings
from their yard. ``Or you can go with a sleek look by using four or
five cylinder vases down the center of the table, all at one
height, and place one stem in each one,'' Tutera said.
</P>
<P>
   8. Lighting the way: Sometimes groups of candles can make a
centerpiece. Try small, inexpensive candles with lampshades, Day
suggests, or place an old lamp in the table's center.
</P>
<P>
   9. Collecting ideas: Use personal collections _ dolls,
figurines, old books _ to create a theme. If you don't have any,
raid the thrift stores and flea markets. ``Make a table eclectic by
using things that don't match,'' Tutera said. ``You can literally
buy 10 cheap place settings and make a table look like it was
designed that way.'' Glue pieces of inexpensive costume jewelry
onto napkin rings, which also make fun keepsakes for guests, Conway
said.
</P>
<P>
   10. Don't overdo it: Details make a theme and create
conversation. But while your imagination's running wild, don't
clutter a table. ``Maintain a few strong focal points,'' Day said,
``and stick to the theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
