<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBC-BERKELEY-BEARS-HN     08-24 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BERKELEY-BEARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY TEAM HAS NIGERIAN CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ There's already talk of a poster _ football
players in blue and gold posing under a banner reading: ``The
Nigerian Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably won't happen until these proud young men have
played in a game or two.
</P>
<P>
   This year's football team at the University of California at
Berkeley includes five new players _ four freshmen and one
sophomore transfer _ with deep roots in Nigeria. They join junior
starting cornerback Chidi Iwuoma in giving the Bears six
Nigerian-American players. Just two were born in Africa but all
were raised by Nigerian-born parents in a culture that values
education, family, religion and unity. Five are members of
Nigeria's Ibo ethnic group and one belongs to the Tiv ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   The team runs from drill to drill at practice. Iwuoma will trot
over and say ``stay strong'' when he spots one of the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always told me that when you see another Ibo you
take care of them,'' Iwuoma said.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in speech, appearance or dress that sets the
Ibos or the lone Tiv, freshman running back Joe Igber of Honolulu,
apart from their teammates. They are typical young Americans,
distinguished by their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our family is, you always have to work really hard at
what you do,'' said freshman running back Joseph Echema of
Hawthorne, in Southern California. ``I try to live up to that
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen, to a man, were recruited by major football
programs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman defensive tackle Daniel Nwangwu of Sugar Land, Texas,
chose UC-Berkeley over Colorado, Kansas, Baylor and Northwestern.
The decision delighted his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my dad being Nigerian, education is a very important
thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Echema, his parents only wanted him to attend one of two
schools _ UC-Berkeley or Stanford University in Palo Alto _ because
of the academics.
</P>
<P>
   When freshman safety Nnamdi Asomugha of Harbor City, in Southern
California, began getting letters from football coaches, his mother
got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom values education so much that she sorted through the
mail,'' he said. She made two piles, schools with excellent
academic credentials and a second with all the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd throw in the football part,'' Asomugha said. ``She didn't
even look at football.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Asomugha has been through this before. An older brother,
Chijioke Asomugha, is a second-year cornerback at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Asomugha was considered a top prospect, a
blue-chipper, and his recruiting was followed across the country. A
sports Web site persuaded him to announce his decision over the
Internet, where he accepted UC-Berkeley's offer and turned down
Colorado, Michigan, Notre Dame and the University of Southern
California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his mother's early involvement, Asomugha made the
decision alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``She set the standard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nwangwu made the decision alone, with some strong guidelines
from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me to know the reasons why I did what I did,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line coach Bill Dutton remembers going to Texas to
recruit Nwangwu. He said the family met in the sitting area of his
hotel room, with the father sitting across from Dutton and four
children seated to his right in descending order of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask the recruit a question and he would look over at
his dad for acknowledgement. Only then would he speak,'' Dutton
said. ``I'm his dad now and he gives me that same total respect.
He's a beautiful kid to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton said he wasn't concerned that Nwangwu might be too ``nice
and polite'' for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will he dig down and gut-bucket?'' Dutton said. ``Oh yeah,
darn right he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Igber and Echema were born in Nigeria. The others and the sixth
team member with Nigerian roots, senior starting defensive end
Mawuko Tugbenyoh, were born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Holmoe said the Nigerian connection occurred
``coincidentally'' and was not planned.
</P>
<P>
   However, he acknowledged that he was delighted with the strong
values the new players brought to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these guys there is a standard that is set,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
