<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SPALDEEN-BALL-NYT &LR;      08-24 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPALDEEN-BALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SPALDEEN BRINGS BACK THE MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This column is about a ball, the most special ball ever
invented. It's better than a baseball, basketball or a football.
It's better than any ball you can name. And although it's been gone
for 20 years, it's finally making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It is called a Spaldeen, which may not mean anything to you
unless you grew up on the East Coast, preferably New York, before
1979. I grew up in Brooklyn in the '50s and '60s, which means my
childhood memories are filled with Spaldeens.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some background. Starting in the 1920s, the Spalding Co.
manufactured tennis balls from its home base in Chicopee, Mass. But
there would be overruns, which means there wasn't enough of the
fuzzy stuff they attach to the outside of tennis balls. Some
anonymous genius _ and I use that word genius with reverence _ got
the bright idea to market the bright pink unused rubber cores as
the ``Spalding High-Bounce Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Because New York people don't talk so good, they pronounced
Spalding as Spaldeen _ ``Hey, Joey, you wanna play? I got a
Spaldeen.''
</P>
<P>
   Spalding would box the Spaldeens and ship them down to New York
where kids would buy them for a quarter apiece. And my God, when
you bought a brand new Spaldeen, the aroma alone would cause
ecstasy _ it was the smell of Bazooka bubble gum and summer and
childhood and joy and hope.
</P>
<P>
   And then you would go out and play. All those legendary New York
street games began and ended with Spaldeens. I'm talking about
games you've heard about but probably never played _ stickball,
punchball, stoopball, hit the penny and a million others. When it
came to inventing games with a Spaldeen, the only limit was your
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   You understand that we didn't have baseball fields or any other
kinds of fields. We played ball in playgrounds, really slabs of
concrete surrounded by a Cyclone fence, or we played in the street
using sewer covers as the bases.
</P>
<P>
   And the virtue of a Spaldeen, besides the fact that you could
whack it a mile, was it didn't break things. You hit Mrs. Samson's
Olds 88 with a Spaldeen, no big deal. No broken glass. No broken
mirror. No broken nothin'. Of course, Mrs. Samson would come
running down her steps screaming, ``I'm gonna tell your motha.''
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, I apologize, Mrs. Samson, wherever you
are.
</P>
<P>
   I mostly played in the park on the corner of Avenue L and East
18th Street. It was called the park but it never had a tree I ever
saw. And every kid would come to the park with a Spaldeen in his
back pocket. If someone had a stick, we'd play stickball. The stick
was an old broom handle or a dowel from the closet. We'd draw a box
on the wall and pitch to it, and if the batter hit it over the
fence it was a homer.
</P>
<P>
   We'd play handball with the Spaldeen, and sometimes we'd go to a
friend's house for stoopball. A kid would throw the ball at the
steps in front of someone's house, and as the ball sailed back
you'd try to catch it on a fly. If it bounced once it was a single,
twice a double, etc.
</P>
<P>
   But the king of Spaldeen games all over New York City was
punchball. You'd toss the ball over your head. You'd swing down
overhand as if you were serving a tennis ball. And then you'd punch
it with your closed fist. Guys could hit it 200 feet, long fly
balls that never came down. And there the puncher would be running
around the bases, actually painted squares on the park's grimy
concrete, while the outfielders ran like hell after the Spaldeen.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest punchball player I ever saw was Ronnie Salmonson,
who could punch the ball to Queens. At least it seemed he could. He
was a legend and now he's a dentist on Long Island, but he still
signs his e-mails, ``The punchball champion of Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spaldeen Era ended in 1979 when Spalding switched its
tennis-ball operation to Taiwan. An entire tradition wiped out just
like that. All those baby boomers forced to go cold turkey with
Spaldeen withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. The ball-playing public did not take this lying
down. It sent a constant flow of letters and e-mails to Spalding:
``Where can I get a Spaldeen? You're robbing me of my memories.''
</P>
<P>
   And get this, Spalding relented last January and began issuing
the Spaldeen as its own product, not as a byproduct of tennis
balls. New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is so excited by this
development he's organized a stickball tournament throughout the
five boroughs, the finals to be played in front of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who's a cost-cutting guy, wanted to know how come a
Spaldeen now costs two bucks. ``Why isn't it still a quarter?'' he
asked Chris Waldeck of Spalding. To which Waldeck replied, ``Mr.
Mayor, why isn't the subway still a quarter?''
</P>
<P>
   Waldeck told me Spaldeens will be sold nationwide. In June, I
tried to buy one in Brooklyn. I took my son along and told him all
about Spaldeens while I lied about how far I could punch one. But
no store I went to had a Spaldeen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're supposed to be reissuing Spaldeens,'' I said to one
shop owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I hoid about dat,'' he replied, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Waldeck assures me demand is outstripping production, but
Spalding will catch up soon. I hope so.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
