<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: FOR `MILLIONAIRE,' THE QUESTION IS WHAT NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' now in its
second week of broadcasts, is the talk of the television world this
summer. It has surpassed the status of mere hit to emerge as a
national phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The show on Sunday drew its largest audience yet, 15 million
viewers, more than for any other show on television in the last
weekly rating period.
</P>
<P>
   Now ABC executives are playing the role of contestants at their
own high-stakes game. What do they do with the show, which is
scheduled to end this week? The question has multiple-choice
answers and there is big, big money _ a lot more than $1 million _
riding on the right selection.
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready, ABC? At a time when prime-time ratings are down
almost everywhere in broadcast television, you have a summer show
that has built on its audience every night for more than one week
straight. How best to capitalize on its potential?
</P>
<P>
   A) Make it a weekly show: throw it into prime time as quickly as
possible and guarantee yourself a new Top 10-rated series for this
television season.
</P>
<P>
   B) Keep it as an occasional, enormously promotable event: Maybe
bring it back every ratings-sweep month, three times a year for
two-week bursts at a time. That is the way it has been done in
Britain, where ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' originated, and it
has been bigger each time it has been broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   C) Make it a three-or-four-times-a-week like NBC's ``Dateline''
or ABC's ``20/20'': that way you can take better advantage of the
suspense that builds when a contestant gets a roll going.
</P>
<P>
   D) Keep it as a summer show: that way it would face weaker
competition and can thrive as a steady source of ratings amid the
repeats.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the show's finale scheduled this Sunday at 8:30 p.m.,
ABC has to face that question. And to borrow another catchword from
the show, the network may look for a lifeline by conducting
research to see how an audience that supports the show would like
it to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a deceptively simple trivia quiz in which
contestants answer questions of escalating difficulty for rapidly
increasing amounts of money. Most critics have called the show's
concept intriguing, especially for its novel introduction of the
so-called lifelines, in which contestants can get help on answers.
Several critics have pointed out that the show has a style that
seems to have come straight from the 1950s, the last time game
shows were hits in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   That it will continue is now a given. Michael Davies, the
executive producer, said he had already been told to keep his staff
on the payroll. He is also on the hunt for a new studio, because,
he said, the current studio looks as if it will not be available
for an early comeback. ``I'd be shocked if it wasn't back on as
soon as the fall,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   That may mean a return in November, the season's first
ratings-sweep month, or, he said, ``We might be back as soon as
October.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Davies himself, who was so confident that the show would be a
hit that he quit his job as a vice president for alternative
programming at ABC to become the show's executive producer, said he
was torn about the choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back and forth from a position saying we should keep it
as an event to a position saying we should strike while the iron is
hot and go for something regular in prime time right away, maybe
like the `20/20' format, a few times a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davies pointed out that in Britain the show had adapted itself
to certain events, putting on special editions like a
movie-oriented version geared to the British version of the Oscars
and a sports version geared to the soccer finals.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that ABC owned the rights to the Oscar broadcast and to
the Super Bowl this year, making it an ideal year for specially
tailored editions of his game.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The show's host, Regis Philbin, who auditioned for the job
aggressively once he had seen the British version, said he was
totally committed to sticking with the show no matter what format
it followed in the future. But he added: ``I think we need to be on
successive nights. I don't think we should be a once-a-week show. I
think having at least a hour on Sunday night would be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies said there were elements he would tinker with whenever he
brought the show back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to simplify the phone-in format,'' he said of the
first round, in which contestants at home qualify by answering
questions over the phone. He said he also wanted to devise a fair
way to diversify the contestants. The show has featured mainly men;
only two female finalists have played the game on its first eight
editions and on several nights the entire roster of 10 potential
contestants were men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd also like to see more minority representation,'' Davies
said. The contestants have all been white. ``Maybe the skew of the
material has been geared to white males, I'm not sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ultimate plan, Davies said: ``I want to be doing
this the rest of my life. There's no doubt about that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   SWITCHING CHANNELS
</P>
<P>
   By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Some couch potatoes showed that they were eager for the new
season to begin. On Monday night, UPN was the first broadcast
network out of the starting gate, kicking off its 1999-2000 season
and attracting, by UPN standards, quite a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The UPN season began with ``Moesha,'' the family comedy starring
Brandy, at 8 p.m. (moved from Tuesdays), followed by a new sitcom
starring Jaleel White, ``Grown-Ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is its fifth season, ``Moesha'' showed no sign of
fading in favor, at least on its opening night. The first episode,
in which Moesha takes an entry-level job at Vibe magazine instead
of going to college, earned a 4.4 overnight rating (a Nielsen
measure taken in the nation's larger cities; each rating point
equals 598,000 homes) and 7 share (percentage of homes watching
television tuned to that show), which was 10 percent better than
the numbers for last year's season premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown-Ups'' did even better, attracting a 4.9 overnight rating
and an 8 share, UPN's best overnight numbers since April 1998 and
virtually double the audience that UPN averaged for that time slot
(8:30 p.m. Mondays) in the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a veteran series to debut in a new time period on a new
night and improve, as `Moesha' did, is encouraging,'' said Tom
Nunan, UPN's entertainment president. ``For Jaleel White and
`Grown-Ups' to build on that number is even more encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Berman, who follows Nielsen ratings trends for Mediaweek
Online, said the overnight numbers would probably translate into a
low three rating when the total national numbers are in, which
would be nothing to brag about at ABC, CBS, Fox or NBC, but would
be better than UPN, perennially the sixth-place network, did on
most nights last season. _  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
