<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV31-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POSTER WOMAN FOR LIBERATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Aug. 31)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we celebrate another anniversary of women getting the vote,
we mark a new triumph: that Hollywood has finally paired a
middle-aged heroine with a middle-aged hero and they have great
desktop sex.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder what Susan B. Anthony, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and the
other stalwarts might be thinking. ``All our work and now all you
want is to be a sex object at any age?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a big marker in the advances of women but it is a small
step for womankind that in the summertime hit ``The Thomas Crown
Affair,'' an adult woman gets the man instead of the man getting
the girl.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, with 47-year-old Pierce Bronsan and 45-year-old Rene
Russo, two people who in real life could have gone to high school
together, has sparked headlines such as ``Russo not ashamed to look
45!''
</P>
<P>
   This is equality, 1999 style.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Mary Ruthsdotter from the National Women's History
Project if the suffragists worried much about losing their sex
appeal and she chuckled. ``No, and I don't think they would have
used the term.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they were trying not to have their value tied to men.
When Stanton wanted to rent an assembly hall for a suffragists
meeting her husband had to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, our foremothers didn't march for the right to remain
sexy past the age of 40, or 50 and so on. They were passionate
about larger issues like getting property rights for women, equal
pay for equal work, and access to the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   They might not have foreseen, however, that as women continued
to push for equality, they'd meet a cultural backlash that said go
ahead and advance, but forget the black satin. As women slowly
began to enjoy advantages once held only by men, Hollywood cut a
secret deal. For having to share the perks of life in all other
arenas, men would be granted eternal hunkability. Women might
demonstrate their new-found status in movie roles which had them
being surgeons and scientists, but they wouldn't get to have sex
much past the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   Were Susan B. and the sisters to try to gauge the status of
American women today by how they're portrayed in film and
television, they might wonder what awful plague carried off the
mature women or turned them into background characters in aprons
and bad shoes.
</P>
<P>
   They might wonder why women of such obvious talent as Meryl
Streep and Jessica Lange ended up playing dying mothers and
shrewish spinsters. More important, they might ask the very good
question of why ordinary American women attach their self-esteem to
movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   But then, they wouldn't understand the power of the media today
to bend reality to fantasy and how, in many ways, the celluloid
ceiling has been as hard to crack as the glass one. If the
fantasy-makers say that women over a certain age are has-beens,
real life women take it personally.
</P>
<P>
   Younger has not always been hotter. By the time America
discovered Sarah Bernhardt when she was the world's greatest sex
symbol, she was in her 60s and had a wooden leg.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood is pretty good at propaganda, and for some time
now it's been making women, as Molly Haskell says, the designated
agers. Even highly acclaimed actresses have been getting dumped
just for hitting their 40s and 50s, even though their male
counterparts go on to score.
</P>
<P>
   Romantic roles dry up for women after 40, and Hollywood would
have us believe so do women in general. Real women know this is far
from the truth, just as the idea of the perpetual stud is more
about the Hollywood male ego than the average guy's. But some like
to pretend there's little romance between same-age couples. Sean
Connery enjoyed an enlightened pairing with Gena Rowlands in one
movie but by the next was dating someone's granddaughter. Susan
Sarandon at 51 played a woman with two men in love with her, but
they were both in their 70s. When Anne Bancroft played older woman
to Dustin Hoffman _ his girlfriend's mother _ in ``The Graduate,''
he was 30 and she was 36. We don't want to make too much of this,
of course. ``Thomas Crown'' is just a movie and Russo was not cast
in the role just to be fair to 45-year-olds but because she is a
beautiful and very fit 45-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still worth a whoop and a holler to see a brainy,
passionate on-screen woman whose dewy face could be the result of a
hot flash.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's more to the movie than the fact that Russo
bares her top and Bronsan his bottom and they're both amazingly
nimble. Her Catherine is every bit as devious, manipulative and
arrogant as his Thomas. I guess that's another kind of equality,
but I'm not sure those who led women to win the vote 79 years ago
had that in mind, either.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
