<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of heavy showers and some thunderstorms will swirl
around a low- pressure center as it meanders eastward through the
Ohio Valley. Weak high- level winds will encourage very slow-moving
showers in the southeastern Great Lakes and northern Ohio Valley,
resulting in areas of local flooding. In the wake of the
disturbance, very warm weather will cover most of the northern and
central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A moist flow from the Atlantic will promote clouds and showers
from the Carolinas to the interior Northeast. The steadiest rain is
expected near the Appalachians from Virginia to Pennsylvania where
the damp winds ascend the sloping terrain. Meanwhile, high pressure
east of New England will keep most of the Northeast coast dry for
much of the day, but clouds and showers will spread over the area
from the southwest at night.
</P>
<P>
   Some strong thunderstorms will develop in the sultry air ahead
of a front in the interior Southeast. Behind the front, drier air
will spread into the western Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy showers from the remnants of Hurricane Bret will continue
to plague parts of the Rio Grande Valley. Farther north, the
interior West will stay warm with afternoon thunderstorms over the
central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Offshore winds will sponsor hot weather near the California
coast. Meanwhile, a few thunderstorms will erupt near the southern
Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Dennis will continue to intensify as it moves
toward the eastern Bahamas. The storm may threaten the Atlantic
seaboard late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Houston Heat
</P>
<P>
   The mercury rose only to 91 degrees in Houston on Monday,
putting an end to the city's streak of 27 consecutive days with
readings of 95 degrees or higher. The 27-day streak ranks fourth on
Houston's all-time list, not far behind the first-place total of 41
consecutive days set in July and August of 1993. August marked the
peak of the heat, with the mercury reaching 100 degrees on seven
days, a total that ranks third on Houston's all-time list of hot
Augusts. Though this month will be remembered as one of Houston's
hottest and driest Augusts, June and July were very close to
average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
