s e BC-BILBAO-GUGGENHEIM-SCU     08-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILBAO-GUGGENHEIM-SCULPTURE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPECTACULAR MEETING OF SCULPTURE AND SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain _ The most impressive exhibition of contemporary
sculpture in a decade, or maybe more, is the show of Richard
Serra's ``Torqued Ellipses'' here at the Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Serra and Frank Gehry, the museum's architect, are old friends
who don't just speak a related language; they have invented the
same sort of elastic, twisting volumes. And the placement of eight
of Serra's gigantic ellipses with his 174-ton, 104-foot-long
``Snake,'' which was already parked in the immense ground-floor
gallery of the museum, is like a declaration on the part of artist
and architect. It is as if they were saying: this is what
architecture, carried to a creative extreme, can do for an art that
is strong enough and sympathetic enough to deal with it, and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry's room, called the ``fish'' because its shape more or less
resembles the inside of a whale, is part of what is surely the most
spectacular museum since Wright's Guggenheim opened in New York 40
years ago. But the persistent question has been whether any art can
thrive in what is really a monumental sculpture. At 433 feet long,
a third again as long as a football field, the ``fish'' dwarfs the
most enormous works of art. The accomplishment of Serra's show is
not so much to match its size _ even these sculptures can't _ but
to make a public space into a series of private ones.
</P>
<P>
   An artist's job today seems to involve working around
architecture. Architecture is often the principal attraction. The
most memorable sights in the current Venice Biennale are the
renovated shipyard buildings in which one section of the show takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   This situation isn't entirely new. Artists stopped regarding the
white cube as a neutral receptacle, an ethically blank exhibition
space, in the '70s, and they became attuned to how galleries affect
the art. Architecture, liberated in the process from the
predictability of the modernist box, turned increasingly assertive.
Now the relationship between art and architecture is competitive,
with artists frequently left to cope with adversarial spaces.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible for any artist showing work at the Guggenheim
here to avoid dealing with its audacious design. Other artists,
unlike Serra in style but alert to the issues of manipulating
sculptural forms, might be able to turn Gehry's Guggenheim to their
advantage, too _ Matthew Barney, maybe, because he is innately
theatrical, or Richard Tuttle, despite the fact that his sculptures
are small, because he makes works to interact with the rooms they
occupy. But the list will be short.
</P>
<P>
   Serra has the advantage of having installed his ``Torqued
Ellipses'' elsewhere. Three of them were shown at the Dia Center
for the Arts in New York a couple of years ago, all eight in Los
Angeles after that.
</P>
<P>
   Being unlike other modern sculptures, they are difficult to
describe. Each one consists of multiple 40-ton, 16-foot steel
plates, bent and twisted at a shipyard and rolling mill in Maryland
that is one of the only places equipped to deal with plates so big
and shapes so odd. They describe free-standing oval enclosures.
Every enclosure has a cut, or opening, so that the sculpture can be
entered. Three of the eight sculptures are also double ellipses,
meaning that one enclosure is contained within another, like
Russian nesting dolls. The degree of torque, or twist, varies from
sculpture to sculpture. One ellipse has a cut at the long end of
the oval, another in the middle. One is twisted so that the walls
seem, from inside, to bellow. Another seems static. The forms run
the gamut. Altogether they make a series.
</P>
<P>
   Serra's inspiration was Baroque architecture. He had been
looking at Borromini. But he was also, it seems, revisiting ideas
from his own early rubber sculptures of the '60s, like ``Belts,''
trying to meld their fluid, draped forms to space-defining steel
works, like ``Circuit'' and ``Terminal,'' that he made in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The drama of the ``Torqued Ellipses'' has a lot to do with the
fact that they are made of steel: steel treated like rubber seems
an impossibility, and the effect is to convey what Serra calls a
kind of ``gravitational pull.'' It's easy to picture concrete being
cast in eccentric forms, but steel, twisted unexpectedly, is
disorienting.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry and Serra clearly are soul mates in their formal and
technological ambitions. Gehry eschewed post-modern pastiche in the
'80s, sticking to industrial materials and new forms, which have
also been Serra's interests. The two of them look to invent
abstract shapes. They think on a vast scale. They're late
modernists pushing at the limits of machine technology and size,
but they also share a sense of the dance, which is to say, the art
of moving people through space.
</P>
<P>
   To grasp this show's particular choreography, bear in mind the
simple differences between a big space and a small space. Intimate
spaces invite repose. Large spaces are about movement; they ask to
be crossed. Walking suits certain kinds of art and not others.
Rodin, for example, might survive in Gehry's room, playing off a
common root in Baroque motion. But Giacometti would not do so well.
Oldenburg's ``Knife Ship,'' when it was here at the Guggenheim's
opening, looked absurd. It is the same close-up or far away. There
was no reason to walk to it. Scale being relative, it didn't even
look big, which it is meant to, in the context.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
