<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BILBAO-GUGGENHEIM-SCU     08-24 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILBAO-GUGGENHEIM-SCULPTURE-2NDTAKE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BILBAO: the context.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serra's sculptures are about walking. They're meant to be
experienced on the move. No work appears the same from two
different points. They create pathways into and around the ellipses
and from one sculpture to another. Three of the eight ellipses are
placed at the front of the room, five at the back with ``Snake'' in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake'' is like the dash in a sentence, separating and setting
off one statement from another. Made of dissimilar S-shaped plates
standing on end, bunched, it forms canyonlike passageways that have
an effect akin to the interior of the double ellipses, but less
memorable. The tension of walking within the double walls of one of
the double ellipses, where the tight spaces become cramped and tilt
steeply, provokes alarm, then exhilaration. There's nothing close
to this feeling with ``Snake.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Snake'' matters very much to the pacing of the show,
breaking up Gehry's room into parts, varying its rhythm, activating
the giant central third of the gallery. Serra has found a way to
insure that the exhibition shapes the room, not the other way
around, a complicated problem that has to do with moving viewers
through spaces in ways determined by the orientation of the art.
</P>
<P>
   To activate all of the spaces around the sculptures, including
the ones between the sculptures and the walls, no ellipse was
placed farther than 13 feet from another _ a considerable feat of
planning: parts of the floor couldn't support the weight of a
sculpture, so placement was affected by load-bearing capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But all rooms set limits on the art they contain. At Dia, in the
building on West 22d Street in Manhattan that used to be the Arnulf
Rainer Museum, the ellipses rose nearly to the trusses of the
skylighted ceiling, a limitation of height that produced a feeling
of intimacy but also placed the sculpture and architecture in
tension.
</P>
<P>
   Here, beneath a vast ceiling that ought to diminish the
sculptures, with light pouring into the room, the ellipses look
even taller than they did at Dia. This sounds contradictory, but
seen from inside, the dark ellipses ``ground'' the room: they draw
a viewer's gaze first down to the floor, then up toward the light,
emphasizing verticality. One's eyes rise to the rim of the
sculpture, then higher, to the curved shapes of the ceiling, which
echo the curves of the ellipses in ways carefully calculated by
Serra when he was working with the Guggenheim's curators Carmen
Gimenez and Susan Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The result, you might say, is to reveal the room through the
sculpture. Art precedes architecture in this case, then does a jig
with it.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk at the Guggenheim about eventually splitting
Gehry's gallery into sections, putting up walls. He had originally
proposed this, but the museum's director, Tom Krens, an agoraphile,
said no. So far, against the odds, the museum has managed in most
cases to make Gehry's architecture work. A retrospective of the
Basque abstract sculptor Eduardo Chillida is also here at the
moment, installed in several galleries that are almost as
peculiarly shaped as the ``fish.'' It looks at home. The Serra
show, here though Oct. 17, is the strongest argument yet against
partitioning. But will anything else look as good?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
