<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8089 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ARCHITECTURE-SERRA-GE     08-24 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-SERRA-GEHRY-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENDING GEOMETRY: TWO OF A KIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BILBAO-GUGGENHEIM-SCULPTURE) 
(For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the sculptor Richard Serra should not have been
surprised when he recently spied a woman who, thinking she was
alone, danced through one of his ``Torqued Ellipses'' at the
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain. His rounded, listing, walk-in
steel sculptures and the long arched gallery of the architect Frank
Gehry glide and curve together in a pas de deux of balletic grace.
Clearly she was inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The dance between Serra's sculpture and Gehry's architecture is
not simply serendipitous. ``Frank and I have been talking to each
other through our work for years,'' says Serra by telephone from
Nova Scotia. ``We find each other very useful. If I say to Frank,
`I have a space 30 feet by 30 feet by 30 feet,' we are both on the
same page; he understands the quality of the volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not that he looks at my work and I look at his, and
together we figure out how to make the next move. We bring each
other support and criticism. The influence is not direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago the worlds of art and architecture were very
separate; even the art-collecting architect Philip Johnson said in
the early 1980s that he never mixed art into the design of his
buildings. But in the '60s Gehry had already outraged his
colleagues by incorporating into his work ideas absorbed from the
artists he palled around with _ first in California and then in New
York. His own breakthrough house, in Santa Monica in 1979, was a
live-in art installation that first put him on Serra's radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an eye opener for everyone,'' says Serra. ``Frank
took the inside and threw it out the window. He really built the
new house around the old _ one continuous inside-outside house. And
he did it with all those raw materials, like cyclone fencing. I
thought, `Pretty good, Frank.'''
</P>
<P>
   The admiration was mutual. ``His sculpture was raw and powerful,
emotional and threatening _ and minimal,'' says Gehry by phone from
Los Angeles. ``Here was a guy who was pushing building-scale stuff
around, and he got the most effect with the fewest number of
moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Their brotherhood was also a defensive compact against
post-modernism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand, for a while we were marginalized,''
says Serra. ``Back in the '70s and '80s, neither of us was part of
the pastiche, plagiarism and parody of post-modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1981 show, the two collaborated on a hypothetical bridge in
New York City connecting the Chrysler Building to the Twin Towers
of the World Trade Center, both ends tethered by pylons: Serra's
was a steel mast rising from the East River, Gehry's a fish
bounding from the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The skyscraper fish, complete with scales, was Gehry's coy
answer to post-modern historicism (``It's a much older form,'' he
says, deadpan), and Serra encouraged the exploration. ``If you
think of the fish as a fuselage, then you can see the form in
different ways _ a carp differs from a sturgeon. I was interested
in the variety of the curvilinear volumes; the fishiness of the
fish never got in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Gehry designed the Fishdance Restaurant in Kobe, Japan,
and later several room-size fish installations with wooden ribs,
each tensed with twisting movement. Working with piscine shapes
gave him the confidence to build difficult compound curves. But
once he chopped off the head and tail and filleted the body, the
fish yielded abstract, sinuous planes that started to resemble the
curved steel plates that Serra had already been working on for more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not possessive in terms of my work that way,'' says Serra.
``I don't think anybody can beat you at your own game. I don't
think anybody can beat Frank at his. Frank really understands the
history of art, particularly his own generation's, and he's
digested it, translated it, reinterpreted it, put it into his own
language. His work doesn't look like watered-down artistic
conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gehry recalls Serra's visit to the California Aerospace Museum
he designed in 1984 in Los Angeles, where a two-story faceted and
torqued shape leans out from the facade, as if straining under
liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard looked at those leaning walls and said, `That taught
me something about the feeling of being under a wall.' In his next
piece, he tilted the walls out.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 competition for a footbridge across the Thames in
London linking the area around St. Paul's Cathedral with the new
Tate Gallery on Bankside, the artist and architect again
collaborated, producing a lyrically curved and arched steel truss
poised on two spring points, which Serra believes neither
collaborator would have produced alone. Gehry says, ``Richard
really got into the design process as an architect would _ into the
reality of the handrails, the texture of the surfaces, the function
and engineering of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for an honesty that can be brutal, Serra didn't like the
front facade of one of Gehry's late designs for the Walt Disney
Hall in Los Angeles, a building that was being hailed as a
masterpiece. ``Richard came by and said I had to change it, and
when he left, I knew he was right,'' says Gehry. ``I solved it with
a curved form that looked a lot like one of Richard's pieces. Then
he saw the results and said that's his piece and asked if he could
do that wall. But, of course, I couldn't take a chunk of the
building out.''
</P>
<P>
   On another studio visit, Serra cut slots for windows in tubular
forms that the architect was composing into a house. ``I used his
idea because it was better than mine,'' says Gehry, ``and Richard
said the round forms excited him, so I was playing in an arena and
he got into it. While he was cutting these shapes, he started
thinking of the `Torqued Ellipses.'''
</P>
<P>
   M R. Serra credits a visit to San Carlo, a baroque church in
Rome by Borromini, as the direct inspiration for the ``Torqued
Ellipses.'' Serra wondered how walls would connect the elliptical
plan and ceiling if the ceiling were rotated 90 degrees, and Gehry
suggested that the sculptor consult about the elusive shapes with
Rick Smith, an aerospace computer expert working in ice on
the Bilbao Guggenheim. The computer program Catia was used to
develop the French Mirage jet. ``When I'm out in Los Angeles, I go
and work with Rick early in themornings when I can book computer
time,'' says Serra.
</P>
<P>
   Independently and jointly, both the artist and architect came to
work on irregular curves, but Catia enabled the two to invent ever
more complex, doubly curved geometries that have pushed their most
recent work into the esthetic complicity that has drawn 300,000
people over the last three months to out-of-the-way Bilbao. (The
show originated earlier this year at the more accessible Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, where Richard Koshalek and Julia
Brown were the curators.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an interconnection between the curvilinearity of
Frank's building and the obvious torquing of my pieces,'' says
Serra. ``So when you're in them, you kind of spin from the
architecture into the pieces and vice versa. The ellipses play off
the architecture and take on a new quality in Frank's building.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
