<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Aug. 25, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Shanghai, China) _ Chinese authorities announce they
are preparing to prosecute top leaders of Falun Gong, a signal that
China has reached the final stage of its broadest political
mobilization campaign in a decade. Falun Gong, a spiritual movement
of more than 20 million members that badly spooked China's leaders
with its ability to organize potent anti-government protests, was
banned last month as the Communist Party galvanized its vast
apparatus in a sweeping crackdown aimed at snuffing out political
dissent. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BERGER-PROFILE (Washington) _ Widely regarded as the president's
closest foreign policy aide, perhaps the most influential national
security adviser since Henry A. Kissinger, Sandy Berger he is at
bottom a political rather than strategic figure. Unlike the
professors, diplomats and military officers who have for the most
part preceded him in his job, he made his way to the White House by
way of the salons and back rooms of Democratic politics. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo. 3,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   KAN-EVOLUTION (Topeka, Kan.) _ The decision by the Kansas Board
of Education to delete mention of evolution from the science
textbooks has, instead of settling the issue, reignited passions on
both sides. For some, the move finally opens the door to let them
teach their own beliefs in things like ``intelligent design,''
which means a leaf is so beautifully complex it must have been
planned by a high intelligence. For others, the move is meaningless
because it is not mandatory. Many, including many science teachers,
plan on ignoring the advice of the board and teaching evolution
anyhow. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHAT-ROOM-SYPHILIS (San Francisco) _ In the first case where a
disease cluster has been traced to the Internet, public health
officials here have tracked an outbreak of syphilis to an America
Online chat room. Officials from the San Francisco Department of
Public Health said that six men who have contracted syphilis since
mid-June have traced their last sexual encounters to partners they
met through an America Online chat room called San Francisco Men 4
Men (SFM4M). The situation has posed a unique problem for health
officials, since some of the infected men know their multiple
partners only by their cyberspace nicknames, or ``handles.'' Since
America Online refused to divulge the identities of its chat room
users, the only way to contact all the men the syphilis-infected
men had sex with has been by posting warnings in the chat room. By
Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EXTRADITE (Washington) _ A Maryland teen-ager who has
been the subject of a 17-month extradition battle between the
United States and Israel has agreed to plead guilty to murder and
accept a 24-year prison sentence in Israel, state prosecutors in
Maryland announced on Tuesday. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve voted to raise
interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point for the second
time in less than two months, saying the action would help avert
inflation while allowing the long economic expansion to continue.
The central bank said it would increase the main rate it controls,
the Federal funds target rate on overnight loans among banks, to
5.25 percent from 5 percent. It said it would raise its discount
rate on loans to banks from the Federal Reserve system to 4.75
percent from 4.5 percent. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
