<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-BRASS     08-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-BRASSERIE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPDATING A BRASSERIE WITH PIZZAZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last June, American architecture took a giant step
into the present with the announcement that Elizabeth Diller and
Ricardo Scofidio, two architects who practice together in New York,
had been awarded a fellowship from the MacArthur Foundation. This
is the first time that the coveted award has been presented to
architects.
</P>
<P>
   The award was beautifully timed. With only a few conventially
built projects to their credit, Ms. Diller and Scofidio are best
known for temporary, mixed-media installations, often commissioned
by museums and public art funds. In the last year, however, they
have expanded their practice beyond these elite venues. Earlier
this year, the pair completed a 100-unit apartment block in Gifu,
Japan. They are now working on large projects in San Francisco, at
Kennedy International Airport and Yverdon-les-Bains, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Such projects represent a departure for these architects, at
least in terms of public recognition. They are already stars in
academia. Ms. Diller, 44, is an associate professor at Princeton
University's graduate school of architecture. Scofidio, 63, is a
professor at Cooper Union in New York. The two have published their
own projects in books like ``Flesh'' and ``Back to the Front'' and
been written about in highbrow journals like ANY and Assemblage.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the MacArthur Foundation chose to honor them
for developing their practice outside the usual commercial routes.
Even so, many who have followed their work have been hoping that
these two would get a bit more commercial. We'll be lining up this
October, when the first restaurant they have designed opens in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the basement of the Seagram Building, the new
Brasserie replaces a restaurant of the same name designed by Philip
Johnson in 1959. Johnson had just collaborated on the Seagram
Building with Mies van der Rohe, the chief architect. The
Brasserie, famous for its onion soup, 24-hour service and
conveyer-belt delivery, was intended as a cut-rate counterpoint to
the glittering Four Seasons upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diller and Scofidio's updated version offers a salient set
of variations on Miesian themes. This will be a snazzy place, with
illuminated glass walls, plastic fixtures and a lavish use of video
technology. But customers will also get a slice of history. Ms.
Diller and Scofidio specialize in projects that heighten our
awareness of our place in history. Their Brasserie throws a light
on the distance from Miess' time to our own.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other American architects in recent years, Ms. Diller
and Scofidio have been working to correct the clownish view of
history put forth by the post-modern movement and its callow
promoters. The clowns took a knock two years ago, with the opening
of the Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain. Frank Gehry's design
awakened many to the idea that buildings articulate their place in
time. Ms. Diller and Scofidio's work shows that historical
awareness can take many forms.
</P>
<P>
   Their temporary installations have typically revolved around
broad cultural themes, like tourism, gardening and real estate
development. Using video screens and projections, photographs,
printed text and a range of motley objects, these projects share no
single formal vocabulary. But they exhibit a common intellectual
approach. Far more than the formalist designs selected for the
Museum of Modern Arts' numbing ``Deconstructivist Architecture''
show in 1988, this work recalls the aggressive stance of Jacques
Derrida. Rigorously analytic, sometimes chilly, always playful,
they are intellectual comedies in a profession where intellect and
the comic sense are in notably short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Ms. Diller and Scofidio practice a form of
meta-architecture. Rather than produce buildings, they analyze the
cultural forces that produce buildings. They explore the ways
architecture itself functions in the postindustrial world.
Reckoning with their work requires a fresh critical vocabulary, one
that deals (like movie criticism) with content as well as form.
</P>
<P>
   Its apt that Ms. Diller and Scofidio's first large-scale New
York project is a restaurant interior, that icon of ephemeral
design. Fitting, too, that they were recommended for the job by
Phyllis Lambert, a Bronfman family member who proposed Mies for the
Seagram Building commission more than 40 years ago. Both choices
reflect a keen sense of the zeitgeist that have also colored the
shows she organized at the Canadian Center for Architecture for
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The new Brasserie design, for which Charles Renfrew is project
architect, retains a few elements from the old. As before, patrons
will enter the restaurant through a revolving door. A staircase, a
redesigned version of the most memorable feature in Johnson's
scheme, descends from street level to the main dining room. An
annex to the right of the entrance opens off the rear of the main
dining room. Otherwise, the place will be unrecognizable. And it
won't be open around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The main dining room will be set within a thin shell of molded
pear wood. One side will be lined with booths. The bar is directly
opposite. Above it, a row of video monitors will screen blurred
images of patrons as they come through the revolving door: an
electronic salute to the nightclub photographers of another day.
</P>
<P>
   Video imagery gets great play here. In the small entrance lobby,
a flat panel screen will display a manipulated real-time picture of
the 53d Street sidewalk just outside. A second panel will show
morphing images, perhaps of Ricky Martin transmuted into Carmen
Miranda. Cool!
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
