<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-2NDTA     08-24 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-2NDTAKE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sun., Aug. 29)  
 NEW YORK: Miranda. Cool!  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Table tops fashioned from thick slabs of translucent, pale green
resin. Bar stools cushioned with silicon seats of resilient,
buttock-shaped contours. Lots of glass: a honeycomb glass divider
between men's and women's restrooms; translucent glass treads and
risers on the entry stair; in the annex dining room, sloping panes
of glass that support cantilevered banquettes. In the same room, a
partition of thin pear wood veneer enclosing a circle of red light.
Hot!
</P>
<P>
   The new Brasserie's location may be East 53d Street, but its
context is the history of ideas. The architects accept as a given
that the Seagram Building is a key landmark in that history, a work
whose roots go back to the Industrial Revolution, the
Enlightenment, Renaissance classicism and beyond. Ms. Diller's and
Scofidio's design is a further offshoot of that history.
</P>
<P>
   They have described the Seagram basement as Mies' subconscious.
The space was not designed to be habitable. It is a maze of columns
and beams belied by the tower's crisp, rational facade. The new
Brasserie design brings this subterranean world into the
(artificial) light. It peers at the difference between Mies'
intentions and the results he achieved.
</P>
<P>
   For architects of Mies' generation, for example, glass held
symbolic connotations. It symbolized a modern society of clarity,
reason and integrity that they hoped their designs would encourage.
With Ms. Diller and Scofidio, glass becomes an instrument for
creating illusion and provoking voyeurism. Again, in the classic
Miesian tower, glass is draped over structure. In the Brasserie,
glass will be used structurally, to support banquettes in the
annex.
</P>
<P>
   The most important link to Mies' plan is the emphasis Ms. Diller
and Scofidio have placed on the relationship between interior and
exterior space. In the procession from the street, across the
plaza, into the elevator lobby on Park Avenue , Mies dramatized the
reduction of the Seagram Building's wall to a transparent membrane
and the erosion of the division between interior and exterior
space. Ms. Diller and Scofidio pick up the theme with an interplay
between openness and enclosure, evident in the spatial relationship
between the booths and the bar, and in the screening device of the
pear wood shell.
</P>
<P>
   The video gadgets elaborate the theme. In place of direct views
of the street, the design substitutes media renditions of the
sidewalk and entering patrons. This runs contrary to the Miesian
ideal of transparency. But, in fact, even with Mies' design, the
experience was mediated by the play of reflections, the pink tint
of the glass, the framing of views provided by columns and window
mullions: Structure and materials induced a clear separation
between inside and outside, turning each into a spectacle of
inclusion and exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diller and Scofidio update these effects for a time when
mediated reality has partly displaced direct social contact. They
remind us that Mies, too, was a meta-architect, a man who reduced
building to the spare essentials of structure and space. ``Almost
nothing'' was the phrase Mies used to describe his work. He saw
himself as a zeitgeist channeler. His work was more about letting
it happen than about making it happen. As Mies put it, architecture
is the will of an epoch translated into space. In the basement of
his masterpiece, we will see that the epoch has changed more
swiftly than Mies could have known.
</P>
</TEXT>
