<HEADER>
A8096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SINGLE-SEX MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For me, taking sides in the gender wars is usually
a breeze. My sympathy is with my sex.
</P>
<P>
   Too many men still don't get it, after all these decades of
equal rights legislation and sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   As individuals, a lot of them are swell. I married one that is.
But collectively the male animal still tends to hog the best jobs,
resent affirmative action and stick women with the lion's share of
the child-rearing and household duties. It ain't fair.
</P>
<P>
   But a stunning example of feminism gone bananas turned up
recently and it's only fair to acknowledge that my side makes
mistakes too. This one's a doozy.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College brought it to our attention this summer by
forcing a tenured professor, Mary Daly, 70, into retirement. A
teacher of feminist ethics, Daly did not go gracefully. She is
angrily suing for reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is that the college did not give her the boot sooner.
For more than two decades, she had refused to teach male students,
insisting on sharing her educational insights only with other
females. The college finally developed a spine when a male student
who was locked out of her classroom complained to the Center for
Individual Rights, an advocacy group in the nation's capital which
threatened to file a discrimination suit on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Daly has a reputation as a radical feminist, well known for her
hardline defense of same-sex education and what she calls ``women
space.'' But her brand of feminism does women no favor. She was not
advancing the cause of women's rights; she was betraying it. Women
deserve equality, not favoritism that sets them apart.
</P>
<P>
   The professor thinks female students are so intimidated by the
opposite sex that they can't learn to stand up for themselves
properly if males are studying in the same room. ``Women in classes
with men ... have to be sexy and they can't really think,'' Daly
said on National Public Radio after her forced departure. This is
also the theory behind the few private schools in the country that
admit only women.
</P>
<P>
   But an artificial single-sex school setting is no preparation
for the real world, in which women work side-by-side with men, deal
with them socially and professionally and relate to them both
intellectually and emotionally. Delaying integration merely puts
off the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Segregation of the sexes in a classroom or anywhere else except
a boxing mat or a public toilet is stupid. In most cases it is also
morally, ethically and legally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College, a Jesuit-run Catholic university, is a
coeducational institution that receives federal funds in the form
of research grants and various student assistance. Title IX of a
1972 civil rights law bars gender discrimination in programs and
services at schools that receive taxpayer funds. Women, you see,
pay taxes just as men do and therefore have a right to share the
resultant benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It was under this law that the courts forced the Virginia
Military Institute and ultimately the Citadel, famous bastions of
the male military establishment, to reluctantly admit female
recruits. If the women met the physical and intellectual
requirements, they could not be denied entry simply because of
their gender. Both schools have survived the change.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same principle that makes Daly's position impossible
to defend. Yet some feminists like Gloria Steinem can't accept this
rebuke of their friend and have echoed Daly's
women-are-repressed-and-need-special-help theme. They have also
suggested ominously that Daly's removal is part of a political
backlash against feminism and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   They have a point, but not the one they meant to make. A
backlash is usually generated by outrage over some policy or
philosophy that has exceeded rational bounds and lost broad popular
support. And outraged we are. Daly went too far.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping male students at bay may have seemed like a bright idea
when Daly began ideologically thrashing the masculine power
structure long ago. The women's movement was still fragile and did
not pick up steam until the late 1970s. But we have come a long way
since then, men and women together, and continued progress in
rational interaction depends on cooperation rather than isolation.
</P>
<P>
   What Daly was doing is disturbing. She took advantage of her
control over her classroom to discriminate against male students
just as males in control of jobs and other economic opportunities
used to have free rein to discriminate against women. Turnabout is
not fair play. It is a violation of the Golden Rule: Do unto others
as you would have them do unto you.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is a good one. Wars have been fought because rival
groups have not figured this out. Kosovo, where the ethnic
Albanians are now persecuting the Serbs just as the Serbs recently
persecuted them, is a tragic, classic example.
</P>
<P>
   Daly doesn't belong in a college. She was sending her students
the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
