<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-FOUNDATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS TURN TO NEW FOUNDATION TO FILL VOID LEFT BY NEA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To judge by the experience of a new cultural support
foundation, many of the nation's artists are clamoring for
financial aid even in these prosperous times.
</P>
<P>
   By last week's deadline for the Creative Capital Foundation's
first round of grants, applications from 1,810 visual, performing
and media artists had flooded into the Greenwich Village office of
the new group. The foundation was formed to fill the gap created
when the National Endowment for the Arts ended most grants to
individuals in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That is 50 percent to 80 percent more than the 1,000 to 1,200
submissions expected by Creative Capital, which was started in May
to finance artists whose innovative, often difficult work
challenges society's conventions. So far, Creative Capital has
raised over $5 million from two dozen foundations and
philanthropists, including the Andy Warhol Foundation for the
Visual Arts, the Lily Auchincloss Foundation and the Thomas S.
Kenan Institute for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The applications, including about 600 that arrived on the final
day, came from artists in 46 states, the District of Columbia and
Puerto Rico. The largest number by far, 720 or 40 percent,
originated in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Lerner, Creative Capital's executive director, was elated
by the geographic spread. ``This says a lot about the need that is
out there, about the pent-up demand,'' she said, ``because we made
it clear that we were not talking about huge sums of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The grants will range from $5,000 to $20,000 and in this round
will go to 60 artists, or 3.3 percent of those who applied.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the late 1980s, the National Endowment awarded as
much as $10.5 million a year to more than 750 individuals, and in
fiscal year 1995, the last full year of grants, it received 9,036
applications and gave $7.1 million to 616 artists. Congress, after
years of controversy over grants to artists whose works dealt with
provocative themes, ordered it to halt most individual grants
(leaving only a few for literary, jazz and folk artists).
</P>
<P>
   Creative Capital will disperse only about $1 million this year,
though that may increase if the organization realizes its hope of
raising $40 million. A small portion of Creative Capital's kitty is
also expected to come from artists who win grants, who must then
agree to return a small portion of any proceeds from their projects
to Creative Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,810 submissions, 30 percent came from visual artists,
26.4 percent from performing artists, 22 percent from artists in
emerging fields like computer and installation art and 21.6 percent
from film or video artists. The awards will be split equally among
the four areas.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, California came in second, with 285 submissions,
followed by Pennsylvania, with 67, and Texas, Illinois and
Massachusetts, with 55, 53 and 52 respectively. There were no
submissions from Arkansas, Idaho, North Dakota or Utah. At first
glance, Ms. Lerner estimated that nearly three-quarters of the
applications came from emerging artists and only 1 or 2 percent
from established artists.
</P>
<P>
   The applications will now go to outside evaluators, who are to
choose about 200 finalists. They will be asked to submit detailed
plans, budgets, time frames and work samples. The awards should
come soon thereafter. ``I am determined to be able to say `Merry
Christmas' to 60 artists,'' Ms. Lerner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1822EDT &QL; 
