<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GSU-EMBA-COX     08-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GSU-EMBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GSU joins world web of e-commerce studies
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's an underconstruction atmosphere at Georgia
State University's Center for Digital Commerce, which in a sense
mirrors the industry it's being set up to study.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there isn't much to look at, just piles of boxes and
empty cubicles in the business school's downtown classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   As with any Internet start-up, the faculty and staff at GSU are
hoping their ambitious plans to form a worldwide consortium to
teach the basics of conducting business in the global electronic
marketplace will make them the Amazon.com of e-commerce education.
But they are gambling and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   The program's premise is that the Internet is a global medium
for companies providing goods and services. Top managers now find
themselves grappling with policy, regulatory and social issues they
haven't had to tackle before.
</P>
<P>
   For example, insurance company Met Life ran into a worldwide
dilemma several years ago trying to launch its first Web site.
Between international regulations governing where the company is
permitted to sell insurance and copyright restrictions on the
``Peanuts'' cartoon characters the company uses in its ads, Met
Life faced roadblocks to doing business on the Web it didn't
encounter offline.
</P>
<P>
   The GSU program is designed to educate executives, policy makers
and entrepreneurs to manage such problems in the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the fall of 2000, the school will offer a program
called the global electronic master's degree, a venture between GSU
and some of the top business schools in Europe, Asia and North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Executives enrolled in the GSU program will take classes with
other students from top business schools all over the world.
Universities in Norway, Germany, Greece, the Netherlands,
Australia, Denmark and Australia and possibly Canada will take part
in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed program of study will take 16 months to complete
and will include three week-long international seminars with
students at the other participating schools.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Welke, chairman of GSU's computer information systems
department, has also worked in the private sector and taught school
in Canada and the Netherlands. In 1995, Welke authored a white
paper for the Georgia Research Alliance suggesting the time was
right to develop a center for digital commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Welke says while he was working on funding for the e-commerce
center, the G7 summit of highly industrialized nations had met. The
world economic leaders were excited about electronic commerce. Out
of that conference came an organization called GCommNet _ the
Global Electronic Commerce Management network. Its goal was to
bring a number of universities around the world together to develop
e-commerce programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I had been a professor in Europe for a time, we became
rather directly involved in that entire process,'' Welke says.
``Two groups were formed, one was more technology-oriented from the
tech schools and the other was focused on the MBA side of things.''
</P>
<P>
   What emerged was a consortium of 10 of Europe's top business
schools, GSU and a university in Australia. Seven of the schools
will be offering digital commerce programs in the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The program will kick off with students meeting in the
Netherlands at the Rotterdam School of Business. In 2001, the
one-week seminar will take place at GSU, and in 2002, students will
meet for a week at an Asian or Australian university to be
arranged. The rest of the coursework will be done at the GSU campus
with students remaining in constant touch with their international
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see technology as a driver not as an entity in itself. We
are interested in (students) who are going to reshape industry and
public policy.'' It's important to understand international laws,
regulations and regional restraints, Welke says.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``You can't do drugstore.com in Germany. The
regulations won't permit it. Our perspectives are three-pronged.
The first is policy _ what can you do in the e-commerce space. It's
going to be controlled by national and international policy. It's
also about the movement of personal data.''
</P>
<P>
   The second prong is entrepreneurship. ``The focus is on what you
should be doing and how you should be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The third aspect is to teach students how to work within
national and international frameworks to develop e-commerce sites
that dovetail with the way the world does business.
</P>
<P>
   Welke acknowledges that it's hard to launch a program teaching
students to understand an industry that hasn't fully evolved. But
he believes the global nature of the GSU program should give
students a better framework for doing business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our students will be people who understand the answers aren't
yet fully known,'' he says. ``Students need to have the mental
agility to go beyond the classroom and be enticed by the notion
that this is a new way of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
