<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DEEP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-24 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN TOO DEEP': A CONFLICTED DETECTIVE, A DRUG LORD NAMED GOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: production notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In Too Deep'' is the story of an undercover police detective
who finds himself with conflicting loyalties, especially where the
matter of doing God's business is concerned. That's because God is
the blasphemous moniker of a Cincinnati drug lord played by the
rapper LL Cool J with impressive bluster.
</P>
<P>
   And it becomes increasingly impressive to Jeff Cole (Omar Epps),
who has adopted the alias J. Reid for his work at infiltrating
God's operation. The film means to be a semi-subtle look at the
conflicts in which Cole finds himself entangled.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the film treats its characters seriously and
doesn't resort to the obvious very often. And it was directed by
Michael Rymer, the Australian director whose ``Angel Baby,'' about
a desperate, fiery love affair, had a tragic intensity that this
film sometimes approaches. But ``In Too Deep'' has to make its
accommodations to the lurid genre of drug-dealer stories, and it
does so with more enthusiasm than absolutely necessary. God's cruel
streak is well documented long before he is seen torturing a naked,
disloyal subordinate with a pool cue.
</P>
<P>
   Epps plays his role with earnest conviction, so that not even
the obligatory romantic subplot (with Nia Long, as a model and
dancer living well outside the realm of Cole's police activities)
seems overly tacked on. But despite the fact that there is much for
him to say in the screenplay by Michael Henry Brown and Paul Aaron,
there is too much about Cole that goes unexpressed.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most delicate nuances are supplied by Ellery Ryan's
cinematography, which presents both the daylit world in which God
fancies himself a doting father and the color-infused realm of
crime. Within the characters themselves, the distinctions are
blurrier and less vivid.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN TOO DEEP'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Rymer; written by Michael Henry Brown and
Paul Aaron; director of photography, Ellery Ryan; edited by Dany
Cooper; music by Christopher Young; production designer, Dan Leigh;
produced by Aaron and Brown; released by Dimension Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 104 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``In Too Deep'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity,
nudity, sexual situations and some ugly violence.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Omar Epps (Jeff Cole/J. Reid), L L Cool J (Dwyane Gittens,
God) and Nia Long (Myra). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-24 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN VOLUNTEER SHOULD HEED DRESS CODE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves in the
``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box 260057,
Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to LloydOnJobaol.com.
Names will be withheld upon request.) 
BY KEN LLOYD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Q: I am a volunteer for a citizens group whose
dress code requires each male member to wear a coat and tie at all
formal functions. One of our members began wearing a T-shirt to the
formal meetings. Several of our members have asked him to respect
our dress code or resign, but he has done neither. His attitude is
that he doesn't care how he looks or what we think about it. Our
leader wants nothing to do with the problem and ignores it. How can
this issue be handled? R.L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Just as participating in volunteer organizations is optional,
some people think that following the rules of these organizations
is optional as well. The attitude of these people is something
like: I'm a volunteer. If you don't like what I'm doing, that's too
bad. I can always volunteer somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the rules can also be a power play. This particular
volunteer may be trying to show everyone that he is above you and
the other volunteers, above the rules and so important that he can
do whatever he wants. However, when people get to choose which
rules they follow or ignore, there is no need for any rules.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem in this situation is the leader. In fact, the
indifference indicates that he or she is not a leader at all. You
and the other volunteers should meet with this person and present
some suggestions. In a word, either the rule should be followed or
abolished. If the organization is trying to project a particular
image at formal events and the T-shirted volunteer feels this image
is not for him, then perhaps the organization is not for him
either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was walking down the hall ahead of a few of my employees.
When I turned around, I saw one problem employee mimicking me in a
very derogatory way. I made an instant decision to avoid a
confrontation, so I ignored it. I'm fuming over what happened and
unsure if I did the right thing. S.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Wondering whether you did the right thing is not the right
thing to do. The fact is that, for better or worse, you let the
behavior slide. Rather than wondering about the past, it is time to
think about the future.
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of time, problem employees should either become
solid employees or former employees. In the broadest sense, this
type of employee should be given specific guidance, feedback and
counseling, along with a clear understanding of the consequences
associated with inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While imitation may be the highest form of flattery, mimicking
may just as easily be the highest form of insult. As a result, if
you ever see that employee engaging in this type of behavior again,
or in any behavior that is designed to degrade, mock or ridicule
you, the next step is to call a meeting with the employee, discuss
the behavior and document it. If the employee continues to act out
against you, it is time for that employee to take the act on the
road _ and out of your company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have changed a core aspect of our hiring process. In the
past, we looked for people who had all of the training and
expertise needed for the job, and we did not put much emphasis on
personality, friendliness or cooperation. Now we are putting more
emphasis on those factors and less on the others. How does this
sound? F.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds like you are going to build a productive,
cooperative and stable work force. Growing numbers of companies in
many sectors are placing major emphasis upon such factors as a job
candidate's social skills, communication skills, emotional maturity
and energy, while placing less emphasis on his or her expertise or
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying philosophy is that the technology needed for many
positions can be taught, while it is far more difficult to teach
someone how to be friendly, communicative, persistent, reliable or
caring. Related to this, companies have been finding that employees
are more likely to fail as a result of inability to get along with
others than inability to do the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   Screening for such factors in the hiring process can be
difficult. Obviously, it is essential to take a thorough work
history, use competency questions and take job references. Some
companies also use consulting firms to help. In doing so, it is
essential that their techniques be job-related and validated for
the particular firm.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer term, it makes sense to analyze your new
approach to see if it is really working and if the people hired
under it are really working.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GSU-KALAKOTA-COX     08-24 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GSU-KALAKOTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A man with e-vision
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ravi Kalakota, Georgia State University's 32-year-old
Eminent Scholar, is a blend of personality, drive and interests
that make him a thoroughly modern man, Georgia style.
</P>
<P>
   Born in India, educated in India, Hawaii and Texas, he is fully
absorbed in his engrossing specialty _ the Internet and its power
to reshape business. Though he is concerned about the potentially
convulsive side-effects of the Internet on society and the
workplace, he has no doubts it can be a boon for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized as early as 1991, back in Texas, that Internet
communication was destined to change the world, not just
business,'' said Kalakota, ``and that is when I decided to make it
a focus of my study.'' He was 24 years old .
</P>
<P>
   Dean Sidney Harris of the J. Mack Robinson College of Business
said Kalakota has rare vision. ``His ability to comprehend and look
downstream at broad implications adds something very special to our
program at Georgia State. In so many ways he reminds me of Peter
Drucker, the management expert who was a colleague of mine, and it
is so surprising in one so young as he.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Worldwide Web was scarcely more than an idea,
Kalakota made it the subject of his doctoral dissertation in the
early 1990s. And then in 1994 on advice from his academic advisers
in Austin, at the age of 27, he drafted his first popular take on
this new phenomenon, an 800-page book, ``Frontiers of Electronic
Commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I embraced the idea that, to get ahead, I needed to try to
write a book that others would follow,'' said Kalakota.
</P>
<P>
   He followed up a year later with ``Manager's Guide to Electronic
Commerce.'' And now he has published his most encompassing work,
``e-Business: Roadmap for Success,'' which looks at electronic
commerce at the heart of a business plan, instead of a fancy
adjunct. Marcia Robinson is co-author.
</P>
<P>
   The essentially radical aspect of Kalakota's work is that he is
analyzing the huge change in commerce as it takes shape, not unlike
writing a geography book in the 16th century as explorers and
conquistadors made discoveries almost daily that modified the body
of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   And so, though Columbus failed to find his way to the East
Indies, Kalakota of India has found his way to e-commerce, one of
the most compelling phenomena of Western industrial culture.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably young for his accomplishments, Kalakota did not touch
a computer until he was 17 and a student in junior college. `` My
interest in mathematics is what drove my initial interest in
computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Math, science and computers have been his passion. But
communication, in broad terms, has been a consuming interest too.
He has won two awards for teaching excellence.
</P>
<P>
   When he graduated with a degree in computer science in India in
1987 at 20, he made a beeline for the University of Hawaii for his
master's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaii did some of the earliest work on networks, as well as
packet-switching technology, and that's what attracted me. They
developed that technology, in part, as a matter of necessity, to
transmit large quantities of data among the Hawaiian Islands.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he thought about working on a master's in business at
Harvard but decided instead to stay in computer science attending
the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With degree in hand he turned to writing and consulting. Asked
if he planned to teach this year, Kalakota said no. ``Not teaching
in the ordinary sense. I teach executives. The things I have to say
need to be implemented or dismissed. They have little shelf life,
and so it is worth my time to talk to clients and others who can
make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   His first contract out of school was with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``That experience is what taught me how difficult it is to get
major businesses to change and accommodate to the new technology of
the Internet,'' said Kalakota. ``It's like they are sailing along,
doing good business, and then somebody off-stage says they have to
lose weight. Lose weight! You are working hard, getting results,
headed fast in the direction of solving company problems and
meeting challenges, you have no spare time... you don't want to
hear lose weight or get involved in this e-commerce thing that you
don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Kalakota thinks hisexperience with AT&AMP;T, is instructive about
the problems of change. ``I spent eight months working with teams
of people within the company, trying to identify the products and
services that lend themselves to electronic commerce. Then Robert
Allen (former CEO) was out, and the slate was wiped clean, and the
idea of moving toward electronic commerce was changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If managers at the top do not push, no move toward electronic
commerce will occur,'' he said. ``Many managers are petrified of
this business, the unknown, and they are literally like deer in
headlights, blinded, scared but unable to move.'' In his book,
Kalakota writes
</P>
<P>
   ``e-Business is an alluring concept for most business
executives: buying and selling online, expanding the customer base;
improving customer loyalty, and interacting seamlessly and
efficiently with suppliers and business partners...
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers, however, need to look past the hype to realize that
e-business is bringing about fundamental changes...''
</P>
<P>
   The gist of his book is that e-commerce is substantially more
than a glamorous add-on. ''It reshapes the structure of entire
industries, creates niches for new sets of (intermediaries), and
enables businesses with well-executed business applications to take
quantum leaps forward, while those without them suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the traditional business might simply put up a Web
site with company information, perhaps selling a certain line of
goods on the Net, but otherwise conducts its business, marketing
and distribution in customary ways.
</P>
<P>
   An e-commerce savvy company might use its Web presence to order
basic materials, conduct marketing surveys, set up direct
distribution as close to the end user as possible, and be prepared
to switch sources of materials or distributors quickly. Kalakota
repeatedly stressed that the changed relationships between primary
businesses and their customers, ranging from households and
individuals to commercial and industrial customers, will wipe out
vast ``middle man'' enterprises, eliminating tens of thousands of
jobs and functions.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, the change to electronic commerce is
occurring in fits and starts, faster among smaller, entrepreneurial
businesses, and more slowly among major businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Yankee Group, a Boston consultancy, found
that even among small to medium-sized companies, Web sites often
gave company information but did not allow customers to do business
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most surprising is how overall technology goals are
not in line with how these companies use the Internet, `` says
Michael Lauricella, a Yankee Group analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance has to do with fears of upsetting the tempo of
the company and its orientation to quarterly earnings expected by
investors, Kalakota said. It also has to do with the difficulty in
reorganizing internal investments, ``sometimes forcing you to
starve profitable activities and divert funds to something that is
basically unproven, from the manager's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But change they must, Kalakota said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that pressure makes change. Companies move toward
e-commerce to the extent they fear bankruptcy, or direct threats
from entrepreneurs who take aim at a share of their business. ``
</P>
<P>
   Asked who seems to be doing a good job, Kalakota said, without
hesitation, ``Lucent Technologies.'' Lucent, originally a part of
AT&AMP;T, was spun off and became an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freed from its bonds and allowed to make its own decisions,
the company has been able to marshal its considerable talent very
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Kalakota and his students and associates have put
together their own Website for an e-business, and it could well go
public in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Called hSupply.com, the site is designed to bring together the
hospitality industry and allied enterprises such as customers, and
suppliers of various consumables, such as soaps, detergents, towels
_ ``all the things that get used up by hotels, motels and other
similar businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just keep your eye on us, and see if we know our stuff,'' said
Kalakota.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Research Alliance expects he does. ``Ravi Kalakota
is just what we seek in this program,'' said Mike Cassidy of
Alliance, which co-sponsors the Eminent Scholar program with the
colleges. He combines scholarship and the instincts for putting
ideas into practice, to develop the commercial side of things. He
was a real catch for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
