<P>
   ELWAY-ONLINE _ ATLANTA _ Pro football great John Elway partners
with Atlanta firm to develop new Web site focusing on sports and
fitness for men 35 and older. The Atlanta firm had originally
suggested Elway be a spokesman for an online brokerage firm they
were developing, but Elway decided to take the venture in a
different direction. Site is expected to launch during the Super
Bowl in Atlanta in January. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ More than 1,400 customers and computer
industry big wigs start arriving in Austin today for Dell's
Directconnect gathering. We chat up those who are arriving. Why are
they here? What are they hoping to hear from the likes of Michael
Dell, Bill Gates, Craig Barrett? And do they have confidence in
those three to meet demands in the growing Internet economy?
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ELDER-BEERMAN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Elder-Beerman reports $1.3
million loss for the second-quarter, compared to a $200,000 gain
last year. Will update through the day, checking stock price.
(Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   EGSU-EMBA _ ATLANTA _ Georgia State University readies its eMBA
program and center for Digital Commerce for Fall 2000 opening.
Innovative program will allow GSU students to learn about
e-commerce from an international and policy perspective. It is the
only American college participating in this program, along with top
biz schools from all over the world. GSU is forming the program
with international components including classwork with European
students taking place overseas. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GSU-KALAKOTA _ ATLANTA _ Ravi Kalakota, Georgia State's Eminent
Scholar, is a man of intellect and here-and-now practicality. Not
content with high thoughts alone, he has produced a masterful
handbook on e-Business and already has his students embarked on a
business that could go public in months. His singular contribution
has been to distinguish electronic commerce, simply doing business
on the Web, from eBusiness, the art and science of changing a core
business plan to capitalize on the flexibility of superfast,
far-reaching communication now becoming possible. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-LONGDISTANCE _ ATLANTA _ In-depth look at BellSouth's
struggle to get into long-distance: Folks have been hearing about
BellSouth getting into long-distance for a long time _ at least
since passage of the Telecom Act in 1996. Entry hinges on
BellSouth's readiness to have rivals in local service connect to
its network. This summer, HP is testing BellSouth. An update.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PRATT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The vultures have landed in
northern Palm Beach County. Every major company that has something
to do with putting things in the air is trying to swipe engineers
and technicians from Pratt &AMP; Whitney, which is moving operations
north. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   RELEVANT-Q&AMP;A _ ATLANTA _ Q&AMP;A with Jeff Levy, founder of Relevant
Knowledge, which was bought out by Media Metrix. Coming back strong
with new company called eHatchery. What will new company do, what
are his plans, why Atlanta, etc. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SURVEY - A new survey says that less than half the country's
big companies have readied their computer systems for 2000 but
local anecdotal evidence suggests metro Atlanta is doing better
than the national average. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-HAIRCARE _ ATLANTA _ A growing number of African American
women are forsaking chemicals in favor of natural styles - locs,
twists and short afros, even braids. This change in hair fashion is
also affecting the industry, though many black women still prefer
relaxers. We take a look at this growing segment of the industry.
(Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT _ ATLANTA _ Varner-Bass Enterprises, a defunct peanut
farmer based in Leslie, Ga., won a $22 million verdict in a
breach-of-contract lawsuit against Alpharetta-based Golden Peanut
Co., whose partners include Archer-Daniels Midland and Gold Kist. A
look at what impact the verdict may have on Golden Peanut's local
operations. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PAWN-BUSINESS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ These are tough days in the pawn
business. A booming economy and record-low unemployment means fewer
people are in hock _ literally. Pawnshops such as EZ Pawn, the
nation's second-largest chain behind Cash America International,
are feeling it. (Pletz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
