<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-ACHEBE-NYT &LR;      08-24 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ACHEBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR CHINUA ACHEBE RETURNS TO NIGERIA AFTER 9-YEAR ABSENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ The Nigerian author, Chinua Achebe, whose 1958
novel ``Things Fall Apart'' has become one of the most popular
works of African fiction in the West, returned here Monday night
after a nine-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Achebe, 69, left Nigeria in 1990 to seek medical treatment in
the United States following a car accident that left him partially
paralyzed. The 69-year-old author did not make a statement on his
arrival at Lagos international airport with his family, according
to The Guardian, Nigeria's leading newspaper. Since then, he has
kept a low profile, and it is not clear whether he intends to stay
here permanently or to return to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Achebe's visit comes three months after the inauguration of a
new civilian government and more than a year after the death of
Gen. Sani Abacha, whose repressive five-year rule drove many
Nigerians into exile. His arrival was seen as a positive
development in a country whose military rulers permitted little
criticism until last year and, in fact, became international
pariahs in 1995 after hanging the writer and political critic Ken
Saro-Wiwa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirms the fact that civilian rule is taking root,'' Gani
Fawehinmi, a prominent human rights lawyer in Lagos, said of
Achebe's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because Achebe was not regarded as an exile, his arrival
lacked the political symbolism of the return last year of Wole
Soyinka, the 1986 Nobel laureate for literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a literary milestone,'' said Mma Agbagha, a member of
the editorial board and a columnist for The Post-Express, a
newspaper based in Lagos. ``But he was never considered a very
political person, so as a political event it will not be as
significant as a literary one.''
</P>
<P>
   Achebe's novel ``Things Fall Apart'' deals with the effects of
colonialism on a Nigerian village in the early part of this
century; only one of his books, ``The Problem with Nigeria,'' was
an explicit attempt at describing the corruption and political
misrule that have bedeviled Nigeria since independence from Britain
in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having had one of the most repressive military
governments in Africa, Nigeria has produced some of the continent's
greatest writers and boasts some its most vibrant newspapers and
magazines. Writers and journalists, who took the lead in
criticizing the country's military rulers, were often imprisoned in
recent years, and some died under mysterious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after Abacha's death, his successor, Gen.
Abdulsalami Abubakar, came to the United States and met with
Soyinka, the Nobel laureate, as a sign of his sincerity in pressing
for political reform. Shortly after the meeting, Soyinka, who is as
famous here for his political defiance as for his writing, visited
Nigeria and has returned several times since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
