<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR-NYT &LR;      08-24 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S MULTIBILLION-DOLLAR SETTLEMENT WITH SLAVE LABORERS
DELAYED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The German government and leading corporations here
have been obliged to abandon a Sept. 1 target date for a
multibillion-dollar settlement with slave laborers and others
forced to work by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The date, the 60th anniversary of Hitler's invasion of Poland
and the start of World War II, had considerable symbolic resonance
because many of the forced laborers were Polish. But officials
gathering Tuesday in Bonn for talks said the negotiations remained
mired in difficulties that would not be resolved by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still some way from arriving at a figure in terms of
the size of the payment, and the Sept. 1 date has become
unrealistic,'' said Wolfgang Gibowski, a spokesman for the planned
fund to which many of Germany's largest corporations have said they
will contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the creation of the fund last February, Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said payments should start ``very quickly, if
possible before Sept. 1, 1999,'' because of the advanced age of
many of the people concerned. The average age of the surviving
victims is believed to be about 80.
</P>
<P>
   But a dispute has hardened over the number of people who qualify
as ``forced laborers,'' and so over the amount of money that should
be paid. While the companies argue that the people concerned
probably number 500,000 to 800,000, lawyers for the victims have
put forward figures as high as 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the wide difference stemmed from the fact that
the companies _ which include DaimlerChrysler, Deutsche Bank,
Siemens and Volkswagen _ contend that only those put to work by
private industry should be covered, while lawyers have suggested
that agricultural laborers and state employees should also be
compensated.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, initial German proposals that the fund should total
about $1.7 billion have been met with claims for as much as $11
billion, officials said. Otto Graf Lambsdorff, the chief German
negotiator, said Tuesday that the latter figure was ``far removed
from any realistic possibility'' and that any compromise figure
would be closer to the original offer.
</P>
<P>
   Lambsdorff was joined in Bonn Tuesday by Stuart Eizenstat, the
deputy U.S. treasury secretary, officials from the 16 companies
ready to contribute to the fund, representatives of several central
and east European governments and of the Jewish Claims Conference,
and American and German class-action lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sticking point really is the numbers,'' said Alissa
Kaplan, a spokeswoman for the Jewish Claims Conference. ``Although
the talks have been going on since February, the sides are some way
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, the German government has paid
out about $80 billion in war reparations and aid, most of it to
Jews who survived concentration camps or fled. But forced laborers
_ generally non-Jews deported to Germany from central and eastern
European countries _ often have not been compensated.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has a far smaller category of slave laborers, now estimated
to number between 100,000 and 200,000, who were put to work in
concentration camps. Many of these, but by no means all, were Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Gibowski said another important unresolved issue was that of the
assurances sought by German companies that, once the fund is
established, they will be immune from any further legal claims.
``Legal closure is critical,'' he said, ``and should be the subject
of an executive agreement between the German and American
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly global economy, and at a time when many major
German corporations have either made or are contemplating big
investments in the United States, this legal issue has become
critical. But although progress has been made toward an accord, the
issue remains outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, do the questions of who would administer the fund in
the event that an agreement was reached, and whether the fund
should include payments for those Jews whose money or other assets
were ``Aryanized'' _ forcibly transferred to non-Jewish Germans _
during Hitler's rule and have not yet been compensated.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials gathering for the three days of talks in Bonn
suggested the difficulties were such that an accord might still be
several months away. But with each month that passes, more of the
victims die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is aware that these are the final years,'' Ms. Kaplan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-SECT-665&AMP;ADD-NY     08-24 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECT-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SET TO PROSECUTE LEADERS OF SPIRITUAL MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ The Chinese authorities announced on Tuesday
that they were preparing to prosecute senior members of Falun Gong,
the spiritual movement that was banned last month after it startled
China's leaders with its ability to organize potent anti-government
protests.
</P>
<P>
   To deliver a strong message that Beijing will tolerate no
protests of any kind, the judicial authorities are now expected to
charge Falun Gong's leaders with subversion and direct that they be
sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   An order jointly issued by the Communist Party's Central
Committee and China's Cabinet specified that core members of Falun
Gong must be punished severely, the official New China News Agency
reported on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by President Jiang Zemin, the campaign against Falun
Gong has provided a vehicle for a political crusade that seems
aimed at invigorating the Communist Party's authoritarian
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's strong embrace of Marxist ideology appears to
have renewed the political firepower of security and propaganda
operations, but it seems out of touch with popular concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the explosive role that mystical forces have played
in toppling weak authorities at transitional periods throughout
Chinese history, government leaders have conducted the campaign
against Falun Gong with marked thoroughness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what many Chinese analysts see as the campaign's overkill
has led them to question whether Jiang is pursuing his own
political objectives as well, using the campaign to extend his
authority at a time when he faces multiple challenges, notably with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's order did not specify how many people would be
prosecuted. But more than 50 leaders are believed to be facing
harsh punishment for leading anti-government protests that the
authorities later described as an attempt to overthrow the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Official efforts continue to blame the leaders of Falun Gong
while ordinary followers are pardoned and encouraged to disavow the
movement. The order said that only a ``tiny minority'' of Falun
Gong followers would be charged with crimes.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong-based human rights monitor said lawyers in Beijing
had been told to get official permission before taking on cases
involving Falun Gong members, and to report any instances of Falun
Gong members approaching them for advice.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong mixes elements of Buddhism and Taoism with breathing
exercises and meditation. It also preaches frugality and abstinence
from liquor and tobacco as aids to leading a moral life.
</P>
<P>
   Disillusioned by wrenching changes in Chinese society, including
unemployment and growing corruption, millions of dispossessed
people yearning for spiritual fulfillment have been drawn to the
movement. Many are retired or unemployed workers who lost their
health benefits and believed Falun Gong's promise that illness
could be avoided or cured through meditation and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the movement by government skeptics provoked
numerous small protests in different parts of China in recent
years. But the movement came to the attention of China's top
leaders on April 25, when more than 10,000 followers surrounded
Zhongnanhai, the leadership compound in central Beijing, to demand
official recognition.
</P>
<P>
   That event, expertly organized by Falun Gong leaders, so
frightened China's high officials that they later labeled it an
attempt to overthrow the government. When the authorities formally
banned Falun Gong on July 22, they accused the movement of
corrupting people's minds and sabotaging national stability.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Falun Gong followers were detained as the
government ordered a huge campaign that reached down to every
state-run workplace in the nation and has dominated the nation's
media for weeks on end.
</P>
<P>
   Although most detainees were let go and sent home within days,
the government has proceeded with a campaign of vilification of Li
Hongzhi, who founded the movement in 1992 and now lives in New
York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Falun Gong supporters in London said on Tuesday that Li had
abandoned plans to attend a movement gathering in Britain this
weekend. Although Britain did not agree to a request from China
that Li be blocked from entering the country, Li has told reporters
in New York that he fears assassination or kidnapping by the
Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   China issued an arrest warrant for Li last month and offered a
$10,000 reward for information leading to his arrest. But Interpol
rejected a request from Beijing for help in apprehending Li, saying
the request was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Li has protested that his movement is apolitical and poses no
threat to social stability. But his credibility has been undermined
by his conflicting statements about his role in the April 25
protest, which China accuses him of masterminding.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's Communist Party statement said it was necessary to
prosecute harshly anyone who ``plotted from behind the scenes and
deliberately sabotaged social stability.'' At the same time, it
encouraged leading members of the movement to admit their mistakes
and to expose the inner workings of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Although Falun Gong leaders have insisted that the movement has
no formal organization, it was evident from the April 25 protest
that they could mobilize large groups of followers to act in a
disciplined and effective manner.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's order did not name any of Falun Gong's top leaders.
But those expected to receive the greatest punishment include Li
Chang, a former deputy director at the Ministry of Public Security,
and Wang Zhiwen, a former Railway Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed to discover that several senior military officers were
also Falun Gong followers, Chinese leaders have conducted a
crackdown in the army to root out any Falun Gong members.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the campaign, the authorities also confiscated and
destroyed millions of books, cassette tapes and videos about Falun
Gong.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's order advised work teams to treat most Falun Gong
followers as victims who were unaware of the political goals and
motives of the movement's leaders. The same attitude will probably
extend to more than 1,000 government officials who were identified
during the first week of the crackdown as Falun Gong followers and
were detained in Communist Party schools and forced to renounce any
belief in the movement.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's announcement, the campaign is evidently in its
third and final stage.
</P>
<P>
   First the authorities outlawed the movement and accused it of
threatening social stability, illustrating their assertions with
testimony of former adherents who described how harmful it was,
saying it had caused some members to die from refusing medical
treatment and others to commit suicide in fits of delusion.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the authorities expanded their campaign with accounts that
purported to show how Falun Gong was organized for political
purposes, with the ultimate aim of overthrowing the government.
</P>
<P>
   The final stage of the campaign is now expected to publicize the
punishment of the movement's leaders as an example to anyone
considering ways to challenge the authority of the Communist Party.
It is likely to be wrapped up in the coming weeks, before Oct. 1,
when the party is planning a huge celebration of its 50 years in
power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
