<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-WASTE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AUDIT URGES CANCELATION OF FEDERAL GRANTS TO FOUR TENANT GROUPS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four Atlanta tenant organizations used federal
funds to write checks to ``cash,'' order an 800 phone line, and buy
excessive equipment, says a federal audit that recommends
terminating their grants.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the third to charge abuses in the Tenant
Opportunity Program in Atlanta, part of a five-year nationwide
effort to encourage residents to manage their own public housing
and gain job skills.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development's inspector general concluded that 31 Atlanta tenant
groups that had received $100,000 grants were incapable of managing
those funds. Federal officials hired consultants and decided to
keep most of the programs in operation, despite continuing findings
of misspent funds.
</P>
<P>
   The latest inspector general audit, issued earlier this month,
advised that the Housing Department cancel further funding to the
resident associations at McDaniel Glenn, Martin Luther King Senior
Highrise, Jonesboro North and Jonesboro South public housing
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Allen, Atlanta spokeswoman for the federal housing
department, said Tuesday the findings ``look very serious.'' She
said that the four associations would be invited to respond.
Termination of the grants could take as long as six months, Allen
said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, most of the current tenant self-help grants will have
already been phased out. However, the U.S. Housing Department has
developed a replacement program, Resident Opportunities and
Self-Sufficiency, to continue giving grants.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general audit of the four Atlanta associations
found that bookkeeping was lax or non-existent. Two of the
association's had spent large sums of money, with little to show
for the expenditures, the audit reports.
</P>
<P>
   At the King Senior Highrise, for example, the tenant group spent
$47,401, nearly half of its grant, but the auditors found that
progress reports ``did not indicate any significant
accomplishments.'' Jonesboro North's group spent $38,477 of its
grant ``but had not made any substantial progress'' in
accomplishing its goals, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Three of the associations hired a contractor for job training
assistance, despite a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the approximately $130,000 in spending closely examined by
auditors, $38,000 was either ineligible for grant funding or
unsupported by documentation. For example the treasurer of one
group wrote three checks to ``cash,'' totalling $4,559. One group
paid more than $1,200 for three telephone lines, including one for
toll-free long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   _ One association had no bank statements, cash receipts or
disbursement records prior to August 1998, leaving $10,618
unaccounted for. ``The association president stated that the prior
president did not turn the books and records over to her,'' said
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The audit cited federal housing officials who directly oversee
the program but also assigned some of the blame to city housing
officials, who have an agreement to offer technical assistance to
the tenant groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rick White, spokesman for the Atlanta Housing Authority,
protested that the city had no authority in these direct federal
loans. ``There was no accountability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a toothless tiger'' when it comes to the tenant
associations, he said. ``We're unable to control how they spend
their HUD grants.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy is not new to the tenant assistance program.
Congress held hearings in 1996, when it was discovered that members
of public housing tenant associations from around the country spent
$335,000 in federal money to attend a conference in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
