<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EX-PMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PREMIERS JOINING PARTIES TO OPPOSE YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ For aspiring politicians in Russia, getting sacked by
President Boris N. Yeltsin looks increasingly like a great career
move.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for the second time in as many weeks, one of Yeltsin's
recently jilted prime minister's joined an electoral alliance that
turned Moscow's chatty political class on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   This time it is Sergei Stepashin, who served as premier for just
82 days before being fired by Russia's mercurial and increasingly
capricious president, who was at the center of attention. In a
surprise move late Tuesday night, Stepashin announced that he was
joining forces with Russia's main liberal opposition party, Grigory
Yavlinsky's Yabloko.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very fortunate alliance for both Yabloko and
Stepashin,'' said Moscow-based political analyst Andrei
Piontkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   After being fired by Yeltsin on Aug. 9, Stepashin has watched
his public approval ratings rise _ something that has become a bit
of a trend for ex-premiers lately. According to polls released over
the weekend, Stepashin is now Russia's second most trusted
politician _ behind another ex-prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov,
who was abruptly canned by Yeltsin in May.
</P>
<P>
   And while last week it was Primakov _ by far the counntry's most
popular public figure _ who made waves by forming an anti-Kremlin
political bloc with Moscow's ambitious Mayor Yury Luzhkov, Tuesday
it was Stepashin's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was sacked, Stepashin was considered by many pundits
here to be Yeltsin's hand-picked successor. The fact that he has
joined forces with a staunch Kremlin critic like Yavlinsky shows
just how isolated the deeply unpopular Yeltsin and his inner circle
have become.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin had been heavily courted by various political parties,
including Luzhkov's Fatherland-All Russia and a fledgling liberal
coalition that three of Yeltsin's other fired prime ministers _
Yegor Gaidar, Viktor Chernomyrdin and Sergei Kiriyenko _ were
trying to piece together.
</P>
<P>
   But in choosing Yavlinsky's Yabloko _ which means ``apple'' in
Russian _ analysts say Stepashin has made the best possible choice.
A widely respected economist, the prickly and principled Yavlinsky
has refused several invitations to join Yeltsin's cabinet, saying
he wants nothing to do with what he calls a corrupt oligarchic
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky's attitude drawns criticism in some quarters, where he
is accused of being unconstructive perpetual opposition figure. But
it has also won him a reputation with cynical voters as something
that many in this vast country have long considered to be an
endangered species _ an honest politician.
</P>
<P>
   Yabloko, which won 7 percent of the vote in parliamentary
elections four years ago, is the only democratic party in Russia
that is not associated in the public mind with the rampant cronyism
and corruption of the Yeltsin years. With Stepashin on board,
analysts say the party will win many more votes when Russians go to
the polls to choose a new parliament in December.
</P>
<P>
   And by hooking up with the squeaky clean Yavlinsky, Stepashin _
who recently told a Moscow newspaper that he was fired as prime
minister because he ``couldn't be bought'' _ will give his own
image a boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Stepashin, Yabloko will be able to realistically compete
with the Communists and Fatherland for the most seats in the
Duma,'' said Piontkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Stepashin and Yavlinsky pledged to work
together to form either ``an honest and effective democratic
government or a honest and effective law-abiding opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin will run for parliament from his hometown St.
Petersburg, in a district formerly represented by Galina
Starovoitova, a friend and political ally who was assassinated last
year. Stepashin said that he felt it his ``moral duty'' to
Starovoitova to win the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin and Yavlinsky also agreed to work as a team in the
presidential elections scheduled for next summer. Yavlinsky, who
finished fourth in Russia's 1996 presidential poll, has already
announced his intention to run in 2000. But given the new alliance
with Stepashin, also widely considered a presidential hopeful, it
is not clear who will be Yabloko's candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
