u f BC-TOYSMART-BOS &LR;      08-24 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY UNIT BUYING INTO WEB RETAILER OF EDU-TOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A division of the Walt Disney Co. said Tuesday that it plans to
purchase a majority stake in toysmart.com, a e-commerce retailer of
educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com aims to be the dominant e-commerce player in
educational toys, and the partnership with the Buena Vista Internet
Group, which operates Disneystore.com and ESPNstore.com, among
other Web initiatives, should help it to achieve that goal quickly,
said toysmart.com chief executive David Lord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great news for toysmart,'' said Forrester Research
analyst David Cooperstein. ``It gives them distribution they could
only dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a downside to being part of Disney's Mickey
Mouse empire _ a loss of autonomy if sales targets aren't met.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have to beware,'' Cooperstein said of toysmart. ``The
mouse that roars can eat everything in its path.''
</P>
<P>
   Buena Vista operates many Web sites, including Family.com, which
offers advice on parenting.
</P>
<P>
   With toysmart, Buena Vista can marry such ``content sites'' as
Family.com with one devoted to selling products that are ideal for
consumers who visit Family.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first stage of a transformation of a
family-content site for parenting being tied in with the best
e-commerce for families,'' said Chuck Davis, Buena Vista's
president of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Buena Vista declined to say how large a stake it bought in
toysmart.com and how much it paid for it, but industry sources
pegged the investment at between $40 million and $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for Buena Vista to fill three of the five seats on
toysmart's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart could see part of Buena Vista's investment come in the
form of promotional considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is somewhat open-ended,'' Davis said. ``But when
Disney puts its synergy machine in motion, toysmart will get reach
both on-line and off-line.''
</P>
<P>
   A privately held company, toysmart.com does not disclose
financial information, including revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com grew out of the Internet component of Holt Co., a
school supply business. Late last year, Lord, then Holt's chief
executive, bought the Web-site toy business from family-owned Holt
and dubbed it toysmart.com. Its headquarters is in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   What eToys is to Barbie and G.I. Joe, toysmart.com wants to be
for so-called ``good toys'' such as a miniature solar-powered
windmill from K'Nex, for example.
</P>
<P>
   In the brick-and-mortar world, mainstream toys are dominated by
such retailers as Toys 'R Us and Wal-Mart Stores Inc., but the
retail category for specialty toys is highly fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   Fragmented retail catergories can be ripe for e-commerce, said
analyst Cooperstein. The Internet is a great vehicle for products
that are under-marketed and hard to find, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lord, specialty toys account for nearly 40 percent
of sales for the $25 billion US toy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart already had planned a $20 million advertising campaign
to drive holiday sales; with the Disney publicity machine now
behind it, holiday expectations are even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for toysmart to add Disney toys to its product mix
and also to expand into baby products and children's furniture.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that promotes a philosophy of selling only
educational and nurturing toys, adding too many Disney toys to the
product mix could pose a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mission could get diluted if there are too many Disney
products'' on toysmart's Web site, Cooperstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
