<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHESS-MATCH-NYT &LR;      08-24 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHESS-MATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MARATHON FIRST GAME, CHESS RIVALS QUICKLY DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBERT BYRNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day after their nearly six-hour opener, Alexander Khalifman
of Russia and Vladimir Akopian of Armenia agreed to a short draw on
Monday in Game 2 of their International Chess Federation
Championship Match. That gives Khalifman a 1{-{ lead over Akopian
in the six-game series, which is under way at Caesar's Palace in
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The game was strategic and undramatic in character, with
Akopian, as Black, choosing a highly regarded defense and Khalifman
unable to make serious headway against it.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the quality of the moves, both players were surely
worn out by their demanding 58-move first-round encounter and in no
mood to risk another so soon. This time they played only 18 moves.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, too, that Akopian was waiting until he has the
advantage of the white pieces before making his move to get back on
even terms. But the pressure is on him to win. If he cannot,
Khalifman can take the title by merely drawing the next four games.
All he needs is a total of 3{ points.
</P>
<P>
   The Capablanca Variation of the Nimzo-Indian Defense, 4 Qc2, is
a conservative, positional line that protects against the doubled
pawns resulting from ... Bc3 bc. White often plays to obtain the
bishop pair, but not that way. The idea is to avoid weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no hindrance to attacking the d4 pawn (the queen
is not protecting it), Black, as here, thrusts 4 ... c5, knowing
that a routine defense like 5 e3 could be met easily by 5 ... Nc6 6
Nf3 cd 7 ed d5 8 a3 Bc3 9 bc Bd7.
</P>
<P>
   Khalifman's choice, 5 dc, opens the d line for possible later
pressure against the backward d7 pawn. The point of the development
with 5 ... Qc7 is to prohibit 6 Bf4, which could otherwise serve as
an important step in controlling d6.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategical finesse in the system Akopian adopted is 7
... Qb6, forcing 8 e3, after which the white queen bishop cannot
get to f4.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Akopian's labored mobilization, he had gotten his last
piece out with 17 ... Bb7 and had a compact, weakness-free
formation. There was no way that Khalifman could exploit the d6
pawn now. He still maintained a little space advantage, but it was
not obvious how that could be augmented.
</P>
<P>
   The one attempt at a trick, after 18 ... Nf6, would have been 19
Rd6?, which would have been proved faulty at once by 19 ... Be4 20
Be4 Bd6. Khalifman offered a draw and Akopian accepted.
</P>
<P>
   NIMZO-INDIAN DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   White Black
</P>
<P>
   Kha'man Akopian
</P>
<P>
   1. d4 Nf6
</P>
<P>
   2. c4 e6
</P>
<P>
   3. Nc3 Bb4
</P>
<P>
   4. Qc2 c5
</P>
<P>
   5. dc Qc7
</P>
<P>
   6. Nf3 Bc5
</P>
<P>
   7. g3 Qb6
</P>
<P>
   8. e3 Be7
</P>
<P>
   9. Bg2 a6
</P>
<P>
   10. 0-0 Qc7
