<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TURKEY, AN EARTHQUAKE CHANGES THE POLITICAL AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and map are being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ As recently as two weeks ago, advocates of
political and economic reform in Turkey were looking forward to a
busy and perhaps momentous autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament was to consider several far-reaching proposals,
including measures to address the Kurdish conflict, which has cost
tens of thousands of lives over the past 15 years. With the main
Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, in prison and calling for an
end to the violence, the time seemed ideal for new government steps
to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's earthquake blew even the Kurdish war off the
national agenda. Debate over the government's proposal to offer
amnesty to guerrillas who surrender, for example, has been
postponed indefinitely. Although Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit had
announced his support for large investments to combat poverty and
unemployment in the mostly Kurdish southeast, there will probably
be no money to pay for such programs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much money around anyway, but now even the modest
funds that might have gone to development projects in the southeast
are going to be diverted to earthquake relief,'' said Dogu Ergil,
director of a foundation that has advocated new approaches to
Kurdish nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask any politician today what is going to happen to the
Kurds now, he will say, `Are you crazy? What are you talking about?
This is no time to talk about the Kurdish situation.' It is no
longer a primary or even a secondary item on the political
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from the quake has passed 18,000 and is expected
to climb still higher. Rescue teams found no survivors on Tuesday
and do not expect to find any more. Tens of thousands of people are
still missing, and hundreds of thousands of survivors are homeless.
The government issued a new appeal for aid, saying it especially
needs tents, flashlights, blankets, garbage trucks, disinfectants
and tetanus vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old Turkish soldier was quarantined on Tuesday after
doctors determined that he appeared to have contracted typhoid
fever. Government officials have said they fear epidemic diseases,
but there was no indication that the soldier was more than an
isolated case.
</P>
<P>
   Caring for earthquake victims and rebuilding destroyed homes and
businesses will cost billions of dollars, which means not only that
many other projects will be postponed, but also that new taxes may
be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey had been negotiating with the International Monetary Fund
for a multibillion-dollar loan, and officials say they are
determined not to relax fiscal discipline despite the pressing need
for earthquake relief. ``Any revision in macroeconomic policies and
other reforms is out of the question,'' said the Central Bank
president, Gazi Ercel.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials said in Washington on Tuesday that they were also
considering an emergency loan.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish politicians, who won some sweeping victories in
southeastern cities in elections in April, are eager to show they
share the concerns of the rest of the country. They are helping to
raise funds for earthquake victims and have carefully avoided
pleading their own case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been through a similar situation,'' said Huseyin Umit,
mayor of Hakari and a leader of the pro-Kurdish People's Democracy
Party. ``We had our own `earthquake' when our villages were
evacuated, and we became very poor'' during the fighting between
Turkish troops and Kurdish rebels. ``Nobody has given us any help
or compensation, but we want to be mature and patient. Although
promises have been made to us, we cannot expect that they will be
kept until these difficult days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Turks hope the widespread public anger over failures in the
relief effort will lend new urgency to proposals to restructure the
state. But others fear that the anger will dissipate and that
politics will continue as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is still in a daze,'' said Kemal Koprulu, an advocate
of political reform who has been working to coordinate private
relief efforts. ``Not just the Kurdish issue but every issue has
been pushed off the agenda because the country is focused on just
one thing. But they'll come back, because they have to be tackled
in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Kurds go, there may be some positive results of
this tragedy,'' Koprulu added. ``First of all, we've been seeing
how even the poorest Kurdish towns in the southeast are sending
help to the earthquake area, which shows that they feel very much a
part of this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, some of the resistance to changing policy toward the
Kurds has been the fear that this issue is part of a plot by the
rest of the world, which hates us and is out to destroy us. That
thesis has been destroyed by the fantastic aid we've gotten from 60
countries, starting with Greece. So maybe we'll be able to look at
this situation more rationally now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
