<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8174 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 That stuff about the deficit affecting interest rates? Don't buy
it  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most enduring economic myths of this generation is
the widely held but erroneous belief that federal budget deficits
cause high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of such thinking abounded over the weekend in responses
to a Saturday column challenging a Wall Street Journal story about
how Johnson Countians seem lukewarm to the Republican tax-relief
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was fairly balanced pro and con, but typical of
those opposing the GOP tax-cut plan was a StarTouch call from a
county resident whose opposition was based on a desire to lower the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   This, he said, would keep interest rates down and thus ``help
the stock market, businesses and anyone that pays interest.''
</P>
<P>
   First of all, those who share this view should be informed that
the national debt is being paid down, even as we speak. This week's
Treasury sale of about $15 billion in two-year notes will result in
an $11.36 billion paydown of the national debt because $26.36
billion in similar notes are maturing. This is how federal debt
gets pared. Not with partisan political posturing, but with
maturing issues of Treasury securities quietly being refunded with
smaller amounts of new debt.
</P>
<P>
   As for the relationship among deficits, debt and interest rates,
the surprising reality of the past two decades is how rates
declined as deficits soared and debt ballooned. As 1981 dawned and
the national debt neared the $1 trillion mark, the prime rate banks
charge their most creditworthy business borrowers peaked at 21.5
percent. Mortgage rates and yields on long Treasuries and
investment-grade corporate bonds were headed for tops in the
mid-teens.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the long secular trend for interest rates
and inflation has been down. This has happened even though Uncle
Sam added more than $4.5 trillion to the national debt with
relentlessly humongous annual budget deficits. Only recently have
interest rates shown signs of resurgence, and the development comes
paradoxically as the federal budget is moving from red ink to
black.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for the myth seems perfectly logical. The more the
Treasury must borrow, it stands to reason, the smaller the pool of
credit available for businesses and consumers. It's called
``crowding out'' and assumes increased federal borrowing demand
will push rates higher for both government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened, but the conventional wisdom is so compelling
that most average people never stopped to ponder how conventional
wisdom had turned on its head. Now it's being turned on its head
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury expects to record a budget surplus of close to $100
billion for the fiscal year ending next month. Never mind that
nearly all of this surplus will result from excess Social Security
revenue; it's still on the books as a surplus. Nevertheless,
interest rates show signs of ending their era of decline despite
the continuing absence of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Although what's happening in the real world is counterintuitive,
it's still the reality, even without a reasonable explanation.
Therefore, if you're against a tax cut, it has to be for a more
rational reason than believing high taxes ensure relatively low
interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
