<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GAMBLING-RECORD-KAN &LR;      08-24 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-RECORD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY'S RIVERBOAT GAMBLING BREAKS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gamblers left $44.7 million behind at Kansas City's riverboats
in July, shattering monthly casino revenue records.
</P>
<P>
   That's about 60 percent of what City Hall spends during an
average month to run the whole city.
</P>
<P>
   The old record, $42.8 million, was set in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It exceeds our expectations,'' said John Finamore, Station
Casino Kansas City president and general manager, of the local
appetite for casino games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have thought a year ago it would be at this point
_ almost $45 million.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Station edged past Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP;
Hotel to seize the market share crown for the second time ever.
Last September, Station surpassed Harrah's by a fraction of a
point, but then slipped back to second place the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's General Manager Michael St. Pierre predicts the same
pattern this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely in a horse race'' with Station, St. Pierre
said. ``But their facility attracts more tourists than gamblers,
and July is the number one tourist month in Kansas City. So you'd
expect to see Station do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to another one-month run of Station
leading the market. We intend to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Station, Harrah's and Argosy Riverside Casino all set individual
revenue marks in July, with Station and Harrah's each topping $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said Station's $15.8 million month also appeared to be
a statewide record, surpassing Harrah's $15.6 million month in
August 1996 and $15.7 million last month.
</P>
<P>
   Casino revenue is expected to grow even more dramatically after
the Missouri Gaming Commission eliminates restrictive boarding
times and allows the public unfettered access to slot machines and
other betting games at the state's 15 casinos.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, that change is still at least a month away.
</P>
<P>
   The commission last week launched an open boarding pilot project
on the east side of the state. Open boarding for casinos here is
expected to be on the agenda today when the commission meets in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Commission staff members met with local casino executives
Tuesday to begin discussing the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably six to eight weeks down the road,'' Finamore
said, as casinos refine their computer programs and make physical
alterations to accommodate the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a worst-case scenario,'' he added. ``Hopefully, it's
not a big problem and we can go quicker than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaming Commission Executive Director Mel Fisher said Tuesday
that the timetable was largely up to the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their call,'' he said. ``The only thing we're interested
in is that they all do it at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the experiment in St. Louis is a success, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's going well,'' he said. ``They've had large
crowds and handled it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre said admissions and revenue were up at Harrah's
Maryland Heights property, but he declined to disclose specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore also declined to reveal financial performance figures
at Station's St. Charles casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone in our industry thinks this (open
boarding) is a pot of gold,'' Finamore said. ``I've always felt it
would be nominal. It's not insignificant. But it's somewhere
between a push and 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   State gambling officials agree. They estimate the statewide
effect at around 8 percent, or $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said early estimates in St. Louis showed that admissions
were up as much as 40 percent _ which means a big boost for state
and local governments' casino head-tax collections. Statewide, a 40
percent annual admissions bump could mean $32 million more in
head-tax collections alone.
</P>
<P>
   When Illinois' riverboats went to open boarding in late June,
admissions jumped 50 percent while revenue soared to all-time
highs. But Finamore said he didn't expect Missouri to encounter the
same kinds of revenue increase as Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Open boarding in Missouri could bring other changes as well.
</P>
<P>
   If the pilot project emerges as permanent state policy, Harrah's
twin casinos in Maryland Heights and Station's twins in Kansas City
are expected to undergo physical renovations as single-floor
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   And Harrah's North Kansas City has ambitious plans, as yet
unannounced, to expand its Mardi Gras vessel's gambling capacity
and perhaps also operate as a one-boat casino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
