<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-LONGDISTANC     08-24 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-LONGDISTANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long-distance eludes BellSouth in '99
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. is still waiting for a long-distance
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Three-and-one-half years after passage of the 1996
Telecommunications Act, officials of BellSouth are still champing
at the bit, waiting for federal regulators to let them offer
long-distance service in the nine Southeast states that make up
BellSouth turf.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like it will not happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   In touting the 1996 telecom law, politicians of both parties and
industry executives predicted a grand competition of all against
all. Regional Bells would burst into long-distance, long-distance
providers would leap into local service and consumers would reap
the benefits of choice in all manner of telecom services.
</P>
<P>
   The act has not yet delivered on those promises.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Georgia consumers _ at least those paying attention _
have been treated to a long debate, as BellSouth's competitors
insist the company doesn't deserve to be in long-distance. The
question is: Has BellSouth opened its network so that a competitive
local exchange carrier _ a CLEC _ can compete on equal footing for
local customers? That is what the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has spent more than $500 million improving its network
to make connections smoother, said Phil Jacobs, president of
BellSouth for Georgia. ``We think we have met both the letter and
the spirit of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivals argue that their orders are handled clumsily. Brian
Sulmonetti, regional director of public policy for MCI WorldCom,
scoffed at the notion that BellSouth deserves entry into
long-distance. ``I don't think BellSouth is close. Long-distance
was supposed to be the carrot so that BellSouth would open its
local network, but it doesn't seem to be enough of a carrot.''
</P>
<P>
   Caught between competing stories, the state Public Service
Commission voted in June to let neutral parties test BellSouth's
network. Hewlett-Packard and KPMG were chosen to set up a kind of
shadow CLEC. With offices in Alpharetta and Dunwoody, they will
place orders and see how they are handled. The idea is to correct
problems along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Testers were to issue a report Aug. 19, but the process was a
bit more complicated than expected, said PSC Commissioner David
Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it takes more time, we want to do it right,'' Burgess
said. ``By the end of the year, we will be in a position to make a
yea or nay decision. The results of the test are a big piece of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T both loudly called for testing, but now
criticize the process in Georgia, contrasting it to testing planned
for other states, including BellSouth in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some concerns,'' said Jaimie Hardin, AT&AMP;T vice
president for government affairs. ``This test was designed by
BellSouth. It's not a true CLEC experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess said competitors will have plenty of chance to comment
once the testers are through. But with PSC endorsement, BellSouth
could quickly file with the Federal Communications Commission for
the right to offer long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   At stake now is the long-distance market in the Southeast _ $10
billion a year flowing from BellSouth customers to AT&AMP;T, MCI
WorldCom, Sprint and others.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance has become an increasingly cutthroat business with
thinning margins, as evidenced by the spate of ads touting
dime-a-minute and even nickel-a-minute calling. Still, some of its
value is strictly defensive. Telecom companies now offer
``bundles'' of services, hoping to hold an answer for all customer
needs. So if customers have to go elsewhere for one piece _
long-distance _ they may just decide to get it all somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Packaging clearly is important,'' said BellSouth's Jacobs.
``Being able to have long-distance in your portfolio will be
critical. We don't want to be in a position where we cannot
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   And while BellSouth holds the lion's share of phone business in
its nine-state region, the horizon is filling with potential foes.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominously, AT&AMP;T has plunked down $120 billion to purchase
cable television companies like MediaOne with the idea that
upgraded cable lines will eventually offer virtually all
telecommunications services. AT&AMP;T also plans to use pieces of
BellSouth's network outside MediaOne turf, Hardin said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AT&AMP;T joins MCI WorldCom, and a pack of providers are
already offering bundles, starting with local service, to business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is lost business. While BellSouth continues to report
record profits each quarter, it has seen a steady loss of customers
to the new competition.
</P>
<P>
   About 250,000 customer lines have been lost in Georgia, and more
than 1 million lines have been taken by competitors across the
nine-state region. BellSouth has 4 million lines in Georgia and 23
million regionwide, so the loss is but a fraction of BellSouth's
business. However, it often represents the most lucrative portion _
business customers in large metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Even when allowed into long-distance, BellSouth cannot expect to
take all or even most of that long-distance market, of course. But
company Chief Executive Duane Ackerman has predicted the company
will take 20 percent of that market, expressing frustration that
the company cannot try.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. The final gatekeeper is the FCC, which has
slammed the gate shut on each bid by a Bell.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has already gone to the FCC three times _ twice for
Louisiana, once for South Carolina _ and come away with three
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Political pressure has lately mounted on the gatekeeper to let
somebody through. But it may not be BellSouth. Also working their
way toward an FCC showdown early next year are SBC in Texas and
Bell Atlantic in New York, both also going through third-party
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
