u a BC-SEATBELT-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATBELT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SEAT BELT LAW BEGINS SEPT. 1 IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Beginning Sept. 1, children under the age of 15 riding
in a motor vehicle in Texas must wear seat belts no matter where
they are seated.
</P>
<P>
   Before the state Legislature changed the law during the last
session, children between the ages of 4 and 14 did not have to wear
seat belts if they were sitting in the back seat of a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see kids that are 6 or 7 years old standing up in the back
seat,'' said Texas Department of Public Safety Trooper Steve
Hargett. ``They didn't have to wear seat belts in the back seat
under the old law. Well, now they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The law still requires the use of safety seats for children
under the age of 2 and safety seats or seat belts for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Hargett said unrestrained children become projectiles when
vehicles are involved in traffic accidents and that injury and
death can result in even minor incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen where young children were killed and there wasn't
even a collision. They are standing up on the front seat, the
parent hits the brake and they go forward and hit their head on the
dashboard,'' Hargett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hargett said motorists usually offer two basic excuses for not
using seat restraints for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they normally do, but they didn't this time because
they were in a hurry. Or, basically they don't want to fight with
the kid to make him do it because he cries or doesn't want to stay
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to DPS statistics, during the first six months of last
year, 123 children under the age of 15 were killed in Texas motor
vehicle accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Of those killed, 29 were wearing restraints while 50 were not.
In eight cases restraint usage was not known and in the remaining
incidents seat belt use was not applicable.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joan Shook, director of the emergency department of Texas
Children's Hospital in Houston, said motor vehicle accidents are
the leading cause of death and disability for children over the age
of 1.
</P>
<P>
   She said most injuries could be reduced in terms of seriousness
and in many cases prevented completely if people would use seat
belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a high-velocity wreck these children become missiles and
are propelled out of the motor vehicle and can have severe or often
fatal head injuries,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shook said progress has been made in recent years as more and
more people use seat restraints for their children but added there
is still room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   She said the excuses that are given to police are the same ones
heard in the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it is an inconvenience or they say the children
don't want to wear them,'' she said. ``You should tell them you are
not starting the motor until your seat belt is on.''
</P>
<P>
   Shook said she can understand that some people resent the law as
another government intrusion of their lives but added that in this
case the law has a worthy goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how a parent or anyone could ever forgive
themselves if they were driving a car and a child was needlessly
killed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other traffic law changes becoming effective Sept. 1 include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The legal threshold for driving while intoxicated was lowered
from .10 blood alcohol concentration to .08.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large trucks, vehicles pulling trailers, and certain types of
school buses will now be able to drive the same speed limit as cars
on interstate and state highways.
</P>
<P>
   _ The speed limit on beaches was lowered to 15 mph.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vehicle inspection fees were increased.
</P>
<P>
   _ New driver's licenses and renewals will have a surface that
the license holder can use for entering a telephone number for use
by law enforcement agencies in the event there is a need to contact
next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
