<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SURVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta reportedly ahead of U.S. in readiness
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new survey says that less than half the country's
big companies have readied their computer systems for 2000, but
local anecdotal evidence suggests metro Atlanta is doing better
than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds more severe than what I'm hearing about Atlanta
businesses,'' says Ted Fisher, a Y2K consultant who is secretary to
the Governor's Y2K Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the state's business community is safe from
computer failures triggered by an inability to recognize 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing that 10-20 percent of small businesses are facing
possibly serious problems because of Y2K,'' says Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   That percentage may not sound like a lot, but Georgia has
265,000 small businesses, representing 40 percent of the state's
work force. A small business is defined as one with fewer than 250
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The small companies in Georgia unprepared for Y2K snafus are in
good company, according to information and management consultant
Cap Gemini America.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey, the New York-based company found that only
48 percent of the biggest companies expect to have all of their
most critical computer systems upgraded to recognize 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even more worrisome is that 75 percent of the 144 corporate
information executives surveyed by Cap Gemini reported experiencing
at least one computer failure related to the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   The most common failure involved financial miscalculations. The
second-biggest problems were disruptions in processing and customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   These failures apparently have awakened companies to the Y2K
bug's potential as a troublemaker. ``The time has finally arrived
when top management views the Year 2000 challenge as a business
problem and not merely a technology problem,'' says Jim Woodward,
Cap Gemini's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini has been periodically surveying corporate information
managers at big companies about their Y2K readiness for more than a
year. Its respondents include companies from all major industries
and 17 government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
