<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-GOV-SUIT (Washington) _ Government employees are suing
their own agency seeking what they consider is fair treatment on
overtime for which they have not been paid. By David Johnston.
(Eds.: The story is exclusive and competitive; details to come;
will move at 9:30 p.m. ET in the ``w'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHAT-ROOM-SYPHILIS (San Francisco) _ In what health officials
believe is the first time a disease cluster has been traced to the
Internet, the department of public health here has tracked an
outbreak of syphilis cases to an America Online chat room. Health
officials said that six men who have contracted syphilis in the
last three months have traced their last sexual encounters to
partners they met through an America Online member-created chat
room called San Francisco Men 4 Men (SFM4M). By Evelyn Nieves.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EXTRADITE (Washington) _ A Maryland teen-ager who has
been the subject of a 17-month extradition battle between the
United States and Israel has agreed to plead guilty to murder and
accept a 24-year prison sentence in Israel, state prosecutors in
Maryland announce. By Philip Shenon. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KAN-EVOLUTION (Topeka, Kan.) _ The decision by the Kansas Board
of Education to delete mention of evolution from the science
textbooks has reignited passions on both sides. For some, the move
finally opens the door to let them teach their own beliefs in
things like ``intelligent design,'' which means a leaf is so
beautifully complex it must have been planned by a high
intelligence. For others, the move is meaningless because it is not
mandatory. Many plan on ignoring the advice of the board and
teaching evolution anyhow. By Jacques Steinberg. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-LAUNDER (Undated) _ The federal money laundering
investigation at the Bank of New York is intensifying as Attorney
General Janet Reno, Congress and British authorities joined in the
effort. By Timothy L. O'Brien and Raymond Bonner. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHER (Chicago) _ One day before the start of the
school year in Cleveland, a federal judge issues an injunction
blocking the city's four-year-old voucher program, preventing
several thousand children from attending private and parochial
schools at taxpayer expense. By Pam Belluck. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE (Williamsport, Pa.) _ With the stadium
thumping to chants of ``East! East! East!'' the boys from Toms
River stormed back into semifinals of the Little League World
Series. The swaggering bunch from New Jersey won their third
straight game, beating Brownsburg, Indiana, 3-1, in front of 15,300
fans By Tarik El-Bashir. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s''
news file.)
</P>
