<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC-NYT &LR;      08-24 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ORAHOVAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN BLOCKADE CONTINUES TO DELAY RUSSIAN PEACEKEEPERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The Netherlands, Germany, Russia)   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ Negotiations between peacekeeping commanders
and local Kosovo Albanians failed on Tuesday to end the blockade
around the town of Orahovac that is preventing Russian peacekeepers
from moving into the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians have formed mile-long blockades on the roads into
the town with trucks, cars and tractors to stop the Russians. The
Albanians kept a nightlong vigil and stayed out in force all day on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They oppose the presence of Russian troops because, they say,
Russia sided with Serbia during the NATO bombing campaign this
spring and Russian mercenaries fought in Kosovo alongside Serbian
troops. The Albanians vowed to stay until NATO revises its plan and
sends other troops.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Russian unit that is to be stationed in
Orahovac met there with commanders of the Dutch and German
peacekeepers who are there now. The Russian arrived by helicopter
to avoid the roadblocks. Together, they met with Albanian leaders,
and then with local Serbs, but the Albanians refused to back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it once again clear they don't want to have Russian
troops here in Orahovac and they want Dutch troops to stay,'' Maj.
Marcel Van Weerd, the chief of staff of the Dutch battalion, told
Reuters news agency after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Serbs with whom the peacekeepers met said they
did not care about the nationality of peacekeepers stationed in
their town. But the Serbs in the town seem to be divided on the
issue. Some say they prefer the status quo, which has brought a
certain calm to their little enclave. Others see the Russians as
potential allies and protectors.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force in Kosovo is intent on ending the protest
peacefully, and talks are to resume on Wednesday morning, said
Capt. Mike Bos, spokesman for the Dutch troops now in charge of the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't let anyone hurt anyone else, that's the most
important thing,'' he said. ``For the moment we will just hang on,
wait, keep on talking to the people so that everyone benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Dutch troops in Orahovac, Lt. Col. Tony van
Loon, said they had decided against using force to remove the
barricades and would continue trying to persuade the Albanians to
back down.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the peacekeeping force in Pristina, the
provincial capital, said that there was no chance of changing the
plan to station the Russian troops in Orahovac and suggested that
the standoff could be resolved within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, the Russian Foreign Ministry denounced the blockade
as an ``open challenge'' to the other countries involved and to
Russia's participation in the Kosovo peacekeeping force, Reuters
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's deputy defense minister, Alexander Avdeyev, said it was
up to the peacekeeping commanders to sort out the problem so the
Russians could take their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops who were supposed to move into the town,
members of the elite paratrooper division, were taking the blockade
calmly, and spokesmen for the peacekeepers commended their
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could chopper them in,'' Bos said, ``but the Russians are
thinking about the future. We are going to make sure the Albanians
and Serbs, and the Dutch, Germans and Russians, all sit down and
agree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
