u a BC-DESERT-KILLING-BOS &LR;      08-24 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-KILLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSED MURDERER'S DIARY SIFTED FOR PSYCHOLOGICAL CLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behavior scientists at a New Mexico federal crime lab are
studying murder defendant Raffi Kodikian's handwritten account of a
desert canyon slaying earlier this month, trying to discern his
state of mind when he stabbed his best friend to death.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico authorities said much of the evidence in the death of
David Coughlin, whose body was found in a shallow grave in Carlsbad
Caverns National Park on Aug. 8, was hand-delivered Tuesday to a
State Police crime lab in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   But Kodikian's journal _ a spiral notebook considered to be the
key piece of evidence _ was already being examined by the FBI's
crime lab in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Behavioral specialists are trying to use Kodikian's writings to
help unearth more information about exactly what occurred at the
bottom of remote Rattlesnake Canyon on a steamy summer weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, 25, of Boston, has told authorities that he and
Coughlin, 26, of Millis, Mass. had gotten lost in a rugged region
of the park and had run out of water. Desperate and dehydrated,
Kodikian has said he mercifully complied with Coughlin's request to
end the suffering. Authorities, however, are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studying the diary ``will do a lot of things,''
said Gary W. McCandless, the Eddy County sheriff's office chief of
detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll give us a profile. They'll be able to tell us about
this guy's life and the state of mind he was in when this was
written,'' McCandless said. ``You wouldn't believe what they can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kodikian's lawyer, Gary Mitchell of Ruidoso, N.M., said the
FBI will search in vain for any nefarious motive. Coughlin's death,
he said, was an act of mercy _ not murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to the FBI, it's not as simple as letting
some behavioral scientists tell us what happened,'' Mitchell said.
``I appreciate the fact that they're checking things out, but it's
something we don't fear from Raffi's point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said there was no dispute between Kodikian and Coughlin
at the time, and no lingering resentment over some distant
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it'll boil down to their lives being in
jeopardy,'' he said, ``and how we react to that and how people
react to heat stroke and sun stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   According to autopsy results from the Albuquerque Medical
Examiner's Office, Coughlin was suffering from moderate to severe
dehydration at the time of his death and, under those conditions,
both men could have been delusional.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, who was accompanying Coughlin cross-country on his way
to graduate school in Santa Barbara, Calif., is staying at his
family's home in Pennsylvania while awaiting trial, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rutledge, the Carlsbad prosecutor whose office will try
the case against Kodikian, said he has not decided what degree of
murder chargehe will face. Kodikian, who has waived his
arraignment, is charged with an open count of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motive is not the issue,'' Rutledge said Monday on the CNN
program ``Burden of Proof.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an element that we have to prove,'' he said. ``Juries
often want to hear a motive, but it's not an element required by
law'' to prove a defendant's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he does not expect Kodikian's trial to begin until
after Christmas. And while usually defendants are expected to
attend status conferences in New Mexico, he said Kodikian may not
have to return to the West until the trial opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no evidence in this case to justify a first- or
second-degree murder charge,'' Mitchell said. ``This is more like a
case where a wife is dying from cancer and begs to be put out of
her misery. Most of us look at that as involuntary manslaughter,
not murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, a former Boston Globe editorial assistant who had
penned an account of a 1997 cross-country trip, wrote of Coughlin's
death, ``I killed and buried by best friend today,'' according to
Eddy County Sheriff M.A. ``Chunky'' Click, who read excerpts of the
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items sent to the police crime lab in Sante Fe Tuesday
were the hunting knife authorities believe was used in the
stabbing, a poncho and plastic cover with a red stain, a rock, a
T-shirt, and a bedroll.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said Kodikian is still in ``shock'' over Coughlin's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coping. He's stable. But he needs time to mourn the loss
of his friend and he needs time to put his life in order,'' the
attorney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
