<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-ACRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DA MOVES TO BLOCK JUDGE'S ORDER FOR FELLS ACRES MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a move that one local attorney called ``highly
unusual,'' Superior Court Judge Isaac Borenstein has ordered both
sides in the Fells Acres child sex-abuse case to appear in court
Monday _ an order that Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley's
office has asked the state's highest court to quash, saying
Borenstein no longer has jurisdiction in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein's directive, issued Friday, came two days after the
Supreme Judicial Court overturned his decision granting a new trial
to Cheryl Amirault LeFave, who was convicted in 1987 of sexually
abusing children at her family's Malden day care center.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein offered no reason for the hearing in his order.
</P>
<P>
   But a court administrator said there will be ``no fireworks,''
just a routine status conference to determine when and where LeFave
will appear for the reinstatement of her conviction and sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has told me that he felt a responsibility to see this
through,'' Dana Leavitt, the administrator, said of Borenstein.
``Those were his words. He is not going to be critical of the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt also described as ``much ado about nothing'' speculation
that Borenstein is planning to publicly recuse himself from the
case, just as Superior Court Judge Robert A. Barton did in 1997
after the SJC overturned his decision to set aside the convictions
of LeFave and her mother, Violet Amirault, several years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed Monday with the SJC, Coakley's office argued
that Borenstein no longer has authority over the case and that the
court hearing should be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley's office contends that the case is within the sole
jurisdiction of the SJC until the ruling is final, 28 days from the
date it was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the decision is finalized, Coakley's office argued,
Borenstein is no longer needed to reinstate Amirault's conviction
and sentence. That process should be handled in a Middlesex County
courtroom, her office said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere in its opinion does this court order this case to be
remanded to Justice Borenstein for further action, because no
further action by him is necessary,'' argued Assistant District
Attorney David W. Cunis in the prosecution's filing.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Rankin, a defense attorney for LeFave, called
Borenstein's order and Coakley's motion to quash it a ``strange
turn of events,'' but said he planned to appear in court
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's decision by the SJC means that LeFave, who had
served eight years of an 8- to 20-year prison sentence before being
released when her conviction was overturned in 1995, will almost
certainly be returning to prison in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Rankin, who has said LeFave will no longer pursue her case in
state courts, said he had not yet decided whether to begin a
federal court appeal of her conviction or to seek clemency from
Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically back to square one trying to figure out what
legal options Cheryl has,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rankin also said that, should LeFave return to prison as
expected, it is unclear how much more time she will have to spend
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   During their imprisonment, LeFave and her mother _ who died of
cancer in 1997 _ were repeatedly denied parole, apparently because
they refused to admit guilt, Rankin said. An admission of guilt is
typically required for sex offenders to be paroled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when LeFave would be eligible for parole if she returns to
prison, a spokeswoman for the state's Parole Board said she ``can't
really speculate on the prognosis for parole at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether a prisoner has ever been paroled without first
admitting guilt, spokeswoman Alberta Cook said: ``All I can say is
that the Parole Board considers many factors. I'd rather leave it
at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
