<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-RELEVANT-Q-AND-A-COX     08-24 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELEVANT-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EHatchery brings aid, comfort to Internet-savvy entrepreneurs
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jeff Levy is an Internet success story. With his
friend and colleague Tim Cobb, he founded Relevant Knowledge, a
firm that proposed to measure Web traffic the way Nielsen measures
TV viewers. It was a novel idea at the time, but quickly became an
industry standard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Relevant Knowledge merged with rival firm Media Metrix.
As the company's vice chairman, Levy helped lead the company to its
successful initial public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Now Levy is on his own again with a new Atlanta-based company
called eHatchery, an Internet-based incubator where entrepreneurs
can literally bring in an idea scrawled on the back of a napkin.
EHatchery will help turn it into a full-fledged company complete
with office space, strategic alliances, feature articles in the
trades and one day, perhaps an IPO of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dreams certainly came true with Relevant Knowledge,'' Levy
says. ``I'm excited by the opportunity to make other entrepreneurs'
dreams come true. It's exciting to look across the entire Internet
and all the opportunities out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Levy's first-person experience combined with
a stellar management team should give eHatchery a running start.
Former MCI WorldCom veteran Bill Wallace is chief operating
officer, and ex-Coca-Cola marketing guru Sergio Zyman is a senior
adviser. Levy also has the backing of the Pasadena, Calif-based
idealab, one of the top Internet incubators in the country whose
success stories include GoTo.com, eToys and Free-PC.
</P>
<P>
   Levy believes the next wave of Web entrepreneurs will be
Atlanta-based. From vacation in Martha's Vineyard, Mass., he spoke
about the changing landscape of Internet start-ups and the changing
shape of Atlanta's growing Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How different is it starting an Internet company today from
when you began Relevant Knowledge in 1996?
</P>
<P>
   A: Atlanta is much more Internet-savvy than it was three years
ago. There are several venture capital firms, law firms, accounting
firms, public relations and marketing firms focused on the
Internet, which you did not see in 1996. You had to go out of town
in 1996. Relevant Knowledge used a Palo Alto, Calif., law firm
then. Now we use an Atlanta firm. The Internet has been
mainstreamed, and it's been accepted by the establishment. It's not
some way-out-there thing to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What makes Atlanta the place to start a venture like this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think this is the best place to start an Internet business
in the country. There's a wonderful infrastructure, thanks to the
Olympics. There's a sense in the venture capital community that
Atlanta is up and coming, and they see Atlanta as a new source of
venture opportunities. There's also a great labor supply, and I
don't mean people who've been working for Internet companies, but
people who've been working for large companies like Turner, Cox,
BellSouth, MCI, Lucent and UPS who have skill sets you can apply to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you see eHatchery fitting into Atlanta's incubator
landscape? Isn't having ATDC (the Advanced Technology Development
Center) incubator at Georgia Tech enough?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're really very different from ATDC or almost any incubator
you've ever heard of.
</P>
<P>
   We're different in that we invest equity in our companies,
focusing exclusively on Internet companies. We won't be
technology-driven, but technology-enabled. Our companies won't be
selling hardware or software, but using technology to enable their
businesses. We are really focused on turning a great idea into a
great business. We provide all the financial and administrative
benefits. This is really plug and play _ you can have an idea one
day and a business the next.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will eHatchery do that other incubators can't, won't or
don't do?
</P>
<P>
   A: We want to bridge the gap between the time the company has an
idea and the time they can accept traditional venture capital. We
grow the business from an idea to 20 employees and a prototype.
That's really our sweet spot. I'm one of the few people in the
country that's seen an idea through from concept to public
offering. So I'm able to share experience with people as they go
through the process themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
