<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SAVARESE LOOKS TO FIRST WIN WITH REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He was the last man off the practice field Monday
evening at Babson College, but before he reached for a water
bottle, Revolution defensive midfielder and two-time MLS All-Star
Leonel Alvarez had a few words of encouragement for his new
teammate, Giovanni Savarese.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into his tenure with the Revolution, the 34-year-old
former Colombia national team mainstay _ traded from the
playoff-bound Dallas Burn to the struggling Revolution on Aug. 13 _
prefers not to look back at opportunity lost, but to look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And if his experience and stature can rub off on his new team,
which is mired in a seven-game losing streak going into Wednesday
night's road game against the MetroStars, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy has always been to work extra hard with my
teammates, in order to win and to always take advantage of the home
field,'' said Alvarez through interpreter and Revolution media
relations assistant Jurgen Mainka. ``It is very important to me to
give our fans the satisfaction of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened lately, because the Revolution haven't won
since July 4, when they knocked off New York/New Jersey
(Wednesday's foe) at Foxboro Stadium. Simply put, the Revolution
have fallen and they can't find the net _ at least not very often
and not early enough. In those seven losses, the Revolution have
never taken a lead.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot, though, has been Alvarez, who has the
reputation as a fearless defender and smooth passer and has shown
his new team both of those attributes. Still, Alvarez admits has
has walked into a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from a team that had already qualified for the playoffs
with 14 games to go, a team that had a need to win,'' he said.
``Here, the key is for us to all have a big heart, a great heart.
It is a hard transition to come from a team with a lot of happiness
to a team that needs a lot of work in order to be happy with their
play.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alvarez said he has nothing to prove to the Revolution or to
his old team; rather, the task ahead is to maintain his presence as
a world-class player and leader while blending into the team
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot demonstrate anything new,'' he shrugged. ``The
important thing is to practice and play as a group. I look forward
to the task and the new responsibility of coming here. Our
salvation is not me, it's us. All of us. We must be more positive
and work _ for a good coach, Walter Zenga. Many players in the
world would trade places with players here to play for Zenga.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Revolution, Zenga's accumulation of yellow
cards has resulted in a one-game suspension, so he'll be coaching,
but not playing in goal. Some pressure will thus fall on Alvarez to
provide a veteran presence on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese, the former MetroStar, is happy that Alvarez will be
there to try to end the long losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win,'' said Savarese. ``We have been very lucky
that teams we are chasing for a playoff spot have also been losing
or only winning 1 point and we have to take advantage of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonel brings a lot of things to this team,'' he added. ``He's
a leader, he controls the ball, he's experienced, but most of all
he's a warrior who wants to win. Every time you're with him, he's
talking about the game and ways to win it. He's a big asset for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese said that during a break at Monday's practice, ``Leonel
was talking to me about Wednesday's game, what we need to do and
how we could become better as a team. With his experience, it's
great to have him. He says what he believes and what he thinks.
He's the first one to come to the practice field to help the other
players and he's the last to leave and that's to his credit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
