<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-COLA-WARS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLA-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT DRINK COMPANY PLAYS HARDBALL IN TEXAS SCHOOL LAWSUITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Coke may claim to be the ``real thing'' in its ads,
but Dr Pepper says in a lawsuit filed Monday that it, and not Coke,
should be the only thing at Pearland Junior High East.
</P>
<P>
   The Dr Pepper Bottling Co. of Texas, based in Dallas, has sued
the Pearland Independent School District and the former principal
of the junior high school, Jacqueline Cobbin, because it claims it
had an exclusive contract to sell its soft drink products at the
Houston-area school.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Dr Pepper Bottling paid $2,640 to
erect a scoreboard at the Pearland Junior High East gym in 1996, in
exchange for the right to be the only soft drink sold at the school
until 2001. A contract signed by Dr Pepper Bottling and Cobbin in
March 1996 was included with the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But in October, the school district decided things go better
with Coke. The school district signed a contract to receive
$910,000 from Coca-Cola in exchange for selling only Coke soft
drinks at all its schools for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr Pepper is seeking unspecified damages in its state district
suit and is also asking that its contract be honored.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taszarek, executive vice president of Dr Pepper Bottling Co.
of Texas, said Tuesday that the company has 10 similar lawsuits
pending across the state. He said he believes the suit against the
Pearland district will be resolved before trial, but declined to
comment further.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to discuss why the Texas bottler of Dr Pepper _
a drink invented in Waco in 1885 _ has so many lawsuits against
school districts in the state. Taszarek said Dr Pepper is owned by
Cadbury Schweppes of London.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lenamon, spokeswoman for the 10,000-student Pearland
school district, said the district is not aware of any exclusive
contracts Cobbin may have signed with Dr Pepper. She said
principals do not have the authority to sign such contracts, and
that if it were signed it would not have legal standing.
</P>
<P>
   Lenamon said Cobbin left the school district two years ago to
work for a state education agency that oversees a five-county
region. She said Cobbin's departure had nothing to do with the Dr
Pepper flap.
</P>
<P>
   Lenamon said the scoreboard at the 680-student junior high does
not sport a Dr Pepper logo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
