<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENDORSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush gets significant backing of state GOP
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Days before his first campaign swing through Georgia,
Republican presidential frontrunner George W. Bush increased his
backing in the state to include a majority of GOP legislators.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of them encouraged Bush to put an end to the
questions over possible past drug use that have dogged the campaign
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Bob Irvin, one of the 52 Republican
lawmakers who endorsed the Texas governor, said he should ``tell
the truth and the full truth as soon as possible . . . Something
somebody does a long time ago is a whole lot less important than
their behavior as an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had refused to answer any questions about rumors that he
had taken drugs as a young man. Recently he has indicated that he
had not taken illegal drugs for at least the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the frenzy over the side-stepped question apparently did
little to diminish Bush's support in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 100 Republican lawmakers in the state
House and Senate, along with all five of the party's statewide
elected officials, endorsed Bush in a campaign-coordinated release
timed just before Bush's fund-raising visit Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a choice whether to try to play it safe, or whether
you want to help lead the process,'' said Irvin (R-Atlanta), who
called Bush's record as Texas governor a solid basis for a
successful presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Among those throwing their support behind Bush are 33 of the 78
House Republicans and 19 of the 22 GOP Senate members.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP leadership in both bodies, though, remains split
among Bush and other GOP contenders, including former American Red
Cross President Elizabeth Dole. On Friday, Bush plans to tour MUST
Ministries at 10:30 a.m. Nancy Morris, director of the inter-faith
agency that helps people in need, said her organization is
nonpartisan but welcomes a visit from any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased to represent the poor in our community to a
national candidate,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathey Pruitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
