<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENTAL DOUBLE TRANSPLANT GIVES WOMAN NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was a medical Catch-22 that pushed Janet McCourt to
volunteer for an unprecedented experiment in transplantation that
would save her life _ and perhaps, researchers said Tuesday, mark a
turning point in organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble paid off when McCourt, 57, a contractor from
Pembroke, received successful bone marrow and kidney transplants
simultaneously from her sister in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital say the double
transplant showed for the first time that giving bone marrow along
with an organ transplant from the same donor can eliminate the need
for anti-rejection drugs most transplant recipients need for the
rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The sister's bone marrow ``educated'' McCourt's own immune
system so that it wouldn't reject the transplanted kidney as
foreign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that this will be the beginning of trying to extend''
this strategy to many more transplant patients in the future in
hopes of avoiding lifelong immunosuppression, said Dr. David Sachs,
head of the transplant biology research center at MGH, where
McCourt underwent the procedure last September.
</P>
<P>
   McCourt's double bind was created in 1997 when she was diagnosed
with multiple myeloma _ a form of blood cancer _ and kidney
failure. Because of the life-threatening cancer, she didn't qualify
for a kidney transplant, and, conversely, her kidney disease ruled
out a bone marrow transplant for the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been a fighter all my life, and I wasn't going to
accept that I was going to die,'' McCourt said Tuesday. In
particular, she vowed to live long enough to see her pregnant
daughter give birth to a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   After scouring the Internet and knocking on doctors' doors in
search of some new hope, she was referred to MGH, where Sachs, Drs.
Thomas Spitzer and Megan Sykes, and other researchers awaited a
good candidate for testing their strategy of using bone marrow
transplants to make the patient's body safe for an organ transplant
from the same person. It had already given spectacular results in
animals: One monkey is still healthy five years after a transplant,
without taking anti-rejection drugs. But the researchers would try
it for the first time in a human only in someone who needed both
the bone marrow and organ transplants anyway, to make sure they did
no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCourt said Tuesday that the doctors were at first
reluctant to try the technique on her, in part because she was so
weakened from the kidney disease that they didn't know if she would
survive the transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors also insisted that McCourt find a bone marrow donor
who was a perfect immunological match, to reduce the risks that the
transplants would be rejected. Again, fortune was in her favor:
Tests found that one of her sisters was an exact match. And of the
three sisters who were tested, the one who matched ``was the one
sister I knew would go ahead and do it, without letting her family
or anyone stop her,'' McCourt said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report this week in the journal Transplantation, the MGH
researchers describe the successful maneuver, in which they
undertook the double transplant and weaned her off
immunosuppressive drugs. That was nearly a year ago. Today she is
healthy, with no sign of organ rejection, and her cancer is in
remission. ``I feel very lucky,'' she said. ``I was not only able
to see my grandson born, but a granddaughter, too'' when her son's
wife gave birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important study,'' said Dr. Abdul Rao, director of
cell transplantation at the University of Pittsburgh Medical
Center, where related experiments are under way. ``But there has to
be an element of caution, because what will happen with another
individual is a different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow transplants for cancer are common, and are done
because the high doses of radiation or chemotherapy needed to
eradicate the cancer also destroy the patient's own bone marrow
tissues. Bone marrow generates blood cells, including the white
cells that form the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   A key difference in the new experiment is that the MGH
researchers gave McCourt a milder form of chemotherapy than would
be given in a conventional transplant. McCourt was so sick she
couldn't tolerate the normal doses of chemo, and and the doctors
wanted to make sure some of her own bone marrow cells would
survive. Part of the chemotherapy was aimed at killing off the
mature immune T-cells in her own bone marrow, so that they would
not attack the kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy created a ``mixed chimera'' in McCourt _ a mingling
of hers and her sister's bone marrow cells so that neither
dominated. ``It's believed that allowing some of the recipient's
bone marrow to survive may suppress'' a common complication of
transplants in which the donor marrow or organ attacks the host,
said Spitzer, lead author of the report, which also included as
authors Drs. Sachs, A. Benedict Cosimi, and Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the MGH researchers say they will use this strategy
only in patients who already need a bone marrow and organ
transplant at the same time, because the safety of the double
transplant is still not certain. Eventually, patients who need only
an organ may be pre-treated with the bone marrow solely to
``educate'' the host immune system not to attack the graft, they
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
