<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-CBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY, CBS IN HUGE MULTIMEDIA AD DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fidelity Investments and CBS Corp. have signed an
advertising deal reportedly worth $50 million that gives the Boston
mutual fund company a huge presence on CBS television, radio,
Internet sites, and billboards, the companies said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which begins this fall, is one of the first and
said to be the largest deal so far assembled by CBS Plus, the
network's new sales unit set up last fall to peddle big multimedia
advertising packages.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the kind of deal that analysts said will become more
common as companies struggling for attention in a world cluttered
by an unprecedented cacaphony of advertising look to mega-giants
that control outlets across the electronic and print spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will put Fidelity spots in virtually every market in
the country and include specially tailored slots on drive-time
radio, cable television, local broacast affiliates as well as on
national news and popular Internet sites like CBS.com,
CBS.MarketWatch.com, and CBS.Sportsline.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a more synergistic approach to
advertising,'' said Steve Cone, president of Fidelity's customer
and marketing development unit. ``We're getting a very large amount
of exposure out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cone nor CBS would discuss the value of the deal, but
the respected trade publication Advertising Age reported the $50
million figure.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity will have a ``dominant presence'' on each of CBS's
major Web sites, especially CBS.Marketwatch _ an interactive site
with business and financial news _ where Fidelity plans to have
banner advertisements and to sponsor new content, Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Billboard and other outdoor advertising through CBS-owned
Transit Display Inc. and soon-to-be acquired Outdoor Systems will
be pumped up in selected cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Fidelity will sponsor a segment on the CBS
Evening News with Dan Rather called ``The American Dream.'' The
four-to five-minute segment, slated to debut Sept. 15 and run each
Wednesday, will be an upbeat feature on people who pursue and
achieve their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity and its ad agency, Hill Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos,
will create ads specifically for ``American Dream,'' Cone said.
Under terms of the sponsorship arrangement, CBS will plug Fidelity
before the segment runs and give the company the first advertising
slot after it ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will be a very uplifting, very positive segment,''
Cone said of ``American Dream.'' ``It's something we can promote to
our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusually close arrangement between an advertiser and a
specific news segment could raise questions among media critics
about Fidelity's influence on the segment's content, observers
said.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS spokesman Dana McClintock said the segment was conceived
and produced independent of the Fidelity deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not created with Fidelity or any other sponsor in
mind,'' he said. ``It was pre-existing content. This was a concept
Fidelity wanted to wrap itself around. The Evening News has high
standards of objectivity and would not allow any relationship to
interfere with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity said it approached other networks about doing a similar
deal but found CBS the only one able to put together a single
package that provided advertising through all its media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Plus assembled the deal after Fidelity approached the
company in January. Previously, the unit has done similar deals
with Penzoil and Taylor-Made-Golf, but Fidelity is the largest to
date, CBS said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, meanwhile, says it may look for similar deals with
other media giants, like Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll probably see us doing more of this in the future,''
Cone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
