<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GUNS-EDITORIAL-COX     08-24 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-EDITORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outlaw sniper rifles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sharp-shooting rifleman has long been canonized in American
mythology. The war for independence supposedly was won, in part,
because the British insisted on marching in formation, while the
wily colonials hid behind rocks and trees, firing their muskets to
pick off the enemy one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Frontiersmen like Davy Crockett and Daniel Boone were legendary
marksmen. From Gary Cooper playing Sgt. York to Audie Murphy
playing himself, Hollywood has often turned the country boy who
could hit a running rabbit at 100 yards into the man whose skills
with a rifle made him a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder then, that in a nation awash in guns, the
.50-caliber sniper rifle has become one of the most coveted weapons
among American gun enthusiasts. It promises armor-piercing
firepower and accuracy that allows it to hit a target a mile away.
If you've got about $6,000 or so to spend, you can get it through
your local gun dealer. Or if you want to shop around for a bargain,
you can check out the ones offered over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But more than showing the power of an American myth, the
popularity and easy availability of this weapon shows the level of
an American madness: Our tolerance for guns and our resistance to
reasonable regulation of their sale and possession.
</P>
<P>
   Like other rifles and long guns, the .50-caliber sniper rifle is
exempt from most of the minimal restrictions placed on handguns. An
18-year-old can buy one. And the armor piercing ammunition that has
been banned for use in handguns can be legally purchased and used
in rifles. Congress has refused to treat the .50-caliber sniper
rifle any differently from any other long gun since it began
circulating among civilians in the 1980s. Even pleas from the
Secret Service _ justifiably concerned that the weapon made
protecting the president more difficult _ went unheeded.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and other pro-gun groups argue
that concern about having the sniper rifle in civilian hands is
unfounded. They say the weapon is too expensive and too large to be
of use to criminals and the other people we worry about. The sniper
rifle, they say, is much more likely to wind up with the well-off,
responsible gun aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   However, the FBI says it has tracked at least 17 incidents in
which suspected criminals had .50-caliber sniper rifles. The weapon
has been found in the possession of drug dealers and terrorists.
Clearly, ownership of this gun is not and will not be the exclusive
domain of gun hobbyists. And the more sniper rifles in circulation,
the more likely that some of them will fall into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills dealing with .50-caliber sniper rifles are part of the
renewed push to get gun control legislation through a Congress
aroused by the recent string of shootings across the nation. One
would ban civilian possession of the gun outright. The other would
ban the sale of armor-piercing ammunition for the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Banning both the weapon and the ammunition is what's called for.
We don't need this kind of firepower on our streets. But at the
very least, we shouldn't allow the sale of ammunition that makes
this rifle more dangerous, especially for law enforcement officers
and public officials who are subject to the threat of
assassination. The .50-caliber sniper rifle can make the president
_ riding in an armored limousine _ as vulnerable as those British
soldiers marching across open fields.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in The Atlanta Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
