A8234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STAROFDAVID-COX     08-24 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAROFDAVID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit over Jewish star likely to end
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Now that a student in Gulfport, Miss., is allowed
to wear his Star of David necklace to school, the American Civil
Liberties Union likely will abandon its lawsuit against the
district that banned the Jewish symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The Harrison County School Board on Monday voted to lift the ban
on the necklace, which resembles a local gang symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pretty much resolves the issue,'' said David Ingebretsen,
head of the Mississippi chapter of the ACLU. ``It's likely we will
withdraw our suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, school board members voted unanimously to prohibit
high school junior Ryan Green from wearing the necklace because
they said it would give gang members the right to wear their
six-pointed stars. Gang symbols are strictly forbidden on school
grounds in the Gulf Coast district. The ACLU, along with Tom Green,
Ryan's father, filed for an injunction Friday in federal court to
prevent the board from enforcing its policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake, that's it,'' said Randy Williams, president
of the school board. ``The decision to ban the Star of David was
strictly a safety decision, and we never considered the religious
implications or that we were denying the student his first
amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began two weeks ago when Ryan Green wore the
Star of David to the first day of classes. Green's grandmother gave
him the necklace over the summer. A teacher noticed its resemblance
to a local gang symbol and told him he could not wear it to school.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the board members decided to let Ryan Green wear
the necklace because they realized religious freedom is more
important than fear of gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real victory for the Green family,'' Ingebretsen
said. ``But it's a shame they had to go through this ordeal to get
his religious rights restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
