<HEADER>
A8235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-24 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: BRITAIN, RUSSIA, VENEZUELA, ARGENTINA,
MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: IT'S LORD ROBERTSON NOW
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary George Robertson, 53, who is leaving the
government to become general secretary of NATO, has been made a
peer with the title of Lord Robertson of Port Ellen, the village on
the Hebridean Island of Islay where he was born. His elevation to
the House of Lords moves up the date of the by-election for his
seat in Parliament to Sept. 23, helping the governing Labor Party
by limiting the time the Scottish Nationalists can mount an
organized challenge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: DAILY DUE BACK ON STANDS
</P>
<P>
   Kommersant, one of Moscow's most respected daily newspapers,
will resume publication Wednesday after it was shut down for a day
by city authorities for what were said to be violations of fire
safety codes. Editors of the paper, which was recently bought by
Boris Berezovsky, a financier and media magnate with close ties to
the Kremlin, denounced the shutdown as a ``silly'' attempt by Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow to put pressure on the news media.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: DAGESTAN CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said they were on the verge of reclaiming
control of territory seized two weeks ago by Islamic militants who
crossed into Dagestan Province from the secessionist republic of
Chechnya. A spokesman for the militants said they had withdrawn in
order to regroup as they shift tactics in their fight for
Dagestan's independence. According to military reports, Russian
troops were still engaged in scattered fighting in the mountainous
region between Dagestan and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: NEW OPPOSITION ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Stepashin, one of Russia's former prime ministers,
announced that he would join forces with Grigory Yavlinsky's
liberal opposition party Yabloko in parliamentary elections in
December. Stepashin, whose three months in office gave him a
national reputation and modest popularity, backed out of a
coalition last weekend with parties made up of former allies of
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: HIGH COURT CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Accusing her colleagues of capitulating to political pressure by
ruling that a new constitutional assembly has authority to take
control of the judicial system, the chief justice of the Supreme
Court, Cecilia Sosa, has resigned. ``The court simply committed
suicide to avoid being assassinated,'' she said in a nationally
televised news conference. ``But the result is the same: It is
dead.'' She also criticized Congress and political parties for not
resisting what she called attempts by President Hugo Chavez to
concentrate power in his own hands through the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: GAYS IN MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Martin Balza, who retires as the commander of the army in
December, suggested that the military code should be amended so
that military personnel found to be homosexuals would no longer
face prison sentences of up to six years. But he added that he did
not want to allow declared homosexuals to enter the military. Any
change in the military code must be approved by the high command
and the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: OPPOSITION TALKS FALTER
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations to form a coalition of opposition parties for
Mexico's July 2000 general elections turned difficult. Eight
parties opposed to President Ernesto Zedillo's Institutional
Revolutionary Party have written a joint electoral platform but
have failed to agree on how to select a single presidential
candidate. The center-left Party of the Democratic Revolution
suggested that the months of talks should end, in success or
failure, by Aug. 31. But the pro-business National Action Party
said it would ignore that deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
