<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-DISEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE SURVIVORS FEAR DISEASE THREAT, DESPITE ASSURANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ Medical experts say the chances of an epidemic
sweeping Turkey are slight. But in areas hit hard by last week's
earthquake, many survivors are panicked by the stench of rotting
corpses, the government's distribution of surgical masks, and local
newspaper reports of cities under quarantine.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of last week's quake, which killed nearly 18,000
people and left hundreds of thousands homeless, have been besieging
medical care units, looking for vaccinations against infectious
diseases like cholera and typhoid fever, and stocking up on
medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are coming and asking for a special vaccination that can
cover all kinds of infectious diseases, but what they really want
is something that can give them back their happiness,'' said Sahika
Yuksel, a psychiatrist working in a clinic in Adapazari.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the region hit by the quake is completely without
running water and electricity has not yet been fully restored. For
many living in makeshift tent camps without proper toilets or
washing facilities, the threat of killer diseases seems real.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish newspapers have run reports _ false ones, as it turned
out _ that some of the areas hit hardest by the quake were put
under quarantine. People have started walking around their now
rubble-strewn cities with masks covering their noses and mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what might break out, we must protect ourselves with
whatever we can,'' said Sukru Atar, 52, wearing a green surgical
mask as he rummaged through a pile of donated clothing in
Adapazari.
</P>
<P>
   But international health experts say the chance of cholera,
typhoid fever or plague epidemics are low as long as basic sanitary
measures are taken, like providing clean water and reminding people
to wash their hands and stay away from feces.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish authorities have been distributing bottled water to
people in the quake region and medical workers have gone around and
explained to people the need to take sanitary measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see in some areas they have resumed collecting trash.
. . . It's spotty but it shows a level of capacity to deal with the
problem and that the system is coping,'' said Steve Catlin, leader
of the disaster assistance response team for the US Agency for
International Development, or USAID.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say panic after such disasters is common _ it
happened after the quakes in Mexico, Los Angeles and Armenia _ but
epidemics much less so.
</P>
<P>
   Epidemiologists from the US Centers for Disease Control have
been scouring Turkey to asses the health risks in the wake of the
earthquake and so far they have not found evidence of a possible
outbreak of killer diseases, USAID officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always concern after a disaster about disease . . .
but I have reviewed the records of earthquakes over the past 25
years and it's very, very rare to have an epidemic, virtually
unheard of,'' said Eric Noji, an epidemiologist with the World
Health Organization sent here to evaluate the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The report Tuesday of what might be the first case of typhoid
fever was sure to increase panic, however.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli doctors working in the city of Adapazari, where
thousands are without homes or running water, Tuesday hospitalized
a Turkish soldier showing signs of typhoid, including diarrhea and
fever. But they said he could have a different infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it is typhoid it's not a big deal, you have it in
America and in Israel. . . . We have antibiotics for this type of
thing and it's not a problem to bring in more medicines right away
if we need it,'' said Carlos Gruzmann, a doctor at the Israeli
field hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal authorities, meanwhile, have been spreading lime
around collapsed buildings, but the fear of infection has led some
workers to keep on spraying the lime, even over people walking down
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably creating a respiratory problem more than
alleviating any contaminationa,'' said USAID's Catlin. ``In
general, bodies don't pose a health risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
