<HEADER>
A8239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH-WHITE-COX     08-24 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-WHITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech receiver credits mom for stardom
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask Dez White whom he credits for helping turn his
football fortunes around.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech receiver caught just 10 passes as a high school
senior in Jacksonville and none as a Yellow Jackets freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as a sophomore, White had 46 receptions for a
school-record 973 yards and nine touchdowns, including five
touchdown catches of 50 yards or more. He also had 1,655
all-purpose yards, including a 100-yard kickoff return against
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The All-America candidate doesn't brag about his turnaround. And
he doesn't give the credit to head coach George O'Leary or
receivers coach Stan Hixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, my mother has been my inspiration,'' White says.
``She instilled in me such a strong work ethic that I couldn't help
but keep working on getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been driven in me by my mother from the beginning. I
don't tell her enough how much I love her.''
</P>
<P>
   Desiree White, an insurance auditor who also worked as a
beautician and financial consultant to put her son, Edward Dezmon,
and daughter, Christalyn, through the expensive, private Bolles
School in Jacksonville, gushes when told about her son's praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a sweetie,'' Desiree White said. ``He really does love
our family, and he shows it. When he comes home from school, he
doesn't go anywhere. He just wants to be with all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers aren't the most impressive thing about Dez White.
And they aren't what impress his teammates most about one of the
premier receivers in college football and a contender for the
Biletnikoff Award.
</P>
<P>
   In one spring practice this year, White went into motion during
a goal-line drill, lined up right, then came back toward the middle
and made a fantastic block. The wipeout of the defensive end
allowed a teammate to score and brought shouts of joy and slaps on
the back from quarterback Joe Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``People block for me all the time when I get out in the open
field,'' White said, ``so I like to return the favor every chance I
get.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a speedy _ although his 40-yard-dash time is a closely
guarded Tech secret _ and now sure-handed wide receiver tough
enough to cut back and block big defensive ends _ and humble enough
to warm his mother's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dez White is the type of guy who, if he drops passes, he will
stay after practice,'' Hamilton said. ``He's the type of guy you
want to go to war with, because you know he will be there.
Everything with Dez White is the total package.''
</P>
<P>
   This preseason, White and the No. 11-ranked Yellow Jackets have
attracted plenty of attention. For White, it surely will continue.
When he lines up, more than one defensive back certainly will
follow.
</P>
<P>
   He is comfortable with the attention, because he knows that it
should open the field for speedy receivers Kelly Campbell and Kerry
Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to do whatever it takes to help this team win,''
White said. ``If that means a reduced role for me, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Desiree White, who would not let Dez play sports in high school
when his grades were not up to her standards, is proud of her son's
success. But that's not what gives her the most joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a football family,'' said Desiree, whose brother,
Adrian White, played nearly 10 years in the NFL. ``But I'm not a
football mom. With Dez, I'm really most proud about how he has held
on to his Christian values.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves football, and if he reaches his (NFL) goals, that's
great. But just knowing he has a relationship with the Lord is
enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   FILE ON DEZ WHITE
</P>
<P>
   _ Full name: Edward Dezmon White.
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: Aug. 23, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ht., wt.: 6-1, 214.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Orange Park, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Major: Management.
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Did you know? Was an all-state soccer player . . . Highly
sought after as strong safety as well as wide receiver . . . Only
third player in Tech history (Drew Hill and Gary Lee are the
others) to return two kickoffs for touchdowns in a career.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
