<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     08-24 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS, ANGELS: DOG DAYS INDEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital) Today's well-rested edition of The Sporting Muse
(ital):
</P>
<P>
   Short of Kevin Brown suffering a career-ending injury, perhaps
tearing a rotator cuff while toweling off after a game, there
doesn't appear to be anything left to dog the Dodgers for the
balance of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros has been shopped on the open market and discounted
like extra linen at a white sale. Raul Mondesi's fan base has
turned on him after he turned on Dodger management. Davey Johnson
has worn that ``what-the-hell'' look on his face so much that it
has become his regular appearance. And G.M. Kevin Malone is still
talking.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a situation that could sustain the Dodgers'
embarrassment through the postseason and into spring training. That
would be the New York Mets winning the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the regret if Mike Piazza gets a World Series ring with
the Mets. As bad as The Trade was at the time, this would make it
worse. It would also show what a non-issue those leadership and
chemistry debates were while he was here.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the despair if Bobby Valentine, one of the most
disingenuous people in baseball, gets the Mets a title, thereby
giving credibility to Dodger-for-life Tommy Lasorda's Hall of Fame
comment that he'd hire Valentine to manage a team.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets winning the World Series would be proof that things can
always get worse. ...
</P>
<P>
   Could they? Yes, and for multiple reasons. The Mets play the
best defense in all baseball, have the deepest bullpen, and are
pounding the ball. Their bullpen is strong despite the absence of
John Franco, with Armando Benitez, Turk Wendell and Dennis Cook
tag-teaming opponents.
</P>
<P>
   And seven of the eight regulars in the lineup entered Tuesday's
game hitting .300 or better. The only guy under .300 is defensive
whiz Rey Ordonez (.263). Edgardo Alfonso has 20 home runs and 87
runs scored. John Olerud has 15 homers and 75 RBI. Piazza is at 30
and 97, and Robin Ventura, who several teams passed on, has 28 home
runs and 101 RBI. Oh, and ex-Dodger Roger Cedeno leads the N.L. in
steals (58).
</P>
<P>
   The only area the Mets are subpar has been starting pitching,
with none of the regulars stepping up as an ace. But postseason
play often brings out the best in struggling pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the competition to consider. It helps the Mets a
great deal that the Atlanta Braves must deal with postseason
psychological issues. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'd comment at length on the Angels situation, but it appears no
one cares, and that includes the players and owners.
</P>
<P>
   If they did care, then the players wouldn't have let their angst
about Terry Collins' methodology get the best of them. They also
wouldn't have spent so much time back-biting each other. They've
all bitten more than Marv Albert and Mike Tyson combined.
</P>
<P>
   If Disney cared, they wouldn't have let reports about a sale go
by without comment. All this trauma may have come from different
places, but it afflicts the fans most of all. Why should they care,
and why should be they be the only one? ...
</P>
<P>
   That said, I expect Bill Bavasi and Collins to both get
launched, along with several regulars who will be replaced by
cheaper and younger talent. By next June, Mo Vaughn will feel more
like a day-care operator than a first-baseman. ...
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson reportedly will play a game for a Swedish
professional team this fall. This could make one shudder about
another comeback attempt, but it makes me wonder how different
things might have been if we knew as much about AIDS and HIV in
1991 as we do now.
</P>
<P>
   Magic is only 40, and he was just 32 when he made his HIV
announcement in November of 1991. In the last half of 1999, we've
come to know that HIV isn't necessarily a death sentence, that its
transmission is not capricious, and that physical activity is a
plus in its containment.
</P>
<P>
   If HIV education of '99 had been in place eight years ago,
Johnson likely would have continued his NBA career. Every move of
the organization since has been related in some way to Magic's
retirement, from coaching to personnel decisions as well as his own
aborted comebacks as a player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson still plays, maybe Mike Dunleavy doesn't split. Maybe
the Lakers challenge the Bulls and Michael Jordan for their second
and third titles, rather than Portland and Phoenix. Maybe the
Lakers and not Houston play for NBA titles during Jordan's baseball
break.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Lakers ease into a transition period with Magic and
James Worthy and don't feel the need to play free agent roulette
and sign Shaquille O'Neal. If it's the Lakers and Magic beating
Orlando in the 1995 finals, maybe the career of Shaquille O'Neal
takes a different turn. ...
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of three years of courageous play by Jeff
Hostetler, the Raiders haven't had a credible quarterback since Jim
Plunkett took off his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   That has rarely been as vividly true as today. The Raiders have
surrounded themselves with numerous suspects since the Jeff George
experiment failed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is Bobby Hoying, acquired from the Eagles Tuesday for
a draft pick. The former Ohio State quarterback attempted 224
passes last season, and he did not throw one touchdown pass, which
has to be some kind of perverse NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   Hoying joins a camp that includes 40-year-old Wade Wilson and
well-traveled veteran Rich Gannon, late of K.C., who has been
handed the starting job on the strength of his mobility. The
Raiduhs decided they needed a quarterback with legs since their
offensive line is among the league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates read like the waiver wire. There's last year's
part-time starter Donald Hollas; Pat Barnes, who was MVP of the
World Bowl; left-hander Paul Justin; Redskins washout Heath Shuler;
former Heisman winner Andre Ware, who couldn't win a starting job
in the CFL; and rookie free agent Scott Dreisbach, who was being
considered for the starting job before breaking his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Take this QB quandary and add a mean schedule and you have a
potential disastrous year. The Raiders open at Green Bay and at
Minnesota, and after a home game versus Chicago, they play at
Seattle, Denver, at Buffalo, and host the N.Y. Jets and Miami. Can
you say 1-7? ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
