<HEADLINE>
FED BOOSTS INTEREST RATES AS IT CONTINUES TO BATTLE INFLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve Board nudged up interest rates
for the second time in less than two months Tuesday in a continuing
battle to keep a hold on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers, in an anticipated move, raised the federal
funds rate _ the interest rate banks charge one another for
overnight loans _ by a quarter of a percentage point Tuesday to 5
1/4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in a more surprising move, Fed officials also hiked the
less-frequently used discount rate by a quarter of a percentage
point to 4 3/4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time in more than four years the Federal
Reserve has pushed up the rate it charges banks for loans.
</P>
<P>
   The ``increase in the federal funds rate, together with the
policy action in June and the firming of conditions more generally
in U.S. financial markets over recent months, should markedly
diminish the risk of rising inflation going forward,'' Fed
officials said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials also maintained an official neutral stance on
interest rates, meaning they have no preference either for raising
or lowering interest rates in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors interpreted the Fed's statement to mean
policy-makers have no plans to raise rates any further this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've basically said short of any drastic change in the
market place this is ... the last dose of medicine the market place
needs,'' said David Lapin, president of Lapin &AMP; Wigginton Asset
Management, a Houston-based money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   But when confronted with the Fed's unexpected move on the
discount rate, Wall Street dithered.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, after leaping into record
territory Monday on expectations of a rate hike, bounced up and
down after the announcement Tuesday before finally closing at
11,283.30, down 16.46. The Nasdaq Composite Index, however, rose 33
points, or 1.2 percent, to close at 2752.48.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds rose on the Fed news Tuesday, with 30-year bonds climbing
23/32, or $7.19 per $1,000 face amount, to close at 102 22/32.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed picture,'' said Bryan Jordan, economics adviser
for Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio. ``Basically,
(Fed Chairman Alan) Greenspan is saying `It's OK to have a rally,
just don't let it get out of hand.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks _ led by Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and Bank One Corp. _
quickly responded to the Fed's actions by raising their own prime
lending rates a corresponding quarter of a percentage point to 8
1/4 percent. The prime is a bank's benchmark rate, used to
determine rates on everything from car loans to credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Home mortgage rates, while not directly tied to the federal
funds rate, are also strongly influenced by Fed actions. Mortgage
rates, which have risen significantly over the last year in
anticipation of Fed moves to tighten the money supply, have
actually eased in recent weeks as lenders became more persuaded
Tuesday's moves would be the final increases of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's decision Tuesday to raise the federal funds rate
followed a similar quarter point increase June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had applauded that move, persuaded at that time the
Fed's decision to adopt a neutral bias toward interest rates
indicated there would be no further rate increases this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But then a few weeks later, Greenspan used his scheduled
testimony on Capitol Hill to disabuse investors of that notion. By
issuing a strongly worded warning about inflation, Greenspan
telegraphed the Fed's likelihood of raising rates Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee is slated to convene three
more times before the end of the year, with its next meeting
scheduled for Oct. 5. But Fed watchers are becoming increasingly
more confident those sessions will be non-events.
</P>
<P>
   While recent inflation numbers gave Fed officials some cover for
Tuesday's strike against inflation, the data have been less than
compelling. Last week, the Labor Department said its seasonably
adjusted Consumer Price Index rose 0.3 percent in July after
remaining flat the previous two months.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists believe, even without Fed intervention, the
economy will slow over the next few months, as we edge closer to
the Year 2000 and business managers become increasingly concerned
about the so-called Millennium Bug. Many business managers are
expected to delay purchases to wait out the change in the calendar
and ensure they don't run into computer troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception of a Y2K problem, more than the reality of a
Y2K problem, will be enough to slow down the economy as we go into
next year and everybody sits on their hands,'' Lapin said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wachtel, market analyst for Prudential Securities in New
York, believes Fed policy-makers _ armed with the data they had _
had to struggle to raise rates Tuesday. The Y2K problem will make
it even more difficult to raise rates down the road, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Fed officials have raised rates a total of half a
percentage point this year, they still have not taken back all of
the ground they gave last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed cut interest rates three times in 1998 for a total of
three quarters of a percentage point in a successful attempt to
shield the U.S. economy from the effects of an economic crisis that
was ricocheting around much of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``With financial markets functioning more normally, and with
persistent strength in domestic demand, foreign economies firming
and labor markets remaining very tight, the degree of monetary ease
required to address the global financial market turmoil of last
fall is no longer consistent with sustained, noninflationary,
economic expansion,'' the Fed committee said.
</P>
<P>
   By raising rates Tuesday, Fed policy-makers ignored the pleas
from parties ranging from he Small Business Survival Committee to
Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In raising rates again, the Fed committed a blunder,'' Forbes
said in a statement. ``Yet, the insulated governors of the Federal
Reserve Board will not pay for this mistake. U.S. farmers, business
owners, and home buyers will suffer the severity of this
miscalculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Regalia, chief economist at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
argued the effect of a quarter of a percentage point on the economy
will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest impact is probably psychological,'' Regalia said
in a prepared statement. ``While a quarter point increase can price
marginal homebuyers out of the market and make buying on credit
slightly more expensive, it is not likely to bring the spending
Juggernaut to a halt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
