<SLUG> BC-MA-BUCKINGHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI NAMES STAFF CHIEF TO HEAD MASSPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a move designed to rid Massport of its ``frat-boy''
culture, Governor Paul Cellucci Tuesday chose his chief of staff,
Virginia Buckingham, to be the agency's new executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci personally rounded up votes on Massport's board to
install Buckingham, who will become the first female to run the
port authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's important to have a strong leader at that
agency,'' Cellucci said. ``We are basically sending our best person
over to that agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham will lead Cellucci's controversial push to build a
new runway at Logan Airport, a plan that has touched off protest
from community groups and other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has told Buckingham, who is returning from a maternity
leave, to clean out the old boy culture he believes set the stage
for last week's agency-funded Boston Harbor party cruise that cost
director Peter Blute's his job, sources said. That boat trip
featured heavy drinking and swimsuit-clad young women.
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham, 33, who also served as a press secretary and chief
of staff for ex-Governor William F. Weld, said she is prepared to
change the heavily male culture at the authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am used to dealing with the old boys network having worked
in politics for some many years,'' said Buckingham, in a telephone
interview with the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   She said said power is shifting in Massachusetts politics with
the election of more women, like Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift and
State Treasurer Shannon O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of culture change can be made at Massport,''
Buckingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham began her political career as an intern to Governor
Michael S. Dukakis, and joined Cellucci as a campaign aide in the
1990 campaign. She has been one of the most powerful figures at the
Statehouse for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci told Massport board members Buckingham will bring
stability to the agency, which has been the target of ridicule
since photographs of Blute's cruise were published in the Boston
Herald last week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the runway plan, Massport is trying to improve
regional aviation, moving to take over the city airport in
Worcester and increase traffic to Hanscom Air Field in Bedford. The
authority is also involved in critical waterfront development
questions, with control of key parcels of land as Boston's
construction boom continues.
</P>
<P>
   At a press briefing, Cellucci brushed aside suggestions that
Buckingham is too young and inexperienced to run the multi-billion
agency. He said she can provide leadership and rely on the
``experts'' at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham is believed to be the youngest person ever to serve
in the job. Cellucci said Buckingham would have the unanimous
support of the seven-member board when it meets later this month.
Her salary has not been set but Blute was paid $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Buckingham at the State House, Cellucci said he is
giving the $92,000-a-year chief of staff job to Steven O'Neill, his
chief secretary. In his current post as chief secretary, O'Neill
has been primarly in charge of patronage hiring and managed the
administration's relations with the Democratic-controlled
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's selection of Buckingham caught the political and
government worlds by surprise. Massport board leaders, including
its chairman Mark Robinson, had talked last week of whitling down a
list of candidates quickly, but Buckingham's name was not among
those mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   But administration sources said Cellucci wanted to make a move
that appeared decisive and bold, to quell criticism that his
administration is drifting.
</P>
<P>
   They said the governor is convinced Buckingham's political
skills, strong ties to the administration and public relations
background make her the perfect person to turn Massport around.
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut native and Boston College graduate who is married
to District Court judge David Lowy, Buckingham has been at the
center of key decisions during most of the Weld and Cellucci
administrations. She earned a reputation as a tough inside player
whom Weld and Cellucci heavily depended for political advice and
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Weld appointed Lowy a judge as one of his final appointments as
governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
