<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ANCIENT-BODY-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINS OF ANCIENT MAN DISCOVERED IN MELTING CANADIAN GLACIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES JUNCTION, Yukon Territory _ Tribal leaders and
archeologists announced here on Tuesday that hunters have
discovered the well-preserved body of an ancient man, partially
uncovered by a melting glacier.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a cloak sewn of small pelts, probably of arctic
ground squirrels, the body of the ancient man was found on a
melting glacier flank that was strewn with his belongings: a finely
woven, broad-brimmed hat, a stout walking stick, a spear, and a
leather pouch containing edible leaves and the remains of a fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's comparable to the Alps find,'' said Al Mackie, the lead
archeologist here, referring to the well-preserved body of a
prehistoric hunter found in an Alpine glacier in 1991 that is
thought to be at least 5,000 years old. ``In the Alps, it was a
person crossing a glacier who ran afoul of the weather and died
there. He also had with him a tool kit. The condition of the body
was comparable.''
</P>
<P>
   The body here in northern Canada could have lain frozen in the
blue ice for hundreds or thousands of years, Mackie said. There was
no sign of European tools, which were first brought to the area
where the body was found, about 50 miles from the Alaskan coast, by
Russian traders 250 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The body was found on Aug. 14 by three Canadian sheep hunters
who were hiking through the Tatshenshini-Alsek Provincial
Wilderness Park in British Columbia, almost 1,000 miles north of
Vancouver. It is now in cold storage in Whitehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed since the time when the ancient hunters lived
here. At the close of the 20th century, this wild region remains
one of North America's roughest and most unforgiving terrains.
</P>
<P>
   For the last week, about a dozen planes from Canada and the
United States have searched in vain for an American pilot and his
plane that vanished somewhere between Eastern Alaska and
Whitehorse, which is about 100 miles east of here. In Whitehorse,
surgeons on Monday implanted metal eye sockets in the face of a
local man whose face was smashed over the weekend by a grizzly
bear.
</P>
<P>
   A torrent of water melting from the glacier and a chance
encounter exposed the remains, one of the hunters, Bill Hanlon,
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably walked by it the day before,'' he said of their
hike above the tree line, a tundra plateau at about 6,500 feet.
``We went up on the ice and started to pick up pieces of wood,
which seemed kind of strange given the elevation we were at.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We noticed carvings in the pieces of wood, and they were
notched,'' continued Hanlon, a high school teacher from southern
British Columbia. ``We looked closely at what looked like a
backpack. You could see the actual threading and the holes where it
was sewn together.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Ward, one of his hunting companions, recalled discovering
the body: ``I looked at it through my binoculars and I saw it _ it
looked like the National Geographic pictures we'd been seeing for
years. I could see a lot of tattered bucked leather, and pieces of
fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon added, ``Being hunters and finding a hunter _ because all
the tools he was carrying lead us to believe he was a hunter, same
as we were _ that was kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally excited by the find, Mackie, the archeologist, said,
``You don't just have a few tools lying around _ you have got the
person. You have the potential for learning what he had been
eating, where he had been traveling, what his health history was.''
</P>
<P>
   Another archeologist, Knut Fladmark, of Simon Fraser University,
said on Tuesday from Vancouver, ``There have been very few
discoveries of human soft tissue of this age in North America.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Announcement of the most recent discovery was delayed for 10
days as archeologists consulted with elders of the
Champagne-Ashihik First Nations, the 1,140-member tribe that has
legal control over historical artifacts discovered in the park,
part of their ancestral homeland, which straddles British Columbia
and the Yukon Territory.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier discovery with possible tribal ties led to a battle
between the tribe and scientists. A skeleton found on the shore of
the Columbia River near Kennewick, Wash., in 1996, thought by
scientists to be more than 9,000 years old, led to a challenge by
the Umatilla Indian tribe. Its leaders claimed the bones as those
of a tribal ancestor under a 1990 law to protect Indian graves and
tried to block scientific study of the bones.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, tribal elders here say they favor scientific study
of the remains and artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elders did say that they felt it was as important to get
as much information as possible from this person _ that's kind of
an endorsement of scientific study,'' Ron Chambers, a tribal member
of the park management board, said at the tribal headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Waving a hand toward an arctic squirrel robe on a wall and a
wooden spear on a table, he added, ``Some of the material that this
person was carrying is some of the things from our elders that we
display right now _ this throwing stick, the robe.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Strand, the tribe's heritage resource officer, said that
she believes that the ancient man caught in the ice was a tribal
ancestor. ``According to stories recorded by our elders, we have
been here since time immemorial, since when animals could speak to
people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who also serves on a local search and rescue team,
noted another link between the present and the ancient past. ``He
appears to have fallen, wedged upright in a crevasse,'' he said.
``That remains the biggest danger in the area today. In the
springtime, there is old snow hiding these crevasses -- you are
walking along, and you are gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
