<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MERCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEEF UP PLAYOFF BID WITH LEFTIE MERCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Finally, the pieces fit. The Red Sox snapped up
veteran lefthander Kent Mercker Tuesday and fully expect him to
play a role in their bid to reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, 31, became the latest addition to a Red Sox rotation
that has been plagued all season by injuries and high earned run
averages. He was obtained from the St. Louis Cardinals in exchange
for a pair of minor leaguers, pitcher Mike Matthews and catcher
Dave Benham, neither of whom is considered a prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker is expected to join the Red Sox Wednesday; he has been
penciled in to the Friday start that ordinarily would have been
Bret Saberhagen's spot. The veteran righthander Saberhaqgen is on
the 15-day disabled list, retroactive to Aug. 18, because of
shoulder soreness.
</P>
<P>
   With St. Louis this year, Mercker had a 6-5 record and a 5.12
ERA in 25 appearances (18 starts). Since July 1, he was 4-2 with a
3.99 ERA. He last worked Saturday, going 5 1/3 innings and taking
the loss in a 7-4 setback to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very versatile pitcher who has the ability to be
effective as a starter and a reliever,'' said Sox general manager
Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Mercker went 11-11 in 30 starts, leading the St. Louis
staff in victories, but had a 5.07 ERA. His career log is 60-58.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker is a well-traveled product of the Atlanta Braves system.
He spent six years in Atlanta after coming up for good in 1990. He
was traded to Baltimore after the 1995 season, and from there moved
on to Cleveland in 1996, Cincinnati in 1997, and St. Louis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He has postseason experience, having pitched for Atlanta in the
1991 and 1995 World Series. Sox manager Jimy Williams, who was a
coach on those Braves teams, knows Mercker well and thinks highly
of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, he's been pitching good lately,'' said
Williams. ``He throws fastball, curveball, and changeup. I haven't
seen much of him lately but he knows how to pitch. With the Braves,
I saw him pitch a no-hitter against the Dodgers and be part of
another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker pitched six innings of a no-hitter Sept. 11, 1991,
combining with Mark Wohlers and Alejandro Pena in a 1-0 victory
over San Diego. On April 8, 1994, he threw a no-hitter to beat the
Dodgers, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been used a lot of different ways,'' said Williams. ``But
primarily he's a starter. I feel like we got a good arm. It's a
good addition for our club.''
</P>
<P>
   The rotation now is Pedro Martinez, who pitched Tuesday night,
Mark Portugal, Pat Rapp, Tim Wakefield, and Mercker.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't officially made room on the roster for Mercker,
though they put some wheels in motion Tuesday. Marino Santana was
moved from the 15-day disabled list to the 60-day list, making room
on the 40-man roster. The likely suspect to be dropped from the
25-man major league roster is Japanese righthander Tomokazu Ohka,
who was recalled from Pawtucket Monday to replace Brian Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker will be the first lefthander to start for Boston this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for good pitchers, it doesn't matter if it's
a right or lefthander,'' said Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
