<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-ART     08-24 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TEAM ADVANCES TO SEMIFINALS OF LITTLE LEAGUE WORLD
SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ind., Ala., Idaho, Japan, Puerto Rico) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ With the stadium thumping to chants of
``East! East! East!'' the boys from Toms River Tuesday afternoon
stormed into the semifinals of the Little League World Series in
quest of a second consecutive championship.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey team defeated Brownsburg, Indiana, 3-1, before
15,300 fans at Howard J. Lamade Stadium, completing a 3-0 sweep of
the United States bracket and advancing to the U.S. championship
game on Thursday. The winner of that game plays the international
bracket winner for the Little League championship on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The three other American teams had varying chances of advancing
to the national championship game. Phenix City, Ala., (1-1) would
clinch the spot with a victory over the Boise, Idaho, (0-1) in the
late game Tuesday night. But Boise would advance by winning Tuesday
night and then again on Wednesday against Brownsburg (0-2).
However, if Boise won, then lost, three teams would finish with 1-2
records, and tie breakers would determine the other finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Yabucoa, Puerto Rico (2-0) closed in on
clinching a berth in Thursday's international final with a 3-1
victory over Osaka, Japan. Jorge Colon hit a two-run homer in the
bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   By winning on Monday and Tuesday, Toms River had virtually
assured itself of a spot in the U.S. championship game. So Tuesday
was a chance for the boys to have some fun, and judging from the
smiles and giggles when power-hitter Steve Bernath entered the game
to pitch the final inning, that's exactly what they did.
</P>
<P>
   Between the fifth and sixth innings, Mike Gaynor, the Toms River
manager, walked into the dugout and asked, ``Who wants to pitch?''
His team was leading by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve raised his hand with a big smile on his face,'' Gaynor
said. ``I said, `Go ahead, it's all you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bernath strutted out to the mound, barely able to contain
himself. He tossed a few warm-up pitches, most of them several feet
off the plate. But that didn't bother him. Bernath, who
occasionally pitches during the regular season, struck out the
first Indiana batter be faced. The next batter grounded out.
Bernath walked the next two batters, then allowed them to advance
on a wild pitch. He shrugged, gathered himself, and struck out the
last batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like throwing,'' said Bernath, whose nickname is
Big Unit because his gangly frame reminds people of the
Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson. ``I had been begging him all week to
let me go out there and pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve's mom, Nancy Bernath, added: ``I saw him walking out to
the mound. I didn't know what was going on. I was very nervous,
probably more nervous than he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Fontenelli, usually the shortstop, started Tuesday's game
for Toms River and earned his first victory of the post-season. In
four innings, he allowed four hits and no walks and struck out
eight. Until Tuesday, he had only pitched two innings for Toms
River. Eric Campesi pitched the fifth inning and allowed the only
run on three hits.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, it seems, was to pitch Fontenelli Tuesday so that
Campesi, the team's No. 2 starter, could pitch in the U.S.
championship game. By throwing Campesi on Thursday, the team will
have Casey Gaynor, the staff ace, rested for Saturday's World
Series title game, assuming Toms River wins on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River took a 2-0 lead on two hits in the second inning. The
Indiana pitcher, Zach Mills, got himself in trouble after walking
the first two Toms River batters he faced. With Fontenelli and Dave
Cappello on base, Bernath hit an infield single to load the bases.
Then Mike Casale drove in the first run with base hit up the
middle. Casale's hit sent the hundreds of Toms River supporters
into a tizzy. They stood and chanted, ``Beast is back! Beast is
back!''
</P>
<P>
   On that play, however, Bernath overran second base and was
thrown out by the Indiana catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River got its second run that inning when Mills threw over
his catcher's head, allowing Cappello to score from third base. The
No. 8 and No. 9 hitters, Chris Cunningham and Zack Del Vento, then
struck out swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Mills struggled with his control again in the third inning,
walking the first two batters he faced. He was replaced by Collin
Steele, who had been playing shortstop. Steele got Jeff Burgdorff
to hit into a double play, but Campesi baited the Indiana first
baseman into throwing the ball to third. The throw bounced and got
away from the third baseman and Campesi trotted home to make the
score 3-0. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
