<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-CHAIR-COX     08-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photos of executed inmate may sway decision in electric chair
debate
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida's seven-decade tradition of
electrocuting its murderers may have fallen Tuesday onto the
shoulders of a single man _ a man who just last month wrote that
use of the electric chair ``continues to walk the edge of
constitutional propriety.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Fred Lewis, who joined the Florida Supreme Court nine
months ago, could be the swing vote on a divided panel that once
again must decide whether putting enough electricity to light up a
small neighborhood through a human being violates the prohibition
against cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful,'' anti-death penalty lawyer Marty McClain said
after the hour-long oral arguments that included the first-ever
appearance of photos of an executed man. ``It's just too ghastly.''
</P>
<P>
   A retiring of the chair could translate into a years-long delay
in executions in Florida as lawyers for Death Row inmates scramble
to challenge lethal injection, which, under a 1998 law, would
automatically become the state's method of execution should the
electric chair be ruled unconstitutional. ``Capital punishment is
the law of the land,'' Gov. Jeb Bush said.``We'll adapt to whatever
the Supreme Court decides, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis did not say a single word through Tuesday's hour-long oral
arguments, even as the two confirmed electric chair foes on the
court and a third colleague peppered lawyers with questions.
Observers were left with his single written pronouncement on the
matter: a July 1 concurring opinion that, for the time being,
approved the electrocution of Orange County courthouse killer
Thomas Provenzano.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discussion and debate will be never ending so long as this
mechanism exists,'' Lewis wrote of the electric chair. ``And
although we must have stability in legal precedent to respect the
rule of law, we must never fear confrontation with precedent when
the factual underpinnings of such precedent lack validity.'' The
high court narrowly retained the electric chair in 1997, but
advised in its majority opinion that lawmakers switch to lethal
injection. Among the 38 states where capital punishment is legal,
Florida is the largest of four that rely solely on electrocution
for executions.
</P>
<P>
   Since that ruling, the court has acquired three new members.
One, Peggy Quince, is a former assistant attorney general who once
argued to uphold death sentences. Observers generally believe she
will vote to keep the chair, along with justices Major Harding and
Charles Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Harry Lee Anstead and Leander Shaw, meanwhile, have
consistently opposed the electric chair. New justice Barbara
Pariente has raised concerns about the chair, as well. Her July 1
opinion said the court's recent approval of the electric chair was
based on the understanding that condemned inmates did not suffer
conscious pain and that the Department of Corrections follow
established protocol regarding voltage and current.
</P>
<P>
   Those guidelines were attacked Tuesday as justices delved into _
and at times tripped over _ a discussion of elementary physics.
</P>
<P>
   McClain accused the state of giving mere lip service to the
protocol of delivering 9.5 amperes of electricity at 2,300 volts
when its own experts knew the equipment could not guarantee those
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the words they think this court wants to hear,''
McClain said, and then ignore the published figures when it comes
time to actually putting an inmate to death.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Richard Martell apologized to the
court for misstating the electrical levels in the past, but said it
was based on the information that was provided to him. He countered
McClain's contention that condemned inmates felt pain with a
reminder of the point of executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking his life, and he's paying the ultimate
punishment,'' he said. ``It's not going to be pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments did not seem persuasive, though, to Shaw and
Anstead.
</P>
<P>
   Anstead pointed to McClain's photographs of murderer Allen Lee
Davis, whose nosebleed-marred execution on July 8 spurred the
latest inquiry into the chair. ``Can you hold that photo up to the
State of Florida and say this is what we want to do?'' Anstead
asked Martell. ``They look like they're right out of some horror
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Martell told the court that the electric chair was originally
invented as a humane method of execution, to which Pariente asked:
``And what century was that?''
</P>
<P>
   Provenzano is scheduled to be electrocuted Sept. 14, so the
court will likely rule before then, unless justices grant the
killer a hearing to determine his sanity. In that case, a ruling on
the chair could be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
