<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CONGO-ACCORD-NYT &LR;      08-24 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ACCORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS KEY REBELS AGREE TO A 50-MAN SIGNING PROCEDURE, CONGO PEACE
ACCORD ADVANCES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The Congo peace negotiations took a major step
forward on Tuesday when two rival rebel factions agreed to sign a
cease-fire document already approved by other combatants in the
yearlong civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But like almost everything else about the war, the compromise
between the two groups is decidedly complex. Rather than have two
or three rebel leaders sign the peace document, as originally
envisioned, the compromise calls for some 50 rebel officials from
all three rebel groups to sign.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, rebel officials said, they plan to
travel en masse to Lusaka, the Zambian capital, to sign the peace
accord that was drafted there on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel officials themselves conceded the plan's awkwardness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's really a good compromise,'' said Moise
Nyarugabo, vice president of the main rebel group, the Congolese
Rally for Democracy. ``This can just help us move in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But some outside analysts wondered if the compromise was
actually aimed at peace or merely at making the accord so unwieldy
that the deal would fall apart and the fighting would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a complicated thing,'' said Hannelie de Beer,
senior researcher at the Institute for Strategic Studies in South
Africa. ``I want to see if it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The war has been a major source of instability in central
Africa, and peace has been elusive, in part because there are so
many warring parties with so many different aims. At least six
countries, including Congo itself, are fighting, along with the
three rebel groups that are trying to overthrow President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations, all the parties agreed in July in
Lusaka to sign the peace accord. It calls for an immediate
cease-fire, for the outside nations to withdraw their troops, for
international observers to monitor the peace and for a national
``dialogue'' inside Congo among Kabila, the rebels and other
opposition leaders to decide the country's future.
</P>
<P>
   But at the last minute, squabbling broke out among the rebel
groups at the peace conference and they walked away without
signing.
</P>
<P>
   Nyarugabo's group refused to sign if its former leader, Ernest
Wamba dia Wamba, also signed. Wamba dia Wamba was ousted in May and
set up his own faction in the northeastern city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the third rebel faction, Jean-Pierre Bemba, said
he would not sign if Wamba dia Wamba did not.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dispute was on some level an internal struggle
among the rebels, the failure to sign also reflected disagreements
between Rwanda and Uganda, two of the outside countries fighting in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   They are normally close allies. But Rwanda has given military
support to the Congolese Rally for Democracy, and Uganda has
supported Wamba dia Wamba's breakaway faction and Bemba.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the two countries _ and their forces on the
ground _ erupted a week and a half ago when Ugandan and Rwandan
soldiers fought a three-day battle in Kisangani in which at least
200 people were reported killed.
</P>
<P>
   After so much bloodshed, the leaders of the two nations met last
week and pledged to put pressure on the rebel groups they support
to sign the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's agreement appears to be the fruit of that meeting.
Officials from Rwanda and Uganda praised the deal, saying it
resurrected the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they are going to sign, that gets rid of one
stumbling block,'' said Hope Kivengeri, the spokeswoman for the
President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda. ``Then we have to get down to
the nitty-gritty. We're really confident that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromise calls for all 50 original leaders of the
rebellion to sign the document, not only Wamba dia Wamba and his
replacement in the Rally for Democracy, Dr. Emile Ilunga. The
compromise, Nyarugabo said, makes the point that Wamba dia Wamba
holds no special status above any other of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``To allow Wamba to sign alone is to accept the creation of
another faction,'' Nyarugabo said. ``We said, `Let all the founders
sign, because Wamba is one of them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wamba dia Wamba said on Tuesday that he would accept the
compromise, though with some bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``One probably needs to be angry,'' he said. ``Because it wasn't
necessary _ this delay and loss of human lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bemba, who has already signed on his own, said he also was
content with the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really good news,'' he said. ``If we can agree among
each other and put Kabila out smoothly, it's OK''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and the leaders of the nations that support him,
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, have signed the accord. But the
signing is only the first step in what will be a long and difficult
path toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the most pressing question is whether extremist
forces from the Hutu ethnic group, fighting alongside Kabila, will
lay down their arms in their struggle against the Tutsi-led
government in Rwanda, which borders on Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The outside nations _ each rumored to be taking away a piece of
Congo's vast wealth, in diamonds, oil, gold, timber or cotton _
will have to learn to do without those riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of problems in the air,'' Ms. de Beer said.
``What's going to be very important is continued international
attention, even after everyone signs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
