<SLUG> BC-PRATT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pratt's `buffet' of talent has firms lining up for a seat
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The vultures have landed in northern
Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Major aircraft and engine manufacturers have roosted in the land
of Pratt &AMP; Whitney, hoping to snap up workers. Several ran large
advertisements in Sunday's Palm Beach Post with lists of job
openings.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were ABB Power Generation Ltd. of Baden, Switzerland;
General Electric-Harris Railway Electronics of Melbourne; GKN
Westland Aerospace of Tallassee, Ala.; Gulfstream Air of Savannah,
Ga.; Lockheed Martin Electronics &AMP; Missiles Division of Orlando;
Motorola, with plants in Boynton Beach and Plantation;
Siemens-Westinghouse Power Corp. of Findlay, Ohio; Westinghouse
Commercial Nuclear Fuel Division of Columbia, S.C., and Williams
International of Walled Lake, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are looking for gas turbine engineers, aircraft
and engine mechanics, electrical engineers, physicists, and systems
and software engineers. But they also are hiring accountants and
human resources specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt spokesman Tim Burris said the company isn't surprised.
``When you are making the changes that we're making, you expect
this sort of thing, especially when you have talented employees,''
Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt gave these companies the incentive they needed by
announcing a major restructuring this month that will include
moving 2,500 to 2,800 engineers involved in the development of jet
engines for the military from Florida to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second move by Pratt this year. It sent 600 engineers
to Connecticut, starting in April.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the companies _ Siemens-Westinghouse and Williams
International _ are holding open houses this week at the Embassy
Suites Hotel in Palm Beach Gardens, in Pratt's back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feast. They want to visit the free Pratt &AMP; Whitney
buffet,'' said one engineer who expects to be moved to New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the engineers at Pratt &AMP; Whitney, if you have a choice
between Florida and Connecticut, you choose Florida. If the choice
is between Connecticut and the rest of the country, you might pick
the rest of the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are lining up for a crack at Pratt's engineers
this week because employees at the plant on Beeline Highway in
northwestern Palm Beach County will learn if they will receive an
invitation to move with the company. Letters have already begun to
go out.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorsky Aircraft, Pratt's sister company, is moving its
helicopter plant. Pratt and Sikorsky are subsidiaries of Hartford,
Conn.-based United Technologies Corp. Sikorsky hasn't said whether
it will move its employees.
</P>
<P>
   New Piper Aircraft in Vero Beach is expanding its operation and
has openings. It employs 1,100 people in the manufacture of small
planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about a hundred openings, ranging from customer
service to engineering to manufacturing,'' said Patrick Faller,
director of human resources. ``I have been approached by both Pratt
and Sikorsky employees.''
</P>
<P>
   One group of employees won't have to worry _ 200 computer
programmers and operators who were transferred to Computer Sciences
Corp. from Pratt in May.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based company will move them to other offices.
CSC has 700 offices, with 21 in Florida including two in Miami and
one in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key message is that everyone will have jobs, but it may
involve relocation,'' spokeswoman Mary Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pounds writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
