<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ISRAEL-EXTRADITE-600&AMP;     08-24 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EXTRADITE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN WHO FLED TO ISRAEL WILL PLEAD GUILTY TO U.S. MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Maryland teen-ager who has been the subject of a
long extradition battle between the United States and Israel has
agreed to plead guilty to the gruesome murder of another Maryland
youth and to accept a 24-year prison sentence in Israel, state
prosecutors in Maryland announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said they were angry over the plea agreement
between Israeli authorities and the 19-year-old defendant, Samuel
Sheinbein, who fled to Israel days after the charred, dismembered
body of Alfredo Tello Jr. was found in an empty garage in September
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli embassy in Washington confirmed the latest, and
perhaps final, twist in a murder case that has frustrated U.S.
prosecutors and outraged lawmakers in both the United States and
Israel, who alleged that Sheinbein had manipulated the legal
systems of both countries in an effort to avoid punishment for an
especially grisly crime.
</P>
<P>
   An embassy spokesman acknowledged that Israeli prosecutors had
settled on a plea bargain with Sheinbein that would require him to
plead guilty to murder at a court hearing on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors in Montgomery County, Md., where the murder
took place, had sought the extradition of Sheinbein to the United
States, where he could have faced life in prison without parole if
convicted of the strangling death of Tello, who was 19. Prosecutors
here would have been unable to seek the death penalty because
Sheinbein was a minor at the time of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Justice Ministry and Foreign Ministry supported the
extradition of Sheinbein, who was born and raised in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But in February the Israeli Supreme Court refused the request
from U.S. prosecutors, accepting the argument of defense lawyers
that Sheinbein could claim Israeli citizenship by virtue of his
father's birth in 1944 in what was then British-occupied Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Sheinbein's hasty departure from the United
States two years ago, Israeli law barred the extradition of Israeli
citizens for trial abroad. As a result of the furor over the
Sheinbein case in Israel, the law has since been changed to make it
possible for Israel to extradite citizens who are not residents.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States does, Israel permits the prosecution of its
citizens at home for serious crimes committed outside its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Eitan Maoz, a lawyer for Sheinbein, refused to comment Tuesday
except to say that developments in the case would be revealed at a
court appearance next week in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   The chief prosecutor in Montgomery County, state's attorney
Douglas F. Gansler, said in a telephone interview Tuesday that the
plea bargain was ``an insult to justice'' because it would allow
Sheinbein to go free on parole in as little as 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an insult that Sheinbein will now be walking free in the
streets of Israel in all probability at the age of 33 years old,''
Gansler said. ``Sheinbein undoubtedly would have served a sentence
of life in prison without parole had he been held accountable
here.''
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors in Maryland have said that, despite the plea
bargain in Israel, Sheinbein would face prosecution if he ever
returned to the United States. There is no statute of limitations
on the case, and Gansler has vowed that the murder charges against
Sheinbein will remain on the books indefinitely. ``There's no
double jeopardy question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's flight to Israel and the refusal of Israeli courts
to extradite him to the United States in the killing of Tello, a
Hispanic youth, raised a furor in Maryland's Latino community and
led members of Congress from the state to threaten cuts in the
$3-billion-a-year U.S. aid package to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Tello's family released a statement Tuesday in response to
reports of a plea bargain: ``The Tello family feels that justice
has not been achieved in this case, that Mr. Sheinbein and his
family have continually manipulated the judicial systems of both
Israel and the United States.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gansler acknowledged that by the standards of the Israeli
criminal justice system, Sheinbein had agreed to a harsh sentence,
especially since he might likely have been shown some leniency as a
result of his youth and his lack of a violent criminal record
before 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually a longer term of incarceration than we had been
expecting,'' the Gansler said. ``Once you accepted the fact that he
was not going to be extradited to the U.S., then it's not so
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Israeli embassy, Mark Regev, confirmed that
a plea bargain had been reached. But he cautioned that the
agreement was not final until it had been reviewed and approved by
Israeli courts. ``The courts have the right to accept it or throw
it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler has said that if the trial were held in Maryland, he was
prepared to call as many as 80 witnesses who would weave together
evidence showing that the murder of Tello was a ``thrill kill,''
and that Sheinbein and a friend, Aaron Needle, had plotted the
crime in elaborate, grisly detail.
</P>
<P>
   Needle hanged himself with a bedsheet in a Maryland prison just
before his trial was to start in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently Tello had disrespected Aaron Needle in front of
Aaron Needle's girlfriend,'' Gansler said. ``You couldn't have had
a stronger case. We have DNA evidence. We have fingerprint
evidence.'' He said prosecutors had obtained a handwritten document
in which Sheinbein ``wrote out this recipe for murder, including
identifying the make of the circular saw he was going to use on the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   In court arguments in Israel during the extradition fight,
Sheinbein's lawyers promised that he would admit to the murder if
he were tried in Israel instead of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In a court appearance last month, however, he pleaded not guilty
to murder, although he acknowledged that he had burned and
dismembered Tello's body. The prosecutors in Maryland said they
were shocked by the plea and that it signaled an effort by
Sheinbein to win acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's lawyer, David Libai, a former Israeli justice
minister, told the Tel Aviv court that Sheinbein would not admit to
any role in the strangling death of Tello, leaving the clear
suggestion that Needle was the sole murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's father, Sol, a patent lawyer who arranged his son's
departure from the United States and has joined him in Israel, is
still wanted in Montgomery County on charges of obstruction of
justice and hindering a criminal investigation. He has said that he
feared for his son's life in a U.S. prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT &LR;      08-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP WILL RE-EXAMINE AUCTION TAX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Canada, Calif.)   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Reacting to criticism from the breeders
and buyers of race horses, the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association has announced that it will re-examine the way it raises
money, specifically the 1 per cent tax imposed on the buyers of
horses at auction sales.
</P>
<P>
   The association, created 16 months ago to unify the horse
business, caused a storm recently over its decision to add the
surcharge to the bills sent to people who buy horses at auction. In
a statement on Monday, it said it would appoint a task force to
review its money-raising formulas for its new fiscal year, which
begins next April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stronach, the Canadian industrialist who recently bought
Santa Anita and Gulfstream Park and became the most powerful force
in the racing business, said Tuesday from his office in Toronto:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say somebody else should pay for something. Why
tax the buyers of horses? The key question is: Will it be for the
common good of racing?
</P>
<P>
   ``The NTRA has a noble purpose, but it is going in too many
directions with a sizable budget and overhead. I don't like clubs
where people are appointed; the stakeholders should elect the
directors. And you've got to fix the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Caesar Kimmel, the prominent horseman, said: ``If they have to,
there are many other ways for the NTRA to raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA upset many buyers in the booming horse market recently
when it notified them that the tax would be applied to bills at the
September sale of yearlings at Keeneland in Kentucky. Criticism was
also reported from a meeting of the Thoroughbred Owners and
Breeders Association in Saratoga last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Tuttle, vice president for communications for the NTRA,
said that ``some of our marketing programs would be put in serious
jeopardy'' if they were restructured now. But he said that the task
force would be set up to review the association's funding
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC FAVORITE OUT OF RACE
</P>
<P>
   Another NTRA program suffered a blow Tuesday morning when Mazel
Trick, the favorite in Sunday's $1 million Pacific Classic, pulled
up with damaged sesamoid bones during a workout at Del Mar in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic has been billed as the climactic event in
the NTRA ``championship series'' for handicap horses, but the race
has suffered the loss of top horses like Silver Charm, Victory
Gallop and Real Quiet. In their absence, Mazel Trick, with a
four-race winning streak, inherited the favorite's role. He is
trained by Bobby Frankel, who has won the Pacific Classic four
times in the eight years it has been run. But his star was pulled
up during a workout Tuesday morning, and was scheduled for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he passed the three-eighths pole, he took a bad step,''
said Bob Baffert, who trains two of the survivors for the race,
General Challenge and River Keen. ``He pulled up right away, so he
has a chance. General Challenge followed him on the track, and
worked three-quarters of a mile in 1:11, and River Keen went in
1:11 4/5, the best he's ever worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd have to say Malek has the most experience of those who
are left, and it should be his race to win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
