<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCRECEIVERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESHMEN COMPETE FOR RECEIVING JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcell Allmond was speaking about himself but he might as well
have included USC teammates Kareem Kelly and Steve Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just sat back and watched, I would be bored,'' said
Allmond after a recent Trojan fall camp practice at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Allmond, Kelly and Stevenson who, collectively make
up one of the nation's best freshman receiving groups to spend much
time sitting back this season. And, beginning with the
season-opener Sept.4 at Hawaii, none of them will probably have too
much time to get bored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 3 receiver is (basically) a starter,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``The first (five receivers) in our system see a lot
of action.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the third, fourth and fifth receivers are named
Allmond, Kelly and Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans don't have the luxury to let these guys mature
slowly. Senior Windrell Hayes has established himself as the
Trojans first receiving option and R. Jay Soward, when healthy and
motivated, is a proven threat to score at any time. After that,
though, there's not any experienced reliability and it doesn't help
that junior college transfer Craig Mitchell is having trouble
getting into camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to throw them in and just go,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually their ability to go or, more directly, go fast
that makes Hackett think the new receivers can help right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to coach a long time to know that they're
fast,'' Hackett said. ``They bring an element of speed to our
perimeter that we didn't have last year.''
</P>
<P>
   No California prep athlete was faster than Kelly last year as
the Poly graduate claimed the state 100 and 200 meter sprint
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else had a 10.3 (100-yard dash guy) at receiver,'' Poly
receiver coach Merle Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Allmond, a St. Paul alum, raced to the state championship in the
110-high hurdles and Stevenson also made his mark in the sprints at
Charter Oak.
</P>
<P>
   On the football field, the speed led to a combined 66 touchdowns
last year as each helped their team reach a CIF Southern Section
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But speed comes in many forms in college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``College defensive backs are not slow,'' Allmond said. ``You
find that out right away. They are either one step behind or one
step ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the new receivers has excellent size for the position.
Stevenson is 6-foot-2 and 205 pounds, Kelly is 6-1, 185, and
Allmond is 6-2, 180. But trying to best utilize the size and speed
means trying to learn a complicated West Coast offense playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge gap between learning the system in high school
and learning the system here,'' Kelly said. ``They've thrown 200
plays at us in the past couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   For Allmond, it's a lot different than lining up for St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in here blind,'' Allmond said.
</P>
<P>
   All three received an early start on their college football
education by attending summer workouts on campus. It was there that
one of them Allmond earned some early respect from a pretty
important guy on campus starting quarterback Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcell really stood out,'' Palmer said. ``He came right in
and got a couple of touchdowns (in 7-on-7 passing games). You can
tell he wants the ball and you can tell he wants to play right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   When camp opened, each of them knew that early playing time was
not only a possibility but a necessity. And that isits
</P>
<P>
   something each would welcome with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it pressure,'' Stevenson said. ``I would call
it a challenge. Early on, they told us it was up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Each has shown moments of promise during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Allmond was one of the offensive stars during the 100-play dress
rehearsal scrimmage on Tuesday at the L.A. Coliseum. He showed
excellent concentration on a 16-yard reception with safety David
Gibson in his face and flashed his speed by getting behind the
defense on a post pattern for a 34-yard score on a pass from
Palmer. Kelly caught two passes for 26 yards and Stevenson had two
receptions for 34 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly may be the most polished route-runner simply because he
was strictly a receiver at Poly. Allmond lined up at different
spots on offense for the Swordsmen and was also a full-time
defensive back. Stevenson played receiver, running back and
defensive back at Charter Oak.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has plagued Kelly is dropsinconsistent hands
</P>
<P>
   . In this summer's Texas-California Shrine All-Star game, Kelly
caught a touchdown pass but he also had several catchable balls
sail through his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make excuses but it was rustiness,'' Kelly
said. ``Until the Shrine practices, I really hadn't caught any
balls since the (CIF) championship game in December. I haven't
dropped too many balls (in camp). I just need to work on that part
of my game to be a complete receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they leave school each will have plenty of opportunity to
show their ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a group, I think we can be the best to ever come out of
USC,'' Kelly said. ``We're coming in at the right time. Carson, to
me, is the prototype quarterback. He always puts the ball in the
right spot and makes it easy for a receiver. Carson is the best
thing to happen to me since (former Poly teammate and Stanford
freshman) Chris Lewis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
