<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-COLORADO-PREVIEW-     08-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLORADO-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNETT AIMS TO RE-ESTABLISH COLORADO AS BIG 12 BRUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soft.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Colorado football had become. Finesse football. In
four years under Rick Neuheisel, the Buffaloes had regressed from
the brass knuckles program that won a national championship in 1990
and challenged Nebraska for dominance to a team that couldn't run
the football, couldn't stop the run and didn't win enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK at some schools, but not Colorado,'' wide receiver
Marcus Stiggers, a former Richardson Lake Highlands star, said of
last season's 8-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel left for Washington in early January. His replacement
is Gary Barnett, who was an assistant coach from 1984-91 at
Colorado when the Buffaloes became dominant. At his introductory
Colorado news conference, Barnett made it clear there was a new
sheriff in town. He promised the Buffaloes would visit the old
days. His theme: Return to Dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how soft and finesse-oriented we had become when
I said that,'' Barnett said. ``I had to create a vision. Unless you
have a vivid picture of where you want to go, you won't get there.
You want a standard, and we have one here \Rthe 1990 title\S.
Having done it before really helps. When I say `return to
dominance' around here, everybody has a clear picture of what that
means.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes probably won't contend for a national championship
this season. But Barnett's return along with a large group of
talented players has Colorado ranked a consensus No. 15 in 10
preseason polls. The belief is that if Barnett can win at
Northwestern, where he spent nine seasons and won two Big Ten
Conference titles by revitalizing a tepid program, he should have
success at a state school like Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel was a surprise pick to replace Bill McCartney in 1995.
Neuheisel won 10 games each of his first two seasons and received
notoriety as a New Age coach. He took his team rafting, staged
water-gun and snowball fights and played guitar on stage with Jimmy
Buffett. He was a cool coach.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Buffs went 5-6 in 1997 _ a season littered with
penalties and turnovers _ there were questions about a lack of
discipline. And even eight victories last season didn't quiet the
doubters.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has set about emphatically answering those questions.
Practices are fast-paced and hard hitting. The winning team in the
spring game ate steak; the losers ate beans. Barnett showed his
team the statistics from the 1989, 1990 and 1991 teams (combined
record: 30-5-2) and compared those numbers with last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very vivid,'' Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   How vivid? From 1989-91, Colorado averaged 289 yards rushing a
game and 36 rushing touchdowns a season while allowing 126 yards
rushing per game and an average of 10 rushing TDs a season. Last
season, the Buffs allowed 147 rushing yards per game and 24 rushing
TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we needed to change our image, and I don't know if we
would have had there not been a \Rcoaching\S change,'' center Andre
Gurode said. ``We've been a finesse team, but now it's a whole new
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I want. I want smash-mouth,'' defensive back
Rashidi Barnes said. ``That's what the team wants. We want to come
up and hit people. As a defensive player, that's what you live
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett had been living for a chance to return to Boulder. When
he left Colorado in 1992 to take over at Northwestern, many of his
colleagues believed he had snuffed out a bright career. But when
the Wildcats reached the Rose Bowl in 1996, Barnett became ``the''
hot coach. He interviewed at UCLA and Georgia. His name was linked
to the Notre Dame opening and the Detroit Lions job. In December
1997, he was interviewed by Texas, a job he said was
``intriguing.'' His name come up as a possible replacement for John
Blake at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   When Neuheisel resigned, Barnett thought he would get the job
after being interviewed by Colorado officials. But the announcement
was delayed when Colorado spent time trying to lure Denver Broncos
assistant coach Gary Kubiak. Barnett even e-mailed Northwestern
players telling them that he would stay in Chicago to honor his
10-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to pull out after \RColorado\S told me that they
were going with Kubiak,'' Barnett said. ``I realized it was a job
that I really wanted. A few days later, I'm out recruiting and get
the message that Kubiak has turned the job down. Things changed I
didn't have control over.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett knows that his yearly candidacy for job openings has
followed him to the Rocky Mountains. So, Gary, is this your last
coaching move? ``I have been asked that, and my answer is `I
certainly hope so.' I get tired of the questions, but I understand
them. I wouldn't have left Northwestern if it hadn't been for
Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has gone home again. His goal is to take the Buffaloes
on a similar nostalgia tour, back to the days of 10-win seasons,
significant bowl games, national championship hunts and
knock-your-breath-out football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last spring we changed the total approach, and I thought the
kids handled it well,'' Barnett said. ``They were surprised at the
tempo and the physical nature. At the end of the spring, we were
more physical than we had been. We're not a mentally disciplined or
tough team yet. But we're closer to that than we were. We
definitely set a tone. A loud one. We're going to run the football
effectively, we're going to become a physical team instead of a
finesse team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
