<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THARP-BROWN-DANCE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAIR OF DARING LEAPS INTO CLASSICAL TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By JACK ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two wonderful surprises danced their way across stages this
summer. The choreographers of both took what seemed like foolhardy
risks. Yet, instead of plummeting into catastrophe, both Twyla
Tharp and Trisha Brown managed to soar creatively. Ms. Brown, in
fact, even levitated a dancer. Ms. Tharp wrestled with Beethoven,
and she and Beethoven both emerged with honor.
</P>
<P>
   When she announced the score for the premiere that her company,
Tharp!, staged last month at the American Dance Festival in Durham,
N.C., some music-loving dancegoers must have felt like fainting.
Ms. Tharp set her ``Grosse Sonata'' to Beethoven's Piano Sonata No.
29 in B flat (Op. 106), the ``Hammerklavier.'' This is precisely
the sort of imposing score that dance-composition teachers warn
against, for its formal intricacy and emotional urgency can make
choreography look irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Tharp relishes challenges. Indeed, inspired
choreographers sometimes produce wonderful works by sheer daring.
Back in the '30s, to the horror of music critics, Leonide Massine
created exciting ballets to Tchaikovsky's Fifth Symphony (``Les
Presages'') and Brahms' Fourth Symphony (``Choreartium''). As
revived by the Joffrey Ballet and England's Birmingham Royal
Ballet, respectively, these works retain their power.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the director of the Hamburg Ballet, John
Neumeier, has found Mahler's fervent but lengthy symphonies
perfectly suited to his own creative temperament. Jerome Robbins
successfully choreographed Bach's ``Goldberg Variations'' for the
New York City Ballet. Molissa Fenley, in ``State of Darkness,''
used Stravinsky's clamorous ``Sacre du Printemps'' _ a score that
most choreographers would tackle by filling the stage with hordes
of people _ for a striking solo about a woman warrior. And the
Dutch choreographer Hans van Manen once successfully created a
ballet to one movement of the ``Hammerklavier.'' Ms. Tharp had
precedents to encourage her.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a dance to the entire ``Hammerklavier,'' which lasts
about 40 minutes? What chutzpah! Nevertheless, from the moment Ms.
Tharp matched Beethoven's bold opening statement by having Andrew
Robinson and Thomas Lund swoop Gabrielle Malone across the stage,
one knew all would go well. There was a joyous solo on point for
Stacey Caddell, a former member of the City Ballet. Ms. Malone, a
modern dancer, was not on point. Yet ``Grosse Sonata'' did not
treat ballet and modern dance as rivals. Rather, their techniques
provided Ms. Tharp with a wide range of movement possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   She explored ways in which Ms. Malone and Robinson could cling
together. Beethoven's theme and variations sequence prompted
unexpected choreographic slowings and speedings, as if time were
stopping and restarting. And, to Beethoven's mighty concluding
fugue, Ms. Tharp repeated and wove together some of the significant
movements she had introduced earlier. So much happened that it was
hard to believe there were only four dancers. But, of course,
Beethoven's musical complexities involve only two hands (in Durham,
the capable hands of Paige Hoffman).
</P>
<P>
   If it was at least conceivable that Ms. Tharp would turn to
Beethoven, since she often employs classical music, who could have
imagined Ms. Brown as the choreographer and stage director for an
opera? Or that the opera would be ``L'Orfeo,'' a Monteverdi work
that ranks among the masterpieces of the 17th century? To be sure,
Ms. Brown created incidental dances for a staging of ``Carmen''
back in 1986. But this production, seen at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music in June, was her own conception, and surely even some of her
admirers could not have predicted it.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, Ms. Brown participated in the experiments of the
Judson Dance Theater, which emphasized ordinary movements. Later,
she made dancers climb walls with the aid of harnesses. More
recently, she has favored deliberately elusive choreography in
which complicated phrases are introduced, only to be swept away
almost instantly. Ms. Brown's artistic progress has been
fascinating. Somehow, it led her to Monteverdi.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the designs of Roland Aeschlimann and the performances
by Concerto Vocale and Collegium Vocale, conducted by Rene Jacobs,
``L'Orfeo'' was scenically and musically notable, as well as
choreographically distinctive. Ms. Brown did much to stress
Monteverdi's contrasts between earth and air, light and darkness,
mortals and deities.
</P>
<P>
   The opera opened magically when, through a circular panel
resembling a porthole, the audience beheld a spirit floating,
seemingly weightless, through space. This figure kept returning
like an emissary from the heavens. The movements for the earthly
characters, many in loosely fitting white suits, were often based
on walking steps. Ms. Brown blended singers and dancers so
skillfully that it was sometimes hard to distinguish who was
dancing and who was singing. Yet, at emotionally charged moments,
the dancers' movements grew more complex, the dancing thereby
heightening the singers' dramatic gestures.
</P>
<P>
   When Euridice died and Orpheus journeyed to the underworld in
search of her, the backdrop darkened with what looked like an
eclipse, huge walls moved forward and Pluto's kingdom became a
realm of darkness. Stage lights were kept so low that shapes were
barely visible. And where some choreographers who stage operas
might have been tempted to keep the cast compulsively busy, Ms.
Brown was not afraid to have people stand still when immobility was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit came flying back to push away black curtains (and,
presumably, the forces of darkness), and Ms. Brown's staging
combined the two endings Monteverdi composed for the opera.
Exemplifying the way in which Renaissance artists could
Christianize Greek mythology, she had Apollo appear as a
Christ-like figure on the backdrop and promise immortality, even as
Orpheus met a martyr's death at the hands of the Bacchantes.
</P>
<P>
   Monteverdi's music often seems to glow. So, finally, did this
production. Ms. Brown and Ms. Tharp both demonstrate that when
experienced choreographers have vision and daring, miracles can
result.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
