<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERTIME, AND THE LIVING IS EASY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Gloria Stuart &LR; , 89, nominated for an Oscar for her role in
``Titanic,'' tells tales of her many lovers in her forthcoming
autobiography, ``I Just Kept Hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart says she's been an advocate and beneficiary of free love
since the '30s, and ``all my lovers have been handsome and
amusing.'' On the other hand, says a passage quoted in the New York
Post, ``I do not need a man. I am devoted to masturbation. I think
it's probably one of the most pleasurable experiences in life. I
had and have no guilt whatsoever when it comes to pleasuring
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yale Club in Manhattan has declared Fridays in the summer
to be casual days, allowing members to show up with neither jacket
nor tie, reports the New York Times. ``We need to engage the
interest of more and more younger members,'' said club President
 &UR; William Weber &LR; , ``professional people who are not just lawyers and
accountants but also architects and people who work on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Club, on the other hand, will not tolerate such
informality in the main dining room. ``Even in the late 1990s,''
said member  &UR; John Sicher &LR; , ``there should be a few havens for
proper attire and decorum. I wouldn't expect the rowdies from New
Haven to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The calm after the storm:  &UR; Gordon Getty &LR; , said to be
vacationing aboard a friend's yacht last week, quietly dined at a
table in the window of Garibaldi's on Monday night. His assistant
said he had returned to San Francisco on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Philippine Senate committee is conducting hearings into
allegations that a Swiss bank account containing $13.4 billion
belongs to the family of the late &UR; Ferdinand Marcos &LR; . ``I wouldn't
be surprised,''  &UR; Imelda Marcos &LR;  said. ``I know we used to have
money.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; William Shatner &LR;  was paid by the National Enquirer to tell
the tabloid that his late wife had been suffering ``from the
serpent of alcoholism,'' notes MSNBC, which says  &UR; Nerine &LR; 
 &UR; Shatner &LR; 's friends are ``appalled.'' Shatner's agent said the
money, $100,000, will be used to set up a center for treatment of
alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   _ An InStyle magazine survey found out that twice as many people
think communication is sexier via the Postal Service than either
voice mail or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WAR BETWEEN THE GIRLS' MAGAZINES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The hottest magazines in the country are for teenage girls, so
it's natural that the competition is equally fiery. Twist says that
CosmoGIRL is a copycat.
</P>
<P>
   Every teen magazine has a most-embarrassing-moment feature;
Twist notes that its ``Blushometer'' rating system, featuring
drawings of three faces with varying degrees of redness, was ripped
off by CosmoGIRL's ``Blush-o-meter,'' featuring three similar
faces. Furthermore, Twist says its ``Whatever'' feature, in which
made-up statements are attributed to celebrities pictured, has been
copied by CosmoGIRL's ``Reading Lips'' feature, which does the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   CosmoGIRL editor  &UR; Atoosa Rubenstein &LR;  denies the charge: ``I had
to run out and buy Twist to figure out what they were referring to.
... I think it's great that our competition is dissecting our first
issue down to a rating system on our embarrassing-moment page, but
there's no truth to what they're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING EVEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Regarding Monday's item about the  &UR; Dalai Lama &LR;  turning down
 &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR; 's invitation: It is said, on good authority, that
the last time he was in the United States, Winfrey turned down his
offer to be on the show.
</P>
<P>
   A representative for Harpo (Winfrey's production company) said
it's true that the Dalai Lama and Winfrey had ``scheduling
conflicts'' for this visit, but she could not confirm any
negotiations about prior visits.
</P>
<P>
   _ And regarding  &UR; Mike Barnicle &LR; 's grandstanding after the death
of  &UR; John F. Kennedy Jr. &LR; , the Boston Herald reports that Sen.  &UR; Ted &LR; 
 &UR; Kennedy &LR; , D-Mass., is furious and has vowed never again to speak to
Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1997, I have been working on a project called Buns of
Butter. I have become a fitness guru and have developed a fitness
program which uses high-caloric foods. ... Buns of Butter has
become a live show, and in 1999, I performed Buns of Butter at the
Performance Art Festival in Cleveland, Ohio. I will be opening a
Buns of Butter gym.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alumnae Kristen Baumlier's description of her professional
achievements, as submitted on the occasion of Founder's Day at the
California College of Arts and Crafts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
