<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE BRET LEAVES TEXANS FEELING LUCKY   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The remnants of Hurricane Bret moved into northern
Mexico on Tuesday after officials in the Texas border town of
Laredo blamed heavy rainfall from the storm for a traffic accident
in which four people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Laredo had feared that the storm would stall over
the low-lying city and repeat the heavy flooding that Tropical
Storm Charlie brought last year to another Texas border town, Del
Rio. Instead, the storm kept moving, causing sporadic flooding in
Laredo but no serious damage there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dodged a major bullet,'' said Jerry Garza, a spokesman for
the city of Laredo. Garza said city officials had declared a state
of emergency after the National Weather Service predicted up to 20
inches of rain, which might have caused the creeks throughout the
city to overflow. ``The creeks filled up,'' Garza said, ``but it
stopped raining.''
</P>
<P>
   Designated Category 4, or extremely dangerous, because of its
145 mile-per-hour winds, the storm veered away from heavily
populated Corpus Christi and came ashore on Sunday in Kenedy
County, a rural expanse of pasture land with only 460 people. Once
ashore, the storm quickly weakened and was downgraded to a tropical
storm by Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cox, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Public Safety,
said officials had estimated that casualties could have been as
high as 1,500 people if the storm had delivered a direct blow to
Corpus Christi. Instead, it meandered westward from Kenedy County
through areas with few, if any, people. The National Weather
Service estimated that the storm had dropped from 25 to 35 inches
of rain in Kenedy County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very lucky,'' said Brian LaMarre, a weather service
meteorologist. ``If it had landed in Corpus Christi or Houston or
any populated area, it would have caused phenomenal damage. As it
was, it turned out to be a rainmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   As thousands of evacuees continued to return home on Tuesday
from inland shelters and hotels, utility workers all but restored
electricity in affected areas. The Texas Public Utility Commission
reported that 3,000 people remained without power but predicted
that all power would be restored by Wednesday. Nearly 3,000 people
remained without telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal traffic accident in Laredo occurred on Monday
afternoon as heavy rains from the storm deluged the city. Officials
said that a tractor-trailer truck jackknifed on a rainy, windy
highway and smashed into a pickup truck. Three people in the pickup
were killed, as was the driver of the tractor-trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That accident happened right when the really heavy part of
Tropical Storm Bret starting affecting Laredo,'' Garza said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2108EDT &QL; 
