<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ANALYST SHIFTS, AND TIME WARNER SHARES FALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Brazil and Japan)   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Time Warner Inc. tumbled about 7 percent
Tuesday after a Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. analyst who has been a strong
supporter of the stock sharply reduced her earnings estimates for
the company, citing problems in its music business.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Time Warner fell $4.5625, to $61.625, after falling as
low as $60. More than 15.6 million shares changed hands, making the
company's stock the seventh most traded issue.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst, Jessica Reif Cohen, lowered her earnings estimate
for 1999 to 35 cents a share from 48 cents and her estimate for
2000 to 80 cents from 82 cents. She cited Time Warner's declining
share in the American music market and weakness in key foreign
markets like Germany, Brazil and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The revision spooked Wall Street because Time Warner stock over
the last three years has been a stellar performer, although it has
been falling in the last month or so. ``Any kind of a
disappointment in a momentum stock like that gets people nervous,''
said David Londoner, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors saw the fall in the stock price as an
over-reaction by the market and a buying opportunity. After all,
some noted, Ms. Cohen's estimate had been much higher than those of
most other analysts, and her revision merely moves her close to the
average estimate of 37 cents a share for this year and 67 cents for
next year, as compiled by First Call Corp., which tracks company
earnings. Moreover, some said, the problems in the record business
have generally been known. Also, even Ms. Cohen herself still rates
Time Warner a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually bought some more stock this morning,'' said Mark
Greenberg, portfolio manager of the Invesco Leisure Fund, which
counts Time Warner as one of its 10 largest holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg noted that Time Warner named a new head of its music
division last week and said it was not unusual for new executives
to try to lower expectations at the start so they have some room to
show improvement. ``I don't believe there's a fundamental problem
at Time Warner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new chairman of Warner Music, Roger Ames, is taking over
from Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel, who were known primarily for
running the Warner Brothers movie studio and had little experience
in music. Ames, a former head of music operations at Polygram NV,
will be faced with ending years of management turmoil at Warner
Music, stemming a slide in market share and strengthening the
company's international operations, which have never been as strong
as its American business.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Tuesday, Ms. Cohen said that despite healthy
conditions for the music industry as a whole, ``Warner Music has
been experiencing a downturn in its domestic and international
music sales.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's share of the overall album business in the United
States declined to 16.6 percent in the first half of this year from
18.3 percent in the period a year earlier, she said, while
Seagram's Universal Music gained strength after its acquisition of
Polygram.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, which ended in June, Time Warner reported
a decline in revenue in its record business but an improvement in
earnings, in part because of cost savings. But Ms. Cohen said cost
cuts would make less of a difference going forward. She cut her
estimate of music division earnings before interest, taxes and
amortization to $478 million for this year from a previous estimate
of $540 million. Last year, the company had music earnings of $493
million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen also increased her estimates of the losses to be
recorded by the WB Network, citing its additional spending on
distribution in smaller markets.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has in recent years replaced the struggling Walt
Disney Co. as the queen of media stocks. Time Warner stock, which
trades under the symbol TWX, has gone from a 52-week low of less
than $38 to a recent high of more than $78. But it has been falling
in the last few weeks as the market began to view the stock as
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen recommends the stock, with a 12-month price target of
$85. ``While we continue to recommend TWX as a core media holding,
we believe the shares may continue to tread water near term as
current year estimates decrease,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
