<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-BRADY-LADN     08-24 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BRADY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S BRADY MOLDED IN FLOWERS' IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to mistake the coach and quarterback for teammates,
because they were.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Aaron Flowers was playing his final season at Cal State
Northridge and Marcus Brady was a 17-year-old freshman. Now, less
than two years after his final game as a Matador, Flowers is
teaching Brady everything he knows about the run-and-shoot offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the best quarterback situation in the
country,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin said. ``What Marcus
Brady has been able to absorb from Aaron is the nuances of the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The molding of Brady into Flowers' image has been so successful
that Flowers' father, Norm, can instantly see the similarities when
he watches film of his son's senior year and Brady from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brady)'s drop and release looks so much like Aaron,'' said
Norm Flowers, a former high school coach. ``I don't know if that's
a natural thing, or what.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see Aaron Flowers in Brady. Both are about the
same height and build, although Flowers said there is one
noticeable difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When stuff breaks down and he starts to scramble, he doesn't
look like me,'' he said, noting Brady's superior athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, who had the best passing season in CSUN history in 1996
when he threw for 3,540 yards and 30 touchdowns, is in the unusual
situation of watching his records be smashed _ from the sideline.
He thinks Brady has a good chance to break those records this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the day comes sooner than everyone thinks,'' Flowers
said. ``I'm going to be happy for him on that day. I'm one of the
guys that got this thing started and he's going to be known as one
of the guys who got it to the next level, that won a Big Sky
championship, that won a national championship.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Easy transition
</P>
<P>
   For Flowers, becoming a coach was a natural progression. His dad
was a coach and Aaron played like a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Flowers was the head coach at Artesia from 1990-95. He said
other parents' objections to Aaron becoming the starting
quarterback ended quickly when they saw the kid's uncanny
combination of intensity and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things he had as a player, they are intangibles you just
can't coach,'' Norm said. ``Someone once said (Aaron) was obsessed
with football.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady has talked about Flowers' ability to ``control the
offense.'' It wasn't hard for Flowers, considering he was calling
his own plays as a sophomore _ in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knows the offense,'' Brady said of his first-year
coach. ``It makes it that much easier. What I see is what he saw.''
</P>
<P>
   And what most see is a young coach who has a firm grasp of the
run-and-shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers was a graduate assistant last year when Brady threw for
2,983 yards and 26 touchdowns. After the season ended, and to the
delight of Brady, then head coach Ron Ponciano promoted Flowers to
quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, Flowers could easily be playing and not coaching
football, but that doesn't matter. Because he is only 6-foot,
Flowers _ the Big Sky Newcomer of the Year in '96 and second-team
all-conference two consecutive years _ never thought about playing
in the NFL, or even the Canadian Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to leave my family to go up to Canada... just
to take a shot,'' he said. ``I felt I had done what I wanted to do
in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers transferred his competitive energy to coaching. When the
lease on the house he shared ended this summer, Flowers slept in
the Matadors' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neatest thing I notice about Aaron is how much he cares
about the players,'' said Amber Saenz, Flowers' girlfriend of
almost two years. ``He never reflects on what he has (done). He
would rather bring it out of someone else. He could care less if
his name is ever brought up in a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brags about the records Marcus is going to break,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's All-American
</P>
<P>
   Brady spent the summer doing clerical work for the County of San
Diego. Every once in a while, he would get a call from Flowers.
``Just to make sure nothing was distracting me,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be easy for Brady to relax or let down after the impact
he made as a freshman. But that hasn't happened, given his
performance during the team's first weeks of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is playing at a high, high level,'' Kearin said after a
recent practice.
</P>
<P>
   That should be no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, who played three sports in high school, started at
quarterback and was the team captain at San Diego's Morse High in
1996, and the Eagles went 12-1. As a junior, he started at
off-guard for the basketball team. He pitched, played shortstop and
outfield for a baseball team that once beat the No. 1 team in the
nation _ Mt. Carmel, which featured future first-round draft
choices Eric Chavez and Eric Munson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports has been pretty much my whole life,'' Brady said.
``(Sports) fits my personality. I love to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was growing up, Brady spent hours playing basketball in
his driveway. He played to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd lose, he wanted to get another teammate,'' said Drew
Amerson, a redshirt freshman wide receiver at CSUN who grew up near
Brady in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Brady graduated from high school with a 3.6 GPA and scored 1,150
on the SAT. If he was two or three inches taller, Brady could have
played for any team in the nation. But at 5-11, his options were
limited to the Ivy League, which doesn't offer athletic
scholarships, or the service academies.
</P>
<P>
   Brady chose the Navy. After only a few months of what he called
``boot camp,'' he quit and came home.
</P>
<P>
   Brady ended up at CSUN simply because the coaching staff didn't
block his desire to play quarterback. Every college that recruited
him out of high school wanted Brady to play defensive back or wide
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Brady spent the season on the sideline as a redshirt,
watching Flowers. He had never heard of Flowers before, but he
admired Flowers' toughness as he played through a stress fracture
in his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Brady hurt his elbow against Northern Arizona last year but came
back to play against Eastern Washington the next week. He completed
19 of 24 passes for 285 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way I was going to sit out that next game,''
Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year, Brady displayed the toughness and leadership
that marked Flowers' two years at CSUN. Now he has Flowers teaching
him the system.
</P>
<P>
   Is this destiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I have one of the greatest jobs for a young coach
because I have a kid like (Brady),'' he said. ``I see it as a big
risk. He was the Big Sky Newcomer of the Year (last year). What if
his numbers drop and he throws 20 interceptions? Where is the blame
going to go? To me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay up at night thinking about if he gets hurt or if I am
doing too much stuff with him, putting too much in his brain,'' he
said. ``Time will tell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
