<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UVA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia hurting on defense
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ Virginia has won at least seven games 12
years in a row, but that success could be in jeopardy as coach
George Welsh prepares for his 18th season with the Cavaliers. Four
defensive players have been suspended for the season for either
academic or legal problems. A fifth, backup tailback Antwoine
Womack, who rushed for 708 yards and made second-team All-ACC in
1998, has taken a leave of absence for this season because of legal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Among the defenders, only end Darryl Sanders (academics) was
projected as a starter, but safety Devon Simmons (legal trouble)
and linebackers Donny Green (academics) and John Duckett (legal)
would have had significant playing time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers expect problems on defense, the unit that has been
strong in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply don't have the talent we've had in the past,'' Welsh
said. ``The talent and the depth on defense is not what it's been.
I'd rather win games with defense. I've won games with defense and
a good running game in the past, but that's not enough today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs appear strong on offense. Most of the starters are
back. One who isn't is quarterback Aaron Brooks, who graduated. His
replacement is Dan Ellis, who says he doesn't run as well as Brooks
and can't throw as far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a pocket-type quarterback,'' he said. ``I guess
I'm the one big question mark coming into the season, although I
don't see myself as a question mark.'' Ellis will be Virginia's
seventh quarterback in eight seasons, but that isn't necessarily a
detriment, starting tailback Thomas Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's going to do a good job,'' Jones said. ``He's really
smart and makes good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones rushed for 1,303 yards last season to lead the ACC. He
scored 15 times and is the No. 4 returning rusher in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10, 205-pounder and native of Big Stone Gap, Va.,
attended three summer schools, took an overload of course hours
each year and graduated in three years with a degree in psychology.
He is in graduate school this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said contact is what he likes best about football.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may sound kind of weird, being a running back, but it
makes me feel good to play hard for 60 minutes,'' he said. ``With
Antwoine out, I may have to carry four or five times more per game,
but I feel I get better as the game goes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the biggest disappointment of his career has been
last season's 41-38 loss to Georgia Tech. Virginia led 38-17 before
the Yellow Jackets scored 24 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had won that game,'' Jones said, ``we could have easily
jumped into the top five (in the rankings).''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems worried about a drop in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be second in the ACC,'' linebacker Shannon
Taylor said. ``We want to be involved in the BCS (Bowl Championship
Series). We had a chance last year and lost to Georgia Tech. Coach
said this is the fastest team he's ever had. I believe strongly
we're a top 10 team.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
