<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL GUERROUJ EXTENDS WINNING STREAK IN 1,500-METER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ As he floated toward the finish line and his
second straight 1,500-meter world championship, Hicham El Guerrouj
had time to throw kisses. First with one hand, then the other,
finally both. With the tender expression on his boyish face, there
was never a question of boastfulness: This was a young man thanking
someone.
</P>
<P>
   One was for his family, he explained later. Another for the
crowd. And the third? To pay tribute, the 24-year-old Moroccan
said, to having just run in ``one of the best races of this
century, and that makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   El Guerrouj's winning time of 3 minutes 27.65 seconds (the
fifth-fastest in history) was just 1.65 seconds off his world
record, and as he came through the final 100 meters, many in the
crowd of 50,810 rocking Estadio Olimpico thought they were about to
see it broken. El Guerrouj knew he would fall short, but said there
are more important things in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have the world record,'' he said with a smile.
``This is about winning the world title.''
</P>
<P>
   Just behind him, as expected, was Noah Ngeny, the 20-year-old
Kenyan who helped push El Guerrouj to his world record in the mile
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm not unhappy,'' said Ngeny, whose 3:28.73 is a
Kenyan national record. ``El Guerrouj is a wonderful runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ngeny was followed by Reyes Estevez of Spain (3:30.57).
Noureddine Morceli of Algeria, the Olympic gold medalist and
three-time world champion, was running in fifth as they began last
lap, but soon began to lose ground and did not finish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the conditions _ 92 degrees and 50 percent humidity at
the 9:10 p.m. start _ it was the fastest 1,500 meters in World
Championship history, with El Guerrouj's countryman, Adil Kaouch,
setting a strong pace of 1:52.15 though 800 meters. As the last lap
began, El Guerrouj was in the lead, followed by Estevez, Ngeny, and
former Olympic champion Fermin Cacho of Spain. With about 300
meters left, the medalists became clear, as El Guerrouj began to
pull away and Ngeny passed Estevez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like that,'' American Steve Holman
(3:34.32, ninth) said of El Guerrouj's race. ``To run 3:27 after
rounds in this heat was otherworldly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Estevez complained of pace-setting by Kaouch (``the
beauty of the final was taken away''), El Guerrouj denied the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We entered the race each one for himself,'' he said. ``There
was no preplanned tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaouch finished last.
</P>
<P>
   And El Guerrouj, once again, first.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has not lost at 1,500 meters since his bell-lap fall
in the 1996 Olympics said doubt never entered his mind Tuesday
night that his streak would live on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure about winning the race before and throughout my run
tonight,'' he said. ``It is as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second marquee event of the night, world record-holder
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia became a four-time world champion
with his 27:57.27 victory at 10,000 meters, a distance at which he
has not lost since 1993. Runner-up was Paul Tergat of Kenya
(27:58.56), with Assefa Mezgebu (27:59.15) of Ethiopia taking the
bronze. Americans Brad Hauser (29:18.21) and Peter Julian
(29:20.31) were 21st and 22d, while Alan Culpepper did not finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
