<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-EXCLUSIVE-GOV-SUIT-97     08-24 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-GOV-SUIT-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT SUED OVER NOT PAYING OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Workers for a large and well-known employer in the
nation's capital have accused their bosses of juggling the books to
cheat them out of overtime pay in violation of the law and then
lying about to it to conceal the illegality. Sounds like a case for
the Justice Department, except in this instance the employer is the
Justice Department, the agency charged with enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a federal judge said the court would ask more than
12,400 current and former Justice Department lawyers whether they
wanted to join a class-action lawsuit filed last year by nearly 200
lawyers against the agency. The lawsuit seeks a half-billion
dollars for what the lawyers charge are millions of hours of
overtime that the department owes them.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly candid internal Justice Department documents have
been provided to the plaintiffs by the agency. They show that
department officials knew they were in violation, but kept, in
effect, two sets of books.
</P>
<P>
   One set, on which paychecks were based, required lawyers to
state that they worked 40 hours a week, no matter how much time
they actually put in.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials also kept a second set of records _
detailed, computerized time sheets that clocked overtime hours. The
records were used by superiors to measure their lawyers' effort, to
ask Congress for bigger budgets and even to bill legal fees to
losing adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are individuals who have devoted their professional
lives to enforcing the law,'' Robert A. Van Kirk, a lawyer at the
firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly who represents the Justice Department
employees, said, ``and, as a matter of principle, many object to
the nation's chief law-enforcement agency purposefully ignoring the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that the Justice Department ranked the 94
U.S. Attorneys' offices according to how many overtime hours were
worked in each office each month. The results were distributed to
supervisors who exhorted prosecutors, in some cases by name, to log
more overtime hours so the office would advance in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also show that Justice Department officials have
known for many years that lawyers worked more hours than the
official 40 a week and realized that a 1945 law, the Federal
Employees Pay Act, required the Justice Department and other
executive branch agencies to pay all employees overtime or to give
them compensatory time off.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is represented in the case by lawyers
from the civil division who have been granted a waiver from their
superiors to defend the agency even though they have a financial
stake in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials would not discuss the specifics of
the lawyers' case because of the pending litigation. But a senior
Justice Department official speaking on condition of anonymity said
that almost no lawyers at the department had ever expected to
receive overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   The official questioned the applicability of federal overtime
statutes to Justice Department employees and said that it was
generally understood within the agency that only overtime
pre-approved by an authorizing official was eligible for
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the official said, if the lawyers prevailed, the
culture of professionalism at the Justice Department would be
altered, forcing lawyers to work in the less desirable environment
of the hourly wage worker.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from seeking legislation to bar lawyers from being
paid for overtime, the Justice Department has not corrected the
problem, in part because of the administrative headaches, a work
ethic that regards lawyers as professionals who are expected to
work long hours, and the high cost of a fix, estimated to be $40
million to $50 million a year, or more.
</P>
<P>
   The case, filed in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, which has
jurisdiction over claims against the government exceeding $10,000,
is potentially embarrassing for the agency that routinely
prosecutes companies for infractions that seem no more serious. It
may also embarrass Attorney General Janet Reno, who in in-house
speeches has frequently emphasized her desire to make the Justice
Department a worker- and family-friendly workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with Justice Department lawyers suggest that
government lawyers, who once might have have been reluctant to sue
their employer, have gone to court because the overtime issue has
widened the gulf between their salaries and the hefty ones of
lawyers in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers fresh out of law school make about
$40,000 a year. The most battle-hardened Justice litigators make
about $125,000 a year, which is a little more than the beginning
salary for law school graduates who land jobs as associates at some
of the country's top private firms.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors. Although the government was once
thought of as a dignified public service refuge for lawyers who
wanted to avoid the high-pressure environment of private firms, the
working lives of lawyers at the Justice Department have changed in
recent years. Criminal, civil and appellate litigation is
increasingly complicated, stressful and enormously time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, many career lawyers have grown weary of putting
in punishing hours on a case without overtime or compensatory time
while some must submit a written request to take a few hours of
vacation time to attend a child's school event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud to be an assistant United States Attorney,'' said
Kenneth C. Bauman, a veteran federal prosecutor in Portland, Ore.,
who has joined the class-action suit. ``I love my job. My job is to
enforce the laws of the United State adhering to the highest
ethical standards. I was surprised when this suit was filed and
later on when I was told that my employer, the Department of
Justice, had not followed the law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Justice Department administrators have told lawyers who work in
the agency's U.S. Attorneys' offices and at its Washington
headquarters that they are not entitled to overtime or compensatory
time. As the agency's manual said, ``Assistant U.S. Attorneys are
professionals and should expect to work in excess of regular hours
without overtime pay.''
</P>
<P>
   But the law appears to say otherwise. Van Kirk's team has
uncovered internal memorandums dating back nearly 20 years in which
the Justice Department acknowledged that lawyers were entitled to
overtime pay. One review of the issue, in 1980, determined that
``attorneys, other than members of the senior executive service,
are entitled to overtime or compensatory time.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers have uncovered a paper trail of documents that they
say indicate that the Justice Department has continued to violate
the law long after its officials plainly knew they were breaking
it.
</P>
<P>
   In one 1998 memorandum, a senior Justice Department lawyer, Fran
M. Allegra, addressed the issue. ``I believe it is problematic
(some might use the term unconscionable) for the department to
continue to not pay its attorneys overtime knowing full well that
the overtime statute applies,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a prophetic conclusion, Allegra wrote, ``In any event, if the
department continues to ignore this problem, sooner or later, an
intrepid attorney will develop a class action on this issue and
major problems will result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
