<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAILEY-CONTEMPT-COX     08-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-CONTEMPT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bailey skips contempt hearing, rushes to bedside of critically
ill wife
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In 40 years of limelight trials, F. Lee Bailey's
presence in a courtroom seldom created more drama, consternation
and skepticism than his absence _ and the reason for it _ in U.S.
District Court here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TV cameras and reporters waited in vain outside the federal
building for the famous defense lawyer who was scheduled to defend
himself against a contempt of court citation for refusing to turn
over $2 million belonging to a convicted client and claimed by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the pugnacious legal lion in cowboy boots, U.S.
Magistrate James Glazebrook and federal prosecutors found
themselves facing owlish and soft-spoken Richard Lubin, pleading
for a humanitarian delay of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey had been called away from his hotel at 4 a.m. to the
bedside of his critically ill wife, Lubin said. Patricia Bailey,
56, had nerve-block surgery Monday at Indian River Memorial
Hospital in Vero Beach to relieve excruciating pain from pancreatic
cancer, Lubin said. But ``something had gone wrong with the
surgery,'' he said, and early Tuesday she was unconscious and
starting to experience organ failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors required that he be there,'' Lubin said. ``He is
in no condition to assist me or to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from Bailey's defense of infomercial king William
McCorkle, a former stripper, and his wife, Chantal, who were
convicted last year of fraud and money laundering. The jury that
convicted the McCorkles of swindling people with a get-rich-quick
real estate scheme ordered them to forfeit $10.6 million in assets,
including $7.1 million in Cayman Islands bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The government got $5.1 million from the accounts and demanded
the remaining $2 million, but Bailey said it was his for legal fees
and costs, and most had already been spent. Glazebrook ordered him
to pay $2 million into the court registry, Bailey refused, and the
judge set the contempt hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The McCorkles, who are appealing their 24-year prison terms, sat
through the hearing in ankle chains and bright orange jumpsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bailey spent 44 days in jail in Tallahassee in a
similar fight with the government, over $17 million in stock he
refused to turn over after representing Canadian drug dealer Claude
DuBoc. McCorkle loaned Bailey $100,000 to help him get out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   To pay off debts he'd accumulated by borrowing against the
stock, he mortgaged his 74-foot yacht Spellbound, and the $1.2
million home he and Patricia Bailey own in Manalapan.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's reputation for tricky legal strategy appeared to work
against him at first, as
</P>
<P>
   federal prosecutors were clearly skeptical about the last-minute
emergency plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is at a loss,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Marie
DeMarco said, noting that Bailey had filed motions to delay the
hearing on other grounds before bringing up his wife's medical
problems. ``We just don't know about her condition.''
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that Bailey had transferred $400,000 of the
Cayman Islands money into his wife's personal bank account in West
Palm Beach at one time.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco and Glazebrook both said the magistrate had admonished
Bailey repeatedly to get another attorney to represent him.
</P>
<P>
   Glazebrook said he sympathized with Lubin, who'd had only two
days to review the complex case, but that was no grounds for
delaying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Bailey chose not to retain you in time, then his case
may be jeopardized by your inability to argue it on your feet,'' he
told Lubin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, Bailey had never mentioned his wife's medical
condition in all the grounds he'd cited trying to get the hearing
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who did not want to use that as a reason,''
Lubin said. ``This is a proud man. This thing took a horrible turn
... and just overwhelmed him. These are last ditch efforts to save
this lady's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Glazebrook recessed the hearing, called all the lawyers into his
chambers and had a private hearing in which he telephoned Patricia
Bailey's primary physician, Dr. Jeremy Geffen of the Geffen Cancer
Center and Research Institute in Vero Beach. Then Glazebrook came
back into the courtroom and postponed the hearing until Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no question that Mr. Bailey needs to be
with his wife over the next few days,'' the magistrate said.
</P>
<P>
   The Geffen Center describes its program as a mixture of
conventional treatments _ surgery, chemotherapy, radiation _ with
alternative therapies such as nutrition, psychotherapy, massage,
acupuncture, and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bailey nor Geffen could be reached for comment late
Tuesday. Lubin said Bailey was in the hospital's intensive care
unit with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always hope,'' he said, ``so they're hoping she can
recover from this downturn and respond to treatment. That's all I
can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McLachlin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
