08-24 -- A jet with Sun Country Airlines, a small carrier that
started flying a regular schedule to 15 destinations in June, taxis
near airliners with Northwest, the nations fourth largest carrier.
Most cities root unabashedly for a home-town business to make it
big. But here, where Northwest Airlines has its headquarters,
employs 21,000, and controls 80 percent of the airline seats out of
the city, many people are rooting for Sun Country Airlines. (Steve
Woit/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- FBN-GIANTS, 08-24 --
Giants free safety Percy Ellsworth during a team practice on
Tuesday. The Giants have done little to distort the importance of
their preseason meeting this weekend with the Jets. With starting
jobs on the line and key players returning from injury, mythical
territorial struggles hardly raise the stakes in the preseason.
(David Jennings/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Aug. 24, 1999 --
HAIR-MAKEOVER-COX, 08-24 -- Lisa Fulp, before and after her hair
makeover at the Babor Institute. ``I just don't know what to do
with it,'' she told stylist George Elliott. (Stephanie Welsh/Palm
Beach Post Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ATLANTA -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- COLORS-COX, 08-24 -- In the
world of color, nothing is just blue anymore. Increasingly it's not
even navy or sky or lapis. Crayola seems to now favor wholesome
all-American names, like Macaroni and Cheese (orange, of course)
and chestnut. When there are a bazillion shades of rose cosmetics
or crayons or paints on the market, giving them all specific,
sometimes strange names is a practical way to tell them apart.
(Joey Ivansco/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- BERGER-PROFILE-2, 08-24
-- National Security Advisor Sandy Berger in his White House in
1998. Widely regarded as Clinton's closest foreign policy aide,
perhaps the most influential national security adviser since Henry
Kissinger, Berger is a political rather than strategic figure.
Unlike the professors, diplomats and military officers who have for
the most part preceded him in his job, he made his way to the White
House by way of the back rooms of Democratic politics while
pursuing a public career as a trade lawyer. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- BERGER-PROFILE-1, 08-24
-- National Security Adviser Sandy Berger confers with President
Clinton in a hallway outside the Cabinet Room that leads to the
Oval Office in April, 1997. Widely regarded as Clinton's closest
foreign policy aide, perhaps the most influential national security
adviser since Henry Kissinger, Berger is a political rather than a
strategic figure. Unlike the professors, diplomats and military
officers who have for the most part preceded him in his job, he
made his way to the White House by way of the back rooms of
Democratic politics while pursuing a public career as a trade
lawyer. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WEST BARNSTABLE, Mass. -- Aug. 24, 1999 --
MILLENNIUM-PILGRIMS-COX-2, 08-24 -- Rev. Reed Baer delivers his
sermon from atop the high altar during services at United Church of
Christ. The Congregationalist church, erected in 1717, is the
nation's oldest in continuous operation. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WEST BARNSTABLE, Mass. -- Aug. 24, 1999 --
