<P>
   (NYT15) IZMIT, Turkey -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- TURKEY-QUAKE-2, 08-24
-- Earthquake damage and flooding along the coast of Izmit is seen
from a U.S. Navy helicopter on Monday. The death toll from the
quake has passed 18,000 and is expected to climb much higher. The
Turkish government estimates that not only caring for earthquake
victims but rebuilding destroyed homes and businesses is expected
to cost billions of dollars. (Seth Rossman, U.S. Navy/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) IZMIT, Turkey -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- TURKEY-QUAKE-2, 08-24
-- Oil slicks are seen off Izmit on Monday near fuel facilities
that were damaged in last week's earthquake. The death toll from
the quake has passed 18,000 and is expected to climb much higher.
The Turkish government estimates that not only caring for
earthquake victims but rebuilding destroyed homes and businesses is
expected to cost billions of dollars. (Seth Rossman, U.S. Navy/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- DIMSUM-BOOK-REVIEW, 08-24 --
``Dim Sum: The Essential Kitchen'' by Vicki Liley. The book gives
advice on serving dim sum and tea (never serve sugar and milk with
the tea), and on what place settings are best with what dishes.
Beautiful photographs accompany each recipe, though the ones for
shrimp balls and clams in black bean sauce were reversed. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HOLLYWOOD -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- TV-CHICAGO-HOPE, 08-24 --
Mandy Patinkin prepares to shoot a scene on ``Chicago Hope.'' The
show is, in effect, being hit with a triple heart bypass,
electroshock therapy, multiple organ transplants and a fashion
makeover, in the form of new producers, a new writing staff, the
replacement of nearly half the cast and a new time slot - not to
mention new opening titles and new theme music. (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- SIMPLE-COOKING, 08-24 --
Combine canned Thai curry paste (shown) with canned coconut milk,
and you have the equivalent of Campbell's soup for the '90s. This
sauce has launched a thousand dishes. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- EGGPLANT-3, 08-24 -- In
their quiet way, eggplants can bring harmony to a variety of
dishes. In the eastern Mediterranean, the eggplant is a beloved
staple. It replaces meat in stews; it is sliced thin, grilled and
drizzled with fruity olive oil; it is charred, peeled and blended
into a silky, garlicky puree; it is layered with tomatoes, onions
and oil, and baked until it is creamy and caramelized. Eggplants
are even cooked in sugar syrup and eaten as a sweet. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- EGGPLANT-2, 08-24 -- The
ratatouille at Tabla, which combines white, purple and Asian
eggplants, is served with lamb. It is said in the Middle East that
a woman is not ready to marry until she knows 1,000 ways to cook
eggplant. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- EGGPLANT-1, 08-24 --
Eggplant, at its freshest now, is served roasted at Etats-Unis in
Manhattan. In their quiet way, eggplants can bring harmony to a
variety of dishes. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 29 --
THEATER-MUSICALS-2, 08-24 -- Bill Rosenfield, senior vice president
for shows and soundtracks at RCA Victor, is the executive behind
both big-budget extravaganzas like ``Ragtime,'' and nontraditional
works like ``Bring In da Noise/Bring In da Funk'' and Stephen
Sondheim's ``Assassins.'' ``We know that to get the smashes down
the road, there have to be relationships established with promising
composers early on,'' says Rosenfield, 45, in his Manhattan office.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 29 --
THEATER-MUSICALS-1, 08-24 -- Recordings of musicals have become a
staple, even if some don't make a profit. ``In every area in which
we record, I look to establish long-term relationships with artists
whose talent is so big the world eventually is going to come
around,'' says Robert Hurwitz, the 50-year-old president of
Nonesuch records, in his Manhattan office. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- KITCHEN-WARES, 08-24 -- The
Tomato Core-It ``bites'' the core out of a tomato. Made by Prince
Castle Inc. in Carol Stream, Ill., it looks a lot like a melon
baller with teeth. Tomato Core-It works remarkably well, scooping
out the core of a tomato in a single circular motion. It can also
hull strawberries and core halved apples and pears. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- CULTURE-YIDDISH-BOS-2, 08-24
-- Mark David reads a Yiddish story to his children, Michael, 9,
and Rebecca, 7, on his living room couch as his wife Debbie Ellerin
looks on. David and his wife are among a tiny handful of
English-speaking couples in Massachusetts teaching their children
to speak Yiddish, the language of their East European Jewish
forebears. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- CULTURE-YIDDISH-BOS, 08-24 --
Mark David, left, looks on as his son Michael David, 9, reacts to
losing at a game of Yiddish Lotto. David and his wife are among a
tiny handful of English-speaking couples in Massachusetts teaching
their children to speak Yiddish, the language of their East
European Jewish forebears. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) OAKVILLE, Calif. -- Aug. 24, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 08-24 --
Andrew Hoxley, left, and Robert Lawson tending the wares at the
Napa Wine Company. The company is what is known in the trade as a
custom crush facility. It makes wine in someone else's winery. For
a small production winemaker, the economic benefits of what is
known in the the trade as a custom crush winery are incredibly
beneficial. For a fee, the company will handle the entire wine
making process. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 24, 1999 --
HELP-YOURSELF-EATING-WELL-B&AMP;W, 08-24 -- A self-service counter in a
Manhattan eatery. Recent inspections by health authorities suggest
that chances of getting sick from these types of help-yourself
establishments may be greater than people think, especially if they
have compromised immune systems. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
