<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED RAISES INTEREST RATES TO HELP AVERT INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve raised interest rates by a quarter of a
percentage point, its second increase in less than two months, to
help avert inflation while allowing the long economic expansion to
continue. Over objections from farmers, labor unions and
manufacturers, the Fed, which is headed by Alan Greenspan, raised
the target for the federal funds rate on overnight loans among
banks, to 5.25 percent from 5 percent and the discount rate on
loans to banks from the Federal Reserve system to 4.75 percent from
4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BANK ONE ISSUES EARNINGS WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Bank One, the nation's fifth-largest banking company, said that
its 1999 earnings per share could be as much as 8 percent below
forecasts because of lower-than-expected revenues from its First
USA credit card unit.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SCRUTINY OF BANK OF NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, Congress and the British
authorities have joined in the money laundering investigation at
the Bank of New York. At issue is whether the bank helped uncover
questionable Russian funds, some tied to crime, or simply looked
the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE FIRMS TO OFFER LATE TRADING
</P>
<P>
   Two more online brokerage firms have agreed to offer customers
after-hours stock trading. Discover Brokerage and Dreyfus Brokerage
Services plan to start today.
</P>
<P>
   WALT DISNEY TOY DEAL EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney is expected to announce Wednesday that it has bought
a 60 percent stake in Toysmart.com, a small online retailer of
educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   Disney completed the sale of its Fairchild Publications division
to the Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   FORD MAY NOT BE CONTRACT TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Ford is facing labor troubles even as GM's labor relations
improve, auto executives and UAW leaders say. Consequently, the
union may not negotiate first with Ford in this year's contract
talks, as it did in 1993 and 1996 to Ford's competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL NETWORKS TO BUY PERIPHONICS
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to create technology that combines phone and Internet
services, Nortel Networks agreed to acquire Periphonics, a maker of
telephone-processing and call-center systems, for about $436
million in stock. Periphonics stock rose $2.375 to $27.625, in
Nasdaq trading on news of the deal, which values the stock at
$29.23 a share.
</P>
<P>
   SPIRITED SESSION FOR INTERNET GROUP
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks and controversy that have become its trademark
marked the opening session of the Internet's new governing body,
Internet Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, in Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   PLEA FOR PEACE IN AN OIL BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Jaffre, chairman of Elf Aquitaine SA, which is locked
in a takeover battle with the French-Belgian oil company Total Fina
SA pleaded for a peaceful deal.
</P>
<P>
   FREE NETSCAPE SERVICE IN BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   America Online introduced free Internet service in Britain under
the name Netscape Online. It hopes to overtake the growing crowd of
competitors that already offer free access.
</P>
<P>
   35 MILLION POUNDS PAY FOR WPP CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Martin Sorrell, chief executive of WPP Group, is to receive
company shares worth 35 million pounds ($56 million) as part of a
much-disputed performance-based compensation package that he
created.
</P>
</TEXT>
