<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYCHEM-3S </SLUG>
 D1  
 Raychem Lays Off 646 In Bay Area Consolidation
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Henry Norr and Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In one of the biggest Silicon Valley layoffs in recent years,
Raychem yesterday announced it will cut 646 jobs in Menlo Park,
Redwood City and Fremont as its new parent company begins
consolidating operations.
</P>
<P>
   The news came less than two weeks after shareholders of Menlo
Park-based Raychem approved a $2.9-billion buyout by Tyco
International, a fast growing conglomerate based in Bermuda. The
new owners are combining Raychem, which makes a diverse array of
wiring devices, fuses and other electronic components, with AMP, an
even larger component manufacturer acquired by Tyco earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 2,200 positions, half of them abroad, are to be
eliminated from the Raychem and AMP payrolls by the end of the
year. Most of the cuts will be completed by the end of September,
company officials said. Some local workers were shown the door
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   All of the jobs being eliminated in this area are white-collar
positions, according to company spokeswoman Maryanne Kane.
</P>
<P>
   Raychem is one of several large Bay Area employers that have
recently announced major job cuts. Last week disk drive maker
Quantum said it would lay off 750 to 800 employees, including about
600 in Milpitas, or about a quarter of its local work force.
Yesterday Quantum arch-rival Seagate Technologies chimed in with
news of 1,600 layoffs in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The new job cuts at Raychem come on top of 300 announced in
June. After the latest round of layoffs, the company will continue
to employ some 2,500 people in the Bay Area and about 7,000 total.
Together, AMP and Raychem will employ about 45,000 people
worldwide. Their combined sales will amount to about $7.2 billion
this year. Overall, Kane said, the companies expect that
``hundreds'' of employees whose jobs are scheduled for elimination
will be able to transfer into different positions on the
AMP/Raychem payroll. Those who are laid off will be offered
``generous'' severance payments, she said, but she refused to
provide details, citing privacy considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Workers knew they would find out yesterday who would go and who
would stay. ``I called this `the big day.' We knew for the last two
weeks we would find out today,'' said a Raychem saleswoman who did
not lose her job.
</P>
<P>
   Laid-off workers were given notice in the morning and had the
day to clean out their desks. In the parking lot, one worker left
behind a grocery bag containing a green lamp, a box of chocolates,
a bottle of wine and a crinkled old birthday card.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of RAYCHEM2 (16447 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Among those laid off, emotions were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some were sad because they'd been there for a real long time,
15 or 20 years. It was like their family,'' said one female
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Others ``had been here for a long time and they wanted the
severance pay and, around here, it's not too hard to find another
job,'' a salesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Outplacement consultants were on site yesterday, helping
laid-off workers brush up their resumes and interviewing
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The job reductions are part of a larger plan under which AMP and
Raychem operations will be reorganized into a series of integrated
business units defined by the market segments they serve, such as
communications, energy and automotive, Kane said. Products,
however, will continue to be sold under the AMP or Raychem brand
names.
</P>
<P>
   AMP President Jurgen Gromer will preside over the combined
operation. Former Raychem CEO Richard Kashnow will serve as
executive vice president for business development and investments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
