<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISNEY-FAIRCHILD-NYT &LR;      08-24 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-FAIRCHILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION MAGAZINE INDUSTRY CONSOLIDATES WITH A BIG DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DISNEY-TOYSMART) 
(mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fashion magazine world consolidated Tuesday with
the agreement to sell Fairchild Publications Inc. to Advance
Publications, the parent company of Conde Nast. Advance will now be
the publisher not just of its current stable of Vogue, Vanity Fair
and Mademoiselle, but also of Women's Wear Daily, W and Jane.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the magazines was not disclosed Tuesday, but last
week executives at both Advance and Walt Disney Co., which owns
Fairchild, confirmed that Advance had offered $650 million,
outbidding Hearst Corp., its archrival in the magazine publishing
business.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney executives, apparently mindful of the potential value
of fashion news and photographs on the Internet, got Advance to
agree that Disney's Buena Vista Entertainment Group, which includes
Web sites like espn.com and abc.com, will retain the right to
publish articles and photographs from W, Women's Wear Daily and
Jane. A joint news release by the companies indicated a new women's
Web site might be the venue for the material.
</P>
<P>
   The news release also said that Disney and Advance ``have agreed
to explore forming an Internet joint venture using the content of
all appropriate Advance and Disney magazines.'' Spokesmen for the
two companies would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Disney struck a deal with Infoseek Corp.
combining Infoseek's search engine and other online assets with the
assets of the Buena Vista Internet Group. The combined company,
Go.com, is expected to issue a tracking stock that would reflect
the performance of the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from keeping the Internet rights to the editorial material
of Jane, Women's Wear Daily and W for an unspecified period of
time, Disney is also keeping outright ownership of Los Angeles
magazine, the city magazine in its hometown.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Tuesday whether the deal, which was announced
late in the day, would permit Advance to offer advertisers a
multiple buy of advertising in all the fashion publications. The
remaining large competitors are Harper's Bazaar, published by
Hearst, and Elle, published by the Hachette Filippachi magazines
unit of Lagardere Group.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, which must be approved by regulators, should be
complete ``by the end of the 1999 calendar year,'' according to the
news release.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Advance control of more fashion advertising
revenue than any of its rivals _ revenue amounting to hundreds of
millions of dollars annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
