<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELOAN-ELOAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Loan Shares Up 27% After Forging Alliance With BofA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Shares of E-Loan rocketed up 27 percent yesterday, the day after
the Dublin online mortgage company said it is expanding into auto
finance and forming an alliance with Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan's stock rose $6.38, to $29.75, on trading of 4.84 million
shares, nearly four times the average daily volume since the
company's initial public offering two months ago. That was still
far below $63, the stock's highest closing price, reached a few
days after E-Loan went public.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine out of a total of 13,900 trades in E-Loan's stock
yesterday were for blocks of 5,000 shares or more, according to the
brokerage firm Goldman Sachs. And only 3.5 million shares were sold
to the public in the June offering.
</P>
<P>
   The small number of large trades and total volume exceeding the
number of shares in public hands indicated that large institutions
played little part in yesterday's stock surge. Instead, it appears
to have been powered by small-time speculators who bought and, in
many cases, quickly sold E-Loan shares.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan said on Monday yesterday  &LR; that it had agreed to buy
CarFinance.com, the leading online auto lender, from BofA, which
owns 80 percent of the company's stock. In exchange, the bank will
get a 5 percent ownership stake in E-Loan, which already is the
largest mortgage company based on the Internet, though it is not
yet profitable.
</P>
<P>
   That move fueled a sense that the company is poised to dominate
two major categories of lending on the Internet and will have the
financial backing of North Carolina's BofA, the nation's largest
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors see E-Loan establishing a relationship with a major
financial institution,'' said J.H. Lee, a New York analyst with the
brokerage firm EBI Securities.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan and BofA plan to jointly develop new loan products to
sell over the Internet. ``We want the entire right side of the
consumer balance sheet, and we'll look at all opportunities in that
category,'' said E-Loan chief executive Chris Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   BofA already lends money to E-Loan, which the company uses to
fund consumer mortgages. Partnership with BofA offers ``favorable
and long-term access to capital,'' which should boost E-Loan's
profit margins, Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they build an alliance, the two will continue to compete
as lenders. E-Loan funds mortgages and also acts as a mortgage
broker for other lenders, including BofA.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan's shares have been hurt recently by rising interest
rates, which tend to lower consumer demand for mortgages and erode
lender profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
