<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PACBELL-PACBELL_SFCHR     08-24 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PACBELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell to Offer Discount Deals
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Gearing up for its coming battle with AT&AMP;T, Pacific Bell said
yesterday that it will begin selling customers discounted packages
of telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Corp., the parent company of Pac Bell, plans to roll out
``bundled'' packages first in Fremont and Dallas and then expand
the offering throughout California and other SBC states.
</P>
<P>
   A ``significant part'' of the Bay Area will be able to buy the
discounted bundles by the end of the year, according to a Pac Bell
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to offer packages of services such as local
phone, wireless, satellite TV, high-speed Internet connections and
Internet service at prices that are lower than if customers bought
each service separately.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell also plans to offer long-distance service if and when
its application to be a long-distance provider is approved by
regulators. The regional phone company now has an application
pending with the state Public Utilities Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell is offering several ``Simple Solutions'' plans that
start at $34.95 per month for a package that includes local phone
service, voice mail and Caller ID. Subscribers to this package also
get to choose three other services such as call waiting and call
forwarding. Local phone service alone, excluding taxes and other
fees, is $11.25 per month.
</P>
<P>
   The $83.95-per-month plan bundle includes high-speed Internet
service using digital subscriber line technology, Caller ID and a
choice of three other phone services. Customers who buy this
package pay 31 percent less than if they bought all the services a
la carte, Pac Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is going slowly in its rollout so that it can keep
on top of demand, said Steve Dimmitt, Pac Bell vice president of
consumer marketing. Pac Bell could not keep up with demand for DSL
earlier this year after it cut the price for the service.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's bundle is part of a growing trend among companies to
give customers one-stop shopping for all their telecommunications
needs.
</P>
<P>
   As competition heats up in the telecommunications industry,
companies are trying desperately to hold on to consumers, who tend
to jump to whichever provider offers the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Selling customers a multitude of services at a discounted rate
reduces the chance that customers will leave, because they have a
financial incentive to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you buy from a single company, the less tempted you
are to go away when somebody else offers a good deal,'' said Roger
Wery, executive vice president in charge of the communications
practice at Renaissance Worldwide, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a financial incentive, industry watchers say,
customers like bundles because they can go to one provider for all
their needs and get all their telecommunications services itemized
on a single bill.
</P>
<P>
   Dimmitt said that initially, customers who buy a bundle will get
local phone, Internet and digital subscriber line service on a
single bill. Wireless will be added before the end of the year, and
DirecTV, whose satellite TV service Pac Bell is reselling, soon
should be added to the package bills.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as AT&AMP;T and RCN Corp., also plan to offer
Bay Area consumers packages of local, long-distance, cable TV and
high-speed Internet access in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates caution that bundles are not for
everybody. Because they include so many items, customers need to
make sure they actually will use all the services they pay for in a
bundle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers need to be cautious that they're really not adding
on additional features and services to their phone that, no matter
how much money you supposedly save, you would never use anyway,''
said Charles Carbone, consumer advocate with The Utility Consumer
Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   Carbone said that before customers sign up for a package, they
should do an analysis of their bill to see which services they want
and need.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said Pac Bell's bundle is a direct swipe at
AT&AMP;T, which is testing its own local phone service in Fremont and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which bought TCI and is in the process of acquiring
MediaOne, plans to compete with Pac Bell and other regional phone
companies by offering local phone service over its cable TV lines.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Fremont is the only place where AT&AMP;T customers can
get local phone service via TCI's cable TV lines, but AT&AMP;T plans to
expand the trial to 10 cities _ including Pleasanton _ before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, AT&AMP;T is testing local phone service using ``fixed
wireless'' antennas that attach to the side of a customer's home.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as it finishes upgrading its cable network across the
country, AT&AMP;T plans to offer local phone service, high-speed
Internet access and cable TV as part of its own bundled package.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AT&AMP;T rolled out its Personal Network plan, which
costs $29.99 per month, plus 10 cents per minute, for all
long-distance, wireless and calling card calls, including those to
Canada, the United Kingdom and parts of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing Fremont for its first rollout, Wery said, SBC is
sending a message to AT&AMP;T that it's ready to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``SBC is clearly signaling to the market that they are going to
go after AT&AMP;T,'' Wery said. ``This is the first time that you see a
pretty broad suite of services and products offered by a regional
Bell operating company.''
</P>
<P>
   And while AT&AMP;T may have been first to market with its bundle,
industry watchers said, SBC's offering includes more immediate
services for consumers _ especially in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T offers long-distance as part of its package, but Bay Area
customers cannot get wireless service from AT&AMP;T. And it will be
awhile before the local phone product is rolled out to all
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell cannot yet offer long-distance, but is able to offer
wireless phone service and satellite TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us what we believe is the right offering to compete
head-to-head against AT&AMP;T,'' Pac Bell's Dimmitt said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials said Pac Bell's selection of Fremont ``doesn't
seem like a coincidence'' but said the competition will be good for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that Fremont has emerged as the center of
universe,'' said James Peterson, a spokesman for AT&AMP;T. ``But it
would appear that Pac Bell has discovered what we've discovered _
that customers want to be able to purchase bundles of telecom
services at reasonable prices.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
