<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   `Kidpreneurs' Can't Sign Contracts 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Please advise if there are age restrictions in forming companies
and, if so, how do ``kidpreneurs'' get around them? Can minors be
legally liable for business transactions?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are under 18 years of age, you are considered
incompetent from a legal standpoint, and it makes no difference if
you are the next Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child can't enter into a contract or be held responsible or
liable for a contract,'' says San Francisco attorney James Millar.
``If you are under 18, any contract you sign is not legally
binding.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean minors can't start business ventures any more
than it means they can't be child actors or money-making athletes.
</P>
<P>
   It just means they must have a parent or other guardian sign the
documents to establish the business, borrow the money, sign the
sales agreements and deal with all other contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Parents commonly are managers for their child actors and
athletes, and that's probably the first choice for underage
entrepreneurs. But Millar suggests that if the parent or parents
don't share the child's vision, it might be preferable to find some
other guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure it's someone you trust,'' advises attorney Mark
Radcliffe of the Palo Alto law firm Gray Cary Ware Freidenrich.
``Get the legal documents explained to you, don't sign away rights
for the rest of your life, and understand how the money is being
managed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most kid entrepreneurs, from Web site designers to
lemonade stand operators, do not set up formal businesses or have
anyone sign contracts on their behalf. They simply do it, and
neither they nor their parents give much thought to potential legal
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kids' enterprises fall below the radar screen,'' Millar
acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   In case of a lawsuit against a young entrepreneur, the parent or
legal guardian could be subject to damages if the plaintiff
prevails. Such suits are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing for minors and their employers to consider are
strict laws governing underage workers. Self-employed minors are
not subject to California's permit requirements, but anyone under
18 who works for someone else should visit the state's Department
of Industrial Relations Web site at  &LR; www.dir.ca.gov/dlse &LR; 
 &LR; /childlabor.htm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The site discusses work permits, age limitations for specific
jobs, and penalties for violations of the child labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Getting Known Online
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have established a Web site for our baby-products
business. But how do we get it noticed and attract customers
without spending a lot of money?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Whether you have a storefront or a Web site, generating
traffic still is the name of the game. The first step is to get
your site listed on search engines such as Yahoo, HotBot, Excite,
AltaVista, Infoseek, Go2Net/MetaCrawler, Ask Jeeves, LookSmart and
Google.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Heeter Lundquist, author of ``Selling Online for Dummies
(IDG Books, $24.99), says the easiest way to get your business home
page listed on online directories is to go directly to the various
search engine sites and apply to have your company's site added in
the appropriate product category. Such listings usually are free.
</P>
<P>
   To increase your venture's visibility further, consider trading
links with other retail or information sites that share a common
theme with yours or offer complementary products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Ask them by phone or e-mail if they would be interested in
adding your site to their ``hot link'' list if you do the same for
them. You might set an expiration time for such a link, such as a
month or two, to test the concept.
</P>
<P>
   You also might scrape together some dollars to buy banner ads on
popular sites that can direct your pitch specifically to viewers
who click on baby products. Or you might advertise on a retail site
that caters specifically to young or expectant parents.
</P>
<P>
   The price of banner ads is based on ``impressions'' or page
views, and the cost typically runs from 2 cents to 15 cents per
impression. It is important that your ad is directed at the
appropriate audience.
</P>
<P>
   And Lundquist notes that ad innovation and rotation are crucial.
Like wary trout, if Web surfers don't bite (or click) after a few
casts, you've lost them.
</P>
<P>
   To improve your chances of making a sale, Lundquist says it is
helpful to post your customer service and privacy policies, company
history and partners, press clippings and testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   You also can use various services to track customer traffic as
well as manage and monitor your advertising. Once customers do
respond, be prepared to answer their e-mails and orders promptly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Ca 94103
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
