<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WILDBRAIN-WILDBRAIN_S     08-24 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDBRAIN-WILDBRAIN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wild Brain Is Filling Airwaves
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By David Lazarus &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
It isn't necessary to ask how business is going at Wild Brain, San
Francisco's leading animation studio. Artists, computer wizards,
directors and others occupy just about every available cubbyhole in
the company's 17,000-square-foot office in a former Inner Mission
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem,'' said chief executive Jeff Ulin. ``We're
OK at the moment. But as soon as the next big project hits, we'll
outgrow the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Wild Brain has a steady stream of projects, big and
small, in the works, so the lack of elbowroom will only get worse.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dilemma most young companies would kill for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had any quiet time,'' admitted Phil Robinson, Wild
Brain's vice president and one of three co-founders. ``There's
always more work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, that work has been all over the airwaves in the form of
the animated Colonel in Kentucky Fried Chicken commercials. Past
ads have included ``Super Mom'' for Coca-Cola and spots for Nike,
Levi Strauss and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Wild Brain will resurrect one of the giants of the
advertising world _ the Jolly Green Giant _ in a major campaign for
Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   But animated commercials are only part of Wild Brain's
activities. Among other things, the company also has created
episodes for HBO's adult-oriented ``Spawn'' series and for Steven
Spielberg's DreamWorks Television, and produced its first animated
feature, direct-to-video ``FernGully cq &LR;  2: The Magical Rescue,''
for 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   In the wings is an extensive Internet venture with a
high-profile partner. The Wild Brain folks don't want to tip their
hand too quickly on this, but Ulin allowed that it would be
``something complementary'' to the firm's existing animation
business.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Brain came into being about five years ago when Robinson,
John Hays and Jeff Fino _ who all worked at various times for
Colossal Pictures, a San Francisco production house now on its last
legs _ agreed to pony up $5,000 apiece to launch their own company.
</P>
<P>
   The first job, animation for a computer game, arrived within a
week. Subsequent gigs quickly fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Wild Brain now has about 100 full-time employees,
with more coming aboard as various projects require. ``We've been
profitable every year of our existence,'' Ulin said, ``and have
grown every year in terms of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   He's projecting revenue growth of as much as 50 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   By way of comparison, Pixar, headquartered in Richmond, last
month reported second-quarter income of $6.4 million on revenues of
$13.5 million. This was up from profit of $2.1 million and revenues
of $3.8 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the number of employees, Pixar is about four times
Wild Brain's size.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Wild Brain announced a $6.5 million
investment from Interfase Capital Partners, a new-media venture
capital firm. The money will be used for Wild Brain's pending
Internet initiative and to position the company as a leading player
in computer graphics.
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to say that Wild Brain never met a form of animation
it didn't like. From CD-ROMs to computer-generated images, the
company's artists, directors and producers are constantly on the
lookout for new creative outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``FernGully 2'' was perhaps Wild Brain's most important turning
point to date. Delivering a complete feature film on time and on
budget confirmed that the studio can handle ``long-form'' projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us less than a year and a half,'' said co-founder
Fino. ``It was a real lucky break. But the ultimate goal always has
been to create our own properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild Brain is doing just that with a 26-episode original series
tentatively titled ``Poochini's Yard.'' Based on an award-winning
short film, ``A Dog Cartoon,'' which tells the story of a dog and
his favorite bone, the series represents Wild Brain's first major
long-form endeavor developed entirely in-house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poochini's Yard,'' which may remind some viewers of the
slapstick, anything-goes Looney Tunes from Warner Bros., is being
co-produced by Germany's EM.TV, which will handle international
distribution of the series. Wild Brain is now seeking a domestic
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the long-form projects to be the anchor,'' said
co-founder Hays, who also serves as president of the company.
``Feature films are the real goal. They allow us to do our craft on
a higher scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild Brain has a number of feature-length projects in various
stages of development, including a production for Nickelodeon
described by Hays as ``American mythology with a slight Western
angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works is a computer-generated short film intended in
part to serve as a training ground for a similarly produced
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be a recognizable Wild Brain style in the company's
animated movies? On this point, all the company's bigwigs
unanimously agree: no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our studio is strong because we do a lot of styles,'' said
Fino. ``You can't look at something we do and see a Wild Brain
look. Some marketers may think this isn't a good thing, but we do.
We can do every style.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who recently completed animated sequences for the
upcoming live-action film versions of ``Dudley Do-Right'' and
``Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' sees Wild Brain charting a course between
``traditional'' two-dimensional animation and the
computer-generated 3-D stuff.
</P>
<P>
   As examples of the sort of work that catches his fancy, he cited
Disney's latest, ``Tarzan,'' and director Brad Bird's ``The Iron
Giant.'' Both films combined rich, hand-drawn techniques with
swooping 3-D landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The two movies also offered another lesson. Despite glowing
reviews for each, ``Tarzan'' packed in crowds via Disney's vast
marketing machinery, while ``The Iron Giant'' has done relatively
little business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to have a good idea and tell it well,''
Robinson concluded. ``You also have to market and strategize it.
You have to get the enthusiasm of the big studios behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wild Brain has proven more than adept at playing nice with
corporate clients, it remains to be seen how cooperative the
company will be when its creative vision is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the company's leaders see Wild Brain's free
spirit and independence as advantages and insist that they expect
to work with any and all partners, as opposed to Pixar's exclusive
relationship with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood generates these big projects, a lot of executives
get involved and decisions get made by committee,'' Robinson said.
``These are the juggernauts that end up hosing money down the
drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to make films without that huge budget overhead and
layers and layers of executives. We've learned how to do things
leaner.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild Brain's business associates are quick to sing the company's
praises. ``They're top echelon,'' said Matthew Anderson, who
produced the Kentucky Fried Chicken spots for the Young &AMP; Rubicam
advertising agency in New York. ``They're really mellow,
fun-to-work-with people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of their creative approach and the way they do
things, they're one of the top animators we've worked with,'' said
Joe Stanley, senior vice president of Dailey &AMP; Associates in Los
Angeles, which tapped Wild Brain for a series of Willy Wonka candy
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Such raves hopefully will continue as Wild Brain approaches a
near-inevitable public offering of its shares. While no such plans
have been announced, CEO Ulin revealed that he's already pondering
the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing and events are starting to overtake us,'' he
said. ``We're exploring the feasibility of growing further.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Ulin will be the first to concede: Wild Brain is going to
need a bigger office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
