<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HOTEL-HOTEL_SFCHRON &LR;      08-24 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-HOTEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   San Francisco Hotel Strike A Possibility 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Steve Ginsberg &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; The operators of 11 of San Francisco's largest hotels will try to
stave off a strike by its union employees with another round of
labor negotiations scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Casey, president of Local 2 of the Hotel and Restaurant
Workers union, warned that a strike could come as early as next
month, during the height of the convention season.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents room cleaners, dishwashers and
restaurant workers, has voted overwhelmingly to authorize their
negotiating committee to strike.
</P>
<P>
   The union's five-year pact with management that expired August
14 affects 8,000 workers at 50 hotels and motels in the city. A new
agreement with 11 of the city's largest hotels would set the
guidelines for workers at the remaining 39 hotels and motels.
</P>
<P>
   The union is planning a demonstration Friday in Union Square to
air its complaints. Casey said there also is a campaign under way
to make travel agents, corporate executives and hotel customers
aware of the workers' plight.
</P>
<P>
   The last major hotel strike in San Francisco occurred in 1980
when the hotel workers union struck several hotels for a month and
cost the city well over $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the hotel workers union struck the Mark Hopkins, the
only major hotel targeted during the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the two sides in the current dispute are
far apart on wages, workloads and health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants to raise its employees' hourly wage rates from
$12 to at least $13.50. Union officials say management has not made
a wage proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The union also says management is attempting to maintain health
benefits at current levels. The union said many of its workers,
especially room cleaners, who represent 40 percent of the union
workforce, suffer from repetitive stress injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Progress toward a new contract has been slow. Union spokeswoman
Valerie Lapin said management did agree to double pension
contributions to between $700 and $800 a month.
</P>
<P>
   One hotel operator who requested anonymity insisted that San
Francisco hotel workers already are the nation's highest paid and
that the companies can't afford the increases. They say their
occupancy rates peaked in 1997 and have fallen each year since.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most controversial union demands calls for the new
owners of acquired hotels to keep the union workforce.
</P>
<P>
   The union lost the Sir Francis Drake hotel when it changed hands
in 1997 and has been unsuccessful in organizing there since.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are with 11 of the city's Class A hotels,
including the Westin St. Francis, Sheraton Palace, the Fairmont and
Hyatt Regency and Grand Hyatt. The San Francisco Marriott is not
included.
</P>
<P>
   Should there be a strike, Casey said it would be selective,
targeting one or a few high-profile properties to maximize impact.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Korshak, the hotel operators' chief negotiator and a Los
Angeles attorney, was unavailable for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is one of San Francisco's biggest industries. In 1998,
the city's hotels hosted 4.2 million visitors who spent $3.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of this year, hotel occupancy in the
city was 76.4 percent, 1.2 percent more than it was a year ago,
according Smith Travel Research, a tourism industry consulting
company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HOTEL-HOTEL_SFCHRON &LR;      08-24 0582
