<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MINNEAPOLIS-AIRLINE-A     08-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINNEAPOLIS-AIRLINE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING ON FORTRESS NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Minn., Texas, Ariz. ) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Most cities root unabashedly for their big
hometown companies. But here _ where Northwest Airlines has its
headquarters, employs 21,000 and controls 80 percent of the airline
seats out of the city _ many people are rooting for Sun Country
Airlines, a small local charter airline that started flying a
regular schedule to a mere 15 destinations in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northwest is doing anything it can to put Sun Country out of
business,'' said the Rev. Brian Kimbler, a pastor in Brainerd,
Minn. He recently flew with Sun Country to New York with his wife
and a group of eight teenagers from his church, paying $228 apiece,
below Northwest's advanced-purchase fare of $308 and a world away
from its $1,200 midweek round-trip fare. ``I like competition,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hatch, Minnesota's attorney general, also likes
competition. In January, after Sun Country said it would begin
scheduled service, he sent a letter to John H. Dasburg, Northwest's
chief executive, putting him on notice that the attorney general's
office would be watching the airline's reaction to Sun Country. For
local news organizations, the David-versus-Goliath battle between
the two airlines has been one of the biggest stories of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation in Washington, after being
alerted by a letter from Hatch in April, told Northwest, the
nation's fourth-largest airline, to report each competitive action
it takes in relation to Sun Country.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest says that such scrutiny is unwarranted. ``The impetus
here is not to penalize or punish Sun Country,'' said Douglas M.
Steenland, executive vice president and general counsel at
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the support Sun Country is receiving, its
experience shows how difficult it is for a small airline to make it
in head-to-head competition with one of the industry's giants at
its so-called fortress hub.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS)
</P>
<P>
   Scores of new airlines have been started since the industry was
deregulated in 1978, but only one _ America West Airlines, a unit
of the America West Holdings Corp. of Tempe, Ariz. _ has managed to
enter the ranks of the majors. The rest have struggled to stay
alive or have folded, either as a result of mismanagement, ruthless
competition from the major airlines or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same two decades the industry has consolidated into a
cadre of giant competitors, each of which dominates one or more of
the nation's major airports, where they are able to charge premium
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Northwest and Republic Airlines each carried
roughly 40 percent of the passengers in the Twin Cities. But in
1986, Northwest bought Republic, giving the airline a dominant
position overnight.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the General Accounting Office found that fares
in Minneapolis were, on average, 49 percent higher than those at
comparable airports where there is competition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIMS)
</P>
<P>
   Northwest now controls 54 of the 70 gates at the main terminal
of Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport, forcing Sun Country
to use the Hubert H. Humphrey Terminal, a converted hangar on the
opposite side of the tarmac. That and Sun Country's comparatively
limited schedule make it difficult for the airline to attract the
lucrative business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Country executives say that Northwest has matched its low
fares on routes where the two compete and has even added flights on
some competing routes. They also say that Northwest has threatened
to retaliate against travel agents who book flights on the airline
and has even stopped sharing spare parts with the airline, a
courtesy commonly extended between airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest denied pressuring travel agents and said that it had
matched Sun Country's low prices selectively, leaving in place many
of its higher walk-up fares. It said it had stopped sharing parts
with Sun Country, but only because Sun was asking for so many.
</P>
<P>
   Steenland added that Sun Country likes to present itself as a
struggling upstart but is really a potent competitor because its
owners, the La Macchia family, also own the Mark Travel Corp. of
Milwaukee, one of the biggest package-tour companies in the
country, with more than $1 billion in annual sales. (Northwest's
revenues last year were $9 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to competing primarily in the leisure markets of
Las Vegas and Orlando, they are the Goliath and we're the David,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS)
</P>
<P>
   Despite what it sees as Northwest's unfair tactics, Sun Country
is not giving up. In June, the airline announced that it would
lease six new long-range Boeing 737's to replace some of its aging
727's and to expand its fleet. Last week, Sun Country announced
that, beginning this fall, it would add a second daily flight to
Detroit and Milwaukee and expand its service from Minneapolis with
new flights to San Diego, Harlingen, Texas, and three Florida
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the gum stuck to the bottom of their shoe,'' said Bill
La Macchia Jr., 33, Sun Country's president. Then he paused and
added, ``And they just can't get us off.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIMS)
</P>
<P>
   Resentment against Northwest _ long referred to unaffectionately
here as ``Northworst'' _ has been simmering for years. It grew
after two outside investors, Alfred A. Checchi and Gary L. Wilson,
took it over in the early 1990s, loading the airline with debt in
the process. But the situation boiled over last fall when Northwest
pilots went on strike, shutting the airline down for 15 days and
stranding thousands of travelers all over the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   After the strike, calls went out from politicians and community
groups to find some way to relax Northwest's stranglehold on the
city. Sun Country and La Macchia stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Country, which is based in nearby Mendota Heights, started
as a charter airline in 1983, carrying gamblers to Las Vegas, Nev.,
and shoppers from around the country to Minneapolis' giant Mall of
America. The La Macchias decided to buy 75 percent of the airline
in 1997 to guarantee that flights would be available for their
package-tour company.
</P>
<P>
   But almost immediately, the purchase seemed to be a disaster.
Sun Country lost $11 million in 1997. Rather than let the airline
die, the La Macchias invested an additional $5.5 million to buy the
25 percent they did not own. ( La Macchia, whose father founded and
still runs Mark Travel, would not say how much the family paid for
its initial stake.)
</P>
<P>
   Sun Country was profitable in the first eight months of last
year. But it went into the red in the last four months, when the
charter market traditionally declines. One of Sun Country's biggest
customers had been Northwest's package-tour company. But in recent
years, La Macchia said, especially after Sun Country quietly
started offering some scheduled flights in 1996, Northwest began
steering more business to its own charter airline.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest strike convinced La Macchia that he could balance
Sun Country's wobbly revenues by expanding scheduled service and
promoting it heavily. ``Northwest, with its lock on this market,
really presented the company with an opportunity,'' said Paul
Miller, a Northwest veteran who is now Sun country's vice president
for market planning.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Sun Country began a newspaper advertising
campaign claiming credit for bringing low fares to Minneapolis and
offering the chance to win free flights for a year. The airline
received more than 80,000 responses, including many handwritten
notes of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill, it would be great to fly out of Minneapolis and be
treated like a paying customer, not a
take-it-or-leave-our-service-stinks attitude like Northwest!,'' one
correspondent wrote. ``And I am a gold member at Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   La Macchia, who spent 10 years working for Mirage Resorts, Inc.
in Las Vegas, has followed in the footsteps of his old boss, the
casino magnate Stephen A. Wynn, by starring in his company's ads.
</P>
<P>
   A first set of arch television spots shows La Macchia going door
to door in a white shirt and tie, introducing himself to mystified
Twin Cities residents. ``All we want to do is make air fares
reasonable,'' La Macchia tells one indifferent housewife. ``Our
walk-up fares are very reasonable,'' he explains to two young boys,
as the three sit on a curb licking popsicles.
</P>
<P>
   La Macchia's strategy is to offer superior service at a lower
price. Customers are not penalized for buying one-way tickets and
are not required to stay over a Saturday night to get a low fare, a
feature designed to appeal to business and other travelers who are
forced to pay exorbitant fares for last-minute travel during the
week on large airlines.
</P>
<P>
   If a recent flight from New York's Kennedy International Airport
to Minneapolis is any guide, the strategy may soon pay dividends.
``It's clean, it's nice, and it gets me there,'' said Don Eatz,
president of Monterey Fashions of Manhattan, one of the few
business travelers on board. He was skeptical at first but agreed
to fly Sun Country when he compared the $318 fare with a $1,200
fare on Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Several Sun Country employees also appeared to be happy with the
new management. Cathy Steffens, a flight attendant, joined Sun
Country in 1989 after 20 years at Northwest. She said she was very
impressed with the changes at the airline under the La Macchias and
that morale was much higher at Sun Country than at Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the girls are grumpy and growly,'' she said of her
former Northwest colleagues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sun Country is also working hard to make the disadvantage of
being at the old Humphrey terminal into a plus. Though it is far
from the main terminal and has no rental car facilities, its small
size makes it easy to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   After coming under intense public pressure, the Minneapolis-St.
Paul Metropolitan Airports Commission, the public agency that
operates the Twin Cities airport and has long been seen as an
extension of Northwest, agreed this year to spend $73 million to
build a new Humphrey terminal that will be occupied primarily by
Sun Country in 2001. In the meantime, the commission earmarked
$450,000 to spruce up the existing terminal.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Sun Country's first month flying its new schedule, the
airline managed to fill 64.3 percent of the seats on its 15 jets,
while Northwest filled 80 percent of the seats on its fleet of 419
airplanes. James R. Olsen, one of Sun Country's founders and now
vice president for strategic planning, said that the July figure
was 70 percent and that the airline might be profitable for the
month of August.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that Sun Country can maintain that
performance in the fall, when leisure travel traditionally drops.
The airline is still little known outside Minneapolis, where 85
percent of its passengers now originate. It also does not offer
frequent-flyer benefits and must persuade skeptical travel agents
that it is a viable alternative to Northwest. Most Minneapolis
travel agents depend on Northwest for the bulk of their business
and receive incentives from the airline if they book more of their
passengers on Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Country plans to introduce a frequent-flyer program soon,
though La Macchia said it would not be like those offered by other
airlines. He explained that he wanted it to be more like the
``relationship marketing'' he learned in Las Vegas, with prizes
linked to local merchants, like pizza chains.
</P>
<P>
   Two Sun Country executives pointed out that it took five years
for Vanguard Airlines of Kansas City, Mo., and the Denver-based
Frontier Airlines, two other low-price airlines, to begin to show
profits. Are the La Macchias willing to wait that long?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely in this thing for the long haul,'' La
Macchia said. ``We are prepared to do what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
