<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-TOYSMART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TO BUY BIGGEST STAKE IN ONLINE TOY RETAILER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DISNEY-FAIRCHILD) 
(mk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giving a major lift to a small online retailer of educational
toys, Walt Disney Co. is expected to announce Wednesday that it has
bought a majority stake in Toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Buena Vista Internet Group, which oversees Disney's
Internet properties, indicated the company would have a 60 percent
stake in Toysmart. Disney would not say how much it paid for the
stake, citing regulatory restrictions in advance of a planned sale
of shares in the Go Network.
</P>
<P>
   But one electronic commerce analyst, David Cooperstein of
Forrester Research, said Disney had paid $20 million and would also
provide Toysmart with another $25 million in free advertising. The
ads would appear on the Go Network, which includes ESPN.com and
ABCNews.com, and on media outlets like the Disney Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Davis, president of electronic commerce for Buena Vista,
said the company would promote Toysmart heavily through its
Family.com site, which offers articles and advice on parenthood and
has roughly 3 million visitors a month. Family.com will recommend
Toysmart merchandise in its editorial areas, Davis said, while
Toysmart will use Family.com's editorial content in various areas
of its site.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said Toysmart would retain control over the site,
including decisions about which toys to sell. Analysts said this
would improve the site's chances of success, since Disney could
erode Toysmart's value if it insisted on promoting its own toys _
some of which are not educational _ through Toysmart.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing extensive online promotion for
Toysmart, said Cooperstein of Forrester, ``Disney gets more people
spending more money through its network.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lord, Toysmart's chief executive, said the company defined
``educational'' toys as any products that are ``developmental, high
quality, fun, and open-ended,'' meaning they let children be
creative.
</P>
<P>
   Such toys make up 38 percent of the $23 billion toy market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Toysmart uses the Disney relationship to promote its
brand name, the site will broaden its offerings beyond educational
toys. Lord said that in the coming months Toysmart will sell
children's furniture and baby products, increasing the number of
products offered from 20,000 to 75,000 by November.
</P>
<P>
   When it does that, the company will provide competition not only
to major online toy retailers like Etoys and Smarterkids.com, but
also to sites like iBaby, a division of iVillage, which stock a
wide range of products for children, and to traditional outlets
like Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that in concept, at least, the prospects for an
online retailer of educational toys are promising. First, the toys
are highly profitable _ Toysmart anticipates margins of 40 percent,
versus 20 percent to 30 percent for mass-market toys sold online _
because they appeal to highly educated and affluent parents who are
willing to pay more. Second, because of the toys' high prices,
major chains have been reluctant to carry them.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the market for these toys through traditional
channels has been fragmented, with small chains like Noodle
Kidoodle catching on in some areas but failing to create a national
presence. This week one such retailer, Zany Brainy Inc., announced
a loss of 15 cents a share, after a loss of 80 cents in the
comparable quarter in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that started in January and began its first ad
campaign just last week, Toysmart has been a surprisingly hot
property. Toys ``R'' Us, which has failed to develop a successful
e-commerce strategy, had sought to acquire Toysmart but failed
because it insisted on controlling merchandise decisions,
Cooperstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Lord started developing the idea for Toysmart in 1997 when he
was chief executive of Holt Educational Outlets, which sells
products like audio-visual equipment to teachers and corporations.
After creating an educational toys division at Holt, he left the
company, bought the division in December and changed the name to
Toysmart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
