<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-STATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW STATES ARE USING SETTLEMENTS IN TOBACCO SUIT TO CUT SMOKING
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ky., N.C., Mass., Ore., Calif., Fla., Hawaii, Minn., Md.,
Vt., Wash., Texas, Miss.)   (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite overwhelming evidence that anti-tobacco
campaigns reduce smoking, most states are in danger of wasting an
opportunity to fight death and disease with money from the tobacco
industry, federal health officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only six of the 46 states that participated in last year's $206
billion settlement with tobacco companies have made major
commitments to use their windfalls to cut down on tobacco use, Dr.
Jeffrey Koplan, the director of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, told a conference in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The hesitation is especially frustrating because statistics show
that aggressive anti-smoking efforts sharply lower the ranks of
tobacco users, Koplan told the National Conference on Tobacco and
Health in Kissimmee, Fla.. ``We have nothing to show when we
prevent something,'' he said. ``All you can show are fewer
smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   And fewer early deaths from lung cancer, his colleague Dr.
Michael Eriksen added in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Eriksen, director of the CDC's Office on Smoking and Health,
said the states must wrestle not just with a public-policy
question, but something more basic: ``This raises fundamental
issues about where your moral values are.''
</P>
<P>
   To Koplan and Eriksen, the statistics are irrefutable. They
cited California, Massachusetts and Oregon, where higher tobacco
taxes were enacted in recent years after anti-tobacco advertising
and educational campaigns were undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   Per capita cigarette consumption declined 16 percent in
California from 1992 to 1996, the officials said, and 20 percent in
Massachusetts for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, probably the state whose economy is most dependent on
tobacco, has the highest smoking rate in the nation, Eriksen said.
In 1996, nearly 26 percent of adults in the state smoked, and 47
percent of students in grades nine through 12 reported having
smoked in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deplorable that we have the highest youth-smoking rate,
but understandable given our culture,'' said Amy Barkley, head of
Kentucky Action, a tobacco-control coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is second only to North Carolina in tobacco production,
but Kentucky's economy relies on it more; two-thirds of the farms
in the state grow tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC provide detailed recommendations for states on how to
combat tobacco use. The greatest emphasis is on preventing smoking
among teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The six states that the agency said had made anti-tobacco,
public-education commitments in line with its recommendations are
New Jersey, Hawaii, Vermont, Minnesota, Maryland and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Four states _ Florida, Minnesota, Mississippi and Texas _
entered into earlier settlements with the tobacco companies. The
settlements, arising from the public-health costs associated with
tobacco use, are to be paid out over 25 years. (New York is to get
about $25 billion, New Jersey $7.6 billion and Connecticut $3.7
billion.)
</P>
<P>
   The states are not bound to use their settlement money fighting
tobacco, or on health programs in general, for that matter. They
can use it to build schools or to reduce debt _ all worthy goals,
Eriksen conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he said, they can use it to help people live longer. Unless
things change, Eriksen said, five million Americans who are under
18 will die prematurely because they smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
