<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-24 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: KEEP YOUR SHIRT ON! 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I will never forget the shock of hearing dirty
talk in the Senate for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   A pubic hair on a Coke can ... Long Dong Silver ... bestiality
movies.
</P>
<P>
   I looked around the Senate Judiciary hearing room. Jaws were
slack, if not dropping.
</P>
<P>
   The stricken senators listening to Anita Hill on that October
day in 1991 looked as if they wanted to dive under the green felt
skirts of the dais, or stick bags over their heads. How could such
graphic sexual language crack that marble dignity, in the same room
where Congress investigated the sinking of the Titanic, the bombing
of Pearl Harbor, Watergate and Iran-Contra, and where Joe Welch
once demanded of Joe McCarthy, ``Have you no sense of decency,
sir?''
</P>
<P>
   Decency blushed during the Thomas-Hill hearings. There was a
sense that weekend that the scalding spectacle would not end until
one of the combatants was fatally gored.
</P>
<P>
   So it was again in the bitter contest between Ken Starr and Bill
Clinton, when Senate dirty talk made Thomas-Hill look like Disney.
By the time they got to the 1998 sex scandal, the Democrats were
wiser and meaner. They applied the ruthless, truthless lessons they
had learned watching Republicans in the Thomas hearings: Save your
guy at any cost. Only the appearance of the Gap dress interrupted
the Clintonite whispers that, as the Republicans once said of
Anita, Monica was an erotomaniac, a little nutty and a little
slutty.
</P>
<P>
   After the wild ride of the Clinton years, what shocked us in
1991 is no longer shocking enough. ``Strange Justice,'' the new
Showtime movie recreating the Thomas-Hill imbroglio that premiered
in Hollywood Tuesday night (based on the book by my friends Jane
Mayer and Jill Abramson, a New York Times editor) has goosed up the
story.
</P>
<P>
   The docudrama or adaptation _ cutting and pasting history and
fiction, real news clips and interpretive dramatizations _ features
a bizarre scene in which Clarence Thomas, played by Delroy Lindo,
rips off his shirt during his Senate testimony and prances around
half-naked and barefoot. When he utters his famous ``high-tech
lynching'' line, Lindo uses his tie as a noose.
</P>
<P>
   The prim and stoic Anita Hill, played by Regina Taylor, is given
more ratings oomph here _ with flashes of anger and trails of
tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actors tried to give three-dimensional portraits of these
icons,'' said Jacob Epstein, the screenwriter and executive
producer. ``They may not have been representational portraits. They
were figurative and impressionistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reviews have praised the movie's edgy style, not
minding the imaginary flourishes that the film makers ``cooked
up,'' as Epstein put it.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner and Rupert Murdoch both bought the rights to the book
first and both chickened out of making the movie. Turner must not
have wanted to risk offending a Supreme Court justice. Murdoch, a
Thomas friend, killed the project as it was going into production.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime has won praise for daring to take on such a provocative
subject. And the movie convincingly portrays the Biden committee's
failure to call two other key witnesses who could have offered
evidence corroborating Ms. Hill, and the Bush White House's slick
packaging of an inexperienced judge.
</P>
<P>
   But it evades the truly ulcerous issue: One of these two people
told a monumental lie and got away with it. Showtime takes the easy
way, making the villain the cynical Washington process. Clarence
and Anita are merely two dignified people used by spin doctors and
partisan interests.
</P>
<P>
   With Rene Russo in ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' and the law vamps
on ``Ally McBeal'' exploiting sex for professional advantage,
feminine wiles are in fashion again. ``Strange Justice'' fits this
mood, treating sexual misconduct in the office as no-fault
behavior, a matter of Rashomon.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, during his grand jury testimony, volunteered that
although it seemed irrational, Thomas and Ms. Hill ``both thought
they were telling the truth ... you're dealing with, in some ways,
the most mysterious area of human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a Bill &AMP; Monica movie in the works. We can
only hope that the actor playing the president keeps his shirt on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
