<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC CLASSIC FAVORITE BREAKS DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mazel Trick, who would have taken a four-race winning streak and
a ``rising star'' aura into Sunday's Pacific Classic, broke down
Tuesday morning at Del Mar as he sped through a scheduled 5-furlong
workout.
</P>
<P>
   The fractures in both sesamoid bones above the horse's right
front ankle will end the 4-year-old's promising career.
Veterinarian Helmuth Von blucher said it ``can be
life-threatening.... We'll see how it is in the next day or two.''
Surgery is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick, removed from the track in a horse ambulance, was
fitted with a splint and given a sedative. He remained in his stall
at trainer Bobby Frankel's barn late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said he was ``cautiously optimistic'' the colt will
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert was watching his horse General Challenge train at
the same time, and saw Mazel Trick's injury occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he passed the three-eighths (mile) pole, you could see he
took a bad step, and Chris McCarron pulled him up,'' Baffert said.
``Chris pulled him up quick, so maybe he has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a further blow to the $1 million Pacific Classic, which
lost Real Quiet and Victory Gallop to injuries in the past two
weeks. The favorites' role now goes to Malek, the 1998 Santa Anita
Handicap winner and the likely front-runner, and General Challenge,
the Santa Anita Derby winner who's the only 3-year-old in the
remaining field of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick was brought to California from France midway through
his 10-race, six-win career for new owners Audrey Skirball-Kenis,
her husband Charles and former Kentucky Gov. Brereton Jones.
Bone-chip surgery and laser treatments on both front ankles forced
a seven-month layoff.
</P>
<P>
   The layoff ended dramatically when Mazel Trick broke Hollywood
Park's 7-furlong record with a 1:19 4/5 clocking in winning the
Triple Bend Handicap in June and dominated the San Diego Handicap
at Del Mar on Aug. 7. His 4-for-4 record since switching from turf
to dirt tracks prompted comparisons to 1995-96 Horse of the Year
Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been a sound horse since I got him. I can't blame
the racetrack,'' Frankel said, alluding to criticism of the Del Mar
racing surface following a cluster of fatal breakdowns in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The expected field for the 1\-mile Pacific Classic: Malek,
General Challenge, Lazy Lode, Smile Again, River Keen, Barter Town
and Jack Grandi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
