<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE OFFERS FREE INTERNET SERVICE IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ America Online Inc. introduced its own free Internet
service in Britain on Tuesday, with the goal of overtaking the
growing crowd of competitors that already offer customers access to
the World Wide Web at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   The new service, known as Netscape Online, is managed by AOL
Europe, a joint venture of America Online and Bertelsmann AG, the
large German media conglomerate. First announced last month,
Netscape Online represents a strategic about-face for America
Online, which had historically relied on monthly subscriptions and
only three months ago questioned whether Britain's
free-subscription businesses could be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of Netscape Online comes at a precarious time
for America Online in Britain, where its formerly large share of
the market has eroded.
</P>
<P>
   A main reason is the subscription-free newcomer Freeserve PLC,
which was created last September by Dixons Group PLC, a British
retailing chain, and in three months surpassed America Online as
Britain's most-used Internet service provider. Freeserve sold
shares of itself to the public a month ago in a bid to gain
financing for further expansion.
</P>
<P>
   By using the Netscape brand for the new service, America Online
hopes to differentiate it and not cannibalize its content-rich
subscription services like AOL U.K. and Compuserve. It is not only
going after Freeserve but the hundreds of other Internet service
providers that have sprung up around Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, America Online took out full-page advertisements in
almost all of Britain's national newspapers for its new service
with a headline that read: ``Beware part-time Internet providers _
the N is nigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Internet service business in the United States, where
access over a telephone line is relatively inexpensive, access in
Britain and in most parts of Europe can be quite expensive for
users because they must pay by the minute for local phone calls, in
addition to the charge levied by the Internet access provider. As a
result, subscription-free Internet services have emerged, luring
customers by not charging them the monthly subscription fee for
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the services share a percentage of the revenue
generated by the cost of a user's telephone call with the phone
company, which charges all calls by the minute. A subscription-free
service also derives revenue from advertising and electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts called America Online's move a short-term solution to a
significantly longer-term problem, notably how America Online can
make money and how it can keep its higher-margin businesses from
losing customers to the subscription-free service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't answer the question of how AOL competes
internationally,'' said Evan Neufeld, vice president and director
for international research at Jupiter Communications in London. ``I
don't buy it as a long-term strategy to move the customers upstream
to their subscription services.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether subscription-free Internet services
are a passing fancy or are here to stay. As telephone companies
consider flat-rate pricing and upgrade their systems for faster and
more sophisticated connections, ``Netscape Online could be like the
flavor of the day,'' Neufeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll all be talking about these wacky companies
offering free Internet access five years from now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
