<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playoff return is Seanez's goal
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A stress fracture like the one in reliever Rudy
Seanez's right elbow normally takes six to eight weeks to heal. Six
weeks off would have Seanez returning from the disabled list just
in time for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez is cautiously optimistic about that possibility. ``Six to
eight weeks is the worst-case scenario,'' he said. ``Best-case
scenario is a couple weeks. If it doesn't happen then, I'll give it
two more weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Working against him is the fear that if he pitches before his
arm is ready, he could blow out his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to jeopardize my career, and I don't want to
jeopardize the team's chance to win,'' Seanez said. ``I don't want
to go out there if I'm not 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Seanez said the arm started bothering him Friday night after he
pitched a scoreless inning against the Padres. It improved over the
weekend, but Seanez had had a similar injury and knew he should get
it checked out.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the Braves probably will turn to Russ Springer
and Mike Remlinger for the setup role.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm trained to do; that's what I've been doing the
last three or four years,'' said Springer, who had offseason back
surgery to repair a herniated disc. ``I started off the year in
rehabilitation, but I'm in a different situation now. I'm
physically able to do the job now. It's good enough to where I
don't think about it on the mound. I have days when I wake up and
it's stiff, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer earned his first save of 1999 Monday by throwing one
pitch to Eddie Taubensee and inducing a groundout.Bring in Cortes
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may have caught a break from the Rockies, who had
acquired David Cortes from the Braves last July as part of the Greg
Colbrunn deal. The Rockies thought Cortes had an arm problem, so
they returned him to the Braves and took Anthony Briggs instead.
The Braves are now calling on Cortes to fill in while Seanez is on
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said Cortes, a 25-year-old right-hander who
had 22 saves for AAA Richmond. ``I was hoping to get a call-up in
September. ...I'll just try to do the same thing here I was doing
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood said his back was feeling much better the day
after Monday's start and it would not limit him in his next start.
Millwood felt a twinge making a pitch in the fourth inning, which
is why he left after seven innings. ``It didn't hurt when I was
pitching; it hurt when I swung a bat,'' he said. ... The Braves
sent minor-league pitcher Joey Nation to the Cubs as the player to
be named in the July 31 trade for Jose Hernandez and Terry
Mulholland. Nation, a second-round pick in 1997, was 5-4 with a
4.39 ERA for Class A Myrtle Beach. ... The Braves have mailed out
playoff ticket applications to their 28,000 season-ticket holders.
The package includes applications for the Division Series, National
League Championship Series and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle and Tom Glavine will square off today in a meeting
of former Braves lockermates. Neagle said Glavine was probably his
closest friend on the Braves. ``It's always weird when you face
ex-teammates,'' said Neagle, who jokingly added. ``If I have to
drill him in the earhole I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
