u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-COLUMN25-C     08-24 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resiliency keeps Braves playoffs in sight
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To fully appreciate the wonderful psyche of the
current Braves, we'll return to Sunday's game at Turner Field
against the Padres. The setting is the home dugout. It is the
bottom of the fifth inning, and Brian Jordan is doing the
equivalent of making the sun tumble from the sky by letting his
pain conquer his will.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in baseball is tougher than Jordan, but after two months
of a throbbing right hand, even the Braves' right fielder wrapped
inside a strong safety's body is threatening a Roberto Duran.
</P>
<P>
   No mas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in so much pain that I really wanted to pull myself out
of the game,'' said Jordan, recalling Tuesday night how he relayed
his thoughts to pitcher Greg Maddux, sitting nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that, after a few words from Maddux, Jordan stays
around long enough to knock in the winning run in the bottom of the
ninth inning. Jordan said, ``When I wanted to leave the game, Greg
looked at me and said, `Hey, you gotta be like a dog. You gotta be
aggressive. You gotta suck it up. You just have to forget about the
pain.' I said, `Wow. This is a pitcher motivating an everyday
player.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This also is why the Braves will survive their little war with
the Mets along the way to flashing a pulse for one of the few times
in October. You see, despite the Braves' mighty forefathers through
the 1990s, producing four pennants and a World Championship, never
have they fielded a team with more guts, more courage, more
something.
</P>
<P>
   For our discussion, you can forget that bunch in '91, when the
Tomahawk Chop was as fresh as the guys on the roster. They were the
current Reds, just glad to have a worthy August and September.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Braves slipped by the Giants with 104
victories to their 103. That was another test of the Braves nerves,
all right. But those '93 Braves trailed the Giants by as much as 9
and 1/2 games in early August. Anything the Braves did afterward
was dandy, and it wasn't as if they were without their clean-up
hitter. They also had their closer, and one of their primary clutch
hitters did leave the roster for the rest of the season after
damaging his knee in July.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the plight of the current Braves, and we didn't even
mention that their starter in this one against the Reds was John
Smoltz, still battling elbow and thigh problems. As a result, he
did the unusual earlier this month by altering his pitching motion
to ease his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, with the healthy Mets nipping at their cleats,
the Braves continued to do well enough to enter Tuesday night's
action with the best record in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it goes back to spring training, after we lost
Andres Galarraga (the cleanup hitter) and Kerry Ligtenberg (the
closer),'' said Glenn Hubbard, the Braves' first base coach, who
played second base for the team during the 1980s. ``(Braves
manager) Bobby (Cox) said, `Hey guys we've got the talent to win
it, and we ain't going to cry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: This scrappy bunch that threatens to keep clawing its
way toward better things. Jordan said, ``We're sucking it up. We're
gutting it out. So, to me, that just makes you better come playoff
time, because you've been through so much all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
