<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8369 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-MOZART-$ADV29-2     08-24 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MOZART-$ADV29-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOZART RECITATIVE HIDDEN IN PLAIN SIGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (For release Sun., Aug. 29) 
(jt) 
 By TAMARA BERNSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few pinholes in an old musical score _ and a Canadian
musicologist's passion for the chaotic world of 18th-century opera
_ have led to the discovery of what appears to be a long lost
recitative by Mozart. Dorothea Link, a specialist in the operas of
Mozart and his contemporaries, came across the setting for strings
and voice, 35 bars long, in the Austrian National Library in Vienna
a few months ago. The recitative precedes the well-known aria
``Vado, ma dove?'' (K. 583), which Mozart wrote for the singer
Luisa Villeneuve. Although the recitative is not in Mozart's hand,
all the evidence points to his authorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge discovery, but it's a nice one,'' said the
English musicologist Stanley Sadie, an eminent Mozart scholar and
the editor of The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians. ``It
helps fill in a bit of a picture. For generations, people thought
they knew everything Mozart had written. But lately a few things
have come to light.''
</P>
<P>
   Those few things include ``Der Stein der Weisen'' (``The
Philosopher's Stone''), a collectively composed Viennese opera to
which Mozart seems to have contributed several numbers. It was the
return of German music archives seized by the Soviets during World
War II that enabled David J. Buch, an Iowa musicologist, to
discover Mozart's apparent involvement in ``Der Stein'' in 1996.
But the recitative to ``Vado, ma dove?'' has been staring
musicologists in the face all along.
</P>
<P>
   The authenticity of Mozart's setting of ``Vado, ma dove?'' has
always been rock-solid, Ms. Link said recently from Halifax, Nova
Scotia, where she was wrapping up a year of teaching at Dalhousie
University. The autograph copy is in a library in Berlin; Mozart
also entered the piece in his handwritten catalog of his works. We
know that Mozart wrote the aria in 1789, at Villeneuve's request,
to replace one of her arias in ``Il Burbero di Buon Cuore'' (``The
Surly Benefactor''), an opera by Vicente Martin y Soler, who was
the most popular Viennese opera composer of Mozart's day.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute arias, as they are called, made news last fall, when
the mezzo-soprano Cecilia Bartoli, appearing in ``Le Nozze de
Figaro'' at the Metropolitan Opera, overrode the wishes of the
director Jonathan Miller and sang two alternative arias Mozart had
written for Adriana Ferrarese del Bene, the second soprano to sing
the role of Susanna, also in 1789. A furor resulted, and the
superstar mezzo was taken to task in these pages.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 18th century, it was standard practice to ``bring
your own aria,'' so to speak, the idea being that singers were
entitled to music that suited their voices and acting
personalities. Ms. Link, whose current scholarly focus is the
original singers of Mozart's operas, noted that Villeneuve _ the
first Dorabella in ``Cosi Fan Tutte,'' in 1790 _ seems to have been
particularly fond of Mozart's work; she asked him to provide
several substitute arias in the months preceding the premiere of
``Cosi Fan Tutte.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Ms. Link added, Villeneuve had good reason to want to
upgrade her arias for the 1789 revival of ``Il Burbero.'' ``The
singer who created her role clearly wasn't as good or famous as
Villeneuve, and Martin wrote the part accordingly,'' Ms. Link said.
``It was dime-store music.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most 18th-century arias, ``Vado, ma dove?'' was preceded by
a recitative: a short text set not with a lyrical melody but with
speechlike ``patter,'' harmonized with a few chords.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart's autograph of ``Vado, ma dove?'' contains no recitative,
so it was generally assumed that when Villeneuve performed in ``Il
Burbero,'' she simply sang Martin's recitative _ a ``secco''
setting, for voice and continuo _ before lighting into Mozart's
aria. Singers today perform Mozart's ``Vado, ma dove?'' without
recitative. But when Ms. Link examined the score to ``Il Burbero''
used by the conductor of the Vienna Court Theater for all the
performances of the opera, she found a different story.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the score contains both Martin's and Mozart's
settings of ``Vado, ma dove?'' Mozart's aria, written out by a
court copyist, has been sewn into the original score. The pages
containing Martin's setting of the aria, meanwhile, show tiny
pinholes; these, Ms. Link explained, indicate that at one time
those pages were sewn shut, the 18th-century way of crossing out
unused material in a performing score.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But those pinholes show that Martin's secco recitative was also
sewn shut; it was replaced by a more elaborate setting, an
``accompanied'' recitative, for strings and voice. And the new
recitative was added at the same time as Mozart's aria.
</P>
<P>
   How can Ms. Link tell this? The accompanied recitative, she
explained, is written on the same type of paper as Mozart's ``Vado,
ma dove?'' and in the same hand. Recitative and aria were sewn into
the score in a single bundle. Most telling, perhaps, Mozart's aria
starts on the flip side of the last page of the accompanied
recitative.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Link proposes this scenario: Mozart finished the aria,
entered it into his catalog and delivered it to Villeneuve for a
run-through. But when they tried out the piece, they decided that
the immediately preceding passage of text now called for something
more elaborate than Martin's secco setting. So Mozart composed a
new accompanied recitative that captures the text's emotional
instability and rising tension.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied, he then submitted the two pieces, recitative and
aria, to the theater copyist, who wrote them out and inserted them
into the score together. The fact that Mozart did not include the
recitative in his catalog is not damning; he left out a number of
other small works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the evidence that it's fully by Mozart really is
strong,'' said Sadie, who had seen a copy of the accompanied
recitative and read a paper Ms. Link had written about her
discovery, as yet unpublished. ``I don't think there's any reason
to question it.'' Sadie, speaking from his home in London, added
that the physical evidence _ pinholes, paper, binding, handwriting
_ is backed up by musical content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a number of his musical fingerprints on it,'' he
said: notably, a distinctive, downward arpeggio in the violins that
crops up frequently in ``Le Nozze di Figaro,'' and ``a way of
building excitement'' through carefully gauged harmonic
progressions.
</P>
<P>
   In the light of 18th-century theatrical practice, Sadie said, it
is highly improbable that someone else would have written a new
recitative for Mozart's aria. Obviously, you cannot be 100 percent
certain without an autograph, he added. ``But if you were a betting
person, you could put 95 percent odds'' on Mozart's authorship.
</P>
<P>
   If those odds satisfy singers and conductors, the recitative
will add weight and dramatic tension to future performances of
``Vado, ma dove?,'' which is now heard chiefly in concert. (Plans
for a first performance and recording of the aria with its ``new''
recitative are underway at Lawrence University, in Appleton, Wis.,
where Ms. Link has just joined the music faculty.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Link's recitative and a handful of similar finds in
recent years have broader significance. They show that 18th-century
opera was, in her words, ``always a confluence of artistic
imagination and circumstances.'' It is no longer sufficient to take
an autograph score as the composer's last word; musicologists and
performers will have to pay more attention to conductors' scores,
with their record of what actually happened on stage. ``The
veneration of autographs has gone too far,'' Ms. Link said.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``Vado, ma dove?'' likewise gives a revealing
glimpse of Mozart as, in Sadie's words, ``a practical man of the
theater.'' It helps dislodge the popular image of the composer as a
divine, mad genius, a cliche hard-wired into the modern imagination
by Peter Shaffer's play ``Amadeus'' and the film based on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in Mozart's day was writing for posterity,'' Sadie
said. ``They were writing to make sure that next week's
performances went well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Link picked up the theme: ``Nowadays we think that singers
have to give in to the score, that come hell or high water, they
have to `sing those notes.' But in the 18th century, it was the
composers who had to bend. It was a part of their pride in their
craft to say, `I don't care how bad that tenor is, I'll write
something that works.'''
</P>
<P>
   That, Ms. Link pointed out, is exactly what happened to Mozart
with ``Don Giovanni'': he had a good tenor for the original
production in Prague and a lousy one for the subsequent one in
Vienna. So in Vienna, he replaced the challenging tenor aria ``Il
mio tesoro'' with a new, simpler one, ``Dalla sua pace.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the Vienna Elvira was a soprano of greater
stature than the Prague one, so Mozart added a new aria for her,
``Mi tradi,'' which no one today would dream of leaving out. If,
right from the start, Mozart was writing for specific singers, with
all their strengths and weaknesses, who is to say what his
``ideal'' version was? What today's public thinks of as the
``correct'' version of ``Don Giovanni,'' Ms. Link noted, is in fact
a composite of the Prague and Vienna productions. ``Yet we won't
tolerate a hodgepodge version of the two productions of `Figaro.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the Bartoli affair. ``She was perfectly
right,'' Ms. Link said of Ms. Bartoli's decision to sing Mozart's
alternative arias for Susanna. ``Her voice is much more like
Ferrarese's than Sto-race's'' _ Nancy Storace having been the
original Susanna. Ms. Link speaks of those historic singers as if
they were old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period-instrument movement is authentic in so many ways,''
she added. ``Now it's time to expand that to the actual material
being sung, to reflect the operatic practices of the time. Today's
audiences expect to hear ornamentation added to arias. Why not add
the element of surprise of which arias are actually going to be
sung? The notion of what is authentic is a whole lot wider than
what we've heretofore thought.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
