<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streak's 6 as Smoltz ends slide
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz was mired in the longest winless streak of
his career, and now this?
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th start of that stretch, which by Tuesday night was
more than two months old, Smoltz had Reds ace Pete Harnisch and his
eight-game winning streak to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Maybe that was the best way for Smoltz to put an end
to his frustrations, with a 6-4 victory that extended the Braves'
winning streak to six games, matching their longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves used a pair of lively innings to rough up Harnisch
for six runs, the most he'd allowed all season. That helped Smoltz
overcome a three-run home run that shouldn't have happened and earn
his first win since June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Since that win over the Diamondbacks in the desert, Smoltz has
gone on and come off the disabled list with an inflamed elbow. He
strained his groin and didn't miss a start. He has lowered his arm
angle to three-quarters and added a different change-up to his
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched well in Pittsburgh and lost, pitched well against the
Astros and took no-decision, and defied science in Denver by
holding the Rockies to two runs in six innings before taking yet
another a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   All that brought him to Tuesday as the one the Braves turned to
continue their roll against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves spotted Smoltz a 2-0 lead in the first inning after
jumping on Harnisch for five hits, then erased a 3-2 deficit with
another four runs in the sixth. The first five Braves hitters of
that inning reached base on three singles, a walk and a two-run
double by Jose Hernandez for a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams had sent Harnisch's first pitch of the game past
Aaron Boone at third base for a double and eventually scored on a
Chipper Jones flare over Boone's head into shallow left field. But
the rally ended prematurely when Ryan Klesko was thrown out at
home, and Aaron Boone has some offensive revenge in store.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had a chance at an inning-ending double play in the
second on a grounder by catcher Eddie Taubensee but came up
empty-gloved as the ball stuck in the infield dirt. That allowed
Aaron Boone a trip to the plate, and he worked the count to 3-1
before depositing a Smoltz fastball into the left field seats to
give the Reds a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
