A8378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL-COX     08-24 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell shows its guests a hot time
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Rob Edinger's boss at Warner-Lambert Co.
decided to send him to Austin for Dell Computer Corp.'s
DirectConnect trade show, the computer technician pictured a
respite from New Jersey's stiflingly hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch that.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the mid-80s Tuesday in Morris Plains, N.J., where the
huge pharmaceuticals concern is based. At one point Tuesday
afternoon, the electronic billboard welcoming attendees to
DirectConnect registered 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   No sweat, Edinger said Tuesday from inside the Austin Convention
Center, where he was one of the first of about 1,400 customers to
arrive at the invitation-only event being held through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He still gets to hear Microsoft Corp. Chairman and Chief
Executive Bill Gates speak today and Intel Corp. Chief Executive
Craig Barrett speak Thursday on the future of personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know what they're (thinking) and how they're
going to implement it,'' said the 28-year-old Edinger, whose job
includes updating the software in 3,000 or so computers that
Warner-Lambert employees use in Morris Plains.
</P>
<P>
   That's why most of the DirectConnect attendees from around the
world _ ranging from computer technicians like Edinger to
executives at companies in various industries _ converged on Austin
Tuesday: To get a glimpse of the future of computing.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Gates, speakers at DirectConnect include host and
Dell CEO Michael Dell and Cisco Systems Inc. Chief Executive John
Chambers. Dell partners such as IBM Corp., Novel Corp., Sony Corp
and Tivoli Systems Inc. will show their latest products in the
exhibit hall.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, the gathering is Dell's effort to show the world that it
is working with other industry giants to help customers do business
in an era when e-commerce is expected to reach $1 trillion. With
Microsoft, for instance, Dell will show its customers how they can
upgrade from Windows NT to Windows 2000, when Microsoft's highly
anticipated operating system comes out next year.
</P>
<P>
   But some news also is expected: Dell officials are scheduled to
announce today a new initiative in Internet services _ an area that
the company sees as ripe for expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Details on Windows 2000 and new Dell initiatives are the sort of
information that Edinger and others can take home with them as
their companies decide whose computers will position them to thrive
in the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   But while Dell's two most recent quarters have been the best in
the industry, it will be a tough sale with some customers.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials Inc., which recently decided IBM will provide
its desktop computers, has about 50 servers made by Compaq Computer
Corp. at its manufacturing plant in Austin, said Mike LaMarre, a
network manager who is attending DirectConnect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the NT space, Compaq is still the best,'' said LaMarre, who
has a lot to say about how Applied spends $1 million annually on
servers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is concerned about Compaq's recent executive turnover
and signs that it is losing market share to Dell and others. But
LaMarre claims no other computer company can match Compaq's system
of detecting problems early, which allows Applied to avoid bigger
problems.
</P>
<P>
   For Edinger, LaMarre and scores of other Dell guests, Gates is
the highlight of the two-day gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the richest men in the world,'' LaMarre said.
``He's made a giant (company) and I use his products every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
