<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSIONALS, AMATEURS AND A HOBBYIST HAVE A BUSY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ The busiest night yet of this world track and
field championship was one for professionals, like Hicham
el-Guerrouj and Haile Gebrselassie, who both underscored their
dominance by winning gold medals. It was one for amateurs, like the
meet officials who mistakenly told the American pole vaulter Jeff
Hartwig he had qualified. It was even one for a hobbyist like
Anthony Washington, a part-time discus thrower who became the first
American to win his technical event at a major championship since
Mac Wilkins in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, this is a hobby; I work for a living,'' Washington
said, after his final throw of 226 feet 8 inches had lifted him
from fourth to first and past two Germans, Jurgen Schult and the
four-time world champion Lars Riedel, for whom the discus is a
full-time and very good living.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, a 33-year-old graduate of Syracuse who is married
and has two young sons, has worked for US West as a market analyst
in Denver since November. Though he finished fourth at the last
Summer Olympics in Atlanta, he has flirted with retirement with
varying degrees of sincerity since 1994, a year in which he said he
competed in only one event.
</P>
<P>
   But like his former high-school rival in New York state, C.J.
Hunter, who won the shot put with a lengthy and timely final effort
on Saturday, Washington found a way to rise above his past
frustrations in major championships in the sultry evening air of
Seville.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw C.J. hit that big throw on his last attempt, it was
fantastic, and I said, `If C.J. can get one, maybe it's possible
for me,''' Washington said. ``He's been doing it a long time, just
like me, but I didn't want to have to win it on the last throw.
That takes years off your life.''
</P>
<P>
   The track and field news Tuesday night was not only about good
lines and good performances, however. The International Amateur
Athletic Federation also announced that two athletes _ the sprinter
Davidson Ezinwa of Nigeria and the middle-distance runner Mohamed
Ibrahim Aden of Somalia _ tested positive for banned substances in
drug tests administered here.
</P>
<P>
   Ezinwa, who reached the 100-meter final at the 1992 and 1996
Olympics, tested positive for Hcg, a substance that can help
produce testosterone in men, and has been suspended and could face
a two-year ban. He failed to reach the 100 final. Aden's urine
sample showed traces of ephedrine. He finished sixth in the first
semifinal of the 1,500 and has been disqualified and was issued a
public warning.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Aden had reached the final on Tuesday night, he
certainly would not have troubled el-Guerrouj, the world-record
holder and defending world champion in the 1,500. An acute case of
hemorrhoids kept him out of action for a month after he set the
world mark in the mile on July 7 in Rome with Noah Ngeny of Kenya
on his heels, but since his return, the Moroccan has now beaten
Ngeny, his main competition, twice more at 1,500: in Zurich and on
Tuesday night in a time of 3 minutes 27.65 seconds, which was a
championship record and, remarkably for a meet of this sort, the
fifth-fastest time in history. In the final 20 meters, el-Guerrouj
pinched his fingers together and brought them to his lips, blowing
kisses into the air.
</P>
<P>
   El-Guerrouj's most pressing goals now are to hold the world
record at every distance from 1500 to 5,000 and to win his first
Olympic gold medal next year in Sydney, Australia. But
Gebrselassie, the small and preternaturally smooth Ethiopian,
already has won every distance title that matters, and Tuesday
night he won his fourth consecutive world title in the 10,000 in a
time of 27:57.27. It was a closer race than most that the Ethiopian
runs: Paul Tergat of Kenya was second in 27:58.56; his fellow
Ethiopian Assefa Mezgebu third in 27:59.15.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no attempt to double in the 5,000.
Gebrselassie finds the conditions in Seville too hot. Even at 9:30
p.m., when his race began, it was 88 degrees with considerable
humidity in the stadium. He also wants to conserve his energy to
try to break his own world record in the 5,000 next month.
</P>
<P>
   The American 100-meter champions Maurice Greene and Marion Jones
both qualified for the semifinals of the 200 by getting through two
rounds on Tuesday, but two of their teammates, Allen Johnson and
Hartwig, had a day to forget in the heat. Johnson, the reigning
Olympic champion and two-time defending world champion in the
110-meter hurdles, withdrew before the semifinals after reinjuring
the right calf that had kept him out of action since July 8.
Hartwig, one of the favorites for a medal in the men's pole vault,
failed to advance out of qualifying, although he had a good excuse.
</P>
<P>
   After clearing 18 feet 2 inches on his first attempt, short of
the automatic qualifying standard but potentially good enough to
earn a spot in the final anyway, he waited to see if he needed to
jump again. Hartwig said one official finally told him that he had
qualified. ``He showed me the board and said, `It's finished,'''
Hartwig said. ``So I went over and sat down, and the next thing you
know my name is up and the clock is running. They come and they
point to me and say you're up.''
</P>
<P>
   He rushed out to try to clear 18-8\ and said he got a bad grip
on his pole, which slipped and bruised his right thigh, foot and
knee. He ended up missing three times and missing the final by one
spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ELDER-BEERMAN25-COX     08-24 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDER-BEERMAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elder-Beerman reports loss
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Elder-Beerman Stores Corp. reported Tuesday a
second-quarter loss of $1.3 million, but its chief executive said
the company can turn itself around in time for the crucial
Christmas sales season.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments since a major investor publicly
asked for his resignation, Elder-Beerman Chairman and Chief
Executive Frederick J. Mershad said he has no plans to resign and
that changes in company management announced Monday will work.
</P>
<P>
   Mershad also renewed his vow to keep Elder-Beerman independent
even though the company's largest shareholder told Barron's , a
national business weekly, the company would be a ``tremendous
acquisition or merger for somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Mershad said he has full confidence that Charles Shaffer, the
company's new chief merchant, can quickly resolve lingering
merchandise problems that have contributed to recent losses.
Shaffer inherits merchandising duties from Mershad, who handled
them since 1997, when he joined the company. Mershad said Tuesday
he relinquished those duties in part because they spread him too
thin.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer, an executive for the Moraine-based retailer for 14
years, has final say over what items go into the chain's 60 stores,
Mershad said, and will oversee the company's marketing operation.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the earnings loss, management has forecasted more
conservatively for the fall selling season. The company also plans
to cut $3.5 million in expenses, Mershad said.
</P>
<P>
   The change comes as the retailer enters the last six months of
its fiscal year, which generates about 90 percent of its sales.
</P>
<P>
   Elder-Beerman, as predicted, reported Tuesday a second-quarter
net loss of $1.3 million, compared with net income of $0.2 million
during the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share equaled a loss of 8 cents per share, compared
with net income of 2 cents per share during the same period last
year. Sales climbed 11.9 percent to $147.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Stein, a retail analyst with Cleveland-based McDonald and
Co. Securities, said the numbers came in as expected. Elder-Beerman
warned investors Aug. 5 that it would suffer a second-quarter loss
exceeding $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly results came a day after Elder-Beerman announced plans
to bolster its stock's value through such steps as a share
repurchase of up to $24 million over two years, making more
acquisitions and reorganizing merchandising operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the things we've done prepare us for future
growth,'' Mershad said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the top executive for Elder-Beerman's largest
shareholder, Snyder Capital Management Inc. of San Francisco, told
Barron's Elder-Beerman is a tremendous acquisition or merger
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder Capital Management founder and president Alan B. Snyder
told the publication he plans to meet with dissident shareholder
David Nierenberg of D3 Family Fund L.P.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg notified the federal government more than a week ago
his group of 80 investors has acquired 845,000 common shares, or
5.3 percent of Elder-Beerman's 16 million shares outstanding. He
has complained about the company's low share price and has called
for the board to either fire Mershad and president John ``Jay''
Muskovich or to sell the company.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Murtaugh, a portfolio manager with Snyder Capital
Management, said the company would offer higher earnings potential
if it could turn itself around rather than be acquired by another
company.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder Capital Management is more supportive of Elder-Beerman's
executive team than Nierenberg, Murtaugh said. Officials from the
California money management firm have talked with Nierenberg, but
``we haven't decided how we're going to approach this. We want to
see what management says before we make any decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein lauded Elder-Beerman's initiatives to strengthen itself
and improve its share value. Buying back shares, reorganizing the
merchandising and bolstering the private-label credit card segment
should spur small sales gains for the company during this year's
second half, he said. But the real gains should come next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elder-Beerman (NASDAQ:EBSC) shares finished trading Tuesday at
7, down .
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
