<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-OHIO-TAFT-RAISES-COX     08-24 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TAFT-RAISES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft quietly awards cabinet with raises
 &HT;    By William Hershey and Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The members of Gov. Bob Taft's cabinet had been
on the job for no more than six months when Taft quietly awarded
most of them pay raises of at least 3 percent on July 1, the start
of the state's new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the previously unannounced raises on Tuesday,
Scott Milburn, Taft' press secretary, said: ``I didn't think it was
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Milburn said it has been standard practice for several years to
award raises at the start of the fiscal year to most state
employees. The governor wanted to follow that practice for his 23
cabinet members, even though they had not been working a full year,
said Milburn. Had Taft not acted, cabinet members would have had to
wait 18 months before getting raises at the beginning of the next
fiscal year on July 1, 2000, Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the raises ``merit-based, cost-of-living
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Milburn and three other top staffers in the governor's office _
Chief of Staff Brian Hicks, Communications Director Mary Anne
Sharkey and Chief Policy Advisor Scott Borgemenke _ also got 3
percent raises.
</P>
<P>
   Milburn said that Taft believes one of his biggest challenges in
putting a cabinet together is competing with the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these people are top notch individuals who would
command much higher salaries in the private sector,'' Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the raises, 11 cabinet members had salaries larger
than the salaries of their predecessors under Gov. George
Voinovich. Ten cabinet members started their jobs with salaries
equal to those serving under Voinovich and two of Taft's directors
made starting salaries lower than those paid to Voinovich's
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen members of Taft's cabinet earn more than $100,000.
Just six of Voinovich's cabinet members earned that much.
</P>
<P>
   The raises disturbed two Miami Valley lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was very smart thing to do,'' said state Sen.
Charles Horn, R-Centerville. ``If these people started out making
more than Voinovich's people and they just came on board, I don't
think that is very judicious. I'm a fiscal conservative and my
constituents feel that way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, said the state has more
important things to spend money on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you still have a large percentage of Ohioans working two
jobs to make ends meet, it's ridiculous to grant raises to people
who are making that kind of money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the legislature earn $42,427. An effort to raise
their salaries to $44,927 beginning in 2002 died last June as the
result of partisan bickering in the House. Legislators have not had
a raise since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest cabinet raise went to Dr. James ``Nick'' Baird Jr.,
the state health director, who started on June 1 with a salary of
$109,886. His salary was increased to $113,182 on July 1. On July
31, he received a special physician's supplement of about $22,600,
taking his salary to about $135,800. The legislature approved
giving supplements to physicians who fill the health director's
job. The health director under Voinovich was not a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the raise, Baird receives about $110,000 less than
he did at the private health care job he left to take the state
position, Milburn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor was very pleased to be able to recruit him. He's
talented and experienced,'' said Mi,b 5/8rn, whose own salary went
from $83,990 to $86,258 with the raise.
</P>
<P>
   Baird and James Conrad, director of the Bureau of Worker's
Compensation whose salary is $142,043, are the two cabinet members
who earn more than Taft. The governor's salary is $119,235.
</P>
<P>
   Four cabinet members did not receive raises on July 1. They
were: Kenneth W. Ritchey, mental retardation; Sam Speck, natural
resources; Scott Johnson, administrative services, and Gordon
Proctor, transportation. Three of the four, Ritchey, Speck and
Johnson, all only started their jobs since March. Lottery Director
Mitchell Brown received a pay increase of less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another cabinet member, Thomas M. Zaino of taxation, was not
appointed until July 1, the date the raises took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Don Berno, president of the Ohio Public Expenditure Council,
said $100,000 is ``a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``it's getting more and more difficult'' to
persuade quality people to leave private sector jobs to take
government positions, said Berno, whose group is a Columbus-based
nonpartisan think tank that analyses state and local government
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all boils down to you get what you pay for,'' Berno said.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey and Mike Wagner write for the Dayton Daily News,
Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
