<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No verdict in Martin case
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal jury reached no verdict on money-laundering
charges against Dolphins receiver Tony Martin in its first day of
deliberations Tuesday, but will resume today.
</P>
<P>
   That meant no immediate decision for Martin and his family, who
waited in courthouse hallways, but there were indications that the
jury is closely examining charges against Martin's co-defendant,
convicted drug dealer Rickey Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of eight women and four men, all of whom happen to be
black or Hispanic, asked for transcripts of testimony by witnesses
related to Brownlee's portion of the case.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Michael Moore told jurors to use their
collective memory because no transcripts existed for the portions
they requested and could take at least a day to produce.
</P>
<P>
   One juror must register her child for school so deliberations
were not scheduled to resume until 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Martin faces three to five years in prison on five
counts related to money-laundering. The Dolphins have not ruled out
playing him this season even if he is convicted _ presuming he
remains free on bond awaiting sentencing or appeals, and the league
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee, who has already served seven years on two 1980s drug
convictions, faces up to life in prison for convictions on 11
charges against him, including trafficking in cocaine and heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's lawyers said it is impossible to know how long it might
take for the jury to reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be they decide quickly on one (defendant) but not the
other,'' attorney Howard Srebnick said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began deliberating about 11:30 a.m. Tuesday, following
closing statements by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing, which began Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ron
DeWaard reminded jurors that they do not set the sentences, and are
not allowed to let ``sympathy'' affect their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed aimed at jurors who may be unsure about voting to
convict Martin, whose lawyers say he was only trying to help
Brownlee, a longtime family friend whom Martin calls uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Martin gave Brownlee ``the benefit of the doubt,'' Srebnick told
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   DeWaard said an NFL player should know better before agreeing to
write checks for more than $200,000 for cash from someone
previously convicted on drug charges. The checks were for cars and
attorney fees for Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   Get updates on the Martin case at www.GoPBI.com/sports
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
