<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-HALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio congressman to visit North Korea
 &HT;    By Scottt Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea has retreated from the brink of famine,
and so far hasn't made good on recent threats to test launch a
long-range missile, creating an unexpected lull in the turbulent
life of the last Stalinist nation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall ( D-Ohio) sees it as a good time to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Hall will arrive in the North Korean capitol of Pyongyang on
Thursday to begin a three-day trek through the rural areas of the
country that only recently began climbing out of a massive food
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, an expert on hunger and humanitarian issues, plans to
monitor the distribution channels of U.S. food aid by meeting with
workers from the United Nations, private charities and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is making his fifth trip to North Korea since 1996, when
the first signs of starvation began appearing. The communist
country invited Hall to view the deepening crisis first-hand to
help make the case for international food aid.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the head of World Food Programme of the UN returned
from a trip into the secretive country and said conditions had
significantly improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an absolute difference in the children,'' Catherine
Bertini told The Washington Post. ``Before, we saw children who
were almost skeletal. You could see the bones in their head.''
</P>
<P>
   But North Korea continues to rely on international food
donations to provide about one quarter of the 4 million tons of
food needed to feed its 23 million people. And Bertini warned that
any disruption of that aid would have dire consequences, noting,
too, that she was not permitted to visit many areas of the country
where people may still be suffering from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also is worried that while conditions may no longer be
deadly, the country remains deeply in need of assistance. The
country still cannot grow enough food to feed its people, and
Hall's office said ``the pipeline of international food aid is
running dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall plans to meet with top government officials in North Korea,
as well as the president of South Korea, Kim Dae Jung. Hall will
hold a press conference during his two days in Seoul early next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-24-99 1855E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
