<SLUG> BC-WPP-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: SORRELL RAISES ANTE, INCENTIVES AND POTENTIAL PAYOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To the British tabloids, Martin Sorrell is no ordinary
advertising executive. He is ``Mr 35M,'' as the bold-faced headline
read in The Sun last week. At the end of next month, Sorrell, chief
executive of the WPP Group PLC, will receive shares of the company
worth about (PS)35 million ($56 million) as part of a much-disputed
performance-based compensation package that he created four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   And if he has his way, he and 14 other top executives could
collect (PS)100 million ($160 million) more as part of a new
compensation plan he introduced last week.
</P>
<P>
   The board of WPP, which owns J. Walter Thompson Co. and Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide, will not vote on the compensation plan for
several weeks, but the issue is already stirring discussion in
Britain's advertising community.
</P>
<P>
   A $56 million payday in the United States may not raise too many
eyebrows for a chief executive of a major company with offices all
over the world, but in Britain, which keeps a watchful eye over
``fat cat'' compensation packages, Sorrell's deal is far from
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   While senior executives at Omnicom and Interpublic in the United
States have become rich as the value of their stock options has
climbed with the market, most advertising executives in Britain
tend to get standard salaries without lottery-like stock options or
huge bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the stock option plans that U.S. executives often get,
however, the incentive plan that Sorrell is proposing has a couple
of strings attached. The proposal would require executives to sink
almost a year's worth of their salaries into the company beyond any
profits they might have taken previously from shares of WPP and
would require them to stay locked in for four years. In addition,
the company has to rank as the No. 1 or No. 2 advertising and
communications company in the world, based on its share price and
reinvested dividends. If the company falls short of that goal, the
executives would still be eligible for smaller compensation.
</P>
<P>
   It is a risky gamble for Sorrell, 53, and his 14 colleagues
because the advertising business, so often fickle, is hard to
predict as companies move their accounts from agency to agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word entrepreneur means risk taker,'' Sorrell said in an
interview last week. ``I'm committing virtually all of my net worth
to the company.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I'm not cashing in to reload,'' explaining that he
is not going to sell any of the shares he will get next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrell has been a bit of a gambler since he took control of WPP
in 1986. He engineered the first hostile takeover of an advertising
agency, J. Walter Thompson in 1987, and then two years later bought
one of Madison Avenue's most famous names, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, for an
astonishing figure at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The buying spree pushed WPP to within an eyelash of going under,
as debts taken on during the acquisition binge were aggravated by
the worldwide advertising recession.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Sorrell has succeeded in bringing WPP back from the
brink, he wants in on the action. ``From a personal point of view,
I always wanted a major equity stake in a company,'' said Sorrell,
who left Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi to take the reins of WPP. ``I'm trying
to put us on par with our U.S. competition.''
</P>
<P>
   As he proposes radically changing the compensation structure,
others in Britain's advertising community question whether the
creative side of the business will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will ask whether an incentive scheme which is linked
entirely to WPP's stock price will serve to further erode the
creative standing of the two networks by making City and Wall
Street performance, rather than advertising pedigree, the prime
motivator,'' wrote Caroline Marshall, deputy editor of the British
trade magazine Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And, she added, ``There will, of course, be concerns from those
in ad land who resent Sorrell's formidable unseen influence or who
detest his financial leverage over treasured advertising icons like
J. Walter Thompson and Ogilvy &AMP; Mather.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Sorrell, all of this is just business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the holdings of my peers, compared with me, the
compensations are not dissimilar,'' he said. ``But I'm putting my
money where my mouth is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
