<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RATE-INCREASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CAUTIOUS RATE INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 25:
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board is acting cautiously in trying to slow
the American economy and head off a resurgence of inflation.
Investors appear to be confident that such a gradual approach will
have a minimal impact on the economy. In the near term, they are
probably right.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed on Tuesday raised the Federal funds rate, the rate at
which banks borrow from each other, by a quarter of a percentage
point, to 5.25 percent. It also raised the discount rate, at which
banks borrow from the Fed when they are in severe need of capital,
by the same amount, to 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, had signaled the increases in
congressional testimony at which he warned that the economy was
growing too rapidly to prevent inflationary pressures in a very
tight labor market. As a result, the Fed's move Tuesday surprised
no one.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street now expects that the Fed is through raising rates
for the rest of this year, and that the next meeting of the Fed's
Open Market Committee, on Oct. 5, will be a nonevent. It also
believes that neither corporate profits nor financial markets will
be damaged by higher interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial
average, which closed at a record high on Monday, slipped a bit
Tuesday, but the more broadly based Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and
Nasdaq composite indexes advanced. Bond prices also rose, sending
long-term interest rates down a bit even as the Fed was pushing up
short-term rates.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with the domestic economy strong but fears of
worldwide recession intense, the Fed cut interest rates three
times. In explaining its decision to raise rates Tuesday, the Fed
said that ``the degree of monetary ease required to address the
global financial market turmoil of last fall is no longer
consistent with sustained, noninflationary economic expansion.''
Still, the fact that the Fed sees no need to reverse all of last
year's cuts is viewed by Wall Street as a sign that Greenspan and
his colleagues are not going to spoil the party that has sent stock
prices to unprecedented valuations and roused fears of a financial
bubble.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the Fed will be forced to tighten credit
again this year, even if inflation does not accelerate. That could
happen if the dollar comes under pressure. It has already begun to
weaken against both the Japanese yen and the euro.
</P>
<P>
   That weakening might be the first indication that investors are
beginning to move capital overseas, a potentially serious problem
given that the United States must continue to attract large amounts
of capital to finance its big trade deficit. Higher interest rates
are one way to attract that capital, and a very weak dollar might
force the Fed to raise rates again.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is acting responsibly in trying to slow the economy
gradually. President Clinton and Congress should cooperate by
pursuing a lean fiscal policy. In particular, as Greenspan has
asked, they should avoid tax cuts that would unnecessarily
stimulate the economy and increase the chances that the Fed will
have to raise interest rates again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
