<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-BRAVES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The good, the bad and the ugly: Reds fall to Braves again
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The good news: The Atlanta Braves stole zero bases
against the Cincinnati Reds on Tuesday night in Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: They didn't have to steal any.
</P>
<P>
   The real bad news: The Braves hammered the Reds again, 6-4, the
fifth straight time this season they've taken care of business
against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The awful news: The Houston Astros were given a chance to extend
their lead in the National League Central to 1 games if they beat
the New York Mets on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the recent effectiveness of Cincinnati starter Pete
Harnisch (eight straight victories) and the recent ineffectiveness
of Atlanta starter John Smoltz (winless in nine starts, during
which he was 0-4) could reverse the depths of despair in which the
Reds fall against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch gave up a season's high six runs and ten hits, tying
his season's high, and was gone before the sixth inning was over.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who pitched a one-hit shutout against the Reds here
April 30, is battling an elbow problem and has altered his delivery
from straight over the top to three-quarters. It doesn't matter
against the Reds. He is 11-0 against Cincinnati in his last 14
tries.
</P>
<P>
   Negative numbers continue to pile up for the Reds against the
Braves _ nine total runs (1.8 per game) and 18 hits (3.6 per game)
in the five losses. By losing the first two of his three-game
series, the Reds won't extend their streak of winning nine straight
series. Instead, they extend a losing streak, eight straight series
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After Smoltz quickly put down the Reds 1-2-3 in the first, the
Braves became the first team in Harnisch's 26 starts to score more
than one run in the first inning, putting two on the board on five
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams opened with a double, the 50th straight game in
which the Braves have hit at least one double. Williams took third
on Bret Boone's deep fly to right and scored on a jam-job flare
single to left by Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko and Andruw Jones singled for the second run, then
Jose Hernandez made it three straight hits with a single off second
baseman Pokey Reese's glove, but when Klesko tried to score Reese
threw him out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds grabbed a 3-2 lead in the fourth when Aaron Boone drove
his ninth home run into the left field seats, scoring Barry Larkin
(single) and Eddie Taubensee (error).
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch retired 13 of 14 from the second through the fifth,
including 10 straight entering the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Then, carnage.
</P>
<P>
   The first five Braves reached base in the sixth, four hits and a
walk, and Harnisch was finished after giving up four more runs,
leaving with a 6-3 deficit. Klesko had a run-scoring single, Andruw
Jones ripped a two-run single and Hernandez crushed a two-run
double over center fielder Mike Cameron's head. Both Harnisch and
the Reds were done for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
