<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICANN-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET'S GOVERNING BODY DEBATES DOMAIN NAMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ A major meeting of the Internet's new
governing body opened Tuesday with the fireworks and controversy
that have become its trademark, including protests over a closed
session of one of its advisory groups and a dispute over what
should be voted on later this week.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of much of the discussion was the theme that has
dominated much of the debate about the organization, the Internet
Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers: how to guarantee that
individual Internet users and noncommercial interests have a voice
before it starts making key policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which has largely been busy with organizational
issues at past meetings, is scheduled to begin that process on
Thursday when it considers a proposal for cracking down on
cybersquatters _ people who buy domains with popular names or
trademarks in hopes of reselling them at a hefty profit.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit corporation, known as Icann, was selected last
year by the U.S. Commerce Department to take over administration of
the Internet. The Internet's domain name system has been
administered until now by government contractors, including Network
Solutions, a Herndon, Va., company that built a lucrative business
as the exclusive registrar of names in the domains of .com, .net
and .org.
</P>
<P>
   One of Icann's initial charges was to open that business to
competition, creating a difficult tug of war for the board between
commercial interests who want the rules completed quickly and those
who want no decisions to be made until all Internet users can be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that big business and trademark interests have
dominated the process for drafting the proposed rules for resolving
cybersquatting disputes, a newly formed group of holders of
noncommercial domain names circulated petitions Tuesday asking that
the board delay that vote.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the noncommercial interests said they were
concerned that the proposal needs to define cybersquatting more
narrowly to insure that free speech is protected and that large
companies cannot use the process to take domain names away from
individuals who might have a legitimate claim to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Icann board will hold a public forum on Wednesday to take
comment on that and other issues before its meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But while Icann, under pressure from the U.S. Congress, agreed
to open this board meeting to the public for the first time, some
who came here were disturbed Tuesday to find that its governmental
advisory committee was continuing to close its sessions to
outsiders. The committee is composed of representatives of national
governments and multinational organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I find it outrageous,'' said Therese Amato, who came
from Chicago to represent the Citizens' Advocacy Center, a Ralph
Nader consumer organization.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, Paul Twomey, a special adviser for the
Australian government on information economy and technology, said
the group makes no policy recommendations but needs to be able to
hold candid meetings to discuss Internet issues affecting its
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
