<HEADER>
A8399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-24 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC NOT TOO CONCERNED ABOUT BUSH'S PAST; FOR RHODE ISLAND
CANDIDATE, HONESTY IS BEST; MCCAIN'S ABORTION PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, R.I., Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXAS: Voters Seem Inclined to Forgive and Forget
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Gov. George W. Bush of Texas used drugs may still
be good grist for the media mill. But evidence is building that the
American public is not overly concerned about the issue and would
be inclined to forgive Bush if it turns out that, to use his
phrase, when he was young and irresponsible, he was young and
irresponsible, and tried a snort or two of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   In a new ABC News poll, more than half of the respondents say
the governor should not answer the drug question. And better than
three of every four say that if he never does, his refusal will not
affect their opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   Even more telling, better than three of every four respondents
say that should the governor confess to having tried cocaine in his
youth, their opinion of him will not change.
</P>
<P>
   Another new poll, this one a CNN/Time survey, came up with
similar results, though not weighted quite as heavily in Bush's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   There also was an added question in that poll. Asked whether
they thought Bush had used cocaine at some point in his life, the
number of respondents who thought he had exceeded the number who
thought he had not by almost 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In neither poll is there any significant evidence that the drug
controversy is likely to cost Bush votes in the coming Republican
primaries and caucuses. Nor has it hurt him in theoretical matchups
with Vice President Al Gore, the current front-running Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still leads his closest Republican rival in national polls,
Elizabeth Dole, the former Red Cross president, by a good 40
points. And he still leads Gore by a good dozen.
</P>
<P>
   RHODE ISLAND: In Rhode Island, a Decision to Tell All
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts say that the ABC and CNN/Time poll
results indicate that the American public may be growing more
tolerant of wrongdoing by public figures, in part because so much
wrongdoing has been in the news in recent years, especially
presidential wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it comes to past drug usage, at least one candidate,
Mayor Lincoln Chafee of Warwick, R.I., is not taking the public's
tolerance for wrongdoing for granted, if that tolerance is indeed
growing. Having watched Bush swing and twist on the drug issue, he
figures that the best course is not only to trust the tolerance of
the American voter but also to tell the truth, and the whole truth,
right up front. Get it out and get it over with, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the political game, that is known not just as forthright
honesty but also as ``inoculation.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Sunday, Chafee, a Republican who is running to succeed his
father, John Chafee, in the U.S. Senate, did not hesitate when a
television interviewer asked, ``Have you ever used drugs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have,'' he replied, confessing that while he was in
college in the early 1970s he had inhaled marijuana and snorted
cocaine ``several times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were very tumultuous times,'' he went on. ``I'm not
proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he told The Providence Journal that having watched the
media doggedly press Bush for an answer, he had anticipated that
he, too, would face questions about drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled with what's the politically correct answer,'' he
said. ``But in the end, honesty is the best policy. It was part of
the culture. People are tolerant and understanding. If you're
forthright and honest with the public and you've got nothing to
hide, I don't see why it's such a big story. If you try to cover it
up, it becomes a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the press overdoing the looking into candidates' past?
</P>
<P>
   ``They enjoy getting on the trail of what they think is a story,
even if the public just isn't interested in it,'' Chafee replied.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Confusion Follows McCain on Abortion
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has been getting
some pretty good political reviews as he has crisscrossed the
country in quest of the Republican presidential nomination. His
organizing and fund raising and campaign appearances have been
going well, and many political analysts have come to see him as the
candidate best positioned to be his party's alternative choice
should George W. Bush falter.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly there is trouble on the horizon for McCain, trouble
as serious as any he has confronted thus far in the campaign year.
He has run afoul of the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of two decades, he has been an outspoken
opponent of abortion, especially Roe vs. Wade, the landmark
decision that protects abortion rights. But a statement he made
last Thursday on the issue in an interview with The San Francisco
Chronicle has left people on both sides confused as to where he now
stands. Discussing Roe vs. Wade, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see a point where it is irrelevant and could be
repealed because abortion is no longer necessary. But certainly in
the short term, or even the long term, I would not support repeal
of Roe vs. Wade, which would then force X-number of women in
America to illegal and dangerous operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he misspeak? Was he edging toward abortion rights? Or, like
some of the more moderate Republican candidates, such as Bush and
Mrs. Dole, was he simply trying to push the issue off the front
burner because it was too politically hot and divisive, a tricky
move in itself?
</P>
<P>
   His office says that all he was saying was that if Roe vs. Wade
was repealed, repeal should be accompanied by expansion of adoption
and family counseling programs so as to minimize the rush to
illegal abortions that surely would follow.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee says that sounds like
back-pedaling. The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League worries that it is ``political posturing.'' And, summing up
the view of some of the more conservative Republican contenders,
Steve Forbes, the publisher, says McCain has lost his ideological
way and is suddenly ``stuttering and stammering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
