<SLUG> BC-KILLER-NABBED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED KILLER ARRESTED AFTER 8-YEAR `FISHING TRIP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE and CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Eight years ago, convicted killer Alan Echols
said he was going fishing and left before a judge could sentence
him to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing trip ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Echols, a Raytown, Mo., resident who was convicted of stabbing
an Independence man 61 times with a large hunting knife, was
arrested at a truck stop near Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   Behind that capture, prosecutors said, was another strange twist
in a bizarre case.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, Echols did not deny he stabbed Ronald Nichols on Oct.
12, 1990, in the parking lot of a Kansas City are bar. Echols'
lawyer described him as a ``lovesick puppy,'' guilty of only
second-degree murder. Echols said he killed because he loved
Nichols' wife, Billie Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1991, a Jackson County jury convicted Echols of
first-degree murder, which carries a sentence of life without
parole. But in an unusual move, the judge allowed him to remain
free on bond.
</P>
<P>
   Echols, now 35, vanished after he told his parents he was going
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least 1994, he has been living in Shreveport under an
alias. Ironically, prosecutors said, the woman he loved helped end
his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's wife, Billie, sometimes visited Echols in
Louisiana, said Kevin Pose, assistant county prosecutor. She
recently told an acquaintance who Echols was and that man alerted
authorities, said Pose.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Police Detective Al DeValkenaere said Billie Nichols
was part of an ongoing investigation and declined to comment
further. She has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   DeValkenaere said the source on Thursday told authorities he
knew where to find a killer featured recently on ``America's Most
Wanted,'' which carried a report on the search for Echols. He knew
details about the slaying, about the slayer's and widow's families
and about things that the victim said to the slayer before the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The source gave authorities the name Robert Byle _ a man who
died in 1972. Officials checked the photograph on Byle's driver's
license. It resembled Echols, now with glasses and a full beard,
DeValkenaere said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities called Byle's number and the answering machine said,
``Sorry, I got called away for the weekend. If you are calling
about the car, leave a message.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities called Monday and left a message, pretending to be
interested in buying the car. Echols called back and made an
appointment to meet ``the buyer'' at 10 a.m. Tuesday, DeValkenaere
said.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't want to arrest Echols at his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The source told us he would either commit suicide or shoot it
out with police, so we didn't want to go to his home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the buyer's suggestion, Echols showed up at the Flying
J Truck Stop near Shreveport, where authorities arrested him
without any problems.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he maintained he was Robert Byle, but he changed his
story when detectives told him they were going to check his
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he said, `OK. I'm Alan Echols,' '' said DeValkenaere, who
has hunted Echols for years.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Trusty, spokesman for the Caddo Parish Sheriff's Office,
said Echols was wearing a T-shirt and jeans and sported a ``scruffy
beard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd been living down here without a hint of trouble since at
least 1994,'' Trusty said. ``As far as we can tell, he didn't do
much illegal down here, other than hide out from the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Trusty said Echols blended with other residents in northwest
Louisiana, a quiet area with many lakes that provide good fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Echols was in a Louisiana jail late Tuesday awaiting extradition
to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Nichols' sister, Denise Goode of Kansas City, praised
police for finally catching Echols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see him one last time,'' she said, ``at
sentencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Peters, a former assistant prosecutor who won the
conviction at trial, said the capture ends the legend of a criminal
who seemed to beat the system.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Cain, Echols' defense lawyer, said he had not heard from
his client since he left. Cain said he assumed Echols went to a
Mexican state that does not extradite U.S. criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Cain added, ``I can't blame the kid (for running); what's he got
to lose?'' Cain said he did not know if Echols' grandparents would
be able to get back the $100,000 bond they lost after he fled eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Circuit Judge K. Preston Dean, who allowed Echols
to remain free after bond was posted, declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
