<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS REGULATORS APPROVE TENTATIVE TERMS OF UTILITY MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ The Kansas Corporation Commission on Tuesday outlined a
tentative order that would allow the proposed merger of Western
Resources Inc. and Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co., but would keep
the utilities from charging customers for many merger costs.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-hour work session with staff members, the three
commissioners agreed that customers of the new utility, Westar
Energy, would not see any merger-related rate increase on their
monthly bills for at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   During that moratorium, the utility would keep all savings it
was able to glean from streamlined and consolidated operations,
estimated to be $191 million. After that, ratepayers would receive
all remaining merger savings.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, as expected, rejected more favorable terms for
the utilities that the companies had worked out with the
commission's staff. Under the staff recommendation, the new utility
eventually could have put up to $300 million into its rate base to
cover Western's acquisition premium _ the amount of KCP&AMP;L's sale
price over its book value.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the commissioners said, merger costs would be treated
as an expense and amortized over the 36 years after the moratorium
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Western and KCP&AMP;L said Tuesday that they would have no comment
until the commission's final order was issued, probably in four to
six weeks. Utility officials previously have said that substantial
changes in the staff recommendations on recovering merger costs
could scuttle the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also needs approval from Missouri and federal
regulators. The utilities have agreed to terms with those
regulators' staffs and with the agency that represents Missouri
consumers. Under the Missouri agreement, Western will not recover
the acquisition premium from customers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the order outlined Tuesday, the new utility would file a
Kansas rate case after four years. The resulting order, expected
about eight months later, would determine whether users of
electricity from the utility would see lower bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ray of hope for ratepayers is that savings will be
significant enough at the time of the next rate case that they will
be able to realize the benefits from the merger,'' said Walker
Hendrix, counsel for the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned, ``It's not a home run for the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Brian Moline said the agreement was designed to
protect the ratepayers while dealing fairly with the companies'
desire to merge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what we've done today is coming as close as we can
to balancing those interests,'' Moline said.
</P>
<P>
   The two other commissioners agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very difficult case,'' said Commissioner
Cynthia Claus. ``I'm comfortable we've all considered the evidence
very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission Chairman John Wine said, ``I'm satisfied we've done
all we can with what we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
