u d BC-HELP-YOURSELF-EATING-     08-24 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELP-YOURSELF-EATING-WELL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALAD BARS:   HOW MUCH E COLI, BACTERIA AND FLIES WILL STATE 
 INSPECTORS ALLOW? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., Minn.)  (ART ADV: A photo and map are being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A small child snags a piece of melon from a salad bar
with her chubby little fingers. A man sneezes, then picks up the
tongs resting on a bed of potato salad. A woman runs her finger
along the edge of a tuna salad bowl and puts it in her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of help-yourself food bars, there are many more
opportunities for food to be contaminated than at a full service
delicatessen _ and little enforcement of the rules that do exist.
</P>
<P>
   A laboratory analysis of seven establishments in Manhattan
selected by the Dining section found far more problems than New
York State records would indicate: not one would have passed a
state inspection. At best, the quality of some of the food tested
was very low because of age, mishandling or contamination. A review
of state inspection records after the testing showed that four of
the seven establishments failed inspections in 1998 or 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There are no regulations that specify how long food can stay on
a salad bar or in a deli display case, and none that prevent food
from being recycled from one day to the next. There are no food
police to prevent people from sticking their fingers into the
dishes. The state oversees food safety in 28,000 supermarkets and
delis _ but it employs only 75 inspectors to do the work. In the
early 1990s, there were 63.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory analysis done for the Dining section found high
levels of bacteria, yeasts or molds in most samples, indicating
that the food had been kept at improper temperatures and for too
long, and that much of it was either spoiled or on the verge of
spoiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major concerns is the length of time food is on a
salad bar,'' said Dr. Michael Doyle, the director of the Center for
Food Safety and Quality Enhancement at the University of Georgia.
``Many keep refilling it without washing up the containers.
Sometimes they take the food off the salad bar, replenish it and
refrigerate it overnight, and that gets them in more trouble than
anything because of temperature abuse, which is one of the leading
causes of food-borne disease. That's what frightens me the most.
And who knows where hands have been prior to touching food? I don't
eat at them because of all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dining section's survey is not large enough to be
representative, but it does provide a snapshot of conditions at
places that are among the least and the most expensive. Six were
help-yourself food bars, and one had food displayed in the open
where customers could touch it, although it was packaged by
servers. The cleanliness of the food had nothing to do with the
price.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Groth, a biologist and food safety specialist at
Consumers Union, said that conclusions could not be drawn about the
safety of the food because the sampling was much too small to be
statistically reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``High bacteria count is a quality issue, not a safety issue,''
he added. ``Scientists call it the yuck factor. It's not lethal,
but a big yuck...''
</P>
<P>
   It is very difficult to trace the source of gastrointestinal
illnesses. Most food-borne illness is never reported, and neither
New York state nor the federal government keeps records on
help-yourself food. But Dr. Michael Osterholm, a former
epidemiologist for the Minnesota health department, said that
``produce is the No. 1 vehicle for transmission of food-borne
disease over the last decade, and much of that has been associated
with salad bars.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Dining section's survey, two food samples were taken
from each of the seven stores: Dean &AMP; DeLuca in SoHo; Eli's, at
Third Avenue and 80th Street; the Food Emporium at Third Avenue and
63d Street; Fresh N' Plus, on Third Avenue between 78th and 79th
Streets; Morton Williams Associated Stores, at Broadway and 57th
Street; Exotic Flower Deli, at 202 Avenue of the Americas, and
Whole Foods, at 117 Prince Street.
</P>
<P>
   The food was tested for the total amount of bacteria (a high
level indicates poor refrigeration or poor manufacturing
practices); for the presence of coliform (a high level indicates
possible contamination from other sources, poor food handling or
improper storage); for yeasts and molds, which are present in
spoiled food; for E. coli, a type of coliform that indicates the
presence of fecal matter; for staphylococcus, a germ that causes an
infection that can lead to death, and for listeria, the bacteria
that causes listeriosis.
</P>
<P>
   There are no regulations for total allowable bacteria in New
York State, only guidelines: five million colony-forming units per
gram for raw food, and one million for cooked food. The guideline
for coliform is 10 parts per million for cooked food.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria levels as high as those are ``a red flag to us,'' said
Peter Gregg, a spokesman for the State Department of Agriculture
and Markets, which is responsible for inspecting supermarkets and
delis. ``It will trigger us to look further, check for pathogens
and see why the product is spoiling.'' The inspectors try to visit
each place once a year, giving the food a visual inspection and
taking the temperature of various dishes.
</P>
<P>
   In each store in the Dining section's survey, one of the two
items sampled had levels of bacteria or coliform that exceeded the
guidelines. Some food also had high levels of yeasts and molds. One
tested positive for staphylococcus (which did not mean that someone
would contract the disease but that the food had been handled by
someone with a staph infection). There were no detectable levels of
E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   The food was bought and tested by Associated Analytical
Laboratories Inc. of Manhattan. Temperatures were taken after
purchase. Then the food was placed in chilled containers and taken
to the laboratory. The state inspection process is the same, except
that the state takes the temperature of the food while it is still
on display.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances the temperature of the hot foods was as much
as 40 degrees below the required temperature, 140 degrees
Fahrenheit, while the cold food was as much as 35 degrees above the
required maximum, 45. Bacteria thrive at around 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Dining section's spot check was far worse
than the state's annual findings, which suggests either that by
chance the section's choices were not as clean or fresh as the food
normally displayed in a vast majority of stores, or that 75
inspectors cannot do a thorough job of inspecting 28,000 places.
Less than 9 percent of those 28,000 failed two consecutive
inspections, said Gregg, who added that the department tries to
inspect each place once a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspecting once a year does not adequately deal with the
problems,'' Ms. Kleiner said. ``What I have seen in food
preparation facilities is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors arrive unannounced, with a list of two types of
potential violations: critical deficiencies, which are likely to
cause immediate health problems, and general deficiencies, which
are not deemed immediate health hazards. The temperatures of foods
are tested. Critical deficiencies include the presence of insects
or rodents in the food, the handling of food without gloves, and
the display of food at improper temperatures. Any critical
infraction means a failed inspection; this can result in a fine
that varies depending on how many problems are found and whether
the store has failed its previous inspection. Reinspection follows
within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   If a store fails three inspections, the owner is usually taken
to State Supreme Court. There were about 190 court cases in 1997
and 1998, but the judge ordered only 10 of the stores in each of
those years to close. So far this year there have been 91 court
cases.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Inspection reports on the seven establishments were obtained
from the state after the Dining section's spot check.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven places in the Dining section's survey had
failed inspections in 1998 or 1999 and three paid fines; one, Whole
Foods, had failed twice.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods was inspected in August 1998 and had 3 critical
deficiencies and 14 general ones; it paid $1,200 in fines. Upon
reinspection in October it had 2 critical deficiencies and paid
$1,800 more in fines. By May 1999, it had cleared up all critical
deficiencies but still had 9 general ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the laboratory work done for the Dining section, one dish
from Whole Foods _ cold brussels sprouts _ had extremely high
levels of bacteria, coliform and yeast and tested positive for
staphylococcus. The other item _ hot kale with peppers _ had a high
total bacteria count and very high coliform and yeast counts.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rosenbloom, the owner of Whole Foods, was shocked by the
findings. ``We had to let two of our managers go because they
couldn't pass inspection,'' he said. ``We were concerned we were
going to lose our license. Lately the state has gotten pretty
stringent. The salad bar is exceptionally difficult to control. You
have lots of customers, and hopefully they are not putting their
fingers in it. It's terribly worrisome. If we hadn't passed the May
inspection, we would have had a hearing and the state would have
closed us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would eat from his help-yourself food bar, he said:
``I wouldn't want my grandson eating in a salad bar in this kind of
food service. I will talk to my managers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Morton Williams Associated Stores location at Broadway
and 57th Street, the June 1998 inspection report listed two
critical deficiencies that included dozens of live and dead flies.
At an inspection in November 1998, three critical deficiencies were
found and a $300 fine was levied. The store was inspected again in
March and had no critical deficiencies but a number of general
ones. The latest inspection, last Friday, found no critical
deficiencies and 13 general ones.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Sloan, who owns Morton Williams Associated Stores with
his brother, William, said: ``To highlight our store on a
comparative basis is an injustice. We think we run a first-class,
clean operation. The difference in zealousness between one
inspector and another is 1,000 percent. Inspectors are trying to
make a name for themselves. We spend a lot of money on a clean,
healthy environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The July 1998 inspection report for Dean &AMP; DeLuca, where the
food is packed by employees but can be touched by customers, listed
four critical deficiencies, including the presence of live roaches
and houseflies on food or food-handling equipment, and 14 general
ones. The company was fined $300. On a follow-up inspection in
October there were no critical deficiencies and 11 general ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as these things come to anyone's attention we try to
keep things up,'' said Emil Grosso, the vice president for finance
at Dean &AMP; DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   At the Exotic Flower Deli, where one item had high bacteria, the
owner, Jimmy Noh, said he checks the food ``a couple of days a week
with a thermometer,'' and throws away food ``after 2 o'clock when
the temperature is too high outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The high level of bacteria, yeasts and molds in a sample of
chicken salad from the Food Emporium store at Third Avenue and 63d
Street was ``an isolated incident,'' said Cheryl Palmer, the senior
vice president for strategic marketing at the Great Atlantic and
Pacific Tea Company, the chain's owner. She said the company had
been talking to the maker of some salad bar foods about the
products. ``We run our own tests and we have proper procedures in
place and are constantly updating our procedures,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, spokesmen for the stores blamed poor help for their
problems. ``People are lazy,'' said Ross Breen, the manager of
Eli's, a sentiment echoed by other store officials. ``They are
always trying to do shortcuts, and that's what gets us in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kleiner, the sanitation consultant, is even more critical.
``They assume people are capable of handling the food and they are
not,'' she said. ``Keeping a place clean starts from the top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
