<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB INTERVIEWS AREN'T THE PLACE TO SHARE YOUR PERSONAL OPINIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A job interview is not the place for politics. Or religion. Or
dirty jokes. Or racial or sexist rantings.
</P>
<P>
   Duh, you say?
</P>
<P>
   You'd be surprised. At careers fairs and in conversations with
job hunters, it's disappointing to find so many individuals who
don't understand that, no matter how much they hate President
Clinton, it's not the time or place to pontificate.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping personal opinions private is paramount in job
interviews. The same caution should be exercised when attending
professional association meetings or talking informally to people
at potential places of employment.
</P>
<P>
   I've written before about the problems caused by politically
charged conversations in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to discuss politics and feel no reason to reveal
my views to someone I barely know, so I keep quiet,'' said one
Kansas City area worker who had to share a cubicle with an
opinionated blatherer. ``However, if I don't openly disagree with
the person, he assumes I do agree and continues on, which makes me
uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Transfer that kind of reaction into a setting where a job
applicant is trying to make a good impression. The discomfort is
magnified. The interviewer _ or even the friend who's being asked
to make a job referral _ is likely to recoil from recommending
spewers of dogma or sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Inappropriate rantings aren't limited to touchy politics. I once
tried to cut short (with no success) a job hunter who apparently
thought I wanted to hear about the potholes in his street. I don't
like potholes, either, but a high-tech job fair isn't the place for
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of thinking, ``Here's a smart, qualified job
candidate,'' I was thinking, ``There's no way in the world I'd want
that guy in my department.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal opinions about politics, race, religion, gender or
sexual orientation have little bearing on job competence. It's wise
to keep those views, whatever they are, private when looking for
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ANIMALS-SURVIVE-     08-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ANIMALS-SURVIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BACK FROM THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 25:
</P>
<P>
   This has been a positive summer for several bird and animal
species that human carelessness had once driven to the brink. In
July the Interior Department disclosed its intention to remove the
bald eagle and the Aleutian Canada goose from the
endangered-species list, pending a brief period of public comment.
Last Friday the department formally removed the peregrine falcon
from the list. One day later the White House announced that it had
secured 9,300 acres of land adjacent to Yellowstone National Park
to provide critical winter range for the park's fragile bison herd,
which has been alternately ravaged by starvation and the animosity
of Montana's cattle ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   This good news sends a timely and important message to a
Congress that has often been indifferent to the needs of nature.
The message is that recovery programs can work, and that it would
be foolish to deny the funds that make these triumphs possible.
</P>
<P>
   The peregrine falcon is only the sixth species to warrant
de-listing since the passage of the Endangered Species Act in 1973,
leaving about 1,200 plant and animal species on the list. In 1970
only 39 breeding pairs existed in the entire country. There are now
more than 1,650 pairs. The bird's recovery owes much to the late
Rachel Carson, who first drew attention to the dangers of DDT and
to the subsequent passage in 1972 of a federal law banning the
pesticide. But credit is also due the Endangered Species Act, which
enabled the federal government to intervene vigorously on the
bird's behalf, breeding falcons in captivity and protecting habitat
where they could flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone's beleaguered bison are not officially listed as
endangered, but they are clearly in trouble. In harsh winters, the
bison descend from Yellowstone's high plateau and wander peaceably
across park boundaries in search of food. But because some bison
carry a disease called brucellosis, which is potentially dangerous
to cattle, they are routinely shot or captured for slaughter by
state agents, largely at the behest of Montana's cattle ranchers.
In 1997 the Montana Department of Livestock killed 1,000 bison,
nearly one-third of Yellowstone's herd _ even though nobody stopped
to ask which animals were carrying the disease, and even though
there have been no documented cases of the disease ever jumping
from bison to cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The federal purchase from private owners of 9,300 acres adjacent
to the park _ made possible by $13 million from the Federal Land
and Water Conservation Fund _ will give the animals what amounts to
a safety valve, a big piece of land where they can forage for food
without fear of being shot. It is only the first step in what must
be a broader effort to reconcile the needs of the bison and the
ranchers. But even this small gesture would not have happened
without the negotiating skills of local conservation groups like
the Greater Yellowstone Coalition and pressure from Montana's Sen.
Max Baucus and the Clinton administration to extract the necessary
funds from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many in Congress have yet to see the value of the
very federal programs that have helped the falcon and the bison.
President Clinton's request for a modest $80 million for innovative
public-private partnerships to preserve habitat for endangered
species has been slashed by 80 percent by House and Senate
appropriations committees. Likewise, congressional appropriators
have cut his $1 billion request for the Land and Water Conservation
Fund and other open-space initiatives by two-thirds. A more
generous Congress could guarantee more success stories in the years
ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
