<SLUG> BC-RIVER-PACT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT ON MISSOURI RIVER FLOW MAY BE NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The eight states in the Missouri River basin
_ which for years have fought over the river's flow, especially in
times of drought _ may be close to agreement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're near a historic consensus,'' said Richard Opper,
executive director of the Missouri River Basin Association, who has
worked for several months to achieve an agreement among the states
and a group of American Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues being considered is an agreed-upon water level
if a drought similar to that of the 1980s reoccurred, Opper said.
</P>
<P>
   The group may also propose that the river between Fort Peck and
Gavins Point dams _ about 188 miles in Montana and South Dakota _
be allowed to rise in spring, as unmanaged rivers do, and be
monitored for its impacts on fish and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri River, in its 2,500-mile cut through the Plains to
the Mississippi River, has for years spawned more fury than
concord. And this new effort for consensus may still have farther
to go.
</P>
<P>
   A Missouri official involved in the negotiations cautioned
Tuesday that the states have not agreed on all crucial issues. A
final agreement may not be completed until Monday, when the
association meets in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   This battle over the Missouri's flow has continued more than a
decade as the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has reconsidered how it
operates the flow out of six upstream dams.
</P>
<P>
   The corps began in 1989 to study how to regulate the flow, when
it attempted to revise its master control manual. Five years later,
it made its proposal, but was met with so much criticism that it
withdrew its plan and start anew.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the basin association's board _ which consists of
representatives of the eight basin states, each appointed by the
governor, and a group that represents nearly 30 American Indian
tribes _ hopes to reach consensus by next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations will be forwarded to the Corps of Engineers,
which will choose in early September a new operating plan for
managing the flows each year. The plan won't be revealed until
October, the corps said.
</P>
<P>
   Opper and corps officials said Tuesday that it appeared likely
that consensus, at least among the eight states, was possible,
despite years of conflict. Further negotiations with the Indian
tribes may be required.
</P>
<P>
   Getting eight states to agree is an achievement, Opper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked very, very hard on this,'' Opper said. ``And
there's been a lot of movement. When we first started on this, we
were millions of acre-feet apart. Now, the differences are largely
insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   The basin association is also proposing a new biological
monitoring program and the establishment of an endangered species
recovery team. It may also push for more flexibility for the corps
to experiment or change its operations to accommodate endangered
species and other interests.
</P>
<P>
   Such recommendations, if agreed to by all the states, would have
great influence with the corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus of eight governors will weigh heavily,'' said
Rosemary Hargraves, project manager for the corps master manual
revision.
</P>
<P>
   Hargraves stressed that the corps will consider the positions of
other interests in the basin, including environmental groups that
are pushing for dramatic changes in the river's flow.
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers, a national conservation group that has pushed
for an end to navigation on the lower Missouri, has begun a drive
for a Missouri River management plan that would split the
navigation season on the lower river. A split season would provide
enough flow for barge traffic in spring and fall, but not in
summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of U.S. Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, a Democrat,
the corps has modeled the split navigation season in three ways,
Hargraves said.
</P>
<P>
   A split season ``is obviously the best choice for the Missouri's
fish and wildlife,'' said Chad Smith, who leads American Rivers'
Missouri River campaign. ``But it's also the best people
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Navigation interests on the lower Missouri have long opposed a
split navigation season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just have to close up shop,'' said John Madgett, senior
vice president of Mid-West Terminal Warehouse Co., which operates
the largest river facility in the Kansas City reach of the
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river would be just a wild, wild river, never again to be
seen by you or I,'' Madgett continued. ``But I don't think that
will come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Madgett said he had seen Missouri officials make concessions to
try to reach agreement with upper basin states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very interesting to see how the states have shown
interest in trying to cooperate,'' Madgett said. ``For years,
they've fought and done things behind each other's backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all agree to something, and there's going to be people
who are not going to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kucera, the Missouri Department of Natural Resources' deputy
director of policy, said he still had questions for the corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to agree to anything yet,'' Kucera said.
``We're still a ways from agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   A key issue will be how to address environmental issues related
to the river's management, Kucera said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has maintained that allowing
a spring rise could help threatened and endangered fish and
wildlife, as their reproductive cycles are tied to the natural
spring rise.
</P>
<P>
   Hargraves said it's unclear which of the natural disruptions of
the river has a greater impact on endangered species. For example,
does the loss of a spring rise have a greater impact than the
dramatic loss of fish and wildlife habitat?
</P>
<P>
   To get some answers, Hargraves said, the corps has asked the
National Academy of Sciences to conduct a two- to three-year study
on the status of scientific knowledge on fish and wildlife issues
on the Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the corps has increased its efforts to restore
habitat for fish and wildlife along the river. Hargraves hopes
those efforts, combined with other recent efforts to restore
habitat, will help the corps weather any challenges to its new plan
as being neglectful of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get something done on the river,'' Hargraves said, ``and
let's quit fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
