<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSINESS TRAVEL: CROWDED PLANES; AIRLINE UPDATE; WILL CARNIVAL BUY
PRINCESS?  (Duplication warning: also moving in ``f'' category) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you wonder whether the flights you have been on in recent
months are always crowded, or whether you are just a victim of bad
timing or bad luck, the load factors _ the percentages of available
seats occupied by paying passengers _ for most U.S. airlines last
month are revealing. So are the year-to-date load factors.
</P>
<P>
   Every major carrier had load factors at least in the 70s in
July, and most had them in the mid- to high-70s. Two airlines,
Trans World Airlines and Northwest Airlines, had them in the 80s
that month; TWA's 2.4 million domestic passengers resulted in what
the airlines said was its ``best month in modern history'' for
domestic boardings.
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines also broke records in July. The 79.1 percent load
factor at Delta Air Lines, for example, was the highest for any
month in its 70-year history, while the 77.8 percent at Continental
Airlines was not only the highest of any July in its history, but
its second-highest month ever.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think you can easily get an overnight ``red eye''
flight or a Saturday flight, both of which used to be readily
available because few business travelers flew then. Now they have
to fly when there are seats. On several recent Saturdays, for
example, occupancies on Delta flights have averaged above 80
percent, and on a recent Saturday reached 86.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has driven people to what used to be underused
flights, because those fares tend to be cheaper and passengers are
willing to fly at those times for a bargain price,'' said John
Kennedy, a Delta spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The only two major airlines whose year-to-date passenger loads
were below 70 percent are America West at 67.4 percent and Alaska
Airlines at 62.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The annual average load factors hovered in the high-50s and
low-60s throughout the 1980s. In 1994 they rose to 69.3 percent and
thereafter began their ascent into the 70s, where they remain
today. What this means, of course, is that packed airplanes are not
just the result of the luck of the draw but a permanent condition
for most passengers, at least until the economy weakens.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Airlines
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who joins the British Airways frequent-flier program and
then takes a trans-Atlantic flight on a full-fare business-class
round-trip ticket, or two one-way tickets (either way, the cost is
$5,366 between New York or Newark and London), will receive two
free coach tickets to almost anywhere in the world. Now for the
fine print: Passengers must travel by Dec. 15, 1999, and no later
than Dec. 31, 1999, and they also must write a note, letter or
treatise expressing their opinion of British Airways' business
class. The free tickets are valid for travel between Jan. 15, 2000,
and Dec. 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Airtran is the latest airline to offer 10 percent discounts for
travel booked over its site on the Internet (www.airtran.com).
Airtran's hub is in Atlanta and its destinations include Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.; Miami; New Orleans; Orlando, Fla.; Savannah, Ga.,
and Tampa, Fla. Fares require at least a three-day advance
purchase, but do not require a round-trip purchase or Saturday
night stay.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next February, Aloha Airlines will fly from Hawaii to
the mainland for the first time in its 53-year history. Using new
Boeing 737-300s, it will fly two daily round trips _ between
Honolulu and Oakland, Calif., and Maui and Oakland. If customers
find on-time performance, baggage handling or customer service
lacking, Aloha said it would give them a free one-way inter-island
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery Deal
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are not all convinced that Carnival Corp. will succeed
in buying Princess Cruises, but neither do they think it is a pipe
dream, especially since Carnival confirmed that it had held talks
with Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Co., Princess'
British owner. On Tuesday, Tim Gallagher, a Carnival spokesman,
said that the talks had occurred ``earlier this year,'' adding that
there were no talks currently and the company had no comment on
whether it had made an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Princess expects delivery of seven new ships between next year
and 2004, and that hardly seems like the action of a company
wanting to sell. On the other hand, when Carnival speaks, much of
the cruise industry rejoices or trembles. Its 35 percent market
share is far and away the largest, as is its fleet of more than 44
ships, with nine on order. Princess, by contrast, has a 15.5
percent market share and nine ships plus the seven on order. And a
British newspaper, The Daily Mail, reported that Carnival offered
$11 billion for Princess.
</P>
<P>
   If Carnival does buy Princess, within three years it is likely
to command at least 50 percent of the worldwide cruise market. If
it does not, Carnival still has come a long way since its inception
in 1972. It acquired its first ship _ the Empress of Canada _ from
Canadian Pacific for $5 million. Renamed the Mardi Gras, it
promptly ran aground on its maiden voyage from the Port of Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      08-24 0868
