<HEADLINE>
INJURIES HOLD BACK UCLA'S HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No member of UCLA's prized 1998 recruiting class
was more celebrated than cornerback Lovell Houston _ not guard Mike
Saffer, not defensive tackle Ken Kocher, not even tailback prodigy
DeShaun Foster. Houston was a USA Today and Parade Magazine
first-team All-American and he turned down Florida State to play
for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons later, Foster, Kocher and Saffer are starting, while
Houston has little chance of entering the lineup. His trouble has
nothing to do with talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovell is like a freshman who just reported again because he's
missed so much time with the injuries,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston missed training camp last year because of a strained
thigh. He redshirted, then had surgery on both shoulders to repair
high school injuries. He worked diligently in the offseason to
regain strength and flexibility, and when practice began Aug. 14,
Houston figured he'd join the rotation. After all, UCLA had
suspended two starters (Ryan Roques and Marques Anderson) and was
desperate for cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Houston reinjured his left thigh and the
frustration began anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to play, not be a training room trophy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who had a 3.6 grade-point average at Denver's Jefferson
High, has channeled his football frustration into academic
performance. He'll probably major in political science, but he
loves unusual subjects. He took an astronomy class on the nature of
the universe, a political theory class on anarchy and the
Federalist Papers, and a history class on African-American
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's often a separation between American history and black
history,'' he said. ``But the truth is, black history in the United
States is American history. The class opened a lot of gateways for
a multitude of students.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Houston is concentrating on his strained left
thigh. The daily medical report lists him as day-to-day, but his
angst compounds by the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can play,'' he said. ``But to get to the point where
I'm actually on the field, I'll have to take the long road.''
</P>
<P>
   Parking-placard update: Fullback Durell Price and guard Jim
Ghezzi will be arraigned today in L.A. Municipal Court for their
part in the disabled parking scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set our mind to getting the same (punishment) as
everyone else,'' Price said, referring to the $1,485 fine and 200
hours of community service that nine players received at the July
28 arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruins Craig Walendy, DuVal Hicks and Mark Reynosa also
will be arraigned.
</P>
<P>
   Heartache: Junior tackle Brian Polak was a Bishop Amat teammate
of Paul Reyna, the Boise State freshman who died Monday from head
injuries suffered last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about it, my heart sunk,'' said Polak, who
comes from Hacienda Heights. ``I've been thinking of him
constantly....
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him at a San Gabriel Valley all-star game this summer. I
told him to work hard, but when he came down here, I'd kick his
butt.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA plays Boise State on Sept. 4 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna, 19, suffered a torn blood vessel between his brain and
skull, and the bleeding developed into a blood clot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
