<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE COACHES CAREFUL WITH ABDUL-MALIK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge coaches don't want to take any chance with
Hassan Abdul-Malik.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how important Abdul-Malik is to the Matadors' secondary:
He remains the starting free safety even though he's missed the
last week of practice with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have him back for the first game,'' defensive
coordinator Foster Andersen said, ``but I want to have him for the
second game. We are being very, very careful with him.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN opens the season Sept. 4 at home against Western Oregon.
The Matadors play the next week at Kansas. Abdul-Malik, who earned
the starting job after an excellent spring, said he's growing
frustrated. He hurt his right leg on Aug. 16, the third day of
practice for the returners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel guilty,'' he said. ``There's a lot of good competition
out there. It's hard to miss practice and the new defensive
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   His role is even more important because Jeremy Golden, last
year's leading tackler, is academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can do what (Golden) did last year, I'll do all right,''
Abdul-Malik said.
</P>
<P>
   Shocking news: Junior offensive lineman Ernie Fierro received
sad news Monday when he found out Boise State defensive lineman
Paul Reyna died four days after suffering a brain injury in the
team's first fall practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fierro and Reyna were teammates at Bishop Amat four years ago
and they have been friends for almost a decade. Fierro's younger
sister graduated with Reyna in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' Fierro said Tuesday. ``I saw him a week
before he left (for Boise). I got a call at (midnight) the night
before last saying he had taken a turn for the worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Fierro plans on attending Reyna's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a friend of mine, not just someone I knew,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar face: Mike Ogas is back on the Matadors' practice field
as a volunteer assistant coach. Ogas, who caught 40 passes for CSUN
last year as a senior, signed as an undrafted free agent with the
St. Louis Rams in April. He was cut after one minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had six practices and about 100 meetings,'' Ogas said. ``I
got to play pool with Marshall Faulk and Isaac Bruce. I also
learned about a million things that I can help teach these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Good news, better news: Getting a key signature Monday afternoon
helped Kaleon Green further his bid for a sixth year of eligibility
from the NCAA. He obtained a signed letter from a Kaiser Permanente
doctor who confirmed Green was advised not to play football in 1995
when he was showing symptoms of recurrence of cancer he had the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was supposed to be faxed to the NCAA on Tuesday, and
Green is confident he'll find out he'll be eligible for the
upcoming season by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back Sean Atkins won his case with the NCAA on Monday
to sit out just one year instead of the usual two because he
transferred within the Big Sky Conference. He started practicing
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins, who played at San Fernando High, went to Sacramento
State last year but didn't receive any scholarship money from the
school until the spring. He'll be eligible to play next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
