<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-FORWARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs will audition for small forward
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The San Antonio Spurs have more candidates at
small forward than the Republicans have for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Republicans, the Spurs do not have a
front-runner. Unable to find a replacement for Sean Elliott, the
Spurs might give half the team a shot at the position when training
camp begins Oct. 2. Elliott underwent a kidney transplant and was
released from the hospital Tuesday but is unlikely to play this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be (small forward) by committee,'' said R.C.
Buford, assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have all but given up hope of signing Utah's Shandon
Anderson, the most coveted free agent available this year who can
play small forward. The Spurs say that, for whatever reason,
Anderson's agent, Dan Fegan, has kept them at a distance from his
client. Fegan has not returned phone calls to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected trade or a change of heart by Anderson,
here are the Spurs' candidates:
</P>
<P>
   _Malik Rose. Buford said Rose, a 6-foot 7-inch, 250-pound backup
to Tim Duncan at power forward last season, has the quickness and
aggressiveness to play small forward on defense. Rose, however, is
neither an adept ballhandler nor a reliable shooter. This move has
turnover written all over it. ``Maybe we won't let him dribble,''
Buford said, joking. ``But he can post up smaller players.''
</P>
<P>
   _Mario Elie. A small forward during most of his five seasons
with Houston, the 6-5 Elie moved to shooting guard in San Antonio.
Elie lacks Elliott's quickness, but few are more tenacious.
</P>
<P>
   _Jaren Jackson. Primarily a shooting guard, the 6-6 Jackson has
played some small forward. Jackson shoots much better than Rose but
lacks ballhandling and passing skills.
</P>
<P>
   _Jerome Kersey. Too slow to work significant minutes at small
forward, Kersey filled in last season primarily against bulky
players like himself.
</P>
<P>
   _Tim Duncan. As a rookie two seasons ago, the 7-foot Duncan,
normally a power forward and center, played small forward for short
periods in a lineup that included the 7-1 David Robinson and 7-foot
Will Perdue. The Spurs did not use that lineup during their recent
NBA championship season, having improved their depth on the
perimeter when Elliott returned from a knee injury and Elie and
Kersey joined the team. Coach Gregg Popovich has considered going
back to the ``three bigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Perdue, a free agent, has yet to re-sign, but the Spurs say they
are close to completing a deal with him. Meanwhile, they are
talking to Samaki Walker, a 6-9 free agent power forward for
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   _Chucky Brown. The Spurs are considering making an offer to
Brown, a free agent who played for Charlotte last season. The 6-8
Brown averaged 25 minutes and 8.5 points per game last season,
converting 37.5 percent of his three-point shots, playing primarily
small forward.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Bexar County commissioners approved an agreement Tuesday
with the Spurs for a $175 million tax-funded arena and called a
Nov. 2 vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
