<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT &LR;      08-24 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI USED VAGARIES OF PAC LAWS TO PROMOTE PRESIDENTIAL HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (mk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George Pataki's two political action
committees, one in New York and one in Virginia, were established
in January to promote what he called a ``positive message of
change'' by helping like-minded Republicans win office around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But their reports show that the Pataki PACs used the vagaries of
Virginia and federal election law to put corporate money and large
individual donations behind Pataki's brief hopes for the
presidential nomination. Many other politicians have taken similar
advantage of the laws. Here is how things worked in Pataki's case.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate funds and individual contributions of more than $5,000
to a federal political action committee are barred under federal
law. One of Pataki's committees is covered under federal law. But
the other, organized in Virginia, is subject to its much looser
laws. In Virginia, there are no limits on the size or sources of
contributions to PACs. So the Virginia committee raised $395,300
through June 30, while the federal PAC raised only $185,702.
</P>
<P>
   The federal version of the Pataki PAC announced that it planned
to give 75 percent of its donations to state (as opposed to
federal) candidates. That stipulation allowed it to take money from
the fatter Virginia PAC for 75 percent of its ``expenses,'' a word
that political figures tend to define quite flexibly.
</P>
<P>
   The promise to donate to state candidates in turn enabled Pataki
to use the Virginia-raised money for any political expense he
chose, including the costs of pursuing his own presidential
ambitions. Now that he is no longer pursuing that goal, he can use
the money for anything else he wants.
</P>
<P>
   But the commitment to state candidates meant that Bell
Atlantic's $50,000 in corporate funds helped pay the bills when
Peggy Noonan, a speechwriter for Presidents Reagan and Bush, sat
down with Pataki last winter and discussed several speeches that he
wanted to give. She was paid $10,000, and 75 percent of that came
through the Virginia PAC.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Stephen Moore, an economist with the Cato Institute
in Washington, was paid $15,000 last winter to work with Pataki on
a tax-cutting plan. The governor proposed it at the Detroit
Economic Club on June 24, one month after he had abandoned his own
presidential ambitions and endorsed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
for the Republican nomination. Of that sum, $11,250 came through
the Virginia PAC.
</P>
<P>
   The same formula was used to pay at least $10,115 for the
governor's travel bills, and $2,617 to reimburse his communications
director, Zenia Mucha, for travel and phone costs.
</P>
<P>
   The federal PAC's promised contributions to candidates for state
office, which opened the door to transferring money from one PAC to
another, have not materialized. So far, Pataki's federal PAC has
given nothing to state candidates. But Adam Stoll, who runs the
political action committee in New York City, said both PACs may
``quite possibly'' make further donations this year. The Virginia
PAC has given $31,600 to nine Republican legislative candidates in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's light regulatory touch has won it the nickname ``the
Cayman Islands of campaign finance,'' and Pataki is hardly the
first out-of-state politician to discover its uses. Two Republican
presidential hopefuls, former Vice President Dan Quayle and former
Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, both moved more than a million
dollars in the last several months through Virginia PACs to aid
their campaigns. And Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority
leader, has established a PAC, the New Republican Majority Fund, in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are such practices legal in Virginia, they also do not
come close to violating federal election laws, under which ``soft
money'' of the sort collected in Virginia plays an increasing role.
</P>
<P>
   The only illegal contributions shown in the Pataki PAC reports
were two contributions of $12,500 each to the federal PAC in New
York City from Reba White Williams, a Republican candidate for the
New York City Council, and her husband, David Williams, head of
Alliance Capital Management, a mutual funds company. The donations
violated the law because they exceeded the $5,000 limit on
contributions to federal PACs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pataki camp will hold on to those contributions anyway.
Stoll said those contributions would become legitimate when $7,500
from each of them was transferred from the federal PAC to the
non-federal PAC in Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
