<HEADLINE>
GOODYKOONTZ: FALL TV IS HARD TO STOM ACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never let it be said there's nothing new under the television
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Each fall season brings with it a raft of new shows brimming
with the promise of hope, the joy of discovery, the sight of people
puking on each other, and the threat of eating dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sorry. Those last two apply only to ``this'' fall season.
</P>
<P>
   They may seem like unlikely trends, but at least five new shows
include eruptive nausea; characters in two others threaten to eat
the canine pets of other characters.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just in the pilot episodes. It could be a long,
sloppy season. Though the potential for Pepto-Bismol advertising
seems limitless.
</P>
<P>
   The vomiting is almost always captured in living color, complete
with retching sounds. The dog-eating, thankfully, remains only a
threat. Which means the upchucking is never actually caused by
gobbling up Fido. But it's early yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think this is a pathetic cry for attention from
struggling young writers and producers, know that the rich and
famous are in on the act as well. Chris Carter, the creator of
``The X-Files,'' penned the pilot for the Fox network's ``Harsh
Realm,'' about a soldier trapped inside a virtual war game.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbes, the soldier, finds a dog while trying to escape this
alternate reality. He enlists the help of Pinocchio, another
soldier trapped in Harsh Realm. Pinocchio is reluctant to help
Hobbes, and more than once threatens to eat his dog.
</P>
<P>
   The sensible viewer may ask: Why?
</P>
<P>
   `I wanted to distinguish the Pinocchio and Hobbes characters
from one another,'' Carter said earlier this summer. ``I wanted
(Hobbes) to be a very sort of saucy character, who I felt is an
idealized hero who doesn't want men speaking poorly to women, who
would always be chivalrous and gentlemanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want Pinocchio to sound different, and to be a
character of some dangerous consequence. And I think that's why you
have a place like Harsh Realm where things like animals are
commodities, and might, in fact, be eaten if let off their leash.''
</P>
<P>
   (Yes, Carter really talks that way. And you wondered why ``The
X-Files'' is so hard to follow sometimes.)
</P>
<P>
   The other threatened dog-munching occurs in ``Get Real,''
another new Fox show. Kenny, a high-school freshman, is threatened
by a bully who promises to beat him up and then, yes, eat his dog.
</P>
<P>
   Woof.
</P>
<P>
   As for vomiting, well, take your pick. In ``Action,'' Fox's
much-talked-about new comedy, producer Peter Dragon gets the
box-office numbers for his latest movie and pukes.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley, of ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice'' fame,
jumps on the blow-chunks bandwagon with his new ABC show
``Snoops,'' in which a queasy private detective riding in the back
seat of a car during a high-speed chase lets go with lunch out the
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manchester Prep,'' yet another new Fox show, gets in on the
puke parade when a geeky freshman girl downs too many Long Island
Iced Teas, but doesn't keep them down for long.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Third Watch,'' a new NBC show about cops and emergency
medical technicians and the like, we are treated to not one but two
intestinal events. First, a drunk throws up on a rookie cop. Then a
teenage junkie tosses her dinner. The hat trick is threatened
several times, but never comes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in ``The Badland,'' another new Fox show (is anyone
surprised that so many of these disgusting scenes take place on the
network that once whelped ``Married With Children'', yet another
drunk pukes on yet another rookie cop.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the same cop, Ryan Caulfield, is involved in a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you doin'?'' his streetwise partner asks. ``Nauseous
yet?''
</P>
<P>
   No, Caulfield assures him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, naturally, he pukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really trying to show is sensitivity to what's
going on in the world as far as violence goes,'' ``Badland''
executive producer Kevin Fox said, ``and a real, honest,
responsible reaction to real violence and what goes on in the
street. And I think that's one really strong way to show that, you
know, violence is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Extremely strong, though not of stomach. But it could have been
worse.
</P>
<P>
   At least he didn't eat his dog. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
