<DOCNO> NYT19990824.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RUN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     08-24 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEVILLE, Spain _ Nobody expected all of this from Michael Johnson.
Not the coaches who got their first glimpses of his unorthodox
running style. Not even his parents, who were only interested in
raising their five children to go through life with their feet
planted firmly on the ground and a plan to succeed somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a month, Paul Johnson, a truck driver, would gather his
three girls and two boys _ Michael is the youngest _ around the
dinner table and conduct family meetings. Ruby Johnson, an
elementary school teacher, was a few feet away preparing their
meal.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects varied, depending on which of the siblings happened
to be the most talkative that day. But always, in the end, the
discussion would return to Paul Johnson's favorite theme _ setting
goals and then doing all you can to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   On the laundry list of achievements of the greatest long
sprinter of all time, there is now just one goal left to fulfill:
the world record for 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's glaring,'' Johnson candidly admits.
</P>
<P>
   Time on the bigger stopwatch of life says he'd better do it
soon. Johnson will turn 32 next month and cannot realistically
expect to have many more seasons left to eclipse Butch Reynolds'
1988 record of 43.29 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's career best is 43.39, set in the 400 finals at the
1995 World Championships in Sweden, coming in the middle of a
grueling eight rounds of heats that went into his unprecedented
200/400 double, which Johnson repeated in 1996 at the Olympics in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Considering he will likely attempt the double again in Sydney
next summer, this championship in which he's running only the 400
could be his best chance.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Hart, Johnson's coach, had calculated that a time of 43.26
was forthcoming. But based on Johnson's lap in Tuesday night's
semifinals, that may be too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   In a performance that appeared equally amazing and effortless,
Johnson turned off his jets coming down the stretch and spent the
last 60 meters looking all around to his left and his right, like a
sightseer on a tour bus, and still clocked 43.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I've got to do, I'm prepared for it,'' he said. ``We
have a day of rest now, and we'll see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get it, I'm not going to cry over it. Any time I'm
in this kind of shape, it's possible. I would like to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, that statement is the equivalent of leaping onto a
table in a sequined toreador outfit and dancing the flamenco, since
he normally ranks just a bit behind Al Gore on the flamboyancy
scale. Throughout his career _ and perhaps it is one of the keys to
the broad body of his success _ Johnson has been a champion as
remarkable for his containment as for his speed and durability.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, as the finish line comes into sight, it is clear
that breaking the oldest running record on the books would mean
something special and might also help Johnson answer some critics
who have risen up recently to hint that he had come up with several
convenient injuries this summer in order to keep his mantle of
invincibility intact.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson withdrew from a showdown in the 200 at the U.S.
Nationals with Maurice Greene in June, Track &AMP; Field News hinted
that he was suffering from the ``9.79 flu,'' a reference to
Greene's world record in the 100 that had been set just a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   How could Johnson have been injured, Track &AMP; Field News
wondered, if just one week later, he ran a 43.92 in the 400, the
fastest time in the world this year, and a very hot 19.93 in the
200?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also pulled out of a meet July 30 in Europe, again
citing injury. Again he was greeted by cynicism. So what gives?
</P>
<P>
   According to Johnson's physical therapist, it's his sacroiliac,
where the pelvis meets the spine. Johnson suffers occasionally when
the joint rotates out of alignment.
</P>
<P>
   It is not considered a career-threatening condition but is a
bothersome one that can be corrected quickly with immediate
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson admits he has never been forthcoming concerning
injuries. But the recent spate of criticism has angered him. Since
1990 in the 200 meters, he has run against either the No. 1- or No.
2-ranked man in 49 percent of his races. And in the 400, that
figure tops 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 10 years, I'd say my reputation has been built
on handling pressure, taking on all comers,'' he said. ``And over
the last six weeks, it's like that's been forgotten and wiped away.
I'd like to do something to change this mistaken impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Like finally running down Butch Reynolds' 400 record.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a goal. Something Michael Johnson learned all about a
long time ago in those discussions around the dinner table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
