<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MANAGER REBORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Dierker cannot remember the bad parts _
collapsing in the dugout, the game suspended, the Houston Astros
huddling in public prayer, the television cameras capturing all of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the pain, the anguish, the emotion was spent by other
people,'' Dierker said evenly. ``My wife, my family, my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the good parts _ the sacks of letters, full of
personal experience, along with the prayers he acknowledges as a
force in his healing.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has been back for six weeks, after a month recuperating
from surgery following a seizure from malformed blood vessels in
his brain. He was enjoying his fourth career Tuesday night,
managing Houston to a 5-1 victory in 10 innings over the New York
Mets in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   He was not all right on June 13, when he went down in the dugout
in the eighth inning. He has talked so much that he might be
tempted to be bored, but Dierker is not the typical manager.
</P>
<P>
   First he was a pitcher, then he sold season tickets and then he
was a broadcaster, a droll presence in a Hawaiian shirt who knew
the game and also read hardcover books in his spare time. But until
he managed the Astros in 1997, he had never called for that most
intricate of sporting maneuvers, the National League double switch
on the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   His broadcasting career taught him a few things, including the
fine art of entertaining during rain delays and pitching changes.
Using those same skills, Dierker graciously talked about the ordeal
Tuesday, surely for the 1,000th time. He seemed motivated to talk
not by narcissism but by his appreciation for strangers, and his
new love of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unconscious for four days and I lost my sense of time,''
Dierker said. ``I knew I had surgery on the second day, that I had
seen doctors, had an MRI, but other people had to put the pieces
together for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The terror was in the eyes of the people who were with him in
the first frightening days _ his wife, Judy, two grown daughters,
Ashley and Julia, and Ryan, 14. Dierker was told he had an
arteriovenous malformation, a condition present from birth, and
that the dangerous vessels had been removed, and his prognosis was
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four days in the hospital, I got out of bed and found I
had balance,'' Dierker said. ``I could walk, normally. I went down
to the nursing station and got a cup of coffee and the newspaper. I
found I could walk and talk and read and smell the coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a period of one minute, I had a check on my senses,''
Dierker said. ``It was such a marvelous experience, the greatest
experience in my life. Everything was so vivid to me. For me, it
was better than scuba diving on a coral reef, better than being on
the top of a mountain in Aspen, better than playing golf in Hawaii.
Just sitting and reading the paper and drinking coffee. We take
these things for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he could, Dierker answered every one of perhaps 1,000
letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy who had brain surgery had self-published a book of 80
pages,'' Dierker recalled. ``A lady who was so immobilized that she
could hardly walk or talk had written 30 pages on her experience.
It wasn't just get-well cards. These people had empathy with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed by how many people wrote me from St. Louis and
Chicago and New York and Los Angeles, people who weren't Astros
fans. I got one from Australia and one from Astros fans who were
visiting in France. I heard about people who prayed when they saw
it happen on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, who calls himself ``a Christian of recent vintage,
after 20 years of prodding by my wife,'' said he was aware of the
spiritual message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised with a rational bent to me, but it took me a
while to come around to understand this,'' Dierker said. ``There's
a good chance it made some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He was back to work on July 15, noticing for a few weeks that
``I was quick to anger, not just during games but things at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker added: ``But that has dissipated, too. Now I'm back to
where I was.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one difference: Dierker received a letter from a
12-year-old in New York whose best friend had died ``and was
feeling pretty bad about it,'' and Dierker arranged to meet the
boy, and the family of the boy who died, before Monday's game. He
feels it is the least he can do to give thanks for a support system
that already existed by the time he woke up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
